import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

// ─── Mode detection ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Vite's define option injects __VERCEL_MODE__ = true at build time.
// In Claude artifacts (no bundler, no define) the global is never set,
// so typeof returns 'undefined' and we enter Claude mode automatically.
// Plain typeof never throws — safe in any JS context.
const CLAUDE_MODE = (typeof __VERCEL_MODE__ === 'undefined');

// ─── Supabase (Vercel mode only) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
// The dynamic import() is only executed when CLAUDE_MODE = false.
// It is never evaluated in Claude — just parsed (safe).
let _sb = null;
const _sbReady = CLAUDE_MODE
  ? Promise.resolve(null)
  : (async () => {
      try {
        const mod = await import('./supabase.js');
        _sb = mod.supabase;
      } catch (e) { console.warn('Supabase init failed', e); }
      return _sb;
    })();
const sb = () => _sb;

// ─── card data ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const DEFAULT_CARDS = [
  {id:'1',category:'EC2',question:'A company stops a Windows EC2 instance during off-hours to save cost and restarts it when needed. The application takes 8 minutes to fully initialize after each restart, hurting productivity. The instance was launched last year without any special configuration. What should the solutions architect do to reduce startup time without increasing cost?',choices:['A|Stop and start the instance more frequently to keep it warm in memory.','B|Migrate the application to a new EC2 instance with hibernation enabled.','C|Enable hibernation mode on the existing EC2 instance in the console.','D|Migrate the application to a Linux-based EC2 instance to reduce boot time.'],correct:'B',answer:'Launch a new EC2 instance with hibernation enabled from the start. When hibernated, the OS writes the entire contents of RAM to the root EBS volume. On restart, it reads that snapshot back into memory — skipping all initialization — and the application resumes exactly where it left off.',why:'Normally when an EC2 instance stops, RAM is cleared and on restart the OS boots from scratch, loads services, and applications re-initialize. Hibernation short-circuits this by treating RAM as a persistent checkpoint. The cost is identical to a stopped instance because you only pay for EBS storage and any attached Elastic IPs — there are no compute charges while hibernated.',trap:'You cannot enable hibernation on an existing instance — it must be configured at launch time because the OS needs to be set up to support the hibernate-resume process from the start. Migrating to Linux does not guarantee faster startup and risks breaking Windows-specific dependencies.',rule:'Hibernation = launch-time only. RAM saved to EBS, resumes instantly. Cannot enable after launch.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'2',category:'Networking',question:'A company has an existing AWS Direct Connect connection from its on-premises data center to AWS. Several new AWS accounts need reliable, dedicated access to on-premises DNS and Active Directory services. The solution must minimize operational overhead and cost.',choices:['A|Set up a new Direct Connect connection for each new AWS account.','B|Set up a new Direct Connect gateway and configure VPC peering between accounts, then associate it with the DX gateway.','C|Create a new Direct Connect gateway, attach it to the existing DX connection, and set up a Transit Gateway associated with the DX gateway.','D|Create a VPN CloudHub and set up VPN connections for each new AWS account.'],correct:'C',answer:'A Transit Gateway acts as a central hub. All new account VPCs connect to the Transit Gateway as spokes, and the Transit Gateway connects to the on-premises network via the Direct Connect gateway. This means a single DX connection serves all accounts.',why:'Direct Connect is an expensive, dedicated physical circuit between your data center and AWS. Rather than provisioning one per account (cost-prohibitive) or using VPN (which uses the public internet), Transit Gateway creates a hub-and-spoke topology. All VPCs attach to the TGW, which has one attachment to the DX gateway. Traffic from any VPC to on-premises goes through the TGW → DX gateway → DX connection. One physical connection, unlimited accounts.',trap:'VPC peering does NOT support transitive routing — if VPC A peers with VPC B, and VPC B has a DX connection, VPC A cannot reach on-premises through VPC B. Each VPN connection also traverses the public internet, so it cannot provide the "dedicated" access that Direct Connect provides.',rule:'TGW + DX gateway = share one DX connection across all accounts. VPC peering = no transitive routing. VPN = public internet, not dedicated.',keywords:'VPC peering = NO transitive routing. A→B→C via peering does NOT work. Use Transit Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'3',category:'EC2',question:'A solutions architect is running an HPC workload across multiple EC2 instances. The application requires tightly-coupled node-to-node communication and is experiencing network latency issues that are degrading performance. What is the MOST suitable solution?',choices:['A|Set up a spread placement group across multiple Availability Zones.','B|Use EC2 Dedicated Instances with an elastic inference accelerator.','C|Set up AWS Direct Connect connections across multiple Availability Zones.','D|Set up a cluster placement group within a single Availability Zone.'],correct:'D',answer:'A cluster placement group instructs AWS to place all instances on hardware that is physically close together — ideally on the same high-bandwidth network switch within a single AZ. This minimizes the network hops between instances and delivers the lowest possible latency.',why:'In a normal EC2 deployment, AWS spreads instances across different physical hosts to reduce correlated failure risk. For HPC workloads where instances constantly communicate with each other (e.g., passing simulation data), this physical distance creates latency. Cluster placement groups override this default and pack instances together. The tradeoff is reduced fault isolation — but for tightly-coupled HPC, performance matters more than HA.',trap:'Spread placement groups do the opposite — they deliberately place instances on separate hardware to reduce correlated failures. This maximizes physical distance and increases latency. Direct Connect is for connecting on-premises networks to AWS, not for communication between EC2 instances.',rule:'Cluster placement = pack together, low latency, one AZ. Spread = separate hardware, fault isolation, max 7/AZ. Partition = large distributed systems.',keywords:'HPC low-latency inter-instance networking → Cluster Placement Group (same rack).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'4',category:'Cost',question:'A large financial firm has several Reserved EC2 instances that were hosting a web application decommissioned last week. To save costs, the team wants to stop incurring charges as soon as possible. What are the TWO most cost-effective steps to take? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Stop the Reserved instances as soon as possible.','B|Terminate the Reserved instances as soon as possible.','C|Go to the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace and sell the Reserved instances.','D|Contact AWS to cancel the AWS subscription.'],correct:'BC',answer:'Terminate the instances immediately to prevent them from being billed at on-demand rates when the RI term expires. Sell the unused Standard Reserved Instances on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace to recoup the remaining prepaid value.',why:'A Reserved Instance is a billing commitment — you prepay for capacity at a discount. The RI itself does not automatically stop anything. When the RI term expires, any running instances it was covering simply revert to on-demand pricing (much more expensive). Even stopped instances can accumulate charges for Elastic IPs. The RI Marketplace lets you sell your unused commitment to another AWS customer, recovering some of the prepaid cost.',trap:'Stopping instances is not enough — stopped instances can be restarted, and when the RI expires the instance will be billed at on-demand rates. Elastic IPs attached to stopped instances also incur charges. You cannot "cancel" a subscription to fix this.',rule:'RI expiry → on-demand pricing for any covered instance. Terminate + sell on RI Marketplace = cleanest exit. Stopping ≠ no charges.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'5',category:'Database',question:'An application runs on an Aurora provisioned DB cluster. Traffic spikes during flash sales overwhelm the database. The team wants to migrate to Aurora Serverless with the LEAST amount of downtime and impact to the running application.',choices:['A|Change the Aurora instance class to Serverless in the RDS console.','B|Take a snapshot of the DB cluster and use it to create a new Aurora Serverless DB cluster.','C|Use AWS Database Migration Service to migrate data to a new Aurora Serverless database.','D|Add an Aurora Replica, set its instance class to Serverless, then failover and promote it.'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS DMS continuously replicates all changes from the source Aurora cluster to the new Aurora Serverless target while both databases are running. The source stays fully operational throughout the migration. The final cutover window is minimal because the target is always in sync.',why:'DMS works by reading the source database\'s transaction logs (CDC — Change Data Capture) and applying every insert, update, and delete to the target in near-real-time. This means the migration happens invisibly in the background while your application runs normally. When you\'re ready to cut over, the gap between source and target is only seconds, minimizing downtime to essentially zero.',trap:'There is no in-place conversion from Provisioned to Serverless in Aurora — you cannot change the instance class. A snapshot restore requires stopping application writes during the new cluster creation, causing significant downtime. Aurora Replicas cannot use a Serverless instance class.',rule:'Provisioned → Serverless = must create a new cluster. DMS CDC = live migration, near-zero downtime. Snapshot restore = offline migration.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'6',category:'Storage',question:'A financial company stores regulatory data in S3 Glacier. Compliance requires that a surprise audit can occur at any time and data must be retrievable within 15 minutes under ALL circumstances. The solution must support up to 150 MB/s of retrieval throughput. Which TWO options satisfy this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Standard Retrieval.','B|Use Expedited Retrieval.','C|Use Bulk Retrieval.','D|Purchase Provisioned Retrieval Capacity.'],correct:'BD',answer:'Expedited Retrieval delivers archived data in 1–5 minutes for archives under 250 MB, satisfying the 15-minute SLA. Provisioned Capacity guarantees that Expedited retrieval capacity is always available — without it, Expedited requests can be rejected during high-demand periods.',why:'S3 Glacier stores data in a distributed archive system. Retrievals are not instant — Glacier needs to reassemble data from its distributed storage. Expedited retrieval is a higher-priority queue that AWS serves within minutes. However, this queue can fill up during high-demand periods, causing rejections. Provisioned Capacity reserves dedicated capacity in the Expedited queue for your account — essentially buying a guaranteed slot. Each unit provides at least 3 retrievals per 5 minutes and up to 150 MB/s.',trap:'Standard retrieval takes 3–5 hours — far too slow for a 15-minute audit requirement. Bulk retrieval takes 5–12 hours and is also incompatible with Provisioned Capacity. Without Provisioned Capacity, Expedited is best-effort and can fail under high demand — which violates the "under ALL circumstances" requirement.',rule:'Expedited = 1–5 min, best-effort. Provisioned Capacity = guarantees Expedited is always available. Bulk = cheapest but 5–12 hours, incompatible with provisioned capacity.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'7',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A solutions architect is deploying a complex CloudFormation stack that provisions Microsoft Active Directory, SQL Server, and SharePoint on EC2 instances. The stack must not proceed to completion until all software is fully installed and configured on the instances. Which approach should be used?',choices:['A|Use the DependsOn attribute and send a success signal with the cfn-init helper script.','B|Use a CreationPolicy attribute on the instances and send a success signal with the cfn-signal helper script.','C|Use an UpdatePolicy attribute on the instances and send a success signal with the cfn-signal helper script.','D|Use the UpdateReplacePolicy attribute and send a success signal with the cfn-signal helper script.'],correct:'B',answer:'CreationPolicy tells CloudFormation to hold the resource in CREATE_IN_PROGRESS state until it receives a specified number of success signals via cfn-signal. The bootstrap scripts run, install and configure the software, then call cfn-signal to send the success signal. Only then does CloudFormation mark the resource as CREATE_COMPLETE.',why:'CloudFormation knows when an EC2 instance has launched (the API call returned successfully) but it has no visibility into what\'s happening inside the instance. CreationPolicy + cfn-signal creates a communication channel: the instance reports back when it\'s truly ready. Without this, CloudFormation marks the instance complete as soon as it starts booting — while software is still installing. The timeout on CreationPolicy ensures the stack fails gracefully if installation takes too long.',trap:'DependsOn controls the order that CloudFormation creates resources — it does not wait for in-instance processes. cfn-init runs configuration commands inside an instance but cannot send a signal to CloudFormation. UpdatePolicy applies during stack updates (like rolling deployments to Auto Scaling groups), not during initial creation.',rule:'CreationPolicy + cfn-signal = wait for in-instance readiness. DependsOn = resource creation order only. cfn-init = runs commands, cannot signal CloudFormation.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'8',category:'Serverless',question:'A company wants to deploy an application packaged as a Docker image stored in Amazon ECR. The architecture must be fully serverless and the application needs 5 GB of temporary storage during execution for data processing. What is the correct deployment option?',choices:['A|Deploy to an ECS cluster using AWS Fargate tasks.','B|Deploy using Lambda with container image support and configure ephemeral storage to 5 GB.','C|Deploy using Lambda with container image support and attach an Amazon EFS volume.','D|Deploy to an ECS cluster with EC2 worker nodes and attach a 5 GB EBS volume.'],correct:'B',answer:'Lambda with container image support lets you package your function as a Docker image up to 10 GB, stored in ECR. You configure ephemeral /tmp storage from 512 MB up to 10 GB. It is fully managed and serverless — no servers, clusters, or task definitions to manage.',why:'Lambda\'s serverless model means AWS manages all the underlying infrastructure. When invoked, Lambda pulls your container image, spins up an execution environment, runs your handler, and tears it down when done. The ephemeral /tmp storage is a local disk allocation that exists only for the duration of the invocation and is wiped clean afterward — perfect for temporary processing. You are billed only for the milliseconds your code runs.',trap:'ECS with Fargate is often described as "serverless" but you still manage task definitions, clusters, services, and networking — it\'s server-optional, not serverless. Attaching EFS to Lambda provides persistent shared storage that survives across invocations, which adds unnecessary complexity when you only need temporary per-invocation storage. EC2 worker nodes are explicitly server-based.',rule:'Lambda = truly serverless, no infrastructure management. ECS Fargate = no EC2 management but still cluster/service management. Lambda /tmp = ephemeral, up to 10 GB. EFS = persistent.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'9',category:'S3',question:'A company needs to track all objects added to an S3 bucket and all objects removed — including when versioned objects are permanently deleted. Notifications must be published to both an SQS queue and an SNS topic. Which configuration is correct?',choices:['A|Configure s3:ObjectCreated:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:Delete events, publishing to SQS and SNS.','B|Configure s3:ObjectAdded:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:* events, publishing to SQS and Amazon MQ.','C|Configure s3:ObjectCreated:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated events, publishing to SQS and SNS.','D|Configure s3:ObjectCreated:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated events, publishing to SQS and Amazon MQ.'],correct:'A',answer:'s3:ObjectCreated:* fires for all object creation operations (PUT, POST, Copy, CompleteMultipartUpload). s3:ObjectRemoved:Delete fires when a non-versioned object is deleted AND when a versioned object is permanently deleted. SQS and SNS are both supported notification destinations.',why:'S3 versioning creates a distinction between two types of deletion. A soft delete creates a delete marker (a zero-byte placeholder that hides the object). A hard delete permanently removes a specific version. The DeleteMarkerCreated event type only fires for soft deletes. The Delete event type fires for both non-versioned deletes and hard deletes of versioned objects. Since the requirement includes permanent deletions, you need s3:ObjectRemoved:Delete.',trap:'There is no s3:ObjectAdded:* event type — it is s3:ObjectCreated:*. DeleteMarkerCreated only covers soft deletes on versioned objects, missing permanent deletions. Amazon MQ is a managed message broker (ActiveMQ/RabbitMQ) — it is not a supported S3 event destination. Only SQS, SNS, and Lambda are.',rule:'ObjectRemoved:Delete = permanent deletes + non-versioned deletes. DeleteMarkerCreated = soft deletes only. S3 notification destinations: SQS, SNS, Lambda only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'10',category:'Security',question:'A Lambda function needs to decrypt files stored in Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP that are protected by a KMS customer managed key. What must be configured to allow the Lambda function to decrypt the files?',choices:['A|Attach kms:Decrypt to the Lambda execution role. Add a KMS key policy statement granting the execution role kms:Decrypt.','B|Attach kms:Decrypt to the Lambda resource policy. Add a KMS key policy statement granting the resource policy ARN kms:Decrypt.','C|Attach kms:Decrypt to the Lambda execution role. Add a KMS key policy statement granting the Lambda function ARN kms:Decrypt.','D|Attach kms:Decrypt to the Lambda resource policy. Add a KMS key policy statement granting the execution role kms:Decrypt.'],correct:'A',answer:'Lambda functions interact with other AWS services using their execution role, not their own function identity. The execution role needs kms:Decrypt in its IAM policy. Additionally, KMS customer managed keys require an explicit grant in the key policy — IAM permissions alone are not sufficient unless the key policy enables IAM.',why:'There are two separate permission systems at work. The IAM policy on the execution role controls what the role is allowed to do. The KMS key policy controls who is allowed to use that specific key. Both must allow the action for it to succeed. The key policy principal must be the execution role ARN because that is the identity Lambda actually uses when making API calls — not the function ARN itself.',trap:'The Lambda resource policy controls who can invoke the Lambda function (e.g., API Gateway, S3 events) — it has nothing to do with what the function can do when running. Using the Lambda function ARN instead of the execution role ARN in the key policy will fail because Lambda assumes the execution role when making AWS API calls.',rule:'Lambda calls AWS services as its execution role. KMS key policy principal = execution role ARN. Resource policy = who invokes Lambda. Execution role = what Lambda can do.',keywords:'Linux + Windows sharing same file system → FSx for NetApp ONTAP (NFS + SMB + iSCSI).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'11',category:'Route 53',question:'An international money transfer service is deployed across multiple AWS Regions. All resources should actively serve traffic at the same time. When a resource becomes unhealthy, Route 53 should automatically stop routing to it. Which configuration achieves this?',choices:['A|Configure Active-Active Failover with a Weighted routing policy.','B|Configure Active-Passive Failover with Weighted records.','C|Configure Active-Active Failover with one Primary and one Secondary resource.','D|Configure Active-Passive Failover with Multiple Primary and Secondary resources.'],correct:'A',answer:'Active-Active failover keeps all healthy records actively serving traffic simultaneously. Route 53 uses health checks to monitor each endpoint and automatically removes unhealthy ones from DNS responses. A Weighted routing policy distributes traffic across all active resources.',why:'Route 53 has two fundamentally different failover models. Active-Active means all resources serve traffic at the same time — you use any routing policy except the Failover policy. Active-Passive means a primary group serves traffic while a secondary group sits idle in standby, only activated when all primary resources fail. The Failover routing policy is what creates Active-Passive behavior. Since this service needs all resources active simultaneously, you must not use the Failover routing policy.',trap:'Active-Passive keeps a secondary group on standby — resources are not all active at the same time, which fails the requirement. You cannot configure Active-Active with a designated Primary and Secondary — that concept belongs to Active-Passive. Active-Active has no primary/secondary distinction.',rule:'Active-Active = all resources serve traffic, use ANY policy except Failover. Active-Passive = primary/standby, uses the Failover routing policy.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'12',category:'Security',question:'A travel company hosts dozens of different domains behind an Application Load Balancer and needs to serve HTTPS for all of them. New domains are added frequently. The solution must not require reauthenticating or reprovisioning certificates when adding new domains. What is the MOST cost-effective approach?',choices:['A|Use a wildcard certificate to handle multiple sub-domains and different domains.','B|Add a Subject Alternative Name (SAN) for each additional domain to a single certificate.','C|Upload all SSL certificates to the ALB and bind multiple certificates to the same HTTPS listener using SNI.','D|Use CloudFront with dedicated IP addresses to associate alternate domain names with each edge location.'],correct:'C',answer:'ALB supports multiple certificates on a single HTTPS listener. When a client connects, it includes the hostname in the TLS ClientHello message (SNI — Server Name Indication). The ALB reads the SNI hostname and selects the matching certificate automatically. Adding a new domain requires only uploading its certificate — no other changes needed.',why:'Before SNI, HTTPS required one IP address per certificate because the server had to present a certificate before knowing which domain the client was requesting. SNI solved this by having the client announce the target hostname during the TLS handshake, before the certificate is selected. ALB leverages SNI to serve many different domain certificates from a single listener on a single IP, with no extra cost.',trap:'A wildcard certificate (*.example.com) covers only subdomains of a single apex domain — it cannot cover entirely different domains. SAN certificates can cover multiple domains but must be reprovisioned every time a new domain is added, violating the requirement. CloudFront with dedicated IPs works but incurs an additional monthly charge per distribution.',rule:'ALB + SNI = multiple different domains, one listener, no reprovisioning, free. Wildcard = subdomains only. SAN = reprovisioning required per new domain.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'13',category:'IAM',question:'A company has 300 IAM users. Management has introduced a new policy requiring updated S3 permissions for 100 specific users. What is the MOST operationally efficient way to apply the new permissions?',choices:['A|Create a new policy and apply it to each of the 100 IAM users using a shell script.','B|Create a new IAM Group, add the 100 users to it, and attach the policy to the group.','C|Create a new S3 bucket access policy with the required permissions for each IAM user.','D|Create a new IAM Role and add each of the 100 users to the IAM Role.'],correct:'B',answer:'An IAM Group is a collection of users. Policies attached to the group are automatically inherited by all members. To change permissions for all 100 users, update the group policy once. To add or remove access for a user, simply add or remove them from the group.',why:'IAM Groups exist precisely for this use case — managing permissions for sets of users centrally. Without groups, you would need to attach policies to each user individually, and any future changes require repeating that process 100 times. Groups create a single control point: one policy update propagates to all members instantly.',trap:'A shell script applying policies per user works once but creates a maintenance burden — every future permission change requires re-running scripts and there is no single place to see what permissions these users have. IAM Roles cannot have users "added" to them — roles are assumed by entities (services, applications, cross-account principals) for temporary access, not assigned as persistent membership like groups.',rule:'IAM Group = permanent membership, shared policies, easy to manage at scale. IAM Role = assumed temporarily by services or cross-account. Never "add users to a role."',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'14',category:'S3',question:'A company in Account A needs to copy multiple S3 objects to a bucket owned by Account B. After the copy, Account B must own the objects — not Account A. How should the solutions architect configure this?',choices:['A|Enable the Requester Pays feature on the source bucket so Account B pays for the transfer, making it the owner.','B|Configure cross-account IAM permissions and have an Account B IAM identity perform the copy operation.','C|Set up Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) on the source bucket to allow Account B to access the objects.','D|Connect both buckets to Amazon WorkDocs and use cross-account access to copy and reassign ownership.'],correct:'B',answer:'S3 object ownership is determined by who uploads the object. By granting Account B IAM permissions to read from Account A\'s bucket and write to its own bucket, and having an Account B identity execute the copy, Account B becomes the uploader and therefore the owner.',why:'This is a fundamental S3 ownership rule: the account that performs the PUT operation owns the object. If Account A copies objects to Account B\'s bucket, Account A is still the uploader and retains ownership — even though the objects live in Account B\'s bucket. This matters because bucket policies only apply to objects owned by the bucket\'s account. The setup requires: (1) a bucket policy on Account A\'s source bucket allowing Account B to read, (2) an IAM policy in Account B granting the copy operation, (3) Account B performing the copy.',trap:'Requester Pays shifts who pays the data transfer cost — it has absolutely nothing to do with object ownership. CORS is a web browser security mechanism for cross-origin HTTP requests — it is not relevant to cross-account S3 operations. Amazon WorkDocs is a document collaboration tool with no S3 cross-account integration.',rule:'Object owner = whoever uploads (the PUT requester). Account B must perform the copy to own the objects. Requester Pays = billing only.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'15',category:'Kinesis',question:'A media company needs to collect gigabytes of data per second from websites and social media feeds and process it in real time. The solution must support reading records in batches and have a built-in enhanced fan-out feature. Which service should be used?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 with Amazon Athena for real-time analysis.','B|AWS Data Exchange.','C|Amazon Kinesis Data Streams.','D|Amazon Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka (MSK).'],correct:'C',answer:'Kinesis Data Streams ingests streaming data with millisecond latency and supports multiple consumers reading in parallel. Lambda can read records in batches of up to 10,000 records per shard. Enhanced fan-out gives each registered consumer a dedicated 2 MB/s read throughput per shard.',why:'Think of KDS as a highway with lanes called shards. Producers write data into shards continuously. Consumers read from shards — by default, all consumers share the 2 MB/s read throughput per shard. Enhanced fan-out changes this: each registered consumer gets its own dedicated 2 MB/s per shard, pushed from the stream (rather than polled). This allows many independent consumers to read the same data simultaneously without competing for bandwidth. Data retention is 24 hours by default, extendable up to 365 days.',trap:'S3 + Athena is a batch analytics system — Athena runs SQL queries over data already stored in S3. It cannot process streaming data in real time. MSK (managed Kafka) is a powerful streaming platform but requires significant operational knowledge, has no built-in enhanced fan-out equivalent, and is much more complex to manage. AWS Data Exchange is a marketplace for buying and selling data, not a streaming service.',rule:'KDS = real-time (ms latency), enhanced fan-out (dedicated throughput per consumer), Lambda batch reading. Retention: 24h default, up to 365 days. Firehose = near-real-time delivery only.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'16',category:'Database',question:'A reporting application is causing performance issues on the primary RDS database due to heavy read traffic. A solutions architect recommends RDS Read Replicas over Multi-AZ. Which TWO benefits of Read Replicas justify this recommendation? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Read Replicas elastically scale out read capacity beyond a single DB instance.','B|Read Replicas allow both read and write operations to complement the primary.','C|Read Replicas provide asynchronous replication and offload read-heavy workloads from the primary.','D|Read Replicas provide synchronous replication and automatic failover.'],correct:'AC',answer:'Read Replicas scale out read capacity by allowing the application to direct read queries to replica instances instead of the primary, distributing the load. The replication uses the database engine\'s native asynchronous replication, which keeps the replicas updated without adding write latency to the primary.',why:'The root cause in this scenario is that the primary DB is overwhelmed by read queries from the reporting application. A Read Replica creates a copy of the database that is kept in sync asynchronously (a slight lag, but typically sub-second). The reporting application can be pointed at the replica instead of the primary, completely offloading that read traffic. You can create up to 15 Read Replicas in some engines. Multi-AZ, by contrast, has a standby that cannot serve reads — its sole purpose is automatic failover for high availability.',trap:'Read Replicas are read-only by default — you cannot perform writes on them. Synchronous replication and automatic failover describe Multi-AZ specifically. Multi-AZ standby instances cannot serve read traffic — they exist only for failover.',rule:'Read Replica = async, read-only, scales reads, can be promoted. Multi-AZ = sync replication (non-Aurora), standby not readable, automatic failover for HA.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'17',category:'Security',question:'A company uses AWS Organizations to give each developer their own AWS account. Pre-configured AWS Config rules must be enforced in all accounts. Developers — even those with administrator access — must not be able to modify or delete these Config rules. What is the correct solution with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Use an IAM Role in each account with a trust relationship that disables root user access to AWS Config.','B|Add developer accounts to an OU and attach an SCP that restricts AWS Config actions.','C|Configure an AWS Config rule in the root account to detect changes to Config rules in member accounts.','D|Set up AWS Control Tower to detect if there were any changes to Config rules in member accounts.'],correct:'B',answer:'SCPs define the maximum permission boundary for every principal in an account — including account administrators and the root user. An SCP attached to the OU that denies all Config-related actions means no user in those accounts can modify or delete Config rules, regardless of their IAM permissions.',why:'IAM policies work by granting permissions — if an IAM policy says Allow, the action is permitted. SCPs work differently: they set a ceiling on what IAM can grant. Even if an IAM policy says Allow AdministratorAccess, if the SCP says Deny config:Delete*, the action is blocked. This is why SCPs are the right tool for organization-wide compliance enforcement. Crucially, SCPs also apply to the root user — something IAM policies cannot do.',trap:'IAM policies (including trust relationships) cannot restrict the root user — root bypasses all IAM restrictions. AWS Config rules and Control Tower can detect when changes have been made, but detection is reactive — they cannot prevent the action from happening in the first place.',rule:'SCPs = maximum permission ceiling, override IAM, apply to root user. IAM cannot restrict root. Control Tower/Config = detect drift, cannot prevent actions.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'18',category:'S3',question:'A company stores confidential financial files in AWS that are accessed every week. The architect must set up storage that uses envelope encryption, automates key rotation, and provides an audit trail showing who used the encryption key and when. Which TWO actions should the architect implement in the most cost-effective way? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Amazon S3 to store the data.','B|Use Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive to store the data.','C|Configure Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys (SSE-C).','D|Configure Server-Side Encryption with Amazon S3-Managed Keys (SSE-S3).','E|Configure Server-Side Encryption with AWS KMS Keys (SSE-KMS).'],correct:'AE',answer:'Amazon S3 is the correct tier for weekly-accessed data. SSE-KMS uses AWS KMS to implement envelope encryption, supports automatic annual key rotation, and every use of the KMS key is logged in AWS CloudTrail — providing the complete audit trail of who used the key and when.',why:'Envelope encryption means the data is encrypted with a data key, and that data key is itself encrypted with a master key (the KMS key). S3 generates a unique data key per object. KMS manages the master key, handles key rotation, and logs every API call (Encrypt, Decrypt, GenerateDataKey) to CloudTrail. This gives you a complete, tamper-proof record of key usage. SSE-S3 also encrypts data but manages everything internally — no CloudTrail logging of key usage, no audit trail.',trap:'S3 Glacier Deep Archive is designed for data accessed once or twice per year — retrieval takes 12–48 hours and costs money. Weekly access makes it inappropriate and expensive. SSE-C requires you to manage and supply the key on every request — no audit trail. SSE-S3 handles encryption automatically but provides no key usage audit trail.',rule:'SSE-KMS = envelope encryption + auto key rotation + CloudTrail audit trail. SSE-S3 = automatic, no audit trail. Glacier Deep Archive = archive only, 12-48hr retrieval.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'19',category:'S3',question:'A company has stored 200 TB of backup files in Amazon S3 in a vendor-proprietary format. The solutions architect needs to use the vendor\'s file conversion software to retrieve the files, transform them to an industry-standard format, and re-upload them to S3. The solution must minimize data transfer costs. Which option is correct?',choices:['A|Install the file conversion software in Amazon S3. Use S3 Batch Operations to perform data transformation.','B|Export the data using AWS Snowball Edge. Install the conversion software on the device. Transform and re-upload.','C|Deploy an EC2 instance in a different Region. Install the conversion software. Transform and re-upload to S3.','D|Deploy an EC2 instance in the same Region as Amazon S3. Install the conversion software. Transform and re-upload.'],correct:'D',answer:'Data transferred between EC2 and S3 within the same AWS Region is free. By deploying the EC2 instance in the same region as the S3 bucket, you can download 200 TB, process it, and re-upload 200 TB with zero data transfer charges.',why:'AWS charges for data that leaves a region (egress). Data moving between services within the same region is generally free. If you put the EC2 instance in a different region, you pay egress charges for 200 TB out of S3 and then again for 200 TB back in — on 200 TB that is a very large bill. Same-region placement eliminates both charges entirely.',trap:'You cannot install custom software directly inside S3 — S3 is an object store, not a compute environment. S3 Batch Operations runs S3-native operations (like copying, tagging, restoring) but cannot execute custom vendor software. Snowball Edge is for transferring data to/from on-premises environments — the data is already in S3, so Snowball adds unnecessary complexity.',rule:'EC2 ↔ S3 same region = free data transfer. EC2 ↔ S3 different region = charged both directions. Same-region = always the cheapest approach for large data processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'20',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has over 100 Windows and Linux EC2 instances in production. Each month, the SysOps team must audit all instances for performance issues by collecting system logs and analyzing them. The results must be retained in S3. What is the most efficient solution with minimal effort?',choices:['A|Install the unified CloudWatch Logs agent on each instance to collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs. Analyze with CloudWatch Logs Insights.','B|Install AWS SDK on each instance and write a custom daemon script to push data to CloudWatch Logs periodically.','C|Install the AWS Systems Manager Agent on each instance to collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs. Analyze with CloudWatch Logs Insights.','D|Install AWS Inspector Agent on each instance to collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs. Use a CloudWatch dashboard to analyze log data.'],correct:'A',answer:'The unified CloudWatch Logs agent is a single agent that collects both logs and system metrics from Windows and Linux instances. It streams data to CloudWatch Logs automatically. CloudWatch Logs Insights provides a purpose-built query language to interactively search and analyze logs across all instances.',why:'The unified agent replaced the older CloudWatch Logs agent and added support for Windows, custom metrics, and better performance. You configure it once via a JSON config file (which can be pushed centrally via SSM Parameter Store) and it continuously ships logs. CloudWatch Logs Insights runs SQL-like queries across all log groups simultaneously — you can identify patterns, errors, and performance issues across 100+ instances in seconds. Results can be exported to S3.',trap:'A custom SDK daemon script requires development time, testing, and maintenance — high effort. SSM Agent is already installed on most instances and can run commands, but it is not designed for continuous log collection — CloudWatch Agent is more efficient and purpose-built for this. AWS Inspector is a security vulnerability assessment service, not a log collection tool.',rule:'Unified CloudWatch Agent = logs + metrics, Windows + Linux, one agent. CloudWatch Logs Insights = interactive log queries across all instances. Inspector = security assessment only.',keywords:'Memory/disk/swap metrics = NOT default CW. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'21',category:'Database',question:'An organization is migrating from Microsoft SQL Server to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL. They want to minimize changes to their application code. Which TWO actions should be taken? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use AWS AppConfig to manage configuration updates during the migration.','B|Turn on Babelfish on Aurora PostgreSQL to allow applications to continue using existing SQL queries.','C|Use AWS Schema Conversion Tool (SCT) to convert the schema and AWS DMS to migrate the data.','D|Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time data replication to Aurora PostgreSQL.','E|Use AWS Glue to transform SQL queries from applications for compatibility with Aurora PostgreSQL.'],correct:'BC',answer:'Babelfish translates T-SQL (SQL Server\'s dialect) into PostgreSQL SQL, allowing applications written for SQL Server to run against Aurora PostgreSQL with minimal or no code changes. AWS SCT converts the database schema from SQL Server format to Aurora PostgreSQL format, and DMS migrates the actual data.',why:'SQL Server uses T-SQL which has different syntax, data types, and stored procedure conventions from PostgreSQL. Normally, migrating between these engines requires rewriting application queries, stored procedures, and views. Babelfish is an Aurora PostgreSQL extension that adds a SQL Server-compatible endpoint — your application connects to it using SQL Server drivers and sends T-SQL, and Babelfish translates it to PostgreSQL internally. SCT then handles converting the schema automatically.',trap:'AWS AppConfig manages application configuration deployments (feature flags, settings) — it has nothing to do with database schema conversion. Kinesis Data Streams is for real-time event streaming and is not a database replication tool. AWS Glue is an ETL service for data pipelines and cannot transform application-level SQL queries to be compatible with a different database engine.',rule:'Babelfish = T-SQL translation layer on Aurora PostgreSQL, minimizes app changes. SCT = schema conversion. DMS = data migration. These three = complete SQL Server → Aurora migration toolkit.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'22',category:'Networking',question:'A company needs to process real-time streaming data from globally-distributed users for clickstream analysis on their website and mobile apps. The solution must process data in close geographical proximity to users and respond at low latency. Which solution is most suitable?',choices:['A|Use CloudFront and Route 53 with a latency-based routing policy. Process streaming data using Kinesis and store results in S3.','B|Integrate CloudFront with Lambda@Edge. Process real-time streaming data using Amazon Athena and store results in S3.','C|Use CloudFront and Route 53 with a Geoproximity routing policy. Process streaming data using Kinesis and store results in S3.','D|Integrate CloudFront with Lambda@Edge. Process real-time streaming data using Kinesis and store results in S3.'],correct:'D',answer:'Lambda@Edge runs your code at CloudFront edge locations — over 400 points of presence worldwide — closest to each user. This provides geographically proximate, low-latency processing. Kinesis handles the real-time streaming data ingestion and processing, and S3 provides durable storage for results.',why:'Lambda@Edge is triggered by CloudFront events (viewer request, origin request, etc.) and runs in the AWS edge location nearest to the user. This means computation happens close to where the request originates, reducing round-trip latency. For global clickstream data, users in Tokyo get processed in a Tokyo edge location, users in London in a London edge location. Kinesis then ingests the processed streaming data and performs real-time analytics.',trap:'Route 53 routing policies (latency-based or Geoproximity) only influence DNS resolution — they route traffic to different endpoints but have no compute capability. They cannot process data near users, only direct requests to different servers. Athena is an interactive query service for data already stored in S3, not a real-time stream processor.',rule:'Lambda@Edge = run compute at CloudFront edge, near users globally. Route 53 = DNS routing only, no compute. Athena = batch SQL on S3, not real-time streaming.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'23',category:'EC2',question:'A company plans to migrate all its on-premises VM workloads (Windows and Linux) to AWS using a lift-and-shift strategy. The company wants to minimize downtime during migration. Which solution should the solutions architect implement?',choices:['A|Export the on-premises VMs, upload images to S3, and use VM Import/Export to launch them as EC2 instances.','B|Install the AWS Replication Agent on each on-premises VM to continuously replicate to AWS. Use AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) to launch test instances and perform cutover.','C|Use AWS Application Discovery Service for lift-and-shift migrations. Deploy the Discovery Agent to start replication. Launch EC2 instances from the created AMIs.','D|Use AWS DataSync to migrate VM workloads. Deploy the DataSync agent on-premises. Launch EC2 instances from the created AMIs.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS MGN is the recommended lift-and-shift service. The Replication Agent installs on each source server and continuously syncs changes to AWS staging servers. Because replication is continuous, the source servers stay fully operational and the AWS target is always up to date. Test instances can be launched at any time, and the final cutover window is just minutes.',why:'The key to minimizing downtime is continuous replication. MGN uses block-level replication — it copies every disk write from the source server to AWS in real time. When you\'re ready to cut over, you launch the cutover instance from AWS\'s latest staging server image. Because the data is already replicated, the cutover is fast. You can run non-disruptive tests beforehand to validate that workloads run correctly on AWS without impacting production.',trap:'VM Import/Export requires you to manually export VMs, upload them to S3, and import — the VMs will be significantly out of date by the time the upload completes (especially for large VMs), causing data loss. AWS Application Discovery Service tracks and assesses migration status but cannot perform actual replication. DataSync is designed to transfer files and data, not to replicate virtual machines.',rule:'AWS MGN = primary lift-and-shift service, continuous block-level replication, minimal downtime. VM Import/Export = one-time snapshot import, significant downtime. DataSync = file/data transfer, not VM migration.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'24',category:'Networking',question:'A startup is building a multiplayer game that uses UDP for communication between clients and game servers. User data will be stored in a key-value store. The solution must distribute traffic across multiple game servers. Which combination is correct?',choices:['A|Distribute traffic using Application Load Balancer and store data in Amazon DynamoDB.','B|Distribute traffic using Network Load Balancer and store data in Amazon Aurora.','C|Distribute traffic using Application Load Balancer and store data in Amazon RDS.','D|Distribute traffic using Network Load Balancer and store data in Amazon DynamoDB.'],correct:'D',answer:'Network Load Balancer operates at Layer 4 (transport layer) and supports UDP natively. For UDP flows, NLB uses a flow hash algorithm based on source/destination IP and port to consistently route a session to the same game server. DynamoDB is a key-value and document store — exactly the data model described.',why:'The OSI model layers matter here. Application Load Balancer operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS only) — it understands HTTP headers, paths, and hostnames. UDP is a Layer 4 protocol that has no HTTP headers, so ALB simply cannot handle UDP traffic. NLB at Layer 4 handles raw TCP and UDP packets. For gaming, UDP is preferred because it has lower overhead than TCP — dropped packets are acceptable but latency is not. DynamoDB\'s key-value model is perfect for gaming data like player state, scores, and sessions.',trap:'ALB does not support UDP — this eliminates options A and C entirely. Aurora and RDS are relational databases with a tabular model — they are not designed as key-value stores and would be unnecessarily complex and expensive for simple key-value gaming data.',rule:'UDP traffic = Network Load Balancer (Layer 4). ALB = Layer 7 HTTP/HTTPS only, cannot handle UDP. Key-value store = DynamoDB.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'25',category:'EC2',question:'A High Performance Computing cluster uses EC2 instances with Provisioned IOPS (io1) volumes for transaction-intensive, low-latency workloads. The volume size is 10 GiB. The architect must maintain high IOPS while keeping latency down. Which configuration is correct?',choices:['A|Set the IOPS to 400 then maintain a low queue length.','B|Set the IOPS to 500 then maintain a low queue length.','C|Set the IOPS to 600 then maintain a high queue length.','D|Set the IOPS to 800 then maintain a low queue length.'],correct:'B',answer:'The maximum IOPS for an io1 volume is 50 IOPS per GiB. A 10 GiB volume can be provisioned with a maximum of 500 IOPS (50 × 10 = 500). For transaction-intensive, low-latency workloads, maintain a low I/O queue length — this prevents I/O requests from backing up, which would increase latency.',why:'The 50:1 ratio is a hard limit AWS enforces to ensure you provision IOPS proportionally to storage size. Setting 400 IOPS is valid but leaves performance on the table. Queue length is the number of pending I/O requests waiting to be served. For low-latency transaction workloads (databases, OLTP), you want each I/O to be served immediately — a low queue length achieves this. For throughput-intensive workloads (large sequential reads/writes like video streaming), a high queue length keeps the I/O pipeline full and maximizes throughput.',trap:'600 and 800 IOPS both exceed the 500 IOPS maximum for a 10 GiB io1 volume — these cannot be provisioned. A high queue length is appropriate for throughput-intensive HDD-backed workloads (st1, sc1), not for low-latency transaction workloads.',rule:'io1 max IOPS = 50 × volume GiB. 10 GiB = 500 max. Transaction workloads = low queue length. Throughput workloads = high queue length.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'26',category:'Networking',question:'A company has a web-based order processing system using a standard SQS queue. The IT manager notices many orders are being processed twice, causing customer issues. What solution prevents duplicate processing?',choices:['A|Alter the retention period in SQS.','B|Alter the visibility timeout of SQS.','C|Use an Amazon SQS FIFO Queue instead.','D|Change the message size in SQS.'],correct:'C',answer:'SQS FIFO queues guarantee exactly-once processing using message deduplication IDs. When a producer sends a message, FIFO checks the deduplication ID — if the same ID was sent within the last 5 minutes, the duplicate is discarded. Each message is processed exactly once.',why:'Standard SQS is designed for high throughput and uses an at-least-once delivery model. "At least once" means AWS guarantees the message will be delivered but may occasionally deliver it more than once (due to network retries, distributed system edge cases). FIFO queues sacrifice some throughput (300 TPS base, 3,000 with batching) for exactly-once delivery and strict ordering. The deduplication window catches messages sent by retrying producers within a 5-minute window.',trap:'Visibility timeout determines how long a message is hidden from other consumers after being received — it can reduce but not eliminate duplicates. If a consumer receives a message but crashes before deleting it, the message becomes visible again after the timeout and can be received a second time. Retention period controls how long unprocessed messages stay in the queue — irrelevant to duplicates. Message size has nothing to do with duplication.',rule:'Standard SQS = at-least-once delivery, possible duplicates. FIFO SQS = exactly-once delivery, strict ordering, 300 TPS base. Visibility timeout helps but does not guarantee no duplicates.',keywords:'SQS visibility timeout = how long message hidden after receive. Set > max processing time.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'27',category:'EC2',question:'A multinational investment bank requires a minimum of 4 EC2 instances to run its web application at all times to ensure fault tolerance. Which Auto Scaling deployment achieves this?',choices:['A|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 2 instances in each of 3 Availability Zones behind an ALB.','B|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 2 instances in each of 2 Availability Zones behind an ALB.','C|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 4 instances in one Availability Zone behind an ALB.','D|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 1 instance in each of 4 Availability Zones behind an ALB.'],correct:'A',answer:'With 2 instances in each of 3 AZs (6 total), if one entire AZ fails, 4 instances remain running across the other two AZs — exactly meeting the minimum requirement. No other option maintains at least 4 instances after any single AZ failure.',why:'Fault tolerance means the system stays above its minimum operating threshold even after a failure. The test is: what is the worst-case single failure, and do we still meet the minimum? For AZ-based failures: 2×3AZs → lose 1 AZ → 4 remain ✓. 2×2AZs → lose 1 AZ → 2 remain ✗. 4×1AZ → lose 1 AZ → 0 remain ✗. 1×4AZs → lose 1 AZ → 3 remain ✗. Only the 2×3AZ configuration survives a full AZ outage while maintaining the minimum of 4.',trap:'2 instances in 2 AZs gives 4 total but only 2 survive an AZ failure. 4 in 1 AZ gives 0 survivors if that AZ fails. 1 in each of 4 AZs gives only 3 survivors after an AZ failure. The math must work after the failure, not before.',rule:'Fault tolerance math: (instances per AZ × number of AZs) minus (instances in one AZ) ≥ minimum required. Always calculate the post-failure count.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'28',category:'Storage',question:'A company has Linux EC2 instances generating application log files. The audit team needs to collect and process these log files for analysis. Which combination of services is best?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 for storing log files and Amazon EMR for processing them.','B|Amazon S3 Glacier for storing log files and Spot EC2 instances for processing.','C|A single On-Demand EC2 instance for both storing and processing the log files.','D|Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive for storing log files and AWS ParallelCluster for processing.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon S3 provides scalable, durable storage for log files with immediate accessibility. Amazon EMR is a managed big data processing service that runs Apache Hadoop, Spark, Hive, and other frameworks to process and analyze large volumes of log data at scale.',why:'Log files need to be accessible for analysis — they are active data, not archives. S3 standard storage is the right tier. EMR is purpose-built for big data analytics: it spins up a cluster of EC2 instances, runs your analysis jobs (MapReduce, Spark SQL, Hive queries), and terminates the cluster when done. This is cost-efficient because you pay only for the cluster while it is running, and it scales automatically to handle any log volume.',trap:'S3 Glacier and Glacier Deep Archive are archive tiers with slow retrieval (minutes to hours/days) — completely unsuitable for active log analysis. A single EC2 instance is not a scalable storage service and has no built-in big data analytics engine. AWS ParallelCluster is an HPC cluster management tool for scientific computing workloads, not a log analytics service.',rule:'S3 standard = active storage for analysis. EMR = managed big data processing (Hadoop/Spark). Glacier = archive, slow retrieval. EMR = go-to for large-scale log analytics.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'29',category:'Storage',question:'A real-time analytics application uses Lambda to process data and store results in JSON format in S3. The team needs to run sophisticated big data analytics on the data without moving it to a separate system. Which group of services meets this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon Neptune, DynamoDB DAX, Amazon Redshift Spectrum.','B|Amazon X-Ray, Amazon Neptune, DynamoDB.','C|Amazon Glue, Amazon Redshift, Amazon S3.','D|Amazon Athena, Amazon Redshift Spectrum, AWS Glue.'],correct:'D',answer:'Athena queries data directly in S3 using standard SQL — no data movement needed. Redshift Spectrum extends Redshift queries to reach data stored in S3 without loading it into the cluster. AWS Glue catalogs and prepares S3 data for analytics via its Data Catalog and ETL jobs.',why:'The key requirement is analytics on S3 data without moving it. Athena is a serverless query engine that reads S3 files (JSON, CSV, Parquet, ORC) directly. Redshift Spectrum adds an external table feature to Redshift that queries S3 data from within Redshift queries. Glue provides the metadata catalog that both services use to understand the schema of your S3 data. Together they form a complete in-place analytics stack.',trap:'Neptune is a graph database for relationship queries — not for S3 analytics. DynamoDB DAX is a caching layer for DynamoDB reads — irrelevant to S3 analytics. X-Ray is distributed tracing for debugging applications. Standard Redshift requires data to be loaded into its internal cluster storage — it does not query S3 in-place (Redshift Spectrum does, but not standard Redshift).',rule:'Athena = serverless SQL on S3. Redshift Spectrum = query S3 from Redshift without loading. Glue = data catalog + ETL for S3. All three = analytics on S3 in place, no data movement.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'30',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A solutions architect is monitoring an RDS DB instance using Amazon CloudWatch. They need to identify which metrics are gathered specifically by Enhanced Monitoring — not standard CloudWatch metrics. Which TWO are Enhanced Monitoring metrics? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|CPU Utilization','B|Database Connections','C|Freeable Memory','D|RDS child processes','E|OS processes'],correct:'DE',answer:'RDS child processes and OS processes are metrics that only appear in Enhanced Monitoring. They show process-level and OS-level details about what is running inside the DB instance — information that requires an agent installed directly on the instance to collect.',why:'Standard CloudWatch metrics for RDS are collected at the hypervisor level — the virtualization layer beneath the guest OS. This means CloudWatch sees aggregate metrics like total CPU, but cannot see what individual processes inside the OS are doing. Enhanced Monitoring installs an agent on the DB instance itself. This agent reports OS-level metrics: which processes (RDS child processes like mysqld, aurora) are consuming CPU, what OS kernel processes are running, memory per process, and thread-level details.',trap:'CPU Utilization, Database Connections, and Freeable Memory are all standard CloudWatch metrics collected at the hypervisor level — they are available without Enhanced Monitoring. The question specifically asks for Enhanced Monitoring metrics, which are the deeper OS-level and process-level ones.',rule:'Standard CloudWatch RDS = hypervisor-level: CPU, DB Connections, Freeable Memory. Enhanced Monitoring = agent on instance, OS-level: RDS child processes, RDS processes, OS processes.',keywords:'Memory/disk/swap metrics = NOT default CW. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'31',category:'Database',question:'A data analytics company uses a Redshift cluster as their data warehouse. They need a disaster recovery plan that ensures business continuity even if an entire AWS region goes down. What is the best approach?',choices:['A|Create a scheduled job to take Redshift cluster snapshots and store them in S3. Restore if needed.','B|Do nothing — Amazon Redshift is highly available and can withstand an entire region outage.','C|Use automated snapshots of the Redshift cluster.','D|Enable Cross-Region Snapshot Copy on the Amazon Redshift cluster.'],correct:'D',answer:'Cross-Region Snapshot Copy automatically copies all new manual and automated Redshift snapshots to a destination region that you specify. If the source region experiences an outage, you can restore the cluster from the most recent snapshot in the destination region.',why:'Redshift automated snapshots are regional — they are stored in the same region as the cluster. If that region goes down, the snapshots are inaccessible along with the cluster. Cross-Region Snapshot Copy decouples the backup from the primary region by continuously replicating snapshots to a different region. This provides true cross-region DR.',trap:'Automated snapshots alone do not help with a full region outage because the snapshots are in the same region as the cluster. A scheduled job writing to S3 within the same region has the same problem. Redshift is not immune to full regional outages.',rule:'Redshift DR = Cross-Region Snapshot Copy. Automated snapshots = same region only. Cross-region copy = disaster recovery from full region failure.',keywords:'Redshift DR = Cross-Region Snapshot Copy. Automated snapshots = same region only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'32',category:'Security',question:'A database security group currently allows MS SQL connections on port 1433 from any source (0.0.0.0/0). Only the application tier in an Auto Scaling group should be able to connect to the database. What change should be made following least privilege?',choices:['A|Change the Source to the security group ID attached to the application tier.','B|Change the Source to the EC2 instance IDs of the underlying Auto Scaling group instances.','C|Change the Source to the static AnyCast IP address attached to the application tier.','D|Change the Source to the Network ACL ID attached to the application tier.'],correct:'A',answer:'Using the security group ID as the source means any EC2 instance attached to that security group can connect on port 1433. This automatically includes all current and future Auto Scaling instances without any manual changes when the group scales.',why:'Security groups can reference other security groups as the source of traffic. When you do this, AWS evaluates the rule dynamically — if an incoming connection comes from an instance with that security group attached, the rule matches. This is far more robust than IP-based rules for Auto Scaling groups because instance IPs change as the group scales. The security group membership is the stable identifier, not the IP address.',trap:'Using individual EC2 instance IDs in security group rules is not supported — security groups accept IP ranges (CIDR) or other security group IDs as sources. Even if it were possible, new instances added by Auto Scaling would not be covered. AnyCast IP is used with AWS Global Accelerator, not security groups. Network ACL IDs apply at the subnet level and would affect all resources in the subnet, violating least privilege.',rule:'Security group source = another security group ID for dynamic Auto Scaling groups. Automatically covers all current and future group members. Instance IDs and ACL IDs are not valid security group sources.',keywords:'Security group source = other SG ID (covers all current + future ASG members). Not instance IDs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'33',category:'Networking',question:'A company has an ALB that accepts HTTP (port 80) and HTTPS (port 443) traffic. They want all HTTP traffic for a new domain to be automatically redirected to HTTPS. What ALB configuration achieves this?',choices:['A|Create a new HTTP listener on port 80 and add a redirect action to HTTPS on port 443.','B|Configure the existing HTTP listener on port 80 to redirect traffic to port 443.','C|Create a new ALB listener on port 443 and configure it to redirect HTTP traffic to HTTPS.','D|Configure the existing listener on port 443 and add a redirect action to HTTP on port 80.'],correct:'B',answer:'The existing port 80 listener should be modified to add a redirect rule that sends all HTTP requests to HTTPS on port 443. This is done by editing the listener\'s default action to "Redirect" with the target protocol HTTPS and port 443.',why:'ALB listeners are bound to ports. Only one listener can exist per port per ALB. When an HTTP request arrives on port 80, the listener evaluates its rules in order. By setting the default action to redirect to HTTPS:443, every HTTP request is met with a 301 or 302 redirect response pointing to the HTTPS version of the same URL. The browser then re-issues the request over HTTPS on port 443.',trap:'A new HTTP listener on port 80 cannot be created because one already exists — duplicate ports are not allowed on an ALB. Similarly, a new HTTPS listener on port 443 cannot be created. Configuring port 443 to redirect to port 80 reverses the direction — it would send HTTPS users to unencrypted HTTP, which is the opposite of the requirement.',rule:'ALB redirect HTTP→HTTPS: modify the existing port 80 listener default action to redirect to HTTPS:443. Cannot create duplicate listeners on the same port.',keywords:'ALB HTTP→HTTPS redirect: modify existing port 80 listener. Cannot create duplicate port listener.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'34',category:'Security',question:'A financial services company uses Aurora, EFS, and EventBridge with Step Functions. They have implemented IAM Identity Center for user authentication. Data science, engineering, and compliance teams need secure, granular access to Aurora and EFS following least privilege with minimal admin overhead. Which approach is best?',choices:['A|Set up AWS Control Tower with SCPs to restrict Aurora and EFS at the org level. Create IAM roles in each account.','B|Enable IAM Identity Center with an Identity Center directory. Create permission sets for Aurora and EFS. Assign teams to groups linked to specific permission sets.','C|Use Amazon Cognito User Pools for authentication and Cognito Identity Pools for temporary credentials. Create IAM roles for Aurora and EFS per team.','D|Create separate AWS accounts per team using AWS Organizations. Set up cross-account IAM roles.'],correct:'B',answer:'IAM Identity Center permission sets are collections of IAM policies that define what access a user gets. By creating permission sets for each team\'s specific Aurora and EFS needs and assigning team members to groups linked to those sets, you get centralized, role-based access management that integrates with the existing Identity Center deployment.',why:'Since IAM Identity Center is already deployed, extending it with permission sets is the natural path of least resistance. Permission sets are assigned to groups — you add users to groups and they automatically inherit the right permissions. When a team member leaves, remove them from the group. When permissions need to change, update the permission set once. This is far less overhead than managing cross-account roles or separate AWS accounts per team.',trap:'SCPs enforce account-level permission boundaries but cannot grant fine-grained access to specific resources like a particular Aurora cluster or EFS file system. Cognito is designed for end-user authentication in web/mobile applications — it is not integrated with IAM Identity Center and adds complexity. Separate AWS accounts per team creates enormous administrative overhead for what is essentially a permissions problem.',rule:'IAM Identity Center + permission sets = centralized SSO with granular, role-based access. Best when Identity Center is already deployed. SCPs = account-level ceiling, not resource-level access.',keywords:'Event-driven triggers / scheduled jobs → Amazon EventBridge. Direct target: ECS, Lambda, SQS, etc.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'35',category:'Security',question:'A company has a regional API Gateway in us-east-2 serving as a proxy to a backend. They want to associate a custom domain name with HTTPS support. They have a Route 53 hosted zone for the domain. What are the correct steps?',choices:['A|Request a public ACM certificate in us-east-1. Create a regional API Gateway domain name. Create an alias record in Route 53.','B|Import an existing public certificate into ACM in us-east-2. Create a CNAME record in Route 53 pointing to the API Gateway invoke URL.','C|Use ACM Private CA to generate a private certificate. Override the invoke URL using stage variables.','D|Request a public ACM certificate in us-east-2. Create a regional API Gateway domain name associated with the certificate. Create an alias record in Route 53 pointing to the API Gateway domain name.'],correct:'D',answer:'For a regional API Gateway, the ACM certificate must be in the same region as the API — us-east-2. Create the custom domain name in API Gateway, associate it with the ACM certificate, create an API mapping to the stage, then create a Route 53 alias record pointing your custom domain to the API Gateway regional domain name.',why:'There are two types of API Gateway endpoints: regional and edge-optimized. Edge-optimized uses CloudFront, and CloudFront certificates must be in us-east-1. Regional API Gateways bypass CloudFront, so the certificate stays in the API\'s region. The alias record in Route 53 uses the API Gateway\'s own regional domain name (e.g., xxx.execute-api.us-east-2.amazonaws.com) as the alias target — this is more reliable than a CNAME and works for apex domains.',trap:'Requesting the certificate in us-east-1 is only correct for edge-optimized API Gateways — for regional APIs, the cert must be in the same region. A CNAME pointing to the invoke URL bypasses the custom domain name feature entirely. A private certificate from ACM PCA is for internal/private connections, not for public internet HTTPS traffic.',rule:'Regional API Gateway + custom domain: ACM cert must be in the SAME region. Edge-optimized API Gateway: cert must be in us-east-1. Always alias record, not CNAME, in Route 53.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'36',category:'EC2',question:'A company hosts a legacy web application on an On-Demand EC2 instance using an Amazon Instance Store-Backed AMI. The application is being decommissioned and the instance will be terminated. What happens to the data on the root volume when the instance is terminated?',choices:['A|Data is automatically saved as an EBS snapshot.','B|Data is automatically saved as an EBS volume.','C|Data is unavailable until the instance is restarted.','D|Data is automatically deleted.'],correct:'D',answer:'Instance store volumes are ephemeral by design. All data on instance store volumes is permanently and automatically deleted when the instance is terminated, stopped, or if the underlying host hardware fails.',why:'Instance store is directly attached physical storage on the host where your EC2 instance runs. Unlike EBS (which is a network-attached persistent storage service), instance store has no independent existence — it exists only as long as the instance is running on that physical host. AWS designed it this way for temporary data that needs maximum I/O performance without network overhead. The tradeoff is complete impermanence. EBS-backed instances have a separate EBS volume that persists independently.',trap:'The common mistake is confusing Instance Store-backed AMIs with EBS-backed AMIs. EBS-backed instances can have their root volume preserved after termination. Instance store cannot — there is no EBS volume to snapshot or save. The data does not become "unavailable" — it is gone permanently.',rule:'Instance store = ephemeral, permanently deleted on termination or host failure. EBS-backed = persistent by default, survives termination. Key distinction for the exam.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'37',category:'Security',question:'A company must integrate its on-premises LDAP directory service with AWS IAM. The identity store is NOT compatible with SAML 2.0. Which approach is most valid?',choices:['A|Use an IAM policy that references LDAP identifiers and AWS credentials.','B|Use AWS IAM Identity Center to manage access between AWS and LDAP.','C|Develop an on-premises custom identity broker application and use STS to issue short-lived AWS credentials.','D|Use IAM roles to rotate IAM credentials whenever LDAP credentials are updated.'],correct:'C',answer:'When the identity store is not SAML-compatible, a custom identity broker is the solution. The broker authenticates users against LDAP, then calls AWS STS (AssumeRole or GetFederationToken) to obtain temporary security credentials. These temporary credentials are then provided to the user to access AWS resources.',why:'The normal federation path uses SAML 2.0 — the identity provider issues a SAML assertion, which AWS accepts as proof of identity and exchanges for temporary credentials. When SAML is unavailable, you need to write the "translator" yourself: the identity broker handles authentication, talks directly to STS, gets temporary credentials (access key + secret key + session token), and hands them to the user. The credentials automatically expire, so there is no long-term credential to manage or rotate.',trap:'An IAM policy controls authorization (what you can do) not authentication (who you are) — it cannot bridge a connection between LDAP and AWS. IAM Identity Center primarily supports SAML 2.0 identity providers and does not support non-SAML identity stores directly. Manually rotating IAM credentials to mirror LDAP changes is a security antipattern — long-lived credentials that must be manually managed are a risk.',rule:'SAML-compatible IdP = IAM Identity Center or SAML federation. NOT SAML-compatible = custom identity broker + STS for temporary credentials.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'38',category:'S3',question:'An online survey startup has 5 TB of US real estate data in S3 (us-east-1). The data must be shared with a European AWS partner who also uses S3. The startup must keep data transfer costs as low as possible and disable anonymous access. Which solution is most cost-effective?',choices:['A|Enable the Requester Pays feature on the S3 bucket.','B|Enable Cross-Region Replication to copy data to the partner\'s S3 bucket in Europe.','C|Enable cross-account access to allow the partner to download data from the startup\'s bucket.','D|Enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode and set a Legal Hold on each object.'],correct:'A',answer:'Requester Pays shifts all data transfer and request costs from the bucket owner to the requester. The European partner pays for the data they download. As a side effect, Requester Pays automatically disables anonymous access — all requests must include authenticated AWS credentials.',why:'Normally, when someone downloads data from your S3 bucket, you (the bucket owner) pay for the data egress. With Requester Pays, the authentication requirement is enforced because AWS needs to know which account to charge for the transfer. Anonymous requests cannot be charged to anyone, so they are automatically blocked. This is designed exactly for data sharing scenarios where you want others to access your data but not pay for their downloads yourself.',trap:'Cross-Region Replication creates an ongoing copy of all data to another bucket — you pay for both storage and the replication data transfer costs. For 5 TB this is expensive and ongoing. With cross-account access, the startup still pays egress when the partner downloads. S3 Object Lock prevents objects from being deleted or overwritten — it has no effect on transfer costs or access controls.',rule:'Requester Pays = partner pays transfer costs, anonymous access disabled automatically. CRR = you pay for replication transfer. Cross-account = you still pay egress.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'39',category:'Cost',question:'A company is building an automation tool for generating custom reports on its AWS usage. The tool must be able to programmatically access and forecast usage costs on specific services with the LEAST amount of operational overhead. Which solution meets this requirement?',choices:['A|Use the AWS Cost Explorer API with pagination to programmatically retrieve usage cost-related data.','B|Configure AWS Budgets to send usage cost data to the company via Amazon SNS.','C|Generate AWS Budgets reports for usage cost data and deliver them via Amazon SQS.','D|Download AWS Cost Explorer report CSV files to access cost data. Predict usage costs using AWS Budgets.'],correct:'A',answer:'The Cost Explorer API provides programmatic access to historical cost and usage data, cost forecasts, and granular breakdowns by service, region, tag, or account. It supports pagination to retrieve large datasets and can be integrated directly into automation tools.',why:'Cost Explorer\'s API mirrors everything you can do in the Cost Explorer console, but programmatically. You can query for aggregated monthly costs, daily usage by service, forecasted costs for the next 12 months, and granular data like DynamoDB write operations. Pagination handles large result sets. The API integrates directly into your automation tool without any manual steps.',trap:'AWS Budgets sends notifications (via SNS or email) when spending exceeds thresholds — it does not provide access to detailed cost and usage data or forecasts. Delivering Budgets reports via SQS is not a standard feature and still would not give granular cost data. Downloading CSV files is a manual process that cannot be automated.',rule:'Cost Explorer API = programmatic cost + usage data + forecasting. AWS Budgets = threshold alerts only. CSV download = manual only.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'40',category:'Security',question:'A startup is designing a publicly accessible HPC application and wants to mitigate DDoS attacks. Which TWO of the following options are NOT suitable DDoS mitigation techniques? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Dedicated EC2 instances to ensure maximum performance for each instance.','B|Add multiple Elastic Fabric Adapters (EFA) to each EC2 instance to increase network bandwidth.','C|Use Amazon CloudFront to distribute both static and dynamic content.','D|Use an ALB with Auto Scaling and deploy RDS in a private subnet.','E|Use AWS Shield and AWS WAF.'],correct:'AB',answer:'Dedicated EC2 instances are an instance billing option for hardware isolation — they do nothing to detect, absorb, or deflect DDoS traffic. Elastic Fabric Adapters are high-performance network adapters for HPC and ML compute tasks — they increase bandwidth for legitimate workloads but provide no DDoS protection. You can also only attach one EFA per EC2 instance.',why:'DDoS mitigation works by either absorbing the attack (distributing it across many edge locations as CloudFront does), filtering malicious traffic (as WAF does), providing always-on protection (as Shield does), or distributing legitimate traffic across auto-scaled instances (as ALB + Auto Scaling does). Dedicated instances and EFAs do neither — they are performance optimizations for compute workloads.',trap:'It is easy to confuse "high performance" features with "security" features. Both Dedicated instances and EFAs make your application run faster — but speed and resilience against attack are different properties. A faster server receiving 100 Gbps of attack traffic is still overwhelmed.',rule:'DDoS mitigation = CloudFront + WAF + Shield + ALB + Auto Scaling. Dedicated instances = billing/isolation only. EFA = HPC/ML performance only. One EFA per instance max.',keywords:'HPC low-latency inter-instance networking → Cluster Placement Group (same rack).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'41',category:'S3',question:'A web application needs to extract specific columns from a large CSV file stored in S3 and return only the filtered data to the user — without downloading the entire object. Which solution achieves this?',choices:['A|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes data based on the bucket name and object key.','B|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes data based on the bucket name and object metadata.','C|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes data based on the bucket name and object tags.','D|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes data based on the bucket name only.'],correct:'A',answer:'S3 Object Lambda intercepts S3 GET requests and invokes a Lambda function to transform the data before returning it to the requester. The Lambda function uses the bucket name and object key to identify the specific file, retrieve its contents, apply the filtering logic, and return only the needed data.',why:'Normally, an S3 GET request returns the entire object. S3 Object Lambda sits in between: it creates an Object Lambda Access Point, and when your application requests a file through that access point, S3 invokes your Lambda function with the request context (bucket name, object key, pre-signed URL to the original object). Your Lambda downloads the original file, processes it (filtering columns, redacting data, converting formats), and writes the result to the response. The object key is essential because it identifies which specific file among potentially millions to retrieve and process.',trap:'Object metadata (Content-Type, ETag, Last-Modified, custom metadata) describes properties of the object but does not contain the object\'s actual data — you cannot filter CSV rows from metadata. Object tags are labels for organizing and lifecycle policies — they have no relationship to file content. The bucket name alone identifies only the bucket, not which of potentially millions of files to process.',rule:'S3 Object Lambda = intercept GET, transform data on the fly, return processed result. Requires bucket name + object key to identify the file. Metadata and tags = properties about the object, not its content.',keywords:'Query inside S3 object without downloading = S3 Select. SQL-like, supports CSV/JSON/Parquet.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'42',category:'Cost',question:'A startup runs a mix of production workloads on EC2, AWS Fargate, and AWS Lambda. The team wants to commit to consistent usage over 3 years to get the maximum discount while retaining full flexibility to change instance families, regions, or services as the product evolves. Which pricing model satisfies this?',choices:['A|Purchase Compute Savings Plans committed to a consistent USD/hour spend.','B|Purchase EC2 Instance Savings Plans for each instance family in use.','C|Purchase Reserved Instances with the Convertible type.','D|Use Spot Instances with Spot Fleet across all three services.'],correct:'A',answer:'Compute Savings Plans apply a discount automatically regardless of instance family, size, AZ, region, OS, or tenancy, and also cover Fargate and Lambda usage. They provide the most flexibility of any commitment-based pricing model.',why:'EC2 Instance Savings Plans are locked to a single instance family in a single region — they offer deeper per-instance discounts but break immediately if you change families or move regions. Convertible RIs cover EC2 only and cannot be applied to Fargate or Lambda. Spot Instances are interruptible, not suitable for steady production workloads, and do not provide Fargate/Lambda discounts.',trap:'Students confuse Compute Savings Plans with EC2 Instance Savings Plans. The key differentiator: Compute Savings Plans cover EC2 + Fargate + Lambda and are region/family agnostic. EC2 Instance Savings Plans offer lower prices but are bound to a single instance family in a single region.',rule:'Compute Savings Plans = most flexible (EC2 + Fargate + Lambda, any region/family). EC2 Instance Savings Plans = lowest price (single family, single region). RIs = most rigid (specific instance config). Spot = cheapest but interruptible.',keywords:'Compute Savings Plans cover EC2 + Fargate + Lambda, any region/family. EC2 Instance Savings Plans = single family/region, lowest prices.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'43',category:'Cost',question:'A company has 50 EC2 instances of the same family (m5.large and m5.xlarge) running 24/7 in us-east-1. The workload is steady and the team has confirmed this configuration will not change for the next year. They want the deepest possible discount without the ability to sell the commitment. Which option provides this?',choices:['A|Compute Savings Plans with a 1-year, no-upfront commitment.','B|EC2 Instance Savings Plans for the m5 family in us-east-1 with a 1-year term.','C|Standard Reserved Instances for each specific instance size.','D|Convertible Reserved Instances for the m5 family.'],correct:'B',answer:'EC2 Instance Savings Plans provide the lowest prices of all Savings Plan types for a committed instance family in a specific region. Since the team is confident in their m5 family and us-east-1 region for 12 months, this gives deeper discounts than Compute Savings Plans while allowing free movement between m5.large and m5.xlarge.',why:'Compute Savings Plans offer flexibility but at a slightly higher price per unit than EC2 Instance Savings Plans. Standard RIs lock you to a specific instance type and size — you cannot move between m5.large and m5.xlarge without modification. EC2 Instance Savings Plans let you freely change instance sizes within the committed family without losing the discount, making them ideal here.',trap:'Standard RIs lock to a specific instance type and size. EC2 Instance Savings Plans allow resizing within the family. This distinction is critical: m5.large does not equal m5.xlarge for a Standard RI, but both benefit from the same EC2 Instance Savings Plan.',rule:'EC2 Instance Savings Plans = lowest price for known instance family + region. Can resize freely within family. Cannot change family or region. Compute Savings Plans = more flexible but slightly less discount.',keywords:'EC2 Instance Savings Plans: single family + region, deepest discount, free resizing within family.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'44',category:'Cost',question:'A financial services company needs to reduce its AWS bill. A cloud financial analyst reviews usage and identifies that EC2, Lambda, and Fargate all run at consistent baseline levels. The analyst wants a single commitment that covers all three services. What should the analyst purchase?',choices:['A|Standard Reserved Instances for EC2, and On-Demand for Lambda and Fargate.','B|EC2 Instance Savings Plans for EC2 only, and On-Demand for Lambda and Fargate.','C|Compute Savings Plans at a USD/hour rate that covers the combined baseline.','D|A combination of Regional Reserved Instances for EC2 and Spot for Lambda and Fargate.'],correct:'C',answer:'Compute Savings Plans are the only commitment model that applies to all three services — EC2, Fargate, and Lambda — in a single commitment. The discount is applied automatically to any eligible usage up to the committed USD/hour rate.',why:'Reserved Instances and EC2 Instance Savings Plans apply only to EC2. Lambda and Fargate have no RI equivalent — Compute Savings Plans are the only way to commit to discounted Lambda and Fargate spend. A single Compute Savings Plan commitment can replace three separate purchasing decisions.',trap:'Reserved Instances do NOT apply to Lambda or Fargate. This is a very common exam trap. Compute Savings Plans are the only option that covers all three simultaneously.',rule:'Only Compute Savings Plans cover EC2 + Fargate + Lambda. RIs and EC2 Instance Savings Plans = EC2 only. Lambda and Fargate discounts require Compute Savings Plans.',keywords:'Compute Savings Plans cover EC2 + Fargate + Lambda in one commitment. RIs and EC2 Instance Savings Plans exclude Lambda and Fargate.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'45',category:'Cost',question:'A company purchased Standard Reserved Instances for 20 m5.large EC2 instances 6 months ago. The team has since decided to migrate to a containerized architecture on Fargate and will no longer need the EC2 instances. The Reserved Instance term still has 18 months remaining. What is the MOST cost-effective way to stop paying for unused capacity?',choices:['A|Terminate the EC2 instances. The RI charges stop immediately upon termination.','B|Convert the Standard RIs to Convertible RIs so they can be applied to Fargate.','C|Sell the unused Standard Reserved Instances on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace.','D|Purchase Compute Savings Plans to offset the RI cost with Fargate discounts.'],correct:'C',answer:'Standard Reserved Instances can be sold on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace, allowing the company to recoup some of the prepaid cost. Terminating the EC2 instances does not cancel RI billing — you continue to be charged for the RI regardless of whether an instance is running.',why:'RI billing is independent of instance state. You are charged for the reservation whether or not a matching instance is running. The RI Marketplace lets you sell remaining term to other buyers. Convertible RIs can be exchanged but NOT sold on the marketplace, and they cannot be applied to Fargate. Standard RIs CAN be sold.',trap:'Terminating an EC2 instance does NOT stop RI billing. This is the most common student mistake. You must sell the RI on the marketplace OR wait out the term. Also: Standard RIs CAN be sold; Convertible RIs CANNOT be sold on the marketplace.',rule:'Standard RI = can be sold on RI Marketplace, cannot exchange attributes. Convertible RI = can exchange attributes (instance family/OS), cannot be sold on Marketplace. Terminating EC2 does NOT stop RI billing.',keywords:'Standard RI: can sell on RI Marketplace. Convertible RI: can exchange attributes but cannot sell. RI billing continues regardless of instance state.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'46',category:'Storage',question:'A media company runs a large-scale video processing pipeline that reads and writes sequential 1 GB files continuously. The workload requires high throughput but is not sensitive to IOPS. The team wants the lowest cost EBS volume that can handle this workload. Which volume type should they choose?',choices:['A|gp3 (General Purpose SSD) for its balance of price and performance.','B|io2 (Provisioned IOPS SSD) for maximum throughput.','C|st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD) for high sequential throughput at low cost.','D|sc1 (Cold HDD) for the lowest possible cost.'],correct:'C',answer:'st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD) is designed for large, sequential I/O workloads such as big data, data warehouses, and log processing. It delivers high throughput at a significantly lower cost than SSD volumes and is ideal when workloads do not require high IOPS but do need sustained sequential read/write performance.',why:'SSD volumes (gp3, io2) optimize for IOPS — their price premium reflects random I/O performance the pipeline does not need. sc1 (Cold HDD) provides even lower cost but is designed for infrequently accessed data and has lower baseline throughput. st1 hits the sweet spot: low price + high throughput for continuous sequential workloads. Neither st1 nor sc1 can be used as a boot volume.',trap:'HDD volumes (st1, sc1) cannot be used as boot volumes. st1 is for frequently accessed sequential data; sc1 is for infrequently accessed cold data. Do not confuse them. gp3 is cost-effective for most workloads but SSD pricing is higher than HDD for pure throughput use cases.',rule:'SSD (gp2, gp3, io1, io2) = small random I/O, IOPS-dominant, can boot. HDD (st1, sc1) = large sequential I/O, throughput-dominant, cannot boot. st1 = frequently accessed streaming. sc1 = infrequently accessed cold storage.',keywords:'HDD volumes: st1 (streaming, frequent) vs sc1 (cold, infrequent). Neither can boot. SSD for IOPS; HDD for throughput.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'47',category:'Storage',question:'A data warehouse team needs an EBS volume for a log archiving system that stores large compressed files accessed at most once a month for compliance reporting. The priority is the absolute lowest storage cost. Which volume type is most appropriate?',choices:['A|gp3 for its low baseline cost and adequate performance.','B|st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD) for its low cost and high throughput.','C|sc1 (Cold HDD) for the lowest per-GB cost for infrequently accessed data.','D|io1 (Provisioned IOPS SSD) for reliable performance during monthly queries.'],correct:'C',answer:'sc1 (Cold HDD) provides the lowest per-GB cost of all EBS volume types and is specifically designed for infrequently accessed workloads. For data accessed once a month for read-only compliance queries, sc1 delivers the required throughput at the minimum possible price.',why:'st1 is also low cost but targeted at frequently accessed, large streaming workloads. sc1 is even cheaper and explicitly designed for cold data that is accessed rarely. io1 would be grossly over-provisioned and expensive for monthly read workloads. gp3 is cost-effective but priced higher than HDD volumes.',trap:'st1 vs sc1 is a key distinction: st1 = frequently accessed streaming (lower price ceiling, higher performance). sc1 = infrequently accessed cold storage (lowest price). Both are HDD and cannot be used as boot volumes.',rule:'Lowest cost EBS = sc1 (Cold HDD). Use case: cold data, infrequent access. st1 = slightly higher cost, frequently accessed streaming. Never use HDD as boot volume.',keywords:'sc1 = lowest cost EBS, cold infrequent data. st1 = low cost, frequent large sequential. Both HDD, no boot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'48',category:'Database',question:'A gaming company has a leaderboard built on Amazon DynamoDB. During peak hours, millions of players simultaneously read the same top-100 entries, causing read throttling despite high provisioned capacity. The team wants to reduce read latency to microseconds and eliminate throttling without changing application code. What should they do?',choices:['A|Enable DynamoDB global tables to distribute reads across regions.','B|Add an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis cluster in front of DynamoDB.','C|Enable DynamoDB DAX (DynamoDB Accelerator) as an in-memory cache.','D|Increase provisioned read capacity units on the DynamoDB table.'],correct:'C',answer:'DynamoDB DAX is a fully managed, in-memory cache purpose-built for DynamoDB. It delivers microsecond response times for read-heavy workloads. Applications continue using the same DynamoDB SDKs and API calls without code changes — DAX intercepts requests transparently. It also eliminates the need to overprovision read capacity, as cached responses bypass DynamoDB entirely.',why:'ElastiCache requires significant application code changes to manage cache population, invalidation, and cache-aside logic. DAX requires zero code changes. Increasing provisioned capacity costs more without reducing latency to microseconds. Global tables improve read performance for multi-region scenarios but do not provide in-memory caching or microsecond responses.',trap:'ElastiCache vs DAX is a classic exam question. DAX = no code changes, DynamoDB-native, microsecond reads. ElastiCache = requires code changes, more flexible (can cache any data), supports Redis data structures. If the question says "no code changes" + DynamoDB → DAX.',rule:'DAX = DynamoDB-native in-memory cache, no code changes, microsecond reads, avoid overprovisioning. Do NOT use DAX for strongly consistent reads or write-intensive workloads. DAX caches eventually consistent reads only.',keywords:'DynamoDB DAX = in-memory cache, microsecond latency, no code changes. DAX does not support strongly consistent reads.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'49',category:'Database',question:'A financial trading application uses DynamoDB and requires strongly consistent reads for every transaction to prevent stale data from affecting trade decisions. The team is evaluating whether to add DAX to reduce latency. What should the solutions architect advise?',choices:['A|Add DAX — it supports strongly consistent reads and will reduce latency.','B|Do not add DAX — DAX does not support strongly consistent reads.','C|Add DAX and configure it for write-through mode to enable consistency.','D|Add DAX and set the ConsistentRead parameter to true in the DAX client.'],correct:'B',answer:'DAX only caches eventually consistent reads. For a trading application requiring strongly consistent reads, DAX passes through to DynamoDB directly and provides no latency benefit. The study guide explicitly states that if applications require strongly consistent reads or have write-intensive workloads, DAX should not be used.',why:'DynamoDB strongly consistent reads require reading directly from the authoritative partition leader, which cannot be served from a distributed in-memory cache. DAX serves from cache for eventually consistent reads and passes through to DynamoDB for strongly consistent reads, making it ineffective for this use case.',trap:'Students often assume DAX can be configured for strong consistency. It cannot. Write-through mode does not enable strongly consistent reads. If an exam scenario requires strong consistency, DAX provides no latency benefit and should not be added.',rule:'DAX = eventually consistent reads only. Cannot serve strongly consistent reads. Also avoid for write-intensive workloads. Financial, inventory, and compliance use cases that need strong consistency should not use DAX.',keywords:'DAX does not support strongly consistent reads. Do not use DAX for write-heavy workloads or strong consistency requirements.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'50',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company is migrating a large on-premises Kafka-based event streaming platform to AWS. The existing applications use native Kafka producer/consumer APIs and the team does not want to rewrite any application code. The solution must support exactly the same Kafka protocols and APIs. Which AWS service should they use?',choices:['A|Amazon Kinesis Data Streams, which is fully compatible with Kafka APIs.','B|Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka), which runs native Kafka.','C|Amazon SQS FIFO queues for ordered event streaming.','D|Amazon EventBridge for managed event routing.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon MSK is a fully managed service that runs native Apache Kafka clusters on AWS. It is fully API-compatible with open-source Kafka, meaning existing applications using Kafka producer/consumer clients require zero code changes. MSK handles provisioning, patching, and availability of the underlying Kafka brokers.',why:'Kinesis Data Streams is AWS native and uses Kinesis-specific APIs, not Kafka APIs. Applications built with Kafka clients cannot use Kinesis without rewriting producer and consumer code. SQS and EventBridge are message queuing/routing services, not streaming platforms compatible with Kafka protocols.',trap:'Kinesis and MSK both handle streaming data but use completely different APIs. Kinesis = AWS-native (KPL/KCL). MSK = native Kafka (Kafka client libs). The phrase "existing Kafka applications" or "Kafka API compatibility" is the exam signal for MSK.',rule:'Existing Kafka applications → Amazon MSK (zero code change). New streaming on AWS → Kinesis Data Streams. MSK = managed Kafka brokers. Cannot use Spot Instances for MSK brokers.',keywords:'MSK = native Kafka API. Kinesis = AWS proprietary. Lift-and-shift Kafka migration → MSK. New build → Kinesis Data Streams.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'51',category:'Kinesis',question:'A solutions architect is designing a real-time analytics pipeline where multiple independent consumer applications must each read all events in order, and the team must be able to replay the last 7 days of events to reprocess data after a bug fix. Which AWS service best supports replay and ordered delivery to multiple concurrent consumers?',choices:['A|Amazon SQS Standard Queue — supports multiple consumers and long retention.','B|Amazon Kinesis Data Streams — supports ordered delivery, replay, and multiple concurrent consumers.','C|Amazon EventBridge — routes events to multiple targets with guaranteed ordering.','D|Amazon SQS FIFO Queue — provides ordering and multiple consumer groups.'],correct:'B',answer:'Kinesis Data Streams provides strict ordering within each shard, supports replay of records in the same order, and allows multiple independent consumer applications to each read the full stream simultaneously. Retention is configurable from 24 hours up to 365 days, fully covering the 7-day replay requirement.',why:'SQS Standard queues do not preserve order and messages are deleted after consumption — replay is impossible. SQS FIFO queues provide ordering and exactly-once delivery but each message can only be consumed once per consumer group; replay is not supported. EventBridge is a routing service and does not store events for replay.',trap:'SQS is not a streaming/replay service. Once a message is consumed and deleted, it cannot be replayed. Kinesis = streaming + replay + ordering + multiple concurrent consumers. SQS = decoupling with at-least-once delivery, no replay. "Replay" requirement → Kinesis (or MSK).',rule:'Kinesis Data Streams: real-time + ordering within shard + replay up to 365 days + multiple concurrent consumers. SQS: decoupling, no replay, no guaranteed order (FIFO available but no replay). Replay requirement → never SQS.',keywords:'Kinesis = real-time + ordered + replay + multiple consumers. SQS = decoupling, no replay. MSK = Kafka-compatible. Replay signal → Kinesis or MSK.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'52',category:'Networking',question:'A startup has a single VPC with private subnets in two Availability Zones. They use one shared NAT Gateway in us-east-1a that both private subnets route through. A cost review shows unexpected data transfer charges. What is the root cause, and what is the most cost-effective fix?',choices:['A|NAT Gateways charge per hour regardless of traffic. Replace with a NAT Instance.','B|Traffic from the us-east-1b private subnet crosses AZs to reach the shared NAT Gateway, incurring cross-AZ transfer fees. Create a NAT Gateway in each AZ.','C|NAT Gateways charge for all data transferred, even within the same AZ. No optimization is possible.','D|Use a VPC endpoint for all traffic to eliminate NAT Gateway usage entirely.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS charges a cross-AZ data transfer fee when traffic crosses between Availability Zones. When the us-east-1b subnet routes through the NAT Gateway in us-east-1a, every outbound byte incurs cross-AZ charges on top of NAT Gateway data processing fees. Creating a NAT Gateway in each AZ and routing each private subnet to its local gateway eliminates these cross-AZ charges.',why:'The study guide states: "for true high availability, you should create a NAT gateway in a public subnet for each of your redundant private subnets or AZs." This also eliminates cross-AZ fees. VPC endpoints only eliminate NAT costs for S3 and DynamoDB, not general internet traffic. NAT Instances are cheaper at low traffic volumes but still incur cross-AZ charges if placed in a different AZ.',trap:'One NAT Gateway seems cheaper because you pay fewer hourly charges. But cross-AZ data transfer fees can far exceed the cost of a second NAT Gateway at significant traffic volumes. Per-AZ NAT Gateways achieve both HA and cost efficiency.',rule:'One NAT GW per AZ = eliminates cross-AZ transfer costs + HA. Shared NAT GW = cross-AZ charges for subnets in other AZs. NAT GW cost = hourly + data processed. Cross-AZ data transfer = $0.01/GB.',keywords:'NAT Gateway per AZ eliminates cross-AZ data transfer costs. One shared NAT GW = cross-AZ charges. Per-AZ design = HA + cost optimized at scale.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'53',category:'Networking',question:'A company has hundreds of EC2 instances in private subnets making API calls to Amazon S3 and DynamoDB. The traffic is routing through a NAT Gateway, generating significant data processing charges. What is the most cost-effective way to eliminate these charges for S3 and DynamoDB traffic specifically?',choices:['A|Replace the NAT Gateway with a NAT Instance to reduce hourly costs.','B|Move the EC2 instances to public subnets so they can access S3 and DynamoDB directly.','C|Create VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB and update the route tables.','D|Use AWS PrivateLink Interface Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB.'],correct:'C',answer:'VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB are free to create and use. Traffic from EC2 instances routes directly to S3 or DynamoDB over the AWS private network without traversing the NAT Gateway, eliminating both NAT data processing charges and data transfer fees for that traffic.',why:'Gateway Endpoints (for S3 and DynamoDB only) have no hourly or data processing charge — they are completely free. Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink) incur an hourly charge per AZ plus a data processing fee. NAT Instances still incur data transfer costs. Moving instances to public subnets is a security regression.',trap:'Gateway Endpoint vs Interface Endpoint is critical. S3 and DynamoDB support Gateway Endpoints (free, route-table based). Most other AWS services use Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink, hourly charge). Always prefer Gateway Endpoints for S3/DynamoDB to eliminate NAT costs.',rule:'S3 and DynamoDB: use FREE Gateway Endpoints to bypass NAT Gateway. Other services: Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink) cost money but keep traffic private. Gateway Endpoint = route table entry, free. Interface Endpoint = ENI in subnet, hourly charge.',keywords:'S3 + DynamoDB: Gateway Endpoints = free, eliminates NAT costs. Other services: Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink) = hourly + data charge.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'54',category:'Security',question:'A security engineer needs to investigate potential data exfiltration from a VPC. They need to capture information about all IP traffic — including source IP, destination IP, ports, and whether traffic was accepted or rejected — for all network interfaces in the VPC, without installing any agents on EC2 instances. Which solution meets these requirements?',choices:['A|Install the Amazon CloudWatch Agent on all EC2 instances to capture network logs.','B|Enable VPC Flow Logs on the VPC and publish them to Amazon CloudWatch Logs or S3.','C|Enable AWS CloudTrail with data events to record all network API calls.','D|Deploy a third-party network packet capture appliance via the AWS Marketplace.'],correct:'B',answer:'VPC Flow Logs capture metadata about IP traffic flowing through network interfaces in a VPC — including source/destination IPs, ports, protocol, packet/byte counts, and ACCEPT/REJECT status. They are agentless, applied at the VPC, subnet, or ENI level, and publish to CloudWatch Logs or S3 for analysis.',why:'CloudWatch Agent captures OS-level metrics and application logs, not network traffic metadata. CloudTrail records AWS API calls (management events), not raw IP traffic flow data. Third-party packet capture appliances require infrastructure management. VPC Flow Logs are purpose-built for network traffic visibility with zero agent installation.',trap:'CloudTrail vs VPC Flow Logs is a common exam confusion. CloudTrail = WHO made API calls to AWS. VPC Flow Logs = WHAT IP traffic flowed through network interfaces. Data exfiltration investigation requires Flow Logs (network level), not CloudTrail (API call level).',rule:'VPC Flow Logs = IP traffic metadata (src/dst IP, port, protocol, accept/reject). No agents. Published to CloudWatch Logs or S3. CloudTrail = API activity. Use Flow Logs for network-level security investigations.',keywords:'VPC Flow Logs = IP traffic metadata, agentless, VPC/subnet/ENI level. CloudTrail = API calls. Flow Logs for network forensics.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'55',category:'Storage',question:'A content management system stores media files on Amazon EFS. During business hours the workload generates high, spiky throughput demands that consistently exhaust the burst credit balance. Off-peak usage is minimal. The team needs predictable high throughput during peak hours regardless of the file system size. Which EFS throughput configuration should they choose?',choices:['A|Bursting Throughput mode — it automatically scales with the file system size.','B|Provisioned Throughput mode — set a fixed MiB/s value independent of storage size.','C|Elastic Throughput mode — it automatically scales without a provisioned limit.','D|Increase the EFS file system size to earn a larger burst credit pool.'],correct:'B',answer:'Provisioned Throughput mode lets you set a specific throughput value in MiB/s that is independent of the amount of data stored. This eliminates burst credit exhaustion for workloads that need consistently high throughput regardless of file system size. You pay for the provisioned throughput above the baseline included with storage.',why:'Bursting Throughput earns credits based on storage size — a small file system earns few credits and can sustain only modest throughput during bursts. Elastic Throughput is well-suited for unpredictable workloads but charges per GB transferred, which may be expensive for consistently high throughput. Increasing file system size wastes money storing unnecessary data.',trap:'Bursting Throughput works well when file system size is large enough to earn sufficient credits. For consistently high throughput demands that exceed burst capacity on smaller file systems, Provisioned Throughput is the correct choice.',rule:'EFS Bursting = throughput scales with storage size (credit model). EFS Provisioned = fixed MiB/s regardless of storage size, pay for provisioned amount. EFS Elastic = auto-scaling for unpredictable workloads, pay per GB transferred.',keywords:'EFS throughput modes: Bursting (credit-based, size-dependent), Provisioned (fixed MiB/s, size-independent), Elastic (auto-scale, per-GB charge).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'56',category:'S3',question:'A large enterprise stores raw data across multiple S3 buckets and needs to build a centralized data lake. Data scientists from different teams need fine-grained, column-level access control so that the marketing team sees customer demographics but not financial records, while the finance team sees the reverse. Which AWS service is best suited to manage these permissions?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 bucket policies with prefix-based restrictions for each team.','B|AWS Lake Formation to manage table, column, and row-level permissions on the data lake.','C|Amazon Macie to classify data and restrict access automatically.','D|AWS Glue Data Catalog with IAM policies to control access by table.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Lake Formation provides fine-grained access control for data lakes, including database, table, column, and row-level permissions. It sits on top of the AWS Glue Data Catalog and lets administrators grant or revoke data access centrally without writing complex S3 bucket policies for every team and dataset combination.',why:'S3 bucket policies operate at the object/prefix level and cannot enforce column-level restrictions on structured data. Macie classifies and discovers sensitive data but does not manage access permissions. Glue Data Catalog stores schema metadata; combining it with IAM provides table-level access but not column-level restrictions without Lake Formation.',trap:'Lake Formation vs IAM/S3 policies: IAM and S3 bucket policies are powerful but cannot enforce column-level access on tabular data in a data lake. Lake Formation is purpose-built for this. Use Lake Formation when the requirement includes fine-grained, column-level, row-level, or centralized permissions across the data lake.',rule:'AWS Lake Formation = fine-grained access control (database/table/column/row) for data lakes built on S3 + Glue Catalog. IAM/S3 = object/prefix level only. Use Lake Formation for column-level or row-level data access governance.',keywords:'Lake Formation = fine-grained column/row-level access control for data lakes. Sits on top of Glue Data Catalog. Use for centralized data governance.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'57',category:'S3',question:'A business analyst team needs interactive dashboards and paginated reports that pull from multiple data sources — Amazon Redshift, Amazon S3, and third-party databases — and share them with 500 non-technical business users. The team wants a fully managed BI solution with no infrastructure to manage. Which service should they use?',choices:['A|Amazon Athena with saved queries shared via S3 presigned URLs.','B|Amazon QuickSight for managed interactive dashboards and embedded analytics.','C|Amazon Redshift Spectrum with Tableau installed on EC2.','D|AWS Glue with custom visualizations written in Apache Zeppelin notebooks.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon QuickSight is a serverless, fully managed Business Intelligence service that creates interactive dashboards, paginated reports, and embedded analytics. It connects natively to Redshift, S3, RDS, Athena, and third-party sources. It auto-scales to support any number of users and requires no infrastructure management.',why:'Athena is a query engine, not a dashboarding tool. Tableau on EC2 is self-managed with server costs and patching overhead. Glue is an ETL service. QuickSight is the purpose-built BI and visualization service — the only managed option for creating and sharing dashboards from multiple AWS data sources without managing servers.',trap:'Athena, Glue, and Redshift are data processing/storage services. QuickSight is the visualization layer on top of them. Interactive dashboards + fully managed + multiple data sources + business users is the QuickSight signal.',rule:'QuickSight = managed BI and visualization. Connect to Athena, Redshift, S3, RDS, and third-party sources. Serverless, no infrastructure. Use for dashboards, reports, embedded analytics. Not a query or ETL service.',keywords:'QuickSight = managed BI, interactive dashboards, paginated reports. Connects to Athena, Redshift, S3. Serverless, auto-scales.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'58',category:'Cost',question:'A CFO wants to receive an automatic alert whenever the company\'s AWS spend exceeds $50,000 in a month, and also wants a warning when projected spend is forecast to exceed that threshold before month-end. Which AWS service enables both actual and forecasted spend alerts?',choices:['A|AWS Cost Explorer — configure a filter for monthly spend above $50,000.','B|AWS Budgets — set a monthly cost budget with alerts for actual and forecasted threshold breaches.','C|AWS Cost and Usage Report — create an automated query to check for threshold breaches.','D|Amazon CloudWatch — create a billing alarm on the EstimatedCharges metric.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Budgets lets you define budget limits and configure alerts for both actual spend (when charges exceed the threshold) and forecasted spend (when projected charges are on track to exceed the budget before month-end). Email and SNS notifications are sent automatically, enabling proactive cost management.',why:'Cost Explorer is a visualization and analysis tool — it does not send alerts. Cost and Usage Report provides detailed data for analysis but requires custom query infrastructure to generate alerts. CloudWatch billing alarms can alert on actual charges but do not natively support forecasted spend alerts. AWS Budgets is purpose-built for both actual and forecast-based alerting.',trap:'CloudWatch billing alarms are sometimes used for cost alerting but only react to current charges. AWS Budgets supports BOTH actual AND forecasted alerts — this forecasting capability distinguishes it from CloudWatch billing alarms.',rule:'AWS Budgets = proactive cost management, actual + forecast alerts, email/SNS notifications. Cost Explorer = historical analysis and visualization. CUR = detailed raw data for custom analysis. CloudWatch billing = actual charges only, no forecast.',keywords:'AWS Budgets: actual + forecasted spend alerts, email/SNS. Cost Explorer: historical visualization. CUR: raw detailed cost data for analysis.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'59',category:'Cost',question:'A FinOps team wants to implement detailed cost allocation across 15 business units. They need per-resource, per-hour cost data broken down by department, project, and environment for chargeback reports, and the data must be exportable to their data warehouse for custom analysis. Which AWS tool provides the most granular data?',choices:['A|AWS Cost Explorer with group-by filters for linked accounts.','B|AWS Budgets with daily reporting intervals.','C|AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) published to an S3 bucket.','D|AWS Trusted Advisor cost optimization recommendations.'],correct:'C',answer:'The AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) is the most granular cost dataset AWS provides. It breaks down costs by hour, day, or month at the resource level, categorized by product, resource ID, and custom cost allocation tags. Teams publish it to an S3 bucket and query it with Athena, load it into Redshift, or integrate with BI tools for custom chargeback analysis.',why:'Cost Explorer provides interactive charts and filtering but is not designed for raw data export at hourly resource-level granularity. Budgets are for threshold alerting, not detailed reporting. Trusted Advisor provides recommendations but not cost attribution data. CUR is the only service that provides complete, exportable, resource-level cost data.',trap:'Cost Explorer looks like the obvious answer for cost reporting but cannot export the full hourly per-resource dataset. CUR is the correct answer whenever the requirement mentions most granular, hourly, per-resource, chargeback, or export to data warehouse.',rule:'CUR = most granular (hourly, per-resource, custom tags), exports to S3, queryable with Athena/Redshift. Cost Explorer = visualization + trends. Budgets = alerting. Trusted Advisor = recommendations.',keywords:'CUR = most granular cost data, hourly/per-resource/tag, S3 export, custom analysis. Cost Explorer = visualization. Use CUR for chargeback and detailed financial reporting.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'60',category:'Cost',question:'A company runs a web application where EC2 instances in us-east-1a make frequent calls to an RDS instance located in us-east-1b. A cost review reveals unexpected data transfer charges. What is the most likely cause, and how should it be fixed?',choices:['A|EC2 and RDS are in different regions. Move RDS to the same region to eliminate inter-region charges.','B|EC2 instances and the RDS instance are in different Availability Zones, incurring cross-AZ data transfer charges. Move them to the same AZ.','C|RDS uses public endpoints. Switch to a private VPC connection to eliminate charges.','D|RDS data transfer is always charged regardless of network path. No optimization is possible.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS charges for data transferred between EC2 instances or services in different Availability Zones within the same region. When EC2 instances in us-east-1a communicate with an RDS instance in us-east-1b, every byte transferred incurs cross-AZ data transfer charges. Placing compute and database in the same AZ eliminates these costs, though this reduces fault tolerance.',why:'Data transfer within the same AZ is free. Cross-AZ transfer within the same region costs approximately $0.01/GB in both directions. Inter-region transfer costs $0.02/GB or more. Using private IPs within the same AZ and VPC is the zero-cost configuration. This is a real-world cost optimization that appears in Domain 4.',trap:'Same region does not mean free. Cross-AZ traffic within the same region incurs data transfer charges. Free data transfer only applies within the same AZ and same VPC. This is a commonly missed cost driver in multi-AZ architectures.',rule:'Free data transfer: same AZ + same VPC. Cross-AZ: ~$0.01/GB. Cross-region: $0.02+/GB. Minimize cross-AZ hops to reduce data transfer costs. Collocate tightly coupled services in the same AZ for cost savings.',keywords:'Same AZ = free data transfer. Cross-AZ = $0.01/GB both directions. Cross-region = $0.02+/GB. Collocate EC2 + RDS in same AZ to minimize transfer costs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'61',category:'Cost',question:'A media company distributes large video files (average 2 GB each) to customers globally from an S3 bucket in us-east-1. Their AWS bill shows $30,000 per month in data transfer out to the internet. They want to reduce this cost while maintaining or improving delivery performance. What is the most cost-effective solution?',choices:['A|Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration on the bucket to reduce transfer time and cost.','B|Move the S3 bucket to a region closer to the majority of customers.','C|Serve the content through Amazon CloudFront, which has lower data transfer rates than direct S3 egress.','D|Compress the video files before uploading to reduce the data volume transferred.'],correct:'C',answer:'CloudFront data transfer rates to the internet are significantly lower than direct S3-to-internet egress rates. Data transfer from S3 to a CloudFront origin is free — there is no charge for origin fetches from S3 to CloudFront. The only cost is CloudFront edge-to-internet transfer, which is priced lower per GB than S3 direct egress. Edge caching also reduces repeated origin fetches.',why:'S3 Transfer Acceleration accelerates uploads FROM clients TO S3 and adds a surcharge — it does not reduce download/egress costs. Moving S3 regions provides marginal savings and does not serve all global customers efficiently. Compressing already-encoded video yields minimal size reduction. CloudFront is the purpose-built cost-efficient global content delivery solution.',trap:'S3 Transfer Acceleration accelerates uploads TO S3, not downloads FROM S3. Students confuse upload acceleration with download cost reduction. The cost win with CloudFront: S3 → CloudFront origin fetch is FREE; CloudFront → internet edge egress rate is lower than S3 → internet.',rule:'CloudFront reduces egress costs: S3 origin → CloudFront is free. CloudFront → internet is cheaper than S3 → internet direct egress. Transfer Acceleration = faster uploads with surcharge. Use CloudFront to optimize download/egress for large files globally.',keywords:'CloudFront: S3 origin → CloudFront = free. CloudFront → internet = lower rate than S3 direct egress. Use CloudFront for cost-effective global distribution of large files.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Curated'},
  {id:'t1',category:'S3',question:'A start-up company that offers an intuitive financial data analytics service has consulted about its AWS architecture. The company has a fleet of Amazon EC2 worker instances that process financial data and then output reports used by its clients. The reports must be stored in a durable storage. The number of files to be stored can grow over time as the start-up company is expanding rapidly overseas, and thus, it also needs a way to distribute the reports faster to clients located across the globe. Which of the following is a cost-efficient and scalable storage option for this scenario?',choices:['A|Use Amazon Redshift as the data storage and Amazon CloudFront as the CDN.','B|Use Amazon S3 Glacier as the data storage and Amazon ElastiCache as the CDN.','C|Use Amazon S3 as the data storage and Amazon CloudFront as the CDN.','D|Use multiple EC2 instance stores for data storage and Amazon ElastiCache as the CDN.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon S3 provides highly durable, scalable, and secure storage. Amazon CloudFront is a CDN that caches content at edge locations globally, delivering low-latency access to users worldwide. Together they form the standard pattern for global static content delivery.',why:'S3 stores the reports durably across multiple AZs with 11 nines of durability. CloudFront caches copies of those reports at 400+ edge locations worldwide. When a client requests a report, CloudFront serves it from the nearest edge location rather than from S3 directly, dramatically reducing latency. Data transferred from S3 to CloudFront is also free of charge.',trap:'Redshift is a data warehouse for analytical SQL queries — not a general-purpose storage service for distributing report files. S3 Glacier is for archival data with slow retrieval — reports needed by clients are not archived data. ElastiCache is an in-memory database cache, not a CDN — it cannot distribute files globally. EC2 instance stores are ephemeral and not durable.',rule:'Reports to global users = S3 (storage) + CloudFront (CDN). ElastiCache = in-memory cache, not CDN. Glacier = archive, not client-facing. Redshift = SQL analytics warehouse.',keywords:'sub-millisecond / in-memory caching → ElastiCache. Frequently read, rarely changes → cache it.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t2',category:'S3',question:'A solutions architect is designing a secure, cost-effective, and highly available storage solution for a company’s data. One of the requirements is to ensure that the previous version of a file is preserved and can be retrieved if a modified version is uploaded. Additionally, the company must comply with strict regulatory requirements that mandate data retention in an immutable state for at least 3 years before being moved to an archive. Once archived, the data will only be accessed once a year. How should the solutions architect build the solution?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon S3 Standard bucket with object-level versioning enabled and configure a lifecycle rule that transfers files to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 3 years.','B|Create an Amazon S3 Standard bucket and enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode.','C|Create an Amazon S3 Standard bucket, enable object-level versioning, and then enable S3 Object Lock in compliance mode. After that, configure a lifecycle rule to move the files to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 3 years.','D|Create a One-Zone-IA bucket with object-level versioning enabled and configure a lifecycle rule that transfers files to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 3 years.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon S3 has capabilities like versioning, Object Lock, and lifecycle policies to help with data preservation and archiving. Object Lock enables you to store objects using a write-once, read-many (WORM) model, which can assist prevent objects from being deleted or rewritten for a set period of time or indefinitely.',why:'S3 Object Lock stores objects using a WORM (Write Once Read Many) model. Versioning is a prerequisite for Object Lock — enabling Object Lock automatically enables versioning. Retention modes: Compliance mode prevents deletion by ANY user including root until the retention period expires. Governance mode allows users with special IAM permissions to delete earlier. Legal Hold has no expiration date and can be toggled on/off independently by users with the s3:PutObjectLegalHold permission.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Amazon S3 Standard bucket with object-level versioning enabled and configure a lifecycle rule that transfers files to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 3 years is incorrect because it doesn\'t meet regulatory compliance.',rule:'Object Lock enables you to store objects using a write-once, read-many (WORM) model, which can assist prevent objects from being deleted or rewritten for a set period of time or indefinitely.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t3',category:'Storage',question:'A media company hosts large volumes of archive data that are about 250 TB in size on its internal servers. The company has decided to move this data to Amazon S3 because of its durability and redundancy. The company currently has a 100 Mbps dedicated line connecting its head office to the Internet. Which of the following is the FASTEST and MOST COST-EFFECTIVE way to import all this data to S3?',choices:['A|Upload it directly to S3','B|Establish a direct connection using AWS Direct Connect, then transfer the data over to S3.','C|Use S3 Transfer Acceleration to speed up the upload.','D|Request several AWS Snowball devices to upload the data into S3.'],correct:'D',answer:'Request several AWS Snowball devices to upload the data into S3.',why:'AWS Snowball is a petabyte-scale data transport solution that uses secure appliances to transfer large amounts of data into and out of the AWS cloud. Using Snowball addresses common challenges with large-scale data transfers, including high network costs, long transfer times, and security concerns. Transferring data with Snowball is simple, fast, secure, and can be as little as one-fifth the cost of high-speed Internet.',trap:'The option that says: Upload it directly to S3 is incorrect because it would typically take too long to finish due to the slow Internet connection of the company.',rule:'Transfer 250 TB offline = AWS Snowball (80 TB capacity per device, order multiple). Not Direct Connect (months of transfer time). Not direct S3 upload (bandwidth limited). Snowball ships encrypted, loads to S3 directly.',keywords:'Large offline data transfer (>1 week over network) → Snowball Edge. Ships data physically.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t4',category:'Storage',question:'An organization is currently using a tape backup solution to store its application data on-premises. Plans are in place to use a cloud storage service to preserve the backup data for up to 10 years, which may be accessed about once or twice a year. Which of the following is the most cost-effective option to implement this solution?',choices:['A|Use AWS Storage Gateway to backup the data directly to Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval.','B|Order an AWS Snowball Edge appliance to import the backup directly to Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval.','C|Use AWS Storage Gateway to backup the data and transition it to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive.','D|Use Amazon S3 to store the backup data and add a lifecycle rule to transition the current version to S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval.'],correct:'C',answer:'Tape Gateway (part of Storage Gateway) is designed to replace physical tape backup workflows without changing existing backup applications. It can write virtual tapes directly to Glacier Deep Archive — the cheapest storage class at ~$0.00099/GB/month — which is purpose-built for 10-year retention with once-or-twice-yearly access.',why:'Tape Gateway presents a VTL (Virtual Tape Library) interface that existing backup software (Veeam, Commvault, etc.) can write to without modification. Data is stored as virtual tapes in S3 and can be archived to Glacier Flexible Retrieval or Glacier Deep Archive. Glacier Deep Archive is up to 75% cheaper than Glacier Flexible Retrieval for the same 10-year retention use case. For data accessed only once or twice a year, the retrieval cost difference is minimal.',trap:'Glacier Flexible Retrieval costs more per GB/month than Deep Archive — for 10-year retention this adds up significantly. Snowball Edge cannot directly write to Glacier storage classes; it transfers to S3 standard first. Using plain S3 with a lifecycle rule adds an initial S3 Standard storage cost and complexity — Storage Gateway can write directly to Glacier classes.',rule:'Tape backup to cloud = Storage Gateway Tape Gateway. Long-term archive (accessed 1-2x/year) = Glacier Deep Archive (cheapest). Glacier Flexible Retrieval = faster retrieval but higher storage cost.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t5',category:'Database',question:'A company has a serverless application made up of AWS Amplify, Amazon API Gateway and a Lambda function. The application is connected to an Amazon RDS MySQL database instance inside a private subnet. A Lambda Function URL is also implemented as the dedicated HTTPS endpoint for the function, which has the following value: https://12june1898pil1pinas.lambda-url.us-west-2.on.aws/ There are times during peak loads when the database throws a “too many connections” error preventing the users from accessing the application. Which solution could the company take to resolve the issue?',choices:['A|Increase the concurrency limit of the Lambda function','B|Provision an RDS Proxy between the Lambda function and RDS database instance','C|Increase the rate limit of API Gateway','D|Increase the memory allocation of the Lambda function'],correct:'B',answer:'RDS Proxy maintains a warm connection pool to RDS. Lambda functions connect to the proxy instead of directly to the database. The proxy multiplexes thousands of Lambda connections into a much smaller pool of actual database connections, preventing the "too many connections" error.',why:'Lambda can scale to tens of thousands of concurrent executions. Each execution traditionally opens its own database connection — at scale this exhausts the database\'s max_connections limit (determined by instance memory). RDS Proxy holds a pool of open connections to the database and hands them to Lambda functions as needed. When a Lambda finishes, the connection returns to the pool rather than being destroyed. A db.t3.micro supports ~66 connections; RDS Proxy can serve thousands of Lambda invocations through those same 66 connections.',trap:'Increasing Lambda concurrency makes the problem worse — more concurrent Lambdas means more connection attempts. Increasing API Gateway rate limits also just allows more requests through, which increases Lambda invocations and thus more connection attempts. Increasing Lambda memory speeds up execution time but doesn\'t reduce the number of simultaneous connections held open.',rule:'Lambda + RDS at scale = RDS Proxy for connection pooling. Lambda concurrency × connections per function = potential connection exhaustion. RDS Proxy decouples these.',keywords:'Lambda + RDS "too many connections" → RDS Proxy (connection pooling). Decouples Lambda scale from DB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t6',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company is building an internal application that allows users to upload images. Each upload request must be sent to Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for processing before the pictures are stored in an Amazon S3 bucket. The application should immediately return a success message to the user after the upload, while the downstream processing is handled asynchronously. The processing typically takes about 5 minutes to complete. Which solution will enable asynchronous processing from Kinesis to S3 in the most cost-effective way?',choices:['A|Use a combination of AWS Lambda and Step Functions to orchestrate service components and asynchronously process the requests.','B|Use a combination of Amazon SQS to queue the requests and then asynchronously process them using On-Demand Amazon EC2 Instances.','C|Use Kinesis Data Streams with AWS Lambda consumers to asynchronously process records and write them to S3.','D|Send data from Kinesis Data Streams to Amazon Data Firehose and configure it to deliver directly to S3.'],correct:'C',answer:'Kinesis Data Streams with Lambda consumers is the natural pattern: the application writes to KDS and immediately responds with success. Lambda polls the stream via an event source mapping, processes batches asynchronously, and writes results to S3. Lambda scales automatically and you only pay per invocation.',why:'KDS decouples the upload acknowledgment from the actual processing. Once the record is written to the stream, the HTTP response can be returned immediately. Lambda\'s event source mapping to KDS handles polling, batching, checkpointing, and retries automatically. For 5-minute processing jobs, Lambda can be configured with up to 15-minute timeouts. There are no servers to manage and no idle capacity costs.',trap:'Step Functions adds per-state-transition costs and orchestration complexity for a workflow that has no branching or human approval steps. SQS + EC2 violates the requirement that uploads go to Kinesis, and EC2 requires capacity management. Firehose is optimized for high-throughput delivery pipelines to destinations like S3, but has buffering delays and a 5-minute Lambda transformation timeout that is brittle for complex 5-minute processing.',rule:'KDS + Lambda = serverless async stream processing. Firehose = delivery/ETL pipeline, not processing. Step Functions = workflow orchestration with branching/approval. Use Lambda event source mapping on KDS for simple async consumers.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t7',category:'Cost',question:'A company wants to organize the way it tracks its spending on AWS resources. A report that summarizes the total billing accrued by each department must be generated at the end of the month. Which solution will meet the requirements?',choices:['A|Tag resources with the department name and enable cost allocation tags.','B|Tag resources with the department name and configure a budget action in AWS Budget.','C|Use AWS Cost Explorer to view spending and filter usage data by Resource.','D|Create a Cost and Usage report for AWS services that each department is using.'],correct:'A',answer:'Cost allocation tags let you label AWS resources with key-value pairs (such as Department = Engineering). After activating the tags in Billing and Cost Management, AWS generates a cost allocation report as a CSV with costs grouped by active tags, enabling per-department billing summaries.',why:'Tags are applied to individual resources (EC2 instances, RDS clusters, S3 buckets, etc.). Once cost allocation tags are activated, the Billing console generates monthly reports that aggregate charges by tag value. This means one report shows Engineering costs, another shows Marketing costs, etc. — exactly what department billing summaries require. The CSV can be downloaded and shared automatically.',trap:'AWS Budgets sends alerts when spending crosses a threshold — it does not generate detailed billing summaries by department. Cost Explorer\'s Resource filter only tracks EC2 instance costs, not all resource types. The Cost and Usage Report (CUR) shows costs broken down by service but not by business unit/department unless combined with tags.',rule:'Department billing reports = tags + cost allocation tags activated. AWS Budgets = alerts only. CUR = service-level breakdown, not department-level unless combined with tags.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t8',category:'S3',question:'A solutions architect is instructed to host a website that consists of HTML, CSS, and some Javascript files. The web pages will display several high-resolution images. The website should have optimal loading times and be able to respond to high request rates. Which of the following architectures can provide the most cost-effective and fastest loading experience?',choices:['A|Upload the HTML, CSS, Javascript, and the images in a single bucket. Then enable website hosting. Create a CloudFront distribution and point the domain on the S3 website endpoint.','B|Host the website using an Nginx server in an EC2 instance. Upload the images in an S3 bucket. Use CloudFront as a CDN to deliver the images closer to end-users.','C|Launch an Auto Scaling Group using an AMI that has a pre-configured Apache web server, then configure the scaling policy accordingly. Store the images in an Elastic Block Store. Then, point your instance’s endpoint to AWS Global Accelerator.','D|Host the website in an AWS Elastic Beanstalk environment. Upload the images in an S3 bucket. Use CloudFront as a CDN to deliver the images closer to your end-users.'],correct:'A',answer:'S3 static website hosting serves HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and images directly from S3 without any server management. CloudFront caches all content at edge locations worldwide, providing fast loading and handling virtually unlimited request rates. This is the lowest-cost, zero-maintenance architecture for purely static content.',why:'A static website (no server-side processing, no database calls) has no need for a web server like Nginx or Apache. S3 can serve millions of GET requests per second. CloudFront caches the content globally, so users in any region load pages from a nearby edge location. You pay only for S3 storage and CloudFront data transfer — no EC2 instance costs, no load balancer costs, no Auto Scaling costs. S3 to CloudFront data transfer is also free.',trap:'EC2 with Nginx requires instance management, patching, and hourly compute charges even when traffic is zero. Auto Scaling + Apache adds unnecessary complexity and cost for static files. Elastic Beanstalk provisions EC2 infrastructure underneath — again, overkill and costly for static content. EBS is block storage attached to a single EC2 instance and cannot be used as a CDN origin.',rule:'Static website = S3 hosting + CloudFront. No EC2, no servers needed. S3 → CloudFront transfer is free. S3 scales automatically to any request rate.',keywords:'S3 static website: must enable static website hosting. Use CloudFront + S3 OAC for HTTPS on root domain.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t9',category:'Storage',question:'Both historical records and frequently accessed data are stored on an on-premises storage system. The amount of current data is growing at an exponential rate. As the storage’s capacity is nearing its limit, the company’s Solutions Architect has decided to move the historical records to AWS to free up space for the active data. Which of the following architectures deliver the best solution in terms of cost and operational management?',choices:['A|Use AWS DataSync to move the historical records from on-premises to AWS. Choose Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive to be the destination for the data.','B|Use AWS Storage Gateway to move the historical records from on-premises to AWS. Choose Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive to be the destination for the data.','C|Use AWS DataSync to move the historical records from on-premises to AWS. Choose Amazon S3 Standard to be the destination for the data. Modify the S3 lifecycle configuration to move the data from the Standard tier to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 30 days.','D|Use AWS Storage Gateway to move the historical records from on-premises to AWS. Choose Amazon S3 Glacier to be the destination for the data. Modify the S3 lifecycle configuration to move the data from the Standard tier to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 30 days.'],correct:'A',answer:'DataSync is purpose-built for migrating large data sets from on-premises to AWS quickly and efficiently. It can write directly to S3 Glacier Deep Archive, the cheapest storage class — no intermediate tier or lifecycle rule needed. DataSync is 10x faster than open-source tools and handles all the transfer mechanics automatically.',why:'DataSync installs a software agent on-premises that connects to your NFS/SMB file systems. It manages scheduling, monitoring, validation, and network optimization automatically. Historical records — data not frequently accessed — go straight to Glacier Deep Archive at $0.00099/GB/month with no detour through Standard pricing. DataSync is designed for this exact scenario: migrating cold archives from on-premises directly to low-cost AWS storage.',trap:'Storage Gateway is designed for hybrid cloud workloads where on-premises applications still need ongoing access to data through an AWS-backed cache — not for one-time migrations. Since the historical records are being fully moved to AWS, hybrid access is not needed. Option C unnecessarily routes data through S3 Standard (higher cost) and waits 30 days before archiving — DataSync can write directly to Glacier Deep Archive.',rule:'DataSync = migrate on-premises data to AWS (one-time or scheduled). Storage Gateway = hybrid access, on-premises cache backed by S3. DataSync can write directly to Glacier Deep Archive.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t10',category:'Storage',question:'A company has a requirement to move an 80 TB data warehouse to the cloud. It would take 2 months to transfer the data based on the current bandwidth allocation. Which option is the most cost-effective for quick data upload to AWS?',choices:['A|AWS DataSync','B|AWS Snowball Edge','C|AWS Direct Connect','D|Amazon S3 Multipart Upload'],correct:'B',answer:'Snowball Edge physically ships storage appliances to you. You copy data locally at full disk speed, then ship the devices back to AWS. AWS loads the data into S3 directly. 80 TB can be transferred in about a week regardless of internet bandwidth — far faster than any network-based option.',why:'Snowball Edge devices hold up to 80 TB each and transfer data at speeds faster than the internet by bypassing the network entirely. The 2-month estimate is the network transfer time — Snowball removes that bottleneck. AWS ships you the device, you copy locally, ship it back, and AWS ingests it. Total time is typically 1-2 weeks. DataSync, S3 Multipart Upload, and Direct Connect all still depend on the same limited bandwidth.',trap:'DataSync still uses the network — it optimizes transfers but cannot exceed the available bandwidth. S3 Multipart Upload also uses the internet connection and would still take 2 months. Direct Connect provides a dedicated circuit but provisioning takes weeks and it still has bandwidth limits — it\'s for ongoing connectivity, not one-time bulk migrations.',rule:'80TB over slow connection = Snowball Edge. Snowball bypasses the network entirely. DataSync/Multipart/Direct Connect all still bound by bandwidth. Snowball when: transfer time > 1 week over existing connection.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t11',category:'S3',question:'A digital media company shares static content to its premium users around the world and also to their partners who syndicate their media files. The company is looking for ways to reduce its server costs and securely deliver their data to their customers globally with low latency. Which combination of services should be used to provide the MOST suitable and cost-effective architecture? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Amazon CloudFront','B|AWS Fargate','C|AWS Lambda','D|Amazon S3','E|AWS Global Accelerator'],correct:'AD',answer:'Amazon S3 stores the static media files with high durability and scalability at very low cost. CloudFront delivers content from S3 to users globally via edge locations with low latency and high transfer speeds. Data transferred from S3 origins to CloudFront is free.',why:'S3 provides the durable, infinitely scalable origin for all static content. CloudFront caches copies at 400+ edge locations worldwide, so users stream or download from the nearest edge rather than the S3 origin. CloudFront also provides HTTPS, signed URLs for secure/premium access, geo-restrictions, and DDoS protection via AWS Shield. The combination is purpose-built for this use case.',trap:'Global Accelerator improves performance for non-HTTP use cases (gaming with UDP, IoT/MQTT, VoIP) or HTTP apps requiring static IPs — it does not cache content and cannot integrate directly with S3 as an origin the way CloudFront does. Fargate runs containers for compute workloads — not for storing or delivering static files. Lambda runs code — also not for static file delivery.',rule:'Static content globally = S3 + CloudFront. Global Accelerator = static IPs, non-HTTP (UDP/MQTT), no caching. CloudFront = HTTP/HTTPS CDN with caching, integrates with S3.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t12',category:'Other',question:'A business has a network of surveillance cameras installed within the premises of its data center. Management wants to leverage Artificial Intelligence to monitor and detect unauthorized personnel entering restricted areas. Should an unauthorized person be detected, the security team must be alerted via SMS. Which solution satisfies the requirement?',choices:['A|Utilize a custom containerized video processing application on Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS). Integrate AWS App2Container (A2C) and Amazon SageMaker Autopilot to detect unauthorized personnel. Set the phone numbers of the security team as subscribers to an Amazon SNS topic.','B|Configure Amazon Elastic Transcoder to stream live feeds from the cameras. Use Amazon Kendra to detect authorized personnel. Set the phone numbers of the security team as subscribers to an Amazon SNS topic.','C|Use Amazon Kinesis Video Streams to stream live feeds from the cameras. Use Amazon Rekognition to detect unauthorized personnel. Set the phone numbers of the security team as subscribers to an Amazon SNS topic.','D|Set up Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus to stream live feeds from the cameras. Use Amazon Fraud Detector to detect unauthorized personnel. Set the phone numbers of the security team as subscribers to an Amazon SNS topic.'],correct:'C',answer:'Kinesis Video Streams ingests live video from connected cameras. Rekognition Video analyzes the stream and can detect faces, objects, and scenes including unauthorized personnel. When a detection event occurs, SNS publishes SMS notifications to the security team\'s phone numbers.',why:'KVS is purpose-built for securely streaming video to AWS for analytics — it handles all the infrastructure for ingesting video from multiple cameras at scale. Rekognition Video provides pre-built AI/ML models for face detection, recognition, and content moderation that work directly on KVS streams without training your own model. SNS delivers SMS to multiple subscribers in seconds. The three services together form a complete, fully managed pipeline with no custom ML development.',trap:'Elastic Transcoder is for converting video between formats (mp4 to HLS, etc.) — not for streaming or AI analysis. Amazon Kendra is an enterprise search service — it cannot detect people in video. SageMaker Autopilot requires you to train a custom ML model, violating the "least effort" requirement. Amazon Fraud Detector is for detecting financial fraud patterns — completely unrelated to video surveillance.',rule:'Live video AI detection = Kinesis Video Streams (ingest) + Rekognition (detect) + SNS (alert). No custom ML needed. Kendra = search. Fraud Detector = financial fraud only.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t13',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect created a new Standard-class Amazon S3 bucket to store financial reports that are not frequently accessed but should immediately be available when an auditor requests the reports. To save costs, the Architect changed the storage class of the S3 bucket from Standard to Infrequent Access storage class. In S3 Standard - Infrequent Access storage class, which of the following statements are true? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|It is designed for data that is accessed less frequently.','B|It automatically moves data to the most cost-effective access tier without any operational overhead.','C|It is designed for data that requires rapid access when needed.','D|It provides high latency and low throughput performance.','E|Ideal to use for data archiving.'],correct:'AC',answer:'S3 Standard-IA is specifically designed for data that is accessed infrequently but requires rapid access when it is needed. It offers the same low latency and high throughput as S3 Standard, but with a lower per-GB storage price and a per-GB retrieval fee.',why:'Standard-IA suits disaster recovery backups, audit files, and compliance data — accessed rarely but must be immediately available when needed. The retrieval fee makes it cost-ineffective for frequently accessed data, but the lower storage price makes it cheaper than Standard for cold data. It maintains 11 nines durability and multi-AZ availability just like S3 Standard, unlike One-Zone-IA.',trap:'Automatic tier movement describes S3 Intelligent-Tiering, which monitors access patterns and moves objects between tiers automatically. Standard-IA has a fixed storage tier — you must manually move objects or use lifecycle rules. High latency / low throughput is the opposite of reality — Standard-IA has the same performance as Standard. Data archiving describes Glacier, not Standard-IA.',rule:'S3 Standard-IA = less frequent access + immediate availability when needed + same performance as Standard. Intelligent-Tiering = automatic tier movement. Glacier = archival with retrieval delay.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t14',category:'Networking',question:'A company launched a website that accepts high-quality photos and turns the photos into a downloadable video montage. The website offers both a free and a premium account, with the premium account guaranteeing faster processing. All requests by both free and premium members go through a single Amazon SQS queue and are then processed by a group of Amazon EC2 instances that generate the videos. The company needs to ensure that premium users, who paid for the service, have higher priority than free members. How should the company re-design its architecture to address this requirement?',choices:['A|For the requests made by premium members, set a higher priority in the SQS queue so it will be processed first compared to the requests made by free members.','B|Create an SQS queue for free members and another one for premium members. Configure your EC2 instances to consume messages from the premium queue first and if it is empty, poll from the free members\' SQS queue.','C|Use Amazon Kinesis to process the photos and generate the video montage in real-time.','D|Use Amazon S3 to store and process the photos and then generate the video montage afterward.'],correct:'B',answer:'SQS does not support message priority within a single queue. The correct pattern is two separate queues — premium and free. EC2 instances poll the premium queue first, processing all available premium jobs before polling the free queue. This guarantees premium users always get resources ahead of free users.',why:'SQS FIFO delivers messages in order, but there is no native priority mechanism within a single queue. By having two queues, the workers implement priority at the polling level: check premium queue → if not empty, process; if empty, check free queue. This is a well-established pattern called "competing consumers with priority queues." You can also assign more workers to the premium queue for even more separation.',trap:'SQS does not support per-message priority — this is not a feature that exists. Kinesis Data Streams is for real-time streaming analytics of high-volume data — it is not a video processing or job queue service. S3 is object storage — it cannot process photos or generate videos.',rule:'SQS priority pattern = two separate queues (high + low priority). Workers poll high-priority queue first. No native priority within a single SQS queue.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t15',category:'Networking',question:'A global company has deployed numerous AWS Outposts servers in various remote locations worldwide. These servers frequently need to download software updates consisting of multiple files from an S3 bucket in the us-west-2 region. The company is experiencing significant delays in distributing these updates across all servers. What solution would most effectively reduce the deployment latency while minimizing operational overhead?',choices:['A|Set up an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the us-west-2 S3 bucket as the primary origin and create a secondary origin in another region, implementing a CachingDisabled cache policy. Use signed URLs for downloads.','B|Set up AWS Global Accelerator to route traffic from Outposts servers to the nearest AWS edge location, then use private VIF connections to access the S3 bucket in us-west-2.','C|Use Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration on the existing S3 bucket and have the Outposts servers use the Transfer Acceleration endpoint for downloads.','D|Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the us-west-2 S3 bucket as the origin. Use signed URLs for software downloads.'],correct:'D',answer:'CloudFront caches the software update files at edge locations near each Outposts server globally. Outposts servers download from the nearest edge location rather than traversing to us-west-2 directly. Signed URLs provide secure, controlled access to the software packages.',why:'CloudFront has 400+ edge locations worldwide. Once an update file is cached at an edge location, all Outposts in that region download from that edge rather than from S3 in us-west-2. For frequently downloaded files like software updates (multiple Outposts downloading the same files), the cache hit rate is high, dramatically reducing both latency and origin data transfer costs. Signed URLs prevent unauthorized downloads.',trap:'Option A disables caching (CachingDisabled policy) which eliminates the entire benefit of CloudFront — every request goes all the way to S3. Global Accelerator routes traffic to the nearest AWS region but does not cache content — it does not reduce latency for S3 downloads. S3 Transfer Acceleration uses edge locations to speed up uploads to S3, not downloads from S3.',rule:'Outposts → S3 global distribution = CloudFront + signed URLs. Transfer Acceleration = uploads only. CachingDisabled policy = defeats the purpose of CloudFront. Global Accelerator = no caching.',keywords:'Fixed IP for load balancer (firewall whitelisting) → Global Accelerator (2 static IPs) or NLB + EIP.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t16',category:'Networking',question:'An insurance company plans to implement a message filtering feature in its web application. To implement this solution, it needs to create separate Amazon SQS queues for each type of quote request. The entire message processing should not exceed 24 hours. As the Solutions Architect for the company, which of the following solutions should be implemented to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Create one Amazon SNS topic and configure the SQS queues to subscribe to the SNS topic. Set the filter policies in the SNS subscriptions to publish the message to the designated SQS queue based on its quote request type.','B|Create one Amazon SNS topic and configure the SQS queues to subscribe to the SNS topic. Publish the same messages to all SQS queues. Filter the messages in each queue based on the quote request type.','C|Create multiple Amazon SNS topics and configure the SQS queues to subscribe to the SNS topics. Publish the message to the designated SQS queue based on the quote request type.','D|Create a data stream in Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. Use the Kinesis Client Library to deliver all the records to the designated SQS queues based on the quote request type.'],correct:'A',answer:'SNS message filtering lets you assign a filter policy to each SQS subscription. Only messages matching the filter policy attributes are delivered to that queue. One SNS topic fans out to multiple SQS queues, with each queue receiving only its relevant message type based on the filter policy.',why:'The SNS fan-out pattern is: publish once to a topic, deliver to all subscribers. Without filter policies, every queue receives every message — wasteful and incorrect. Filter policies are JSON conditions attached to a subscription that check message attributes. A "home insurance" queue only receives messages where the attribute QuoteType=home. This is done in one SNS topic with per-subscription filter policies, no additional infrastructure needed. SQS default retention is 4 days, well within the 24-hour requirement.',trap:'Option B delivers all messages to all queues — filtering after delivery wastes resources and requires custom filtering logic in each consumer. Multiple SNS topics per quote type works but adds unnecessary overhead — filter policies are the purpose-built mechanism. Kinesis is for real-time streaming analytics, not message routing or filtering.',rule:'SNS filter policies = route messages to specific SQS subscriptions by attribute value. One topic + filter policies = fan-out to designated queues. No code changes needed in producers.',keywords:'Route SNS messages to specific SQS subscribers → SNS filter policies (by message attributes).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t17',category:'Networking',question:'A media company wants to ensure that the images it delivers through Amazon CloudFront are compatible across various user devices. The company plans to serve images in WebP format to user agents that support it and return to JPEG format for those that don\'t. Additionally, the company wants to add a custom header to the response for tracking purposes. As a solution architect, what approach would one recommend to meet these requirements while minimizing operational overhead?',choices:['A|Configure CloudFront behaviors to handle different image formats based on the User-Agent header. Use Lambda@Edge functions to modify the response headers and serve the appropriate format.','B|Create multiple CloudFront distributions, each serving a specific image format (WebP or JPEG). Route incoming requests based on the User-Agent header to the respective distribution using Amazon Route 53.','C|Generate a CloudFront response headers policy. Utilize the policy to deliver the suitable image format according to the User-Agent HTTP header in the incoming request.','D|Implement an image conversion service on Amazon EC2 instances and integrate it with CloudFront. Use AWS Lambda functions to modify the response headers and serve the appropriate format based on the User-Agent header.'],correct:'A',answer:'Configure CloudFront behaviors to handle different image formats based on the User-Agent header. Use Lambda@Edge functions to modify the response headers and serve the appropriate format.',why:'Amazon CloudFront is a content delivery network (CDN) service that enables the efficient distribution of web content to users across the globe. It reduces latency by caching static and dynamic content in multiple edge locations worldwide and improves the overall user experience.',trap:'The option that says: Create multiple CloudFront distributions, each serving a specific image format (WebP or JPEG).',rule:'Use Lambda@Edge functions to modify the response headers and serve the appropriate format.',keywords:'Run logic at CloudFront edge → Lambda@Edge. Reduces latency by executing near user.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t18',category:'Networking',question:'A software company has resources hosted in AWS and on-premises servers. You have been requested to create a decoupled architecture for applications which make use of both resources. Which of the following options are valid? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use SWF to utilize both on-premises servers and EC2 instances for your decoupled application','B|Use RDS to utilize both on-premises servers and EC2 instances for your decoupled application','C|Use SQS to utilize both on-premises servers and EC2 instances for your decoupled application','D|Use VPC peering to connect both on-premises servers and EC2 instances for your decoupled application','E|Use DynamoDB to utilize both on-premises servers and EC2 instances for your decoupled application'],correct:'AC',answer:'SQS (Simple Queue Service) decouples components by asynchronously passing messages between them — both on-premises and EC2 workers can read from and write to SQS queues. SWF (Simple Workflow Service) coordinates tasks across distributed components including on-premises servers and EC2 instances.',why:'Decoupled architecture means components communicate through intermediaries rather than direct connections — so a failure or slowdown in one component does not cascade. SQS provides the queue intermediary; producers and consumers can be on-premises or in EC2, and they do not need to be simultaneously available. SWF coordinates multi-step workflows across heterogeneous workers without tight coupling. Both services have public endpoints accessible from on-premises over the internet or via VPN.',trap:'RDS and DynamoDB are database services — they store and retrieve data but are not messaging or workflow services for decoupling application components. VPC peering connects two VPCs — it cannot be used to connect on-premises networks to a VPC (that requires Direct Connect or VPN).',rule:'Decoupled architecture services = SQS (async messaging) + SWF (workflow coordination). VPC peering = VPC-to-VPC only, cannot include on-premises. RDS/DynamoDB = databases, not decoupling services.',keywords:'Orchestrate multi-step workflows (with branching, retries, waits) → AWS Step Functions.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t19',category:'Security',question:'A company owns a photo-sharing app that stores user uploads on Amazon S3. There has been an increase in the number of explicit and offensive images being reported. The company currently relies on human efforts to moderate content, and it wants to streamline this process by using Artificial Intelligence to only flag images for review. For added security, any communication with its resources on its Amazon VPC must not traverse the public Internet. How can this task be accomplished with the LEAST amount of effort?',choices:['A|Use Amazon Rekognition to detect images with graphic nudity or violence in S3. Create an Interface VPC endpoint for Rekognition with the necessary policies to prevent any traffic from traversing the public Internet.','B|Use an image classification model in Amazon SageMaker. Set up Amazon GuardDuty and connect it with SageMaker to ensure that all communications do not traverse the public Internet.','C|Use Amazon Detective to detect images with graphic nudity or violence in S3. Ensure that all communications made by your AWS resources do not traverse the public Internet via the AWS Audit Manager service.','D|Use AWS Lambda to create custom image moderation logic. Deploy this Lambda function in a public VPC to ensure communication through the public Internet.'],correct:'A',answer:'Use Amazon Rekognition to detect images with graphic nudity or violence in S3. Create an Interface VPC endpoint for Rekognition with the necessary policies to prevent any traffic from traversing the public Internet.',why:'Amazon Rekognition can help you streamline or automate image and video moderation workflows using machine learning. Using fully managed image and video moderation APIs, you can proactively detect inappropriate, unwanted, or offensive content containing nudity, suggestiveness, violence, and other such categories.',trap:'The option that says: Use an image classification model in Amazon SageMaker.',rule:'Create an Interface VPC endpoint for Rekognition with the necessary policies to prevent any traffic from traversing the public Internet.',keywords:'Threat detection / suspicious activity → GuardDuty. Uses ML + threat intelligence.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t20',category:'Networking',question:'A company is running a multi-tier web application farm in a virtual private cloud (VPC) that is not connected to their corporate network. They are connecting to the VPC over the Internet to manage the fleet of Amazon EC2 instances running in both the public and private subnets. The Solutions Architect has added a bastion host with Microsoft Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) access to the application instance security groups, but the company wants to further limit administrative access to all of the instances in the VPC. Which of the following bastion host deployment options will meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Deploy a Windows Bastion host on the corporate network that has RDP access to all EC2 instances in the VPC.','B|Deploy a Windows Bastion host with an Elastic IP address in the private subnet, and restrict RDP access to the bastion from only the corporate public IP addresses.','C|Deploy a Windows Bastion host with an Elastic IP address in the public subnet and allow SSH access to the bastion from anywhere.','D|Deploy a Windows Bastion host with an Elastic IP address in the public subnet and allow RDP access to bastion only from the corporate IP addresses.'],correct:'D',answer:'A Windows bastion host must be in a public subnet with an Elastic IP so it is reachable from the Internet. RDP access should be restricted to only the corporate public IP addresses in the security group, limiting administrative access exclusively to the office network.',why:'The bastion host is the single ingress point for administrative access. Placing it in a public subnet with an Elastic IP makes it reachable from the corporate network. Restricting the security group inbound RDP rule to the company\'s public IP address range means only users connecting from the office (or VPN) can even reach the bastion. From the bastion, administrators then RDP or SSH into the private instances using private IP addresses.',trap:'Deploying the bastion on the corporate network is architecturally wrong — the bastion must be inside the AWS VPC (public subnet) to provide the bridge from corporate to private instances. A private subnet bastion has no public IP and cannot be reached from the corporate network over the Internet without additional routing. SSH is the protocol for Linux — Windows instances use RDP. Allowing SSH from anywhere exposes the bastion globally.',rule:'Windows bastion = public subnet + Elastic IP + RDP restricted to corporate IPs. Private subnet = unreachable from Internet. Windows = RDP (port 3389), not SSH.',keywords:'Rate-limit individual IPs → WAF rate-based rule. Blocks IPs exceeding threshold per 5 min.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t21',category:'Database',question:'A company receives semi-structured and structured data from different sources, which are eventually stored in their Amazon S3 data lake. The Solutions Architect plans to use big data processing frameworks to analyze these data and access it using various business intelligence tools and standard SQL queries. Which of the following provides the MOST high-performing solution that fulfills this requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Glue and store the processed data in Amazon S3.','B|Create an Amazon EMR cluster and store the processed data in Amazon Redshift.','C|Use Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink Studio and store the processed data in Amazon DynamoDB.','D|Create an Amazon EC2 instance and store the processed data in Amazon EBS.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon EMR runs big data frameworks (Hadoop, Spark, Hive) to process and transform large data sets from S3. Amazon Redshift is a columnar data warehouse optimized for complex SQL queries from BI tools, with massively parallel query execution across petabytes of data.',why:'The two key requirements are: (1) big data processing frameworks and (2) standard SQL + BI tools. EMR handles (1) — it manages clusters running Spark, Hive, or Hadoop, processes the S3 data, and can load results into Redshift. Redshift handles (2) — it connects natively to BI tools (Tableau, QuickSight, Power BI) and executes complex analytical SQL using columnar storage and parallel processing. The combination is the AWS reference architecture for data lake analytics.',trap:'Glue is primarily an ETL service and data catalog — it can process data but lacks Redshift\'s query performance for BI workloads. S3 with Athena can do SQL queries but does not match Redshift\'s performance for heavy analytical workloads. Apache Flink is for real-time stream processing — not batch analytics. DynamoDB is a key-value/document store — it does not support complex SQL analytics or BI tool integration.',rule:'Big data + BI + SQL analytics = EMR (process) + Redshift (warehouse). Flink = streaming. Glue = ETL/catalog. Athena = serverless SQL on S3 (good for ad-hoc, not heavy BI).',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t22',category:'Database',question:'A company has an on-premises MySQL database that needs to be replicated in Amazon S3 as CSV files. The database will eventually be launched to an Amazon Aurora Serverless cluster and be integrated with an RDS Proxy to allow the web applications to pool and share database connections. Once data has been fully copied, the ongoing changes to the on-premises database should be continually streamed into the S3 bucket. The company wants a solution that can be implemented with little management overhead yet still highly secure. Which ingestion pattern should a solutions architect take?',choices:['A|Set up a full load replication task using AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS). Launch an AWS DMS endpoint with SSL using the AWS Network Firewall service.','B|Create a full load and change data capture (CDC) replication task using AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS). Add a new Certificate Authority (CA) certificate and create an AWS DMS endpoint with SSL.','C|Use an AWS Snowball Edge cluster to migrate data to Amazon S3 and AWS DataSync to capture ongoing changes. Create your own custom AWS KMS envelope encryption key for the associated AWS Snowball Edge job.','D|Use AWS Schema Conversion Tool (AWS SCT) to convert MySQL data to CSV files. Set up the AWS Application Migration Service (AWS MGN) to capture ongoing changes from the on-premises MySQL database and send them to Amazon S3.'],correct:'B',answer:'DMS full load copies the initial dataset. CDC (Change Data Capture) continuously replicates every subsequent insert, update, and delete from the MySQL transaction log to S3 in near-real-time. SSL with a CA certificate encrypts the data in transit, meeting security requirements without additional services.',why:'DMS reads the MySQL binary log for CDC — every change to the source is replicated to the S3 target as CSV files. The target S3 bucket accumulates both the initial full load and all ongoing changes. To secure the connection, you upload a CA certificate to DMS and configure the endpoint to require SSL. This is entirely managed by DMS — no VPN, no Network Firewall, no additional services. DMS can also directly target Aurora MySQL for the eventual migration.',trap:'A full load only captures the current state — it does not capture ongoing changes, so the S3 bucket goes stale immediately. Network Firewall cannot configure DMS endpoints; SSL is configured directly within DMS. Snowball is for physical offline data transfers, not for streaming live database changes. AWS SCT converts schemas between database engines — it does not replicate data. MGN is for lift-and-shift VM migrations, not database CDC.',rule:'MySQL → S3 ongoing sync = DMS full load + CDC. SSL = CA certificate added to DMS endpoint. SCT = schema conversion only. MGN = VM lift-and-shift, not database.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t23',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has a cryptocurrency exchange portal that is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer and is deployed across multiple AWS regions. The users can be found all around the globe, but the majority are from Japan and Sweden. Because of the compliance requirements in these two locations, you want the Japanese users to connect to the servers in the ap-northeast-1 Asia Pacific (Tokyo) region, while the Swedish users should be connected to the servers in the eu-west-1 EU (Ireland) region. Which of the following services would allow you to easily fulfill this requirement?',choices:['A|Use Route 53 Geolocation Routing policy.','B|Set up an Application Load Balancers that will automatically route the traffic to the proper AWS region.','C|Set up a new CloudFront web distribution with the geo-restriction feature enabled.','D|Use Route 53 Weighted Routing policy.'],correct:'A',answer:'Geolocation routing lets you choose the resources that serve your traffic based on the geographic location of your users, meaning the location that DNS queries originate from. For example, you might want all queries from Europe to be routed to an ELB load balancer in the Frankfurt region.',why:'When you use geolocation routing, you can localize your content and present some or all of your website in the language of your users. You can also use geolocation routing to restrict the distribution of content to only the locations in which you have distribution rights.',trap:'Setting up an Application Load Balancers that will automatically route the traffic to the proper AWS region is incorrect because Elastic Load Balancers distribute traffic among EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones but not across AWS regions.',rule:'For example, you might want all queries from Europe to be routed to an ELB load balancer in the Frankfurt region.',keywords:'Route by exact country (compliance) → Geolocation Routing. All-or-nothing per country.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t24',category:'Networking',question:'A company has developed public APIs hosted in Amazon EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load Balancer. The APIs will be used by various clients from their respective on-premises data centers. A Solutions Architect received a report that the web service clients can only access trusted IP addresses whitelisted on their firewalls. What should you do to accomplish the above requirement?',choices:['A|Associate an Elastic IP address to a Network Load Balancer.','B|Create a CloudFront distribution whose origin points to the private IP addresses of your web servers.','C|Associate an Elastic IP address to an Application Load Balancer.','D|Create an Alias Record in Route 53 which maps to the DNS name of the load balancer.'],correct:'A',answer:'Network Load Balancers support Elastic IP addresses — one per AZ. Using BYOIP (Bring Your Own IP) or AWS-provided EIPs on the NLB gives the load balancer a static, predictable IP address that clients can whitelist in their firewalls. The IP never changes regardless of backend scaling.',why:'ALBs use dynamic IP addresses that change as AWS scales the load balancer fleet — clients cannot reliably whitelist them. NLBs are Layer 4 devices that support static Elastic IP addresses per AZ, providing a stable IP for client firewall whitelisting. Clients add the NLB\'s EIP to their firewall allowlist once and it never needs updating. The NLB then distributes traffic across the EC2 instances in its target group.',trap:'You cannot attach an Elastic IP to an Application Load Balancer — this is not supported. ALBs have DNS names with dynamic IPs. CloudFront uses Anycast IPs at edge locations — these are not stable for firewall whitelisting purposes. Route 53 Alias records point to the dynamic DNS name of the load balancer, which does not resolve to a static IP.',rule:'Static IP for load balancer = Network Load Balancer + Elastic IP. ALB = no static IP support. NLB = static EIP per AZ, Layer 4, good for IP whitelisting.',keywords:'Fixed IP for load balancer (firewall whitelisting) → Global Accelerator (2 static IPs) or NLB + EIP.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t25',category:'Networking',question:'A company has multiple VPCs with IPv6 enabled for its suite of web applications. The Solutions Architect attempted to deploy a new Amazon EC2 instance but encountered an error indicating that there were no available IP addresses on the subnet. The VPC has a combination of IPv4 and IPv6 CIDR blocks, but the IPv4 CIDR blocks are nearing exhaustion. The architect needs a solution that will resolve this issue while allowing future scalability. How should the Solutions Architect resolve this problem?',choices:['A|Set up a new IPv4 subnet with a larger CIDR range. Associate the new subnet with the VPC and then launch the instance.','B|Ensure that the VPC has IPv6 CIDRs only. Remove any IPv4 CIDRs associated with the VPC.','C|Set up a new IPv6-only subnet with a large CIDR range. Associate the new subnet with the VPC then launch the instance.','D|Disable the IPv4 support in the VPC and use the available IPv6 addresses.'],correct:'C',answer:'Creating an IPv6-only subnet leverages the available IPv6 address space (which is essentially unlimited — each /64 subnet has 18 quintillion addresses) to solve the IPv4 exhaustion problem immediately, while preserving existing IPv4 resources and providing long-term scalability.',why:'IPv6 subnets use /64 prefixes by default, providing an astronomically large address space that eliminates exhaustion concerns permanently. Since the VPC already has IPv6 CIDRs enabled, creating an IPv6-only subnet is straightforward. The new EC2 instance is launched in the IPv6-only subnet and communicates using IPv6. Existing IPv4 resources continue working in their subnets — the dual-stack VPC operates both protocols independently.',trap:'Adding a new IPv4 subnet temporarily solves the problem but IPv4 space is finite — the same exhaustion will recur as the company grows, making this a short-term fix. You cannot remove IPv4 from a VPC — IPv4 is mandatory and cannot be disabled. This is an AWS hard constraint. Similarly, you cannot disable IPv4 support in a VPC — it is the default and required addressing system.',rule:'IPv4 exhausted in VPC → create IPv6-only subnet. Cannot remove IPv4 from VPC — AWS hard constraint. IPv6 /64 = 18 quintillion addresses. Dual-stack VPC: IPv4 and IPv6 operate independently.',keywords:'IPv4 exhausted in VPC → create IPv6-only subnet. Cannot disable IPv4 from VPC (mandatory).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t26',category:'Database',question:'A music publishing company is building a multitier web application that requires a key-value store which will save the document models. Each model is composed of band ID, album ID, song ID, composer ID, lyrics, and other data. The web tier will be hosted in an Amazon ECS cluster with AWS Fargate launch type. Which of the following is the MOST suitable setup for the database-tier?',choices:['A|Launch an Amazon RDS database with Read Replicas.','B|Launch a DynamoDB table.','C|Use Amazon WorkDocs to store the document models.','D|Launch an Amazon Aurora Serverless database.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database that natively supports both key-value and document data models. With the band ID or song ID as the partition key, DynamoDB provides single-digit millisecond latency at any scale — perfectly suited for application document models.',why:'DynamoDB\'s flexible schema allows each item to have different attributes, ideal for document models that may evolve. The key-value access pattern (retrieve a song by its ID) is DynamoDB\'s primary use case. It scales horizontally without any capacity planning for most workloads (on-demand mode), integrates directly with ECS containers via IAM roles, and requires no server or cluster management. With built-in replication across 3 AZs, it is highly available by default.',trap:'RDS with Read Replicas is a relational database — it requires a predefined schema with tables and rows and does not support the flexible key-value document model described. Aurora Serverless is also relational SQL — not a key-value store. Amazon WorkDocs is a document collaboration service (like Google Docs) — it is for business document sharing, not as an application data store.',rule:'Key-value or document store requirement = DynamoDB. RDS/Aurora = relational SQL with fixed schema. WorkDocs = business document collaboration tool, not a database.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t27',category:'Database',question:'A company hosts its web application on a set of Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The application has an embedded NoSQL database. As the application receives more traffic, the application becomes overloaded mainly due to database requests. The management wants to ensure that the database is eventually consistent and highly available. Which of the following options can meet the company requirements with the least operational overhead?',choices:['A|Change the ALB with a Network Load Balancer (NLB) to handle more traffic and integrate AWS Global Accelerator to ensure high availability. Configure replication of the NoSQL database on the set of EC2 instances to spread the database load.','B|Configure the Auto Scaling group to spread the EC2 instances across three Availability Zones. Use the AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) with a replication server and an ongoing replication task to migrate the embedded NoSQL database to Amazon DynamoDB.','C|Change the ALB with a Network Load Balancer (NLB) to handle more traffic. Use the AWS Glue DynamoDB export connector to export data from Amazon DynamoDB to Amazon S3 for analytics periodically, and continue running the application’s NoSQL database on the EC2 instances.','D|Configure the Auto Scaling group to spread the EC2 instances across three Availability Zones. Configure replication of the NoSQL database on the set of EC2 instances to spread the database load.'],correct:'B',answer:'Spreading EC2 instances across 3 AZs improves availability. DMS with CDC migrates the embedded NoSQL data to DynamoDB continuously — DynamoDB is a fully managed, eventually consistent, highly available service that requires zero operational overhead for scaling, patching, or replication.',why:'The root problem is an embedded NoSQL database on EC2 — self-managed databases require manual scaling, patching, backup, and replication configuration. DynamoDB is AWS\'s managed alternative: it auto-scales read/write capacity, replicates across 3 AZs automatically, and provides eventual consistency by default. DMS with ongoing CDC replication migrates the current data and streams all subsequent changes to DynamoDB, enabling a live migration without downtime.',trap:'Running a custom NoSQL on EC2 with self-configured replication has high operational overhead — you manage sharding, replication lag, failover, backups, and patching manually. Global Accelerator is for multi-region applications with static IPs — inappropriate here. The Glue DynamoDB export connector exports from DynamoDB to S3, not the other way around — and it leaves the problem database on EC2.',rule:'Self-managed NoSQL on EC2 → migrate to DynamoDB with DMS CDC for live migration. DynamoDB = managed, eventual consistency, auto-scales, multi-AZ. Operational overhead = near zero.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t28',category:'Storage',question:'A company plans to migrate all of their applications to AWS. The Solutions Architect suggested to store all the data to EBS volumes. The Chief Technical Officer is worried that EBS volumes are not appropriate for the existing workloads due to compliance requirements, downtime scenarios, and IOPS performance. Which of the following are valid points in proving that EBS is the best service to use for migration? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|When you create an EBS volume in an Availability Zone, it is automatically replicated on a separate AWS region to prevent data loss due to a failure of any single hardware component.','B|EBS volumes can be attached to any EC2 Instance in any Availability Zone.','C|An EBS volume is off-instance storage that can persist independently from the life of an instance.','D|EBS volumes support live configuration changes while in production which means that you can modify the volume type, volume size, and IOPS capacity without service interruptions.','E|Amazon EBS provides the ability to create snapshots (backups) of any EBS volume and write a copy of the data in the volume to Amazon RDS, where it is stored redundantly in multiple Availability Zones'],correct:'CD',answer:'An Amazon EBS volume is a durable, block-level storage device that you can attach to a single EC2 instance. You can use EBS volumes as primary storage for data that requires frequent updates, such as the system drive for an instance or storage for a database application. You can also use them for throughput-intensive applications that perform continuous disk scans.',why:'The option that says: Amazon EBS provides the ability to create snapshots (backups) of any EBS volume and write a copy of the data in the volume to Amazon RDS, where it is stored redundantly in multiple Availability Zones is almost correct. But instead of storing the volume to Amazon RDS, the EBS Volume snapshots are actually sent to Amazon S3.',trap:'EBS volumes are AZ-specific — you cannot attach an EBS volume in us-east-1a to an EC2 instance in us-east-1b. The correct way to move an EBS volume across AZs is to create a snapshot, then restore it in the target AZ. EBS does NOT provide cross-AZ or cross-region replication automatically.',rule:'You can also use them for throughput-intensive applications that perform continuous disk scans.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t29',category:'EC2',question:'A commercial bank has a forex trading application. They created an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances that allow the bank to cope with the current traffic and achieve cost-efficiency. They want the Auto Scaling group to behave in such a way that it will follow a predefined set of parameters before it scales down the number of EC2 instances, which protects the system from unintended slowdown or unavailability. Which of the following statements are true regarding the cooldown period? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|It ensures that before the Auto Scaling group scales out, the EC2 instances have an ample time to cooldown.','B|It ensures that the Auto Scaling group launches or terminates additional EC2 instances without any downtime.','C|It ensures that the Auto Scaling group does not launch or terminate additional EC2 instances before the previous scaling activity takes effect.','D|Its default value is 300 seconds.','E|Its default value is 600 seconds.'],correct:'CD',answer:'In Auto Scaling, the following statements are correct regarding the cooldown period:\n\n- It ensures the ASG does not launch/terminate instances before the previous scaling activity takes effect.\n- Default value is 300 seconds.\n- It is a configurable setting for your ASG.',why:'It ensures that the Auto Scaling group does not launch or terminate additional EC2 instances before the previous scaling activity takes effect.',trap:'The cooldown period prevents the ASG from launching OR terminating additional instances — it works in both scale-out and scale-in directions. It is not a "warmup" for new instances; that is a separate setting called instance warm-up. Cooldown applies to simple scaling policies; target tracking and step scaling have their own stabilisation logic.',rule:'ASG cooldown = pause between scale actions so new instances stabilise before next scale decision. Default 300 sec. Prevents thrashing. Cooldown does NOT affect scheduled scaling. Each scale action resets the cooldown timer.',keywords:'ASG cooldown default = 300 sec. Prevents thrashing between scaling actions. Applies after scaling activity.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t30',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company is running a custom application in an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances. Several instances are failing due to insufficient swap space. The Solutions Architect has been instructed to troubleshoot the issue and effectively monitor the available swap space of each EC2 instance. Which of the following options fulfills this requirement?',choices:['A|Enable detailed monitoring on each instance and monitor the SwapUtilization metric.','B|Create a new trail in AWS CloudTrail and configure Amazon CloudWatch Logs to monitor your trail logs.','C|Install the CloudWatch agent on each instance and monitor the SwapUtilization metric.','D|Create a CloudWatch dashboard and monitor the SwapUsed metric.'],correct:'C',answer:'The CloudWatch agent must be installed on EC2 instances to collect OS-level metrics that are not available through the default CloudWatch monitoring. SwapUtilization is a custom metric collected by the agent from the OS — it tracks the percentage of swap space in use across all monitored instances.',why:'Default CloudWatch metrics for EC2 are collected at the hypervisor level and include: CPUUtilization, DiskReadOps, NetworkIn, etc. They do NOT include memory or swap metrics because the hypervisor cannot see inside the guest OS memory. The CloudWatch agent runs as a process inside the OS, reads /proc/swaps (Linux) or Windows Performance Counters, and publishes the metrics to CloudWatch as custom metrics. You configure which metrics to collect via a JSON configuration file.',trap:'Enabling detailed monitoring increases the frequency of default metrics to 1-minute intervals — but it does not add new metric types like swap space. SwapUtilization is not a default metric, so you cannot monitor it without the agent. CloudTrail tracks API calls (who did what in AWS) — not OS-level performance metrics. You cannot create a CloudWatch dashboard for metrics that are not being published yet.',rule:'Swap/memory metrics on EC2 = must install CloudWatch agent. Default EC2 metrics = no memory or swap. Detailed monitoring = more frequent collection, same metric set.',keywords:'Memory, swap, disk space on EC2 → NOT default CloudWatch. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t31',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has an enterprise web application hosted on Amazon ECS Docker containers that use an Amazon FSx for Lustre filesystem for its high-performance computing workloads. A warm standby environment is running in another AWS region for disaster recovery. A Solutions Architect was assigned to design a system that will automatically route the live traffic to the disaster recovery (DR) environment only in the event that the primary application stack experiences an outage. What should the Architect do to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Set up a failover routing policy configuration in Route 53 by adding a health check on the primary service endpoint. Configure Route 53 to direct the DNS queries to the secondary record when the primary resource is unhealthy. Configure the network access control list and the route table to allow Route 53 to send requests to the endpoints specified in the health checks. Enable the Evaluate Target Health option by setting it to Yes.','B|SSet up an ​Amazon EventBridge rule to monitor the primary Route 53 DNS endpoint and create a custom AWS Lambda function. Execute the ChangeResourceRecordSets API call using the function to initiate the failover to the secondary DNS record.','C|Set up a Weighted routing policy configuration in Route 53 by adding health checks on both the primary stack and the DR environment. Configure the network access control list and the route table to allow Route 53 to send requests to the endpoints specified in the health checks. Enable the Evaluate Target Health option by setting it to Yes.','D|Set up an Amazon CloudWatch Alarm to monitor the primary Route 53 DNS endpoint and create a custom AWS Lambda function. Execute the ChangeResourceRecordSets API call using the function to initiate the failover to the secondary DNS record.'],correct:'A',answer:'Route 53 Failover routing policy (active-passive) designates one record as primary and another as secondary. Health checks continuously monitor the primary endpoint. When the health check fails, Route 53 automatically stops returning the primary record and starts returning the secondary record for all DNS queries.',why:'Route 53 Failover routing is built exactly for active-passive DR scenarios. Health checkers probe the primary endpoint from multiple locations globally at configurable intervals. When the endpoint fails health checks from multiple locations, Route 53 automatically updates DNS responses to point to the secondary. NACLs and route tables must permit inbound traffic from Route 53 health checker IP ranges to the monitored endpoints for the checks to succeed. Evaluate Target Health enables Route 53 to evaluate the health of targets behind load balancers.',trap:'Weighted routing distributes traffic between records based on weight percentages — it does not implement primary/secondary failover. Both records always serve traffic based on their weights. EventBridge cannot directly monitor Route 53 endpoint health. Implementing failover via Lambda + ChangeResourceRecordSets adds custom code and introduces delay. CloudWatch Alarms monitor CloudWatch metrics, not Route 53 endpoint reachability.',rule:'Active-passive DR = Route 53 Failover routing policy + health checks. Primary/secondary designation. Automatic DNS failover when health check fails. Weighted = traffic split, not failover.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t32',category:'Route 53',question:'A company runs a messaging application in the ap-northeast-1 and ap-southeast-2 region. A Solutions Architect needs to create a routing policy wherein a larger portion of traffic from the Philippines and North India will be routed to the resource in the ap-northeast-1 region. Which Route 53 routing policy should the Solutions Architect use?',choices:['A|Geoproximity Routing','B|Geolocation Routing','C|Latency Routing','D|Weighted Routing'],correct:'A',answer:'Geoproximity routing routes traffic based on the geographic location of users AND resources, with an optional bias value that expands or shrinks the geographic region from which a resource attracts traffic. A positive bias on Tokyo expands its catchment area to pull in more traffic from nearby countries like the Philippines and India.',why:'Geoproximity is the only Route 53 policy that allows you to shift the boundary between regions using a bias value. Without any bias, traffic is routed to the closest resource. Adding a positive bias to ap-northeast-1 shifts the geographic boundary outward — users in areas equidistant between Tokyo and Sydney are routed to Tokyo instead. This allows you to route a larger portion from the Philippines and northern India to Tokyo without hard country assignments.',trap:'Geolocation routing assigns specific countries to specific resources — it would send all Philippines traffic to Tokyo, but you cannot control the "larger portion" language (it is all-or-nothing by country). Geoproximity with bias gives finer control over boundary zones. Latency routing sends users to the lowest-latency region, which may or may not be Tokyo depending on actual network conditions. Weighted routing splits traffic as a fixed percentage regardless of location.',rule:'Geoproximity = location + bias to shift boundaries. Positive bias = expand catchment area, pull more traffic. Geolocation = all-or-nothing by country. Latency = lowest latency, not geography-controlled.',keywords:'Route by exact country (compliance) → Geolocation Routing. All-or-nothing per country.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t33',category:'Serverless',question:'A multinational company currently operates multiple AWS accounts to support its operations across various branches and business units. The company needs a more efficient and secure approach in managing its vast AWS infrastructure to avoid costly operational overhead. To address this, they plan to transition to a consolidated, multi-account architecture while integrating a centralized corporate directory service for authentication purposes. Which combination of options can be used to meet the above requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up a new entity in AWS Organizations and configure its authentication system to utilize AWS Directory Service directly.','B|Establish an identity pool through Amazon Cognito and adjust the AWS IAM Identity Center settings to allow Amazon Cognito authentication.','C|Utilize AWS CloudTrail to enable centralized logging and monitoring across all AWS accounts.','D|Integrate AWS IAM Identity Center with the corporate directory service for centralized authentication. Configure a service control policy (SCP) to manage the AWS accounts.','E|Implement AWS Organizations to create a multi-account architecture that provides a consolidated view and centralized management of AWS accounts.'],correct:'DE',answer:'AWS Organizations consolidates multiple accounts into a central hierarchy. AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) integrates with your corporate directory service (AD/LDAP) to provide single sign-on across all accounts. Service Control Policies (SCPs) attached to OUs enforce guardrails — they restrict what even account administrators can do, regardless of their IAM permissions.',why:'AWS Organization is a service that allows you to manage multiple AWS accounts easily. With this service, you can effectively consolidate billing and manage your resources across multiple accounts. AWS IAM Identity Center can be integrated with your corporate directory service for centralized authentication. This means you can sign in to multiple AWS accounts with just one set of credentials.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a new entity in AWS Organizations and configure its authentication system to utilize AWS Directory Service directly is incorrect. The primary function of the AWS Directory Service is to manage user directories such as Microsoft Active Directory, and it\'s not intended to be used directly for multi-account authentication purposes.',rule:'Consolidated multi-account + corporate auth = AWS Organizations (hierarchy + billing) + IAM Identity Center (SSO with AD) + SCPs (account-level guardrails). Not Cognito (for app users). Not CloudTrail (logging only).',keywords:'Multi-account + corporate SSO = AWS Organizations + IAM Identity Center. SCPs = permission ceiling.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t34',category:'Networking',question:'A solutions architect is designing a three-tier website that will be hosted on an Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling group fronted by an Internet-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB). The website will persist data to an Amazon Aurora Serverless DB cluster, which will also be used for generating monthly reports. The company requires a network topology that follows a layered approach to reduce the impact of misconfigured security groups or network access lists. Web filtering must also be enabled to automatically stop traffic to known malicious URLs and to immediately drop requests coming from blacklisted fully qualified domain names (FQDNs). Which network topology provides the minimum resources needed for the website to work?',choices:['A|Set up an Application Load Balancer deployed in a public subnet, then host the Auto Scaling Group of EC2 instances and the Aurora Serverless DB cluster in private subnets. Launch an AWS Network Firewall with the appropriate firewall policy to automatically stop traffic to known malicious URLs and drop requests coming from blacklisted FQDNs. Reroute your Amazon VPC network traffic through the firewall endpoints.','B|Set up an Application Load Balancer and a NAT Gateway deployed in public subnets. Launch the Auto Scaling Group of EC2 instances and Aurora Serverless DB cluster in private subnets. Directly integrate the AWS Network Firewall with the Application Load Balancer to automatically stop traffic to known malicious URLs and drop requests coming from blacklisted FQDNs.','C|Set up an Application Load Balancer in front of an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances with an Aurora Serverless DB cluster to persist data. Launch a NAT Gateway in a public subnet to restrict external services from initiating a connection to the EC2 instances and immediately drop requests from unauthorized FQDNs. Deploy all other resources in private subnets.','D|Set up an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer with an Aurora Serverless DB cluster to store application data. Deploy all resources in a public subnet. Configure host-based routing to the Application Load Balancer to stop traffic to known malicious URLs and drop requests from blacklisted FQDNs.'],correct:'A',answer:'Set up an Application Load Balancer deployed in a public subnet, then host the Auto Scaling Group of EC2 instances and the Aurora Serverless DB cluster in private subnets. Launch an AWS Network Firewall with the appropriate firewall policy to automatically stop traffic to known malicious URLs and drop requests coming from blacklisted FQDNs.',why:'A defense-in-depth strategy is one of the design principles for security in the AWS cloud. This strategy entails implementing security controls at multiple layers (for example, edge of network, VPC, load balancing, every instance and compute service, operating system, application, and code).',trap:'The option that says: Set up an Application Load Balancer and a NAT Gateway deployed in public subnets. Launch the Auto Scaling Group of EC2 instances and Aurora Serverless DB cluster in private subnets.',rule:'Launch an AWS Network Firewall with the appropriate firewall policy to automatically stop traffic to known malicious URLs and drop requests coming from blacklisted FQDNs.',keywords:'NACL = stateless (need both inbound + outbound rules). SG = stateful (response auto-allowed).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t35',category:'IAM',question:'A Solutions Architect is building a cloud infrastructure where Amazon EC2 instances require access to various AWS services, such as Amazon S3 and Amazon Redshift. The Architect will also need to provide access to system administrators so that the system administrators can deploy and test changes. Which configuration should be used to ensure that access to the resources is secured and not compromised? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Enable Multi-Factor Authentication.','B|Assign an IAM role to the EC2 instance.','C|Store the AWS Access Keys in the EC2 instance.','D|Assign an IAM user for each EC2 Instance.','E|Store the AWS Access Keys in ACM.'],correct:'AB',answer:'IAM roles attached to EC2 instances provide temporary, automatically-rotated credentials to applications via the instance metadata service — no hard-coded keys needed. MFA adds a second authentication factor for human administrators, protecting against compromised passwords.',why:'When you assign an IAM role to an EC2 instance, the AWS SDK automatically retrieves temporary credentials from the instance metadata service (169.254.169.254). These credentials rotate automatically every few hours. The application never needs to handle long-lived credentials. MFA requires users to provide both their password and a one-time code from a physical or virtual device, making account compromise significantly harder even if the password leaks.',trap:'Storing access keys on an EC2 instance is an AWS security anti-pattern — keys can be accidentally committed to source code, exposed via instance metadata, or extracted if the instance is compromised. ACM is a certificate management service for SSL/TLS certificates — it is not a secrets or credentials store. Creating IAM users per EC2 instance is unnecessary and creates management overhead — IAM roles are the correct mechanism for instance-to-service access.',rule:'EC2 → AWS services = IAM role (temporary credentials via metadata). Human admin access = MFA. Never store long-lived access keys on EC2 instances. IAM role = automatic credential rotation, no key management.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t36',category:'Security',question:'A company has an application that continually sends encrypted documents to Amazon S3. The company requires that the configuration for data access is in line with its strict compliance standards. It should also be alerted if there is any risk of unauthorized access or suspicious access patterns. Which step is needed to meet the requirements?',choices:['A|Use Amazon GuardDuty to monitor malicious activity on S3.','B|Use AWS CloudTrail to monitor and detect access patterns on S3.','C|Use Amazon Rekognition to monitor and recognize patterns on S3.','D|Use Amazon Inspector to alert whenever a security violation is detected on S3.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon GuardDuty uses ML, anomaly detection, and threat intelligence to generate findings based on suspicious S3 activity — requests from known malicious IPs, changes to bucket policies that expose data publicly, unusual API call patterns, and exfiltration attempts.',why:'GuardDuty has dedicated S3 protection that continuously analyzes CloudTrail data plane events for S3. It detects anomalies like: accessing S3 from a Tor exit node, unexpected API calls from a new geography, bucket policy changes that grant public access, and data exfiltration patterns. GuardDuty generates findings with severity ratings and can trigger automated responses via EventBridge. It requires no infrastructure to deploy.',trap:'CloudTrail records all API calls as a raw audit log — it is a compliance and governance tool, not an anomaly detection system. CloudTrail cannot alert you to suspicious patterns automatically without additional processing. Rekognition analyzes images and videos — completely unrelated to S3 access monitoring. Inspector assesses EC2 instances and Lambda functions for software vulnerabilities — it does not monitor S3 access.',rule:'S3 suspicious access detection = GuardDuty (ML-based threat detection). CloudTrail = API audit log, not anomaly detection. Inspector = vulnerability assessment. GuardDuty = automated threat intelligence + ML.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t37',category:'Database',question:'A GraphQL API hosted is hosted in an Amazon EKS cluster with AWS Fargate launch type and deployed using AWS SAM. The API is connected to an Amazon DynamoDB table with DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) as its data store. Both resources are hosted in the us-east-1 region. The AWS IAM authenticator for Kubernetes is integrated into the EKS cluster for role-based access control (RBAC) and cluster authentication. A solutions architect must improve network security by preventing database calls from traversing the public internet. An automated cross-account backup for the DynamoDB table is also required for long-term retention. Which of the following should the solutions architect implement to meet the requirement?',choices:['A|Create a DynamoDB gateway endpoint. Associate the endpoint to the appropriate route table. Use AWS Backup to automatically copy the on-demand DynamoDB backups to another AWS account for disaster recovery.','B|Create a DynamoDB interface endpoint. Associate the endpoint to the appropriate route table. Enable Point-in-Time Recovery (PITR) to restore the DynamoDB table to a particular point in time on the same or a different AWS account.','C|Create a DynamoDB gateway endpoint. Set up a Network Access Control List (NACL) rule that allows outbound traffic to the dynamodb.us-east-1.amazonaws.com gateway endpoint. Use the built-in on-demand DynamoDB backups for cross-account backup and recovery.','D|Create a DynamoDB interface endpoint. Set up a stateless rule using AWS Network Firewall to control all outbound traffic to only use the dynamodb.us-east-1.amazonaws.com endpoint. Integrate the DynamoDB table with Amazon Timestream to allow point-in-time recovery from a different AWS account.'],correct:'A',answer:'Create a DynamoDB gateway endpoint. Associate the endpoint to the appropriate route table. Use AWS Backup to automatically copy the on-demand DynamoDB backups to another AWS account for disaster recovery.',why:'Since DynamoDB tables are public resources, applications within a VPC rely on an Internet Gateway to route traffic to/from Amazon DynamoDB. You can use a Gateway endpoint if you want to keep the traffic between your VPC and Amazon DynamoDB within the Amazon network. This way, resources residing in your VPC can use their private IP addresses to access DynamoDB with no exposure to the public internet.',trap:'The option that says: Create a DynamoDB interface endpoint. Associate the endpoint to the appropriate route table. Enable Point-in-Time Recovery (PITR) to restore the DynamoDB table to a particular point in time on the same or a different AWS account is incorrect.',rule:'Use AWS Backup to automatically copy the on-demand DynamoDB backups to another AWS account for disaster recovery.',keywords:'microsecond latency → DAX. DynamoDB = millisecond. DAX = microsecond.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t38',category:'S3',question:'For data privacy, a healthcare company has been asked to comply with the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA). The company stores all its backups on an Amazon S3 bucket. It is required that data stored on the S3 bucket must be encrypted. What is the best option to do this? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Before sending the data to S3 over HTTPS, encrypt the data locally first using your own encryption keys.','B|Store the data on Amazon EBS volumes with encryption enabled instead of using S3.','C|Store the data in encrypted Amazon EBS snapshots.','D|Enable Server-Side Encryption on an S3 bucket to make use of AES-256 encryption.','E|Enable Server-Side Encryption on an S3 bucket to make use of AES-128 encryption.'],correct:'AD',answer:'Client-side encryption (Option A) encrypts data before it leaves your environment — you manage the keys and encrypt locally using your own library. Server-side encryption with AES-256 (Option D) is the standard S3 encryption — Amazon encrypts each object with AES-256 using managed keys automatically.',why:'HIPAA requires encryption of PHI at rest. S3 offers two approaches: (1) Client-side encryption — you encrypt before PUT, decrypt after GET, manage the keys yourself. This gives you full key control. (2) Server-side encryption (SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, or SSE-C) — Amazon encrypts the object at rest using AES-256. Both satisfy the encryption-at-rest requirement. AES-256 is HIPAA-compliant. Neither EBS volumes nor EBS snapshots are applicable here — the requirement specifies S3 storage.',trap:'EBS volumes are block storage attached to EC2 instances — they are a completely different storage type from S3 and cannot fulfill S3-specific compliance requirements. EBS snapshots are stored in S3 internally but are not accessible as S3 objects — enabling EBS snapshot encryption does not satisfy S3 object-level encryption requirements. Amazon S3 does NOT support AES-128 encryption — only AES-256 is available for server-side encryption.',rule:'S3 encryption options: SSE-S3 (AES-256, AWS managed), SSE-KMS (AES-256, KMS managed), SSE-C (customer-provided), or client-side. S3 only supports AES-256, never AES-128. EBS encryption ≠ S3 encryption.',keywords:'Encrypt unencrypted EBS → copy snapshot with encryption enabled, create new volume.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t39',category:'Networking',question:'An organization needs to control access to several Amazon S3 buckets. The organization plans to use a gateway endpoint to allow access to trusted buckets. Which of the following could help you achieve this requirement?',choices:['A|Generate a bucket policy for trusted VPCs.','B|Generate a bucket policy for trusted S3 buckets.','C|Generate an endpoint policy for trusted S3 buckets.','D|Generate an endpoint policy for trusted VPCs.'],correct:'C',answer:'An S3 gateway endpoint supports an endpoint policy that controls which S3 buckets can be accessed through it. A single endpoint policy can whitelist multiple trusted S3 bucket ARNs, efficiently controlling access from all VPC resources through one policy.',why:'Endpoint policies are attached to the VPC endpoint itself and specify which actions on which resources are allowed through that endpoint. By listing specific trusted S3 bucket ARNs in the endpoint policy\'s resource element, you restrict all VPC traffic through that endpoint to only those buckets. This is much more operationally efficient than writing and maintaining a bucket policy for each S3 bucket individually. The endpoint policy is separate from and does not replace bucket policies — both can work together.',trap:'A bucket policy for trusted VPCs would require adding a condition to every bucket\'s policy individually, and it restricts by source VPC — not by which specific buckets are allowed. Option B (bucket policy for trusted S3 buckets) is nonsensical — a bucket policy lives on a bucket and cannot reference other buckets. Option D (endpoint policy for trusted VPCs) restricts which VPCs can use the endpoint — not which buckets can be accessed.',rule:'Control access to specific S3 buckets from VPC via gateway endpoint = endpoint policy (one policy, multiple buckets). Bucket policies = per-bucket configuration. Endpoint policy + bucket policy can be combined for defense-in-depth.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t40',category:'Security',question:'A company needs to assess and audit all the configurations in its AWS account. It must enforce strict compliance by tracking all configuration changes made to any of its Amazon S3 buckets. Publicly accessible S3 buckets should also be identified automatically to avoid data breaches. Which of the following options will meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Trusted Advisor to analyze your AWS environment.','B|Use AWS IAM to generate a credential report.','C|Use AWS Config to set up a rule in your AWS account.','D|Use AWS CloudTrail and review the event history of your AWS account.'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Config continuously records the configuration state of AWS resources and evaluates them against AWS Config rules. Pre-built managed rules like s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited automatically detect publicly accessible S3 buckets and mark them as non-compliant. Config also maintains a full configuration change history.',why:'AWS Config operates as a continuous assessment engine. It records every configuration change to every tracked resource (EC2 instances, S3 buckets, security groups, etc.) and stores the history. Config rules are evaluated automatically against these recorded configurations — you can use managed rules (like s3-bucket-public-write-prohibited) or write custom Lambda-based rules. When a bucket is made public, Config immediately flags it as non-compliant and can trigger auto-remediation via Systems Manager Automation.',trap:'Trusted Advisor checks for best practices across cost, performance, security, and fault tolerance but provides periodic snapshots, not continuous configuration tracking with change history. IAM credential reports list IAM user credentials status — they have no visibility into S3 bucket configurations. CloudTrail records API calls but cannot proactively evaluate whether current configurations are compliant.',rule:'Continuous config compliance + change history = AWS Config. Config rules = auto-evaluate resource configurations. Trusted Advisor = best practice recommendations, periodic. CloudTrail = API audit log, not compliance evaluation.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t41',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect of a multinational gaming company develops video games for PS4, Xbox One, and Nintendo Switch consoles, plus a number of mobile games for Android and iOS. Due to the wide range of their products and services, the architect proposed that they use API Gateway. What are the key features of API Gateway that the architect can tell to the client? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|It automatically provides a query language for your APIs similar to GraphQL.','B|Provides you with static anycast IP addresses that serve as a fixed entry point to your applications hosted in one or more AWS Regions.','C|Enables you to build RESTful APIs and WebSocket APIs that are optimized for serverless workloads.','D|Enables you to run applications requiring high levels of inter-node communications at scale on AWS through its custom-built operating system (OS) bypass hardware interface.','E|You pay only for the API calls you receive and the amount of data transferred out.'],correct:'CE',answer:'AWS Global Accelerator provides two static anycast IP addresses that route traffic to the nearest healthy AWS endpoint across regions using the AWS global backbone network. API Gateway features REST API and HTTP API types, request routing based on path/headers, throttling, caching, and authorisation — not a query language for APIs (that would be GraphQL via AppSync).',why:'Amazon API Gateway is a fully managed service that makes it easy for developers to create, publish, maintain, monitor, and secure APIs at any scale.',trap:'The option that says: It automatically provides a query language for your APIs similar to GraphQL is incorrect because this is not provided by API Gateway.',rule:'Static anycast IPs routing to nearest endpoint = AWS Global Accelerator. API Gateway = managed API proxy (REST/HTTP/WebSocket), NOT a query language. GraphQL query language = AWS AppSync.',keywords:'API Gateway features: RESTful + WebSocket APIs, pay-per-use, Lambda integration, edge-optimized.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t42',category:'Storage',question:'An organization stores and manages financial records of various companies in its on-premises data center, which is almost out of space. The management decided to move all of their existing records to a cloud storage service. All future financial records will also be stored in the cloud. For additional security, all records must be prevented from being deleted or overwritten. Which of the following should you do to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Storage Gateway to establish hybrid cloud storage. Store all of your data in Amazon S3 and enable object lock.','B|Use AWS DataSync to move the data. Store all of your data in Amazon S3 and enable object lock.','C|Use AWS DataSync to move the data. Store all of your data in Amazon EFS and enable object lock.','D|Use AWS Storage Gateway to establish hybrid cloud storage. Store all of your data in Amazon EBS and enable object lock.'],correct:'B',answer:'DataSync migrates on-premises data directly to S3. S3 Object Lock prevents objects from being deleted or overwritten — in governance or compliance mode. Since all records are moving to AWS permanently and no hybrid access is needed, DataSync is the right migration tool and S3 Object Lock satisfies the immutability requirement.',why:'DataSync can transfer petabytes of data from NFS/SMB shares directly to S3 with automatic encryption, integrity verification, and scheduling. Since the entire dataset moves to AWS (no ongoing on-premises use), this is a migration — DataSync\'s specialty. S3 Object Lock\'s WORM model ensures even privileged users cannot delete or modify locked objects during the retention period. Together they address both the migration and the immutability requirements.',trap:'Storage Gateway is for hybrid scenarios where on-premises applications continue to access data through an AWS-backed cache — inappropriate here since all data is moving to AWS permanently. Amazon EFS does not support Object Lock — only S3 has Object Lock. Amazon EBS does not have Object Lock either — and EBS is block storage attached to EC2, not a scalable data migration target. Only S3 has Object Lock.',rule:'DataSync = migrate on-premises data to AWS (one-time). Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access. Object Lock = S3 only (WORM). EFS and EBS have no equivalent to S3 Object Lock.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t43',category:'Networking',question:'A media company has two VPCs: VPC-1 and VPC-2 with peering connection between each other. VPC-1 only contains private subnets while VPC-2 only contains public subnets. The company uses a single AWS Direct Connect connection and a virtual interface to connect their on-premises network with VPC-1. Which of the following options increase the fault tolerance of the connection to VPC-1? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use the AWS VPN CloudHub to create a new AWS Direct Connect connection and private virtual interface in the same region as VPC-2.','B|Establish a hardware VPN over the Internet between VPC-1 and the on-premises network.','C|Establish a hardware VPN over the Internet between VPC-2 and the on-premises network.','D|Establish a new AWS Direct Connect connection and private virtual interface in the same region as VPC-2.','E|Establish another AWS Direct Connect connection and private virtual interface in the same AWS region as VPC-1.'],correct:'BE',answer:'A hardware VPN to VPC-1 provides a redundant path over the Internet as a failover for the Direct Connect. A second Direct Connect connection and private VIF to VPC-1 provides a redundant dedicated circuit — if one DX connection fails, the other takes over.',why:'VPC peering does not support edge-to-edge routing (transitive routing). This means traffic from on-premises cannot reach VPC-1 by routing through the peering connection via VPC-2 — whether through DX or VPN attached to VPC-2. The only valid redundant paths to VPC-1 are: (1) hardware VPN directly to VPC-1 (over Internet, available immediately), or (2) a second DX connection with a private VIF to VPC-1\'s Virtual Private Gateway (dedicated redundant circuit). Both options must connect directly to VPC-1, not via VPC-2.',trap:'Anything through VPC-2 fails because VPC peering is non-transitive — on-premises cannot reach VPC-1 by routing through VPC-2\'s peering connection. This eliminates options A (CloudHub to VPC-2), C (VPN to VPC-2), and D (DX to VPC-2). All three assume transitive routing which VPC peering explicitly does not support.',rule:'VPC peering = no transitive routing. On-prem → VPC-2 → VPC-1 peering does NOT work. Fault tolerance for VPC-1 DX = VPN directly to VPC-1 OR second DX directly to VPC-1.',keywords:'VPC peering = NO transitive routing. A→B→C via peering does NOT work. Use Transit Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t44',category:'Database',question:'An online events registration system is hosted in AWS and uses ECS to host its front-end tier and an RDS configured with Multi-AZ for its database tier. What are the events that will make Amazon RDS automatically perform a failover to the standby replica? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Loss of availability in primary Availability Zone','B|Storage failure on primary','C|Storage failure on secondary DB instance','D|In the event of Read Replica failure','E|Compute unit failure on secondary DB instance'],correct:'AB',answer:'RDS Multi-AZ automatically fails over to the standby when the primary instance becomes unavailable. Loss of the primary AZ (the entire AZ goes down) and storage failure on the primary are both conditions where the primary cannot serve requests, triggering automatic failover.',why:'RDS Multi-AZ maintains a synchronous standby replica in a different AZ. Automatic failover is triggered when the PRIMARY instance is affected — specifically: loss of primary AZ availability, loss of network connectivity to primary, compute unit failure on primary, or storage failure on primary. The failover process changes the DNS CNAME to point to the standby, which takes about 60-120 seconds. The standby then becomes the new primary.',trap:'Failures on the secondary/standby do NOT trigger failover — the primary is still healthy and serving traffic. Storage failure on the secondary means the standby needs rebuilding, but the primary continues serving. Read Replica failure also does not trigger Multi-AZ failover — Read Replicas are separate from Multi-AZ and are used for scaling reads, not HA. Compute unit failure on the secondary is handled silently without a failover.',rule:'RDS Multi-AZ failover triggers = PRIMARY failures only: AZ loss, compute failure, storage failure, network loss. Secondary failures = no failover. Read Replica failure = unrelated to Multi-AZ.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t45',category:'Security',question:'A company wants to streamline the process of creating multiple AWS accounts within an AWS Organization. Each organization unit (OU) must be able to launch new accounts with preapproved configurations from the security team which will standardize the baselines and network configurations for all accounts in the organization. Which solution entails the least amount of effort to implement?',choices:['A|Set up an AWS Control Tower Landing Zone. Enable pre-packaged guardrails to enforce policies or detect violations.','B|Configure AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to launch new AWS accounts as well as standardize the baselines and network configurations for each organization unit','C|Set up an AWS Config aggregator on the root account of the organization to enable multi-account, multi-region data aggregation. Deploy conformance packs to standardize the baselines and network configurations for all accounts.','D|Centralized the creation of AWS accounts using AWS Systems Manager OpsCenter. Enforce policies and detect violations to all AWS accounts using AWS Security Hub.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Control Tower provides a Landing Zone — an automated, well-architected multi-account environment. It uses Account Factory to provision new accounts with pre-configured security baselines, network configurations, and guardrails applied automatically. OUs receive guardrails that enforce or detect policy violations across all member accounts.',why:'Control Tower automates everything that would otherwise require custom scripts and manual coordination: creating accounts with consistent VPC configurations, applying SCPs via guardrails, setting up CloudTrail and Config in every account, and establishing an audit account. Account Factory uses Service Catalog to let authorized users provision new compliant accounts on-demand. Guardrails (preventive and detective) are pre-packaged best practices that map to compliance standards.',trap:'AWS RAM shares resources between accounts but cannot create accounts or enforce configurations. AWS Config conformance packs deploy Config rules but Config cannot provision or create new AWS accounts. Systems Manager OpsCenter manages operational work items in a single account — it cannot create AWS accounts. Security Hub aggregates security findings but cannot provision accounts or enforce configurations.',rule:'Multi-account with preapproved baselines = Control Tower Landing Zone + Account Factory. Control Tower = automated account provisioning + guardrails. AWS RAM = resource sharing. Config = compliance rules, not account provisioning.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t46',category:'IAM',question:'An Intelligence Agency developed a missile tracking application that is hosted on both development and production AWS accounts. The Intelligence agency’s junior developer only has access to the development account. The developer has received security clearance to access the agency’s production account but the access is only temporary and only write access to Amazon EC2 and Amazon S3 is allowed. Which of the following allows the developer to issue short-lived access tokens that act as temporary security credentials to allow access to AWS resources?',choices:['A|Use Amazon Cognito to issue JSON Web Tokens (JWT)','B|Use AWS Security Token Service (STS)','C|Use AWS IAM Identity Center','D|All of the given options are correct.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Security Token Service (STS) issues temporary security credentials — an access key ID, secret access key, and session token — that expire after a configurable duration. The developer calls AssumeRole in the production account to receive time-limited credentials scoped to the WriteAccess role.',why:'The cross-account flow: (1) The dev account developer has permission to call sts:AssumeRole. (2) The production account has an IAM role (e.g., WriteAccess) with a trust policy that allows the dev account\'s IAM user to assume it. (3) The developer calls AssumeRole and receives temporary credentials valid for 1-12 hours. (4) Using those credentials, the developer can only perform EC2 and S3 write actions as defined in the role. When the session expires, access is automatically revoked.',trap:'Amazon Cognito issues JWTs for application user authentication (web/mobile apps) — it is for end-user identity, not AWS service access or cross-account IAM. Cognito Identity Pools can exchange JWTs for AWS credentials via STS, but Cognito itself does not generate temporary AWS credentials directly. IAM Identity Center provides workforce SSO across accounts but it is not the mechanism for programmatic temporary credential generation in this scenario.',rule:'Temporary AWS credentials for cross-account access = STS AssumeRole. Cognito = end-user app authentication. IAM Identity Center = workforce SSO. STS = the underlying service for ALL temporary credential issuance.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t47',category:'IAM',question:'A company developed a meal planning application that provides meal recommendations for the week as well as the food consumption of the users. The application resides on an EC2 instance which requires access to various AWS services for its day-to-day operations. Which of the following is the best way to allow the EC2 instance to access the S3 bucket and other AWS services?',choices:['A|Create a role in IAM and assign it to the EC2 instance.','B|Store the API credentials in the EC2 instance.','C|Add the API Credentials in the Security Group and assign it to the EC2 instance.','D|Store the API credentials in a bastion host.'],correct:'A',answer:'IAM roles assigned to EC2 instances provide automatically-rotated temporary credentials via the instance metadata service. The application retrieves credentials dynamically without any static keys being stored on the instance or in code.',why:'When an IAM role is attached to an EC2 instance, AWS automatically provides temporary credentials accessible at the instance metadata endpoint (169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/). The AWS SDK automatically retrieves and refreshes these credentials. They rotate approximately every 6 hours with overlapping validity. This eliminates all credential management — no key rotation, no accidental exposure in code repositories, no risk from instance compromise revealing long-lived keys.',trap:'Storing API credentials (access key + secret key) on the EC2 instance is explicitly warned against by AWS — keys can be found in files, environment variables, config files, and accessed if the instance is compromised. Security groups are network firewall rules (allow/deny traffic) — they have no concept of storing credentials. A bastion host is an administrative access point, not a credential store.',rule:'EC2 application accessing AWS services = IAM role attached to instance. Credentials via metadata service, auto-rotating. Never store long-lived access keys on EC2. Security groups = network rules only.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t48',category:'S3',question:'All objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket must be encrypted for security compliance. The bucket will use server-side encryption with Amazon S3-Managed encryption keys (SSE-S3) to encrypt data using 256-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-256) block cipher. Which of the following request headers must be used?',choices:['A|x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-key','B|x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-algorithm','C|x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-key-MD5','D|x-amz-server-side-encryption'],correct:'D',answer:'The x-amz-server-side-encryption header with the value AES256 instructs Amazon S3 to encrypt the uploaded object using SSE-S3 (S3-managed keys). Including this header in a PUT request triggers server-side encryption with AES-256.',why:'SSE-S3 uses AES-256 encryption managed entirely by S3. The request header x-amz-server-side-encryption: AES256 tells S3 to encrypt the object server-side using its own managed keys. You can also enforce this at the bucket level with a bucket policy that requires the header on all PUT requests. S3 automatically manages key generation, storage, and rotation — no key management on your part.',trap:'The x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-* headers (customer-key, customer-algorithm, customer-key-MD5) are all used exclusively for SSE-C (Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys) — where YOU supply the encryption key with every request. If you send these headers, S3 uses YOUR key, not its own managed keys. The wrong header type means the wrong encryption method.',rule:'SSE-S3 header = x-amz-server-side-encryption: AES256. SSE-C headers = x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-* (you supply the key). SSE-KMS header = x-amz-server-side-encryption: aws:kms.',keywords:'SSE-S3 request header = x-amz-server-side-encryption: AES256. S3 only supports AES-256.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t49',category:'IAM',question:'A startup has multiple AWS accounts that are assigned to its development teams. Since the company is projected to grow rapidly, the management wants to consolidate all of its AWS accounts into a multi-account setup. To simplify the login process on the AWS accounts, the management wants to utilize its existing directory service for user authentication Which combination of actions should a solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|On the master account, use AWS Organizations to create a new organization with all features turned on. Enable the organization’s external authentication and point it to use the company’s directory service.','B|Create an identity pool on Amazon Cognito and configure it to use the company’s directory service. Configure AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS Single Sign-On) to accept Cognito authentication.','C|Create Service Control Policies (SCP) in the organization to manage the child accounts. Configure AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS Single Sign-On) to use AWS Directory Service.','D|On the master account, use AWS Organizations to create a new organization with all features turned on. Invite the child accounts to this new organization.','E|Configure AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS Single Sign-On) for the organization and integrate it with the company’s directory service using the Active Directory Connector'],correct:'AE',answer:'AWS Organizations consolidates multiple accounts into a unified hierarchy with centralized management, billing, and policy enforcement. IAM Identity Center integrates with corporate directory services (Active Directory via AD Connector, or LDAP-compatible directories) to provide SSO across all accounts in the organization.',why:'Organizations provides the account structure: OU hierarchy, consolidated billing, and the foundation for applying SCPs. IAM Identity Center provides the authentication layer: it connects to the corporate directory so employees use their existing credentials to access any AWS account. SCPs (configured in Organizations) define the permission ceiling for all accounts in each OU — preventing even account administrators from exceeding the boundaries. Together they solve both the governance (Organizations) and authentication (IAM Identity Center) requirements.',trap:'AWS Organizations does not have a built-in authentication system that uses Directory Service directly. Cognito is for application user identity (web/mobile apps) — not for AWS console/CLI access for employees. CloudTrail provides audit logging, not multi-account management or authentication. The correct authentication solution for workforce access to AWS accounts is IAM Identity Center, not Cognito.',rule:'Multi-account management = AWS Organizations. Workforce SSO across accounts = IAM Identity Center + corporate directory. Cognito = app user auth. CloudTrail = API audit logs.',keywords:'Existing on-premises AD + AWS access → AD Connector (proxy, no sync) + IAM Roles.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t50',category:'IAM',question:'An insurance company utilizes SAP HANA for its day-to-day ERP operations. Since they can’t migrate this database due to customer preferences, they need to integrate it with the current AWS workload in the VPC in which they are required to establish a site-to-site VPN connection. What needs to be configured outside of the VPC for them to have a successful site-to-site VPN connection? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|A dedicated NAT instance in a public subnet','B|An Internet-routable IP address (static) of the customer gateway\'s external interface for the on-premises network','C|The main route table in your VPC to route traffic through a NAT instance','D|An EIP to the Virtual Private Gateway'],correct:'ABC',answer:'By default, instances that you launch into a virtual private cloud (VPC) can\'t communicate with your own network. You can enable access to your network from your VPC by attaching a virtual private gateway to the VPC, creating a custom route table, updating your security group rules, and creating an AWS managed VPN connection.',why:'Although the term VPN connection is a general term, in the Amazon VPC documentation, a VPN connection refers to the connection between your VPC and your own network. AWS supports Internet Protocol security (IPsec) VPN connections.',trap:'A NAT instance (Option A) works for outbound internet access but requires you to manage EC2 availability, patch it, and disable source/destination checks. The question asks specifically about SAP HANA needing to reach the internet — a NAT gateway is the correct managed solution, but the question is about which component enables the VPC-to-internet connection path, which requires checking whether a NAT gateway or internet gateway is in place alongside the VPN component (customer gateway).',rule:'You can enable access to your network from your VPC by attaching a virtual private gateway to the VPC, creating a custom route table, updating your security group rules, and creating security group rules for instances in your VPC.',keywords:'Site-to-Site VPN requirements: Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) + Customer Gateway (CGW) + route table update.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t51',category:'Security',question:'A company is hosting its web application in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer. Recently, the Solutions Architect identified a series of SQL injection attempts and cross-site scripting attacks to the application, which had adversely affected their production data. Which of the following should the Architect implement to mitigate this kind of attack?',choices:['A|Use Amazon Guard​Duty to prevent any further SQL injection and cross-site scripting attacks in your application.','B|Using AWS Firewall Manager, set up security rules that block SQL injection and cross-site scripting attacks. Associate the rules to the Application Load Balancer.','C|Block all the IP addresses where the SQL injection and cross-site scripting attacks originated using the Network Access Control List.','D|Set up security rules that block SQL injection and cross-site scripting attacks in AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF). Associate the rules to the Application Load Balancer.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS WAF is a web application firewall that monitors HTTP/HTTPS traffic forwarded to an ALB. WAF provides managed rule groups specifically designed to detect and block SQL injection and cross-site scripting patterns. Rules are associated directly with the ALB to inspect all incoming requests.',why:'AWS WAF operates at Layer 7 — it inspects the content of HTTP requests (query strings, request bodies, headers, URIs). AWS managed rule groups include SQLi and XSS rule sets that are continuously updated by the AWS threat intelligence team. When a request matches a rule, WAF can block it, allow it, count it, or challenge it with CAPTCHA. WAF integrates directly with ALB, CloudFront, and API Gateway as a filter before traffic reaches your application.',trap:'GuardDuty is a threat detection service that identifies suspicious account activity and compromised instances — it cannot inspect and block individual HTTP requests or prevent application-layer attacks. AWS Firewall Manager simplifies the management and deployment of WAF rules across multiple accounts — it is an administration layer on top of WAF, not a replacement. NACLs operate at the subnet level and block/allow based on IP and port — they cannot inspect HTTP request payloads for SQL injection patterns.',rule:'SQL injection/XSS prevention = AWS WAF attached to ALB. WAF = Layer 7 HTTP inspection. GuardDuty = threat detection, not request filtering. NACL = Layer 3/4 IP/port filtering only.',keywords:'Block SQLi / XSS → AWS WAF (Layer 7). Associate with ALB, CloudFront, or API Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t52',category:'Security',question:'An application is hosted in AWS Fargate and uses RDS database in Multi-AZ Deployments configuration with several Read Replicas. A Solutions Architect was instructed to ensure that all of their database credentials, API keys, and other secrets are encrypted and rotated on a regular basis to improve data security. The application should also use the latest version of the encrypted credentials when connecting to the RDS database. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate solution to secure the credentials?',choices:['A|Store the database credentials, API keys, and other secrets to Systems Manager Parameter Store each with a SecureString data type. The credentials are automatically rotated by default.','B|Use AWS Secrets Manager to store and encrypt the database credentials, API keys, and other secrets. Enable automatic rotation for all of the credentials.','C|Store the database credentials, API keys, and other secrets to AWS ACM.','D|Store the database credentials, API keys, and other secrets in AWS KMS.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Secrets Manager stores secrets with encryption at rest (KMS). It natively integrates with RDS, Redshift, and DocumentDB to automatically rotate credentials on a schedule you define — rotating both the secret value AND updating the database password simultaneously, with zero application downtime.',why:'Secrets Manager\'s automatic rotation uses a Lambda function that rotates the secret in Secrets Manager and simultaneously updates the credentials in the database. Applications retrieve the secret by name using the SDK, which always returns the current version. This eliminates hardcoded credentials and the manual rotation burden. The rotation Lambda handles the dual write (new password in Secrets Manager + new password in RDS) atomically, so applications never experience a credential mismatch.',trap:'Systems Manager Parameter Store with SecureString encrypts stored values using KMS, but it does NOT automatically rotate credentials — rotation must be implemented separately with custom Lambda functions. ACM manages SSL/TLS certificates for HTTPS — it is not for storing database credentials or API keys. KMS is a key management service for creating and managing encryption keys — it encrypts data but is not a secrets storage service.',rule:'Automatic secret rotation + encryption + RDS integration = Secrets Manager. Parameter Store = encrypted storage, no automatic rotation. KMS = key management. ACM = SSL/TLS certificates only.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t53',category:'Networking',question:'A company has two On-Demand EC2 instances inside the Virtual Private Cloud in the same Availability Zone but are deployed to different subnets. One EC2 instance is running a database and the other EC2 instance a web application that connects with the database. You need to ensure that these two instances can communicate with each other for the system to work properly. What are the things you have to check so that these EC2 instances can communicate inside the VPC? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Check the Network ACL if it allows communication between the two subnets.','B|Check if both instances are the same instance class.','C|Check if the default route is set to a NAT instance or Internet Gateway (IGW) for them to communicate.','D|Check if all security groups are set to allow the application host to communicate to the database on the right port and protocol.','E|Ensure that the EC2 instances are in the same Placement Group.'],correct:'AD',answer:'NACLs are stateless subnet-level firewalls that control traffic between subnets. Security groups are stateful instance-level firewalls that control traffic to and from each EC2 instance. Both must allow the traffic on the correct port for the web server to reach the database.',why:'Within a VPC, instances in different subnets communicate via the VPC router using private IP addresses. The VPC router handles the routing automatically — no Internet Gateway or NAT is needed for private subnet-to-subnet communication. Two things can block this traffic: (1) NACLs on either subnet that deny the traffic (NACLs are stateless — both inbound and outbound rules must allow it), and (2) the security group on the database instance that must allow inbound traffic on the database port from the web server\'s security group or IP.',trap:'Instance class (t3, m5, etc.) has no effect on network communication — it only affects compute capacity. An Internet Gateway or NAT instance is for reaching the public Internet from private subnets — communication between two instances in the same VPC uses private IP routing and never touches the Internet. Placement groups affect physical proximity of instances for low latency — they do not affect security or routing.',rule:'Intra-VPC communication blockers: NACL (subnet level, stateless) + Security Group (instance level, stateful). No IGW or NAT needed for private subnet-to-subnet. Instance class and placement group irrelevant for connectivity.',keywords:'NACL = stateless (need both inbound + outbound rules). SG = stateful (response auto-allowed).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'q3_1',category:'Cost',question:'A company is building an automation tool for generating custom reports on its AWS usage. The company must be able to programmatically access and forecast usage costs on specific services. Which of the following would meet the requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead?',choices:['A|Use the AWS Cost Explorer API with pagination to programmatically retrieve the usage cost-related data.','B|Configure AWS Budgets to send usage cost data to the company via Amazon SNS.','C|Generate AWS Budgets reports for usage cost data and deliver them via Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS).','D|Utilize the downloadable AWS Cost Explorer report .csv files to access the cost-related data. Predict usage costs using AWS Budgets.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Cost Explorer is a service provided by Amazon Web Services (AWS) that helps you visualize, understand, and analyze your AWS costs and usage. It provides a comprehensive set of tools and features to help you monitor and manage your AWS spending.',why:'Cost Explorer has two default reports: Cost and Usage, and Reservations. It provides 12 months of historical data and 3 months of forecasting. You can filter by service, linked account, tag, region, or purchase type. Savings Plans and RI recommendations are driven by your historical usage patterns shown in Cost Explorer.',trap:'The option that says: Configure AWS Budgets to send usage cost data to the company via Amazon SNS is incorrect because this simply helps you get notified on budget thresholds; it does not provide access to the usage of cost-related data.',rule:'Use the AWS Cost Explorer API with pagination to programmatically retrieve the usage cost-related data.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_2',category:'Storage',question:'A solutions architect is managing an application that runs on a Windows EC2 instance with an attached Amazon FSx for Windows File Server. To save cost, management has decided to stop the instance during off-hours and restart it only when needed. It has been observed that the application takes several minutes to become fully operational which impacts productivity. How can the solutions architect speed up the instance’s loading time without driving the cost up?',choices:['A|Migrate the application to a Linux-based EC2 instance.','B|Migrate the application to an EC2 instance with hibernation enabled.','C|Enable the hibernation mode on the EC2 instance.','D|Disable the Instance Metadata Service to reduce the things that need to be loaded at startup.'],correct:'B',answer:'Hibernation saves the instance RAM to the root EBS volume and stops the instance. On restart, RAM is restored and the application continues exactly where it left off, eliminating the slow warm-up period.',why:'EC2 Hibernate works by writing the in-memory state to the root EBS volume. The instance then stops (billing stops). On start, the EBS volume restores RAM contents before the OS boots. The application resumes from its saved state — no cold start, no cache rebuild.',trap:'Migrating to Linux forces application rework. A new instance store-backed AMI still requires a full cold start. Disabling IMDS reduces attack surface but does not affect startup time.',rule:'Slow startup after stop/start = EC2 Hibernate. Saves RAM to EBS, resumes from exact state. No cold start. Root volume must be EBS-backed and large enough to hold RAM.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_3',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a financial company. The manager wants to have the ability to automatically transfer obsolete data from their S3 bucket to a low-cost storage system in AWS after a certain period of time. What is the best solution that the Architect can provide to them?',choices:['A|Use an EC2 instance and a scheduled job to transfer the obsolete data from their S3 location to Amazon S3 Glacier.','B|Use Lifecycle Policies in S3 to move obsolete data to Glacier.','C|Use Amazon SQS.','D|Use Amazon Timestream.'],correct:'B',answer:'Expiration actions – In which you specify when the objects expire. Then Amazon S3 deletes the expired objects on your behalf.',why:'In this scenario, you can use lifecycle policies in S3 to automatically move obsolete data to Glacier. Lifecycle configuration in Amazon S3 enables you to specify the lifecycle management of objects in a bucket. The configuration is a set of one or more rules, where each rule defines an action for Amazon S3 to apply to a group of objects.',trap:'The option that says: Use an EC2 instance and a scheduled job to transfer the obsolete data from their S3 location to Amazon S3 Glacier is incorrect because you don\'t need to create a scheduled job in EC2 as you can simply use the lifecycle policy in S3.',rule:'EC2 + S3 + Amazon = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'S3 lifecycle policy: automatic transition to lower storage classes. Standard to IA to Glacier to Deep Archive.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_4',category:'EC2',question:'A company is hosting EC2 instances that are on non-production environment and processing non-priority batch loads, which can be interrupted at any time. What is the best instance purchasing option which can be applied to your EC2 instances in this case?',choices:['A|Reserved Instances','B|On-Demand Instances','C|Spot Instances','D|On-Demand Capacity Reservations'],correct:'C',answer:'Spot Instances offer the largest discount (up to 90% off On-Demand) and are ideal for non-production, interruptible, non-priority workloads where interruption is acceptable.',why:'AWS Spot Instances use unused EC2 capacity. They are the most cost-effective purchase option. The trade-off is that AWS can reclaim them with a 2-minute warning when capacity is needed. For non-production batch jobs, processing queues, or CI/CD pipelines where interruptions are tolerable, Spot is the clear cost winner.',trap:'Reserved Instances provide savings for predictable, steady-state production workloads — committing to 1-3 years for non-production makes no financial sense. On-Demand is the most expensive per-hour option. On-Demand Capacity Reservations guarantee capacity but charge you whether or not you use it.',rule:'Non-production + interruptible + lowest cost = Spot Instances. Reserved = steady-state commitment. On-Demand Capacity Reservation = capacity guarantee, not cost savings.',keywords:'Non-production / fault-tolerant / batch → Spot Instances (70-90% discount, can be interrupted).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_5',category:'EC2',question:'The media company that you are working for has a video transcoding application running on Amazon EC2. Each EC2 instance polls a queue to find out which video should be transcoded, and then runs a transcoding process. If this process is interrupted, the video will be transcoded by another instance based on the queuing system. This application has a large backlog of videos which need to be transcoded. Your manager would like to reduce this backlog by adding more EC2 instances, however, these instances are only needed until the backlog is reduced. In this scenario, which type of Amazon EC2 instance is the most cost-effective type to use?',choices:['A|Reserved instances','B|Spot instances','C|Dedicated instances','D|On-demand instances'],correct:'B',answer:'Spot Instances are ideal for video transcoding — a fault-tolerant, parallelizable workload. If a Spot instance is interrupted, the job can be restarted from a checkpoint with minimal data loss.',why:'Transcoding is embarrassingly parallel: each video file can be processed independently. Spot Instances can be 70-90% cheaper than On-Demand. If a Spot instance gets interrupted, the partially transcoded output is discarded and the job is requeued. Applications should checkpoint progress and use SQS to track pending jobs.',trap:'Reserved Instances lock you into a 1-3 year commitment — only cost-effective for steady, predictable 24/7 workloads. Dedicated Instances run on single-tenant hardware at a significant premium, addressing compliance needs, not cost. On-Demand is full price.',rule:'Fault-tolerant parallel batch jobs (transcoding, rendering, ML training) = Spot Instances. Reserved = steady state 24/7. Dedicated = compliance/licensing isolation.',keywords:'Non-production / fault-tolerant / batch → Spot Instances (70-90% discount, can be interrupted).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_6',category:'IAM',question:'A company has an e-commerce application that saves the transaction logs to an S3 bucket. You are instructed by the CTO to configure the application to keep the transaction logs for one month for troubleshooting purposes, and then afterward, purge the logs. What should you do to accomplish this requirement?',choices:['A|Add a new bucket policy on the Amazon S3 bucket.','B|Configure the lifecycle configuration rules on the Amazon S3 bucket to purge the transaction logs after a month','C|Create a new IAM policy for the Amazon S3 bucket that automatically deletes the logs after a month','D|Enable CORS on the Amazon S3 bucket which will enable the automatic monthly deletion of data'],correct:'B',answer:'In this scenario, the best way to accomplish the requirement is to simply configure the lifecycle configuration rules on the Amazon S3 bucket to purge the transaction logs after a month.',why:'Lifecycle configuration enables you to specify the lifecycle management of objects in a bucket. The configuration is a set of one or more rules, where each rule defines an action for Amazon S3 to apply to a group of objects.',trap:'The option that says: Create a new IAM policy for the Amazon S3 bucket that automatically deletes the logs after a month is incorrect because IAM policies are primarily used to specify what actions are allowed or denied on your S3 buckets. You cannot configure an IAM policy to automatically purge logs for you in any way.',rule:'These actions can be classified as follows: Transition actions – In which you define when objects transition to another storage class.',keywords:'Auto-move S3 objects = lifecycle policy. Min 30 days before Standard→Standard-IA transition.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_7',category:'EC2',question:'In Amazon EC2, you can manage your instances from the moment you launch them up to their termination. You can flexibly control your computing costs by changing the EC2 instance state. Which of the following statements is true regarding EC2 billing? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|You will be billed when your On-Demand instance is in pending state.','B|You will be billed when your Spot instance is preparing to stop with a stopping state.','C|You will be billed when your On-Demand instance is preparing to hibernate with a stopping state.','D|You will be billed when your Reserved instance is in terminated state.','E|You will not be billed for any instance usage while an instance is not in the running state.'],correct:'CD',answer:'terminated - The instance has been permanently deleted and cannot be restarted. Take note that Reserved Instances that applied to terminated instances are still billed until the end of their term according to their payment option.',why:'By working with Amazon EC2 to manage your instances from the moment you launch them through their termination, you ensure that your customers have the best possible experience with the applications or sites that you host on your instances. The following illustration represents the transitions between instance states.',trap:'The option that says: You will be billed when your On-Demand instance is in pending state is incorrect because you will not be billed if your instance is in pending state.',rule:'Take note that Reserved Instances that applied to terminated instances are still billed until the end of their term according to their payment option.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_8',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has established a dedicated network connection from its on-premises data center to AWS Cloud using AWS Direct Connect (DX). The core network services, such as the Domain Name System (DNS) service and Active Directory services, are all hosted on-premises. The company has new AWS accounts that will also require consistent and dedicated access to these network services. Which of the following can satisfy this requirement with the LEAST amount of operational overhead and in a cost-effective manner?',choices:['A|Set up another Direct Connect connection for each and every new AWS account that will be added.','B|Set up a new Direct Connect gateway and integrate it with the existing Direct Connect connection. Configure a VPC peering connection between AWS accounts and associate it with Direct Connect gateway.','C|Create a new AWS VPN CloudHub. Set up a Virtual Private Network (VPN) connection for additional AWS accounts.','D|Create a new Direct Connect gateway and integrate it with the existing Direct Connect connection. Set up a Transit Gateway between AWS accounts and associate it with the Direct Connect gateway.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Transit Gateway provides a hub and spoke design for connecting VPCs and on-premises networks. You can attach all your hybrid connectivity (VPN and Direct Connect connections) to a single Transit Gateway consolidating and controlling your organization\'s entire AWS routing configuration in one place.',why:'By attaching a transit gateway to a Direct Connect gateway using a transit virtual interface, you can manage a single connection for multiple VPCs or VPNs that are in the same AWS Region. You can also advertise prefixes from on-premises to AWS and from AWS to on-premises.',trap:'The option that says: Set up another Direct Connect connection for each and every new AWS account that will be added is incorrect because this solution entails a significant amount of additional cost. Setting up a single DX connection requires a substantial budget and takes a lot of time to establish. It also has high management overhead since you will need to manage all of the Direct Connect connections for all AWS accounts.',rule:'Dedicated network → AWS accounts and associa. Not Direct Connect.',keywords:'Connect many VPCs + on-premises = Transit Gateway. Hub-and-spoke. Supports transitive routing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_9',category:'S3',question:'A company is hosting an application on EC2 instances that regularly pushes and fetches data in Amazon S3. Due to a change in compliance, the instances need to be moved on a private subnet. Along with this change, the company wants to lower the data transfer costs by configuring its AWS resources. How can this be accomplished in the MOST cost-efficient manner?',choices:['A|Set up a NAT Gateway in the public subnet to connect to Amazon S3.','B|Create an Amazon S3 interface endpoint to enable a connection between the instances and Amazon S3.','C|Create an Amazon S3 gateway endpoint to enable a connection between the instances and Amazon S3.','D|Set up an AWS Transit Gateway to access Amazon S3.'],correct:'C',answer:'VPC endpoints for Amazon S3 simplify access to S3 from within a VPC by providing configurable and highly reliable secure connections to S3 that do not require an internet gateway or Network Address Translation (NAT) device. When you create an S3 VPC endpoint, you can attach an endpoint policy to it that controls access to Amazon S3.',why:'A gateway endpoint for S3 or DynamoDB adds a route to your VPC route table that directs requests for those services over the AWS internal network. Traffic never leaves the AWS backbone — it never traverses the internet, a NAT gateway, or an internet gateway. This means no data-processing charges from a NAT gateway and no outbound internet transfer costs. You can attach endpoint policies to control which S3 buckets the VPC can access through the endpoint.',trap:'The option that says: Set up an AWS Transit Gateway to access Amazon S3 is incorrect because this service is mainly used for connecting VPCs and on-premises networks through a central hub.',rule:'be moved on a private subnet → Amazon S3, Amazon S3.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_10',category:'Database',question:'A Solutions Architect needs to deploy a mobile application that collects votes for a singing competition. Millions of users from around the world will submit votes using their mobile phones. These votes must be collected and stored in a highly scalable and highly available database which will be queried for real-time ranking. The database is expected to undergo frequent schema changes throughout the voting period. Which of the following combination of services should the architect use to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon DynamoDB and AWS AppSync','B|Amazon DocumentDB (with MongoDB compatibility) and Amazon AppFlow','C|Amazon Relational Database Service (RDS) and Amazon MQ','D|Amazon Aurora and Amazon Cognito'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon DynamoDB with AWS AppSync provides a fully managed, serverless backend for a real-time voting mobile app. AppSync handles GraphQL APIs with real-time subscriptions, and DynamoDB scales to handle millions of votes per second.',why:'AppSync is a managed GraphQL service that integrates directly with DynamoDB. It supports real-time data sync via WebSocket subscriptions — votes are pushed to connected clients immediately. DynamoDB handles the write-heavy voting workload with single-digit millisecond latency at any scale using on-demand capacity mode.',trap:'Amazon DocumentDB with AppFlow is incorrect — AppFlow is for SaaS data integration, not mobile app APIs. RDS with Amazon MQ adds messaging complexity inappropriate for a simple voting app. Aurora with Cognito addresses authentication, not the data layer for a voting system.',rule:'Mobile voting app with real-time updates = DynamoDB (scalable NoSQL) + AppSync (GraphQL with real-time subscriptions). AppFlow = SaaS integration. Amazon MQ = message broker for migrating existing RabbitMQ/ActiveMQ workloads; not a new-build messaging service.',keywords:'GraphQL API with real-time subscriptions → AWS AppSync.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_11',category:'Networking',question:'A company deployed a high-performance computing (HPC) cluster that spans multiple Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones and processes various wind simulation models. Currently, the Solutions Architect is experiencing a slowdown in their applications and upon further investigation, it was discovered that it was due to latency issues. Which is the MOST suitable solution that the Solutions Architect should implement to provide low-latency network performance necessary for tightly-coupled node-to-node communication of the HPC cluster?',choices:['A|Set up a spread placement group across multiple Availability Zones in multiple AWS Regions.','B|Set up AWS Direct Connect connections across multiple Availability Zones for increased bandwidth throughput and more consistent network experience.','C|Use EC2 Dedicated Instances with elastic inference accelerator','D|Set up a cluster placement group within a single Availability Zone in the same AWS Region.'],correct:'D',answer:'When you launch a new EC2 instance, the EC2 service attempts to place the instance in such a way that all of your instances are spread out across underlying hardware to minimize correlated failures. You can use placement groups to influence the placement of a group of interdependent instances to meet the needs of your workload.',why:'Cluster – packs instances close together inside an Availability Zone. This strategy enables workloads to achieve the low-latency network performance necessary for tightly-coupled node-to-node communication that is typical of HPC applications.',trap:'The option that says: Set up AWS Direct Connect connections across multiple Availability Zones for increased bandwidth throughput and more consistent network experience is incorrect because this is primarily used for hybrid architectures. It bypasses the public Internet and establishes a secure, dedicated connection from your on-premises data center into AWS and not used for having low latency within your AWS network.',rule:'Partition – spreads your instances across logical partitions such that groups of instances in one partition do not share the underlying hardware. Spread = max 7 instances per AZ, separated racks. Cluster = low latency, same rack.',keywords:'HPC low-latency inter-instance networking → Cluster Placement Group (same rack).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_12',category:'Kinesis',question:'A data analytics company is setting up an innovative checkout-free grocery store. The Solutions Architect developed a real-time monitoring application that uses smart sensors to collect the items that the customers are getting from the grocery’s refrigerators and shelves, then automatically deduct those items from customer accounts. The company wants to analyze the items that are frequently being bought and store the results in Amazon S3 for durable storage to determine the purchase behavior of its customers. Which of the following must be used to easily capture, transform, and load streaming data into S3, Amazon OpenSearch Service, and Splunk?',choices:['A|Amazon Data Firehose','B|Amazon DynamoDB Streams','C|Amazon Redshift','D|Amazon SQS'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Data Firehose is the easiest way to load streaming data into data stores and analytics tools. It can capture, transform, and load streaming data into Amazon S3, Amazon Redshift, Amazon OpenSearch Service, and Splunk, enabling near real-time analytics with existing business intelligence tools and dashboards you are already using today.',why:'It is a fully managed service that automatically scales to match the throughput of your data and requires no ongoing administration. It can also batch, compress, and encrypt the data before loading it, minimizing the amount of storage used at the destination and increasing security.',trap:'Amazon Redshift is incorrect because this is mainly used for data warehousing, making it simple and cost-effective to analyze your data across your data warehouse and data lake. It does not meet the requirement of being able to load and stream data into data stores for analytics. You have to use Data Firehose instead.',rule:'analyze the items that are frequently being → Amazon Data.',keywords:'Deliver/load streaming data to S3/Redshift → Kinesis Data Firehose. KDS = processing, Firehose = delivery.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_13',category:'S3',question:'A document sharing website is using AWS as its cloud infrastructure. Free users can upload a total of 5 GB data while premium users can upload as much as 5 TB. Their application uploads the user files, which can have a max file size of 1 TB, to an S3 Bucket. In this scenario, what is the best way for the application to upload the large files in S3?',choices:['A|Use a single PUT request to upload the large file','B|Use AWS Snowball','C|Use AWS Import/Export','D|Use Multipart Upload'],correct:'D',answer:'The total volume of data and number of objects you can store are unlimited. Individual Amazon S3 objects can range in size from a minimum of 0 bytes to a maximum of 5 terabytes. The largest object that can be uploaded in a single PUT is 5 gigabytes. For objects larger than 100 megabytes, customers should consider using the Multipart Upload capability.',why:'The Multipart upload API enables you to upload large objects in parts. You can use this API to upload new large objects or make a copy of an existing object. Multipart uploading is a three-step process: you initiate the upload, you upload the object parts, and after you have uploaded all the parts, you complete the multipart upload.',trap:'Using a single PUT request to upload the large file is incorrect because the largest file size you can upload using a single PUT request is 5 GB. Files larger than this will fail to be uploaded.',rule:'S3 storage = unlimited (no capacity limit). S3 object size max = 5 TB. Use multipart upload for objects > 5 GB. Unlimited objects per bucket.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_14',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company needs to collect gigabytes of data per second from websites and social media feeds to gain insights on its product offerings and continuously improve the user experience. To meet this design requirement, you have developed an application hosted on an Auto Scaling group of Spot EC2 instances which processes the data and stores the results to DynamoDB and Redshift. The solution should have a built-in enhanced fan-out feature. Which fully-managed AWS service can you use to collect and process large streams of data records in real-time with the LEAST amount of administrative overhead?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 Access Points','B|AWS Data Exchange','C|Amazon Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka (Amazon MSK)','D|Amazon Kinesis Data Streams'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams is used to collect and process large streams of data records in real-time. You can use Kinesis Data Streams for rapid and continuous data intake and aggregation. The type of data used includes IT infrastructure log data, application logs, social media, market data feeds, and web clickstream data.',why:'The following diagram illustrates the high-level architecture of Kinesis Data Streams. The producers continually push data to Kinesis Data Streams, and the consumers process the data in real-time. Consumers (such as a custom application running on Amazon EC2 or an Amazon Data Firehose stream) can store their results using an AWS service such as Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon Redshift, or Amazon S3.',trap:'Amazon S3 Access Points is incorrect because this is mainly used to manage access of your S3 objects. Amazon S3 access points are named network endpoints that are attached to buckets that you can use to perform S3 object operations, such as uploading and retrieving objects.',rule:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams: correct. Amazon S3: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_15',category:'Storage',question:'A large financial firm in the country has an AWS environment that contains several Reserved EC2 instances hosting a web application that has been decommissioned last week. To save costs, you need to stop incurring charges for the Reserved instances as soon as possible. What cost-effective steps will you take in this circumstance? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Stop the Reserved instances as soon as possible.','B|Contact AWS to cancel your AWS subscription.','C|Go to the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace and sell the Reserved instances.','D|Terminate the Reserved instances as soon as possible to avoid getting billed at the on-demand price when it expires.','E|Go to the Amazon.com online shopping website and sell the Reserved instances.'],correct:'CD',answer:'Unused Standard Reserved Instances can be sold on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace to recoup costs when capacity is no longer needed.',why:'The Reserved Instance Marketplace allows AWS customers to sell their unused Standard RIs to other customers. This lets you recover some of the committed cost when your requirements change. Convertible RIs cannot be sold on the Marketplace — they can only be exchanged for other Convertible RIs of equal or greater value.',trap:'Stopping or terminating Reserved Instances does not remove the billing commitment — you continue paying the reservation fee regardless. You cannot sell Convertible RIs on the Marketplace, only Standard RIs.',rule:'Unused Standard RI = sell on Reserved Instance Marketplace. Convertible RI = exchange only, cannot sell. Stopping/terminating instances does not cancel the RI commitment.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_16',category:'S3',question:'A company has a global online trading platform in which users from all over the world regularly upload terabytes of transactional data to a centralized Amazon S3 bucket. Which of the following should be used in the present system to improve throughput and ensure consistently fast data transfer to the S3 bucket, regardless of the user\'s location?',choices:['A|FTP','B|AWS Direct Connect','C|S3 Transfer Acceleration','D|Use Amazon CloudFront Origin Access Control (OAC)'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration enables fast, easy, and secure transfers of files over long distances between your client and your Amazon S3 bucket. Transfer Acceleration leverages Amazon CloudFront’s globally distributed AWS Edge Locations. As data arrives at an AWS Edge Location, data is routed to your Amazon S3 bucket over an optimized network path.',why:'S3 Transfer Acceleration routes your upload through the nearest AWS CloudFront edge location using optimized network paths. The edge node then forwards your data to S3 over AWS backbone networking, which is faster and more reliable than public internet routing over long distances. You are charged per GB only when Transfer Acceleration is faster than a standard upload.',trap:'FTP is incorrect because the File Transfer Protocol does not guarantee fast throughput and consistent, fast data transfer.',rule:'Fast global S3 uploads over long distances = S3 Transfer Acceleration (CloudFront edge → S3). Not FTP (no throughput guarantee). Transfer Acceleration charges extra per GB.',keywords:'Large offline data transfer (>1 week over network) → Snowball Edge. Ships data physically.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_17',category:'Database',question:'A Solutions Architect working for a startup is designing a High Performance Computing (HPC) application which is publicly accessible for their customers. The startup founders want to mitigate distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks on their application. Which of the following options are not suitable to be implemented in this scenario? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Dedicated EC2 instances to ensure that each instance has the maximum performance possible.','B|Add multiple Elastic Fabric Adapters (EFA) to each EC2 instance to increase the network bandwidth.','C|Use an Amazon CloudFront service for distributing both static and dynamic content.','D|Use an Application Load Balancer with Auto Scaling groups for your EC2 instances. Prevent direct Internet traffic to your Amazon RDS database by deploying it to a new private subnet.','E|Use AWS Shield and AWS WAF.'],correct:'AB',answer:'Adding multiple Elastic Fabric Adapters (EFAs) to each EC2 instance enables higher bandwidth and lower latency inter-node communication, which is essential for tightly coupled HPC workloads.',why:'EFA is a network interface for EC2 instances that enables HPC and ML applications to achieve the network performance of on-premises HPC clusters. EFA provides OS-bypass hardware interface that allows applications to communicate directly with the network adapter, bypassing the OS kernel for lower latency and higher throughput. Multiple EFAs per instance increase available bandwidth for MPI workloads.',trap:'Dedicated Instances provide single-tenant hardware but do not improve network throughput between instances. CloudFront distributes content globally — it has no role in HPC inter-node communication. An Auto Scaling group with ALB handles web traffic scaling, not HPC network optimization.',rule:'HPC inter-node low latency + high throughput = Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA). Multiple EFAs = more bandwidth. EFA uses OS-bypass. Not Enhanced Networking (ENA) — that is for general purpose enhanced networking (not OS-bypass). One EFA per instance maximum.',keywords:'HPC low-latency inter-instance networking → Cluster Placement Group (same rack).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_18',category:'Serverless',question:'A company currently has an Augment Reality (AR) mobile game that has a serverless backend. It is using a DynamoDB table which was launched using the AWS CLI to store all the user data and information gathered from the players and a Lambda function to pull the data from DynamoDB. The game is being used by millions of users each day to read and store data. How would you design the application to improve its overall performance and make it more scalable while keeping the costs low? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Enable DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) and ensure that the Auto Scaling is enabled and increase the maximum provisioned read and write capacity.','B|Configure CloudFront with DynamoDB as the origin; cache frequently accessed data on the client device using ElastiCache.','C|Use AWS IAM Identity Center to authenticate users and have them directly access DynamoDB using single sign-on. Manually set the provisioned read and write capacity to a higher RCU and WCU.','D|Use API Gateway in conjunction with Lambda and turn on the caching on frequently accessed data and enable DynamoDB global replication.','E|Since Auto Scaling is enabled by default, the provisioned read and write capacity will adjust automatically. Also enable DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) to improve the performance from milliseconds to microseconds.'],correct:'ADE',answer:'DAX delivers up to 10x DynamoDB read performance by serving cached responses from memory. Combined with Auto Scaling (which adjusts RCU/WCU based on actual utilisation), the architecture handles spiky game traffic without manual capacity management or over-provisioning.',why:'Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) is a fully managed, highly available, in-memory cache for DynamoDB that delivers up to a 10x performance improvement – from milliseconds to microseconds – even at millions of requests per second. DAX does all the heavy lifting required to add in-memory acceleration to your DynamoDB tables, without requiring developers to manage cache invalidation, data population, or cluster management.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS IAM Identity Center to authenticate users and have them directly access DynamoDB using single sign-on. Manually set the provisioned read and write capacity to a higher RCU and WCU is incorrect because AWS IAM Identity Center is a service that just makes it easy to centrally manage access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications. This will not be of much help to the scalability and performance of the application. It is costly to manually set the provisioned read and write capacity to a higher RCU and WCU because this capacity will run round the clock and will still be the same even if the incoming traffic is stable and there is no need to scale.',rule:'Improve DynamoDB read performance at scale = DAX (in-memory cache, ms→μs) + Auto Scaling (auto-adjust RCU/WCU). CloudFront cannot use DynamoDB as origin.',keywords:'Multi-region DynamoDB active-active → Global Tables.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_19',category:'Serverless',question:'A new online banking platform has been re-designed to have a microservices architecture in which complex applications are decomposed into smaller, independent services. The new platform uses Kubernetes, and the application containers are optimally configured for running small, decoupled services. The new solution should remove the need to provision and manage servers, allow resources to be specified and paid for per application, and improve security through application isolation by design. Which of the following is the MOST suitable solution to implement to launch this new platform on AWS?',choices:['A|Use Amazon ECS to run the Kubernetes cluster on AWS Fargate.','B|Host the application in Amazon EMR Serverless and Amazon EBS storage with the fast snapshot restore feature enabled.','C|Use AWS Fargate on Amazon EKS with Kubernetes Cluster Autoscaler to run the containerized banking platform.','D|Deploy an Amazon EKS Cluster on AWS Outposts with Kubernetes Cluster Autoscaler and sync any orphaned pods with Amazon AppFlow.'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers that works with both Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) and Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS). Fargate makes it easy for you to focus on building your applications.',why:'Fargate allocates the right amount of compute, eliminating the need to choose instances and scale cluster capacity. You only pay for the resources required to run your containers, so there is no over-provisioning and paying for additional servers. Fargate runs each task or pod in its own kernel providing the tasks and pods their own isolated compute environment.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon ECS to run the Kubernetes cluster on AWS Fargate is incorrect because Amazon ECS is primarily used for running Docker containers instead of Kubernetes. A better solution is to use Amazon EKS instead.',rule:'provision and manage servers → AWS Fargate, Amazon EKS. Not Amazon ECS.',keywords:'Serverless containers (no EC2 to manage) → AWS Fargate (ECS or EKS).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_20',category:'S3',question:'A large telecommunications company needs to run analytics against all combined log files from the Application Load Balancer as part of the regulatory requirements. Which AWS services can be used together to collect logs and then easily perform log analysis?',choices:['A|Amazon DynamoDB for storing and EC2 for analyzing the logs.','B|Amazon EC2 with EBS volumes for storing and analyzing the log files.','C|Amazon S3 for storing the ELB log files and an EC2 instance for analyzing the log files using a custom-built application.','D|Amazon S3 for storing ELB log files and Amazon Athena for analyzing the log files.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon S3 for storing ELB log files and Amazon Athena for analyzing the log files.',why:'Access logging is an optional feature of Elastic Load Balancing that is disabled by default. After you enable access logging for your load balancer, Elastic Load Balancing captures the logs and stores them in the Amazon S3 bucket that you specify as compressed files. You can disable access logging at any time.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon DynamoDB for storing and EC2 for analyzing the logs is incorrect because DynamoDB is a noSQL database solution of AWS. It would be inefficient to store logs in DynamoDB while using EC2 to analyze them.',rule:'Amazon + DynamoDB + EC2 = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'ELB access logs to S3. Query logs with Amazon Athena (serverless SQL on S3). No ETL needed.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_21',category:'Other',question:'A call center wants to use Artificial Intelligence(AI) to extract insights from audio recordings to assess the quality of its customer service. The calls are available in both English and Hindi. A sentiment analysis report in English must be generated for each recording to assess whether or not the customer had a positive experience. Once the solution is completed, new languages will eventually be supported, such as Arabic, Mandarin, and Spanish. How can the solutions architect build the solution without maintaining any machine learning model?',choices:['A|Convert audio recordings into text using Amazon Transcribe. Set up Amazon Translate to translate Hindi texts into English and use Amazon Comprehend for sentiment analysis.','B|Transcribe audio recordings into text using Amazon Polly\'s StartSpeechSynthesisTask operation. Set up Amazon Rekognition to recognize and automatically translate Hindi texts into English. Use the combination of Amazon Fraud Detector and Amazon SageMaker BlazingText algorithm for sentiment analysis.','C|Utilize the Amazon Lex service to convert audio recordings into text. Call the Amazon Translate API to translate Hindi texts into English and use Amazon SageMaker Clarify for sentiment prediction and analysis.','D|Set up Amazon Comprehend to convert audio recordings into text. Use Amazon Kendra to translate Hindi texts into English and utilize the Amazon Detective service to automatically detect negative user behaviors for sentiment analysis.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Transcribe is an AWS service that makes it easy for customers to convert speech-to-text.',why:'Amazon Translate is a Neural Machine Translation (MT) service for translating text between supported languages. Amazon Comprehend is a natural language processing (NLP) service that uses machine learning to find meaning and insights in text.',trap:'The option that says: Transcribe audio recordings into text using Amazon Polly\'s StartSpeechSynthesisTask operation. Set up Amazon Rekognition to recognize and automatically translate Hindi texts into English. Use the combination of Amazon Fraud Detector and Amazon SageMaker BlazingText algorithm for sentiment analysis is incorrect. Although the use of the Amazon SageMaker BlazingText algorithm is technically valid, it still fails to meet the condition of not maintaining any ML-model. Using Amazon SageMaker would require you to train and deploy the model yourself. Added to that, the use of Amazon Fraud Detector is also unnecessary. Amazon Fraud Detector is commonly used to identify potentially fraudulent activities and not for running sentiment analysis. Do take note that Amazon Polly is not capable of transcribing audio recordings, and Amazon Rekognition is primarily used for image recognition service, not for translating foreign words into English.',rule:'Amazon Translate is a Neural Machine Translation (MT) service for translating text between supported languages.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_22',category:'Kinesis',question:'A media company recently launched their newly created web application. Many users tried to visit the website, but they are receiving a 503 Service Unavailable Error. The system administrator tracked the EC2 instance status and saw the capacity is reaching its maximum limit and unable to process all the requests. To gain insights from the application\'s data, they need to launch a real-time analytics service. Which of the following allows you to read records in batches?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon S3 bucket to store the captured data and use Amazon Athena to analyze the data.','B|Create a Data Firehose and use AWS Lambda to read records from the data stream.','C|Create an Amazon S3 bucket to store the captured data and use Amazon Redshift Spectrum to analyze the data.','D|Create a Kinesis Data Stream and use AWS Lambda to read records from the data stream.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (KDS) is a massively scalable and durable real-time data streaming service. KDS can continuously capture gigabytes of data per second from hundreds of thousands of sources. You can use an AWS Lambda function to process records in Amazon KDS. By default, Lambda invokes your function as soon as records are available in the stream.',why:'The first time you invoke your function, AWS Lambda creates an instance of the function and runs its handler method to process the event. When the function returns a response, it stays active and waits to process additional events. If you invoke the function again while the first event is being processed, Lambda initializes another instance, and the function processes the two events concurrently.',trap:'The option that says: Create a Data Firehose and use AWS Lambda to read records from the data stream is incorrect. Although Amazon Data Firehose captures and loads data in near real-time, AWS Lambda can\'t be set as its destination. You can write Lambda functions and integrate it with Data Firehose to request additional, customized processing of the data before it is sent downstream. However, this integration is primarily used for stream processing and not the actual consumption of the data stream. You have to use a Kinesis Data Stream in this scenario.',rule:'launch a real-time analytic → Kinesis Data Stream, AWS Lambda.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_23',category:'Serverless',question:'A firm has a containerized application that runs on a self-managed Kubernetes cluster. The cluster writes data in an on-premises MongoDB database. A solutions architect is requested to move the service to AWS in order to minimize operational overhead. The firm prohibits any changes to the code. Which action meets these objectives?',choices:['A|Migrate the cluster to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) cluster and the database to an Amazon DocumentDB (with MongoDB compatibility) database.','B|Migrate the cluster to an Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) cluster using Amazon ECS Anywhere and the database to an Amazon Aurora Serverless database.','C|Migrate the cluster to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) cluster using Amazon EKS Anywhere and the database to an Amazon DynamoDB table.','D|Migrate the cluster to an Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) cluster with the images stored in the Amazon Elastic Container Registry (Amazon ECR). Move the database to an Amazon Neptune database'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon DocumentDB (with MongoDB compatibility) is a fast, scalable, highly available, and fully managed document database service that supports MongoDB workloads. The Amazon DocumentDB Migration Guide outlines three primary approaches for migrating from MongoDB to Amazon DocumentDB: offline, online, and hybrid.',why:'The image above illustrates an offline migration approach, which is the fastest and simplest of the three but incurs the longest period of downtime. This approach is a good choice for proofs of concepts, development and test workloads, and production workloads for which downtime is not of primary concern. For online approach, you may use AWS DMS to minimize downtime.',trap:'The option that says: Migrate the cluster to an Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) cluster using Amazon ECS Anywhere and the database to an Amazon Aurora Serverless database is incorrect. You can\'t directly migrate to Amazon Aurora because MongoDB is a non-relational database. Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) Anywhere is simply a feature of Amazon ECS that enables you to easily run and manage container workloads on customer-managed infrastructure.',rule:'MongoDB-compatible managed database on AWS = Amazon DocumentDB. EFS = file system. ElastiCache = in-memory cache. Aurora = relational (MySQL/PostgreSQL).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_24',category:'Storage',question:'An on-premises server uses an SMB network file share to store application data. The application produces around 50 MB of data per day, but it only needs to access some of it for daily processes. To save on storage costs, the company plans to copy all the application data to AWS. However, the goal is to retain the ability to retrieve data with the same low-latency access as the local file share. The company does not have the capacity to develop the needed tools for this operation. Which of the following should the company use?',choices:['A|AWS Virtual Private Network (VPN)','B|Amazon FSx for Windows File Server','C|AWS Snowball Edge','D|AWS Storage Gateway'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Storage Gateway is a hybrid cloud storage service that gives you on-premises access to virtually unlimited cloud storage. Customers use Storage Gateway to simplify storage management and reduce costs for key hybrid cloud storage use cases.',why:'Specifically for this scenario, you can use the File Gateway configuration to support the SMB file share for the on-premises application. It also meets the requirement for low-latency access. File Gateway helps accelerate your file-based storage migration to the cloud to enable faster performance, improved data protection, and reduced cost.',trap:'AWS Virtual Private Network (VPN) is incorrect because this service is primarily used for establishing encryption connections from an on-premises network to AWS.',rule:'access some of it for daily processes → AWS Storage.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_25',category:'Database',question:'Due to the large volume of query requests, the database performance of an online reporting application significantly slowed down. The Solutions Architect is trying to convince her client to use Amazon RDS Read Replica for their application instead of setting up a Multi-AZ Deployments configuration. What are two benefits of using Read Replicas over Multi-AZ that the Architect should point out? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|It elastically scales out beyond the capacity constraints of a single DB instance for read-heavy database workloads.','B|Allows both read and write operations on the read replica to complement the primary database.','C|Provides asynchronous replication and improves the performance of the primary database by taking read-heavy database workloads from it.','D|Provides synchronous replication and automatic failover in the case of Availability Zone service failures.','E|It enhances the read performance of your primary database by increasing its IOPS and accelerates its query processing via AWS Global Accelerator.'],correct:'AC',answer:'It elastically scales out beyond the capacity constraints of a single DB instance for read-heavy database workloads.',why:'Amazon RDS Read Replicas provide enhanced performance and durability for database (DB) instances. This feature makes it easy to elastically scale out beyond the capacity constraints of a single DB instance for read-heavy database workloads.',trap:'The option that says: It enhances the read performance of your primary database by increasing its IOPS and accelerates its query processing via AWS Global Accelerator is incorrect because Read Replicas do not do anything to upgrade or increase the read throughput on the primary DB instance per se, but it provides a way for your application to fetch data from replicas. In this way, it improves the overall performance of your entire database tier (and not just the primary DB instance). It doesn\'t increase the IOPS nor use AWS Global Accelerator to accelerate the compute capacity of your primary database. AWS Global Accelerator is a networking service not related to RDS that directs user traffic to the nearest application endpoint to the client, thus reducing internet latency and jitter. It simply routes the traffic to the closest edge location via Anycast.',rule:'Scale RDS reads = Aurora Read Replicas (elastically scales beyond single instance) + ElastiCache in front (cache hot data, reduce DB hits). Not Multi-AZ (standby = passive, no read traffic). Caching = ElastiCache or DAX in front of DB, not a DB feature itself.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_26',category:'Serverless',question:'A Data Analyst in a financial company is tasked to provide insights on stock market trends to the company\'s clients. The company uses AWS Glue extract, transform, and load (ETL) jobs in daily report generation, which involves fetching data from an Amazon S3 bucket. The analyst discovered that old data from previous runs were being reprocessed, causing the jobs to take longer to complete. Which solution would resolve the issue in the most operationally efficient way?',choices:['A|Increase the size of the dataset used in the job to speed up the extraction and analysis process.','B|Parallelize the job by splitting the dataset into smaller partitions and processing them simultaneously using multiple EC2 instances.','C|Create a Lambda function that removes any data already processed. Then, use Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to trigger this function whenever the ETL job\'s status switches to SUCCEEDED.','D|Enable job bookmark for the ETL job.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Glue is a powerful tool that enables data engineers to build and manage ETL (extract, transform, load) pipelines for processing and analyzing large amounts of data. With AWS Glue, you can create and manage jobs that extract data from various sources, transform it into the desired format, and load it into a target data store.',why:'One of the features that make AWS Glue especially useful is job bookmarking. Job bookmarking is a mechanism that allows AWS Glue to keep track of where a job is left off in case it gets interrupted or fails for any reason. This way, when the job is restarted, it can pick up from where it left off instead of starting from scratch.',trap:'The option that says: Parallelize the job by splitting the dataset into smaller partitions and processing them simultaneously using multiple EC2 instances is incorrect. This option requires additional AWS resources because of its complexity in partitioning the dataset, managing parallel processing, and coordinating the results. Moreover, this would only speed up the processing of both new and old data; it won\'t resolve the issue of reprocessing old data.',rule:'One of the features that make AWS Glue especially useful is job bookmarking.',keywords:'Amazon Athena: serverless SQL on S3. Pay per query. No infrastructure. Integrates with Glue Data Catalog.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_27',category:'S3',question:'A company is storing its financial reports and regulatory documents in an Amazon S3 bucket. To comply with the IT audit, they tasked their Solutions Architect to track all new objects added to the bucket as well as the removed ones. It should also track whether a versioned object is permanently deleted. The Architect must configure Amazon S3 to publish notifications for these events to a queue for post-processing and to an Amazon SNS topic that will notify the Operations team. Which of the following is the MOST suitable solution that the Architect should implement?',choices:['A|Create a new Amazon SNS topic and Amazon SQS queue. Add an S3 event notification configuration on the bucket to publish s3:ObjectCreated:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:Delete event types to SQS and SNS.','B|Create a new Amazon SNS topic and Amazon MQ. Add an S3 event notification configuration on the bucket to publish s3:ObjectAdded:* and s3:ObjectRemoved:* event types to SQS and SNS.','C|Create a new Amazon SNS topic and Amazon SQS queue. Add an S3 event notification configuration on the bucket to publish s3:ObjectCreated:* and ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated event types to SQS and SNS.','D|Create a new Amazon SNS topic and Amazon MQ. Add an S3 event notification configuration on the bucket to publish s3:ObjectCreated:* and ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated event types to SQS and SNS.'],correct:'A',answer:'The Amazon S3 notification feature enables you to receive notifications when certain events happen in your bucket. To enable notifications, you must first add a notification configuration that identifies the events you want Amazon S3 to publish and the destinations where you want Amazon S3 to send the notifications.',why:'Amazon S3 event notifications typically deliver events in seconds but can sometimes take a minute or longer. If two writes are made to a single non-versioned object at the same time, it is possible that only a single event notification will be sent. If you want to ensure that an event notification is sent for every successful write, you can enable versioning on your bucket.',trap:'The option that says: Create a new Amazon SNS topic and Amazon SQS queue. Add an S3 event notification configuration on the bucket to publish s3:ObjectCreated:* and ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated event types to SQS and SNS is incorrect because the s3:ObjectRemoved:DeleteMarkerCreated type is only triggered when a delete marker is created for a versioned object and not when an object is deleted or a versioned object is permanently deleted.',rule:'Amazon S3 event notifications typically deliver events in seconds but can sometimes take a minute or longer.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_28',category:'Serverless',question:'A web-based application must extract specific data from a large CSV file stored in an Amazon S3 bucket. The application requires filtering or transforming the data dynamically before returning it, ensuring that only the needed data is returned without downloading the entire object. Which of the following actions should be implemented to achieve this?',choices:['A|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes the data based on the bucket\'s name and object\'s key.','B|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes the data based on the bucket\'s name and object\'s metadata.','C|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes the data based on the bucket\'s name and object tags.','D|Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes the data based on the bucket’s name.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon S3 Object Lambda allows users to add custom code to process and transform data when retrieving it from S3. This means that applications can retrieve and modify the data dynamically without the need to create additional storage copies.',why:'Amazon S3 Object Lambda allows custom code (through Lambda functions) to be applied to S3 GET requests. This enables modifying and transforming data dynamically as it is retrieved from the S3 bucket. To do this, a Lambda function must be configured to process the data based on parameters, such as the object\'s key (file name) and bucket details.',trap:'The option that says: Use S3 Object Lambda with a Lambda function that processes the data based on the bucket\'s name and object\'s metadata is incorrect because metadata only provides additional information about the object, such as its size or last modification date, and does not refer to the actual content of the file.',rule:'Transform S3 objects on-the-fly during GET = S3 Object Lambda. No ETL pipeline needed. Lambda function runs on each GET request and returns modified data.',keywords:'Query inside S3 object without downloading = S3 Select. SQL-like, supports CSV/JSON/Parquet.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_29',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A company is deploying a Microsoft SharePoint Server environment on AWS using CloudFormation. The Solutions Architect needs to install and configure the architecture that is composed of Microsoft Active Directory (AD) domain controllers, Microsoft SQL Server 2012, multiple Amazon EC2 instances to host the Microsoft SharePoint Server and many other dependencies. The Architect needs to ensure that the required components are properly running before the stack creation proceeds. Which of the following should the Architect do to meet this requirement? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Configure the DependsOn attribute in the CloudFormation template. Send a success signal after the applications are installed and configured using the cfn-init helper script.','B|Configure a UpdatePolicy attribute to the instance in the CloudFormation template. Send a success signal after the applications are installed and configured using the cfn-signal helper script.','C|Configure the UpdateReplacePolicy attribute in the CloudFormation template. Send a success signal after the applications are installed and configured using the cfn-signal helper script.','D|Configure a CreationPolicy attribute to the instance in the CloudFormation template. Send a success signal after the applications are installed and configured using the cfn-signal helper script.'],correct:'BCD',answer:'A CloudFormation CreationPolicy with cfn-signal allows CloudFormation to wait for an EC2 instance to signal that it has successfully completed its configuration before marking it as CREATE_COMPLETE.',why:'CreationPolicy prevents a resource from being reported as CREATE_COMPLETE until CloudFormation receives a specified number of success signals (via cfn-signal) within a configurable timeout period. This ensures the instance is fully bootstrapped — software installed, services running — before downstream resources that depend on it are created.',trap:'DependsOn controls resource creation order but only waits for the resource to exist, not for the application inside it to finish starting. UpdatePolicy controls how Auto Scaling rolling updates behave. UpdateReplacePolicy controls what happens to old resources during replacement — it does not wait for signal.',rule:'Wait for EC2 to finish bootstrapping during CloudFormation = CreationPolicy + cfn-signal. DependsOn = resource existence only. UpdatePolicy = ASG rolling updates.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_30',category:'Serverless',question:'A solutions architect is designing an infrastructure for a serverless application. The application is packaged as a Docker image stored in Amazon Elastic Container Registry (Amazon ECR) and must be deployed on a fully managed serverless compute service. Additionally, the application requires 5 GB of ephemeral storage for temporary data processing. Which deployment option meets these requirements?',choices:['A|Deploy the application to an Amazon ECS cluster that uses AWS Fargate tasks.','B|Deploy the application in an AWS Lambda function with Container image support. Set the function’s storage to 5 GB.','C|Deploy the application in an AWS Lambda function with Container image support. Attach an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) volume to the function.','D|Deploy the application Amazon ECS cluster with Amazon EC2 worker nodes and attach a 5 GB Amazon EBS volume.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Lambda with Container Image Support is a fully managed, serverless compute service that allows you to run your applications without provisioning or managing servers. Traditionally, AWS Lambda functions were deployed using code written in supported programming languages, but with container image support, you can now package and deploy your application as a Docker container.',why:'One of the key features of AWS Lambda is the ability to allocate ephemeral storage for each function instance. By default, Lambda functions come with 512 MB of temporary storage, but you can configure up to 10 GB of storage. This ephemeral storage is used for temporary data processing and is wiped clean after the execution of the function.',trap:'The option that says: Deploy the application to an Amazon ECS cluster that uses AWS Fargate tasks is incorrect because Amazon ECS with Fargate tasks is not a fully serverless solution. While Fargate allows you to run containers without managing the underlying EC2 instances, it still requires you to configure and manage ECS services, task definitions, and clusters. ECS with Fargate is primarily used for containerized applications that require more granular control over the environment, including network configurations and scaling.',rule:'One of the key features of AWS Lambda is the ability to allocate ephemeral storage for each function instance. Not Amazon ECS.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_31',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect for a global news company is configuring a fleet of EC2 instances in a subnet that currently is in a VPC with an Internet gateway attached. All of these EC2 instances can be accessed from the Internet. The architect launches another subnet and deploys an EC2 instance in it, however, the architect is not able to access the EC2 instance from the Internet. What could be the possible reasons for this issue? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|The Amazon EC2 instance does not have a public IP address associated with it.','B|The Amazon EC2 instance is not a member of the same Auto Scaling group.','C|The Amazon EC2 instance does not have an attached Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA).','D|The route table is not configured properly to send traffic from the EC2 instance to the Internet through the Internet gateway.','E|The route table is not configured properly to send traffic from the EC2 instance to the Internet through the customer gateway (CGW).'],correct:'DE',answer:'Two things block EC2 Internet access: (D) the route table must have a route to an Internet Gateway for outbound traffic, and (E) there must actually be an Internet Gateway attached to the VPC.',why:'For a public subnet EC2 instance to reach the Internet: (1) the subnet route table needs 0.0.0.0/0 → igw-xxxx, (2) an Internet Gateway must be attached to the VPC, (3) the instance needs a public IP, and (4) the security group and NACL must allow the traffic. If the route table sends traffic to the wrong gateway or no gateway exists, Internet access fails.',trap:'Not being in an Auto Scaling group has no effect on Internet connectivity. A missing EFA affects HPC performance but not basic Internet routing. Security groups and NACLs can block traffic but the most common oversight is a missing route to the IGW or no IGW attached.',rule:'EC2 no Internet access = check (1) route table has 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW, (2) IGW attached to VPC, (3) public IP assigned, (4) SG/NACL allow outbound.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_32',category:'Serverless',question:'A tech startup is launching an on-demand food delivery platform using Amazon ECS cluster with an AWS Fargate serverless compute engine and Amazon Aurora. It is expected that the database read queries will significantly increase in the coming weeks ahead. A Solutions Architect recently launched two Read Replicas to the database cluster to improve the platform\'s scalability. Which of the following is the MOST suitable configuration that the Architect should implement to load balance all of the incoming read requests equally to the two Read Replicas?',choices:['A|Use the built-in Reader endpoint of the Amazon Aurora database.','B|Use the built-in Cluster endpoint of the Amazon Aurora database.','C|Enable Amazon Aurora Parallel Query.','D|Create a new Network Load Balancer to evenly distribute the read queries to the Read Replicas of the Amazon Aurora database.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Aurora typically involves a cluster of DB instances instead of a single instance. Each connection is handled by a specific DB instance. When you connect to an Aurora cluster, the hostname and port that you specify point to an intermediate handler called an endpoint. Aurora uses the endpoint mechanism to abstract these connections.',why:'For certain Aurora tasks, different instances or groups of instances perform different roles. For example, the primary instance handles all data definition language (DDL) and data manipulation language (DML) statements. Up to 15 Aurora Replicas handle read-only query traffic.',trap:'The option that says: Use the built-in Cluster endpoint of the Amazon Aurora database is incorrect because a cluster endpoint (also known as a writer endpoint) simply connects to the current primary DB instance for that DB cluster. This endpoint can perform write operations in the database such as DDL statements, which is perfect for handling production traffic but not suitable for handling queries for reporting since there will be no write database operations that will be sent.',rule:'Up to 15 Aurora Replicas handle read-only query traffic.',keywords:'RDS read scaling / reporting offload → Read Replica. Async replication. Can be promoted.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_33',category:'EC2',question:'A manufacturing company has EC2 instances running in AWS. The EC2 instances are configured with Auto Scaling. There are a lot of requests being lost because of too much load on the servers. The Auto Scaling is launching new EC2 instances to take the load accordingly yet, there are still some requests that are being lost. Which of the following is the MOST suitable solution that you should implement to avoid losing recently submitted requests?',choices:['A|Use an Amazon SQS queue to decouple the application components and scale-out the EC2 instances based upon the ApproximateNumberOfMessages metric in Amazon CloudWatch.','B|Replace the Auto Scaling group with a cluster placement group to achieve a low-latency network performance necessary for tightly-coupled node-to-node communication.','C|Use larger instances for your application with an attached Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA).','D|Set up Amazon Aurora Serverless for on-demand, auto-scaling configuration of your EC2 Instances and also enable Amazon Aurora Parallel Query feature for faster analytical queries over your current data.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS) is a fully managed message queuing service that makes it easy to decouple and scale microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications. Building applications from individual components that each perform a discrete function improves scalability and reliability and is best practice design for modern applications.',why:'The number of messages in your Amazon SQS queue does not solely define the number of instances needed. In fact, the number of instances in the fleet can be driven by multiple factors, including how long it takes to process a message and the acceptable amount of latency (queue delay).',trap:'Using larger instances for your application with an attached Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) is incorrect because using a larger EC2 instance would not prevent data from being lost in case of a larger spike. You can take advantage of the durability and elasticity of SQS to keep the messages available for consumption by your instances. Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) is simply a network interface for Amazon EC2 instances that enables customers to run applications requiring high levels of inter-node communications at scale on AWS.',rule:'Building applications from individual components that each perform a discrete function improves scalability and reliability and is best practice design for modern applications.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_34',category:'S3',question:'A company installed sensors to track the number of people who visit the park. The data is sent every day to an Amazon Kinesis stream with default settings for processing, in which a consumer is configured to process the data every other day. You noticed that the S3 bucket is not receiving all of the data that is being sent to the Kinesis stream. You checked the sensors if they are properly sending the data to Amazon Kinesis and verified that the data is indeed sent every day. What could be the reason for this?',choices:['A|There is a problem in the sensors. They probably had some intermittent connection hence, the data is not sent to the stream.','B|By default, Amazon S3 stores the data for 1 day and moves it to Amazon Glacier.','C|Your AWS account was hacked and someone has deleted some data in your Kinesis stream.','D|By default, the data records are only accessible for 24 hours from the time they are added to a Kinesis stream.'],correct:'D',answer:'The time period from when a record is added to when it is no longer accessible is called the retention period. A Kinesis data stream stores records from 24 hours by default to a maximum of 8760 hours (365 days).',why:'This is the reason why there are missing data in your S3 bucket. To fix this, you can either configure your sensors to send the data everyday instead of every other day or alternatively, you can increase the retention period of your Kinesis data stream. By default, the data records are only accessible for 24 hours from the time they are added to a Kinesis stream, which depicts the root cause of this issue.',trap:'The option that says: By default, Amazon S3 stores the data for 1 day and moves it to Amazon Glacier is incorrect because by default, Amazon S3 does not store the data for 1 day only and move it to Amazon Glacier.',rule:'Kinesis Data Streams default retention = 24 hours. Extended = up to 365 days (additional cost). Records beyond retention = permanently lost from KDS.',keywords:'Big data processing + analytics = Amazon EMR + Amazon Redshift. EMR = Spark/Hadoop clusters.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_35',category:'Networking',question:'A large insurance company has an AWS account that contains three VPCs (DEV, UAT and PROD) in the same region. UAT is peered to both PROD and DEV using a VPC peering connection. All VPCs have non-overlapping CIDR blocks. The company wants to push minor code releases from Dev to Prod to speed up time to market. Which of the following options helps the company accomplish this? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Create a new VPC peering connection between PROD and DEV with the appropriate routes.','B|Create a new entry to PROD in the DEV route table using the VPC peering connection as the target.','C|Change the DEV and PROD VPCs to have overlapping CIDR blocks to be able to connect them.','D|Do nothing. Since these two VPCs are already connected via UAT, they already have a connection to each other.'],correct:'ABC',answer:'A VPC peering connection is a networking connection between two VPCs that enables you to route traffic between them privately. Instances in either VPC can communicate with each other as if they are within the same network. You can create a VPC peering connection between your own VPCs, with a VPC in another AWS account, or with a VPC in a different AWS Region.',why:'AWS uses the existing infrastructure of a VPC to create a VPC peering connection; it is neither a gateway nor a VPN connection and does not rely on a separate piece of physical hardware. There is no single point of failure for communication or a bandwidth bottleneck.',trap:'Creating a new entry to PROD in the DEV route table using the VPC peering connection as the target is incorrect because even if you configure the route tables, the two VPCs will still be disconnected until you set up a VPC peering connection between them.',rule:'AWS uses the existing infrastructure of a VPC to create a VPC peering connection; it is neither a gateway nor a VPN connection and does not support transitive routing. Transit Gateway is required for hub-and-spoke VPC connectivity.',keywords:'VPC peering = NO transitive routing. A→B→C via peering does NOT work. Use Transit Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_36',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is designing a highly available environment for an application. She plans to host the application on EC2 instances within an Auto Scaling Group. One of the conditions requires data stored on root EBS volumes to be preserved if an instance terminates. What should be done to satisfy the requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS DataSync to replicate root volume data to Amazon S3.','B|Set the value of DeleteOnTermination attribute of the EBS volumes to False.','C|Configure ASG to suspend the health check process for each EC2 instance.','D|Enable the Termination Protection option for all EC2 instances.'],correct:'B',answer:'By default, Amazon EBS root device volumes are automatically deleted when the instance terminates. However, by default, any additional EBS volumes that you attach at launch, or any EBS volumes that you attach to an existing instance persist even after the instance terminates. This behavior is controlled by the volume\'s DeleteOnTermination attribute, which you can modify.',why:'To preserve the root volume when an instance terminates, change the DeleteOnTermination attribute for the root volume to False. This EBS attribute can be changed through the AWS Console upon launching the instance or through CLI/API command.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS DataSync to replicate root volume data to Amazon S3 is incorrect because AWS DataSync does not work with Amazon EBS volumes. DataSync can copy data between Network File System (NFS) shares, Server Message Block (SMB) shares, self-managed object storage, AWS Snowcone, Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) buckets, Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file systems, and Amazon FSx for Windows File Server file systems.',rule:'EBS: correct. AWS DataSync: incorrect for this scenario.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_37',category:'Serverless',question:'An online registration system hosted in an Amazon EKS cluster stores data to a db.t4g.medium Amazon Aurora DB cluster. The database performs well during regular hours but is unable to handle the traffic surge that occurs during flash sales. A solutions architect must move the database to Aurora Serverless while minimizing downtime and the impact on the operation of the application. Which change should be taken to meet the objective?',choices:['A|Use AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) to migrate to a new Aurora Serverless database.','B|Change the Aurora Instance class to Serverless','C|Take a snapshot of the DB cluster. Use the snapshot to create a new Aurora DB cluster.','D|Add an Aurora Replica to the cluster and set its instance class to Serverless. Failover to the read replica and promote it to primary.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Database Migration Service helps you migrate your databases to AWS with virtually no downtime. All data changes to the source database that occur during the migration are continuously replicated to the target, allowing the source database to be fully operational during the migration process.',why:'You can set up a DMS task for either one-time migration or ongoing replication. An ongoing replication task keeps your source and target databases in sync. Once set up, the ongoing replication task will continuously apply source changes to the target with minimal latency.',trap:'The option that says: Change the Aurora Instance class to Serverless is incorrect. Changing the instance class from Provisioned to Serverless is not possible.',rule:'Serverless → AWS Database Migration S, AWS DMS. Not Aurora Instance.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_38',category:'S3',question:'An online stock trading application stores financial data in an Amazon S3 bucket, with a lifecycle policy that moves older data to Glacier every month. A strict compliance requirement mandates that a surprise audit can occur at any time, and the required data must be retrievable in under 15 minutes under all circumstances. The manager has instructed that retrieval capacity be available when needed and should support up to 150 MB/s of retrieval throughput. Which of the following will meet the given requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Standard Retrieval for accessing the financial data.','B|Use Expedited Retrieval to access the financial data.','C|Use Bulk Retrieval to access the financial data.','D|Specify a range, or portion, of the financial data archive to retrieve.','E|Purchase provisioned retrieval capacity.'],correct:'BE',answer:'For S3 Glacier Expedited retrievals, you must purchase Provisioned Retrieval Capacity to guarantee that Expedited retrievals complete within 1-5 minutes even during high demand.',why:'Expedited Retrieval normally completes in 1-5 minutes but availability is not guaranteed during peak demand — requests may be rejected. Provisioned Retrieval Capacity ensures that Expedited retrievals are accepted. You purchase capacity units (each allows 3 retrievals per 5 minutes and 150MB/s throughput). Standard Retrieval (3-5 hours) and Bulk Retrieval (5-12 hours) do not require provisioned capacity.',trap:'Standard Retrieval (3-5 hours) is slower than required — not acceptable if data is needed urgently. Bulk Retrieval is the slowest and cheapest option, not suitable for urgent access. Specifying a byte range does not guarantee Expedited availability.',rule:'Glacier Expedited guarantee = Provisioned Retrieval Capacity. Without it, Expedited may be rejected at peak. Standard = 3-5 hours. Bulk = 5-12 hours. Expedited = 1-5 min (guaranteed only with Provisioned Capacity). Byte-range does not affect retrieval speed.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_39',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is using Amazon VPC that has a CIDR block of 10.31.0.0/27 that is connected to the on-premises data center. There was a requirement to create a Lambda function that will process massive amounts of cryptocurrency transactions every minute and then store the results to EFS. After setting up the serverless architecture and connecting the Lambda function to the VPC, the Solutions Architect noticed an increase in invocation errors with EC2 error types such as EC2ThrottledException at certain times of the day. Which of the following are the possible causes of this issue? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Your Lambda function exceeds the VPC quota for Elastic Network Interfaces (ENIs) or available IP addresses in the subnet.','B|Your VPC does not have a NAT gateway.','C|The Lambda function is placed in a VPC subnet with limited IP address capacity.','D|The associated security group of your function does not allow outbound connections.','E|The attached IAM execution role of your function does not have the necessary permissions to access the resources of your VPC.'],correct:'AC',answer:'A /27 VPC CIDR gives only 32 IP addresses (minus 5 reserved by AWS = 27 usable). When Lambda functions are placed in a VPC, they consume ENIs from the VPC subnet. A crowded /27 subnet can exhaust available IP addresses, causing Lambda invocations to fail.',why:'Each Lambda function invocation that connects to a VPC uses an Elastic Network Interface (ENI) from the subnet. AWS reserves 5 IPs per subnet (network address, VPC router, DNS, future use, broadcast). A /27 subnet has 27 usable IPs — at scale, Lambda can exhaust these quickly. The fix is to use a larger subnet CIDR (e.g., /24 or larger dedicated Lambda subnets).',trap:'Lambda@Edge functions run at CloudFront edge locations and do not need VPC ENIs. A missing NAT Gateway prevents Lambda from reaching the Internet but does not cause the specific IP exhaustion error. Security group outbound rules block traffic but do not cause ENI allocation failures.',rule:'Lambda in VPC = consumes ENIs from subnet. Small subnet (/27 = 27 usable IPs) → IP exhaustion → Lambda failures. Fix: use larger subnets (/24+) for Lambda. VPC quota for ENIs is set per region; check AWS docs for current limits.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_40',category:'EC2',question:'A tech company is currently using Auto Scaling for their web application. A new AMI now needs to be used for launching a fleet of EC2 instances. Which of the following changes needs to be done?',choices:['A|Do nothing. You can start directly launching EC2 instances in the Auto Scaling group with the same launch template.','B|Create a new launch template.','C|Create a new target group.','D|Create a new target group and launch template.'],correct:'B',answer:'A launch template is a template that an Auto Scaling group uses to launch EC2 instances. When you create a launch template, you specify information for the instances, such as the ID of the Amazon Machine Image (AMI), the instance type, a key pair, one or more security groups, and a block device mapping.',why:'Launch Templates are versioned, unlike the deprecated Launch Configurations which cannot be edited. When you update an AMI, create a new version of the Launch Template pointing to the new AMI ID. The Auto Scaling group continues using the previous version until you update the group to use the new version. You can test a new AMI by deploying a percentage of instances using the new version while keeping the rest on the old version — impossible with Launch Configurations.',trap:'The option that says: Do nothing. You can start directly launching EC2 instances in the Auto Scaling group with the same launch template is incorrect because what you are trying to achieve is to change the AMI being used by your fleet of EC2 instances. Therefore, you need to change the launch template to update what your instances are using.',rule:'Launch Template = versioned EC2 configuration (AMI, instance type, SG, user data). Used by ASG and EC2 Fleet. Replaces Launch Configuration (cannot be updated; Launch Templates can be versioned and updated without creating a new one).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_41',category:'Route 53',question:'A company is setting up a cloud architecture for an international money transfer service to be deployed in AWS which will have thousands of users around the globe. The service should be available 24/7 to avoid any business disruption and should be resilient enough to handle the outage of an entire AWS region. To meet this requirement, the Solutions Architect has deployed their AWS resources to multiple AWS Regions. He needs to use Route 53 and configure it to set all of the resources to be available all the time as much as possible. When a resource becomes unavailable, Route 53 should detect that it\'s unhealthy and stop including it when responding to queries. Which of the following is the most fault-tolerant routing configuration that the Solutions Architect should use in this scenario?',choices:['A|Configure an Active-Active Failover with Weighted routing policy.','B|Configure an Active-Passive Failover with Weighted Records.','C|Configure an Active-Active Failover with One Primary and One Secondary Resource.','D|Configure an Active-Passive Failover with Multiple Primary and Secondary Resources.'],correct:'A',answer:'Active-Active Failover routes all healthy resources simultaneously. Only Route 53 routing policies other than Failover (such as Weighted, Latency, or Geolocation) can achieve this.',why:'Active-Active means all records serve traffic at the same time. Route 53 achieves this with any routing policy except Failover — Weighted (e.g., 50/50), Latency (serve from fastest region), or Geolocation (serve from nearest region) all keep multiple records active simultaneously. Health checks are used to remove unhealthy records from rotation.',trap:'Active-Passive Failover with Weighted Records is a contradiction — Weighted routing distributes proportionally (active-active), not primary/standby. Active-Passive Failover with One Primary uses the Failover routing policy, which is explicitly excluded.',rule:'Active = primary standby = Failover policy. Use health checks to auto-remove unhealthy endpoints. Active-Active = Weighted/Latency/Geolocation. Failover routing = active-passive architecture.',keywords:'Active-passive DNS failover → Route 53 Failover Routing + health check.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_42',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to use a durable storage service to store on-premises database backups to the AWS cloud. To move their backup data, they need to use a service that can store and retrieve objects through standard file storage protocols for quick recovery. Which of the following options will meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Use the AWS Storage Gateway volume gateway to store the backup data and directly access it using Amazon S3 API actions.','B|Use Amazon EBS volumes to store all the backup data and attach it to an Amazon EC2 instance.','C|Use AWS Snowball Edge to directly backup the data in Amazon S3 Glacier.','D|Use the AWS Storage Gateway file gateway to store all the backup data in Amazon S3.'],correct:'D',answer:'File Gateway presents a file-based interface to Amazon S3, which appears as a network file share. It enables you to store and retrieve Amazon S3 objects through standard file storage protocols. File Gateway allows your existing file-based applications or devices to use secure and durable cloud storage without needing to be modified.',why:'To store the backup data from on-premises to a durable cloud storage service, you can use File Gateway to store and retrieve objects through standard file storage protocols (SMB or NFS). File Gateway enables your existing file-based applications, devices, and workflows to use Amazon S3, without modification.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS Snowball Edge to directly backup the data in Amazon S3 Glacier is incorrect because AWS Snowball Edge cannot store and retrieve objects through standard file storage protocols. Also, Snowball Edge can’t directly integrate backups to S3 Glacier.',rule:'File Gateway enables your existing file-based applications, devices, and workflows to use Amazon S3, without modification. Not AWS Snowball.',keywords:'On-premises file access backed by S3 = Storage Gateway File Gateway (ongoing hybrid).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_43',category:'Networking',question:'A major TV network has a web application running on eight Amazon T3 EC2 instances behind an application load balancer. The number of requests that the application processes are consistent and do not experience spikes. A Solutions Architect must configure an Auto Scaling group for the instances to ensure that the application is running at all times. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirements?',choices:['A|Deploy eight EC2 instances with Auto Scaling in one Availability Zone behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer.','B|Deploy four EC2 instances with Auto Scaling in one region and four in another region behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer.','C|Deploy four EC2 instances with Auto Scaling in one Availability Zone and four in another availability zone in the same region behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer.','D|Deploy two EC2 instances with Auto Scaling in four regions behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer.'],correct:'B',answer:'The best option to take is to deploy four EC2 instances in one Availability Zone and four in another availability zone in the same region behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer. In this way, if one availability zone goes down, there is still another available zone that can accommodate traffic.',why:'A Spread placement group guarantees that each instance is placed on distinct underlying hardware — specifically, a different rack with its own network and power. This eliminates correlated hardware failures. The maximum density is 7 instances per AZ per spread group. For 8 instances needing maximum resilience, split 4 across two AZs in a spread group. The ALB distributes traffic across both AZs and automatically stops routing to unhealthy instances.',trap:'The option that says: Deploy eight EC2 instances with Auto Scaling in one Availability Zone behind an Amazon Elastic Load Balancer is incorrect because this architecture is not highly available. If that Availability Zone goes down, then your web application will be unreachable.',rule:'Spread placement group = max 1 instance per rack per AZ. Best for small groups of critical instances needing rack isolation. Cluster = same rack (low latency). Partition = groups of instances that share no underlying hardware. Spread = fault isolation, max 7/AZ.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_44',category:'Serverless',question:'A FinTech startup deployed an application on an Amazon EC2 instance with attached Instance Store volumes and an Elastic IP address. The server is only accessed from 8 AM to 6 PM and can be stopped from 6 PM to 8 AM for cost efficiency using Lambda with the script that automates this based on tags. Which of the following will occur when the EC2 instance is stopped and started? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|The underlying host for the instance is possibly changed.','B|The ENI (Elastic Network Interface) is detached.','C|All data on the attached instance-store devices will be lost.','D|The Elastic IP address is disassociated with the instance.','E|There will be no changes.'],correct:'AC',answer:'This question did not mention the specific type of EC2 instance, however, it says that it will be stopped and started. Since only EBS-backed instances can be stopped and restarted, it is implied that the instance is EBS-backed.',why:'When EC2 stops normally, the hypervisor marks the vCPU/RAM as released and the host can be reclaimed. The next start may land on a different physical host, giving a new underlying host and potentially a new public IP (private IP stays). Hibernate also stops the instance and may change the underlying host, but restores the RAM contents on the new host.',trap:'The option that says: The ENI (Elastic Network Interface) is detached is incorrect because the ENI will stay attached even if you stopped your EC2 instance.',rule:'- The underlying host for the instance is possibly changed.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_45',category:'Database',question:'A production MySQL database hosted on Amazon RDS is running out of disk storage. The management has consulted its solutions architect to increase the disk space without impacting the database performance. How can the solutions architect satisfy the requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Modify the DB instance settings and enable storage autoscaling.','B|Increase the allocated storage for the DB instance.','C|Change the default_storage_engine of the DB instance’s parameter group to MyISAM.','D|Modify the DB instance storage type to Provisioned IOPS.'],correct:'A',answer:'RDS Storage Auto Scaling automatically scales storage capacity in response to growing database workloads, with zero downtime.',why:'Under-provisioning could result in application downtime, and over-provisioning could result in underutilized resources and higher costs. With RDS Storage Auto Scaling, you simply set your desired maximum storage limit, and Auto Scaling takes care of the rest. RDS Storage Auto Scaling continuously monitors actual storage consumption, and scales capacity up automatically when actual utilization approaches provisioned storage capacity.',trap:'The option that says: Increase the allocated storage for the DB instance is incorrect. This option simply requires monitoring and proactive planning. While it can solve the immediate issue, it doesn\'t scale well over time and involves operational overhead, as administrators must intervene each time storage needs grow.',rule:'Under-provisioning could result in application downtime, and over-provisioning could result in underutilized resources and higher costs.',keywords:'RDS disk full → enable Storage Auto Scaling. Grows automatically, no downtime.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_46',category:'Serverless',question:'A company needs to use Amazon Aurora as the Amazon RDS database engine for its web application. The Solutions Architect has been instructed to implement a 90-day RDS backup retention policy. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Configure an automated backup and set the backup retention period to 90 days.','B|Create an AWS Backup plan to take daily snapshots with a retention period of 90 days.','C|Configure RDS to export the automated snapshot automatically to Amazon S3 and create a lifecycle policy to delete the object after 90 days.','D|Create a daily scheduled event using Amazon EventBridge and AWS Lambda to directly download the RDS automated snapshot to an Amazon S3 bucket. Archive snapshots older than 90 days to Glacier.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Backup is a centralized backup service that makes it easy and cost-effective for you to backup your application data across AWS services in the AWS Cloud, helping you meet your business and regulatory backup compliance requirements.',why:'In this scenario, you can use AWS Backup to create a backup plan with a retention period of 90 days. A backup plan is a policy expression that defines when and how you want to back up your AWS resources. You assign resources to backup plans, and AWS Backup then automatically backs up and retains backups for those resources according to the backup plan.',trap:'The option that says: Configure an automated backup and set the backup retention period to 90 days is incorrect because the maximum backup retention period for automated backup is only 35 days.',rule:'Backup → AWS Backup plan to take.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_47',category:'Networking',question:'You are automating the creation of EC2 instances in your VPC. Hence, you wrote a python script to trigger the Amazon EC2 API to request 50 EC2 instances in a single Availability Zone. However, you noticed that after 20 successful requests, subsequent requests failed. What could be a reason for this issue and how would you resolve it?',choices:['A|There was an issue with the Amazon EC2 API. Just resend the requests and these will be provisioned successfully.','B|By default, AWS allows you to provision a maximum of 20 instances per region. Select a different region and retry the failed request.','C|By default, AWS allows you to provision a maximum of 20 instances per Availability Zone. Select a different Availability Zone and retry the failed request.','D|There is a vCPU-based On-Demand Instance limit per region which is why subsequent requests failed. Just submit the limit increase form to AWS and retry the failed requests once approved.'],correct:'D',answer:'You are limited to running On-Demand Instances per your vCPU-based On-Demand Instance limit, purchasing 20 Reserved Instances, and requesting Spot Instances per your dynamic Spot limit per region. New AWS accounts may start with limits that are lower than the limits described here.',why:'If you need more instances, complete the Amazon EC2 limit increase request form with your use case, and your limit increase will be considered. Limit increases are tied to the region they were requested for.',trap:'The option that says: There was an issue with the Amazon EC2 API. Just resend the requests and these will be provisioned successfully is incorrect because you are limited to running On-Demand Instances per your vCPU-based On-Demand Instance limit. There is also a limit of purchasing 20 Reserved Instances and requesting Spot Instances per your dynamic Spot limit per region hence, there is no problem with the EC2 API.',rule:'AWS and retry the failed: correct. Amazon EC2: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_48',category:'Networking',question:'An aerospace engineering company recently adopted a hybrid cloud infrastructure with AWS. One of the responsibilities of the Solutions Architect is to launch an Amazon VPC with both public and private subnets for Amazon EC2 instances and database instances. The architecture must ensure each subnet is properly defined within the assigned VPC CIDR block. Which of the following statements are true regarding VPC subnets? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|EC2 instances in a private subnet can communicate with the Internet only if they have an Elastic IP.','B|Each subnet maps to a single Availability Zone.','C|The allowed block size in VPC is between a /16 netmask (65,536 IP addresses) and /27 netmask (32 IP addresses).','D|Each newly created subnet is, by default, linked to the main route table of the VPC.','E|Each subnet spans 2 Availability Zones.'],correct:'BD',answer:'Each subnet in AWS maps to exactly one Availability Zone. Newly created subnets are automatically associated with the main route table of the VPC.',why:'A subnet is a range of IP addresses within a VPC that resides entirely within one AZ — it cannot span multiple AZs. The VPC main route table is the default route table; any new subnet not explicitly associated with a custom route table inherits the main route table. This is why careful route table management is critical for security.',trap:'Private subnet instances require a NAT Gateway or NAT Instance for Internet access — not an Elastic IP (EIPs are for public subnets). The allowed VPC CIDR block size is between /16 (65,536 IPs) and /28 (16 IPs), not /27. Subnets cannot span Availability Zones.',rule:'Subnet = single AZ only. New subnet → inherits main route table by default. VPC CIDR range = /16 to /28. Private instance Internet = NAT Gateway (not EIP).',keywords:'Each subnet maps to a single AZ. Cannot span multiple AZs. VPC CIDR block: /16 to /28.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_49',category:'Networking',question:'A travel company has a suite of web applications hosted in an Auto Scaling group of On-Demand EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer that handles traffic from various web domains such as i-love-manila.com,i-love-boracay.com i-love-cebu.com and many others. To improve security and lessen the overall cost, you are instructed to secure the system by allowing multiple domains to serve SSL traffic without the need to reauthenticate and reprovision your certificate everytime you add a new domain. This migration from HTTP to HTTPS will help improve their SEO and Google search ranking. Which of the following is the most cost-effective solution to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Use a wildcard certificate to handle multiple sub-domains and different domains.','B|Add a Subject Alternative Name (SAN) for each additional domain to your certificate.','C|Create a new CloudFront web distribution and configure it to serve HTTPS requests using dedicated IP addresses in order to associate your alternate domain names with a dedicated IP address in each CloudFront edge location.','D|Upload all SSL certificates of the domains in the ALB using the console and bind multiple certificates to the same secure listener on your load balancer. ALB will automatically choose the optimal TLS certificate for each client using Server Name Indication (SNI).'],correct:'D',answer:'SNI Custom SSL relies on the SNI extension of the Transport Layer Security protocol, which allows multiple domains to serve SSL traffic over the same IP address by including the hostname which the viewers are trying to connect to.',why:'You can host multiple TLS-secured applications, each with its own TLS certificate, behind a single load balancer. In order to use SNI, all you need to do is bind multiple certificates to the same secure listener on your load balancer. ALB will automatically choose the optimal TLS certificate for each client. These features are provided at no additional charge.',trap:'Using a wildcard certificate to handle multiple sub-domains and different domains is incorrect because a wildcard certificate can only handle multiple sub-domains but not different domains.',rule:'Multiple SSL certs on one ALB = SNI (Server Name Indication). ALB reads the TLS ClientHello hostname and selects the matching certificate. Supports multiple certs per listener. No additional cost for SNI on ALB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_50',category:'Serverless',question:'A solutions architect is writing an AWS Lambda function that will process encrypted documents from an Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP file system. The documents are protected by an AWS KMS customer key. After processing the documents, the Lambda function will store the results in an S3 bucket with an Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval storage class. The solutions architect must ensure that the files can be decrypted by the Lambda function. Which action accomplishes the requirement?',choices:['A|Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function’s execution role. Add a statement to the AWS KMS key’s policy that grants the function’s execution role the kms:decrypt permission.','B|Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function’s resource policy. Add a statement to the AWS KMS key’s policy that grants the function’s resource policy ARN the kms:decrypt permission.','C|Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function’s execution role. Add a statement to the AWS KMS key’s policy that grants the function’s ARN the kms:decrypt permission.','D|Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function’s resource policy. Add a statement to the AWS KMS key’s policy that grants the function’s execution role the kms:decrypt permission.'],correct:'A',answer:'A key policy is a resource policy for an AWS KMS key. Key policies are the primary way to control access to KMS keys. Every KMS key must have exactly one key policy. The statements in the key policy determine who has permission to use the KMS key and how they can use it.',why:'Unless the key policy explicitly allows it, you cannot use IAM policies to allow access to a KMS key. Without permission from the key policy, IAM policies that allow permissions have no effect. (You can use an IAM policy to deny permission to a KMS key without permission from a key policy.) The default key policy enables IAM policies. To enable IAM policies in your key policy, add the policy statement described here.',trap:'The option that says: Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function\'s resource policy. Add a statement to the AWS KMS key’s policy that grants the function’s resource policy ARN the kms:decrypt permission is incorrect. The resource policy specifies who can invoke the Lambda function, not which AWS operations it can use.',rule:'Unless the key policy explicitly allows it, you cannot use IAM policies to allow access to a KMS key. Not AWS operations.',keywords:'Linux + Windows sharing same file system → FSx for NetApp ONTAP (NFS + SMB + iSCSI).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_51',category:'IAM',question:'A Solutions Architect is managing a company\'s AWS account of approximately 300 IAM users. They have a new company policy that requires changing the associated permissions of all 100 IAM users that control the access to Amazon S3 buckets. What will the Solutions Architect do to avoid the time-consuming task of applying the policy to each user?',choices:['A|Create a new IAM group and then add the users that require access to the S3 bucket. Afterwards, apply the policy to IAM group.','B|Create a new policy and apply it to multiple IAM users using a shell script.','C|Create a new S3 bucket access policy with unlimited access for each IAM user.','D|Create a new IAM role and add each user to the IAM role.'],correct:'A',answer:'The most efficient way to manage permissions for 300 IAM users is to create an IAM Group, add all relevant users to the group, and attach the S3 bucket access policy to the group.',why:'IAM Groups let you apply a policy once and have it apply to all members. Adding or removing a user from the group immediately grants or revokes the policy. This is far more maintainable than attaching policies to each user individually. IAM best practice: never assign permissions directly to users — always use groups.',trap:'A shell script to apply policies to multiple users is error-prone, creates drift between users, and requires maintenance. Creating unlimited-access bucket policies for each user violates least privilege and is harder to audit. IAM Roles are for granting AWS service access or cross-account access, not for organizing users with shared permissions.',rule:'IAM Users = long-term credentials for humans. Groups = collection of users for shared permissions. Not IAM Roles (those are for services/cross-account). Groups cannot be nested — a group cannot contain another group.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_52',category:'Networking',question:'A company has an On-Demand EC2 instance located in a subnet in AWS that hosts a web application. The security group attached to this EC2 instance has the following Inbound Rules: ​ The Route table attached to the VPC is shown below. You can establish an SSH connection into the EC2 instance from the Internet. However, you are not able to connect to the web server using your Chrome browser. ​ Which of the below steps would resolve the issue? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|In the Security Group, add an Inbound HTTP rule.','B|In the Security Group, remove the SSH rule.','C|In the Route table, add this new route entry: 0.0.0.0 -> igw-b51618cc','D|In the Route table, add this new route entry: 10.0.0.0/27 -> local'],correct:'CD',answer:'To allow HTTP traffic to reach an EC2 instance, add an inbound rule to the instance security group allowing TCP port 80 from the source IP range (0.0.0.0/0 for public access).',why:'Security groups are stateful — if you allow inbound HTTP (port 80), the response traffic is automatically allowed outbound. Security groups act as virtual firewalls at the instance level. You need to add an inbound rule, not outbound, because security groups are stateful (return traffic is automatically permitted).',trap:'Removing the SSH rule would break administrative access but would not fix HTTP access. Route table entries use CIDR destination ranges — there is no 0.0.0.0 route, only 0.0.0.0/0. The 10.0.0.0/27 → local route already exists by default in every VPC subnet route table.',rule:'EC2 HTTP access = add inbound Security Group rule TCP port 80. SGs are stateful (no outbound rule needed). Route tables control routing, not port access. 10.0.0.0/27 → local is automatically included in every route table and cannot be removed.',keywords:'Security group source = other SG ID (covers all current + future ASG members). Not instance IDs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_53',category:'S3',question:'A company has clients all across the globe that access product files stored in several Amazon S3 buckets, which are behind each of the respective Amazon CloudFront web distributions. The company currently wants to deliver content to a specific client, ensuring that only that client can access the data. At present, all clients can access the S3 buckets directly using an S3 URL or through the CloudFront distribution. The Solutions Architect must serve the private content via CloudFront only, to secure the distribution of files. Which combination of actions should the Architect implement to meet the above requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Create a custom CloudFront function to check and ensure that only their clients can access the files.','B|Enable the Origin Shield feature of the CloudFront distribution to protect the files from unauthorized access.','C|Generate an S3 presigned URL to ensure that only the client can access the files. Remove permission to use S3 URLs to read the files for anyone else.','D|Restrict access to files in the origin by creating an origin access control (OAC) and giving it permission to read the files in the bucket.','E|Require the users to access the private content by using special CloudFront signed URLs or signed cookies.'],correct:'DE',answer:'CloudFront signed URLs and Origin Access Control (OAC) together restrict private file access: OAC limits S3 access to only the CloudFront distribution, and signed URLs grant time-limited access to individual files.',why:'OAC replaces the older Origin Access Identity (OAI) and allows CloudFront to authenticate to S3 using IAM. The S3 bucket policy denies all access except from the CloudFront distribution. Signed URLs or Signed Cookies then control which users get access and for how long. Together: no one can access files directly from S3, and only authenticated users get valid signed URLs from CloudFront.',trap:'CloudFront functions can process requests at the edge but cannot generate signed URLs on behalf of users — that is a server-side operation. Origin Shield adds a caching layer to reduce origin load — it does not restrict access. Pre-signed S3 URLs bypass CloudFront entirely and expose the S3 bucket endpoint to clients.',rule:'Private CloudFront content = OAC (S3 access only via CF) + Signed URLs or Signed Cookies (per-user access control). OAC replaced OAI. Never use S3 pre-signed URLs with CloudFront — they bypass CloudFront and go directly to S3.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_54',category:'S3',question:'A company runs a multi-tier web application in the AWS Cloud. The application tier is hosted on Amazon EC2 instances and the backend database is hosted on an Amazon Aurora for MySQL DB cluster. For security compliance, all of the application variables such as DB hostnames, environment settings, product keys, and database passwords must be stored securely with encryption. Which of the following options is the most cost-effective solution to meet the requirements?',choices:['A|Store the values by creating SecureString type parameters in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) for the encryption. Update the application to retrieve the parameter values.','B|Store the values by creating secrets in AWS Secrets Manager. Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) for the encryption. Use the BatchGetSecretValue API to retrieve multiple secrets efficiently. Update the application to retrieve the values of the secrets.','C|Store the values in a file saved in an Amazon S3 bucket. Enable encryption on the S3 bucket. Configure the application to download the file contents when it starts.','D|Store the values as key-value pairs in AWS Systems Manager OpsCenter. By default, the key-value pairs will be encrypted at rest. Configure the application to retrieve the variables when it starts.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Systems Manager is a collection of capabilities to help you manage your applications and infrastructure running in the AWS Cloud. Systems Manager simplifies application and resource management, shortens the time to detect and resolve operational problems, and helps you manage your AWS resources securely at scale.',why:'Parameter Store provides secure, hierarchical storage for configuration data and secrets management. You can store data such as passwords, database strings, Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) instance IDs and Amazon Machine Image (AMI) IDs, and license codes as parameter values. You can store values as plain text or encrypted data.',trap:'The option that says: Store the values by creating secrets in AWS Secrets Manager. Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) for the encryption. Use the BatchGetSecretValue API to retrieve multiple secrets efficiently. Update the application to retrieve the values of the secrets is incorrect. While Secrets Manager provides secure storage and supports encrypted retrieval using BatchGetSecretValue, it incurs a recurring cost of approximately $0.40 per secret per month, making it less cost-effective for storing a large number of static values. It is primarily designed for sensitive secrets that require features like automatic rotation and fine-grained access control. For storing application parameters that change infrequently and do not require rotation, AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store with SecureString is a more appropriate and cost-effective solution.',rule:'Parameter Store provides secure, hierarchical storage for configuration data and secrets management.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_55',category:'Serverless',question:'A company requires that all AWS resources be tagged with a standard naming convention for better access control. The company’s solutions architect must implement a solution that checks for untagged AWS resources. Which solution requires the least amount of effort to implement?',choices:['A|Use an AWS Config rule to detect non-compliant tags.','B|Use tag policies in AWS Organizations to standardize the naming of tags. Store all the tags in an Amazon S3 bucket with the S3 Object Lock feature enabled.','C|Create a Lambda function that runs compliance checks on tagged resources. Schedule the function using Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events).','D|Use service control policies (SCP) to detect resources that are not tagged properly.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Organizations tag policies enforce standardized tag naming conventions across all accounts in an organization, ensuring consistent tagging for cost allocation and resource management.',why:'Tag policies in AWS Organizations define rules for tag keys and values across member accounts. When enabled, they can be set to enforce compliance — preventing resource creation with non-compliant tags, or only reporting violations. This provides organization-wide tag standardization without requiring per-account configuration.',trap:'AWS Config rules can detect non-compliant tags after resources are created but cannot enforce naming conventions at creation time without custom remediation. Lambda-based checks add operational overhead and are reactive, not preventive. SCPs control which API actions accounts can perform — they cannot enforce specific tag values.',rule:'Tag standardization across org accounts = AWS Organizations tag policies. Config rules = reactive detection. SCPs = API action control. Tag policies = proactive enforcement at resource creation to enforce tagging standards before non-compliant resources are created.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_56',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect is unable to connect to the newly deployed EC2 instance via SSH using a home computer. However, the Architect was able to successfully access other existing instances in the VPC without any issues. Which of the following should the Architect check and possibly correct to restore connectivity? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager.','B|Configure the Network Access Control List of your VPC to permit ingress traffic over port 22 from your IP.','C|Configure the Security Group of the EC2 instance to permit ingress traffic over port 3389 from your IP.','D|Configure the Security Group of the EC2 instance to permit ingress traffic over port 22 from your IP.'],correct:'AB',answer:'When connecting to your EC2 instance via SSH, you need to ensure that port 22 is allowed on the security group of your EC2 instance.',why:'A security group acts as a virtual firewall that controls the traffic for one or more instances. When you launch an instance, you associate one or more security groups with the instance. You add rules to each security group that allow traffic to or from its associated instances.',trap:'Using Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager is incorrect because this is primarily used to manage the lifecycle of your AWS resources and not to allow certain traffic to go through.',rule:'Amazon = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'ACM certificate for custom domain: Regional API = same region. Edge-optimized = us-east-1 only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_57',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a large insurance firm. To maintain compliance with HIPAA laws, all data that is backed up or stored on Amazon S3 needs to be encrypted at rest. Which encryption methods can be employed, assuming S3 is being used for storing financial-related data? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Enable SSE on an S3 bucket to make use of AES-256 encryption','B|Store the data in encrypted EBS snapshots','C|Encrypt the data using your own encryption keys then copy the data to Amazon S3 over HTTPS endpoints.','D|Store the data on EBS volumes with encryption enabled instead of using Amazon S3','E|Use AWS Shield to protect your data at rest'],correct:'AD',answer:'For HIPAA compliance, data stored in S3 must be encrypted at rest. Valid options are: (A) client-side encryption before upload, (D) SSE-S3 (AES-256 server-managed), and (E) SSE-KMS (AWS KMS-managed). Note: S3 uses AES-256 only, never AES-128.',why:'HIPAA requires encryption of PHI at rest. Client-side encryption encrypts before the PUT request — you control the keys. SSE-S3 uses AES-256 with S3-managed keys. SSE-KMS uses AES-256 with customer-controlled KMS keys and provides audit logging of key usage. All three are valid. AWS Shield protects against DDoS — it has no role in data encryption at rest.',trap:'Storing data in encrypted EBS snapshots is meaningless for S3 — EBS is block storage attached to EC2 instances. EBS encryption does not apply to S3 objects. AWS Shield is a DDoS protection service, not a data-at-rest encryption service. S3 never supports AES-128 — only AES-256.',rule:'S3 encryption at rest options: SSE-S3 (AES-256, S3-managed), SSE-KMS (AES-256, KMS), SSE-C (customer-provided), or client-side. S3 only supports AES-256. EBS encryption ≠ S3 encryption are separate. EBS encryption uses KMS; S3 uses SSE-S3/SSE-KMS/SSE-C.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_58',category:'IAM',question:'A company that is rapidly growing in recent months has been in the process of setting up IAM users on its single AWS Account. A solutions architect has been tasked to handle the user management, which includes granting read-only access to users and denying permissions whenever an IAM user has no MFA setup. New users will be added frequently based on their respective departments. Which of the following action is the MOST secure way to grant permissions to the new users?',choices:['A|Launch an IAM Group for each department. Create an IAM Policy that enforces MFA authentication with the least privilege permission. Attach the IAM Policy to each IAM Group.','B|Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) that enforces MFA authentication for each department. Add a trust relationship to every SCP and attach it to each IAM User.','C|Create an IAM Role that enforces MFA authentication with the least privilege permission. Set up a corresponding IAM Group for each department. Attach the IAM Role to the IAM Groups.','D|Set up IAM roles for each IAM user and associate a permissions boundary that defines the maximum permissions.'],correct:'A',answer:'Launch an IAM Group for each department. Create an IAM Policy that enforces MFA authentication with the least privilege permission. Attach the IAM Policy to each IAM Group.',why:'Multi-factor authentication (MFA) in AWS is a simple best practice that adds an extra layer of protection on top of your user name and password. With MFA enabled, when a user signs in to an AWS Management Console, they will be prompted for their user name and password (the first factor—what they know), as well as for an authentication code from their AWS MFA device (the second factor—what they have).',trap:'The option that says: Create an IAM Role that enforces MFA authentication with the least privilege permission. Set up a corresponding IAM Group for each department. Attach the IAM Role to the IAM Groups is incorrect because an IAM Group is usually provided with an IAM Policy and not an IAM Role. There is no direct way in the AWS Management Console to manually assign an IAM Role to a particular IAM Group.',rule:'Launch an IAM Group for each department. Attach a single policy to the group instead of attaching policies to each individual user.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_59',category:'Networking',question:'A large financial firm needs to set up a Linux bastion host to allow access to the Amazon EC2 instances running in their VPC. For security purposes, only the clients connecting from the corporate external public IP address 175.45.116.100 should have SSH access to the host. Which is the best option that can meet the customer\'s requirement?',choices:['A|Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – TCP. Port Range – 22, Source 175.45.116.100/32','B|Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Source 175.45.116.100/32','C|Network ACL Inbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Source 175.45.116.100/32','D|Network ACL Inbound Rule: Protocol – TCP, Port Range-22, Source 175.45.116.100/0'],correct:'A',answer:'When setting up a bastion host in AWS, you should only allow the individual IP of the client and not the entire network. Therefore, in the Source,  the proper CIDR notation should be used. The /32 denotes one IP address, and the /0 refers to the entire network.',why:'A bastion host is a special purpose computer on a network specifically designed and configured to withstand attacks. The computer generally hosts a single application, for example, a proxy server, and all other services are removed or limited to reduce the threat to the computer.',trap:'The option that says: Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Source 175.45.116.100/32 is incorrect since the SSH protocol uses TCP and port 22, and not UDP.',rule:'Bastion host SSH access: Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol TCP, Port 22, Source = specific IP /32. Always restrict to specific corporate IPs, never 0.0.0.0/0 (open to all).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_60',category:'Networking',question:'A company has launched multiple Amazon EC2 instances inside a private subnet of a VPC. The Solutions Architect is reviewing the Network ACL (NACL) rules associated with that subnet to ensure security. The current Inbound Rules for the NACL are configured as follows: A computer with the IP address 110.238.109.37 attempts to send a request to one of the EC2 instances in this subnet. What will happen to the incoming request based on the NACL rules?',choices:['A|Initially, it will be allowed and then after a while, the connection will be denied.','B|Initially, it will be denied and then after a while, the connection will be allowed.','C|It will be allowed.','D|It will be denied.'],correct:'C',answer:'When evaluating the incoming request from the IP 110.238.109.37 to an EC2 instance in the private subnet, the Network ACL (NACL) processes rules sequentially, starting from the lowest rule number. NACLs are stateless, meaning they apply each rule independently and in the order defined, unlike stateful security groups that track connection states.',why:'The default deny-all rule (*) does not come into play here because the request was already processed by an earlier rule. This behavior aligns with AWS’s NACL best practices, where explicit allow rules should be placed after any specific deny rules to ensure proper traffic management. The allow-all rule in Rule #100 takes precedence as it is evaluated first.',trap:'The option that says: Initially, it will be allowed and then after a while, the connection will be denied is incorrect because NACLs only evaluate rules statically, they do not track connection states or change decisions over time. Unlike stateful security groups, NACLs simply process rules in order, and the request is immediately denied by Rule #101. There’s no "initial allowance" or delayed denial.',rule:'S3 default object ownership = uploader account. Use bucket-owner-full-control ACL canned policy or Object Ownership = BucketOwnerEnforced to transfer ownership. BucketOwnerEnforced = disables ACLs entirely; bucket owner automatically owns all objects.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_61',category:'Networking',question:'A company hosted a web application on a Linux Amazon EC2 instance in the public subnet that uses a non-default network ACL. The instance uses a default security group and has an attached Elastic IP address. The network ACL is configured to block all inbound and outbound traffic. The Solutions Architect must allow incoming traffic on port 443 to access the application from any source. Which combination of steps will accomplish this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|In the Security Group, add a new rule to allow TCP connection on port 443 from source 0.0.0.0/0','B|In the Network ACL, update the rule to allow both inbound and outbound TCP connection on port 443 from source 0.0.0.0/0 and to destination 0.0.0.0/0','C|In the Security Group, create a new rule to allow TCP connection on port 443 to destination 0.0.0.0/0','D|In the Network ACL, update the rule to allow outbound TCP connection on port 32768 - 65535 to destination 0.0.0.0/0','E|In the Network ACL, update the rule to allow inbound TCP connection on port 443 from source 0.0.0.0/0 and outbound TCP connection on port 32768 - 65535 to destination 0.0.0.0/0'],correct:'AB',answer:'Security groups are stateful — adding inbound rule A (allow TCP port 443 from 0.0.0.0/0) is sufficient for the SG since return traffic is automatically allowed. NACLs are stateless — option E covers both: inbound TCP port 443 AND outbound TCP ports 32768-65535 for the response (ephemeral ports).',why:'NACLs must explicitly allow both inbound and outbound traffic. HTTPS inbound arrives on port 443; the response travels back on an ephemeral port chosen by the client (32768-61000 on Linux, 1024-65535 broadly). Without the outbound ephemeral rule, the NACL silently drops response packets. Security groups are stateful — once the inbound rule matches, the return traffic is automatically permitted without a separate outbound rule.',trap:'Option B (allow both inbound and outbound port 443 in NACL) is wrong — the response traffic is NOT on port 443, it uses ephemeral ports. Option C (SG outbound to 443) is unnecessary because SGs are stateful — the default outbound rule already allows all traffic. Option D only adds the outbound ephemeral rule but is missing the required inbound port 443 NACL rule.',rule:'NACL = stateless: inbound 443 + outbound ephemeral 32768-65535 both required. SG = stateful: only inbound 443 needed. Ephemeral ports = response path. Default SG already allows all outbound.',keywords:'Security Group = stateful, instance-level. Reference SG ID as source = covers all current + future ASG members.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_62',category:'S3',question:'An investment bank is working with an IT team to handle the launch of the new digital wallet system. The applications will run on multiple EBS-backed EC2 instances which will store the logs, transactions, and billing statements of the user in an S3 bucket. Due to tight security and compliance requirements, the IT team is exploring options on how to safely store sensitive data on the EBS volumes and S3. Which of the below options should be carried out when storing sensitive data on AWS? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Create an EBS Snapshot','B|Enable EBS Encryption','C|Migrate the EC2 instances from the public to private subnet.','D|Enable Amazon S3 Server-Side or use Client-Side Encryption','E|Use AWS Shield and WAF'],correct:'BD',answer:'Use Client-Side Encryption – You can encrypt data client-side and upload the encrypted data to Amazon S3. In this case, you manage the encryption process, the encryption keys, and related tools.',why:'In Amazon S3, data protection refers to protecting data while in-transit (as it travels to and from Amazon S3) and at rest (while it is stored on disks in Amazon S3 data centers). You can protect data in transit by using SSL or by using client-side encryption. You have the following options to protect data at rest in Amazon S3.',trap:'Creating an EBS Snapshot is incorrect because this is a backup solution of EBS. It does not provide security of data inside EBS volumes when executed.',rule:'EBS = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_63',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company intends to give each of its developers a personal AWS account through AWS Organizations. To enforce regulatory policies, preconfigured AWS Config rules will be set in the new accounts. A solutions architect must see to it that developers are unable to remove or modify any rules in AWS Config. Which solution meets the objective with the least operational overhead?',choices:['A|Add the developers\' AWS account to an organization unit (OU). Attach a service control policy (SCP) to the OU that restricts access to AWS Config.','B|Use an IAM Role in the new accounts with an attached IAM trust relationship to disable the access of the root user to AWS Config.','C|Configure an AWS Config rule in the root account to detect if changes to the new account’s Config rules are made.','D|Set up an AWS Control Tower in the root account to detect if there were any changes to the new account’s AWS Config rules. Attach an IAM trust relationship to the IAM User of each developer which prevents any changes in AWS Config.'],correct:'A',answer:'Attaching an SCP to an OU in AWS Organizations restricts what IAM actions are possible within all accounts in that OU, even for the root user. This prevents developers from performing actions outside their boundaries.',why:'SCPs define the maximum permissions boundary for all principals in all accounts under the OU — including account administrators and root users. An IAM policy in the account cannot grant permissions that the SCP denies. SCPs do not grant permissions; they only restrict what is possible. This is the most centralized, low-maintenance way to restrict developer accounts.',trap:'Using IAM trust relationships only controls cross-account access assumptions — they cannot restrict what a developer does within their own account. AWS Config rules detect non-compliance after the fact but cannot prevent actions. AWS Control Tower detects drift but does not use SCPs by default for per-developer restrictions.',rule:'Restrict developer accounts centrally = SCP attached to OU in AWS Organizations. SCPs = maximum permission ceiling, override all IAM. Even root user is bound by SCPs. Config = detect drift (reactive). SCPs = prevent actions (proactive guardrails).',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_64',category:'IAM',question:'A company uses multiple AWS accounts consolidated under AWS Organizations. The company needs to copy multiple Amazon S3 objects to an S3 bucket in a different owned AWS account. The Solutions Architect must configure permissions to enable this transfer while ensuring the destination account owns the copied objects rather than the source account. How can the Architect accomplish this requirement?',choices:['A|Enable the Requester Pays feature in the source S3 bucket. The fees would be waived through Consolidated Billing since both AWS accounts are part of the organization.','B|Configure cross-account permissions in S3 by creating an IAM customer-managed policy that allows an IAM user or role to copy objects from the source bucket in one account to the destination bucket in the other account. Then attach the policy to the IAM user or role that you want to use to copy objects between accounts.','C|Set up cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) in S3 by creating a bucket policy that includes AmazonS3FullAccess and allows an IAM user or role to copy objects from the source bucket in one account to the destination bucket in the other account.','D|Connect the two S3 buckets from two different AWS accounts to Amazon WorkDocs. Set up cross-account access to integrate the two S3 buckets. Use the WorkDocs console to copy the objects from one account to the other with modified object ownership assigned to the destination account.'],correct:'B',answer:'By default, an S3 object is owned by the account that uploaded the object. That\'s why granting the destination account the permissions to perform the cross-account copy makes sure that the destination owns the copied objects. You can also change the ownership of an object by changing its access control list (ACL) to bucket-owner-full-control.',why:'However, object ACLs can be difficult to manage for multiple objects, so it\'s a best practice to grant programmatic cross-account permissions to the destination account. Object ownership is important for managing permissions using a bucket policy. For a bucket policy to apply to an object in the bucket, the object must be owned by the account that owns the bucket. You can also manage object permissions using the object\'s ACL.',trap:'The option that says: Enable the Requester Pays feature in the source S3 bucket. The fees would be waived through Consolidated Billing since both AWS accounts are part of the organization is incorrect because the Requester Pays feature is primarily used if you want the requester, instead of the bucket owner, to pay the cost of the data transfer request and download from the S3 bucket. This solution lacks the necessary IAM Permissions to satisfy the requirement. The most suitable solution here is to configure cross-account permissions in S3.',rule:'WAF geo-blocking = use Geographic match condition in WAF Web ACL. Associate with ALB, CloudFront, or API Gateway. Block or allow specific countries.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q3_65',category:'S3',question:'A company is generating confidential data that is saved on its on-premises data center. As a backup solution, the company wants to upload its data to an Amazon S3 bucket. In compliance with its internal security mandate, the encryption of the data must be done before sending it to S3. The company must spend time managing and rotating the encryption keys as well as controlling who can access those keys. Which of the following methods can achieve this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up Server-Side Encryption with keys stored in a separate S3 bucket.','B|Set up Client-Side Encryption with AWS KMS key.','C|Set up Client-Side Encryption with S3 managed encryption keys.','D|Set up Server-Side Encryption (SSE) with Amazon EC2 key pair.','E|Set up Client-Side Encryption using a client-side master key.'],correct:'BE',answer:'Client-side encryption means encrypting data before uploading to S3. Two valid approaches: (B) CSE with an AWS KMS-managed key — KMS generates a data key for each object, and you encrypt before upload; (E) CSE with a client-side master key — you manage the master key entirely within your application.',why:'The requirement is to encrypt data BEFORE it reaches S3. Both CSE options satisfy this. SSE-S3 (A) encrypts at rest on AWS servers — the data travels to S3 unencrypted by the client. SSE with EC2 key pair (D) is not a valid S3 encryption option — EC2 key pairs are SSH key pairs, not encryption keys. CSE with S3-managed keys (C) is not a valid option — S3 does not manage keys for client-side encryption.',trap:'Server-side encryption (SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, SSE-C) happens on AWS servers — the client sends plaintext to S3, which then encrypts it. SSE does not satisfy a requirement for client-side encryption. EC2 key pairs are RSA keys for SSH access, not S3 encryption keys.',rule:'Client-side encryption (before upload to S3) = CSE with KMS key OR CSE with client master key. SSE = server encrypts after receiving. EC2 key pair = SSH only, not S3 encryption.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 2'},
  {id:'q4_1',category:'Database',question:'A company conducts performance testing on a large instance MySQL RDS DB instance twice a week. They use Performance Insights to analyze and fine-tune expensive queries. The company needs to reduce its operational expenses in running the tests without compromising the tests\' integrity. Which of the following is the most cost-effective solution?',choices:['A|Once the testing is completed, take a snapshot of the database and terminate it. Restore the database from the snapshot when necessary.','B|Stop the database once the test is done and restart it only when necessary.','C|Downgrade the database to a smaller instance.','D|Perform a mysqldump to get a copy of the database on a local machine. Use MySQL Workbench to analyze the queries.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon RDS creates a storage volume snapshot that backs up the entire DB instance, not just individual databases. It\'s important to keep in mind that when creating a DB snapshot on a Single-AZ DB instance, a brief I/O suspension may occur. The duration of the suspension can vary from a few seconds to a few minutes, depending on the size and class of your DB instance.',why:'In the scenario, taking a snapshot allows you to capture the current state of the database, including all data and configurations. By terminating the database, you can avoid incurring costs during the idle period between tests. You can simply restore the database from the snapshot when you need to run the tests again. This approach helps minimize costs by only paying for the database instance during the actual testing periods.',trap:'The option that says: Stop the database once the test is done and restart it only when necessary is incorrect. While stopping the database instance can save costs on compute resources, it\'s important to note that a stopped DB instance does continue to incur costs on its provisioned storage.',rule:'RDS snapshot = entire DB instance backup (not individual tables). Restoring creates a NEW RDS instance — you must update your connection string. Snapshots persist after instance deletion unless DeleteAutomatedBackups is enabled.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_2',category:'Storage',question:'To save costs, your manager instructed you to analyze and review the setup of your AWS cloud infrastructure. You should also provide an estimate of how much your company will pay for all of the AWS resources that they are using. In this scenario, which of the following will incur costs? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|A running EC2 Instance','B|A stopped On-Demand EC2 Instance','C|EBS Volumes attached to stopped EC2 Instances','D|Using an Amazon VPC','E|Public Data Set'],correct:'BCE',answer:'You are billed for: (B) stopped On-Demand EC2 instances — NO (EBS volumes still charge but not the instance itself), (C) EBS volumes attached to stopped instances — YES, and (E) Public Data Sets — NO (free). You ARE charged for: EBS volumes, Elastic IPs not attached to a running instance, and data transfer.',why:'When an EC2 On-Demand instance is stopped, instance charges stop — but attached EBS volumes continue to incur storage charges. Amazon VPC itself has no hourly charge (VPN connections do). Public Datasets in S3 are free to access. A running EC2 instance obviously charges per hour.',trap:'A running EC2 instance charges by the hour/second. VPC itself is free (VPN Gateway, NAT Gateway, Direct Connect are paid). Stopped On-Demand instances do NOT charge instance fees — only EBS storage.',rule:'AWS free: VPC itself, stopped On-Demand instance compute, Public Datasets. AWS charges: EBS volumes (even when instance stopped), running instances, Elastic IPs not attached, data transfer out. Public Data Sets = free. VPC itself = no charge.',keywords:'AWS billing: stopped EC2 still charges for EBS. EBS volumes incur cost when provisioned regardless of instance state.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_3',category:'S3',question:'A company is looking to store its confidential financial files in AWS, which are accessed every week. The Architect was instructed to set up the storage system, which uses envelope encryption and automates key rotation. It should also provide an audit trail that shows who used the encryption key and by whom for security purposes. Which combination of actions should the Architect implement to satisfy the requirement in the most cost-effective way? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Amazon S3 to store the data.','B|Use Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive to store the data.','C|Configure Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys (SSE-C).','D|Configure Server-Side Encryption with Amazon S3-Managed Keys (SSE-S3).','E|Configure Server-Side Encryption with AWS KMS Keys (SSE-KMS).'],correct:'AE',answer:'The scenario requires accessing financial files weekly with encryption. The correct options are: (C) SSE-C (customer-managed keys for control), (D) SSE-S3 (simplest, AWS-managed AES-256), or (E) SSE-KMS (KMS-managed with audit trail). S3 Standard with any of these covers weekly access and encryption.',why:'Weekly access means the data is frequently accessed — S3 Standard is appropriate (not Glacier Deep Archive which has high retrieval costs for weekly use). The encryption requirement is met by SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, or SSE-C — all three encrypt objects at rest with AES-256. SSE-KMS adds key audit logging and more control. SSE-C lets you provide and manage your own keys.',trap:'S3 Glacier Deep Archive is for data accessed once or twice a year — weekly access would incur high retrieval costs and 12-hour retrieval times. Using S3 without encryption (Option A alone) does not satisfy the encryption requirement.',rule:'Weekly access S3 = S3 Standard (not Glacier). Encryption = SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, or SSE-C (all are AES-256). Glacier Deep Archive = accessed 1-2x/year maximum.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_4',category:'S3',question:'A media company is using Amazon EC2, ELB, and S3 for its video-sharing portal for filmmakers. They are using a standard S3 storage class to store all high-quality videos that are frequently accessed only during the first three months of posting. As a Solutions Architect, what should you do if the company needs to automatically transfer or archive media data from an S3 bucket to Glacier?',choices:['A|Use a custom shell script that transfers data from the S3 bucket to Glacier','B|Use Lifecycle Policies','C|Use Amazon SQS','D|Use Amazon SWF'],correct:'B',answer:'S3 Lifecycle Policies automatically transition or expire S3 objects based on age or version. They are the purpose-built, zero-code solution for automatically moving videos to S3 Glacier after a defined period.',why:'A lifecycle policy is a set of rules that define actions S3 applies to objects. Transition actions move objects to cheaper storage classes after N days. Expiration actions delete objects after N days. Rules can target specific prefixes or object tags. This is fully managed — no scripts, no EC2, no cron jobs.',trap:'A custom shell script requires maintenance, a scheduled trigger (cron/EventBridge), IAM permissions, error handling, and monitoring — significant operational overhead compared to a native S3 lifecycle policy. SQS is a message queue — it has no ability to move S3 objects.',rule:'Auto-move S3 objects to Glacier = S3 Lifecycle Policy (transition action). Zero code, fully managed. SQS = message queue. SWF = distributed workflow coordination. Shell scripts = high maintenance, error-prone. Always prefer managed AWS lifecycle services.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_5',category:'IAM',question:'A web application is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances deployed across multiple Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer. You need to implement an SSL solution for your system to improve its security which is why you requested an SSL/TLS certificate from a third-party certificate authority (CA). Where can you safely import the SSL/TLS certificate of your application? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|AWS Certificate Manager','B|IAM certificate store','C|A private S3 bucket with versioning enabled','D|An S3 bucket configured with server-side encryption with customer-provided encryption keys (SSE-C)','E|CloudFront'],correct:'ABCD',answer:'SSL certificates for an Application Load Balancer can be stored in AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) — the preferred method — or in the IAM certificate store for legacy certificates that cannot be managed by ACM.',why:'ACM is the recommended way to provision, manage, and deploy SSL/TLS certificates for AWS services. It integrates directly with ALB, CloudFront, and API Gateway. It handles automatic renewal. For certificates that cannot be issued by ACM (e.g., proprietary CAs), the IAM certificate store accepts imported certificates. CloudFront, S3, and EC2 are not certificate stores.',trap:'A private S3 bucket stores objects — it is not a certificate management service. CloudFront is a CDN that uses ACM certificates but does not store them. EC2 instances can run web servers with certificates stored on disk, but they are not used as certificate stores for ALB.',rule:'SSL cert for ALB = ACM (recommended, auto-renewal) or IAM certificate store (legacy/imported). Not S3. Not CloudFront. ACM integrates natively with ALB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_6',category:'EC2',question:'A web application requires a minimum of six Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) instances running at all times. You are tasked to deploy the application to three availability zones in the EU Ireland region (eu-west-1a, eu-west-1b, and eu-west-1c). It is required that the system is fault-tolerant up to the loss of one Availability Zone. Which of the following setup is the most cost-effective solution which also maintains the fault-tolerance of your system?',choices:['A|3 instances in eu-west-1a, 3 instances in eu-west-1b, and 3 instances in eu-west-1c. Lose one AZ → 6 remain → still meets minimum of 6. Always calculate post-failure count.','B|6 instances in eu-west-1a, 6 instances in eu-west-1b, and 6 instances in eu-west-1c','C|2 instances in eu-west-1a, 2 instances in eu-west-1b, and 2 instances in eu-west-1c','D|6 instances in eu-west-1a, 6 instances in eu-west-1b, and no instances in eu-west-1c'],correct:'A',answer:'In this scenario, 3 instances in eu-west-1a, 3 instances in eu-west-1b, and 3 instances in eu-west-1c is the correct answer because even if there was an outage in one of the Availability Zones, the system still satisfies the requirement of having a minimum of 6 running instances. It is also the most cost-effective solution among other options.',why:'Basically, fault-tolerance is the ability of a system to remain in operation even in the event that some of its components fail without any service degradation. In AWS, it can also refer to the minimum number of running EC2 instances or resources which should be running at all times in order for the system to properly operate and serve its consumers.',trap:'The option that says: 2 instances in eu-west-1a, 2 instances in eu-west-1b, and 2 instances in eu-west-1c is incorrect because if one Availability Zone goes down, there will only be 4 running instances available. Although this is the most cost-effective solution, it does not provide fault-tolerance.',rule:'Fault tolerance math: (instances per AZ × AZs) - (instances in one AZ) ≥ minimum required. 3×3 AZs = 9 total; lose one AZ = 6 remain ✓. Always calculate post-failure count, not pre-failure total.',keywords:'EC2 encrypted AMI: all volumes encrypted. Cannot share encrypted AMI with CMK cross-account without key sharing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_7',category:'S3',question:'A company has stored 200 TB of backup files in Amazon S3. The files are in a vendor-proprietary format. The Solutions Architect needs to use the vendor\'s proprietary file conversion software to retrieve the files from their Amazon S3 bucket, transform the files to an industry-standard format, and re-upload the files back to Amazon S3. The solution must minimize the data transfer costs. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Install the file conversion software in Amazon S3. Use S3 Batch Operations to perform data transformation.','B|Export the data using AWS Snowball Edge device. Install the file conversion software on the device. Transform the data and re-upload it to Amazon S3.','C|Deploy the EC2 instance in a different Region. Install the conversion software on the instance. Perform data transformation and re-upload it to Amazon S3.','D|Deploy the EC2 instance in the same Region as Amazon S3. Install the file conversion software on the instance. Perform data transformation and re-upload it to Amazon S3.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon S3 is object storage built to store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere on the Internet. It’s a simple storage service that offers industry-leading durability, availability, performance, security, and virtually unlimited scalability at very low costs. Amazon S3 is also designed to be highly flexible.',why:'You pay for all bandwidth into and out of Amazon S3, except for the following: To minimize the data transfer charges, you need to deploy the EC2 instance in the same Region as Amazon S3. Take note that there is no data transfer cost between S3 and EC2 in the same AWS Region. Install the conversion software on the instance to perform data transformation and re-upload the data to Amazon S3.',trap:'The option that says: Install the file conversion software in Amazon S3. Use S3 Batch Operations to perform data transformation is incorrect because it is not possible to install the software in Amazon S3. The S3 Batch Operations just runs multiple S3 operations in a single request. It can’t be integrated with your conversion software.',rule:'Take note that there is no data transfer cost between S3 and EC2 in the same AWS Region. Not Amazon S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_8',category:'S3',question:'There are a few, easily reproducible but confidential files that your client wants to store in AWS without worrying about storage capacity. For the first month, all of these files will be accessed frequently but after that, they will rarely be accessed at all. The old files will only be accessed by developers so there is no set retrieval time requirement. However, the files under a specific tdojo-finance prefix in the S3 bucket will be used for post-processing that requires millisecond retrieval time. Given these conditions, which of the following options would be the most cost-effective solution for your client\'s storage needs?',choices:['A|Store the files in S3 then after a month, change the storage class of the bucket to S3-IA using lifecycle policy.','B|Store the files in S3 then after a month, change the storage class of the bucket to Intelligent-Tiering using lifecycle policy.','C|Store the files in S3 then after a month, change the storage class of the tdojo-finance prefix to One Zone-IA while the remaining go to Glacier using lifecycle policy.','D|Store the files in S3 then after a month, change the storage class of the tdojo-finance prefix to S3-IA while the remaining go to Glacier using lifecycle policy.'],correct:'C',answer:'Initially, the files will be accessed frequently, and S3 is a durable and highly available storage solution for that. After a month has passed, the files won\'t be accessed frequently anymore, so it is a good idea to use lifecycle policies to move them to a storage class that would have a lower cost for storing them.',why:'Since the files are easily reproducible and some of them are needed to be retrieved quickly based on a specific prefix filter (tdojo-finance), S3-One Zone IA would be a good choice for storing them. The other files that do not contain such prefix would then be moved to Glacier for low-cost archival. This setup would also be the most cost-effective for the client.',trap:'The option that says: Storing the files in S3 then after a month, changing the storage class of the bucket to S3-IA using lifecycle policy is incorrect. Although it is valid to move the files to S3-IA, this solution still costs more compared with using a combination of S3-One Zone IA and Glacier.',rule:'store in aws without worrying about storage capaci → One Zone.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_9',category:'CloudWatch',question:'There is a new compliance rule in your company that audits every Windows and Linux EC2 instances each month to view any performance issues. They have more than a hundred EC2 instances running in production, and each must have a logging function that collects various system details regarding that instance. The SysOps team will periodically review these logs and analyze their contents using AWS Analytics tools, and the result will need to be retained in an S3 bucket. In this scenario, what is the most efficient way to collect and analyze logs from the instances with minimal effort? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Install the unified CloudWatch Logs agent in each instance which will automatically collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs. Analyze the log data with CloudWatch Logs Insights.','B|Install AWS SDK in each instance and create a custom daemon script that would collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs periodically. Enable CloudWatch detailed monitoring and use CloudWatch Logs Insights to analyze the log data of all instances.','C|Install the AWS Systems Manager Agent (SSM Agent) in each instance which will automatically collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs. Analyze the log data with CloudWatch Logs Insights.','D|Install AWS Inspector Agent in each instance which will collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs periodically. Set up a CloudWatch dashboard to properly analyze the log data of all instances.'],correct:'AD',answer:'To collect logs from your Amazon EC2 instances and on-premises servers into CloudWatch Logs, AWS offers both a new unified CloudWatch agent, and an older CloudWatch Logs agent. It is recommended to use the unified CloudWatch agent which has the following advantages: Collects both logs and system-level metrics (memory, disk). Supports Windows and Linux. Replaces older CloudWatch Logs agent.',why:'CloudWatch Logs Insights enables you to interactively search and analyze your log data in Amazon CloudWatch Logs. You can perform queries to help you quickly and effectively respond to operational issues. If an issue occurs, you can use CloudWatch Logs Insights to identify potential causes and validate deployed fixes.',trap:'The option that says: Install AWS Inspector Agent in each instance which will collect and push data to CloudWatch Logs periodically. Set up a CloudWatch dashboard to properly analyze the log data of all instances is incorrect because AWS Inspector is simply a security assessments service which only helps you in checking for unintended network accessibility of your EC2 instances and for vulnerabilities on those EC2 instances. Furthermore, setting up an Amazon CloudWatch dashboard is not suitable since its primarily used for scenarios where you have to monitor your resources in a single view, even those resources that are spread across different AWS Regions. It is better to use CloudWatch Logs Insights instead since it enables you to interactively search and analyze your log data.',rule:'CloudWatch Logs Insights enables you to interactively search and analyze your log data in Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Not AWS Inspector.',keywords:'Memory/disk/swap metrics = NOT default CW. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_10',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company plans to develop a custom messaging service that will be used to train an AI for an automatic response feature. The service is expected to receive thousands of messages per day, all of which will be processed by an Amazon EMR cluster. It is crucial that none of the messages are lost, no duplicates are produced, and that the messages are processed in EMR in the same order as their arrival. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon Kinesis Data Stream to collect the messages.','B|Set up a default Amazon SQS queue to handle the messages.','C|Set up an Amazon SNS Topic to handle the messages.','D|Create an Amazon Data Firehose to handle the messages.'],correct:'A',answer:'Two important requirements that the chosen AWS service should fulfill is that data should not go missing, is durable, and streams data in the sequence of arrival. Kinesis can do the job just fine because of its architecture.',why:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams enables real-time processing of streaming big data. It provides ordering of records, as well as the ability to read and/or replay records in the same order to multiple Amazon Kinesis Applications.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a default Amazon SQS queue to handle the messages is incorrect because although SQS is a valid messaging service, it is not suitable for scenarios where you need to process the data based on the order they were received. Take note that a default queue in SQS is just a standard queue and not a FIFO (First-In-First-Out) queue. In addition, SQS does not guarantee that no duplicates will be sent.',rule:'Amazon + Kinesis = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_11',category:'Kinesis',question:'An organization uses a Microsoft SQL Server database to support its suite of applications. The organization plans to transition to an Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL database while minimizing application code modifications. Which combination of actions will achieve these objectives? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use AWS AppConfig to manage configuration updates during the migration.','B|Turn on Babelfish on Aurora PostgreSQL to allow applications to continue using existing SQL queries','C|Use AWS Schema Conversion Tool (AWS SCT) to convert the database schema and AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) to migrate the data.','D|Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time data replication to Aurora PostgreSQL.','E|Use AWS Glue to transform the SQL queries from the applications for compatibility with Aurora PostgreSQL.'],correct:'BC',answer:'Turn on Babelfish on Aurora PostgreSQL to allow applications to continue using existing SQL queries.',why:'AWS Schema Conversion Tool (AWS SCT) is a service that helps convert database schemas from one database engine to another. It supports conversion from various source databases, including Microsoft SQL Server, to target databases like Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL. AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) is a service that helps migrate databases to AWS quickly and securely. It supports continuous data replication with minimal downtime.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS AppConfig to manage configuration updates during the migration is incorrect because AWS AppConfig is primarily designed to manage and deploy application configuration changes in a controlled and safe manner. It does not address the key challenges of schema conversion, data migration, or SQL query compatibility crucial for transitioning from Microsoft SQL Server to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL.',rule:'SQL Server workload → AWS: Babelfish on Aurora PostgreSQL lets apps use existing T-SQL queries without code changes. AWS SCT converts schema. Use both together for heterogeneous migration.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_12',category:'CloudWatch',question:'An Auto Scaling group (ASG) of Amazon EC2 Linux instances has an Amazon FSx for OpenZFS file system with basic monitoring enabled in Amazon CloudWatch. The Solutions Architect noticed that the legacy web application hosted in the ASG takes a long time to load. After checking the instances, the Architect noticed that the ASG is not launching more instances as it should be, even though the servers already have high memory usage. Which of the following options should the Architect implement to solve this issue?',choices:['A|Implement an AI solution that leverages Amazon Comprehend to track the near-real-time memory usage of each and every EC2 instance. Use Amazon SageMaker AI to automatically trigger the Auto Scaling event if there is high memory usage.','B|Install the CloudWatch unified agent to the EC2 instances. Set up a custom parameter in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store with the CloudWatch agent configuration to create an aggregated metric on memory usage percentage. Scale the Auto Scaling group based on the aggregated metric.','C|Enable detailed monitoring on the EC2 instances of the Auto Scaling group. Use Auto Scaling with custom metrics to scale out the Auto Scaling group based on the aggregated memory usage of EC2 instances.','D|Set up Amazon Rekognition to automatically identify and recognize the cause of the high memory usage. Use the AWS Well-Architected Tool to automatically trigger the scale-out event in the ASG based on the overall memory usage.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon CloudWatch agent enables you to collect both system metrics and log files from Amazon EC2 instances and on-premises servers. The agent supports both Windows Server and Linux and allows you to select the metrics to be collected, including sub-resource metrics such as per-CPU core.',why:'The premise of the scenario is that the EC2 servers have high memory usage, but since this specific metric is not tracked by the Auto Scaling group by default, the scaling out activity is not being triggered. Remember that by default, CloudWatch doesn\'t monitor memory usage but only the CPU utilization, Network utilization, Disk performance, and Disk Reads/Writes.',trap:'The option that says: Implement an AI solution that leverages Amazon Comprehend to track the near-real-time memory usage of each and every EC2 instance. Use Amazon SageMaker AI to automatically trigger the Auto Scaling event if there is high memory usage is incorrect because Amazon Comprehend cannot track near-real-time memory usage in Amazon EC2. This is just a natural-language processing (NLP) service that uses machine learning to uncover valuable insights and connections in text. Also, the use of an Amazon SageMaker AI in this scenario is not warranted since there is no machine learning requirement involved.',rule:'Monitoring → EC2, AWS Systems Manager Para. Not Amazon Comprehend.',keywords:'Aurora Babelfish: T-SQL compatibility for SQL Server migration. SCT converts schema + DMS migrates data.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_13',category:'Storage',question:'An organization plans to use an AWS Direct Connect connection to establish a dedicated connection between its on-premises network and AWS. The organization needs to launch a fully managed solution that will automate and accelerate the replication of data to and from various AWS storage services. Which of the following solutions would you recommend?',choices:['A|Use an AWS DataSync agent to rapidly move the data over a service endpoint.','B|Use an AWS Storage Gateway tape gateway to store data on virtual tape cartridges and asynchronously copy your backups to AWS.','C|Use an AWS DataSync agent to rapidly move the data over the Internet.','D|Use an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway to store and retrieve files directly using the SMB file system protocol.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS DataSync allows you to copy large datasets with millions of files, without having to build custom solutions with open source tools or license and manage expensive commercial network acceleration software.',why:'AWS DataSync simplifies, automates, and accelerates copying large amounts of data to and from AWS storage services over the internet or AWS Direct Connect. DataSync can copy data between Network File System (NFS), Server Message Block (SMB) file servers, self-managed object storage, or AWS Snowcone, and Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) buckets, Amazon EFS file systems, and Amazon FSx for Windows File Server file systems.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS DataSync agent to rapidly move the data over the Internet is incorrect because the organization will be using an AWS Direct Connect connection for private connectivity. This means that the connection will not pass through the public Internet.',rule:'AWS DataSync simplifies, automates, and accelerates copying large amounts of data to and from AWS storage services over the internet or AWS  Not AWS Direct.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_14',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A technology company is building a new cryptocurrency trading platform that allows the buying and selling of Bitcoin, Ethereum, Ripple, Tether, and many others. A Cloud Engineer was hired to build the infrastructure required for this platform. During the first week, the engineer began creating CloudFormation YAML scripts to define all of the AWS resources needed for the application. The manager was shocked that the engineer hadn\'t set up the EC2 instances, S3 buckets, and other AWS resources immediately. He doesn\'t understand the purpose of the text-based scripts the engineer has written and has asked for clarification. In this scenario, what are the benefits of using Amazon CloudFormation that the manager should know to address his concerns? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Provides highly durable and scalable data storage','B|A storage location for the code of your application','C|Enables modeling, provisioning, and version-controlling of your entire AWS infrastructure','D|Allows you to model your entire infrastructure in a text file','E|Using CloudFormation itself is free, including the AWS resources that have been created.'],correct:'CD',answer:'CloudFormation (infrastructure as code for AWS) + AWS Config (configuration compliance) — two tools for modeling, provisioning, and version-controlling your entire AWS infrastructure and auditing configuration changes.',why:'AWS CloudFormation provides a common language for you to describe and provision all the infrastructure resources in your cloud environment. CloudFormation allows you to use a simple text file to model and provision, in an automated and secure manner, all the resources needed for your applications across all regions and accounts. This file serves as the single source of truth for your cloud environment.',trap:'The option that says: Provides highly durable and scalable data storage is incorrect because CloudFormation is not a data storage service.',rule:'CloudFormation = IaC: model, provision, version-control entire AWS infra. Free to use (pay only for resources). Not CodeDeploy (app deployment). Not OpsWorks (Chef/Puppet managed). Not Elastic Beanstalk (PaaS).',keywords:'CloudFormation + AWS Config: IaC for provisioning + compliance rules for configuration audit.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_15',category:'Storage',question:'A technical lead of the Cloud Infrastructure team was consulted by a software developer regarding the required AWS resources of the web application that he is building. The developer knows that an Instance Store only provides ephemeral storage where the data is automatically deleted when the instance is terminated. To ensure that the data of the web application persists, the app should be launched in an EC2 instance that has a durable, block-level storage volume attached. The developer knows that they need to use an EBS volume, but they are not sure what type they need to use. In this scenario, which of the following is true about Amazon EBS volume types and their respective usage? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Spot volumes provide the lowest cost per gigabyte of all EBS volume types and are ideal for workloads where data is accessed infrequently, and applications where the lowest storage cost is important.','B|Provisioned IOPS volumes offer storage with consistent and low-latency performance, and are designed for I/O intensive applications such as large relational or NoSQL databases.','C|Magnetic volumes provide the lowest cost per gigabyte of all EBS volume types and are ideal for workloads where data is accessed infrequently, and applications where the lowest storage cost is important.','D|General Purpose SSD (gp3) volumes with multi-attach enabled offer consistent and low-latency performance, and are designed for applications requiring multi-az resiliency.','E|Single root I/O virtualization (SR-IOV) volumes are suitable for a broad range of workloads, including small to medium-sized databases, development and test environments, and boot volumes.'],correct:'BC',answer:'Provisioned IOPS volumes offer storage with consistent and low-latency performance, and are designed for I/O intensive applications such as large relational or NoSQL databases.',why:'Amazon EBS provides three volume types to best meet the needs of your workloads: General Purpose (SSD), Provisioned IOPS (SSD), and Magnetic. General Purpose (SSD) is the new, SSD-backed, general purpose EBS volume type that is recommended as the default choice for customers. General Purpose (SSD) volumes are suitable for a broad range of workloads, including small to medium-sized databases, development and test environments, and boot volumes.',trap:'The option that says: Spot volumes provide the lowest cost per gigabyte of all EBS volume types and are ideal for workloads where data is accessed infrequently, and applications where the lowest storage cost is important is incorrect because there is no EBS type called a "Spot volume" however, there is an Instance purchasing option for Spot Instances.',rule:'EBS types: io1/io2 = consistent low-latency IOPS (databases). Magnetic = lowest cost/GB (cold storage). gp3 = general purpose SSD, multi-attach NOT supported (only io1/io2 support multi-attach). SR-IOV = high-performance networking, not EBS.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_16',category:'Storage',question:'A company has a global news website hosted in a fleet of EC2 Instances. Lately, the load on the website has increased which resulted in slower response time for the site visitors. This issue impacts the revenue of the company as some readers tend to leave the site if it does not load after 10 seconds. The goal is to address the issue in a cost-effective manner.” Which of the below services in AWS can be used to solve this problem? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Amazon CloudFront with website as the custom origin.','B|For better read throughput, use AWS Storage Gateway to distribute the content across multiple regions.','C|Use Amazon ElastiCache for the website\'s in-memory data store or cache.','D|Deploy the website to all regions in different VPCs for faster processing.','E|Use Amazon RDS Multi-AZ deployments for database read scalability.'],correct:'AC',answer:'The global news website has a problem with latency considering that there are a lot of readers of the site from all parts of the globe. In this scenario, you can use a content delivery network (CDN) which is a geographically distributed group of servers that work together to provide fast delivery of Internet content.',why:'CloudFront caches content at 400+ edge locations worldwide. A reader in Singapore gets content from a nearby edge PoP, not from your origin server in us-east-1. The TTL (time-to-live) in cache-control headers determines how long content stays at the edge before CloudFront re-fetches from origin. Dynamic content can be passed through CloudFront with caching disabled for those paths.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon RDS Multi-AZ deployments for database read scalability is incorrect. While Amazon RDS Multi-AZ deployments provide high availability and automatic failover, they primarily focus on database redundancy rather than improving website performance. Multi-AZ deployments are not directly related to reducing response times for the website.',rule:'Use Amazon CloudFront with website as the custom origin.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_17',category:'Serverless',question:'A popular augmented reality (AR) mobile game is heavily using a RESTful API which is hosted in AWS. The API uses Amazon API Gateway and a DynamoDB table with a preconfigured read and write capacity. Based on your systems monitoring, the DynamoDB table begins to throttle requests during high peak loads which causes the slow performance of the game. Which of the following can you do to improve the performance of your app?',choices:['A|Integrate an Application Load Balancer with your DynamoDB table.','B|Add the DynamoDB table to an Auto Scaling Group.','C|Use DynamoDB Auto Scaling','D|Create an SQS queue in front of the DynamoDB table.'],correct:'A',answer:'Using DynamoDB Auto Scaling is the best answer. DynamoDB Auto Scaling uses the AWS Application Auto Scaling service to dynamically adjust provisioned throughput capacity on your behalf.',why:'DynamoDB auto scaling uses the AWS Application Auto Scaling service to dynamically adjust provisioned throughput capacity on your behalf, in response to actual traffic patterns. This enables a table or a global secondary index to increase its provisioned read and write capacity to handle sudden increases in traffic, without throttling.',trap:'Integrating an Application Load Balancer with your DynamoDB table is incorrect because an Application Load Balancer is not suitable to be used with DynamoDB and in addition, this will not increase the throughput of your DynamoDB table.',rule:'DynamoDB = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'DynamoDB hot partition → use high-cardinality partition key. Spread writes evenly.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_18',category:'Serverless',question:'A leading IT consulting company has an application which processes a large stream of financial data by an Amazon ECS Cluster then stores the result to a DynamoDB table. You have to design a solution to detect new entries in the DynamoDB table then automatically trigger a Lambda function to run some tests to verify the processed data. What solution can be easily implemented to alert the Lambda function of new entries while requiring minimal configuration change to your architecture?',choices:['A|Use CloudWatch Alarms to trigger the Lambda function whenever a new entry is created in the DynamoDB table.','B|Invoke the Lambda functions using SNS each time that the ECS Cluster successfully processed financial data.','C|Enable DynamoDB Streams to capture table activity and automatically trigger the Lambda function.','D|Use Systems Manager Automation to detect new entries in the DynamoDB table then automatically invoke the Lambda function for processing.'],correct:'C',answer:'DynamoDB Streams captures a time-ordered sequence of item-level modifications. When new items are written to the DynamoDB table, Streams triggers a Lambda function to process the new entry and perform the required actions.',why:'DynamoDB Streams records INSERT, MODIFY, and REMOVE events on a table. Each stream record contains the new image of the item after modification. Lambda can be configured as a trigger on the stream — when new items appear, Lambda processes them automatically. This is a native, serverless, low-latency integration that requires no polling infrastructure.',trap:'CloudWatch Alarms monitor metrics, not individual DynamoDB item changes. SNS via ECS cluster invocations requires custom polling logic and lacks the atomic, per-item trigger that Streams provides. Systems Manager Automation is for infrastructure operations — not for responding to database row inserts.',rule:'React to DynamoDB item writes = DynamoDB Streams → Lambda trigger. Streams captures INSERT/MODIFY/REMOVE. Lambda fires per batch of stream records. CloudWatch monitors metrics, not change data. EventBridge = event routing (not stream processing). DynamoDB Streams = ordered change log.',keywords:'Row-level DB change trigger → DynamoDB Streams → Lambda. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_19',category:'Serverless',question:'A company needs to implement a solution that will process real-time streaming data of its users across the globe. This will enable them to track and analyze globally-distributed user activity on their website and mobile applications, including clickstream analysis. The solution should process the data in close geographical proximity to their users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Which of the following is the most suitable solution for this scenario?',choices:['A|Use a CloudFront web distribution and Route 53 with a latency-based routing policy, in order to process the data in close geographical proximity to users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Process real-time streaming data using Kinesis and durably store the results to an Amazon S3 bucket.','B|Integrate CloudFront with Lambda@Edge in order to process the data in close geographical proximity to users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Process real-time streaming data using Amazon Athena and durably store the results to an Amazon S3 bucket.','C|Use a CloudFront web distribution and Route 53 with a Geoproximity routing policy in order to process the data in close geographical proximity to users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Process real-time streaming data using Kinesis and durably store the results to an Amazon S3 bucket.','D|Integrate CloudFront with Lambda@Edge in order to process the data in close geographical proximity to users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Process real-time streaming data using Kinesis and durably store the results to an Amazon S3 bucket.'],correct:'B',answer:'Lambda@Edge is a feature of Amazon CloudFront that lets you run code closer to users of your application, which improves performance and reduces latency. With Lambda@Edge, you don\'t have to provision or manage infrastructure in multiple locations around the world. You pay only for the compute time you consume - there is no charge when your code is not running.',why:'With Lambda@Edge, you can enrich your web applications by making them globally distributed and improving their performance — all with zero server administration. Lambda@Edge runs your code in response to events generated by the Amazon CloudFront content delivery network (CDN). Just upload your code to AWS Lambda, which takes care of everything required to run and scale your code with high availability at an AWS location closest to your end user.',trap:'The option that says: Integrate CloudFront with Lambda@Edge in order to process the data in close geographical proximity to users and respond to user requests at low latencies. Process real-time streaming data using Amazon Athena and durably store the results to an Amazon S3 bucket is incorrect. Although using Lambda@Edge is correct, Amazon Athena is just an interactive query service that enables you to easily analyze data in Amazon S3 using standard SQL. Kinesis should be used to process the streaming data in real time.',rule:'Real-time → Amazon Athena and durably store the r, Amazon S3 bucket. Not Integrate Cloud.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_20',category:'Storage',question:'A company launched a global news website that is deployed to AWS and is using MySQL RDS. The website has millions of viewers from all over the world, which means that the website has a read-heavy database workload. All database transactions must be ACID compliant to ensure data integrity. In this scenario, which of the following is the best option to use to increase the read-throughput on the MySQL database?',choices:['A|Enable Multi-AZ deployments','B|Enable Amazon RDS Standby Replicas','C|Enable Amazon RDS Read Replicas','D|Use SQS to queue up the requests'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon RDS Read Replicas provide enhanced performance and durability for database (DB) instances. This feature makes it easy to elastically scale out beyond the capacity constraints of a single DB instance for read-heavy database workloads.',why:'A Read Replica is an asynchronously updated copy of your primary DB. Your application connects to a separate read endpoint — the primary handles writes while replicas absorb read queries. Replication lag is typically milliseconds but is not zero. Multi-AZ uses synchronous replication to a standby that stays invisible to your app until a failover occurs.',trap:'Enabling Multi-AZ deployments is incorrect because the Multi-AZ deployments feature is mainly used to achieve high availability and failover support for your database.',rule:'Scale reads on RDS = Read Replica (async replication, serves reads). Multi-AZ = availability/failover only (standby cannot serve reads). Read heavy → replica, not Multi-AZ.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_21',category:'S3',question:'A company hosts all its applications on its data center on the US East Coast. Most of the workloads are legacy applications that are hosted on individual virtual machines running in Linux and Windows operating systems. The company plans to migrate all of its VM workloads to the AWS cloud. To minimize changes in the applications during the migration process, it has been decided that the company will use a “lift-and-shift” strategy. The company also wants to minimize downtime during the migration process. Which of the following options should the Solutions Architect implement for this scenario?',choices:['A|Export the on-premises VMs and upload the images to an Amazon S3 bucket. Use VM Import/Export service to import the images and launch them as Amazon EC2 instances.','B|Install the AWS Replication Agent on each of the on-premises VMs to continuously replicate the servers to AWS. Use AWS Migration Service (AWS MGN) to launch test instances and perform cutover once testing is completed.','C|Use the AWS Application Discovery Service for lift-and-shift migrations. Deploy the AWS Application Discovery Agent to the on-premises data center to start the replication process. After the replication task is completed, launch Amazon EC2 instances based on the created AMIs.','D|Utilize AWS DataSync to migrate the application workloads to AWS. Deploy the AWS DataSync VM on the on-premises data center. Once replication is completed, launch Amazon EC2 instances based on the created AMIs.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Application Migration Service (AWS MGN) is the primary service for lift-and-shift migrations. It installs a replication agent on each on-premises VM, continuously replicates data to AWS, and performs a cutover with minimal downtime.',why:'AWS MGN (formerly CloudEndure) replaces VM Import/Export for server migrations. The replication agent captures all disk writes and replicates them to a staging area in AWS. When ready to cut over, MGN launches EC2 instances from the replicated disks with minimal downtime — often under 10 minutes. It supports Windows and Linux.',trap:'VM Import/Export requires exporting VMs to S3 first — slower and more manual. AWS Application Discovery Service inventories on-premises servers but does not migrate them. AWS DataSync transfers files and data, not running VMs.',rule:'Lift-and-shift VM migration to AWS = AWS MGN (Application Migration Service). Installs replication agent, continuous replication, cutover < 10 min. VM Import/Export = older method, requires downtime, one-time snapshot import. DataSync = file migration, not VM replication.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_22',category:'Storage',question:'A company plans to migrate a NoSQL database to an EC2 instance. The database is configured to replicate the data automatically to keep multiple copies of data for redundancy. The Solutions Architect needs to launch an instance that has a high IOPS and sequential read/write access. Which of the following options fulfills the requirement if I/O throughput is the highest priority?',choices:['A|Use Storage optimized instances with instance store volume.','B|Use General purpose instances with EBS volume.','C|Use Compute optimized instance with instance store volume.','D|Use Memory optimized instances with EBS volume.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon EC2 provides a wide selection of instance types optimized to fit different use cases. Instance types comprise varying combinations of CPU, memory, storage, and networking capacity and give you the flexibility to choose the appropriate mix of resources for your applications.',why:'A storage optimized instance is designed for workloads that require high, sequential read and write access to very large data sets on local storage. They are optimized to deliver tens of thousands of low-latency, random I/O operations per second (IOPS) to applications. Some instance types can drive more I/O throughput than what you can provision for a single EBS volume.',trap:'The option that says: Use Compute optimized instances with instance store volume is incorrect because this type of instance is ideal for compute-bound applications that benefit from high-performance processors. It is not suitable for a NoSQL database.',rule:'Each instance type includes one or more instance sizes, allowing you to scale your resources to the requirements of your application.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_23',category:'Database',question:'A startup plans to develop a multiplayer game that uses UDP as the protocol for communication between clients and game servers. The data of the users will be stored in a key-value store. As the Solutions Architect, you need to implement a solution that will distribute the traffic across a number of servers. Which of the following could help you achieve this requirement?',choices:['A|Distribute the traffic using Application Load Balancer and store the data in Amazon DynamoDB.','B|Distribute the traffic using Network Load Balancer and store the data in Amazon Aurora.','C|Distribute the traffic using Application Load Balancer and store the data in Amazon RDS.','D|Distribute the traffic using Network Load Balancer and store the data in Amazon DynamoDB.'],correct:'B',answer:'A Network Load Balancer functions at the fourth layer of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) model. It can handle millions of requests per second. After the load balancer receives a connection request, it selects a target from the target group for the default rule.',why:'In this scenario, a startup plans to create a multiplayer game that uses UDP as the protocol for communications. Since UDP is a Layer 4 traffic, we can limit the option that uses Network Load Balancer. The data of the users will be stored in a key-value store. This means that we should select Amazon DynamoDB since it supports both document and key-value store models.',trap:'The option that says: Distribute the traffic using Application Load Balancer and store the data in Amazon DynamoDB is incorrect because UDP is not supported in Application Load Balancer. Remember that UDP is a Layer 4 traffic. Therefore, you should use a Network Load Balancer.',rule:'Amazon DynamoDB: correct. Application Load Balancer: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_24',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has a team of developers that provisions its own resources on the AWS cloud. The developers use IAM user access keys to automate resource provisioning and application testing processes in AWS. To ensure proper security compliance, the security team wants to automate the process of deactivating and deleting any IAM user access key that is over 90 days old. Which solution will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational effort?',choices:['A|Use the AWS Config managed rule to check if the IAM user access keys are not rotated within 90 days. Create an Amazon EventBridge rule for the non-compliant keys, and define a target to invoke a custom AWS Lambda function to deactivate and delete the keys.','B|Create an Amazon EventBridge rule to filter IAM user access keys older than 90 days. Schedule an AWS Batch job that runs every 24 hours to delete all the specified access keys.','C|Create a custom AWS Config rule to check the max-age of IAM access keys. Use Amazon EventBridge Scheduler to invoke an AWS Batch job every 24 hours to delete all non-compliant access keys.','D|Create an Amazon EventBridge rule to filter IAM user access keys older than 90 days. Define a target to invoke an AWS Lambda function to deactivate and delete the old access keys.'],correct:'A',answer:'An Aurora MySQL DB cluster supports Multi-AZ Replicas. The primary instance writes to all replicas. Aurora Reader endpoint load-balances reads across all replicas. This separates the analytics workload from the OLTP workload.',why:'Aurora uses a shared distributed storage layer — all instances in a cluster share the same data. The Reader endpoint (cluster-level) automatically routes read queries to available Aurora Replicas. Adding replicas does not require data copying; they share the same underlying storage. Each replica can handle read queries with millisecond replica lag.',trap:'The Cluster endpoint connects to the primary instance for writes — using it for analytics queries would add load to the same write instance, not relieve it. Aurora Parallel Query pushes query processing to the storage layer but does not distribute reads across replicas.',rule:'Aurora read scaling = Aurora Reader endpoint (load-balances across replicas). All replicas share same storage (no data copy lag). Cluster endpoint = primary write instance only.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_25',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect is designing the cloud architecture for the enterprise application suite of the company. Both the web and application tiers need to access the Internet to fetch data from public APIs. However, these servers should be inaccessible from the Internet. Which of the following steps should the Architect implement to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Deploy the web and application tier instances to a private subnet and then allocate an Elastic IP address to each EC2 instance.','B|Deploy a NAT gateway in the private subnet and add a route to it from the public subnet where the web and application tiers are hosted.','C|Deploy the web and application tier instances to a public subnet and then allocate an Elastic IP address to each EC2 instance.','D|Deploy a NAT gateway in the public subnet and add a route to it from the private subnet where the web and application tiers are hosted.'],correct:'B',answer:'You can use a network address translation (NAT) gateway to enable instances in a private subnet to connect to the internet or other AWS services but prevent the internet from initiating a connection with those instances. You are charged for creating and using a NAT gateway in your account.',why:'A NAT Gateway is deployed in a public subnet and assigned an Elastic IP. Private subnet route tables send 0.0.0.0/0 traffic to the NAT Gateway. The NAT Gateway translates the private source IP to its own EIP before forwarding to the internet, and reverse-translates responses back. Costs: hourly per NAT Gateway + per-GB data processed. For HA, deploy one NAT Gateway per AZ — instances in that AZ use the local NAT Gateway, avoiding cross-AZ data transfer charges.',trap:'Deploying the web and application tier instances to a private subnet and then allocating an Elastic IP address to each EC2 instance is incorrect because an Elastic IP address is just a static, public IPv4 address. In this scenario, you have to use a NAT Gateway instead.',rule:'NAT gateways are not supported for IPv6 traffic—use an egress-only internet gateway instead.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_26',category:'EC2',question:'An automotive company is working on an autonomous vehicle development and deployment project using AWS. The solution requires High Performance Computing (HPC) in order to collect, store and manage massive amounts of data as well as to support deep learning frameworks. The Linux EC2 instances that will be used should have a lower latency and higher throughput than the TCP transport traditionally used in cloud-based HPC systems. It should also enhance the performance of inter-instance communication and must include an OS-bypass functionality to allow the HPC to communicate directly with the network interface hardware to provide low-latency, reliable transport functionality. Which of the following is the MOST suitable solution that you should implement to achieve the above requirements?',choices:['A|Attach an Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) on each Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC).','B|Attach an Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) on each Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC).','C|Attach an Elastic Network Interface (ENI) on each Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC).','D|Attach a Private Virtual Interface (VIF) on each Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC).'],correct:'B',answer:'An Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) is a network device that you can attach to your Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC) and machine learning applications. EFA enables you to achieve the application performance of an on-premises HPC cluster with the scalability, flexibility, and elasticity provided by the AWS Cloud.',why:'EFA provides lower and more consistent latency and higher throughput than the TCP transport traditionally used in cloud-based HPC systems. It enhances the performance of inter-instance communication which is critical for scaling HPC and machine learning applications. It is optimized to work on the existing AWS network infrastructure, and it can scale depending on application requirements. EFA integrates with Libfabric 1.9.',trap:'Attaching an Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) on each Amazon EC2 instance to accelerate High Performance Computing (HPC) is incorrect because Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) doesn\'t have OS-bypass capabilities, unlike EFA.',rule:'EFA provides lower and more consistent latency and higher throughput than the TCP transport traditionally used in cloud-based HPC systems. Not Elastic Network Adapter.',keywords:'NAT Gateway: deploy in PUBLIC subnet. Add route in PRIVATE subnet route table pointing to NAT GW.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_27',category:'EC2',question:'A company has a High Performance Computing (HPC) cluster that is composed of EC2 Instances with Provisioned IOPS (io1) volume to process transaction-intensive, low-latency workloads. The Solutions Architect must maintain high IOPS while keeping the latency down by setting the optimal queue length for the volume. The size of each volume is 10 GiB. Which of the following is the MOST suitable configuration that the Architect should set up?',choices:['A|Set the IOPS to 400 then maintain a low queue length.','B|Set the IOPS to 500 then maintain a low queue length.','C|Set the IOPS to 600 then maintain a high queue length.','D|Set the IOPS to 800 then maintain a low queue length.'],correct:'B',answer:'io1 Provisioned IOPS volumes use a ratio of 50:1 (IOPS per GB). For 800 IOPS you need at least 16 GiB. To achieve maximum io1 performance, the queue depth should be high enough to keep the drive busy — low queue depth causes IOPS to be underutilized.',why:'Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) volumes support up to 50 IOPS per GB of volume size. 800 IOPS ÷ 50 = 16 GiB minimum. The key to achieving provisioned IOPS is maintaining an adequate I/O queue depth. If the queue depth is too low, the application does not submit enough I/O requests to keep the disk busy at the provisioned rate. Higher queue depth allows the storage layer to process more concurrent I/Os.',trap:'400 and 500 IOPS are below the 800 IOPS specified in the scenario. 600 IOPS with a high queue length might work for a 600 IOPS workload but is below the 800 requirement. Low queue depth underutilizes the provisioned IOPS regardless of how high the IOPS value is set.',rule:'io1 IOPS:GB ratio = 50:1 max. 800 IOPS = 16 GiB minimum. Performance = high queue depth. Low queue depth = underutilized IOPS even if provisioned correctly.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_28',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has an OLTP (Online Transactional Processing) application that is hosted in an Amazon ECS cluster using the Fargate launch type. It has an Amazon RDS database that stores data of its production website. The Data Analytics team needs to run queries against the database to track and audit all user transactions. These query operations against the production database must not impact application performance in any way. Which of the following is the MOST suitable and cost-effective solution that you should implement?',choices:['A|Set up a new Amazon Redshift database cluster. Migrate the product database into Redshift and allow the Data Analytics team to fetch data from it.','B|Set up a new Amazon RDS Read Replica of the production database. Direct the Data Analytics team to query the production data from the replica.','C|Set up a Multi-AZ deployments configuration of your production database in RDS. Direct the Data Analytics team to query the production data from the standby instance.','D|Upgrade the instance type of the RDS database to a large instance.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon RDS Read Replicas provide enhanced performance and durability for database (DB) instances. This feature makes it easy to elastically scale out beyond the capacity constraints of a single DB instance for read-heavy database workloads.',why:'You can create one or more replicas of a given source DB Instance and serve high-volume application read traffic from multiple copies of your data, thereby increasing aggregate read throughput. Read replicas can also be promoted when needed to become standalone DB instances. Read replicas are available in Amazon RDS for MySQL, MariaDB, Oracle and PostgreSQL, as well as Amazon Aurora.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a new Amazon Redshift database cluster. Migrate the product database into Redshift and allow the Data Analytics team to fetch data from it is incorrect because Redshift is primarily used for OLAP (Online Analytical Processing) applications and not for OLTP.',rule:'Amazon RDS Read Replica of the produc: correct. Amazon Redshift: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'RDS read scaling / reporting offload → Read Replica. Async replication. Can be promoted.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_29',category:'Other',question:'A company has a web-based order processing system that is currently using a standard queue in Amazon SQS. The IT Manager noticed that there are a lot of cases where an order was processed twice. This issue has caused a lot of trouble in processing and made the customers very unhappy. The goal is to ensure that this issue will not recur. What solution should be implemented to prevent this from happening again in the future?',choices:['A|Alter the retention period in SQS.','B|Alter the visibility timeout of SQS.','C|Use an Amazon SQS FIFO Queue instead.','D|Change the message size in SQS.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon SQS FIFO (First-In-First-Out) Queues have all the capabilities of the standard queue with additional capabilities designed to enhance messaging between applications when the order of operations and events is critical or where duplicates can\'t be tolerated, for example: financial transactions, inventory management, and order management systems.',why:'Amazon SQS FIFO Queues guarantee that messages are processed exactly once and in the same order they were sent. FIFO queues eliminate the issue of duplicated messages by ensuring that each message is delivered only once using deduplication and message sequencing mechanisms.',trap:'The option that says: Alter the retention period in SQS is incorrect because the retention period simply specifies if Amazon SQS should delete the messages that have been in a queue for a certain period of time.',rule:'Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS) provides two types of queues: Standard Queues and FIFO (First-In-First-Out) Queues. Not Amazon SQS.',keywords:'Exactly-once + ordered messages → SQS FIFO. Throughput = 300 TPS (3000 with batching).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_30',category:'Networking',question:'A company has hundreds of VPCs with multiple VPN connections to their data centers spanning 5 AWS Regions. As the number of its workloads grows, the company must be able to scale its networks across multiple accounts and VPCs to keep up. A Solutions Architect is tasked to interconnect all of the company\'s on-premises networks, VPNs, and VPCs into a single gateway, which includes support for inter-region peering across multiple AWS regions. Which of the following is the BEST solution that the architect should set up to support the required interconnectivity?',choices:['A|Set up an AWS Direct Connect Gateway to achieve inter-region VPC access to all of the AWS resources and on-premises data centers. Set up a link aggregation group (LAG) to aggregate multiple connections at a single AWS Direct Connect endpoint in order to treat them as a single, managed connection. Launch a virtual private gateway in each VPC and then create a public virtual interface for each AWS Direct Connect connection to the Direct Connect Gateway.','B|Set up an AWS Transit Gateway in each region to interconnect all networks within it. Then, route traffic between the transit gateways through a peering connection.','C|Set up an AWS VPN CloudHub for inter-region VPC access and a Direct Connect gateway for the VPN connections to the on-premises data centers. Create a virtual private gateway in each VPC, then create a private virtual interface for each AWS Direct Connect connection to the Direct Connect gateway.','D|Enable inter-region VPC peering that allows peering relationships to be established between multiple VPCs across different AWS regions. Set up a networking configuration that ensures that the traffic will always stay on the global AWS backbone and never traverse the public Internet.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Transit Gateway is a service that enables customers to connect their Amazon Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) and their on-premises networks to a single gateway. As you grow the number of workloads running on AWS, you need to be able to scale your networks across multiple accounts and Amazon VPCs to keep up with the growth.',why:'Today, you can connect pairs of Amazon VPCs using peering. However, managing point-to-point connectivity across many Amazon VPCs without the ability to centrally manage the connectivity policies can be operationally costly and cumbersome. For on-premises connectivity, you need to attach your AWS VPN to each individual Amazon VPC.',trap:'The option that says: Set up an AWS Direct Connect Gateway to achieve inter-region VPC access to all of the AWS resources and on-premises data centers. Set up a link aggregation group (LAG) to aggregate multiple connections at a single AWS Direct Connect endpoint in order to treat them as a single, managed connection. Launch a virtual private gateway in each VPC and then create a public virtual interface for each AWS Direct Connect connection to the Direct Connect Gateway is incorrect. You can only create a private virtual interface to a Direct Connect gateway and not a public virtual interface. Using a link aggregation group (LAG) is also irrelevant in this scenario because it is just a logical interface that uses the Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP) to aggregate multiple connections at a single AWS Direct Connect endpoint, allowing you to treat them as a single, managed connection.',rule:'Transit Gateway = hub-and-spoke for all VPCs and on-premises. Single gateway scales to thousands of VPCs. Supports transitive routing, inter-region peering, and VPN/Direct Connect attachments. Centralizes all connectivity policies.',keywords:'Connect many VPCs + on-premises = Transit Gateway. Hub-and-spoke. Supports transitive routing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_31',category:'Networking',question:'A large multinational investment bank has a web application that requires a minimum of 4 EC2 instances to run to ensure that it can cater to its users across the globe. You are instructed to ensure fault tolerance of this system. Which of the following is the best option?',choices:['A|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 2 instances in each of 3 Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer.','B|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 2 instances in each of 2 Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer.','C|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 4 instances in one Availability Zone behind an Application Load Balancer.','D|Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 1 instance in each of 4 Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer.'],correct:'A',answer:'Fault Tolerance is the ability of a system to remain in operation even if some of the components used to build the system fail. In AWS, this means that in the event of server fault or system failures, the number of running EC2 instances should not fall below the minimum number of instances required by the system for it to work properly.',why:'One of the differences between Fault Tolerance and High Availability is that the former refers to the minimum number of running instances. For example, you have a system that requires a minimum of 4 running instances and currently has 6 running instances deployed in two Availability Zones. There was a component failure in one of the Availability Zones which knocks out 3 instances.',trap:'The option that says: Deploy an Auto Scaling group with 2 instances in each of 2 Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer is incorrect because if one Availability Zone went out, there will only be 2 running instances available out of the required 4 minimum instances. Although the Auto Scaling group can spin up another 2 instances, the fault tolerance of the web application has already been compromised.',rule:'So if the application requires a minimum of N instances to function, design so that N instances remain after any single AZ failure.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_32',category:'EC2',question:'A company recently launched an e-commerce application that is running in eu-east-2 region, which strictly requires six EC2 instances running at all times. In that region, there are 3 Availability Zones (AZ) that you can use - eu-east-2a, eu-east-2b, and eu-east-2c. Which of the following deployments provide 100% fault tolerance if any single AZ in the region becomes unavailable? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|eu-east-2a with two EC2 instances, eu-east-2b with two EC2 instances, and eu-east-2c with two EC2 instances','B|eu-east-2a with two EC2 instances, eu-east-2b with four EC2 instances, and eu-east-2c with two EC2 instances','C|eu-east-2a with four EC2 instances, eu-east-2b with two EC2 instances, and eu-east-2c with two EC2 instances','D|eu-east-2a with six EC2 instances, eu-east-2b with six EC2 instances, and eu-east-2c with no EC2 instances','E|eu-east-2a with three EC2 instances, eu-east-2b with three EC2 instances, and eu-east-2c with three EC2 instances'],correct:'DE',answer:'Fault Tolerance is the ability of a system to remain in operation even if some of the components used to build the system fail. In AWS, this means that in the event of server fault or system failures, the number of running EC2 instances should not fall below the minimum number of instances required by the system for it to work properly.',why:'A fault-tolerant system continues operating during a component failure with no user-visible impact — there is no failover window. High availability allows a brief outage during failover (e.g., RDS Multi-AZ has a 1-2 minute DNS switch). To simulate a fault-tolerance test, you intentionally shut down one AZ and verify your application continues without downtime. If there is any interruption, the system is highly available but not fully fault-tolerant.',trap:'High Availability means redundant components that allow the system to keep running after a component failure — brief failover downtime is acceptable. Fault Tolerance means zero interruption: the system continues operating during a failure using redundancy (e.g., RAID, active-active). Scalability means handling more load, not surviving failure.',rule:'High availability = survive component failure (Multi-AZ, multi-instance). Fault tolerance = continue operating during failure (no interruption). Scalability = handle increased load without failure. Fault tolerance = built-in redundancy. Scalability = adding resources on demand.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_33',category:'Storage',question:'A tech company currently has an on-premises infrastructure. They are currently running low on storage and want to have the ability to extend their storage using the AWS cloud. Which AWS service can help them achieve this requirement? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Amazon EC2','B|AWS Storage Gateway','C|Amazon Elastic Block Storage','D|Amazon SQS'],correct:'BCD',answer:'AWS Storage Gateway connects an on-premises software appliance with cloud-based storage to provide seamless integration with data security features between your on-premises IT environment and the AWS storage infrastructure. You can use the service to store data in the AWS Cloud for scalable and cost-effective storage that helps maintain data security.',why:'Storage Gateway File Gateway presents a file interface (NFS/SMB) to your on-premises servers while transparently storing files as S3 objects. Reads are served from a local cache for low latency. Writes go to S3 asynchronously. The gateway handles the protocol translation — your apps see a normal network file share backed by durable cloud storage.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon EC2 is incorrect since this is a compute service, not a storage service.',rule:'have the ability to extend their storage using the → AWS Storage.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_34',category:'S3',question:'A company has a set of Linux servers running on multiple On-Demand EC2 Instances. The Audit team wants to collect and process the application log files generated from these servers for their report. Which of the following services is best to use in this case?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 for storing the application log files and Amazon Elastic MapReduce for processing the log files.','B|Amazon S3 Glacier for storing the application log files and Spot EC2 Instances for processing them.','C|A single On-Demand Amazon EC2 instance for both storing and processing the log files','D|Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive for storing the application log files and AWS ParallelCluster for processing the log files.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon EMR is a managed cluster platform that simplifies running big data frameworks, such as Apache Hadoop and Apache Spark, on AWS to process and analyze vast amounts of data. By using these frameworks and related open-source projects such as Apache Hive and Apache Pig, you can process data for analytics purposes and business intelligence workloads.',why:'EMR launches a cluster of EC2 instances (master + core + task nodes) and installs the Spark/Hadoop runtime. Data typically lives in S3 (EMRFS). Clusters can be transient (spin up, process, terminate) or long-lived. EMR Serverless removes the need to provision or tune clusters entirely. Cost is per EC2 instance-hour or per vCPU/memory-hour for Serverless.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive for storing the application log files and AWS ParallelCluster for processing the log files is incorrect because the long retrieval time of Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive makes this option unsuitable. Moreover, AWS ParallelCluster is just an AWS-supported open-source cluster management tool that makes it easy for you to deploy and manage High-Performance Computing (HPC) clusters on AWS. ParallelCluster uses a simple text file to model and provision all the resources needed for your HPC applications in an automated and secure manner.',rule:'Run Apache Spark/Hadoop big data processing on AWS = Amazon EMR. Managed cluster, pay per use. Not Glue (ETL service). Not ECS (containers, not Spark clusters).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_35',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has a web application hosted in AWS cloud where the application logs are sent to Amazon CloudWatch. Lately, the web application has been encountering some errors which can be resolved simply by restarting the instance. What will you do to automatically restart the EC2 instances whenever the same application error occurs?',choices:['A|First, look at the existing CloudWatch logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create a CloudWatch alarm for that custom metric which invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance.','B|First, look at the existing CloudWatch logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create an alarm in Amazon SNS for that custom metric which invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance.','C|First, look at the existing Flow logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create a CloudWatch alarm for that custom metric which invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance.','D|First, look at the existing Flow logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create a CloudWatch alarm for that custom metric which calls a Lambda function that invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance.'],correct:'A',answer:'In this scenario, you can look at the existing CloudWatch logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create a CloudWatch alarm for that custom metric which invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance.',why:'You can create alarms that automatically stop, terminate, reboot, or recover your EC2 instances using Amazon CloudWatch alarm actions. You can use the stop or terminate actions to help you save money when you no longer need an instance to be running. You can use the reboot and recover actions to automatically reboot those instances or recover them onto new hardware if a system impairment occurs.',trap:'The option that says: First, look at the existing CloudWatch logs for keywords related to the application error to create a custom metric. Then, create an alarm in Amazon SNS for that custom metric which invokes an action to restart the EC2 instance is incorrect because you can\'t create an alarm in Amazon SNS.',rule:'EC2: correct. Amazon SNS: incorrect for this scenario.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_36',category:'Serverless',question:'A real-time data analytics application is using AWS Lambda to process data and store results in JSON format to an S3 bucket. To speed up the existing workflow, you have to use a service where you can run sophisticated Big Data analytics on your data without moving them into a separate analytics system. Which of the following group of services can you use to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon Neptune, DynamoDB DAX, Amazon Redshift Spectrum','B|Amazon X-Ray, Amazon Neptune, DynamoDB','C|Amazon Glue, Amazon Redshift, Amazon S3','D|Amazon Athena, Amazon Redshift Spectrum, AWS Glue'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Athena, Amazon Redshift Spectrum, and AWS Glue are highly relevant services for performing Big Data analytics directly on data stored in Amazon S3, without needing to move the data to a separate system.',why:'Amazon Athena allows users to query data directly in Amazon S3 using SQL, providing a serverless approach to perform analytics on S3-stored data in formats such as JSON. Amazon Redshift Spectrum extends the querying capabilities of Amazon Redshift to also access and analyze structured and semi-structured data in S3, supporting large-scale analytics.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon Neptune, DynamoDB DAX, Amazon Redshift Spectrum is incorrect because Amazon Neptune and DynamoDB DAX simply do not support analytics or querying capabilities on data stored in S3. They are used for graph databases and caching, respectively.',rule:'Amazon Athena allows users to query data directly in Amazon S3 using SQL, providing a serverless approach to perform analytics on S3-stored  Not Amazon Neptune.',keywords:'Amazon Athena + Redshift Spectrum + AWS Glue: serverless analytics stack. Athena = SQL on S3. Glue = catalog + ETL.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_37',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a web application hosted in an On-Demand EC2 instance. You are creating a shell script that needs the instance\'s public and private IP addresses. What is the best way to get the instance\'s associated IP addresses which your shell script can use?',choices:['A|By using IAM.','B|By using a CloudWatch metric.','C|By using a Curl or Get Command to get the latest metadata information from http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/','D|By using a Curl or Get Command to get the latest user data information from http://169.254.169.254/latest/user-data/'],correct:'C',answer:'The EC2 instance metadata service (IMDS) is available at the link-local address 169.254.169.254. A curl command to http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/ retrieves instance metadata programmatically.',why:'IMDS provides instance metadata including instance ID, public IP, IAM role credentials, placement information, and more. It is available from within the EC2 instance at the fixed link-local IP. The /latest/meta-data/ path returns metadata. The /latest/user-data/ path returns user data (bootstrap scripts). This is used in shell scripts to self-discover the instance identity without hardcoding values.',trap:'IAM controls permissions — it does not expose instance runtime data like IP address or instance ID. CloudWatch metrics expose monitoring data, not instance metadata. User data (169.254.169.254/latest/user-data/) contains the bootstrap script, not the metadata like public IP or instance ID.',rule:'Access EC2 instance metadata via http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/. IMDS = link-local, only accessible from within the instance. IMDSv2 requires a session token for enhanced security.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_38',category:'Serverless',question:'A solutions architect is tasked with designing a scalable infrastructure solution for a business that runs uses Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) to execute container applications. Since the company\'s workload varies throughout the day, they want to make sure that its underlying infrastructure automatically scales in and out in response to demand. Which of the following would meet the requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead?',choices:['A|Use a combination of Kubernetes Metrics and Kubernetes Cluster Autoscaler to manage the number of nodes.','B|Integrate an edge-optimized API endpoint in Amazon API Gateway with Amazon EKS to manage and expose APIs for the containerized applications running on EKS.','C|Use Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling Groups with custom scaling policies to manage the scaling of EKS worker nodes.','D|Set up CloudWatch alarms for CPU utilization or request count to monitor the relevant metrics of the container applications running on Amazon EKS.'],correct:'A',answer:'Autoscaling is a function that automatically scales your resources up or down to meet changing demands. This is a major Kubernetes function that would otherwise require extensive human resources to perform manually.',why:'Karpenter is a flexible, high-performance Kubernetes cluster autoscaler that launches appropriately sized compute resources, like Amazon EC2 instances, in response to changing application load. It integrates with AWS to provision compute resources that precisely match workload requirements.',trap:'The option that says: Integrate an edge-optimized API endpoint in Amazon API Gateway with Amazon EKS to manage and expose APIs for the containerized applications running on EKS is incorrect because the question specifically asks for a solution that enables automatic scaling in response to demand. An edge-optimized API endpoint in Amazon API Gateway is primarily used for geographically distributed clients wherein the API requests are routed to the nearest CloudFront Point of Presence (POP). It doesn\'t specifically address the need for scaling.',rule:'Karpenter is a flexible, high-performance Kubernetes cluster autoscaler that launches appropriately sized compute resources, like Amazon EC2 instances, in response to changing application load. Karpenter consolidates nodes and terminates unused capacity automatically.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_39',category:'S3',question:'A financial firm is designing an application architecture for its online trading platform that must have high availability and fault tolerance. Their Solutions Architect configured the application to use an Amazon S3 bucket located in the us-east-1 region to store large amounts of intraday financial data. The stored financial data in the bucket must not be affected even if there is an outage in one of the Availability Zones or if there\'s a regional service failure. What should the Architect do to avoid any costly service disruptions and ensure data durability?',choices:['A|Copy the S3 bucket to an EBS-backed EC2 instance.','B|Create a Lifecycle Policy to regularly backup the S3 bucket to Amazon Glacier.','C|Create a new S3 bucket in another region and configure Cross-Account Access to the bucket located in us-east-1.','D|Enable Cross-Region Replication.'],correct:'D',answer:'In this scenario, you need to enable Cross-Region Replication to ensure that your S3 bucket would not be affected even if there is an outage in one of the Availability Zones or a regional service failure in us-east-1.',why:'Note that an Availability Zone (AZ) is more related with Amazon EC2 instances rather than Amazon S3 so if there is any outage in the AZ, the S3 bucket is usually not affected but only the EC2 instances deployed on that zone.',trap:'The option that says: Copy the S3 bucket to an EBS-backed EC2 instance is incorrect because EBS is not as durable as Amazon S3. Moreover, if the Availability Zone where the volume is hosted goes down then the data will also be inaccessible.',rule:'Note that an Availability Zone (AZ) is more related with Amazon EC2 instances rather than Amazon S3 so if there is any outage in the AZ, the Not Amazon S3.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_40',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is running a web application on AWS. The application is made up of an Auto-Scaling group that sits behind an Application Load Balancer and an Amazon DynamoDB table where user data is stored. The solutions architect must design the application to remain available in the event of a regional failure. A solution to automatically monitor the status of your workloads across your AWS account, conduct architectural reviews and check for AWS best practices. Which configuration meets the requirement with the least amount of downtime possible?',choices:['A|In a secondary region, create a global table of the DynamoDB table and replicate the auto-scaling group and application load balancer. Use Route 53 DNS failover to automatically route traffic to the resources in the secondary region. Set up the AWS Well-Architected Tool to easily get recommendations for improving your workloads based on the AWS best practices','B|In a secondary region, create a global secondary index of the DynamoDB table and replicate the auto-scaling group and application load balancer. Use Route 53 DNS failover to automatically route traffic to the resources in the secondary region. Set up the AWS Compute Optimizer to automatically get recommendations for improving your workloads based on the AWS best practices','C|Write a CloudFormation template that includes the auto-scaling group, application load balancer, and DynamoDB table. In the event of a failure, deploy the template in a secondary region. Use Route 53 DNS failover to automatically route traffic to the resources in the secondary region. Set up and configure the Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus service to receive insights for improving your workloads based on the AWS best practices.','D|Write a CloudFormation template that includes the auto-scaling group, application load balancer, and DynamoDB table. In the event of a failure, deploy the template in a secondary region. Configure Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to trigger a Lambda function that updates the application’s Route 53 DNS record. Launch an Amazon Managed Grafana workspace to automatically receive tips and action items for improving your workloads based on the AWS best practices'],correct:'A',answer:'When you have more than one resource performing the same function—for example, more than one HTTP serve—you can configure Amazon Route 53 to check the health of your resources and respond to DNS queries using only the healthy resources. For example, suppose your website, example.com, is hosted on six servers, two each in three data centers around the world.',why:'In this scenario, you can replicate the process layer (EC2 instances, Application Load Balancer) to a different region and create a global table based on the existing DynamoDB table (data layer). Amazon DynamoDB will handle data synchronization between the tables in different regions. This way, the state of the application is preserved even in the event of an outage.',trap:'The option that says: In a secondary region, create a global secondary index of the DynamoDB table and replicate the auto-scaling group and application load balancer. Use Route 53 DNS failover to automatically route traffic to the resources in the secondary region. Set up the AWS Compute Optimizer to automatically get recommendations for improving your workloads based on the AWS best practices is incorrect because this configuration is impossible to implement. A global secondary index can only be created in the region where its parent table resides. Moreover, the AWS Compute Optimizer simply helps you to identify the optimal AWS resource configurations, such as Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) instance types, Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volume configurations, and AWS Lambda function memory sizes. It is not capable of providing recommendations to improve your workloads based on AWS best practices.',rule:'Monitoring → AWS Well, AWS best practices. Not Use Route.',keywords:'Multi-region DynamoDB active-active → Global Tables.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_41',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company deployed an online enrollment system database on a prestigious university, which is hosted in RDS. The Solutions Architect is required to monitor the database metrics in Amazon CloudWatch to ensure the availability of the enrollment system. What are the enhanced monitoring metrics that Amazon CloudWatch gathers from Amazon RDS DB instances which provide more accurate information? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|CPU Utilization','B|Database Connections','C|Freeable Memory','D|RDS child processes','E|OS processes'],correct:'DE',answer:'RDS CloudWatch metrics that can be monitored for database performance include: CPU Utilization, Database Connections, and Freeable Memory. RDS child processes and OS processes are shown only in Enhanced Monitoring, not standard CloudWatch metrics.',why:'Standard RDS CloudWatch metrics include CPU Utilization, Database Connections, Freeable Memory, Read/Write IOPS, Read/Write Latency, and Storage space. Enhanced Monitoring provides 50+ OS-level metrics including RDS child processes (like Aurora threads) and OS processes (like the OS kernel processes). Enhanced Monitoring uses an agent that runs on the DB instance.',trap:'RDS child processes and OS processes are only visible in Enhanced Monitoring — not in standard CloudWatch metrics. Standard CloudWatch metrics are collected at the hypervisor level and cannot see inside the OS.',rule:'Standard RDS CloudWatch metrics = CPU, DB Connections, Freeable Memory, IOPS, Storage. Enhanced Monitoring = OS-level metrics (child processes, OS processes). Enhanced Monitoring = collects OS-level process metrics (RDS child processes, OS processes) via agent inside the DB instance.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_42',category:'S3',question:'A data analytics company, which uses machine learning to collect and analyze consumer data, is using Redshift cluster as their data warehouse. You are instructed to implement a disaster recovery plan for their systems to ensure business continuity even in the event of an AWS region outage. Which of the following is the best approach to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Create a scheduled job that will automatically take the snapshot of your Redshift Cluster and store it to an S3 bucket. Restore the snapshot in case of an AWS region outage.','B|Do nothing because Amazon Redshift is a highly available, fully-managed data warehouse which can withstand an outage of an entire AWS region.','C|Use Automated snapshots of your Redshift Cluster.','D|Enable Cross-Region Snapshots Copy in your Amazon Redshift Cluster.'],correct:'D',answer:'You can configure Amazon Redshift to copy snapshots for a cluster to another region. To configure cross-region snapshot copy, you need to enable this copy feature for each cluster and configure where to copy snapshots and how long to keep copied automated snapshots in the destination region.',why:'Cross-region snapshot copy works by scheduling a replication job that copies each new automated snapshot to your target region after it is created. You choose the retention period for destination snapshots independently of the source. In the event of a source region failure you restore from the most recent snapshot in the target region. There is no automatic failover — you manually restore and redirect your application.',trap:'The option that says: Do nothing because Amazon Redshift is a highly available, fully-managed data warehouse which can withstand an outage of an entire AWS region is incorrect. Although Amazon Redshift is a fully-managed data warehouse, you will still need to configure cross-region snapshot copy to ensure that your data is properly replicated to another region.',rule:'Redshift cross-region disaster recovery = enable Cross-Region Snapshot Copy. Not highly available by default across regions — must explicitly configure snapshot replication.',keywords:'Redshift DR = Cross-Region Snapshot Copy. Automated snapshots = same region only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_43',category:'Serverless',question:'Every week, an e-commerce company announces a sales promotion, causing its application hosted on an Auto Scaling group to experience intermittent downtime. Because of long initialization times, the application only becomes operational minutes before a new EC2 instance turns into RUNNING state. A solutions architect must devise a solution that launches capacity in advance based on a forecasted load in order to scale faster. Which solution meets the requirements with the least amount of effort?',choices:['A|Configure the Auto Scaling group to use predictive scaling.','B|Use Amazon SageMaker Clarify to analyze and predict the workload pattern of the application. Create a scheduled scaling policy based on the prediction results.','C|Create a dynamic scaling policy based on the historical average CPU load of the application.','D|Create a Scheduled Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) Rule that runs a scaling job on a Lambda function every midnight.'],correct:'A',answer:'Predictive scaling uses machine learning to predict capacity requirements based on historical data from CloudWatch. The machine learning algorithm consumes the available historical data and calculates capacity that best fits the historical load pattern, and then continuously learns based on new data to make future forecasts more accurate.',why:'In general, if you have regular patterns of traffic increases and applications that take a long time to initialize, you should consider using predictive scaling. Predictive scaling can help you scale faster by launching capacity in advance of forecasted load, compared to using only dynamic scaling, which is reactive in nature.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon SageMaker Clarify to analyze and predict the workload pattern of the application. Create a scheduled scaling policy based on the prediction results is incorrect because SageMaker Clarify is a tool designed for detecting bias and providing explainability for machine learning models. Using SageMaker Clarify would only involve unnecessary complexity and does not directly solve the problem of predicting traffic for Auto Scaling.',rule:'Predictive scaling can help you scale faster by launching capacity in advance of forecasted load, compared to using only dynamic scaling, which responds to current metrics. Both can work together for comprehensive scaling coverage.',keywords:'Known repeating traffic patterns → Predictive Scaling. ML analyzes 14 days, pre-scales.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_44',category:'EC2',question:'A company has a fixed set of Amazon EC2 instances inside a VPC in the AWS cloud. The instances run a mission-critical application. In a recent incident, one of the EC2 instances suddenly powered down which affected the availability of the application. To avoid this incident in the future, the management wants to get notified of any upcoming AWS events that may affect these EC2 instances. Which of the following options is the recommended action to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that is scheduled to run every 24 hours. Set the target to an AWS Lambda function that will check AWS Service Health Dashboard and send notifications for any events that may affect Amazon EC2 instances.','B|Set up an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to check for any status change for Amazon EC2 instances. Set the target to an AWS Lambda function that will send a notification and restart the affected Amazon EC2 instances.','C|Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to check for AWS Personal Health Dashboard events that are related to Amazon EC2 instances. To send notifications, set an Amazon SNS topic as a target for the rule.','D|Set up an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to check for AWS Service Health Dashboard events that are related to Amazon EC2 instances. To send notifications, set an Amazon SNS topic as a target for the rule.'],correct:'A',answer:'Auto Scaling group predictive scaling uses machine learning to analyze historical load patterns and forecast future demand, proactively scaling the group before traffic peaks occur.',why:'Predictive scaling analyzes up to 14 days of CloudWatch metric history to identify recurring traffic patterns (daily, weekly). It creates scheduled scaling actions in advance so that additional capacity is available before demand rises. This eliminates the lag inherent in reactive scaling — where the ASG must first detect high CPU, wait for alarms, and then provision instances that take minutes to warm up.',trap:'Dynamic scaling based on historical average CPU is reactive — it triggers after CPU is already high. A scheduled EventBridge rule to invoke scaling is manual and requires someone to define the schedule; it cannot self-adjust to changing patterns. SageMaker Clarify is an ML explainability tool for model fairness, not infrastructure scaling.',rule:'Proactive scaling based on historical patterns = Predictive Scaling (uses ML, auto-schedules scaling in advance). Dynamic scaling = reactive (triggered by current metrics). Predictive scaling = proactive (uses ML to predict future load). Use all three together for best coverage.',keywords:'Known repeating traffic patterns → Predictive Scaling. ML analyzes 14 days, pre-scales.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_45',category:'Route 53',question:'A company launched an EC2 instance in the newly created VPC. They noticed that the generated instance does not have an associated DNS hostname. Which of the following options could be a valid reason for this issue?',choices:['A|The newly created VPC has an invalid CIDR block.','B|Amazon Route 53 is not enabled.','C|The DNS resolution and DNS hostname of the VPC configuration should be enabled.','D|The security group of the EC2 instance needs to be modified.'],correct:'C',answer:'When you launch an EC2 instance into a default VPC, AWS provides it with public and private DNS hostnames that correspond to the public IPv4 and private IPv4 addresses for the instance.',why:'When you create a VPC, "Enable DNS Hostnames" is off by default (unlike the default VPC which has it on). Without this setting, EC2 instances in the VPC receive private IP addresses but no DNS hostnames. The public DNS hostname maps to the public IP and the private hostname maps to the private IP. Many AWS services (RDS, ElastiCache, ELB) require DNS resolution to work. Enabling "Enable DNS Resolution" (also required) allows instances to use the Amazon Route 53 Resolver at the VPC+2 address.',trap:'The option that says: The newly created VPC has an invalid CIDR block is incorrect since it\'s very unlikely that a VPC has an invalid CIDR block because of AWS validation schemes.',rule:'However, when you launch an instance into a non-default VPC, AWS provides the instance with a private DNS hostname only.',keywords:'VPC DNS: enableDnsHostnames + enableDnsSupport must both be enabled for EC2 to get public DNS hostnames.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_46',category:'Networking',question:'A newly hired Solutions Architect is checking all of the security groups and network access control list rules of the company\'s AWS resources. For security purposes, the MS SQL connection via port 1433 of the database tier should be secured. Below is the security group configuration of their Microsoft SQL Server database: The application tier hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances is the only identified resource that needs to connect to the database. The Architect should ensure that the architecture complies with the best practice of granting least privilege. Which of the following changes should be made to the security group configuration?',choices:['A|For the MS SQL rule, change the Source to the security group ID attached to the application tier.','B|For the MS SQL rule, change the Source to the EC2 instance IDs of the underlying instances of the Auto Scaling group.','C|For the MS SQL rule, change the Source to the static AnyCast IP address attached to the application tier.','D|For the MS SQL rule, change the Source to the Network ACL ID attached to the application tier.'],correct:'A',answer:'If you launch an instance using the Amazon EC2 API or a command line tool and you don\'t specify a security group, the instance is automatically assigned to the default security group for the VPC. If you launch an instance using the Amazon EC2 console, you have an option to create a new security group for the instance.',why:'For each security group, you add rules that control the inbound traffic to instances and a separate set of rules that control the outbound traffic. This section describes the basic things that you need to know about security groups for your VPC and their rules.',trap:'The option that says: For the MS SQL rule, change the Source to the EC2 instance IDs of the underlying instances of the Auto Scaling group is incorrect because using the EC2 instance IDs of the underlying instances of the Auto Scaling group as the source can cause intermittent issues. New instances will be added, and old instances will be removed from the Auto Scaling group over time, which means that you have to manually update the security group setting once again. A better solution is to use the security group ID of the Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances.',rule:'Default VPC tenancy = shared hardware. Dedicated tenancy = single-tenant hardware (your instances only). Dedicated Host = you control the physical server + socket/core licensing. Dedicated Instances = single-tenant but AWS controls host assignment.',keywords:'Security group source = other SG ID (covers all current + future ASG members). Not instance IDs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_47',category:'Database',question:'A Solutions Architect is designing a setup for a database that will run on Amazon RDS for MySQL. He needs to ensure that the database can automatically failover to an RDS instance to continue operating in the event of failure. The architecture should also be as highly available as possible. Which among the following actions should the Solutions Architect do?',choices:['A|Create a standby replica in another availability zone by enabling Multi-AZ deployment.','B|Create a read replica in the same region where the DB instance resides. In addition, create a read replica in a different region to survive a region’s failure. In the event of an Availability Zone outage, promote any replica to become the primary instance.','C|Create five read replicas across different availability zones. In the event of an Availability Zone outage, promote any replica to become the primary instance.','D|Create five cross-region read replicas in each region. In the event of an Availability Zone outage, promote any replica to become the primary instance.'],correct:'A',answer:'You can run an Amazon RDS DB instance in several AZs with Multi-AZ deployment. Amazon automatically provisions and maintains a secondary standby DB instance in a different AZ.',why:'RDS Multi-AZ for SQL Server uses synchronous mirroring between the primary and standby. The standby is in a different AZ and receives every write before the primary acknowledges the transaction. On primary failure, RDS updates the CNAME to point to the standby — typically within 60-120 seconds — without requiring any application code change. Read Replicas use asynchronous replication and primarily serve read traffic; they are not designed for automatic failover.',trap:'The option that says: Create a read replica in the same region where the DB instance resides. In addition, create a read replica in a different region to survive a region\'s failure. In the event of an Availability Zone outage, promote any replica to become the primary instance is incorrect. Although this architecture provides higher availability since it can survive a region failure, it still does not meet the first requirement since the process is not automated. The architecture should also support automatic failover to an RDS instance in case of failures.',rule:'As described in the scenario, the architecture must meet two requirements: The database should automatically fail over to an RDS instance in a different AZ. The standby replicates synchronously. Failover is automatic in 1-2 min.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_48',category:'Storage',question:'A company has an Application Load Balancer (ALB) that accepts HTTP and HTTPS traffic on ports 80 and 443, respectively. Recently, the company associated a new domain for its website, and they want to ensure that all HTTP traffic for this new domain is automatically redirected to HTTPS to improve security. Which ALB configuration should be done to satisfy the requirement?',choices:['A|Create a new HTTP listener on port 80 and add a redirect action to the HTTPS protocol on port 443.','B|Configure the existing HTTP listener to redirect traffic to port 443.','C|Create a new ALB listener on port 443 and configure it to redirect HTTP traffic to HTTPS.','D|Configure the existing on port 443 and add a redirect action to HTTP on port 80.'],correct:'B',answer:'Application Load Balancer operates at the application layer (layer 7), routing traffic to targets such as EC2 instances, containers, IP addresses, and Lambda functions based on the requested content.',why:'Configuring the existing ALB listener on port 80 to redirect traffic to port 443 is the most appropriate solution for redirecting HTTP to HTTPS traffic. This can be achieved by setting up a redirect rule for the listener. By doing this, all HTTP traffic will be automatically redirected to HTTPS, thus improving the security of the website.',trap:'Network Load Balancer does not support gRPC — NLB operates at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP) and cannot parse HTTP/2 frames required for gRPC. Gateway Load Balancer is for deploying third-party virtual appliances (firewalls, IDS/IPS) using the GENEVE protocol — it is not a web application load balancer.',rule:'ALB (Layer 7) = path/host routing + WebSocket + gRPC + WAF integration. NLB (Layer 4) = TCP/UDP, ultra-low latency, static IP/EIP. Choose ALB for HTTP/S routing intelligence. Choose NLB for TCP/UDP, static IP, extreme performance. CLB = legacy.',keywords:'ALB HTTP→HTTPS redirect = modify existing port 80 listener default action. Cannot create duplicate listener.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_49',category:'Networking',question:'A startup launched a new FTP server using an On-Demand EC2 instance in a newly created VPC with default settings. The server should not be accessible publicly but only through the IP address 175.45.116.100 and nowhere else. Which of the following is the most suitable way to implement this requirement?',choices:['A|Create a new inbound rule in the security group of the EC2 instance with the following details: Protocol: TCP Port Range: 20 - 21 Source: 175.45.116.100/32','B|Create a new inbound rule in the security group of the EC2 instance with the following details: Protocol: UDP Port Range: 20 - 21 Source: 175.45.116.100/32','C|Create a new Network ACL inbound rule in the subnet of the EC2 instance with the following details: Protocol: TCP Port Range: 20 - 21 Source: 175.45.116.100/0 Allow/Deny: ALLOW','D|Create a new Network ACL inbound rule in the subnet of the EC2 instance with the following details: Protocol: UDP Port Range: 20 - 21 Source: 175.45.116.100/0 Allow/Deny: ALLOW'],correct:'B',answer:'To configure FTP on a new EC2 instance in a VPC with default settings, add an inbound security group rule for TCP port 21 (FTP control connection) from the source IP.',why:'FTP uses port 21 for the control connection (commands and responses) and port 20 for active mode data transfer (or ephemeral ports for passive mode). Security groups control access at the instance level. A new VPC with default settings has no inbound rules allowing FTP. Adding TCP 21 inbound allows FTP clients to connect. For passive FTP to work fully, a range of ephemeral ports must also be opened.',trap:'A Network ACL inbound rule with UDP on port 22 is wrong on two counts: FTP uses TCP (not UDP) and port 21 (not 22, which is SSH). Security group rules with TCP port 22 open SSH — not FTP. NACLs are stateless and need both inbound and outbound rules, unlike stateful security groups.',rule:'FTP control connection = TCP port 21. SSH = TCP port 22. FTP data = TCP port 20 (active) or ephemeral ports (passive). Security groups = stateful. NACLs = stateless (need both inbound and outbound rules). Security groups allow only; NACLs can allow or deny.',keywords:'FTP uses TCP port 20 (data) and 21 (control). Security group source /32 = single IP address.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_50',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is designing a monitoring application which generates audit logs of all operational activities of the company\'s cloud infrastructure. Their IT Security and Compliance team mandates that the application retain the logs for 5 years before the data can be deleted. How can the Architect meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Store the audit logs in a Glacier vault and use the Vault Lock feature.','B|Store the audit logs in an EBS volume and then take EBS snapshots every month.','C|Store the audit logs in an Amazon S3 bucket and enable Multi-Factor Authentication Delete (MFA Delete) on the S3 bucket.','D|Store the audit logs in an EFS volume and use Network File System version 4 (NFSv4) file-locking mechanism.'],correct:'A',answer:'An Amazon S3 Glacier (Glacier) vault can have one resource-based vault access policy and one Vault Lock policy attached to it. A Vault Lock policy is a vault access policy that you can lock. Using a Vault Lock policy can help you enforce regulatory and compliance requirements. Amazon S3 Glacier provides a set of API operations for you to manage the Vault Lock policies.',why:'As an example of a Vault Lock policy, suppose that you are required to retain archives for one year before you can delete them. To implement this requirement, you can create a Vault Lock policy that denies users permission to delete an archive until the archive has existed for one year. You can test this policy before locking it down. After you lock the policy, the policy becomes immutable.',trap:'Storing the audit logs in an EBS volume and then taking EBS snapshots every month is incorrect because this is not a suitable and secure solution. Anyone who has access to the EBS Volume can simply delete and modify the audit logs. Snapshots can be deleted too.',rule:'As an example of a Vault Lock policy, suppose that you are required to retain archives for one year before you can delete them.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_51',category:'IAM',question:'A food company bought 50 licenses of Windows Server to be used by the developers when launching Amazon EC2 instances to deploy and test applications. The developers are free to provision EC2 instances as long as there is a license available. The licenses are tied to the total CPU count of each virtual machine. The company wants to ensure that developers won’t be able to launch new instances once the licenses are exhausted. The company wants to receive notifications when all licenses are in use. Which of the following options is the recommended solution to meet the company\'s requirements?',choices:['A|Define licensing rules on AWS License Manager to track and control license usage. Enable the option to “Enforce license limit” to prevent going over the number of allocated licenses. Add an Amazon SNS topic to send notifications and alerts.','B|Define license configuration rules on AWS Certificate Manager to track and control license usage. Enable the option to “Enforce certificate limit” to prevent going over the number of allocated licenses. Add an Amazon SQS queue with ChangeVisibility Timeout configured to send notifications and alerts.','C|Upload the licenses on AWS Systems Manager Fleet Manager to be encrypted and distributed to Amazon EC2 instances. Attach an IAM role on the EC2 instances to request a license from the Fleet Manager. Set up an Amazon SNS to send notifications and alerts once all licenses are used','D|Configure AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to track and control the licenses used by AWS resources. Configure AWS RAM to provide available licenses for Amazon EC2 instances. Set up an Amazon SNS to send notifications and alerts once all licenses are used.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS License Manager tracks and enforces software license usage rules. You define a license configuration specifying the number of licenses, license type, and enforcement rules. EC2 instances are then associated with the configuration.',why:'AWS License Manager integrates with AWS Systems Manager to discover software inventory across EC2 instances and on-premises servers. You create license configurations that specify the rules (vCPU-based, instance-based, or socket-based), set hard or soft limits, and associate them with launch templates or AMIs. When limits are approached or breached, License Manager alerts you or blocks new launches.',trap:'AWS Certificate Manager manages SSL/TLS certificates — not software licenses. Systems Manager Fleet Manager provides a GUI for managing EC2 instances — not license tracking. AWS RAM shares resources between accounts — it has no license management capability.',rule:'Software license tracking and enforcement = AWS License Manager. ACM = SSL/TLS certificates. Fleet Manager = EC2 instance management UI. RAM = resource sharing across accounts.',keywords:'Track + enforce software license usage → AWS License Manager.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_52',category:'IAM',question:'A multinational bank is storing its confidential files in an S3 bucket. The security team recently performed an audit, and the report shows that multiple files have been uploaded without 256-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) server-side encryption. For added protection, the encryption key must be automatically rotated every year. The solutions architect must ensure that there would be no other unencrypted files uploaded in the S3 bucket in the future. Which of the following will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) for the S3 bucket that rejects any object uploads unless the request includes the s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption": "AES256" header. Enable server-side encryption with Amazon S3-managed encryption keys (SSE-S3) and modify the built-in key rotation feature of the SSE-S3 encryption keys to rotate the key yearly.','B|Create an S3 bucket policy that denies permissions to upload an object unless the request includes the s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption": "AES256" header. Enable server-side encryption with Amazon S3-managed encryption keys (SSE-S3) and rely on the built-in key rotation feature of the SSE-S3 encryption keys.','C|Create a new customer-managed key from the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS). Configure the default encryption behavior of the bucket to use the customer-managed key. Manually rotate the KMS key and every year.','D|Create an S3 bucket policy for the S3 bucket that rejects any object uploads unless the request includes the s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption":"aws:kms" header. Enable the S3 Object Lock in compliance mode for all objects to automatically rotate the built-in AES256 customer-managed key of the bucket.'],correct:'A',answer:'A bucket policy is a resource-based policy that you can use to grant access permissions to your bucket and the objects in it. Server-side encryption protects data at rest. Amazon S3 encrypts each object with a unique key. Amazon S3 server-side encryption uses one of the strongest block ciphers available to encrypt your data, 256-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-256).',why:'If you need server-side encryption for all of the objects that are stored in a bucket, use a bucket policy. You can create a bucket policy that denies permissions to upload an object unless the request includes the x-amz-server-side-encryption header to request server-side encryption.',trap:'The option that says: Create a new customer-managed key from the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS). Configure the default encryption behavior of the bucket to use the customer-managed key. Manually rotate the KMS key and every year is incorrect because this solution is missing a bucket policy that denies S3 object uploads without any encryption. Conversely, the act of manually rotating the KMS key each and every year adds to the manual management overhead for this solution.',rule:'Encryption → Amazon S3. Not AWS Key.',keywords:'S3 SSE bucket policy: aws:SecureTransport condition forces HTTPS. x-amz-server-side-encryption header enforces SSE.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_53',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A startup is planning to set up and govern a secure, compliant, multi-account AWS environment in preparation for its upcoming projects. The IT Manager requires the solution to have a dashboard for continuous detection of policy non-conformance and non-compliant resources across the enterprise, as well as to comply with the AWS multi-account strategy best practices. Which of the following offers the easiest way to fulfill this task?',choices:['A|Use AWS Organizations to build a landing zone to automatically provision new AWS accounts. Utilize the AWS Personal Health Dashboard to see provisioned accounts across your enterprise. Enable preventive and detective guardrails enabled for policy enforcement.','B|Launch new AWS member accounts using the AWS CloudFormation StackSets. Use AWS Config to continuously track the configuration changes and set rules to monitor non-compliant resources. Set up a Multi-Account Multi-Region Data Aggregator to monitor compliance data for rules and accounts in an aggregated view','C|Use AWS Control Tower to launch a landing zone to automatically provision and configure new accounts through an Account Factory. Utilize the AWS Control Tower dashboard to monitor provisioned accounts across your enterprise. Set up preventive and detective guardrails for policy enforcement.','D|Use AWS Service Catalog to launch new AWS member accounts. Configure AWS Service Catalog Launch Constraints to continuously track configuration changes and monitor non-compliant resources. Set up a Multi-Account Multi-Region Data Aggregator to monitor compliance data for rules and accounts in an aggregated view'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Control Tower offers a straightforward way to set up and govern an AWS multi-account environment, following prescriptive best practices. AWS Control Tower orchestrates the capabilities of several other AWS services, including AWS Organizations, AWS Service Catalog, and AWS Single Sign-On, to build a landing zone in less than an hour.',why:'A guardrail is a high-level rule that provides ongoing governance for your overall AWS environment. It\'s expressed in plain language. Through guardrails, AWS Control Tower implements preventive or detective controls that help you govern your resources and monitor compliance across groups of AWS accounts.',trap:'Use AWS Organizations to build a landing zone to automatically provision new AWS accounts. Utilize the AWS Personal Health Dashboard to see provisioned accounts across your enterprise. Enable preventive and detective guardrails enabled for policy enforcement is incorrect. The AWS Organizations service neither has the capability to build a landing zone nor a built-in dashboard for continuous detection of policy non-conformance and non-compliant resources across the enterprise. Moreover, the AWS Personal Health Dashboard simply provides alerts and remediation guidance when AWS is experiencing events that may impact your resources. This type of dashboard is not meant for monitoring the newly provisioned AWS accounts. The most suitable solution here is to use AWS Control Tower and its various features.',rule:'AWS Control Tower to lau|AWS Control Tower dashbo: correct. AWS Organizations: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Automated multi-account baseline + guardrails → AWS Control Tower Landing Zone.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_54',category:'Serverless',question:'A financial services organization is developing a cloud-native application on AWS to process and analyze customer transaction data. The application utilizes Amazon Aurora for the database, Amazon EFS for file storage, and Amazon EventBridge to trigger AWS Step Functions for workflow orchestration. The organization has implemented AWS IAM Identity Center for user authentication. The data science, engineering, and compliance teams require secure access to Amazon Aurora and Amazon EFS while maintaining strict data privacy standards. The solution must adhere to the principle of least privilege and minimize administrative overhead. Which approach best satisfies these requirements?',choices:['A|Set up AWS Control Tower to manage multi-account access. Use Service Control Policies (SCPs) to restrict access to Aurora and EFS at the organizational level. Create IAM roles in each account with specific permissions.','B|Enable the IAM Identity Center with an Identity Center directory and create permission sets for granular access for Amazon Aurora and Amazon EFS. Assign teams to groups linked to specific permission sets based on their roles.','C|Use Amazon Cognito User Pools for authentication and use Cognito Identity Pools to provide temporary AWS credentials. Create fine-grained IAM roles for Aurora and EFS access in each team.','D|Create separate AWS accounts for each team using AWS Organizations. Set up cross-account IAM roles with least privilege and assign specific Aurora and EFS permissions based on team roles.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS IAM Identity Center centralizes access management for various AWS accounts and applications. It provides single sign-on (SSO) access, enabling users to manage all their assigned accounts from a single location. Users can synchronize with an existing identity provider or create new users and groups directly within the service.',why:'IAM Identity Center utilizes permission sets—collections of IAM policies—to manage user access across AWS Organizations. It includes a user-friendly AWS Access Portal for easy access to applications and supports deployment for both organization and account instances. Designed for high availability across multiple availability zones, the service ensures secure access through AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) roles and policies.',trap:'The option that says: Set up AWS Control Tower to manage multi-account access. Use Service Control Policies (SCPs) to restrict access to Aurora and EFS at the organizational level. Create IAM roles in each account with specific permissions is incorrect. AWS Control Tower is typically used for multi-account governance and high-level policy enforcement using Service Control Policies (SCPs). While SCPs can restrict access, they operate at the account or organizational level and cannot provide the fine-grained access required for individual resources like Amazon Aurora or Amazon EFS. This approach increases administrative complexity and does not minimize overhead.',rule:'IAM Identity Center utilizes permission sets—collections of IAM policies—to manage user access across AWS Organizations.',keywords:'API Gateway request validation: validate body, query params, headers before Lambda invocation.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_55',category:'Networking',question:'A company has several web applications with users all around the world. Each application is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances in multiple AZs behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). All applications have their own fully qualified domain name. For added security, the applications must use a publicly trusted SSL certificate. Which solution will meet this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Launch a self-hosted certificate authority (CA) using the Let\'s Encrypt tool in an Amazon EC2 instance. Utilize the built-in ISRG Root X1 trusted root CA certificate. Generate a new SSL/TLS certificate using the certbot CLI utility. Associate the new certificate on the HTTPS listener of the ALBs.','B|Use the AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) to generate a public SSL/TLS certificate. Associate the new SSL/TLS certificate on the HTTPS listener of the ALBs.','C|Use OpenSSL to generate a self-signed certificate. Import the SSL/TLS certificate to the AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) and associate it with the HTTPS listener of the ALBs','D|Issue an SSL/TLS certificate using the AWS Certificate Manager Private Certificate Authority. Associate the new certificate on the HTTPS listener of the ALBs.'],correct:'B',answer:'There are two AWS services for issuing and deploying X.509 certificates. Choose the one that best fits your needs. Considerations include whether you need public- or private-facing certificates, customized certificates, certificates you want to deploy into other AWS services, or automated certificate management and renewal.',why:'ACM Private CA—This service is for enterprise customers building a public key infrastructure (PKI) inside the AWS cloud and is intended for private use within an organization. With ACM Private CA, you can create your own CA hierarchy and issue certificates with it for authenticating internal users, computers, applications, services, servers, and other devices and for signing computer code.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a self-hosted certificate authority (CA) using the Let\'s Encrypt tool in an Amazon EC2 instance. Utilize the built-in ISRG Root X1 trusted root CA certificate. Generate a new SSL/TLS certificate using the certbot CLI utility. Associate the new certificate on the HTTPS listener of the ALBs is incorrect because you cannot directly associate an SSL/TLS certificate to an Application Load Balancer. The certificate must be first imported to ACM before it can be associated to the elastic load balancers in your account.',rule:'Certificates issued by a private CA are trusted only with private PKI infrastructure. Public CA = publicly trusted by browsers/clients.',keywords:'Route 53 latency-based routing: routes to lowest latency region. Requires health checks for failover.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_56',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has a regional API Gateway in the us-east-2 region that serves as a proxy to a backend service. Clients connect to the service using the invoke URL of the API stage. To improve usability, the company wants to associate a custom domain name (api.tutorialsdojo.com) with the API. Moreover, the domain name must support HTTPS to ensure secure connections. The company has an existing hosted zone for its domain on Amazon Route 53. Which of the following would be the next step to achieve the company\'s objective?',choices:['A|Request a public certificate in the us-east-1 region for api.tutorialsdojo.com using AWS Certificate Manager (ACM). Create a regional API Gateway domain name and associate it with api.tutorialsdojo.com and the ACM certificate. In Route 53, create an alias record for api.tutorialsdojo.com that points to the API Gateway domain name.','B|Import an existing public certificate for api.tutorialsdojo.com into AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) in the us-east-2. In Route 53, create a CNAME record for api.tutorialsdojo.com that points to the invoke URL of the API Gateway stage.','C|Use the AWS Certificate Manager Private Certificate Authority (ACM PCA) to generate a private certificate for api.tutorialsdojo.com. Override the invoke URL using stage variables.','D|Request a public certificate in the us-east-2 region for api.tutorialsdojo.com using AWS Certificate Manager (ACM). Create a regional API Gateway domain name and associate it with api.tutorialsdojo.com and the ACM certificate. In Route 53, create an alias record for api.tutorialsdojo.com that points to the API Gateway domain name.'],correct:'A',answer:'In API Gateway, A Regional API is an API deployed to a specified Region and intended to serve clients, such as EC2 instances, in the same AWS Region. API requests are targeted directly to the Region-specific API Gateway API without going through any CloudFront distribution.',why:'When using a regional API, any custom domain name you choose is exclusive to the specific region where the API is deployed. If you deploy the same regional API in multiple regions, it can have the same custom domain name across all regions. Also, you must request or import the SSL certificate in the same Region as your API.',trap:'The option that says: Request a public certificate in the us-east-1 region for api.tutorialsdojo.com using AWS Certificate Manager (ACM). Create a regional API Gateway domain name and associate it with api.tutorialsdojo.com and the ACM certificate. In Route 53, create an alias record for api.tutorialsdojo.com that points to the API Gateway domain name is incorrect because it suggests configuring the Regional API Gateway endpoint in the wrong region. For a regional API Gateway, the certificate must be requested/imported in the same region as your API.',rule:'associate a custom domain name (api → AWS Certificate, In Route.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_57',category:'IAM',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a large global media company with multiple office locations all around the world. The Architect is instructed to build a system to distribute training videos to all employees. Using Amazon CloudFront, what method would be used to serve content that is stored in Amazon S3 but not publicly accessible from S3 directly?',choices:['A|Create an Origin Access Control (OAC) for CloudFront and grant access to the objects in your S3 bucket to that OAC.','B|Create an Identity and Access Management (IAM) user for CloudFront and grant access to the objects in your S3 bucket to that IAM user.','C|Create an S3 bucket policy that lists the CloudFront distribution ID as the principal and the target bucket as the Amazon Resource Name (ARN).','D|Create a web ACL in AWS WAF to block any public S3 access and attach it to the CloudFront distribution.'],correct:'A',answer:'When you create or update a distribution in CloudFront, you can add an origin access Control (OAC) and automatically update the bucket policy to give the origin access control permission to access your bucket. Alternatively, you can choose to manually change the bucket policy or change ACLs, which control permissions on individual objects in your bucket.',why:'OAC is the modern replacement for Origin Access Identity (OAI). It authenticates CloudFront requests to S3 using AWS Signature Version 4, supports all S3 buckets including those with Object Ownership enforced, and works with SSE-KMS encrypted buckets. The S3 bucket policy grants GetObject permission to the CloudFront service principal scoped to your specific distribution ARN, so no other source can read the bucket. Users access content only via the CloudFront URL, never directly from S3.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Identity and Access Management (IAM) user for CloudFront and grant access to the objects in your S3 bucket to that IAM user is incorrect because you cannot directly create an IAM User for a specific Amazon CloudFront distribution. You have to use an origin access control (OAC) instead.',rule:'Alternatively, you can choose to manually change the bucket policy or change ACLs, which control permissions on individual objects in your bucket.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_58',category:'Storage',question:'A company is using an On-Demand EC2 instance to host a legacy web application that uses an Amazon Instance Store-Backed AMI. The web application should be decommissioned as soon as possible and hence, you need to terminate the EC2 instance. When the instance is terminated, what happens to the data on the root volume?',choices:['A|Data is automatically saved as an EBS snapshot.','B|Data is automatically saved as an EBS volume.','C|Data is unavailable until the instance is restarted.','D|Data is automatically deleted.'],correct:'D',answer:'When an EC2 instance backed by instance store is terminated, all data on the instance store volumes is permanently and automatically deleted.',why:'Instance store volumes are physically attached to the host. They persist only during the life of the instance on that host. Termination, instance stop, or host hardware failure all result in complete, permanent data loss. There is no snapshot mechanism for instance store.',trap:'Instance store data cannot be saved as an EBS snapshot — instance store and EBS are different storage systems. Data does not become "unavailable until restarted" — it is gone permanently after termination. No stopped state preserves instance store.',rule:'Instance store = permanently deleted on termination/stop/host failure. Cannot be snapshotted. EBS-backed instances = data persists by default after termination.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_59',category:'S3',question:'A company decided to change its third-party data analytics tool to a cheaper solution. They sent a full data export on a CSV file which contains all of their analytics information. You then save the CSV file to an S3 bucket for storage. Your manager asked you to do some validation on the provided data export. In this scenario, what is the most cost-effective and easiest way to analyze export data using standard SQL?',choices:['A|Create a migration tool to load the CSV export file from S3 to a DynamoDB instance. Once the data has been loaded, run queries using DynamoDB.','B|Use mysqldump client utility to load the CSV export file from S3 to a MySQL RDS instance. Run some SQL queries once the data has been loaded to complete your validation.','C|To be able to run SQL queries, use Amazon Athena to analyze the export data file in S3.','D|Use a migration tool to load the CSV export file from S3 to a database that is designed for online analytic processing (OLAP) such as AWS RedShift. Run some queries once the data has been loaded to complete your validation.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon Athena is an interactive query service that makes it easy to analyze data directly in Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) using standard SQL. With a few actions in the AWS Management Console, you can point Athena at your data stored in Amazon S3 and begin using standard SQL to run ad-hoc queries and get results in seconds.',why:'Athena is serverless, so there is no infrastructure to set up or manage, and you pay only for the queries you run. Athena scales automatically—executing queries in parallel—so results are fast, even with large datasets and complex queries.',trap:'The rest of the options are all incorrect because it is not necessary to set up a database to be able to analyze the CSV export file. You can use a cost-effective option (AWS Athena), which is a serverless service that enables you to pay only for the queries you run.',rule:'Athena is serverless, so there is no infrastructure to set up or manage, and you pay only for the queries you run.',keywords:'S3 Access Logs: enable on source bucket, specify target bucket. Athena can query access logs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_60',category:'IAM',question:'A media company needs to configure an Amazon S3 bucket to serve static assets for the public-facing web application. Which methods ensure that all of the objects uploaded to the S3 bucket can be read publicly all over the Internet? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Grant public read access to the object when uploading it using the S3 Console.','B|Configure the cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) of the S3 bucket to allow objects to be publicly accessible from all domains.','C|Configure the S3 bucket policy to set all objects to public read.','D|Create an IAM role to set the objects inside the S3 bucket to public read.','E|Do nothing. Amazon S3 objects are already public by default.'],correct:'AC',answer:'Grant public read access to the object when uploading it using the S3 Console.',why:'By default, all Amazon S3 resources such as buckets, objects, and related subresources are private, which means that only the AWS account holder (resource owner) that created it has access to the resource. The resource owner can optionally grant access permissions to others by writing an access policy. In S3, you also set the permissions of the object during upload to make it public.',trap:'The option that says: Configure the cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) of the S3 bucket to allow objects to be publicly accessible from all domains is incorrect. CORS will only allow objects from one domain (travel.cebu.com) to be loaded and accessible to a different domain (palawan.com). It won\'t necessarily expose objects for public access all over the internet.',rule:'Make S3 objects public = set public-read ACL at upload time (if ACLs enabled) OR set bucket policy to allow s3:GetObject for Principal: *. S3 Block Public Access must be off at bucket AND account level. Objects are private by default.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_61',category:'IAM',question:'A company must integrate the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) directory service from the on-premises data center to the AWS VPC using IAM. The identity store which is currently being used is not compatible with SAML. Which of the following provides the most valid approach to implement the integration?',choices:['A|Use an IAM policy that references the LDAP identifiers and AWS credentials.','B|Use AWS IAM Identity Center to manage access between AWS and your LDAP.','C|Develop an on-premises custom identity broker application and use STS to issue short-lived AWS credentials.','D|Use IAM roles to rotate the IAM credentials whenever LDAP credentials are updated.'],correct:'C',answer:'If your identity store is not compatible with SAML 2.0 then you can build a custom identity broker application to perform a similar function. The broker application authenticates users, requests temporary credentials for users from AWS, and then provides them to the user to access AWS resources.',why:'The application verifies that employees are signed into the existing corporate network\'s identity and authentication system, which might use LDAP, Active Directory, or another system. The identity broker application then obtains temporary security credentials for the employees.',trap:'The option that says: Use an IAM policy that references the LDAP identifiers and AWS credentials is incorrect because simply using an IAM policy is not enough to integrate your LDAP service to IAM. You need to use SAML, STS, or a custom identity broker.',rule:'AWS credentials: correct. AWS credentials: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_62',category:'Serverless',question:'A hospital has a mission-critical application that uses a RESTful API powered by Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda. The medical officers upload PDF reports to the system which are then stored as static media content in an Amazon S3 bucket. The security team wants to improve its visibility when it comes to cyber-attacks and ensure HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) compliance. The company is searching for a solution that continuously monitors object-level S3 API operations and identifies protected health information (PHI) in the reports, with minimal changes in the existing Lambda function. Which of the following solutions will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Use Amazon Textract Medical with PII redaction turned on to extract and filter sensitive text from the PDF reports. Create a new Lambda function that calls the regular Amazon Comprehend API to identify the PHI from the extracted text.','B|Use Amazon Textract to extract the text from the PDF reports. Integrate Amazon Comprehend Medical with the existing Lambda function to identify the PHI from the extracted text.','C|Use Amazon Transcribe to read and analyze the PDF reports using the StartTranscriptionJob API operation. Use Amazon CloudWatch Logs to detect protected health information (PHI) content by tracking access logs and security events.','D|Use Amazon Textract with the StartDocumentTextDetection API operation to extract text from PDF reports. Analyze the extracted data with a custom-built PHI detection algorithm within the Lambda function.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Comprehend Medical is a natural language processing service that makes it easy to use machine learning to extract relevant medical information from unstructured text.',why:'Amazon Comprehend Medical uses advanced machine learning models to accurately and quickly identify medical information such as medical conditions and medication and determine their relationship to each other, for instance, medication and dosage. You access Comprehend Medical through a simple API call, no machine learning expertise is required, no complicated rules to write, and no models to train.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon Transcribe to read and analyze the PDF reports using the StartTranscriptionJob API operation. Use Amazon CloudWatch Logs to detect protected health information (PHI) content by tracking access logs and security events is incorrect because Amazon Transcribe is an automatic speech recognition (ASR) service designed primarily to help developers integrate speech-to-text capability to their applications, and not for extracting text from image files or PDFs. Moreover, CloudWatch Logs cannot perform PHI detection directly.',rule:'Amazon Comprehend Medical uses advanced machine learning models to accurately and quickly identify medical information such as medical condi Not Amazon Transcribe.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_63',category:'S3',question:'An online survey startup is collecting real estate data in the United States for several years. The startup already has a total of 5 TB of data stored in an Amazon S3 bucket located in the us-east-1 Region. All real estate data must be shared with a European AWS Managed Service Provider (MSP) Partner which also uses Amazon S3 for storage. Due to budget constraints, the startup must keep its data transfer costs in S3 as low as possible and disable anonymous access. Which solution meets this requirement MOST cost-effectively?',choices:['A|Enable the Requester Pays feature on the Amazon S3 bucket to lower data transfer costs and disable anonymous access','B|Enable Cross-Region Replication(CRR) on the startup’s S3 bucket to automatically copy the S3 content to the partner’s S3 bucket in Europe.','C|Enable cross-account access of the startup’s S3 bucket to allow the data downloads and exclusive access from the partner’s AWS account','D|Enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode to lower data transfer costs and set a Legal Hold for each object to disable anonymous access'],correct:'A',answer:'In general, bucket owners pay for all Amazon S3 storage and data transfer costs that are associated with their bucket. However, you can configure a bucket to be a Requester Pays bucket. With Requester Pays buckets, the requester instead of the bucket owner pays the cost of the request and the data download from the bucket. The bucket owner always pays the cost of storing data.',why:'Typically, you configure buckets to be Requester Pays buckets when you want to share data but not incur charges associated with others accessing the data. For example, you might use Requester Pays buckets when making available large datasets, such as zip code directories, reference data, geospatial information, or web crawling data.',trap:'The option that says: Enable Cross-Region Replication(CRR) on the startup’s S3 bucket to automatically copy the S3 content to the partner’s S3 bucket in Europe is incorrect because CRR incurs data request and transfer fee for inter-region Data Transfer Out (DTO) from your S3 bucket to your destination region. This will effectively increase your data transfer costs instead of lowering it.',rule:'Typically, you configure buckets to be Requester Pays buckets when you want to share data but not incur charges associated with others acces Not Data Transfer Out.',keywords:'S3 owner not pay data transfer → enable Requester Pays. Requesters must authenticate.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_64',category:'IAM',question:'A company is using the AWS Directory Service to integrate their on-premises Microsoft Active Directory (AD) domain with their Amazon EC2 instances via an AD connector. The below identity-based policy is attached to the IAM Identities that use the AWS Directory service: { "Version":"2012-10-17", "Statement":[ { "Sid":"DirectoryTutorialsDojo1234", "Effect":"Allow", "Action":[ "ds:*" ], "Resource":"arn:aws:ds:us-east-1:987654321012:directory/d-1234567890" }, { "Effect":"Allow", "Action":[ "ec2:*" ], "Resource":"*" } ] } Which of the following BEST describes what the above resource policy does?',choices:['A|Allows all AWS Directory Service (ds) calls as long as the resource contains the directory ID: d-1234567890','B|Allows all AWS Directory Service (ds) calls as long as the resource contains the directory ID: DirectoryTutorialsDojo1234','C|Allows all AWS Directory Service (ds) calls as long as the resource contains the directory ID: 987654321012','D|Allows all AWS Directory Service (ds) calls as long as the resource contains the directory name of: DirectoryTutorialsDojo1234'],correct:'A',answer:'The policy allows all ds:* (Directory Service) actions but only on the specific directory resource ARN ending in /d-1234567890. The ec2:* with Resource:* allows all EC2 actions on all resources.',why:'In IAM resource-based policies, the Resource element restricts which specific resource the action applies to. The ARN arn:aws:ds:us-east-1:987654321012:directory/d-1234567890 specifies the exact directory by its ID (d-1234567890). The Sid "DirectoryTutorialsDojo1234" is just a statement identifier label — it has no functional effect on permissions. The account ID 987654321012 is the AWS account, not the directory ID.',trap:'The Sid (Statement ID) is purely a label for documentation purposes — it plays no role in evaluating permissions. The account ID in the ARN (987654321012) identifies the AWS account, not the directory. The resource ID d-1234567890 is what identifies the specific directory.',rule:'IAM Resource ARN = last segment is the actual resource ID. Sid = label only, no functional effect. ds:* applies only to the specific directory ARN specified.',keywords:'Existing on-premises AD + AWS access → AD Connector (proxy, no sync) + IAM Roles.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q4_65',category:'Serverless',question:'A new company policy requires IAM users to change their passwords’ minimum length to 12 characters. After a random inspection, you found out that there are still employees who do not follow the policy. How can you automatically check and evaluate whether the current password policy for an account complies with the company password policy?',choices:['A|Configure AWS Config to trigger an evaluation that will check the compliance for a user’s password periodically.','B|Create a CloudTrail trail. Filter the result by setting the attribute to “Event Name” and lookup value to “ChangePassword”. This easily gives you the list of users who have made changes to their passwords.','C|Create a Scheduled Lambda Function that will run a custom script to check compliance against changes made to the passwords periodically.','D|Create a rule in the Amazon CloudWatch event. Build an event pattern to match events on IAM. Set the event name to “ChangePassword” in the event pattern. Configure SNS to send notifications to you whenever a user has made changes to his password.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Config is a service that enables you to assess, audit, and evaluate the configurations of your AWS resources. Config continuously monitors and records your AWS resource configurations and allows you to automate the evaluation of recorded configurations against desired configurations.',why:'In the scenario given, we can utilize AWS Config to check for compliance on the password policy by configuring the Config rule to check the  IAM_PASSWORD_POLICY on an account. Additionally, because Config integrates with AWS Organizations, we can improve the setup to aggregate compliance information across accounts to a central dashboard.',trap:'Create a CloudTrail trail. Filter the result by setting the attribute to “Event Name” and lookup value to “ChangePassword”. This easily gives you the list of users who have made changes to their passwords is incorrect because this setup will just give you the name of the users who have made changes to their respective passwords. It will not give you the ability to check whether their passwords have met the required minimum length.',rule:'AWS Config to trigger an: correct. Event Name: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 3'},
  {id:'q5_1',category:'Kinesis',question:'A wellness company is currently working on a wearable device that monitors key health metrics such as heart rate, sleep, and steps per day. The device is designed to send data to an Amazon S3 bucket for storage and analysis. On a daily basis, the device produces 1 MB of data. In order to quickly process and summarize this data, the company requires 512 MB of memory and must complete the task within a maximum of 10 seconds. Which solution can fulfill these requirements in the MOST cost-effective manner?',choices:['A|Use AWS Lambda with a Python library for processing.','B|Create an AWS Glue PySpark job to process the data.','C|Use Amazon Data Firehose to send the data from the device to Amazon S3. Process the data on an EC2 instance with at least 512 MB of memory.','D|Store the data in Amazon Redshift and process it with AWS Lambda.'],correct:'A',answer:'With AWS Lambda, you pay only for what you use. You are charged based on the number of requests for your functions and the duration of the time it takes for your code to execute.',why:'Lambda counts a request each time it starts executing in response to an event notification or invoke call, including test invokes from the console. You are charged for the total number of requests across all your functions.',trap:'The option that says: Create an AWS Glue PySpark job to process the data is incorrect. While it\'s a valid solution, it\'s a bit of overkill to use AWS Glue for processing 1 MB of data per day. AWS Glue has a minimum billing duration of 1 minute (Glue version 2.0 and later), which is not cost-effective for processing small amounts of data quickly (in 10 seconds).',rule:'Lambda counts a request each time it starts executing in response to an event notification or invoke call, including test invokes from the console. Lambda charges for duration × memory. No charge when function is not running.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_2',category:'S3',question:'A company needs to use Amazon S3 to store irreproducible financial documents. For their quarterly reporting, the files are required to be retrieved after a period of 3 months. There will be some occasions when a surprise audit will be held, which requires access to the archived data that they need to present immediately. What will you do to satisfy this requirement in a cost-effective way?',choices:['A|Use Amazon S3 Standard','B|Use Amazon S3 Standard - Infrequent Access','C|Use Amazon S3 -Intelligent Tiering','D|Use Amazon Glacier Deep Archive'],correct:'B',answer:'S3 Standard is the correct storage class for irreproducible financial documents accessed quarterly. S3 Standard provides 99.999999999% durability and 99.99% availability. Quarterly access is infrequent but frequent enough that Standard-IA or Glacier would add unnecessary retrieval cost and latency.',why:'Quarterly access (4 times per year) means the data is accessed more than once or twice a year — Glacier classes are inappropriate. S3 Standard has no minimum storage duration, no retrieval fee, and immediate access. S3 Standard-IA charges a retrieval fee per GB and has a 30-day minimum storage duration. For irreproducible documents, durability (11 nines) is paramount.',trap:'S3 Standard-IA would incur a per-GB retrieval fee every quarter — for irreproducible financial documents that must be retrieved regularly, this adds cost without benefit. S3 Intelligent-Tiering charges a monitoring fee per object and is designed for unpredictable access patterns.',rule:'Quarterly access + irreproducible = S3 Standard (no retrieval fee, immediate access, 11 nines durability). Standard-IA = retrieval fee + 30-day minimum. Glacier = hours retrieval time. Standard-IA = immediate retrieval with retrieval fee. Best for surprise audit scenarios.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_3',category:'S3',question:'A company is running a batch job on an EC2 instance inside a private subnet. The instance gathers input data from an S3 bucket in the same region through a NAT Gateway. The company is looking for a solution that will reduce costs without imposing risks on redundancy or availability. Which solution will accomplish this?',choices:['A|Replace the NAT Gateway with a NAT instance hosted on a burstable instance type.','B|Deploy a Transit Gateway to peer connection between the instance and the S3 bucket.','C|Remove the NAT Gateway and use a Gateway VPC endpoint to access the S3 bucket from the instance.','D|Re-assign the NAT Gateway to a lower EC2 instance type.'],correct:'C',answer:'A gateway endpoint is a gateway that you specify in your route table to access Amazon S3 from your VPC over the AWS network. Interface endpoints extend the functionality of gateway endpoints by using private IP addresses to route requests to Amazon S3 from within your VPC, on-premises, or from a different AWS Region. Interface endpoints are compatible with gateway endpoints.',why:'The gateway endpoint route is a prefix list entry (e.g., pl-xxxxxxxx for S3) added to the subnet route table. EC2 instances in that subnet automatically use the endpoint route for S3/DynamoDB traffic without any application changes. The endpoint is regional — it serves all S3 buckets in the region. If you need to restrict access to specific buckets from the VPC, use an endpoint policy. The endpoint is highly available and scales automatically.',trap:'The option that says: Replace the NAT Gateway with a NAT instance hosted on burstable instance type is incorrect. This solution may possibly reduce costs, but the availability and redundancy will be compromised.',rule:'There is no additional charge for using gateway endpoints.',keywords:'S3/DynamoDB private VPC access → Gateway Endpoint (free). Other services → Interface Endpoint (PrivateLink).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_4',category:'S3',question:'A company has 10 TB of infrequently accessed financial data files that would need to be stored in AWS. These data would be accessed infrequently during specific weeks when they are retrieved for auditing purposes. The retrieval time is not strict as long as it does not exceed 24 hours. Which of the following would be a secure, durable, and cost-effective solution for this scenario?',choices:['A|Upload the data to S3 then use a lifecycle policy to transfer data to S3-IA.','B|Upload the data to S3 and set a lifecycle policy to transition data to Glacier after 0 days.','C|Upload the data to Amazon FSx for Windows File Server using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol.','D|Upload the data to S3 then use a lifecycle policy to transfer data to S3 One Zone-IA.'],correct:'B',answer:'Glacier is a cost-effective archival solution for large amounts of data. Bulk retrievals are S3 Glacier’s lowest-cost retrieval option, enabling you to retrieve large amounts, even petabytes, of data inexpensively in a day. Bulk retrievals typically complete within 5 – 12 hours.',why:'Glacier has a management console that you can use to create and delete vaults. However, you cannot directly upload archives to Glacier by using the management console. To upload data such as photos, videos, and other documents, you must either use the AWS CLI or write code to make requests by using either the REST API directly or by using the AWS SDKs.',trap:'Uploading the data to S3 then using a lifecycle policy to transfer data to S3-IA is incorrect because using Glacier would be a more cost-effective solution than using S3-IA. Since the required retrieval period should not exceed more than a day, Glacier would be the best choice.',rule:'However, you cannot directly upload archives to Glacier by using the management console.',keywords:'Auto-move S3 objects = lifecycle policy. Min 30 days before Standard→Standard-IA transition.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_5',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is migrating several Windows-based applications to AWS that require a scalable file system storage for high-performance computing (HPC). The storage service must have full support for the SMB protocol and Windows NTFS, Active Directory (AD) integration, and Distributed File System (DFS). Which of the following is the MOST suitable storage service that the Architect should use to fulfill this scenario?',choices:['A|Amazon FSx for Windows File Server','B|Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive','C|AWS DataSync','D|Amazon FSx for Lustre'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon FSx provides fully managed third-party file systems. Amazon FSx provides you with the native compatibility of third-party file systems with feature sets for workloads such as Windows-based storage, high-performance computing (HPC), machine learning, and electronic design automation (EDA).',why:'For Windows-based applications, Amazon FSx provides fully managed Windows file servers with features and performance optimized for "lift-and-shift" business-critical application workloads including home directories (user shares), media workflows, and ERP applications. It is accessible from Windows and Linux instances via the SMB protocol.',trap:'Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive is incorrect because this service is primarily used as a secure, durable, and extremely low-cost cloud storage for data archiving and long-term backup.',rule:'Amazon FSx provides you with two file systems to choose from: Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for Windows-based applications and Amazon FSx for Lustre for high-performance Linux HPC workloads.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_6',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has a web application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure that they want to migrate to AWS cloud. Your manager has instructed you to ensure that there is no downtime while the migration process is on-going. In order to achieve this, your team decided to divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure. Once the migration is over and the application works with no issues, a full diversion to AWS will be implemented. The company\'s VPC is connected to its on-premises network via an AWS Direct Connect connection. Which of the following are the possible solutions that you can implement to satisfy the above requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use a Network Load balancer with Weighted Target Groups to divert the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure.','B|Use an Application Elastic Load balancer with Weighted Target Groups to divert and proportion the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure.','C|Use Route 53 with Failover routing policy to divert and proportion the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure.','D|Use Route 53 with Weighted routing policy to divert the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure.','E|Use AWS Global Accelerator to divert and proportion the HTTP and HTTPS traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Ensure that the on-premises network has an AnyCast static IP address and is connected to your VPC via a Direct Connect Gateway.'],correct:'D',answer:'Route 53 Weighted routing policy distributes traffic proportionally between the on-premises servers and AWS EC2 instances by assigning a weight to each record set, enabling gradual migration traffic shifting.',why:'Weighted routing assigns a numeric weight to each record. Traffic is distributed proportionally — a record with weight 80 gets 80/(80+20) = 80% of traffic. During migration, you start with high weight on on-premises (e.g., 90%) and gradually shift weight to AWS (increasing to 100%) over time with zero downtime. Both endpoints remain active throughout the migration.',trap:'The option that says: Use a Network Load balancer with Weighted Target Groups to divert the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application. Divert 50% of the traffic to the new application in AWS and the other 50% to the application hosted in their on-premises infrastructure is incorrect because a Network Load balancer doesn\'t have Weighted Target Groups to divert the traffic between the on-premises and AWS-hosted application.',rule:'Gradual migration traffic shifting between on-premises and AWS = Route 53 Weighted routing. Assign weights proportionally and shift over time. ALB/NLB target groups = within a single region only. Weighted routing = across any endpoints globally.',keywords:'AWS DataSync: fast online data transfer from on-premises to AWS. Preserves metadata and permissions.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_7',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a multinational telecommunications company. The IT Manager wants to consolidate their log streams including the access, application, and security logs in one single system. Once consolidated, the company will analyze these logs in real-time based on heuristics. There will be some time in the future where the company will need to validate heuristics, which requires going back to data samples extracted from the last 12 hours. What is the best approach to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|First, set up an Auto Scaling group of EC2 servers then store the logs on Amazon S3 then finally, use EMR to apply heuristics on the logs.','B|First, send all of the log events to Amazon Kinesis then afterwards, develop a client process to apply heuristics on the logs.','C|First, configure Amazon Cloud Trail to receive custom logs and then use EMR to apply heuristics on the logs.','D|First, send all the log events to Amazon SQS then set up an Auto Scaling group of EC2 servers to consume the logs and finally, apply the heuristics.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams is designed for real-time, high-throughput streaming data ingestion. Sending all log events to Kinesis and processing them with a consumer (Lambda or KCL application) provides scalable, real-time log analytics.',why:'Kinesis Data Streams ingests streaming data from multiple producers (log generators) with throughput scaling via shards. Each shard handles 1 MB/s write and 2 MB/s read. A Lambda consumer processes records per batch in near real-time. This is the canonical AWS pattern for real-time log analytics at scale.',trap:'Setting up an Auto Scaling group of EC2 servers and storing logs in S3 first makes the pipeline asynchronous and adds S3 storage costs before analytics. Configuring CloudTrail for custom logs is incorrect — CloudTrail captures AWS API calls, not application logs. Using SQS then ASG adds latency and complexity versus a direct Kinesis stream.',rule:'Real-time log analytics at scale = Kinesis Data Streams → Lambda (or KCL application). CloudTrail = AWS API logs only. SQS = message queue, not streaming analytics.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_8',category:'S3',question:'A leading e-commerce company is in need of a storage solution that can be simultaneously accessed by 1000 Linux servers in multiple availability zones. The servers are hosted in EC2 instances that use a hierarchical directory structure via the NFSv4 protocol. The service should be able to handle the rapidly changing data at scale while still maintaining high performance. It should also be highly durable and highly available whenever the servers will pull data from it, with little need for management. As the Solutions Architect, which of the following services is the most cost-effective choice that you should use to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon S3','B|Amazon EFS','C|Amazon EBS','D|Amazon FSx for Windows File Server'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon S3 is incorrect. Although this provides the same level of high availability and high scalability like EFS, this service is not suitable for storing data that is rapidly changing, just as mentioned in the above explanation. It is still more effective to use EFS as it offers strong consistency and file locking, which the S3 service lacks.',why:'Amazon Web Services (AWS) offers cloud storage services to support a wide range of storage workloads such as EFS, S3, and EBS. You have to understand when you should use Amazon EFS, Amazon S3, and Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) based on the specific workloads. In this scenario, the keywords are rapidly changing data and 1000 Linux servers.',trap:'Amazon EBS is incorrect because an EBS Volume cannot be shared by multiple instances.',rule:'Amazon + S3 = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'S3 replication with SSE-KMS: needs kms:Decrypt on source + kms:GenerateDataKey on destination key.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_9',category:'Serverless',question:'A research institute has developed simulation software that requires significant computational power. Currently, the software runs on a local server with limited resources, taking several hours to complete each simulation. The server has 32 virtual CPUs (vCPUs) and 256 GiB of memory. The institute plans to migrate the software to AWS. Their objective is to speed up the simulations by running them in parallel. As a Solutions Architect, which solution will achieve this goal with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Utilize AWS Batch to manage the execution of the software.','B|Consider using Amazon EC2 Spot Instances to run the simulations.','C|Use Lambda functions to process simulation tasks in parallel.','D|Run the simulations using AWS Fargate.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Batch is a powerful tool for developers, scientists, and engineers who need to run a large number of batch and ML computing jobs. By optimizing compute resources, AWS Batch enables you to focus on analyzing outcomes and resolving issues, rather than worrying about the technical details of running jobs.',why:'With AWS Batch, you can define and submit multiple simulation jobs to be executed concurrently. AWS Batch will take care of distributing the workload across multiple EC2 instances, scaling up or down based on the demand, and managing the execution environment. It provides an easy-to-use interface and automation for managing the simulations, allowing you to focus on the software itself rather than the underlying infrastructure.',trap:'The option that says: Run the simulations using AWS Fargate is incorrect. For complex jobs, this approach might not be enough because of the limited processing power that can be allocated to a Fargate task. Moreover, AWS Fargate doesn\'t have its own system to manage tasks and timing, so you would need to use another system for this, which creates more work.',rule:'Migration → AWS Batch to manage the. Not AWS Fargate.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_10',category:'Networking',question:'A company plans to implement a hybrid architecture. A dedicated connection needs to be created from the Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) to the on-premises network. This connection must provide high bandwidth throughput and a more consistent network experience than Internet-based solutions. Which of the following can be used to create a private connection between the VPC and the company\'s on-premises network?',choices:['A|AWS Direct Connect','B|Transit VPC','C|Transit Gateway with equal-cost multipath routing (ECMP)','D|AWS Site-to-Site VPN'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Direct Connect links your internal network to an AWS Direct Connect location over a standard Ethernet fiber-optic cable. One end of the cable is connected to your router, the other to an AWS Direct Connect router.',why:'With this connection, you can create virtual interfaces directly to public AWS services (for example, to Amazon S3) or to Amazon VPC, bypassing internet service providers in your network path. An AWS Direct Connect location provides access to AWS in the region with which it is associated.',trap:'Transit VPC is incorrect because this in itself is not enough to integrate your on-premises network to your VPC. You have to either use a VPN or a Direct Connect connection. A transit VPC is primarily used to connect multiple VPCs and remote networks in order to create a global network transit center and not for establishing a dedicated connection to your on-premises network.',rule:'Dedicated network → AWS Direct Connect. Not Direct Connect.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_11',category:'CloudWatch',question:'An application is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances. To improve the monitoring process, you have to configure the current capacity to increase or decrease based on a set of scaling adjustments. This should be done by specifying the scaling metrics and threshold values for the CloudWatch alarms that trigger the scaling process. Which of the following is the most suitable type of scaling policy that you should use?',choices:['A|Target tracking scaling','B|Step scaling','C|Simple scaling','D|Scheduled Scaling'],correct:'A',answer:'Step Scaling is configured with a CloudWatch alarm and defines step adjustments — different scaling amounts based on the size of the alarm breach. This allows the ASG to respond proportionally to the severity of the metric breach.',why:'Step scaling uses CloudWatch alarms with defined thresholds. You configure multiple step adjustments: small breach → add 1 instance, medium breach → add 2, large breach → add 4. Unlike simple scaling (which has a cooldown wait), step scaling continues to evaluate and scale while instances are being launched. This provides more responsive and proportional scaling than simple scaling.',trap:'Target tracking scaling adjusts capacity to maintain a target metric value (e.g., 50% CPU) — it does not use step adjustments and is better for simpler scaling needs. Simple scaling requires waiting for a cooldown period before responding to additional alarms. Scheduled scaling is for predictable traffic patterns, not dynamic response to load.',rule:'Custom metric-triggered proportional scaling = Step Scaling. CloudWatch alarm + step adjustments (scale differently based on breach magnitude). No cooldown wait between steps. Target tracking = simplest, maintains target metric value (e.g., 50% CPU). Scheduled = known patterns.',keywords:'Scale proportionally to alarm breach size → Step Scaling. Different steps for small/medium/large breach.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_12',category:'S3',question:'An organization plans to run an application in a dedicated physical server that doesn’t use virtualization. The application data will be stored in a storage solution that uses an NFS protocol. To prevent data loss, you need to use a durable cloud storage service to store a copy of your data. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to meet the requirement?',choices:['A|Use an AWS Storage Gateway hardware appliance for your compute resources. Configure Volume Gateway to store the application data and backup data.','B|Use an AWS Storage Gateway hardware appliance for your compute resources. Configure File Gateway to store the application data and create an Amazon S3 bucket to store a backup of your data.','C|Use an AWS Storage Gateway hardware appliance for your compute resources. Configure Volume Gateway to store the application data and create an Amazon S3 bucket to store a backup of your data.','D|Use AWS Storage Gateway with a gateway VM appliance for your compute resources. Configure File Gateway to store the application data and backup data.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Storage Gateway is a hybrid cloud storage service that gives you on-premises access to virtually unlimited cloud storage by linking it to S3. Storage Gateway provides 3 types of storage solutions for your on-premises applications: file, volume, and tape gateways.',why:'Since the company needs to run a dedicated physical appliance, you can use an AWS Storage Gateway Hardware Appliance. It comes pre-loaded with Storage Gateway software and provides all the required resources to create a file gateway. A file gateway can be configured to store and retrieve objects in Amazon S3 using the protocols NFS and SMB.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS Storage Gateway with a gateway VM appliance for your compute resources. Configure File Gateway to store the application data and backup data is incorrect because as per the scenario, the company needs to use an on-premises hardware appliance and not just a Virtual Machine (VM).',rule:'Dedicated network → AWS Storage Gateway hard, Amazon S3 bucket to store a backup of. Not AWS Storage.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_13',category:'Storage',question:'An e-commerce application is using a fanout messaging pattern for its order management system. For every order, it sends an Amazon SNS message to an SNS topic, and the message is replicated and pushed to multiple Amazon SQS queues for parallel asynchronous processing. A Spot EC2 instance retrieves the message from each SQS queue and processes the message. There was an incident that while an EC2 instance is currently processing a message, the instance was abruptly terminated, and the processing was not completed in time. In this scenario, what happens to the SQS message?',choices:['A|When the message visibility timeout expires, the message becomes available for processing by other EC2 instances','B|The message will automatically be assigned to the same EC2 instance when it comes back online within or after the visibility timeout.','C|The message is deleted and becomes duplicated in the SQS when the EC2 instance comes online.','D|The message will be sent to a Dead Letter Queue in AWS DataSync.'],correct:'A',answer:'Immediately after the message is received, it remains in the queue. To prevent other consumers from processing the message again, Amazon SQS sets a visibility timeout, a period of time during which Amazon SQS prevents other consumers from receiving and processing the message. The default visibility timeout for a message is 30 seconds. The maximum is 12 hours.',why:'A "fanout" pattern is when an Amazon SNS message is sent to a topic and then replicated and pushed to multiple Amazon SQS queues, HTTP endpoints, or email addresses. This allows for parallel asynchronous processing. For example, you could develop an application that sends an Amazon SNS message to a topic whenever an order is placed for a product.',trap:'The option that says: The message will automatically be assigned to the same EC2 instance when it comes back online within or after the visibility timeout is incorrect because the message will not be automatically assigned to the same EC2 instance once it is abruptly terminated. When the message visibility timeout expires, the message becomes available for processing by other EC2 instances.',rule:'EC2 = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'EFA = OS-bypass networking for HPC/ML. Lower latency than ENA. Not for general EC2.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_14',category:'Serverless',question:'A healthcare company manages patient data using a distributed system. The organization utilizes a microservice-based serverless application to handle various aspects of patient care. Data has to be retrieved and written from multiple Amazon DynamoDB tables. The primary goal is to enable efficient retrieval and writing of data without impacting the baseline performance of the application as well as ensuring seamless access to patient information for healthcare professionals. Which of the following is the MOST operationally efficient solution?',choices:['A|Utilize AWS AppSync pipeline resolvers','B|Launched AWS Lambda functions with an edge-optimized Amazon API Gateway','C|Set up DynamoDB connector for Amazon Athena Federated Query','D|Use CloudFront functions'],correct:'A',answer:'AppSync pipeline resolvers offer an elegant server-side solution to address the common challenge faced in web applications—aggregating data from multiple database tables.',why:'AWS AppSync is a managed service that makes it easy to build scalable APIs that connect applications to data. Developers use AppSync every day to build GraphQL APIs that interact with data sources like Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, and HTTP APIs. With AppSync, developers can write their resolvers using JavaScript, and run their code on AppSync’s APPSYNC_JS runtime.',trap:'The option that says: Launched AWS Lambda functions with an edge-optimized Amazon API Gateway is incorrect because an edge-optimized API endpoint in API Gateway just leverages a CloudFront distribution to facilitate client access to improve connection time for geographically diverse clients. The solution is more on improving the connection time for the end-users instead of providing access to multiple DynamoDB tables as data sources.',rule:'AWS AppSync is a managed service that makes it easy to build scalable APIs that connect applications to data.',keywords:'Lambda + RDS Proxy: connection pooling for serverless. Reduces database connection exhaustion.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_15',category:'S3',question:'A financial company wants to store its data in Amazon S3 while also keeping frequently accessed data locally on its on-premises server. The company does not have the option to extend its on-premises storage, so it is looking for a durable and scalable storage service to use in AWS. What is the best solution for this scenario?',choices:['A|Use a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances with Amazon EBS volumes to store the commonly used data.','B|Use Amazon ElastiCache with a lazy loading (cache-aside) pattern while storing the primary data in S3.','C|Use AWS Storage Gateway - Cached Volumes.','D|Use Amazon Glacier.'],correct:'C',answer:'By using Cached volumes, you store your data in Amazon S3 and retain a copy of frequently accessed data subsets locally in your on-premises network. Cached volumes offer substantial cost savings on primary storage and minimize the need to scale your storage on-premises. You also retain low-latency access to your frequently accessed data.',why:'Cached volumes are designed for hybrid storage environments where organizations want to extend their local infrastructure to the cloud without expanding their on-premises storage capacity. Since the primary data resides in Amazon S3, the company benefits from highly durable and scalable cloud storage while the local cache ensures fast access to frequently used datasets.',trap:'The option that says: Use a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances with Amazon EBS volumes to store the commonly used data is incorrect because an EC2 instance is simply not a storage service, and it does not provide the required durability and scalability.',rule:'Cached volumes: primary data in S3, frequently accessed subset cached on-premises. Extends local storage to cloud without expanding on-premises hardware. Good for organizations that want to extend their local infrastructure to the cloud without giving up low-latency access to frequently used data.',keywords:'Storage Gateway Cached Volume: primary data in S3, frequently-accessed data cached on-premises.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_16',category:'Storage',question:'A startup needs to use a shared file system for its .NET web application running on an Amazon EC2 Windows instance. The file system must provide a high level of throughput and IOPS that can also be integrated with Microsoft Active Directory. Which is the MOST suitable service that you should use to achieve this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon EBS Provisioned IOPS SSD volumes','B|Amazon FSx for Windows File Server','C|Amazon Elastic File System','D|AWS Storage Gateway - File Gateway'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon FSx for Windows File Server provides fully managed, highly reliable, and scalable file storage accessible over the industry-standard Service Message Block (SMB) protocol. It is built on Windows Server, delivering a wide range of administrative features such as user quotas, end-user file restore, and Microsoft Active Directory (AD) integration.',why:'Amazon FSx supports the use of Microsoft’s Distributed File System (DFS) Namespaces to scale-out performance across multiple file systems in the same namespace up to tens of Gbps and millions of IOPS.',trap:'Amazon EBS Provisioned IOPS SSD volumes is incorrect because this is just a block storage volume and not a full-fledged file system. Amazon EBS is primarily used as persistent block storage for EC2 instances.',rule:'use a shared file system for its → Amazon FSx, Windows File Server.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_17',category:'Serverless',question:'A company needs to accelerate the development of its GraphQL APIs for its new customer service portal. The solution must be serverless to lower the monthly operating cost of the business. Their GraphQL APIs must be accessible via HTTPS and have a custom domain. What solution should the Solutions Architect implement to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Launch an AWS Elastic Beanstalk environment and use Amazon Route 53 for the custom domain. Configure Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) in the Route 53 hosted zone to enable HTTPS communication.','B|Host the application in the VMware Cloud on AWS service. Associate a custom domain to the GraphSQL APIs via the AWS Directory Service for Microsoft Active Directory and provide multiple domain controllers to enable HTTPS communication.','C|Deploy the GraphQL APIs as Kubernetes pods to AWS Fargate and AWS Outposts using Amazon EKS Anywhere for deployment. Create a custom domain using Amazon CloudFront and enable the Origin Shield feature to allow HTTPS communication to the GraphQL APIs.','D|Develop the application using the AWS AppSync service and use its built-in custom domain feature. Associate an SSL certificate to the AWS AppSync API using the AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) service to enable HTTPS communication.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS AppSync is a managed GraphQL service that can serve as the backend for GraphQL APIs with built-in custom domain name support, data source connectors (DynamoDB, Lambda, RDS, HTTP), and real-time subscriptions.',why:'AppSync is purpose-built for GraphQL APIs. It provides built-in integration with DynamoDB, Lambda, RDS, OpenSearch, and HTTP endpoints as data sources. It handles real-time subscriptions via WebSockets and supports offline data synchronization via Amplify. Custom domain names are configured directly in the AppSync console — no separate infrastructure needed.',trap:'Elastic Beanstalk deploys application servers but provides no built-in GraphQL support. VMware Cloud on AWS is for lifting VMware workloads to AWS, not building new serverless APIs. Deploying GraphQL as Kubernetes pods to Fargate and Outposts is over-engineered and adds significant infrastructure management for what is a managed service problem.',rule:'Managed GraphQL API with custom domain = AWS AppSync. Built-in DynamoDB/Lambda/RDS connectors. Real-time subscriptions. No servers to manage. Elastic Beanstalk = application server platform, not a real-time data sync service. AppSync = GraphQL API.',keywords:'GraphQL API with real-time subscriptions → AWS AppSync.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_18',category:'EC2',question:'The start-up company that you are working for has a batch job application that is currently hosted on an EC2 instance. It is set to process messages from a queue created in SQS with default settings. You configured the application to process the messages once a week. After 2 weeks, you noticed that not all messages are being processed by the application. What is the root cause of this issue?',choices:['A|The batch job application is configured to long polling.','B|Amazon SQS has automatically deleted the messages that have been in a queue for more than the maximum message retention period.','C|The SQS queue is set to short-polling.','D|Missing permissions in SQS.'],correct:'B',answer:'SQS long polling reduces empty receives by making the ReceiveMessage API call wait up to 20 seconds for messages to arrive. Set ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to a value between 1-20 seconds to enable long polling.',why:'By default, SQS uses short polling — the ReceiveMessage call returns immediately, even if no messages are available, resulting in empty responses that still count against API call costs. Long polling waits up to 20 seconds for at least one message before returning. This reduces the number of empty responses (and thus API calls/costs) and decreases latency for message delivery.',trap:'Short polling (ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds=0) returns immediately regardless of whether messages are available — this is the cause of the excessive API calls described. Setting the WaitTime to 0 explicitly sets short polling.',rule:'SQS long polling = ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds > 0 (up to 20 seconds). Reduces empty receives and API costs. Short polling = WaitTimeSeconds = 0 (returns immediately). Visibility timeout = hides message from other consumers during processing. Set > max processing time.',keywords:'SQS default retention = 4 days. Maximum = 14 days. Messages auto-deleted after retention period.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_19',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A Solutions Architect joined a large tech company with an existing Amazon VPC. When reviewing the Auto Scaling events, the Architect noticed that their web application is scaling up and down multiple times within the hour. What design change could the Architect make to optimize cost while preserving elasticity?',choices:['A|Change the cooldown period of the Auto Scaling group and set the CloudWatch metric to a higher threshold','B|Upgrade the instance type in the launch template.','C|Increase the base number of Auto Scaling instances for the Auto Scaling group','D|Add provisioned IOPS to the instances'],correct:'A',answer:'Since the application is scaling up and down multiple times within the hour, the issue lies in the cooldown period of the Auto Scaling group.',why:'The cooldown period is a configurable setting for your Auto Scaling group that helps to ensure that it doesn\'t launch or terminate additional instances before the previous scaling activity takes effect. After the Auto Scaling group dynamically scales using a simple scaling policy, it waits for the cooldown period to complete before resuming scaling activities.',trap:'The option that says: Upgrade the instance type in the launch template is incorrect because upgrading the instance type could lead to higher costs, which contradicts the goal of optimizing costs. Moreover, it doesn\'t address the issue of the application scaling up and down multiple times within the hour.',rule:'ASG scaling in/out multiple times per hour = cooldown period too short. Cooldown lets the previous scale action take effect before the next triggers. Increase cooldown or use target tracking scaling which automatically adjusts the cooldown period.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_20',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has multiple research departments that have deployed several resources to the AWS cloud. Each department is free to provision resources as needed. To ensure normal operations, the company wants to track its AWS resource usage so that it does not reach the AWS service quotas unexpectedly. Which combination of actions should the Solutions Architect implement to meet the company requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Create an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic and configure it as a target for notifications.','B|Capture the events using Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) and use an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic as the target for notifications.','C|Query the AWS Trusted Advisor Service Limits check every 24 hours by calling the DescribeTrustedAdvisorChecks API operation. Ensure that your AWS account has a Developer support plan.','D|Write an AWS Lambda function that refreshes the AWS Trusted Advisor Service Limits checks and set it to run every 24 hours.','E|Utilize the AWS managed rule on AWS Config to monitor AWS resource service quotas. Schedule this checking using an AWS Lambda function.'],correct:'BDE',answer:'To monitor and respond to AWS service quota approaching limits: (B) query Trusted Advisor Service Limits check every 24 hours (Trusted Advisor refreshes quotas on a schedule), and (E) utilize AWS Config managed rules to monitor AWS resource service quotas (Config rules evaluate quota usage continuously).',why:'AWS Trusted Advisor checks service limits and flags resources approaching limits. It refreshes its data on a schedule. AWS Config provides managed rules that can evaluate whether resource counts are within quota limits. Both provide automated monitoring without custom code. EventBridge and Lambda approaches would work but add operational overhead.',trap:'Amazon SNS alone cannot query service quotas — it is a notification service. Creating a custom Lambda function that refreshes Trusted Advisor checks requires extra code and scheduling. A CloudWatch Events rule that invokes a custom script adds operational overhead when managed services already provide this capability.',rule:'Monitor service quotas = Trusted Advisor (Service Limits check, refreshed periodically) + AWS Config managed rules (continuous evaluation). Lambda/custom scripts = higher operational overhead. Use managed rules for standard compliance checks.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_21',category:'Route 53',question:'A company plans to use Route 53 instead of an ELB to load balance the incoming request to the web application. The system is deployed to two EC2 instances to which the traffic needs to be distributed. You want to set a specific percentage of traffic to go to each instance. Which routing policy would you use?',choices:['A|Latency','B|Failover','C|Weighted','D|Geolocation'],correct:'C',answer:'Route 53 Weighted routing policy distributes DNS queries proportionally across multiple resources. To load balance across multiple ALBs using Route 53, create Weighted routing records pointing to each ALB with equal weights.',why:'Route 53 Weighted routing assigns a numeric weight to each record. Traffic is directed to each endpoint in proportion to its weight. Equal weights (e.g., 10 and 10) split traffic 50/50. This is the only Route 53 policy that distributes traffic across multiple endpoints by proportion — suitable for load balancing across multiple ALBs in different AZs or regions.',trap:'Latency routing sends users to the lowest-latency region — useful for multi-region but not for equal load distribution. Failover routing implements primary/standby — one record is active at a time. Geolocation routing routes based on user geography — not proportional distribution.',rule:'Load balance across multiple Route 53 endpoints = Weighted routing with equal weights. Latency = lowest-latency region. Failover = primary/standby. Geolocation = by geography.',keywords:'Route to lowest-latency region → Latency Routing. Not geography-based.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_22',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A healthcare company stores sensitive patient health records in their on-premises storage systems. These records must be kept indefinitely and protected from any type of modifications once they are stored. Compliance regulations mandate that the records must have granular access control and each data access must be audited at all levels. Currently, there are millions of obsolete records that are not accessed by their web application, and their on-premises storage is quickly running out of space. The Solutions Architect must design a solution to immediately move existing records to AWS and support the ever-growing number of new health records. Which of the following is the most suitable solution that the Solutions Architect should implement to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Set up AWS Storage Gateway to move the existing health records from the on-premises network to the AWS Cloud. Launch a new Amazon S3 bucket to store existing and new records. Enable AWS CloudTrail with Management Events and Amazon S3 Object Lock in the bucket.','B|Set up AWS DataSync to move the existing health records from the on-premises network to the AWS Cloud. Launch a new Amazon S3 bucket to store existing and new records. Enable AWS CloudTrail with Data Events and Amazon S3 Object Lock in the bucket.','C|Set up AWS Storage Gateway to move the existing health records from the on-premises network to the AWS Cloud. Launch an Amazon EBS-backed EC2 instance to store both the existing and new records. Enable Amazon S3 server access logging and S3 Object Lock in the bucket.','D|Set up AWS DataSync to move the existing health records from the on-premises network to the AWS Cloud. Launch a new Amazon S3 bucket to store existing and new records. Enable AWS CloudTrail with Management Events and Amazon S3 Object Lock in the bucket.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Storage Gateway is a set of hybrid cloud services that gives you on-premises access to virtually unlimited cloud storage. Customers use Storage Gateway to integrate AWS Cloud storage with existing on-site workloads so they can simplify storage management and reduce costs for key hybrid cloud storage use cases.',why:'AWS DataSync is an online data transfer service that simplifies, automates, and accelerates moving data between on-premises storage systems and AWS Storage services, as well as between AWS Storage services. You can use DataSync to migrate active datasets to AWS, archive data to free up on-premises storage capacity, replicate data to AWS for business continuity, or transfer data to the cloud for analysis and processing.',trap:'The option that says: Set up AWS Storage Gateway to move the existing health records from the on-premises network to the AWS Cloud. Launch a new Amazon S3 bucket to store existing and new records. Enable AWS CloudTrail with Management Events and Amazon S3 Object Lock in the bucket is incorrect. The requirement explicitly says that the Solutions Architect must immediately move the existing records to AWS and not integrate or replicate the data. Using AWS DataSync is a more suitable service to use here since the primary objective is to migrate or move data. You also have to use Data Events here and not Management Events in CloudTrail, to properly track all the data access and changes to your objects.',rule:'AWS DataSync is an online data transfer service that simplifies, automates, and accelerates moving data between on-premises storage systems and cloud storage services. Supports NFS, SMB, HDFS. 10x faster than open-source tools.',keywords:'S3 WORM / immutable = Object Lock. Compliance mode = root cannot override. Needs versioning.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_23',category:'Networking',question:'A company has multiple AWS Site-to-Site VPN connections placed between their VPCs and their remote network. During peak hours, many employees are experiencing slow connectivity issues, which limits their productivity. The company has asked a solutions architect to scale the throughput of the VPN connections. Which solution should the architect carry out?',choices:['A|Associate the VPCs to an Equal Cost Multipath Routing (ECMR)-enabled transit gateway and attach additional VPN tunnels.','B|Add more virtual private gateways to a VPC and enable Equal Cost Multipath Routing (ECMR) to get higher VPN bandwidth.','C|Modify the VPN configuration by increasing the number of tunnels to scale the throughput.','D|Re-route some of the VPN connections to a secondary customer gateway device on the remote network’s end.'],correct:'A',answer:'With AWS Transit Gateway, you can simplify the connectivity between multiple VPCs and also connect to any VPC attached to AWS Transit Gateway with a single VPN connection.',why:'AWS Transit Gateway also enables you to scale the IPsec VPN throughput with equal-cost multi-path (ECMP) routing support over multiple VPN tunnels. A single VPN tunnel still has a maximum throughput of 1.25 Gbps. If you establish multiple VPN tunnels to an ECMP-enabled transit gateway, it can scale beyond the default limit of 1.25 Gbps.',trap:'The option that says: Add more virtual private gateways to a VPC and enable Equal Cost Multipath Routing (ECMR) to get higher VPN bandwidth is incorrect because a VPC can only have a single virtual private gateway attached to it one at a time. Also, there is no option to enable ECMR in a virtual private gateway.',rule:'AWS Transit Gateway also enables you to scale the IPsec VPN throughput with equal-cost multi-path (ECMP) routing support over multiple VPN tunnels. ECMP distributes traffic across multiple tunnels increasing effective bandwidth.',keywords:'VPN CloudHub: hub-and-spoke VPN between on-premises sites through single Virtual Private Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_24',category:'EC2',question:'A company has a web-based ticketing service that utilizes Amazon SQS and a fleet of EC2 instances. The EC2 instances that consume messages from the SQS queue are configured to poll the queue as often as possible to keep end-to-end throughput as high as possible. The Solutions Architect noticed that polling the queue in tight loops is using unnecessary CPU cycles, resulting in increased operational costs due to empty responses. In this scenario, what should the Solutions Architect do to make the system more cost-effective?',choices:['A|Configure Amazon SQS to use long polling by setting the ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to zero.','B|Configure Amazon SQS to use long polling by setting the ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to a number greater than zero.','C|Configure Amazon SQS to use short polling by setting the ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to a number greater than zero.','D|Configure Amazon SQS to use short polling by setting the ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to zero.'],correct:'A',answer:'SQS long polling reduces empty API calls by keeping the ReceiveMessage connection open for up to 20 seconds. Set ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to 20 at the queue level to enable long polling.',why:'Long polling makes the ReceiveMessage call wait up to the configured wait time before returning an empty response if no messages arrive. This reduces the number of empty responses that the application must handle and lowers SQS API call costs. The ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds attribute on the SQS queue (1-20 seconds) enables long polling. A value of 0 enables short polling (returns immediately).',trap:'Setting ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds to 0 enables short polling — the default behavior that generates excess empty API responses, which is the problem being solved. MaxNumberOfMessages controls how many messages are returned per API call (up to 10), not the polling behavior.',rule:'SQS long polling = ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds > 0 on queue. 20 seconds = maximum wait. Reduces empty receives. WaitTimeSeconds=0 = short polling (the problem). MaxNumberOfMessages = max batch size (up to 10). Long polling reduces cost by reducing empty receive calls.',keywords:'SQS long polling: ReceiveMessageWaitTimeSeconds > 0 (up to 20s). Reduces empty responses, lowers cost.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_25',category:'S3',question:'A company deployed a web application that stores static assets in an Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) bucket. The Solutions Architect expects the S3 bucket to immediately receive over 2000 PUT requests and 3500 GET requests per second at peak hour. What should the Solutions Architect do to ensure optimal performance?',choices:['A|Use Byte-Range Fetches to retrieve multiple ranges of an object data per GET request.','B|Add a random prefix to the key names.','C|Do nothing. Amazon S3 will automatically manage performance at this scale.','D|Use a predictable naming scheme in the key names such as sequential numbers or date time sequences.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon S3 now provides increased performance to support at least 3,500 requests per second to add data and 5,500 requests per second to retrieve data, which can save significant processing time for no additional charge. Each S3 prefix can support these request rates, making it simple to increase performance significantly.',why:'Applications running on Amazon S3 today will enjoy this performance improvement with no changes, and customers building new applications on S3 do not have to make any application customizations to achieve this performance. Amazon S3\'s support for parallel requests means you can scale your S3 performance by the factor of your compute cluster without making any customizations to your application.',trap:'Using a predictable naming scheme in the key names such as sequential numbers or date time sequences is incorrect because Amazon S3 already maintains an index of object key names in each AWS region. S3 stores key names in alphabetical order. The key name dictates which partition the key is stored in. Using a sequential prefix increases the likelihood that Amazon S3 will target a specific partition for a large number of your keys, overwhelming the I/O capacity of the partition.',rule:'Use Byte-Range Fetches to retrieve multiple ranges of an object data per GET request.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_26',category:'EC2',question:'A company is planning to launch a High Performance Computing (HPC) cluster in AWS that does Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) simulations. The solution should scale-out their simulation jobs to experiment with more tunable parameters for faster and more accurate results. The cluster is composed of Windows servers hosted on t3a.medium EC2 instances. As the Solutions Architect, you should ensure that the architecture provides higher bandwidth, higher packet per second (PPS) performance, and consistently lower inter-instance latencies. Which is the MOST suitable and cost-effective solution that the Architect should implement to achieve the above requirements?',choices:['A|Enable Enhanced Networking with Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) on the Windows EC2 Instances.','B|Enable Enhanced Networking with Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) on the Windows EC2 Instances.','C|Enable Enhanced Networking with Intel 82599 Virtual Function (VF) interface on the Windows EC2 Instances.','D|Use AWS ParallelCluster to deploy and manage the HPC cluster to provide higher bandwidth, higher packet per second (PPS) performance, and lower inter-instance latencies.'],correct:'B',answer:'Enhanced networking uses single root I/O virtualization (SR-IOV) to provide high-performance networking capabilities on supported instance types. SR-IOV is a method of device virtualization that provides higher I/O performance and lower CPU utilization when compared to traditional virtualized network interfaces.',why:'Amazon EC2 provides enhanced networking capabilities through the Elastic Network Adapter (ENA). It supports network speeds of up to 100 Gbps for supported instance types. Elastic Network Adapters (ENAs) provide traditional IP networking features that are required to support VPC networking.',trap:'Enabling Enhanced Networking with Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) on the Windows EC2 Instances is incorrect because the OS-bypass capabilities of the Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) are not supported on Windows instances. Although you can attach EFA to your Windows instances, this will just act as a regular Elastic Network Adapter without the added EFA capabilities. Moreover, it doesn\'t support the t3a.medium instance type that is being used in the HPC cluster.',rule:'Amazon EC2 provides enhanced networking capabilities through the Elastic Network Adapter (ENA). Not Elastic Fabric Adapter.',keywords:'HPC low-latency inter-instance networking → Cluster Placement Group (same rack).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_27',category:'EC2',question:'A company has several microservices that send messages to an Amazon SQS queue and a backend application that poll the queue to process the messages. The company also has a Service Level Agreement (SLA) which defines the acceptable amount of time that can elapse from the point when the messages are received until a response is sent. The backend operations are I/O-intensive as the number of messages is constantly growing, causing the company to miss its SLA. The Solutions Architect must implement a new architecture that improves the application\'s processing time and load management. Which of the following is the MOST effective solution that can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Create an AMI of the backend application\'s EC2 instance. Use the image to set up an Auto Scaling group and configure a target tracking scaling policy based on the CPUUtilization metric with a target value of 80%.','B|Create an AMI of the backend application\'s EC2 instance and replace it with a larger instance size.','C|Create an AMI of the backend application\'s EC2 instance. Use the image to set up an Auto Scaling group and configure a target tracking scaling policy based on the ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage metric.','D|Create an AMI of the backend application\'s EC2 instance and launch it to a cluster placement group.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS) is a fully managed message queuing service that enables you to decouple and scale microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications. SQS eliminates the complexity and overhead associated with managing and operating message-oriented middleware and empowers developers to focus on differentiating work.',why:'The ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage metric is useful when applications have time-sensitive messages and you need to ensure that messages are processed within a specific time period. You can use this metric to set Amazon CloudWatch alarms that issue alerts when messages remain in the queue for extended periods of time. You can also use alerts to take action, such as increasing the number of consumers to process messages more quickly.',trap:'The option that says: Create an AMI of the backend application\'s EC2 instance and replace it with a larger instance size is incorrect because replacing the instance with a large size won\'t be enough to dynamically handle workloads at any level. You need to implement an Auto Scaling group to automatically adjust the capacity of your computing resources.',rule:'EC2: correct. Auto Scaling: incorrect for this scenario.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_28',category:'Database',question:'In a startup company you are working for, you are asked to design a web application that requires a NoSQL database that has no limit on the storage size for a given table. The startup is still new in the market and it has very limited human resources who can take care of the database infrastructure. Which is the most suitable service that you can implement that provides a fully managed, scalable and highly available NoSQL service?',choices:['A|DynamoDB','B|Amazon Neptune','C|Amazon Aurora','D|SimpleDB'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon DynamoDB is a fast and flexible NoSQL database service for all applications that need consistent, single-digit millisecond latency at any scale. It is a fully managed cloud database and supports both document and key-value store models.',why:'The term "fully managed" means that Amazon will manage the underlying infrastructure of the service hence, you don\'t need an additional human resource to support or maintain the service. Therefore, Amazon DynamoDB is the right answer. Remember that Amazon RDS is a managed service but not "fully managed" as you still have the option to maintain and configure the underlying server of the database.',trap:'Amazon Neptune is incorrect because this is primarily used as a graph database.',rule:'DynamoDB = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_29',category:'Networking',question:'A company plans to design a highly available architecture in AWS. They have two target groups with three EC2 instances each, which are added to an Application Load Balancer. In the security group of the EC2 instance, you have verified that port 80 for HTTP is allowed. However, the instances are still showing out of service from the load balancer. What could be the root cause of this issue?',choices:['A|The instances are using the wrong AMI.','B|The health check configuration is not properly defined.','C|The wrong instance type was used for the EC2 instance.','D|The wrong subnet was used in your VPC'],correct:'B',answer:'ALB sticky sessions (session affinity) bind a user session to a specific target using a cookie. However, if some instances have stale state cached, turning sticky sessions OFF ensures the stateless app routes requests to any healthy target, eliminating session imbalance.',why:'Sticky sessions use a duration-based or application-based cookie to route a client to the same target for the session duration. For truly stateless applications, sticky sessions are unnecessary and can cause load imbalance if one instance gets "hot." Disabling sticky sessions allows the ALB to use its round-robin or least-connections algorithm to distribute traffic evenly across all healthy targets.',trap:'A Gateway Load Balancer is for deploying third-party network appliances (firewalls, IDS/IPS) — it is not a replacement for an ALB managing web application routing. Terminating a specific EC2 instance is a disruptive non-solution. Modifying health check intervals changes detection speed but not load distribution.',rule:'Stateless app with uneven load on ALB = disable sticky sessions (session affinity). Sticky sessions = same user goes to same instance. For stateless apps, disable it for even distribution. Use session management service (ElastiCache/DynamoDB) for stateful apps instead.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_30',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has an application hosted in an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer. There are several occasions where some instances are automatically terminated after failing the HTTPS health checks in the ALB and then purges all the ephemeral logs stored in the instance. A Solutions Architect must implement a solution that collects all of the application and server logs effectively. She should be able to perform a root cause analysis based on the logs, even if the Auto Scaling group immediately terminated the instance. What is the EASIEST way for the Architect to automate the log collection from the Amazon EC2 instances?',choices:['A|Add a lifecycle hook to your Auto Scaling group to move instances in the Terminating state to the Pending:Wait state to delay the termination of the unhealthy Amazon EC2 instances. Configure a CloudWatch Events rule for the EC2 Instance-terminate Lifecycle Action Auto Scaling Event with an associated Lambda function. Set up an AWS Systems Manager Automation script that collects and uploads the application logs from the instance to a CloudWatch Logs group. Configure the solution to only resume the instance termination once all the logs were successfully sent.``','B|Add a lifecycle hook to your Auto Scaling group to move instances in the Terminating state to the Terminating:Wait state to delay the termination of the unhealthy Amazon EC2 instances. Set up AWS Step Functions to collect the application logs and send them to a CloudWatch Log group. Configure the solution to resume the instance termination as soon as all the logs were successfully sent to CloudWatch Logs.','C|Add a lifecycle hook to your Auto Scaling group to move instances in the Terminating state to the Terminating:Wait state to delay the termination of unhealthy Amazon EC2 instances. Configure a CloudWatch Events rule for the EC2 Instance-terminate Lifecycle Action Auto Scaling Event with an associated Lambda function. Trigger the CloudWatch agent to push the application logs and then resume the instance termination once all the logs are sent to CloudWatch Logs.','D|Add a lifecycle hook to your Auto Scaling group to move instances in the Terminating state to the Terminating:Wait state to delay the termination of the unhealthy Amazon EC2 instances. Configure a CloudWatch Events rule for the EC2 Instance Terminate Successful Auto Scaling Event with an associated Lambda function. Set up the AWS Systems Manager Run Command service to run a script that collects and uploads the application logs from the instance to a CloudWatch Logs group. Resume the instance termination once all the logs are sent.'],correct:'A',answer:'The EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group have a path, or lifecycle, that differs from that of other EC2 instances. The lifecycle starts when the Auto Scaling group launches an instance and puts it into service. The lifecycle ends when you terminate the instance, or the Auto Scaling group takes the instance out of service and terminates it.',why:'Lifecycle hooks put instances into a wait state (Pending:Wait for launch, Terminating:Wait for termination) for up to 2 hours (configurable). During this window you can run initialization scripts (install agents, warm caches) or drain connections before termination. The instance remains paused until your process sends CompleteLifecycleAction (continue or abandon) or the heartbeat timeout expires. EventBridge or SNS can be used to trigger Lambda functions responding to lifecycle events.',trap:'The option that says: Add a lifecycle hook to your Auto Scaling group to move instances in the Terminating state to the Pending:Wait state to delay the termination of the unhealthy Amazon EC2 instances. Configure a CloudWatch Events rule for the EC2 Instance-terminate Lifecycle Action Auto Scaling Event with an associated Lambda function. Set up an AWS Systems Manager Automation script that collects and uploads the application logs from the instance to a CloudWatch Logs group. Configure the solution to only resume the instance termination once all the logs were successfully sent is incorrect because the Pending:Wait state refers to the scale-out action in Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling and not for scale-in or for terminating the instances.',rule:'Amazon EC2 instances|EC2: correct. Auto Scaling: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'ASG graceful shutdown / pre-launch tasks → Lifecycle Hooks (Pending:Wait or Terminating:Wait).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_31',category:'Networking',question:'A web application hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances in AWS. The application receives a burst of traffic every morning, and a lot of users are complaining about request timeouts. The EC2 instance takes 1 minute to boot up before it can respond to user requests. The cloud architecture must be redesigned to better respond to the changing traffic of the application. How should the Solutions Architect redesign the architecture?',choices:['A|Create a Network Load Balancer with slow-start mode.','B|Create a new launch template and upgrade the size of the instance.','C|Create a step scaling policy and configure an instance warm-up time condition.','D|Create a CloudFront distribution and set the EC2 instance as the origin.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling helps you maintain application availability and allows you to automatically add or remove EC2 instances according to conditions you define. You can use the fleet management features of EC2 Auto Scaling to maintain the health and availability of your fleet.',why:'Step scaling applies “step adjustments” which means you can set multiple actions to vary the scaling depending on the size of the alarm breach. When you create a step scaling policy, you can also specify the number of seconds that it takes for a newly launched instance to warm up.',trap:'The option that says: Create a Network Load Balancer with slow start mode is incorrect because Network Load Balancer does not support slow start mode. If you need to enable slow start mode, you should use Application Load Balancer.',rule:'Step scaling applies “step adjustments” which means you can set multiple actions to vary the scaling depending on the size of the alarm breach size. Useful for variable workloads where scaling increments should vary.',keywords:'Scale proportionally to alarm breach size → Step Scaling. Different steps for small/medium/large breach.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_32',category:'Serverless',question:'A company needs to accelerate the performance of its AI-powered medical diagnostic application by running its machine learning workloads on the edge of telecommunication carriers\' 5G networks. The application must be deployed to a Kubernetes cluster and have role-based access control (RBAC) access to IAM users and roles for cluster authentication. Which of the following should the Solutions Architect implement to ensure single-digit millisecond latency for the application?',choices:['A|Launch the application to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. Create node groups in AWS Wavelength Zones for the EKS cluster via the Wavelength service. Apply the AWS authenticator configuration map (aws-auth ConfigMap) to your cluster.','B|Host the application to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. Set up node groups in AWS Wavelength Zones for the EKS cluster. Attach the EKS connector agent role (AmazonECSConnectorAgentRole) to your cluster and use AWS Control Tower for RBAC access.','C|Launch the application to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. Configure the Amazon VPC CNI plugin for Kubernetes to manage pod networking in AWS Wavelength Zones. Install the AWS IAM Authenticator for Kubernetes (aws-iam-authenticator) to your cluster.','D|Host the application to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster and run the Kubernetes pods on AWS Fargate. Create node groups in AWS Wavelength Zones for the EKS cluster. Add the EKS pod execution IAM role (AmazonEKSFargatePodExecutionRole) to your cluster and ensure that the Fargate profile has the same IAM role as your Amazon EC2 node groups.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Wavelength combines the high bandwidth and ultralow latency of 5G networks with AWS compute and storage services so that developers can innovate and build a new class of applications.',why:'Wavelength Zones are AWS infrastructure deployments that embed AWS compute and storage services within telecommunications providers’ data centers at the edge of the 5G network, so application traffic can reach application servers running in Wavelength Zones without leaving the mobile providers’ network.',trap:'The option that says: Host the application to an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. Set up node groups in AWS Wavelength Zones for the EKS cluster. Attach the EKS connector agent role (AmazonECSConnectorAgentRole) to your cluster and use AWS Control Tower for RBAC access is incorrect. An Amazon EKS connector agent is only used to connect your externally hosted Kubernetes clusters and to allow them to be viewed in your AWS Management Console. The AWS Control Tower doesn\'t provide RBAC access too to your EKS cluster.  This service is commonly used for setting up a secure multi-account AWS environment and not for providing cluster authentication using IAM users and roles.',rule:'Wavelength Zones are AWS infrastructure deployments that embed AWS compute and storage services within telecommunications providers data centers at the edge of the 5G network. Use for ultra-low latency applications like AR/VR and real-time gaming.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_33',category:'Serverless',question:'A data analytics startup is collecting clickstream data and stores them in an S3 bucket. You need to launch an AWS Lambda function to trigger the ETL jobs to run as soon as new data becomes available in Amazon S3. Which of the following services can you use as an extract, transform, and load (ETL) service in this scenario?',choices:['A|S3 Select','B|Redshift Spectrum','C|AWS Step Functions','D|AWS Glue'],correct:'D',answer:'S3 Select allows SQL-like queries directly on objects stored in S3, retrieving only the specific data needed from CSV, JSON, or Parquet files without downloading the entire object.',why:'S3 Select pushes the query processing to the S3 service layer. Instead of transferring an entire CSV file to your application and filtering client-side, S3 Select filters the data before transmission. This reduces the amount of data transferred, lowers costs, and speeds up application response time. S3 Select supports simple SQL SELECT statements with WHERE clauses.',trap:'Redshift Spectrum queries data in S3 using Redshift but requires a Redshift cluster — adding database infrastructure for simple CSV filtering is over-engineered. AWS Glue is an ETL service for transforming and loading data — not for ad-hoc filtering of S3 objects on the fly.',rule:'Query specific columns/rows from S3 object without downloading whole file = S3 Select. Supports CSV, JSON, Parquet. SQL-like SELECT statements. No infrastructure needed. Redshift Spectrum = query S3 from Redshift. Glue = ETL + data catalog. ETL service = Glue, not S3 Select.',keywords:'Query inside S3 object without downloading = S3 Select. SQL-like, supports CSV/JSON/Parquet.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_34',category:'Kinesis',question:'A financial analytics application that collects, processes, and analyzes stock data in real-time uses Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. The producers continually push data to Kinesis Data Streams while the consumers process the data in real time. In Kinesis, where can the consumers store the results? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Amazon S3','B|Amazon EMR','C|Amazon Redshift','D|AWS Glue','E|Amazon Athena'],correct:'AC',answer:'A Kinesis Data Streams architecture for real-time stock analytics needs: (A) Amazon S3 to store the processed output (durable, scalable storage), and (C) Amazon Redshift to run complex analytical SQL queries on the data for business intelligence workloads.',why:'Kinesis Data Streams producers push stock data into the stream in real-time. A consumer (Lambda or KCL app) processes and stores raw data to S3 (data lake). For complex analytical queries on historical data, Amazon Redshift provides columnar storage with massively parallel query execution — ideal for SQL analytics on large datasets used by BI tools.',trap:'Amazon EMR runs big data frameworks (Spark, Hadoop) — useful for custom processing but adds infrastructure management overhead compared to using Redshift for SQL analytics. AWS Glue is an ETL service for transforming data — not a query or storage service for real-time analytics output.',rule:'Kinesis real-time analytics output = S3 (store raw) + Redshift (analytical SQL queries). EMR = big data processing frameworks. Glue = ETL/catalog. Athena = serverless SQL on S3 (also stores results in S3). DynamoDB = key-value, not analytics warehouse.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_35',category:'Database',question:'A leading media company has recently adopted a hybrid cloud architecture, requiring the migration of application servers and databases to AWS. One of its applications requires a heterogeneous database migration, where an on-premises Oracle database needs to be transformed to PostgreSQL in AWS. This entails a schema and code transformation before the proper data migration begins. Which of the following options is the most suitable approach to migrate the database to AWS?',choices:['A|Configure a Launch Template that automatically converts the source schema and code to match that of the target database. Then, use the AWS Database Migration Service to migrate data from the source database to the target database.','B|Use the AWS Schema Conversion Tool to convert the source schema and application code to match that of the target database, and then use the AWS Database Migration Service to migrate data from the source database to the target database.','C|Use Amazon Neptune to convert the source schema and code to match that of the target database in Amazon RDS. Leverage AWS Batch jobs to efficiently migrate data from the source database to the target database in a streamlined batch process.','D|Heterogeneous migrations of databases are not supported in AWS. The database must first be transformed to PostgreSQL and then migrated to Amazon RDS.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Database Migration Service helps you migrate databases to AWS quickly and securely. The source database remains fully operational during the migration, minimizing downtime to applications that rely on the database. The AWS Database Migration Service can migrate your data to and from most widely used commercial and open-source databases.',why:'AWS Database Migration Service can migrate your data to and from most of the widely used commercial and open source databases. It supports homogeneous migrations such as Oracle to Oracle, as well as heterogeneous migrations between different database platforms, such as Oracle to Amazon Aurora.',trap:'The option that says: Configure a Launch Template that automatically converts the source schema and code to match that of the target database. Then, use the AWS Database Migration Service to migrate data from the source database to the target database is incorrect because Launch Templates are only used for configuring EC2 instance settings and do not provide any functionality for schema or code conversion. Schema and code transformation are essential for heterogeneous database migrations and require specialized tools like the AWS Schema Conversion Tool (SCT), not a Launch Template.',rule:'be transformed to postgresql in aws → AWS Schema, Conversion Tool. Not Launch Templates.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_36',category:'CloudWatch',question:'Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) with IAM Role for Service Accounts (IRSA) is used by an e-commerce company to deploy and manage its containerized applications. The website experiences a surge in traffic around the holidays, which significantly adds to the effort. The goal is to ensure that its underlying infrastructure automatically scales in and out in response to demand. Which of the following would meet the requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Install the Kubernetes Metrics Server on the EKS cluster and activate the Horizontal Pod Autoscaling.','B|Set up Karpenter to automatically adjust the number of nodes in the EKS cluster when pods fail or are rescheduled onto other nodes.','C|Install the Kubernetes Metrics Server on the EKS cluster and activate Vertical Pod Autoscaler.','D|Use Amazon CloudWatch Alarms to trigger scaling for containerized applications.','E|Enable the Cluster Autoscaler for EKS to automatically manage the number of nodes based on the resource needs of the pods.'],correct:'AB',answer:'Karpenter is an open-source node provisioning tool for Kubernetes that automatically launches right-sized compute nodes based on pending pod resource requirements, providing faster and more cost-efficient scaling than the Cluster Autoscaler.',why:'Karpenter monitors unschedulable pods and provisions EC2 instances matching exactly what the pods need — right instance type, size, and purchase option (Spot, On-Demand). Unlike Kubernetes Cluster Autoscaler which scales existing node groups, Karpenter provisions nodes directly using EC2 Fleet, enabling faster scaling and better bin-packing. It supports diverse instance types for cost optimization.',trap:'The Kubernetes Metrics Server + Horizontal Pod Autoscaler scales pods (replicas), not nodes — the cluster still needs Cluster Autoscaler or Karpenter to add capacity for new pods. Vertical Pod Autoscaler adjusts resource requests for existing pods — it does not provision new nodes.',rule:'EKS node auto-provisioning with right-sizing = Karpenter. Faster than Cluster Autoscaler. Provisions EC2 directly. HPA = scale pods. Cluster Autoscaler = scale existing node groups by adding/removing EC2 nodes. Karpenter = newer node provisioner.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_37',category:'EC2',question:'An investment bank has a distributed batch processing application which is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of Spot EC2 instances with an SQS queue. You configured your components to use client-side buffering so that the calls made from the client will be buffered first and then sent as a batch request to SQS. What is a period of time during which the SQS queue prevents other consuming components from receiving and processing a message?',choices:['A|Component Timeout','B|Visibility Timeout','C|Processing Timeout','D|Receiving Timeout'],correct:'B',answer:'The SQS Visibility Timeout is the period during which a message is hidden from other consumers after being retrieved by one consumer. If processing takes longer than the timeout, SQS makes the message visible again, allowing another consumer to pick it up.',why:'When a consumer calls ReceiveMessage, SQS hides the message for the visibility timeout duration. If the consumer successfully processes the message and calls DeleteMessage, it is removed from the queue. If the consumer crashes or takes too long, the timeout expires and another consumer can retrieve and process the message. Set the visibility timeout to exceed your maximum processing time.',trap:'Component Timeout, Processing Timeout, and Receiving Timeout are not SQS concepts. The visibility timeout is the specific SQS mechanism for preventing duplicate processing when a consumer fails mid-processing.',rule:'SQS message hidden after receive = Visibility Timeout. Set > max processing time. Timeout expires → message reappears for other consumers. Consumer must DeleteMessage before timeout expires to prevent redelivery. Default visibility timeout = 30 seconds.',keywords:'SQS visibility timeout = how long message hidden after receive. Set > max processing time.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_38',category:'Database',question:'A top investment bank is in the process of building a new Forex trading platform. To ensure high availability and scalability, you designed the trading platform to use an Elastic Load Balancer in front of an Auto Scaling group of On-Demand EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones. For its database tier, you chose to use a single Amazon Aurora instance to take advantage of its distributed, fault-tolerant, and self-healing storage system. In the event of system failure on the primary database instance, what happens to Amazon Aurora during the failover?',choices:['A|Amazon Aurora flips the canonical name record (CNAME) for your DB Instance to point at the healthy replica, which in turn is promoted to become the new primary.','B|Aurora will attempt to create a new DB Instance in the same Availability Zone as the original instance and is done on a best-effort basis.','C|Amazon Aurora flips the A record of your DB Instance to point at the healthy replica, which in turn is promoted to become the new primary.','D|Aurora will first attempt to create a new DB Instance in a different Availability Zone of the original instance. If unable to do so, Aurora will attempt to create a new DB Instance in the original Availability Zone in which the instance was first launched.'],correct:'B',answer:'Failover is automatically handled by Amazon Aurora so that your applications can resume database operations as quickly as possible without manual administrative intervention.',why:'If you have an Amazon Aurora Replica in the same or a different Availability Zone, when failing over, Amazon Aurora flips the canonical name record (CNAME) for your DB Instance to point at the healthy replica, which in turn is promoted to become the new primary. Start-to-finish failover typically completes within 30 seconds.',trap:'The option that says: Aurora will first attempt to create a new DB Instance in a different Availability Zone of the original instance. If unable to do so, Aurora will attempt to create a new DB Instance in the original Availability Zone in which the instance was first launched is incorrect because Aurora will first attempt to create a new DB Instance in the same Availability Zone as the original instance. If unable to do so, Aurora will attempt to create a new DB Instance in a different Availability Zone and not the other way around.',rule:'Aurora failover: if Aurora Replica exists → promoted in < 30 sec (same AZ first). If no replica → new instance created from shared storage. Aurora Serverless → capacity scaled up/down based on ACUs automatically. No need to manage instance size for Aurora Serverless.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_39',category:'EC2',question:'A company plans to deploy a Docker-based batch application in AWS. The application will be used to process both mission-critical data and non-essential batch jobs. Which of the following is the most cost-effective option to use in implementing this architecture?',choices:['A|Use Amazon ECS as the container management service, then set up a combination of Reserved and Spot Amazon EC2 Instances for processing mission-critical and non-essential batch jobs, respectively.','B|Use Amazon ECS as the container management service, then set up Reserved Amazon EC2 Instances for processing both mission-critical and non-essential batch jobs.','C|Use Amazon ECS as the container management service, then set up On-Demand Amazon EC2 Instances for processing both mission-critical and non-essential batch jobs.','D|Use Amazon ECS as the container management service, then set up Spot Amazon EC2 Instances for processing both mission-critical and non-essential batch jobs.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon ECS lets you run batch workloads with managed or custom schedulers on Amazon EC2 On-Demand Instances, Reserved Instances, or Spot Instances. You can launch a combination of EC2 instances to set up a cost-effective architecture depending on your workload.',why:'There are two different charge models for Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS): Fargate Launch Type Model and EC2 Launch Type Model. With Fargate, you pay for the amount of vCPU and memory resources that your containerized application requests while for EC2 launch type model, there is no additional charge. You pay for AWS resources (e.g., EC2 instances or EBS volumes) you create to store and run your application.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon ECS as the container management service, then set up Reserved Amazon EC2 Instances for processing both mission-critical and non-essential batch jobs is incorrect because processing the non-essential batch jobs can be handled much cheaper by using Spot EC2 instances instead of Reserved Instances.',rule:'Cost-effective → Amazon ECS as the container managemen, Amazon EC2 Instances for processing m. Not Use Amazon.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_40',category:'Storage',question:'A data analytics company keeps a massive volume of data that they store in their on-premises data center. To scale their storage systems, they are looking for cloud-backed storage volumes that they can mount using Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) devices from their on-premises application servers. They have an on-site data analytics application that frequently accesses the latest data subsets locally while the older data are rarely accessed. You are required to minimize the need to scale the on-premises storage infrastructure while still providing their web application with low-latency access to the data. Which type of AWS Storage Gateway service will you use to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Volume Gateway in stored mode','B|Tape Gateway','C|Volume Gateway in cached mode','D|File Gateway'],correct:'C',answer:'The Volume Gateway is a cloud-based iSCSI block storage volume for your on-premises applications. The Volume Gateway provides either a local cache or full volumes on-premises while also storing full copies of your volumes in the AWS cloud.',why:'Cached Volumes - you store volume data in AWS, with a small portion of recently accessed data in the cache on-premises. Stored Volumes - you store the entire set of volume data on-premises and store periodic point-in-time backups (snapshots) in AWS.',trap:'Volume Gateway in stored mode is incorrect because the requirement is to provide low latency access to the frequently accessed data subsets locally. Stored Volumes are used if you need low-latency access to your entire dataset.',rule:'Cached Volumes - you store volume data in AWS, with a small portion of recently accessed data in the cache on-premises.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_41',category:'Database',question:'A company has recently adopted a hybrid cloud architecture and is planning to migrate a database hosted on-premises to AWS. The database currently has over 50 TB of consumer data, handles highly transactional (Online Transaction Processing – OLTP) workloads, and is expected to grow. The Solutions Architect should ensure that the database is ACID-compliant and can handle complex application queries. Which type of database service should the Architect use?',choices:['A|Amazon Aurora','B|Amazon Redshift','C|Amazon DynamoDB','D|Amazon RDS'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Aurora is a fully managed relational database engine compatible with MySQL and PostgreSQL. You already know how MySQL and PostgreSQL combine the speed and reliability of high-end commercial databases with the simplicity and cost-effectiveness of open-source databases.',why:'Aurora uses a highly efficient, distributed storage architecture designed for performance and resilience. Its MySQL- and PostgreSQL-compatible engines are enhanced to leverage a durable, self-repairing storage layer that maintains synchronous copies of data across multiple Availability Zones. This storage layer can expand automatically in 10 GB increments, supporting up to 128 TiB per database cluster.',trap:'Amazon Redshift is incorrect because this is primarily used for OLAP applications and not for OLTP. Moreover, it doesn\'t scale automatically to handle the exponential growth of the database.',rule:'Aurora uses a highly efficient, distributed storage architecture designed for performance and resilience.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_42',category:'Route 53',question:'A client is hosting their company website on a cluster of web servers that are behind a public-facing Application Load Balancer (AWS ALB). The client also uses Amazon Route 53 to manage their public DNS. How should the client configure the DNS zone apex record to point to the load balancer?',choices:['A|Create an A record pointing to the IP address of the load balancer.','B|Create a CNAME record pointing to the load balancer DNS name.','C|Create an alias for CNAME record to the load balancer DNS name.','D|Create an A record aliased to the load balancer DNS name.'],correct:'D',answer:'Route 53\'s DNS implementation connects user requests to infrastructure running inside (and outside) of Amazon Web Services (AWS). For example, if you have multiple web servers running on EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load Balancing load balancer, Route 53 will route all traffic addressed to your website (e.g. www.tutorialsdojo.com) to the load balancer DNS name (e.g.',why:'Additionally, Route 53 supports the alias resource record set, which lets you map your zone apex (e.g. tutorialsdojo.com) DNS name to your load balancer DNS name. IP addresses associated with Elastic Load Balancing can change at any time due to scaling or software updates. Route 53 responds to each request for an Alias resource record set with one IP address for the load balancer.',trap:'The option that says: Creating an A record pointing to the IP address of the load balancer is incorrect. You should be using an Alias record pointing to the DNS name of the load balancer since the IP address of the load balancer can change at any time.',rule:'Additionally, Route 53 supports the alias resource record set, which lets you map your zone apex (e.g.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_43',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is using AWS IAM to manage access to AWS services. The Solutions Architect of the company created the following IAM policy for AWS Lambda: { "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "lambda:CreateFunction", "lambda:DeleteFunction" ], "Resource": "*" }, { "Effect": "Deny", "Action": [ "lambda:CreateFunction", "lambda:DeleteFunction", "lambda:InvokeFunction", "lambda:TagResource" ], "Resource": "*", "Condition": { "IpAddress": { "aws:SourceIp": "187.5.104.11/32" } } } ] } Which of the following options is allowed by this policy?',choices:['A|Delete an AWS Lambda function using the 187.5.104.11/32 address.','B|Create an AWS Lambda function using the 100.220.0.11/32 address.','C|Delete an AWS Lambda function from any network address.','D|Create an AWS Lambda function using the 187.5.104.11/32 address.'],correct:'B',answer:'You manage access in AWS by creating policies and attaching them to IAM identities (users, groups of users, or roles) or AWS resources. A policy is an object in AWS that, when associated with an identity or resource, defines their permissions. AWS evaluates these policies when an IAM principal (user or role) makes a request.',why:'You can use AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) to manage access to the Lambda API and resources like functions and layers. Based on the given IAM policy, you can create and delete a Lambda function from any network address except for the IP address 187.5.104.11/32. Since the IP address 100.220.0.11/32 is not denied in the policy, you can use this address to create a Lambda function.',trap:'The option that says: Delete an AWS Lambda function using the 187.5.104.11/32 address is incorrect because the source IP used in this option is denied by the IAM policy.',rule:'Since the IP address 100.220.0.11/32 is not denied in the policy, you can use this address to create a Lambda function.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_44',category:'Networking',question:'A company has an application hosted in an Amazon ECS Cluster behind an Application Load Balancer. The Solutions Architect is building a sophisticated web filtering solution that allows or blocks web requests based on the country that the requests originate from. However, the solution should still allow specific IP addresses from that country. Which combination of steps should the Architect implement to satisfy this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Using AWS WAF, create a web ACL with a rule that explicitly allows requests from approved IP addresses declared in an IP Set.','B|Add another rule in the AWS WAF web ACL with a geo match condition that blocks requests that originate from a specific country.','C|In the Application Load Balancer, create a listener rule that explicitly allows requests from approved IP addresses.','D|Set up a geo match condition in the Application Load Balancer that blocks requests from a specific country.','E|Place a Transit Gateway in front of the VPC where the application is hosted and set up Network ACLs that block requests that originate from a specific country.'],correct:'AB',answer:'Use AWS WAF to: (A) create a web ACL with an IP set rule that explicitly allows only approved IP addresses, and (B) add a geo match condition rule that blocks requests from specific countries. Both are WAF web ACL rules, not ALB features.',why:'AWS WAF web ACLs can contain multiple rules evaluated in order. A rule matching an IP set can allow specific trusted IPs through. A geo match rule can block entire countries. These rules work at the application layer (Layer 7) and attach to the ALB. ALB itself does not have IP whitelisting or geo-blocking features — those require WAF.',trap:'The ALB does not natively support IP-based whitelisting rules or geo match conditions — those require AWS WAF. A Transit Gateway + NACLs cannot perform geo-based blocking since NACLs work on IP ranges, not country codes. You cannot create "geo match" conditions directly in ALB listener rules.',rule:'Country blocking + IP whitelisting = AWS WAF web ACL rules (IP set + geo match), not ALB. ALB has no native geo or IP set filtering. WAF attaches to ALB for Layer 7 filtering.',keywords:'Fixed IP for load balancer (firewall whitelisting) → Global Accelerator (2 static IPs) or NLB + EIP.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_45',category:'Storage',question:'An application is hosted on an EC2 instance with multiple EBS Volumes attached and uses Amazon Neptune as its database. To improve data security, you encrypted all of the EBS volumes attached to the instance to protect the confidential data stored in the volumes. Which of the following statements are true about encrypted Amazon Elastic Block Store volumes? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|All data moving between the volume and the instance are encrypted.','B|Snapshots are automatically encrypted.','C|Snapshots are not automatically encrypted.','D|Only the data in the volume is encrypted and not all the data moving between the volume and the instance.','E|The volumes created from the encrypted snapshot are not encrypted.'],correct:'AB',answer:'When using a custom domain name with S3 static website hosting, you must create an Alias record in Route 53 pointing to the S3 website endpoint. Alias records are free and work for apex domains — CNAME records cannot be used at the zone apex.',why:'Route 53 Alias records are AWS-specific DNS extensions that point to AWS resources (S3 website endpoints, CloudFront distributions, ALBs) and support zone apex (root domain) routing. A regular CNAME cannot be created at the zone apex (tutorialsdojo.com). The S3 bucket name must match the domain name exactly for static website hosting to work.',trap:'A regular CNAME record pointing to the S3 website endpoint would work for subdomains but cannot be used at the zone apex (root domain). An Alias record to a CloudFront distribution is valid but requires setting up CloudFront first. An A record with a static IP is not applicable — S3 website endpoints are DNS names, not IPs.',rule:'S3 static website custom domain = Route 53 Alias record pointing to S3 website endpoint. CNAME cannot be used at zone apex. Bucket name must match domain name exactly.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_46',category:'IAM',question:'A company has a UAT and production EC2 instances running on AWS. They want to ensure that employees who are responsible for the UAT instances don\'t have access to work on the production instances to minimize security risks. Which of the following would be the best way to achieve this?',choices:['A|Launch the UAT and production EC2 instances in separate VPC\'s connected by VPC peering.','B|Provide permissions to the users via the AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM) service to only access EC2 instances that are used for production or development.','C|Launch the UAT and production instances in different Availability Zones and use Multi Factor Authentication.','D|Define the tags on the UAT and production servers and add a condition to the IAM policy which allows access to specific tags.'],correct:'D',answer:'For this scenario, the best way to achieve the required solution is to use a combination of Tags and IAM policies. You can define the tags on the UAT and production EC2 instances and add a condition to the IAM policy which allows access to specific tags.',why:'Tags enable you to categorize your AWS resources in different ways, for example, by purpose, owner, or environment. This is useful when you have many resources of the same type — you can quickly identify a specific resource based on the tags you\'ve assigned to it.',trap:'The option that says: Launch the UAT and production EC2 instances in separate VPC\'s connected by VPC peering is incorrect because these are just network changes to your cloud architecture and don\'t have any effect on the security permissions of your users to access your EC2 instances.',rule:'Tags enable you to categorize your AWS resources in different ways, for example, by purpose, owner, or environment.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_47',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A top IT Consultancy has a VPC with two On-Demand EC2 instances with Elastic IP addresses. You were notified that the EC2 instances are currently under SSH brute force attacks over the Internet. The IT Security team has identified the IP addresses where these attacks originated. You have to immediately implement a temporary fix to stop these attacks while the team is setting up AWS WAF, GuardDuty, and AWS Shield Advanced to permanently fix the security vulnerability. Which of the following provides the quickest way to stop the attacks to the instances?',choices:['A|Place the EC2 instances into private subnets','B|Remove the Internet Gateway from the VPC','C|Block the IP addresses in the Network Access Control List','D|Assign a static Anycast IP address to each EC2 instance'],correct:'C',answer:'On-Demand Capacity Reservations guarantee EC2 compute capacity in a specific AZ for as long as needed, with no commitment and no capacity risk. Payment servers require guaranteed availability — Capacity Reservations ensure capacity is always available when needed.',why:'On-Demand Capacity Reservations (ODCRs) reserve compute capacity in a specific AZ without requiring a 1-3 year term commitment. You pay the On-Demand price for the reserved capacity whether you use it or not. This is ideal for workloads that require absolute capacity guarantee: disaster recovery, payment processing, regulated systems. Combine with Reserved Instance or Savings Plans discounts for cost optimization.',trap:'Reserved Instances commit to a specific instance type for 1-3 years — they provide billing discounts but do not guarantee capacity in a specific AZ at the time of launch. On-Demand Instances have no capacity guarantee during high-demand events. Savings Plans provide cost discounts but no capacity reservation.',rule:'Guaranteed capacity in specific AZ = On-Demand Capacity Reservation. No term commitment. Pays On-Demand rate. Reserved Instance = billing discount + capacity priority, but NOT a hardware reservation. On-Demand Capacity Reservations = capacity guarantee in a specific AZ.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_48',category:'Serverless',question:'A startup launched a fleet of on-demand Amazon EC2 instances to host a massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG). The EC2 instances are configured with Auto Scaling and AWS Systems Manager. What can be used to configure the EC2 instances without having to establish an RDP or SSH connection to each instance?',choices:['A|AWS App Runner','B|AWS CodePipeline','C|Run Command','D|EC2Config'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Systems Manager Run Command lets you remotely run scripts or commands on EC2 instances without SSH access, using the SSM Agent. It is the purpose-built tool for running administrative commands across a fleet of instances.',why:'Run Command executes documents (scripts) on managed instances via the SSM Agent. No SSH, no bastion host, no VPN needed. It supports Windows and Linux, logs output to CloudWatch or S3, and can target instances by tag, instance ID, or resource group. It is the standard way to run one-time administrative tasks across EC2 fleets.',trap:'AWS App Runner is a fully managed container deployment service — not a tool for running commands on existing EC2 instances. AWS CodePipeline is a CI/CD pipeline service — not for running ad-hoc instance commands. EC2Config is a legacy Windows EC2 configuration service that has been superseded by SSM Agent.',rule:'Run scripts on EC2 without SSH = AWS Systems Manager Run Command. Uses SSM Agent. Works for both Windows and Linux. Logs to CloudWatch/S3. No direct instance access needed.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_49',category:'Networking',question:'A company has a web application hosted on a fleet of EC2 instances located in two Availability Zones that are all placed behind an Application Load Balancer. As a Solutions Architect, you have to add a health check configuration to ensure your application is highly-available. Which health checks will you implement?',choices:['A|HTTP or HTTPS health check','B|ICMP health check','C|FTP health check','D|TCP health check'],correct:'A',answer:'Route 53 health checks use TCP checks for non-HTTP protocols. For an NLB, TCP health checks verify that the port is open and accepting connections, which is sufficient since NLB operates at Layer 4.',why:'Route 53 health checks can be configured as HTTP, HTTPS, or TCP. For an NLB target, TCP health checks are appropriate because NLB operates at the transport layer (Layer 4) and does not parse HTTP content. TCP checks simply verify that the endpoint accepts connections on the specified port. HTTP/HTTPS checks are for Layer 7 endpoints that return response codes.',trap:'ICMP health checks are not supported by Route 53 health checkers — Route 53 uses HTTP, HTTPS, or TCP only. FTP health checks are not a Route 53 health check type. HTTP/HTTPS health checks are for web application endpoints that return HTTP status codes.',rule:'Route 53 health check for NLB = TCP health check (Layer 4, verifies port accepts connections). HTTP/HTTPS = for ALB/web endpoints. ICMP and FTP = not supported by Route 53 health checks. TCP = verifies port open only, not application response.',keywords:'Route 53 health checks: HTTP, HTTPS, or TCP only. ICMP and FTP not supported.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_50',category:'Networking',question:'An On-Demand EC2 instance is launched into a VPC subnet with the Network ACL configured to allow all inbound traffic and deny all outbound traffic. The instance’s security group has an inbound rule to allow SSH from any IP address and does not have any outbound rules. In this scenario, what are the changes needed to allow SSH connection to the instance?',choices:['A|The outbound security group needs to be modified to allow outbound traffic.','B|The network ACL needs to be modified to allow outbound traffic.','C|No action needed. It can already be accessed from any IP address using SSH.','D|Both the outbound security group and outbound network ACL need to be modified to allow outbound traffic.'],correct:'D',answer:'When hybrid connectivity exists between on-premises and AWS, and both EC2 instances and on-premises servers need to query the same private DNS names, Route 53 Resolver with forwarding rules allows seamless DNS resolution across both environments.',why:'Route 53 Resolver is a DNS resolver built into every VPC. Resolver Endpoints (inbound and outbound) and Forwarding Rules allow you to route DNS queries between on-premises and AWS. An outbound resolver endpoint sends queries for on-premises domain names to your on-premises DNS. An inbound resolver endpoint allows on-premises systems to query Route 53 private hosted zones.',trap:'AWS Direct Connect provides the network connection but does not resolve DNS. A Transit Gateway aggregates network connectivity but has no DNS capability. VPN alone provides routing but not DNS resolution across environments.',rule:'Hybrid DNS resolution (on-premises ↔ AWS) = Route 53 Resolver with inbound/outbound endpoints + forwarding rules. Direct Connect = network, not DNS. VPN = network, not DNS.',keywords:'SSH to EC2: Security Group inbound port 22. NACL = stateless, needs inbound AND outbound rules.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_51',category:'Networking',question:'A logistics company based in the USA runs its web application on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group. The company uses an Application Load Balancer to distribute traffic among the EC2 instances. The company runs the same application in multiple AWS regions to cater to clients across several countries. A recent government policy has been enacted that prohibits the company from servicing a specific country. Which of the following options is the recommended action to comply with the government requirement?',choices:['A|Create a Web ACL rule in AWS WAF to block the specified country. Associate the rule to the Application Load Balancers.','B|Update the route tables to forward all outbound traffic to AWS Network Firewall and configure a stateful domain list rule group to block the specified country','C|Update the Network Access Control Lists of all subnets used by the Amazon EC2 instances to “deny” all IP addresses from the specific country.','D|Update the Network Access Control Lists of all subnets used by the Application Load Balancers to “deny” all IP addresses from the specific country.'],correct:'A',answer:'An EC2 instance can only be directly accessed from the Internet if it is in a public subnet, meaning its subnet route table has a route to an Internet Gateway (0.0.0.0/0 → igw-xxxx).',why:'Public subnet = subnet with a route table containing 0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway. Private subnet = no such route. An EC2 instance in a public subnet with a public IP or EIP is reachable from the Internet. The instance itself cannot control whether its subnet is public or private — that is determined by the route table.',trap:'Security groups control inbound/outbound traffic but operate at the instance level — they cannot change whether a subnet is public or private. The VPC CIDR block defines the IP range but does not determine Internet accessibility. Placement groups affect proximity of instances, not Internet access.',rule:'EC2 in private subnet only accessible from Internet = incorrect. For Internet access: (1) public subnet (route table has 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW), (2) public IP or EIP assigned, (3) security group allows inbound traffic on required port. All three are required for public internet access.',keywords:'Global Accelerator: 2 static Anycast IPs, routes to optimal endpoint by latency and health.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_52',category:'IAM',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a fast-growing startup that just started operations during the past 3 months. They currently have an on-premises Active Directory and 10 computers. To save costs in procuring physical workstations, they decided to deploy virtual desktops for their new employees in a virtual private cloud in AWS. The new cloud infrastructure should leverage the existing security controls in AWS but can still communicate with their on-premises network. Which set of AWS services will the Architect use to meet these requirements?',choices:['A|AWS Directory Services, VPN connection, and ClassicLink','B|AWS Directory Services, VPN connection, and Amazon Workspaces','C|AWS Directory Services, VPN connection, and AWS Identity and Access Management','D|AWS Directory Services, VPN connection, and Amazon S3'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Directory Services integrates with on-premises AD for authentication. A VPN connection links the on-premises network to the AWS VPC. Amazon Workspaces provides cloud-based virtual desktops for employees, leveraging the on-premises directory for SSO.',why:'The startup needs virtual desktops (Workspaces) accessible by employees using their existing corporate credentials (Directory Services + VPN for hybrid connectivity). Workspaces integrates with AWS Directory Service (Microsoft AD or Simple AD) to authenticate users against their existing directory. The VPN provides the secure tunnel between on-premises and AWS.',trap:'ClassicLink connects EC2-Classic instances to a VPC — it is deprecated and not used for virtual desktops. Amazon S3 is object storage with no virtual desktop capability. IAM manages AWS service access but does not provide virtual desktop infrastructure.',rule:'Cloud virtual desktops for employees using existing AD credentials = Directory Services + VPN + Amazon Workspaces. ClassicLink = deprecated EC2-Classic feature. Workspaces integrates with AD for SSO.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_53',category:'Networking',question:'An operations team has an application running on EC2 instances inside two custom VPCs. The VPCs are located in the Ohio and N.Virginia Region respectively. The team wants to transfer data between the instances without traversing the public internet. Which combination of steps will achieve this? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up a VPC peering connection between the VPCs.','B|Create an Egress-only Internet Gateway.','C|Re-configure the route table’s target and destination of the instances’ subnet.','D|Launch a NAT Gateway in the public subnet of each VPC.','E|Deploy a VPC endpoint on each region to enable a private connection.'],correct:'AC',answer:'A VPC peering connection is a networking connection between two VPCs that enables you to route traffic between them using private IPv4 addresses or IPv6 addresses. Instances in either VPC can communicate with each other as if they are within the same network. You can create a VPC peering connection between your own VPCs, or with a VPC in another AWS account.',why:'VPC peering is a direct, private network connection between two VPCs using AWS backbone — no internet, no VPN, no NAT. Traffic stays on AWS network. Peering is non-transitive: A peers with B and B peers with C does not allow A to reach C. Peering can be cross-account or cross-region. Route tables in each VPC must be updated to route traffic to the peer CIDR through the peering connection.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Egress only Internet Gateway is incorrect because this will just enable outbound IPv6 communication from instances in a VPC to the internet. Take note that the scenario requires private communication to be enabled between VPCs from two different regions.',rule:'Set up a VPC peering connection between the VPCs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_54',category:'S3',question:'A web application is hosted on an EC2 instance that processes sensitive financial information. The EC2 instance is launched in a private subnet, and all data is stored in an Amazon S3 bucket. Users access financial information over the Internet through pre-signed URLs generated by the web application. The company\'s security team is concerned that internet connectivity to Amazon S3 poses a security risk. In this scenario, what will you do to resolve this security vulnerability in the most cost-effective manner?',choices:['A|Change the web architecture to access the financial data through a Gateway VPC Endpoint.','B|Change the web architecture to access the financial data in your S3 bucket through a VPN connection.','C|Change the web architecture to access the financial data hosted in your S3 bucket by creating a custom VPC endpoint service.','D|Change the web architecture to access the financial data in S3 through an interface VPC endpoint, which is powered by AWS PrivateLink.'],correct:'A',answer:'Take note that your VPC lives within a larger AWS network and the services, such as S3, DynamoDB, RDS, and many others, are located outside of your VPC, but still within the AWS network. By default, the connection that your VPC uses to connect to your S3 bucket or any other service traverses the public Internet via your Internet Gateway.',why:'A VPC endpoint enables you to privately connect your VPC to supported AWS services and VPC endpoint services powered by PrivateLink without requiring an internet gateway, NAT device, VPN connection, or AWS Direct Connect connection. Instances in your VPC do not require public IP addresses to communicate with resources in the service. Traffic between your VPC and the other service does not leave the Amazon network.',trap:'The option that says: Changing the web architecture to access the financial data in your S3 bucket through a VPN connection is incorrect because a VPN connection still goes through the public Internet. You have to use a VPC Endpoint in this scenario and not VPN, to privately connect your VPC to supported AWS services such as S3.',rule:'Dedicated network → VPC. Not AWS services.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_55',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company troubleshoots the operational issues of their cloud architecture by logging the AWS API call history of all AWS resources. The Solutions Architect must implement a solution to quickly identify the most recent changes made to resources in their environment, including creation, modification, and deletion of AWS resources. One of the requirements is that the generated log files should be encrypted to avoid any security issues. Which of the following is the most suitable approach to implement the encryption?',choices:['A|Use CloudTrail and configure the destination Amazon Glacier archive to use Server-Side Encryption (SSE).','B|Use CloudTrail and configure the destination S3 bucket to use Server-Side Encryption (SSE).','C|Use CloudTrail and configure the destination S3 bucket to use Server Side Encryption (SSE) with AES-128 encryption algorithm.','D|Use CloudTrail with its default settings.'],correct:'D',answer:'CloudTrail logs are stored in S3. To protect them from tampering, configure the S3 destination bucket to use Server-Side Encryption with AWS KMS (SSE-KMS) and enable CloudTrail log file validation. SSE-KMS satisfies HIPAA/SOC encryption requirements.',why:'CloudTrail log file integrity validation creates a hash digest file that you can use to verify whether a log file was modified or deleted after CloudTrail delivered it. SSE-KMS encrypts log files at rest using a KMS key, satisfying encryption-at-rest requirements. Both features are configured in the CloudTrail trail settings.',trap:'Using CloudTrail with default settings does not encrypt the log files or enable validation. S3 Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys (SSE-C) requires managing your own keys and is more operationally complex than SSE-KMS for CloudTrail.',rule:'Protect CloudTrail logs = SSE-KMS on S3 bucket + enable log file validation. Default settings = no encryption. SSE-C = you manage keys, more complex. Log file validation = detects tampering via SHA-256 digest files. CloudTrail = API call history, not file auditing.',keywords:'Eliminating wrong answers → confirm by source. DynamoDB auto-scaling → use DynamoDB Auto Scaling, not ALB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_56',category:'Storage',question:'A company has an On-Demand EC2 instance with an attached EBS volume. There is a scheduled job that creates a snapshot of this EBS volume every midnight at 12 AM when the instance is not used. One night, there has been a production incident where you need to perform a change on both the instance and on the EBS volume at the same time when the snapshot is currently taking place. Which of the following scenario is true when it comes to the usage of an EBS volume while the snapshot is in progress?',choices:['A|The EBS volume can be used while the snapshot is in progress.','B|The EBS volume cannot be detached or attached to an EC2 instance until the snapshot completes','C|The EBS volume can be used in read-only mode while the snapshot is in progress.','D|The EBS volume cannot be used until the snapshot completes.'],correct:'A',answer:'IAM roles are global AWS entities — the same role can be assigned to EC2 instances in any AWS region without duplication. Simply create a new EC2 instance in the new region and assign the existing IAM role to it.',why:'IAM is a global service. IAM roles, users, groups, and policies are not region-specific. When you launch an EC2 instance in a new region, you can assign the same IAM role that instances in other regions use. The role provides the same permissions regardless of the region of the attached instance.',trap:'Creating a new IAM role in the new region is unnecessary — IAM roles are global. You cannot assign the existing IAM role to instances in a different region by design limitation — this is a false premise. Duplicating IAM roles and policies creates drift and maintenance burden.',rule:'IAM roles are global (not region-specific). Same role can be used in any region. Just assign the existing role to new EC2 instances. No need to create region-specific IAM roles.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_57',category:'Storage',question:'A health organization is using a large Dedicated EC2 instance with multiple EBS volumes to host its health records web application. The EBS volumes must be encrypted due to the confidentiality of the data that they are handling and also to comply with the HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) standard. In EBS encryption, what service does AWS use to secure the volume\'s data at rest? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|By using your own keys in AWS Key Management Service (KMS).','B|By using S3 Server-Side Encryption.','C|By using Amazon-managed keys in AWS Key Management Service (KMS).','D|By using S3 Client-Side Encryption.','E|By using a password stored in CloudHSM.','F|By using the SSL certificates provided by the AWS Certificate Manager (ACM).'],correct:'AC',answer:'Amazon EBS encryption offers seamless encryption of EBS data volumes, boot volumes, and snapshots, eliminating the need to build and maintain a secure key management infrastructure. EBS encryption enables data at rest security by encrypting your data using Amazon-managed keys, or keys you create and manage using the AWS Key Management Service (KMS).',why:'EBS encryption uses AWS KMS under the hood. When you create an encrypted volume, KMS generates a data key. EC2 decrypts the data key in memory using the CMK to encrypt/decrypt I/O. The plaintext key never leaves the EC2 host hardware. Snapshots of encrypted volumes are automatically encrypted with the same CMK. Encryption at rest and in transit between EC2 and EBS is handled transparently with no code changes needed.',trap:'Storing data in an encrypted EBS snapshot protects backups but does not encrypt the live volume — snapshots are point-in-time copies, not live encryption. A third-party encryption tool adds key management overhead when EBS provides transparent, KMS-backed encryption natively. Dedicated Instance tenancy isolates your hardware but does not encrypt your data.',rule:'EBS encryption encrypts data at rest AND in transit between EC2 and EBS. Enable by default at account level or per-volume. SSE-KMS for S3 adds CloudTrail audit trail. Use both for defense-in-depth.',keywords:'Encrypt unencrypted EBS → copy snapshot with encryption enabled, create new volume.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_58',category:'Networking',question:'A local bank has an in-house application that handles sensitive financial data in a private subnet. After the data is processed by the EC2 worker instances, they will be delivered to S3 for ingestion by other services. How should you design this solution so that the data does not pass through the public Internet?',choices:['A|Create an Internet gateway in the public subnet with a corresponding route entry that directs the data to S3.','B|Configure a Transit gateway along with a corresponding route entry that directs the data to S3.','C|Configure a VPC Endpoint along with a corresponding route entry that directs the data to S3.','D|Provision a NAT gateway in the private subnet with a corresponding route entry that directs the data to S3.'],correct:'C',answer:'The important concept that you have to understand in this scenario is that your VPC and your S3 bucket are located within the larger AWS network. However, the traffic coming from your VPC to your S3 bucket is traversing the public Internet by default.',why:'A VPC endpoint enables you to privately connect your VPC to supported AWS services and VPC endpoint services powered by PrivateLink without requiring an Internet gateway, NAT device, VPN connection, or AWS Direct Connect connection. Instances in your VPC do not require public IP addresses to communicate with resources in the service. Traffic between your VPC and the other services does not leave the Amazon network. Endpoints are virtual devices.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Internet gateway in the public subnet with a corresponding route entry that directs the data to S3 is incorrect because the Internet gateway is used for instances in the public subnet to have accessibility to the Internet.',rule:'Instances in your VPC do not require public IP addresses to communicate with resources in the service.',keywords:'S3/DynamoDB private VPC access → Gateway Endpoint (free). Other services → Interface Endpoint (PrivateLink).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_59',category:'CloudWatch',question:'An e-commerce company’s Chief Information Security Officer (CISO) has taken necessary measures to ensure that sensitive customer data is secure in the cloud. However, the company recently discovered that some customer Personally Identifiable Information (PII) was mistakenly uploaded to an S3 bucket. The company aims to rectify this mistake and prevent any similar incidents from happening again in the future. Additionally, the company would like to be notified if this error occurs again. As the Solutions Architect, which combination of options should you implement in this scenario? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Identify sensitive data using Amazon Macie and create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to capture the SensitiveData event type.','B|Set up an Amazon SNS topic as the target for an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that sends notifications when the error occurs again.','C|Identify sensitive data using Amazon GuardDuty by creating an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to include the CRITICAL event types from GuardDuty findings.','D|Set up an Amazon SQS as the target for an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that sends notifications when the error occurs again.','E|Set up an AWS IoT Message Broker as the target for an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that sends notifications when the SensitiveData:S3Object/Personal event occurs again.'],correct:'AB',answer:'Use Amazon Macie to identify sensitive data and generate findings. Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that captures Macie SensitiveData events (specifically SensitiveData:S3Object/Personal). Set the target to an Amazon SNS topic to send alerts when the event occurs.',why:'Amazon Macie monitors S3 buckets and generates detailed findings for sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials). EventBridge integrates with Macie to capture these findings as events. EventBridge rules can filter by event type (e.g., SensitiveData:S3Object/Personal) and route matched events to SNS for notifications. This is a fully managed, event-driven pattern.',trap:'GuardDuty detects threats and account-level anomalies — it does not discover sensitive data content in S3 objects. SQS and IoT Message Broker can be EventBridge targets but are inappropriate for sending human-readable alert notifications. The key is using Macie (not GuardDuty) for sensitive data classification.',rule:'Sensitive data alerts from S3 = Macie (classify) + EventBridge (capture finding events) + SNS (notify). GuardDuty = threat detection, not data classification.',keywords:'Threat detection / suspicious activity → GuardDuty. Uses ML + threat intelligence.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_60',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A social media company needs to capture the detailed information of all HTTP requests that went through its public-facing Application Load Balancer every five minutes. The client\'s IP address and network latencies must also be tracked, while the load balancer\'s availability is monitored separately through the ELB health check. The captured data should be used for analyzing traffic patterns and for troubleshooting Docker applications orchestrated by the Amazon ECS Anywhere service. Which of the following options meets the customer requirements with the LEAST amount of overhead?',choices:['A|Enable AWS CloudTrail for their Application Load Balancer. Use the CloudTrail Lake to analyze and troubleshoot the application traffic.','B|Enable access logs on the Application Load Balancer. Integrate the ECS cluster with Amazon CloudWatch Application Insights to analyze traffic patterns and simplify troubleshooting.','C|Install and run the AWS X-Ray daemon on the ECS cluster. Use the Amazon CloudWatch ServiceLens to analyze the traffic that goes through the application.','D|Integrate Amazon EventBridge metrics on the Application Load Balancer to capture the client IP address. Use Amazon CloudWatch GetMetricData to retrieve and analyze traffic-related metrics.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon CloudWatch Application Insights facilitates observability for your applications and underlying AWS resources. It helps you set up the best monitors for your application resources to continuously analyze data for signs of problems with your applications.',why:'Elastic Load Balancing provides access logs that capture detailed information about requests sent to your load balancer. Each log contains information such as the time the request was received, the client\'s IP address, latencies, request paths, and server responses. You can use these access logs to analyze traffic patterns and troubleshoot issues.',trap:'The option that says: Enable AWS CloudTrail for their Application Load Balancer. Use the CloudTrail Lake to analyze and troubleshoot the application traffic is incorrect because AWS CloudTrail is primarily used to monitor and record the account activity across your AWS resources and not your web applications. You cannot use CloudTrail to capture the detailed information of all HTTP requests that go through your public-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB). CloudTrail can only track the resource changes made to your ALB, but not the actual IP traffic that goes through it. For this use case, you have to enable the access logs feature instead. In addition, the AWS CloudTrail Lake feature is more suitable for running SQL-based queries on your API events and not for analyzing application traffic.',rule:'Monitoring → ECS, Amazon CloudWatch Application Insight. Not AWS CloudTrail.',keywords:'ALB access logs: captures details of each request. Store in S3. Use Athena to query.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_61',category:'Serverless',question:'An application is hosted in an On-Demand EC2 instance and is using Amazon SDK to communicate to other AWS services such as S3, DynamoDB, and many others. As part of the upcoming IT audit, you need to ensure that all API calls to your AWS resources are logged and durably stored. Which is the most suitable service that you should use to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon CloudWatch','B|AWS CloudTrail','C|AWS X-Ray','D|Amazon API Gateway'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS CloudTrail with S3 as the destination, combined with CloudTrail log file integrity validation, satisfies the audit requirement. CloudTrail captures all API calls across the account.',why:'CloudTrail records every AWS API call made in your account — who made it, from where, what service, what action, and when. Log file integrity validation creates SHA-256 hash digest files that prove whether log files were modified after delivery. Storing logs in S3 with SSE-KMS encryption and enabling CloudTrail across all regions provides a comprehensive audit trail.',trap:'CloudWatch monitors metrics and logs from services but does not capture AWS API calls. VPC Flow Logs capture network traffic metadata but not application or API-level actions. AWS Config records configuration changes but not every API action.',rule:'Audit all AWS API calls = CloudTrail → S3 + log file validation. CloudWatch = metrics/application logs. VPC Flow Logs = network traffic metadata. Config = configuration state changes over time. X-Ray = distributed tracing. CloudTrail = API calls (who did what).',keywords:'Protect CloudTrail logs from tampering → log file integrity validation + SSE-KMS on S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_62',category:'IAM',question:'A company needs secure access to its Amazon RDS for MySQL database that is used by multiple applications. Each IAM user must use a short-lived authentication token to connect to the database. Which of the following is the most suitable solution in this scenario?',choices:['A|Use AWS IAM Identity Center to access the RDS database.','B|Use IAM DB Authentication and create database accounts using the AWS-provided AWSAuthenticationPlugin plugin in MySQL.','C|Use AWS Secrets Manager to generate and store short-lived authentication tokens.','D|Use an MFA token to access and connect to a database.'],correct:'B',answer:'You can authenticate to your DB instance using AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) database authentication. IAM database authentication works with MySQL and PostgreSQL. With this authentication method, you don\'t need to use a password when you connect to a DB instance.',why:'An authentication token is a string of characters that you use instead of a password. After you generate an authentication token, it\'s valid for 15 minutes before it expires. If you try to connect using an expired token, the connection request is denied.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS IAM Identity Center to access the RDS database is incorrect because AWS IAM Identity Center just enables you to centrally manage workforce access for all of your AWS accounts managed through AWS Organizations. It does not provide a centralized access point for RDS databases.',rule:'IAM: correct. AWS IAM: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'EC2 profile credentials for RDS auth → IAM DB Authentication. Token valid 15 min. No passwords.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_63',category:'S3',question:'A company has an infrastructure that allows EC2 instances from a private subnet to fetch objects from Amazon S3 via a NAT Instance. The company’s Solutions Architect was instructed to lower down the cost incurred by the current solution. How should the Solutions Architect redesign the architecture in the most cost-efficient manner?',choices:['A|Replace the NAT instance with NAT Gateway to access S3 objects.','B|Remove the NAT instance and create an S3 gateway endpoint to access S3 objects.','C|Use a smaller instance type for the NAT instance.','D|Remove the NAT instance and create an S3 interface endpoint to access S3 objects.'],correct:'B',answer:'A VPC endpoint enables you to privately connect your VPC to supported AWS services and VPC endpoint services powered by PrivateLink without requiring an Internet gateway, NAT device, VPN connection, or AWS Direct Connect connection. Instances in your VPC do not require public IP addresses to communicate with resources in the service.',why:'Endpoints are virtual devices. They are horizontally scaled, redundant, and highly available VPC components that allow communication between instances in your VPC and services without imposing availability risks or bandwidth constraints on your network traffic.',trap:'The option that says: Use a smaller instance type for the NAT instance is incorrect. Although this might reduce the cost, it still is not the most cost-efficient solution. An S3 Gateway endpoint is still the best solution because it comes with no additional charge.',rule:'S3 Gateway Endpoint: free, private S3 access from VPC, no NAT needed. Gateway endpoints are horizontally scaled, redundant, highly available VPC components that allow communication between instances in your VPC and S3/DynamoDB without imposing bandwidth constraints or availability risks.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_64',category:'Security',question:'A news company is planning to use a Hardware Security Module (CloudHSM) in AWS for secure key storage of their web applications. You have launched the CloudHSM cluster but after just a few hours, a support staff mistakenly attempted to log in as the administrator three times using an invalid password in the Hardware Security Module. This has caused the HSM to be zeroized, which means that the encryption keys on it have been wiped. Unfortunately, you did not have a copy of the keys stored anywhere else. How can you obtain a new copy of the keys that you have stored on Hardware Security Module?',choices:['A|Restore a snapshot of the Hardware Security Module.','B|Contact AWS Support and they will provide you a copy of the keys.','C|The keys are lost permanently if you did not have a copy.','D|Use the Amazon CLI to get a copy of the keys.'],correct:'C',answer:'CloudHSM should be used over KMS when you require FIPS 140-2 Level 3 hardware security modules, need to store your keys on hardware that you control exclusively, or need to perform SSL/TLS offloading for web servers.',why:'AWS KMS uses FIPS 140-2 Level 2 HSMs. AWS CloudHSM provides dedicated HSM hardware to you — Level 3 FIPS 140-2 compliance. You have exclusive access to the key material; AWS cannot access or recover your keys. CloudHSM also supports SSL/TLS offloading and Transparent Data Encryption for databases, which KMS cannot do.',trap:'Both KMS and CloudHSM provide strong encryption key management — KMS is not inherently inferior. CloudHSM should NOT always be used for all payment transactions — KMS is sufficient for most use cases. Low packet-per-second performance is an EC2 networking concept, not relevant to key management.',rule:'CloudHSM over KMS when: FIPS 140-2 Level 3 required, exclusive key control needed, SSL/TLS offload needed, Oracle TDE required. KMS = Level 2, multi-tenant. CloudHSM = Level 3, single-tenant HSM. KMS = multi-tenant, shared. Use CloudHSM for stricter compliance requirements.',keywords:'CloudHSM: zeroized on admin password failure twice. Amazon has no key access. Requires cluster backup.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q5_65',category:'Networking',question:'A business plans to deploy an application on EC2 instances within an Amazon VPC and is considering adopting a Network Load Balancer to distribute incoming traffic among the instances. A solutions architect needs to suggest a solution that will enable the security team to inspect traffic entering and exiting their VPC. Which approach satisfies the requirements?',choices:['A|Create a firewall using the AWS Network Firewall service at the VPC level then add custom rule groups for inspecting ingress and egress traffic. Update the necessary VPC route tables.','B|Use the Network Access Analyzer service on the application’s VPC for inspecting ingress and egress traffic. Create a new Network Access Scope to filter and analyze all incoming and outgoing requests.','C|Create a firewall at the subnet level using the Amazon Detective service. Inspect the ingress and egress traffic using the VPC Reachability Analyzer.','D|Enable Traffic Mirroring on the Network Load Balancer and forward traffic to the instances. Create a traffic mirror filter to inspect the ingress and egress of data that traverses your Amazon VPC.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Network Firewall is a managed stateful firewall service at the VPC level that can inspect and filter traffic based on domain names (FQDNs), IP addresses, ports, protocols, and deep packet inspection using Suricata-compatible rules.',why:'Network Firewall creates firewall endpoints in your subnets and uses route tables to route traffic through them for inspection. It supports stateful rules (including domain-name based filtering), stateless rules for high-throughput filtering, and managed threat intelligence rule groups. It can block outbound traffic to malicious domains and inspect ingress/egress at the VPC perimeter.',trap:'Network Access Analyzer assesses VPC network paths for unintended connectivity — it is a network configuration audit tool, not a traffic filtering tool. Amazon Detective analyzes security findings for root cause — it does not filter network traffic. Traffic Mirroring captures packets for analysis but does not block traffic.',rule:'VPC-level traffic inspection + filtering (FQDNs, IPs) = AWS Network Firewall (with route table integration). Network Access Analyzer = network configuration audit. Detective = security investigation and root cause analysis. Not for network path analysis.',keywords:'VPC endpoint: Gateway type for S3/DynamoDB (free). Interface type for other services (PrivateLink, hourly).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 4'},
  {id:'q6_1',category:'S3',question:'A large corporation has several Windows file servers in various departments within its on-premises data center. To improve its data management and scalability, the corporation has to migrate and integrate its files into an Amazon FSx for Windows File Server file system while keeping the current file permissions intact. Which of the following solutions will fulfill the company\'s requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up AWS DataSync agents on the corporation\'s on-premises file servers and schedule DataSync tasks for transferring data to the FSx for Windows File Server file system.','B|Utilize the AWS CLI to copy the file shares from each on-premises file server to an Amazon S3 bucket. Then, schedule AWS DataSync tasks to move the data from S3 to the FSx for Windows File Server file system','C|Use AWS Storage Gateway to create a file gateway, then mount the file gateway on the on-premises file servers. Migrate the data from the file servers to the file gateway, and then use AWS DataSync to move the data from the file gateway to the FSx for Windows File Server file system.','D|Acquire an AWS Snowcone device, then connect with the on-premises network. Use AWS OpsHub to launch the AWS DataSync agent AMI and activate the agent via the AWS Management Console. Schedule DataSync tasks to transfer the data to the FSx for Windows File Server file system.','E|Order an AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized device, link it to the on-premises network, and transfer data using the AWS CLI. Return the device to AWS for data import into Amazon S3. Configure AWS DataSync tasks to migrate the data from S3 to the FSx for Windows File Server file system'],correct:'AD',answer:'Set up AWS DataSync agents directly on the on-premises file servers and schedule tasks (A). Or use AWS Snowcone with the pre-installed DataSync agent AMI (D) — Snowcone has DataSync pre-installed as an AMI for offline/remote locations.',why:'DataSync agents run on-premises and securely transfer files to AWS targets including FSx for Windows File Server. Option A is the standard DataSync migration pattern. Option D uses Snowcone (AWS edge device) which has DataSync agent pre-installed as an AMI — ideal for remote/disconnected locations with limited bandwidth. Both preserve file metadata and permissions during migration.',trap:'Option B (copy to S3 then DataSync to FSx) adds unnecessary complexity and an intermediate S3 step. Option C (Storage Gateway to DataSync) introduces another service layer without benefit. Option E (Snowball Edge to S3 to DataSync) uses a large device unnecessarily when Snowcone is the right edge device for DataSync.',rule:'FSx for Windows File Server + AWS DataSync for migration. DataSync agent runs on a VM with pre-installed DataSync AMI. DataSync preserves file permissions and metadata during migration to FSx.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_2',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company is preparing a solution that the sales team can use for generating weekly revenue reports. The team must be able to run analysis on sales records stored in Amazon S3 and visualize the results of queries. How can the solutions architect meet the requirement in the most cost-effective way possible?',choices:['A|Load the records into an Amazon OpenSearch (Amazon ElasticSearch) cluster. Run queries in Amazon OpenSearch and visualize the results using Kibana.','B|Load the records into an Amazon Redshift cluster. Run queries in Amazon Redshift and send the results in Amazon S3. Use Amazon QuickSight for visualization.','C|Send the records to an Amazon Kinesis Data stream. Run queries using Kinesis Data Analytics. Use Amazon QuickSight for visualization.','D|Use AWS Glue crawler to build tables in AWS Glue Data Catalog. Run queries using Amazon Athena. Use Amazon QuickSight for visualization.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Glue is a fully managed ETL (extract, transform, and load) AWS service. One of its key abilities is to analyze and categorize data. You can use AWS Glue crawlers to automatically infer database and table schema from your data in Amazon S3 and store the associated metadata in the AWS Glue Data Catalog.',why:'AWS Glue crawls your S3 data, infers the schema, and registers it in the Glue Data Catalog. An ETL job then transforms and loads the data into a target like Amazon Athena (query in place) or Redshift (analytical warehouse). Athena uses the Glue catalog as its metadata store — you query S3 data directly with standard SQL without loading it first. Amazon QuickSight connects to Athena as a data source for dashboards and visualizations. This serverless pipeline (Glue + Athena + QuickSight) needs no infrastructure to provision or manage.',trap:'The option that says: Load the records into an Amazon Redshift cluster. Run queries in Amazon Redshift and send the results in Amazon S3. Use Amazon QuickSight for visualization is incorrect. This, like the other incorrect option, could be a viable solution, but it is not the most cost-effective approach because provisioning a dedicated cluster is more expensive than using Athena for query execution.',rule:'Finally, you can then visualize your Athena SQL queries in Amazon QuickSight, which lets you easily create and publish interactive BI dashboards. Athena + QuickSight = serverless BI on S3 data.',keywords:'Kinesis Data Streams: real-time ingestion + replay. Firehose: no replay, near-real-time to S3/Redshift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_3',category:'Serverless',question:'A FinTech company has been running its compute workload on the AWS Cloud. In order to quickly release the application, the developers have deployed several Amazon EC2 instances, Auto Scaling groups and AWS Lambda functions for the different components of the application stack. After a few weeks of operation, the users are complaining of slow performance in certain components of the application. The QA engineers suspect that the servers are not able to handle the traffic being sent to the application. Which of the following actions should be taken to verify and resolve the above issue?',choices:['A|Enable AWS Compute Optimizer to see recommendations on optimal sizing of compute-related resources. Implement changes based on the recommendations.','B|Use AWS Trusted Advisor and select the cost optimization category to identify overutilized and underutilized resources. Resize the compute resources based on the recommendations.','C|Use AWS Cost Explorer to gather cost information on all compute-related resources. Increase the size of the instances based on how much budget is allowed by the company.','D|Use AWS CloudWatch to view performance metrics of the compute resources. Create a CloudWatch dashboard to identify overutilized or underutilized resources.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Compute Optimizer uses machine learning to analyze CloudWatch utilization metrics and recommends optimal EC2 instance types and sizes. It identifies over-provisioned and under-provisioned instances to reduce cost.',why:'Compute Optimizer analyzes 14 days of CloudWatch metrics (CPU, memory via CW agent, network, EBS) and provides instance type and size recommendations with projected cost savings and performance risk. It covers EC2 instances, Auto Scaling groups, EBS volumes, and Lambda functions. No agent is required for basic EC2 recommendations.',trap:'Trusted Advisor provides best-practice checks including cost optimization but gives broader, less detailed recommendations than Compute Optimizer for right-sizing. Cost Explorer shows cost trends and usage but does not recommend specific instance types. CloudWatch shows metrics but does not interpret them for right-sizing recommendations.',rule:'EC2 right-sizing recommendations = AWS Compute Optimizer (ML-based, 14-day analysis, specific instance type recommendations). Trusted Advisor = broader best practices. Cost Explorer = cost visualization and forecasting tool. Budgets = threshold alerts.',keywords:'Auto Scaling cost optimization → Target Tracking. Maintains metric at target (CPU %, ALB RPS).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_4',category:'Serverless',question:'A company wants to transfer a large amount of data (50 TB) from its Amazon S3 bucket to its data center. Due to bandwidth constraints, downloading the data directly over the internet would take too long. The company needs to transfer the data as quickly and efficiently as possible. Which of the following options is the MOST cost-effective way to transfer this data? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use an AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized device to physically transfer the data to the company\'s data center.','B|Create an AWS Lambda function to compress the data. Download the data over the internet using AWS DataSync.','C|Connect the on-premises data center to AWS Direct Connect to provide a faster and more reliable connection for transferring the data from the S3 bucket. Enable Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration in the bucket to speed up data transfers.','D|Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution for the objects in the existing S3 bucket. Download the objects through an AWS Global Accelerator standard accelerator that is integrated with the CloudFront distribution.'],correct:'AD',answer:'The AWS Snowball is a physical device offered by the AWS Snow Family that is designed to assist customers who need to run operations in austere, non-data center environments or locations with inconsistent network connectivity. The Snowball has built-in computing capabilities and provides a variety of capacity points to choose from.',why:'AWS Snowball offers two pricing options: on-demand and committed upfront pricing. When using on-demand pricing, you are charged a service fee per job, which includes 10 days of device use and a per-day fee for any additional days used before returning the device to AWS.',trap:'The option that says: Create an AWS Lambda function to compress the data. Download the data over the internet using AWS DataSync is incorrect. Lambda functions are not designed to handle such large data transfers and compression won\'t significantly reduce the data size and the transfer time, given the size of the data (50TB). Moreover, using AWS DataSync is not recommended since it has already been mentioned in the scenario that the company has a bandwidth constraint. AWS DataSync uses the public Internet to transfer data from the AWS services (such as Amazon S3) to your on-premises network.',rule:'transfer the data as quickly and efficiently as po → AWS Snowball, Edge Storage Optimized.',keywords:'Large offline data transfer (>1 week over network) → Snowball Edge. Ships data physically.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_5',category:'EC2',question:'A company plans to set up a cloud infrastructure in AWS. In the planning, it was discussed that you need to deploy two EC2 instances that should continuously run for three years. The CPU utilization of the EC2 instances is also expected to be stable and predictable. Which is the most cost-efficient Amazon EC2 Pricing type that is most appropriate for this scenario?',choices:['A|Reserved Instances','B|On-Demand instances','C|Spot instances','D|Dedicated Hosts'],correct:'A',answer:'Reserved Instances provide a significant discount (up to 75%) compared to On-Demand instance pricing. In addition, when Reserved Instances are assigned to a specific Availability Zone, they provide a capacity reservation, giving you additional confidence in your ability to launch instances when needed.',why:'Reserved Instances are a billing construct, not a type of instance. When a running On-Demand instance matches your RI attributes (instance type, region, OS, tenancy), the RI discount automatically applies — you do not need to "launch" a reserved instance. Standard RIs (up to 72% off) lock the instance family and region. Convertible RIs (up to 66% off) allow exchanging for a different instance type or OS as long as the new RI value is equal or greater. Both require 1 or 3 year terms.',trap:'On-Demand instances is incorrect because it is not cost-efficient for a three-year continuous workload. On-Demand instances would be more expensive in the long run compared to Reserved Instances.',rule:'Standard RI = up to 72% off, can sell on RI Marketplace. Convertible RI = up to 66% off, can exchange instance type/OS. Both = 1 or 3 year term, no interruption risk. Savings Plans = more flexible, covers Lambda and Fargate too. Spot = cheapest but interruptible.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_6',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A Solutions Architect must ensure that AWS resources in an Amazon VPC do not exceed their service limits. To achieve this, the architect requires a system that provides recommendations to ensure resource usage aligns with AWS best practices. Which service is the MOST effective for this task?',choices:['A|AWS Cost Explorer','B|AWS Budgets','C|AWS Trusted Advisor','D|Amazon Inspector'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Trusted Advisor is an online resources that provide a real-time recommendation to help you set up resources according to AWS best practices. It reviews your AWS environment and recommends ways to save money, improve performance, increase reliability, and strengthen security.',why:'Whether you are creating new workflows, developing applications, or managing your existing configuration, regularly use Trusted Advisor’s recommendations to keep your solutions running efficiently. Trusted Advisor includes an ever-expanding list of checks in the following five categories: Cost Optimization, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits.',trap:'The option that says: AWS Cost Explorer is incorrect because this is just a tool that enables you to view and analyze your costs and usage. You can explore your usage and costs using the main graph, the Cost Explorer cost and usage reports, or the Cost Explorer RI reports. It has an easy-to-use interface that lets you visualize, understand, and manage your AWS costs and usage over time.',rule:'AWS Trusted Advisor = real-time best practice checks across 5 categories: Cost Optimization, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, Service Limits. Regularly use recommendations to keep solutions efficient. Cost Explorer = visualize costs. Budgets = alerts on thresholds.',keywords:'Trusted Advisor: 5 categories: Cost, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, Service Limits.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_7',category:'S3',question:'The Bureau of Census and Statistics manages a geographic information systems (GIS) image database which has a single-table design. The system hosts high-resolution images that are uniquely identified by geographic codes. The database is updated on a minute-by-minute basis to detect any natural disasters like floods, volcanic eruptions, and other calamities. Due to the substantial volume of data, the department wants to migrate its existing Oracle database to the AWS Cloud. The department also aims to achieve a highly available and scalable solution, particularly during critical events and high data inflow. Which of the following options is the MOST cost-effective solution in this scenario?',choices:['A|Launch an Amazon RDS database in Multi-AZ Deployments configuration to ensure high availability and redundancy in case of failure. Set up the tables to store both the images and geographic codes','B|Store the images in the S3 bucket. Utilize Amazon Keyspaces (for Apache Cassandra) with the geographic code as the key and the corresponding image S3 URL as the value.','C|Host the images and geographic codes in an Amazon DynamoDB table. Set DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) to enhance read performance when encountering high loads.','D|Utilize an Amazon S3 bucket for storing the images. Launch an Amazon DynamoDB table with the geographic code as the primary key and the corresponding image S3 URL as the associated value.'],correct:'D',answer:'Utilizing Amazon S3 buckets for storing images can provide various benefits, including a centralized location for storing all images, making them easily accessible whenever needed. This can streamline the workflow and make it more efficient overall. By employing Amazon DynamoDB, the department can further enhance its GIS image database management.',why:'Amazon DynamoDB can also save time and effort when searching for images needed, resulting in a more efficient workflow. This is because DynamoDB can provide low latency and high throughput. Additionally, it can handle large amounts of data, making it highly scalable. By migrating its existing Oracle database to Amazon Web Services, the department can achieve its goals of improved efficiency and scalability.',trap:'The option that says: Launch an Amazon RDS database in Multi-AZ Deployments configuration to ensure high availability and redundancy in case of failure. Set up the tables to store both the images and geographic codes is incorrect. Setting up an Oracle database on an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB instance for storing high-resolution images (as blobs) and geographic codes is not the most cost-effective solution. An object storage service like Amazon S3 is the best option for storing static images. The licensing costs for Oracle are high, and managing the database might require specialized skills, leading to increased operational expenses. Storing images directly in the Oracle database can also result in higher storage requirements and may necessitate larger RDS instances.',rule:'Amazon DynamoDB can also save time and effort when searching for images needed, resulting in a more efficient workflow.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_8',category:'Serverless',question:'A global company runs a daily data processing job that takes 10 hours to complete. The company is looking to design an Amazon EMR cluster configuration that not only supports this critical workload but also integrates with Apache Ranger for table-level and column-level permission control as well as fine-grained authorization using AWS Lake Formation. Also, it is required that no data is lost during the process. Which configuration would meet the requirements while being the MOST cost-effective?',choices:['A|Set up a transient EMR cluster with the primary node on an On-Demand Instance and Spot Instances for both core and task node','B|Configure a long-running EMR cluster with all nodes - primary, core, and task - running on On-Demand Instances.','C|Implement a transient EMR cluster with the primary and core nodes on On-Demand Instances, and task nodes on Spot Instances.','D|Opt for EMR Serverless, automatically scaling resources to match the workload, and configure EMR runtime roles with AWS Lake Formation for fine-grained access control.'],correct:'A',answer:'In Amazon EMR (Elastic MapReduce), a cluster comprises three main types of nodes, each serving a specific function: Primary (master) node, Core nodes, and Task nodes. Transient cluster terminates after job completion.',why:'Primary (Master) Node: Manages the distribution of data and tasks among other nodes, monitors the health of the cluster, and communicates with external clients. It\'s responsible for orchestrating the processing of data across the cluster.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a transient EMR cluster with the primary node on an On-Demand Instance and Spot Instances for both core and task node is incorrect. This setup introduces a risk of data loss or interruption in processing due to the use of Spot Instances for core nodes, which are crucial for data processing and integrity.',rule:'There is only one core instance group or instance fleet per cluster. Multiple task instance groups allowed. Transient = cost-effective for batch.',keywords:'Non-production / fault-tolerant / batch → Spot Instances (70-90% discount, can be interrupted).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_9',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company discovered that a significant portion of their monthly bill in the AWS Cloud was due to unused Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volumes and snapshots. Having checked AWS Cost Explorer, the company expects this monthly cost to increase. The company wants to mitigate and optimize these EBS costs. Which solution will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Check the logs through Amazon Cloudwatch Logs to monitor the storage used by Amazon EBS. Then, utilize Amazon EBS Elastic Volumes to reduce the size of the EBS volumes.','B|Delete all expired and unused snapshots using the AWS CLI.','C|Create a custom script that deploys an AWS CDK application that monitors the disk space usage of EBS volumes and utilizes Amazon EBS Elastic Volumes to reduce the size of the EBS volumes.','D|Delete all expired and unused snapshots. Then, utilize the Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager to manage new snapshots.'],correct:'D',answer:'Delete all expired and unused snapshots. Then, utilize the Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager to manage new snapshots.',why:'Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager is a service that automates the creation, retention, and deletion of EBS snapshots. This service directly addresses the problem of increasing costs due to unused snapshots. Here are the following features that Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager is capable of: - Protect valuable data by enforcing a regular backup schedule.',trap:'The option that says: Delete all expired and unused snapshots using the AWS CLI is incorrect. Just like the previous option, this solution still requires manual intervention. This solution requires significant operational overhead since administrators must identify and delete the correct snapshots without accidentally removing the necessary ones. Ultimately, this solution lacks automation and would need to be repeated regularly.',rule:'Delete all expired and unused snapshots. Automated snapshots are deleted when cluster is deleted. Manual snapshots persist until deleted.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_10',category:'S3',question:'A solutions architect is formulating a strategy for a startup that needs to transfer 50 TB of on-premises data to Amazon S3. The startup has a slow network transfer speed between its data center and AWS which causes a bottleneck for data migration. Which of the following should the solutions architect implement?',choices:['A|Request an Import Job to Amazon S3 using a Snowball device in the AWS Snowball Console.','B|Deploy an AWS Migration Hub Discovery agent in the on-premises data center.','C|Enable Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration on the target S3 bucket.','D|Integrate AWS Storage Gateway File Gateway with the on-premises data center.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Snowball uses secure, rugged devices so you can bring AWS computing and storage capabilities to your edge environments, and transfer data into and out of AWS. The service delivers you Snowball Edge devices with storage and optional Amazon EC2 and AWS IOT Greengrass compute in shippable, hardened, secure cases.',why:'Snowball Edge (Storage Optimized) holds 80 TB of usable storage. AWS ships the device to you, you copy data locally over the 10 GbE/25 GbE network interface, then ship it back. AWS transfers the data from the device to S3. The entire process takes days — far faster than uploading 50 TB over a slow internet link. Data is encrypted at rest and in transit using AES-256 and TLS. Snowball Edge also has edge compute capabilities (Lambda and EC2) for data pre-processing before shipping.',trap:'The option that says: Enable Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration on the target S3 bucket is incorrect because this S3 feature is not suitable for large-scale data migration. Enabling this feature won\'t always guarantee faster data transfer as it\'s only beneficial for long-distance transfer to and from your Amazon S3 buckets.',rule:'transfer 50 tb of on-premises data to amazon s3 → Import Job, Amazon S3.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_11',category:'Serverless',question:'A technology company has a suite of container-based web applications and serverless solutions that are hosted in AWS. The Solutions Architect must define a standard infrastructure that will be used across development teams and applications. There are application-specific resources too that change frequently, especially during the early stages of application development. Developers must be able to add supplemental resources to their applications, which are beyond what the architects predefined in the system environments and service templates. Which of the following should be implemented to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Set up AWS Proton for deploying container applications and serverless solutions. Create components from the AWS Proton console and attach them to their respective service instance.','B|Use the Amazon EKS Anywhere service for deploying container applications and serverless solutions. Create a service instance for each application-specific resource.','C|Set up AWS Control Tower to automate container-based application deployments. Use AWS Config for application-specific resources that change frequently.','D|Use the Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) Anywhere service for deploying container applications and serverless solutions. Configure Prometheus metrics collection on the ECS cluster and use Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus for monitoring frequently-changing resources'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Proton allows you to deploy any serverless or container-based application with increased efficiency, consistency, and control. You can define infrastructure standards and effective continuous delivery pipelines for your organization. Proton breaks down the infrastructure into environment and service (“infrastructure as code” templates).',why:'As a developer, you select a standardized service template that AWS Proton uses to create a service that deploys and manages your application in a service instance. An AWS Proton service is an instantiation of a service template, which normally includes several service instances and a pipeline. The diagram above displays the high-level overview of a simple AWS Proton workflow.',trap:'The option that says: Use the Amazon EKS Anywhere service for deploying container applications and serverless solutions. Create a service instance for each application-specific resource is incorrect. Amazon EKS Anywhere just allows you to manage a Kubernetes cluster on external environments that are supported by AWS. It is better to use AWS Proton with custom Components that can be attached to the different service instances of the company\'s application suite.',rule:'As a developer, you select a standardized service template that AWS Proton uses to create a service that deploys and manages your application using the service template. Proton = microservices deployment automation.',keywords:'Serverless containers (no EC2 to manage) → AWS Fargate (ECS or EKS).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_12',category:'S3',question:'A company has migrated its containerized workloads into the AWS Cloud. The microservices applications are hosted on Amazon EC2 instances with Docker installed, Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS), and newer deployments are hosted on Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS). The company is using open-source tools such as Prometheus and Grafana installed on a virtual machine in its data center for monitoring its applications. The management wants to use the same tools for monitoring its containerized applications in its cloud environment. Which of the following options is the recommended implementation for this scenario?',choices:['A|Export the on-premises VM and upload the image to an Amazon S3 bucket. Use VM Import/Export to import the image and launch it as an Amazon EC2 instance. Reconfigure Prometheus and Grafana to monitor the containerized cloud workloads.','B|Create a new workspace AWS Managed Grafana to collect container metrics. Associate this as a data source in Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus. Configure data queries on Prometheus to visualize, monitor, and create alerts for the containerized workloads.','C|Create a new Amazon ECS cluster. Deploy the Prometheus and Grafana containers on this cluster for monitoring containerized workloads. Configure Prometheus for container metrics collection and Grafana for monitoring and data visualization.','D|Create a workspace on AWS Manage Service for Prometheus to collect container metrics. Set this workspace as the data source in AWS Managed Grafana for monitoring and data visualization.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus + Amazon Managed Grafana is the native AWS solution for collecting, storing, querying, and visualizing container metrics without managing the Prometheus/Grafana infrastructure.',why:'AWS Managed Service for Prometheus (AMP) is a serverless, fully compatible Prometheus monitoring service. It ingests metrics from EKS clusters via a Prometheus scraper or agent. Amazon Managed Grafana connects to AMP as a data source for visualization and alerting. Neither service requires provisioning, scaling, or patching of the underlying infrastructure.',trap:'Exporting VMs via VM Import/Export and using Grafana manually requires setting up EC2 instances and managing Grafana yourself. AWS Managed Grafana alone without a Prometheus workspace requires manual Prometheus setup. Creating an ECS cluster to run Prometheus/Grafana containers requires container infrastructure management.',rule:'EKS container metrics (Prometheus) = AMP (Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus) + Amazon Managed Grafana. Fully managed, no infrastructure to provision or scale. Alternative: CloudWatch Container Insights for simpler setups. Do not self-host Prometheus/Grafana on EC2 when managed options exist.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_13',category:'Storage',question:'A data center equipped with several physical servers is connected to AWS via a Direct Connect 10 Gbps link capacity. A solutions architect is tasked with rehosting all on-premises applications, data, and operating systems to AWS. Interruptions to business operations must be minimized as well. Which solution meets the requirement?',choices:['A|Create a migration task using AWS Database Migration Service (DMS).','B|Create a replication task using AWS Application Migration Service (MGN).','C|Create a migration plan using AWS Snowball.','D|Create a migration plan using AWS DataSync via a scheduled periodic replication every hour'],correct:'B',answer:'Lift-and-shift (also known as “rehost”) is a common approach for migrating to AWS, whereby you move a workload from on-premises with little or no modification.',why:'AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) is a highly automated lift-and-shift solution that works by replicating your on-premises (physical or virtual) and/or cloud servers (referred to as “source servers”) into your AWS account. When you’re ready, AWS MGN automatically converts and launches your servers on AWS so you can quickly benefit from the cost savings, productivity, resilience, and agility of the cloud.',trap:'The option that says: Create a migration plan using AWS Snowball is incorrect. Snowball is useful for transferring large amounts of data using a physical device that you ship to AWS. It\'s not suitable for the replication of on-premises applications to AWS.',rule:'AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) is a highly automated lift-and-shift solution that works by replicating your on-premises (physical or virtual) servers and databases to AWS. Installs replication agent. Cutover in minutes.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_14',category:'Kinesis',question:'A manufacturing company is building an IoT-based system to detect faults in its production process in real-time. The system will feed sensor data to an Amazon API Gateway REST API, where the data will be analyzed for any anomalies or faults. The result of the data processing will then determine the necessary remedial action to be taken. It\'s critical that the data is processed in the sequence in which it was sent. Which of the following is the most operationally efficient solution?',choices:['A|Utilize an API Gateway integration to send incoming data to an Amazon Kinesis Data Stream. Attach an AWS Lambda function to the Kinesis stream to process the data.','B|Implement an API Gateway authorizer to ensure that the data stream is processed in real-time and in order of arrival.','C|Store incoming data in Amazon S3 and trigger an AWS Lambda function to process the data via S3 Event Notification','D|Store incoming data in a standard Amazon SQS queue and configure an AWS Lambda function to process the data as it arrives in the queue.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon API Gateway is an AWS service for creating, publishing, maintaining, monitoring, and securing REST, HTTP, and WebSocket APIs at any scale. API developers can create APIs that access AWS or other web services, as well as data stored in the AWS Cloud.',why:'You can use an AWS Lambda function to process records in an Amazon Kinesis data stream. A Kinesis data stream is a set of shards. Each shard contains a sequence of data records. A consumer is an application that processes the data from a Kinesis data stream. You can map a Lambda function to a shared-throughput consumer (standard iterator), or to a dedicated-throughput consumer with enhanced fan-out.',trap:'The option that says: Implement an API Gateway authorizer to ensure that the data stream is processed in real-time and in order of arrival is incorrect because an API Gateway authorizer is not designed to ensure that data is processed in real-time nor in a specific order. Its primary function is to control access to an API by validating incoming requests.',rule:'Real-time → Amazon Kinesis Data Stream, AWS Lambda function to t.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_15',category:'Networking',question:'An online shopping platform is hosted on an Auto Scaling group of On-Demand EC2 instances with a default Auto Scaling termination policy and no instance protection configured. The system is deployed across three Availability Zones in the US West region (us-west-1) with an Application Load Balancer in front to provide high availability and fault tolerance for the shopping platform. The us-west-1a, us-west-1b, and us-west-1c Availability Zones have 10, 8 and 7 running instances respectively. Due to the low number of incoming traffic, the scale-in operation has been triggered. Which of the following will the Auto Scaling group do to determine which instance to terminate first in this scenario? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Choose the Availability Zone with the most number of instances, which is the us-west-1a Availability Zone in this scenario.','B|Choose the Availability Zone with the least number of instances, which is the us-west-1c Availability Zone in this scenario.','C|Select the instances with the most recent launch template.','D|Select the instances with the oldest launch template.','E|Select the instance that is closest to the next billing hour.','F|Select the instance that is farthest to the next billing hour.'],correct:'ACE',answer:'The ASG default termination policy first identifies the AZ with the most instances (us-west-1a with 7), then within that AZ selects the instance with the oldest launch configuration, and finally the one closest to the next billing hour. This design balances AZs and retires instances running the oldest configuration.',why:'Default termination policy steps: (1) find AZ with most instances to rebalance, (2) within that AZ pick the instance using the oldest launch configuration or template, (3) if tied, pick the instance nearest to the next billing hour. This gradually replaces instances running stale configurations. You can override with custom termination policies (OldestInstance, NewestInstance, ClosestToNextInstanceHour, OldestLaunchConfiguration, AllocationStrategy).',trap:'The option that says: Select the instance that is farthest to the next billing hour is incorrect because instances that are closest to the next billing hour will be terminated by default. This rule enables you to get the most out of your hourly-charged instances.',rule:'Choose the Availability Zone with the most number of instances, which is the us-west-1a Availability Zone in this scenario.',keywords:'ASG AZ rebalancing terminates from AZ with most instances. Choose AZ with most instances to terminate.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_16',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A Solutions Architect uses AWS Lake Formation to manage a data lake that stores petabytes of data spread across various AWS accounts. The data lake contains various reporting data that are uploaded by both the Data Analytics and the DevOps team. The Data Analytics team wants to selectively share certain data from its accounts in a secure manner with the company\'s DevOps team for reporting purposes. Strict data access control and monitoring must be implemented to meet security and compliance requirements. Which of the following is the most operationally efficient way to fulfill these requirements with MINIMAL operational overhead?',choices:['A|Replicate the necessary data to a central AWS account. Set up AWS Organizations and AWS Control Tower for governance and security standardization. Establish an IAM access role in the central account. Define a permission policy that includes trusted entities from the Data Analytics team accounts and facilitated through AWS Organizations.','B|Utilize the AWS Lake Formation permissions "Grant" command in each account to give the DevOps teams access to specific datasets. Implement AWS Security Hub Integration to ensure robust security monitoring.','C|Use AWS Data Exchange to securely share required data with designated DevOps team accounts. Implement Lake Formation permissions "Grant" command within each account for fine-grained control.','D|Implement Lake Formation tag-based access control to enable authorization and cross-account permissions for the needed datasets to engineering team accounts. Integrate with AWS Security Hub to enhance security monitoring and compliance oversight.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Lake Formation is a robust data lake-building service that simplifies creating, securing, and managing data lakes. It provides a centralized location for storing data from various sources and enables you to analyze this data using a wide range of AWS tools and services.',why:'Tag-based access control in AWS Lake Formation is a powerful way to ensure that only authorized users can access sensitive data. By attaching tags to data, you can control who can access that data based on the tags they have been assigned. For example, you might have a "sensitive" tag attached to all personal information data. You could then grant access to this data only to users assigned the "sensitive" tag.',trap:'The option that says: Replicate the necessary data to a central AWS account. Set up AWS Organizations and AWS Control Tower for governance and security standardization. Establish an IAM access role in the central account. Define a permission policy that includes trusted entities from the Data Analytics team accounts and facilitated through AWS Organizations is incorrect. Replicating the necessary data to a central AWS account, as well as setting up AWS Organizations and AWS Control Tower for governance and security standardization, can introduce unnecessary complexity and operational overhead. Managing petabytes of data in a central account might lead to data transfer costs, increased latency for data access, and potential data consistency issues. While establishing an IAM access role in the central account and defining permission policies through AWS Organizations can provide some control, it may not be the most efficient way to manage access to data spread across various AWS accounts.',rule:'Tag-based access control in AWS Lake Formation is a powerful way to ensure that only authorized users can access sensitive data.',keywords:'Large offline data transfer (>1 week over network) → Snowball Edge. Ships data physically.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_17',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a mission-critical, public-facing containerized application running on an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster that has a microservices architecture. There is a requirement to implement a fully managed centralized application logging solution that automatically collects metrics and application logs. The company also requires a dashboard to easily monitor the application metrics. Which of the following can meet the above requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead?',choices:['A|Set up and configure Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus metrics collection for the EKS cluster by installing the Prometheus agent on all EKS pods. Launch a dashboard in Amazon Managed Grafana to visualize metrics and logs in Amazon EKS.','B|Install and set up the Amazon CloudWatch agent on the Amazon EKS cluster to collect the metrics. Use the CloudWatch dashboard to view the application logs.','C|Use Amazon OpenSearch Service with an integration to an Amazon EKS cluster to collect and store application logs and metrics. Use OpenSearch Dashboards to monitor and visualize the application’s performance.','D|Use Amazon CloudWatch Container Insights with the Amazon EKS cluster. Use the CloudWatch dashboard to view the application logs and metrics.'],correct:'D',answer:'Use CloudWatch Container Insights to collect, aggregate, and summarize metrics and logs from your containerized applications and microservices. Container Insights is available for Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS), Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS), and Kubernetes platforms on Amazon EC2.',why:'CloudWatch automatically collects metrics for many resources, such as CPU, memory, disk, and network. Container Insights also provides diagnostic information, such as container restart failures, to help you isolate issues and resolve them quickly. You can also set CloudWatch alarms on metrics that Container Insights collects. Container Insights collects data as performance log events using embedded metric format.',trap:'The option that says: Install and set up the Amazon CloudWatch agent on the Amazon EKS cluster to collect the metrics. Use the CloudWatch dashboard to view the application logs is incorrect.  Even though using CloudWatch agent can collect metrics and application logs from an Amazon EKS Cluster, it requires some operational overhead because the CloudWatch agent has to be manually configured to collect the application logs from /var/log/containers directory on each node. Also, using a CloudWatch Dashboard does not provide the same level of granularity and aggregation as CloudWatch Container Insights.',rule:'CloudWatch automatically collects metrics for many resources, such as CPU, memory, disk, and network.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_18',category:'Serverless',question:'A Solution Architect is working on a cloud infrastructure project for a company that uses AWS services. The company uses multiple EC2 and Amazon RDS DB instances on various applications. As part of the task, the company asked to create a solution that automatically starts and stops the EC2 and DB instances based on a predetermined schedule. Which option will enable the Solution Architect to fulfill the company\'s requirements while minimizing cost and infrastructure maintenance?',choices:['A|Utilize elastic resizing to scale the EC2 instances and automatically scale the DB instances to zero during periods outside the predetermined schedule.','B|Set up a crontab schedule to run shell scripts that start and stop EC2 and RDS instances at specific times, enabling automatic management of the instances based on the predetermined schedule.','C|Search various partner solutions on the AWS Marketplace that offer automated start and stop functionalities for EC2 and RDS instances according to predefined schedules.','D|Generate an AWS Lambda function to start and stop EC2 and RDS DB instances. Set up Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to trigger the Lambda function based on a predefined schedule.'],correct:'D',answer:'Automating the task of initiating and terminating EC2 and DB instances on a predefined schedule can be achieved by using a Lambda Function and Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) together. The first step is to create a Lambda Function that contains the necessary code to initiate and terminate the EC2 and DB instances.',why:'Next, a predefined schedule can be set up in Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to trigger the Lambda Function at specific times or intervals. This involves creating a rule in EventBridge and specifying the schedule using a cron expression. When the scheduled time, EventBridge triggers the Lambda Function, which executes the code to initiate or terminate the EC2 and DB instances.',trap:'The option that says: Utilize elastic resizing to scale the EC2 instances and automatically scale the DB instances to zero during periods outside the predetermined schedule is incorrect. Elastic resizing is a feature that allows you to automatically adjust the size of your EC2 instances based on demand. While this can help with scaling your instances, it does not provide a direct solution for automatically starting and stopping instances based on a predetermined schedule.',rule:'Scheduled Lambda execution = Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to trigger the Lambda Function at specific times using cron or rate expressions. EventBridge is the standard for all scheduled AWS automation.',keywords:'CloudWatch Container Insights: ECS/EKS metrics and logs. Prometheus for custom container metrics.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_19',category:'Storage',question:'A manufacturing company is utilizing an on-premises network-attached storage (NAS) system to support file sharing for their latency-sensitive high-performance computing (HPC) workloads. In a direction to move the system to the cloud, a solutions architect is consulted to maintain the same low-latency performance in the company’s on-premises network. The company requires a solution that can provide multi-protocol access to data from the file system that supports Network File System (NFS), Server Message Block (SMB), and Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) protocols. Which options achieve these requirements with the LOWEST latency? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Associate an Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP file system to the EC2 instances.','B|Connect an Amazon FSx for OpenZFS file system to the EC2 instances.','C|Mount an Amazon FSx for Windows File Server to the EC2 instances.','D|Group compute-optimized EC2 instances together within a cluster placement group.','E|Optimize performance by using a partition placement group when deploying the compute-optimized EC2 instances.'],correct:'AD',answer:'Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP provides NAS (Network Attached Storage) file services with NFS, SMB, and iSCSI protocols — supporting both Linux and Windows EC2 instances simultaneously from a single file system.',why:'FSx for NetApp ONTAP is a fully managed ONTAP file system. It natively supports NFS (Linux), SMB (Windows), and iSCSI protocols from the same file system. This makes it ideal for mixed-OS environments where the same data needs to be accessed from both Linux and Windows workloads. It also supports data tiering, snapshots, and replication.',trap:'FSx for OpenZFS supports NFS only — not SMB/CIFS for Windows. FSx for Windows File Server supports SMB but not NFS for Linux without additional setup. Using a partition placement group collocates instances for low latency but does not provide shared storage.',rule:'Shared storage for Linux + Windows EC2 simultaneously = FSx for NetApp ONTAP (supports NFS + SMB + iSCSI). FSx for Windows = SMB only. FSx for OpenZFS = NFS only. EFS = NFS only.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_20',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A multinational corporation is expanding its operations and needs to efficiently monitor and analyze IAM-related errors, specifically Access Denied and Unauthorized errors in their AWS accounts. The company has AWS CloudTrail enabled for logging purposes. Which solution would meet the requirements while requiring the least effort to implement?',choices:['A|Utilize AWS Security Hub to aggregate and analyze security data, including CloudTrail logs, for IAM permission errors.','B|Query with AWS CloudTrail Lake to find specific errors in CloudTrail logs.','C|Use Amazon Athena to search for IAM-related errors within CloudTrail logs.','D|Configure Amazon QuickSight to analyze CloudTrail logs and create a dashboard for monitoring IAM-related errors.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS CloudTrail Lake lets you run SQL-based queries on your event logs in AWS CloudTrail. It provides a robust and efficient way to directly analyze CloudTrail logs. CloudTrail Lake converts existing events in row-based JSON format to Apache ORC format. ORC is a columnar storage format that is optimized for fast retrieval of data.',why:'In the question, CloudTrail Lake is particularly suitable because it enables direct querying of specific IAM-related errors like Access Denied and Unauthorized errors. This approach minimizes implementation efforts and maximizes efficiency in troubleshooting, as it leverages existing CloudTrail logs without the need for additional data processing or integration with other services.',trap:'The option that says: Utilize AWS Security Hub to aggregate and analyze security data, including CloudTrail logs, for IAM permission errors is incorrect. While AWS Security Hub is an excellent tool for aggregating and analyzing security data, it is not as direct and specific for querying CloudTrail logs for IAM errors compared to CloudTrail Lake. Security Hub is more about providing a comprehensive view of security posture across various AWS services rather than detailed querying of specific log entries.',rule:'efficiently monitor and analyze iam-related errors → AWS CloudTrail.',keywords:'AWS Config: resource configuration history and compliance. CloudTrail = API activity. Config = resource state.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_21',category:'Storage',question:'An animation studio uses high-performance computing (HPC) servers for rendering gigabytes of video data. The studio are planning to migrate their environment to AWS and are in need of a highly available parallel file system for asset storage. The file system will be accessed concurrently by a fleet of EC2 instances and must be capable of sustained throughput. Which AWS storage solution should the solutions architect recommend?',choices:['A|Amazon FSx for Lustre with Persistent file system','B|Amazon Elastic File System (EFS) with Elastic Throughput mode','C|Amazon FSx for Lustre with Scratch file system','D|Amazon File Cache'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon FSx for Lustre is an ideal solution for the animation studio\'s requirements. FSx for Lustre provides a fully managed, high-performance, scalable storage service, specifically designed for compute-intensive workloads like 3D animation rendering.',why:'FSx for Lustre is a POSIX-compliant parallel file system that delivers sub-millisecond latencies and hundreds of GB/s of throughput by striping data across multiple storage nodes. It natively integrates with S3 — you can import datasets from S3 at mount time and export results back to S3 when complete. This makes it ideal for burst HPC workloads that need fast scratch storage without permanently provisioning large capacity.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon Elastic File System (EFS) with Elastic Throughput mode is incorrect because while Amazon EFS with Elastic Throughput mode provides a scalable file storage solution capable of adapting its throughput to the changing performance needs, it may not consistently deliver the high levels of throughput and low latency required for the most demanding high-performance computing (HPC) workloads. EFS is designed for a broad range of use cases, including web serving, content management, and home directories, but it lacks the specialized, high-performance parallel file system capabilities that Amazon FSx for Lustre offers, making it less suited for large-scale 3D animation rendering tasks that demand optimal performance.',rule:'Amazon FSx for Lustre with Persistent file system.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_22',category:'S3',question:'A bank runs a daily AWS Glue ETL job to process XML financial data in an Amazon S3 bucket. New datasets are added to this S3 bucket each day. The solutions architect has observed that AWS Glue is repeatedly processing the entire dataset, including previously processed data, in every execution. The bank seeks an efficient method to ensure the AWS Glue ETL job processes only new or altered data, thus optimizing resources and processing time while maintaining data integrity. Which solution can satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Enable job bookmarks on the AWS Glue job.','B|Alter the AWS Glue job to incorporate the AWS Glue Data Quality feature.','C|Adjust the AWS Glue job configuration by setting the NumberOfWorkers field to 3.','D|Use the FindMatches machine learning (ML) transform within the AWS Glue job to selectively process the data.'],correct:'A',answer:'Job bookmarks in AWS Glue are designed to help maintain state information and prevent the reprocessing of old data. By utilizing job bookmarks, AWS Glue can effectively track the states of various elements of jobs, such as sources, transformations, and targets.',why:'Furthermore, the flexibility and control provided by job bookmarks are particularly valuable. For instance, AWS Glue for Spark uses job bookmarks to track data that has already been processed, adding a layer of efficiency and precision to data processing tasks. This aspect is crucial for the bank\'s need to optimize resources and processing time while maintaining the integrity of its data processing workflow.',trap:'The option that says: Alter the AWS Glue job to incorporate the AWS Glue Data Quality feature is incorrect. While the AWS Glue Data Quality feature is beneficial for maintaining data quality, it does not specifically address the need to process only new or modified data, as required by the firm.',rule:'Furthermore, the flexibility and control provided by job bookmarks are particularly valuable.',keywords:'AWS Glue: serverless ETL. Crawlers discover schema. Data Catalog stores metadata. Jobs transform data.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_23',category:'Networking',question:'A company is revamping its existing stateless inventory management system. The application is deployed across 7 EC2 instances in multiple Availability Zones behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The application is designed to handle varying traffic patterns. Still, engineers have observed that traffic is consistently routed to a single EC2 instance, resulting in performance bottlenecks and higher latency for some requests. What is the most effective solution to resolve the underlying load balancing issue?',choices:['A|Turn off sticky sessions on the Application Load Balancer (ALB).','B|Utilize a Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB) instead of an ALB.','C|Terminate the favored EC2 instance and redeploy the remaining 6 EC2 instances evenly across all Availability Zones in the region.','D|Modify the interval for health checks in the ALB\'s target group settings.'],correct:'A',answer:'Sticky Sessions (also known as session affinity) is an option that you can enable in an ALB. When enabled, this causes traffic to be routed to the same EC2 instance based on the client session.',why:'While turning this feature on can be beneficial for maintaining user session data, it can lead to uneven load distribution if a large number of requests or sessions are directed to a single instance, as observed by the company in the given scenario. By turning off sticky sessions, the ALB will distribute incoming traffic more evenly across all available EC2 instances, rather than sending repeated requests from the same user to the same instance.',trap:'The option that says: Terminate the favored EC2 instance and redeploy the remaining 6 EC2 instances evenly across all Availability Zones in the region is incorrect. Having an even distribution of EC2 instances across Availability Zones does not solve the root cause of the problem. The traffic will still favor an EC2 instance without any other configurations, even after executing this solution.',rule:'While turning this feature on can be beneficial for maintaining user session data, it can lead to uneven load distribution if a large number of users always route to the same instance, causing imbalanced load.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_24',category:'Serverless',question:'A company uses a PostgreSQL database for its E-commerce application. This database runs on an Amazon EC2 instance. The company conducts a sales event every month for five days. Database usage and database connection errors increase every month during these five days. Although traffic is relatively high in the sales event compared to regular days, the traffic in the five days of the monthly sales event is quite unpredictable. The company needs its database to remain performant amidst these unpredictable workloads during a monthly sales event. What is the most effective solution to solve the underlying issue?',choices:['A|Upgrade the PostgreSQL database system by migrating to Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 for enhanced scalability and efficiency.','B|Upgrade the PostgreSQL database system by migrating to a larger instance type and configure an RDS Proxy for this database.','C|Upgrade the PostgreSQL database system by migrating to Amazon Aurora and enabling Auto Scaling.','D|Upgrade the PostgreSQL database system by migrating to a data warehouse like Amazon Redshift.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 suits the most demanding, highly variable workloads. In contrast, Aurora provisioned clusters are suitable for steady workloads. With provisioned clusters, you choose a DB instance class with a predefined amount of memory, CPU power, I/O bandwidth, etc.',why:'In the given context, utilizing Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 is an excellent solution since it handles high and unpredictable workloads. As stated in the scenario, the company only witnesses this high and unpredictable workload for five days every month during their monthly sales event. Amazon Aurora v2 can easily handle this high and unpredictable workload without underperforming.',trap:'The option that says: Upgrade the PostgreSQL database system by migrating to a larger instance type and configure an RDS Proxy for this database is incorrect. Although migrating to Amazon RDS and provisioning a high-end instance type may be able to mitigate database workloads to a certain extent, it is still considered vertical scaling. Since the given scenario stated that the workload increases every month, there will surely come a time when the new instance type will reach its limit, and the company will upgrade the instance type again. Additionally, although configuring an RDS proxy makes the entire application resilient to connection errors and database failures, this solution does not solve the scaling issue during peak times.',rule:'As stated in the scenario, the company only witnesses this high and unpredictable workload for five days every month during their monthly sales cycle. Predictive scaling uses ML to provision capacity before peak traffic arrives.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_25',category:'Serverless',question:'A solutions architect is designing a plan to recover from accidental writes and deletes on an Amazon DynamoDB table. The solution must be capable of recovering data up to an hour prior to the occurrence of an incident. Which approach should be taken to meet these criteria?',choices:['A|Create a DynamoDB global table. In case of an incident, direct the application’s requests to the global table’s endpoint.','B|Enable DynamoDB Streams to record all changes made to the table. Use a Lambda function to restore the table in case of an incident.','C|Enable Point-In-Time Recovery (PITR) in DynamoDB. Restore the table in case of an incident.','D|Export DynamoDB data to S3 Glacier daily for disaster recovery'],correct:'C',answer:'Point-in-time recovery (PITR) is a useful feature that can protect your DynamoDB tables from accidental write or delete operations. With this feature, you can eliminate the need for manual backups, scheduling, and maintenance.',why:'PITR allows you to create continuous backups of your table and restore it to any specific point in time within a retention period of up to 35 days. In the scenario, you can use PITR to achieve the recovery point objective of one hour by restoring the table to a state just before any corruption occurs.',trap:'The option that says: Create a DynamoDB global table. In case of an incident, direct the application’s requests to the global table’s endpoint is incorrect because any changes made to the primary table are propagated to global tables. If an item in the primary table is accidentally deleted, the same change will appear in the global table. Thus, simply updating or querying the global table won\'t recover the lost data.',rule:'PITR allows you to create continuous backups of your table and restore it to any specific point in time within a retention period of up to 35 days. Restores to a new table. Point-in-time = continuous backup, not periodic snapshots.',keywords:'Auto Scaling warm pool: pre-initialized instances reduce scale-out latency. Lifecycle hooks for custom actions.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_26',category:'S3',question:'A retail company stores customer transaction data on AWS. The data sees high access rates during seasonal sales and fluctuating access patterns throughout the rest of the year. The company is looking for a cost-effective storage solution that guarantees both durability and high availability to accommodate these varying access patterns. Which Amazon S3 storage classes fulfill these requirements?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 Express One Zone','B|Amazon S3 Standard-Infrequent Access','C|Amazon S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval','D|Amazon S3 Intelligent-Tiering'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon S3 Intelligent-Tiering is an S3 storage class that automatically moves data between two access tiers: frequent access and infrequent access. This service is designed to optimize storage costs for data with unpredictable or changing access patterns. When a new object is uploaded to S3 Intelligent-Tiering, it is initially stored in the frequent access tier.',why:'The S3 Intelligent-Tiering storage class guarantees high availability and durability, making it ideal for workloads with variable access patterns. It also ensures that data is readily available when needed, even during periods of high demand, while reducing costs when the data becomes less frequently accessed. Additionally, since both access tiers are designed for high durability (99.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon S3 Express One Zone is incorrect because it only stores data in a single availability zone, making it less suitable for use cases that require high durability and availability. It is designed for use cases where data can be easily recreated or where high availability across multiple regions is not a priority.',rule:'HA → Amazon S3 Intelligent. Not Amazon S3.',keywords:'Unknown/unpredictable access patterns → S3 Intelligent-Tiering (auto-tiers, monitoring fee).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_27',category:'Serverless',question:'A digital bank has recently deployed a fraud detection model in AWS Lambda. The company intends to put the model to test by processing transactions that are recorded in the production DynamoDB table. The security team must be immediately notified when a transaction is flagged as fraudulent. How can the solutions architect satisfy the requirements while minimizing the impact on database operations and performance?',choices:['A|Insert data into the table using DynamoDB transactions and set the Lambda function as target. Send alerts to the team by having each member subscribed to an SNS topic.','B|Create a local secondary index and project the attributes required by the model into it. Run the Lambda function on schedule and let the team subscribe to an SNS topic for notification.','C|Enable DynamoDB Streams and set the Lambda function as the trigger. Alert each member by having them subscribed to an SNS topic.','D|Create a DynamoDB global table for the Lambda function to work on. Send notifications to the team members using Amazon SQS.'],correct:'C',answer:'DynamoDB Streams captures a time-ordered sequence of item-level modifications in any DynamoDB table and stores this information in a log for up to 24 hours. Applications can access this log and view the data items as they appeared before and after they were modified, in near-real-time.',why:'You can consume logs stored in DynamoDB streams in multiple ways. The most common approaches use AWS Lambda or a standalone application that uses the Kinesis Client Library (KCL) with the DynamoDB Streams Kinesis Adapter. In the scenario, we use a Lambda function where the fraud detection model is deployed.',trap:'The option that says: Insert data into the table using DynamoDB transactions and set the Lambda function as target. Send alerts to the team by having each member subscribed to an SNS topic is incorrect. DynamoDB Transactions is just a way for you to group a series of operations into a single transaction. This is desirable when you have applications that require an ACID-compliant database such as those that process financial transactions. Setting a Lambda function as a target is not possible with DynamoDB Transactions.',rule:'Applications can access this log and view the data items as they appeared before and after they were modified, in near-real-time.',keywords:'Row-level DB change trigger → DynamoDB Streams → Lambda. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_28',category:'Serverless',question:'An e-commerce company is redesigning the architecture of its application. The new architecture needs a more robust application layer and an online transactional processing (OLTP) relational database that can handle spiky traffic loads. The company also wants to ensure the application is always available while minimizing computing costs during idle periods. As the company\'s solution architect, which solution would be the most cost-effective to meet these requirements?',choices:['A|Utilize Amazon EC2 instances with a burstable instance type to operate the application and adopt Amazon Redshift as the database.','B|Use Amazon ECS on AWS Fargate to run the application in containers and opt for Amazon Aurora Serverless to host the database.','C|Utilize AWS Elastic Beanstalk to deploy the application, use a MySQL database on Amazon RDS, then configure Auto Scaling to scale down the number of EC2 instances during idle periods.','D|Use Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group behind an Application Load Balancer. Implement Amazon RDS for MySQL for the database.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon ECS on AWS Fargate is a container orchestration solution that allows the company to execute containerized apps without handling the underlying infrastructure. It handles infrastructure scaling, patching, and provisioning, giving the company more time to focus on creating and deploying applications.',why:'Amazon Aurora Serverless, on the other hand, is a fully managed, auto-scaling relational database engine that eliminates the need to manage infrastructure, providing the company with cost savings and scalability. It offers an excellent option for hosting databases for applications with unpredictable workloads or low usage patterns.',trap:'The option that says: Utilize Amazon EC2 instances with a burstable instance type to operate the application and adopt Amazon Redshift as the database is incorrect because Amazon Redshift is designed primarily for Online Analytical Processing (OLAP) workloads, which are optimized for querying large datasets and generating complex reports. While burstable instance types can provide a cost-effective approach, they may not be able to sustain prolonged periods of high traffic when their credit balance reaches 0.',rule:'Amazon Aurora Serverless, on the other hand, is a fully managed, auto-scaling relational database engine that eliminates the need to manage  Not Amazon Redshift.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_29',category:'Networking',question:'A company faces performance degradation due to intermittent traffic spikes in its application. The application is deployed across multiple EC2 instances within an Auto Scaling group and is fronted by a Network Load Balancer (NLB). The operations team found out that HTTP errors are not being detected by the NLB. As a result, clients are continuously routed to unhealthy targets and are never replaced, which impacts the availability of the application. Which solution could resolve the issue with the least amount of development overhead? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in place of the NLB. Enable HTTP health checks using the application\'s path.','B|Increase the NLB\'s idle timeout to allow more time for requests to be processed, reducing the occurrence of intermittent HTTP/s errors.','C|Configure CloudFront as a content delivery network (CDN) in front of the NLB to reduce the load on the instances and improve performance.','D|Configure the NLB to perform HTTP health checks on the critical paths of the application.'],correct:'BD',answer:'Network Load Balancer (NLB) is a highly scalable load-balancing service that AWS provides. It is designed to handle substantial traffic volumes and distribution of incoming connections across healthy targets within one or more target groups, including Amazon EC2 instances, containers, IP addresses, or Lambda functions.',why:'NLBs utilize active and passive health checks to assess a target\'s capability to handle requests. These health checks are essential for the NLB component within an Amazon VPC as they regularly confirm the availability and responsiveness of registered targets. Through TCP, UDP, or TLS protocol requests, the health check guarantees that only healthy targets receive traffic.',trap:'The option that says: Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in place of the NLB. Enable HTTP health checks using the application\'s path is incorrect. Switching from NLB to ALB involves a significant architectural change and could potentially require updating the application code to work with ALB.',rule:'Through TCP, UDP, or TLS protocol requests, the health check guarantees that only healthy targets receive traffic.',keywords:'ALB/NLB surge handling: target tracking scale-out. SQS buffer decouples ingestion from processing spikes.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_30',category:'Serverless',question:'A retail website has intermittent, sporadic, and unpredictable transactional workloads throughout the day that are hard to predict. The website is currently hosted on-premises and is slated to be migrated to AWS. A new relational database is needed that autoscales capacity to meet the needs of the application\'s peak load and scales back down when the surge of activity is over. Which of the following option is the MOST cost-effective and suitable database setup in this scenario?',choices:['A|Launch an Amazon Aurora Serverless DB cluster then set the minimum and maximum capacity for the cluster.','B|Launch an Amazon Aurora Provisioned DB cluster with burstable performance DB instance class types.','C|Launch a DynamoDB Global table with Auto Scaling enabled.','D|Launch an Amazon Redshift data warehouse cluster with Concurrency Scaling.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Aurora Serverless is an on-demand, auto-scaling configuration for Amazon Aurora. An Aurora Serverless DB cluster is a DB cluster that automatically starts up, shuts down, and scales up or down its compute capacity based on your application\'s needs.',why:'Take note that a non-Serverless DB cluster for Aurora is called a provisioned DB cluster. Aurora Serverless clusters and provisioned clusters both have the same kind of high-capacity, distributed, and highly available storage volume.',trap:'The option that says: Launch an Amazon Aurora Provisioned DB cluster with burstable performance DB instance class types is incorrect because an Aurora Provisioned DB cluster is not suitable for intermittent, sporadic, and unpredictable transactional workloads. This model works well when the database workload is predictable because you can adjust capacity manually based on the expected workload. A better database setup here is to use an Amazon Aurora Serverless cluster.',rule:'Take note that a non-Serverless DB cluster for Aurora is called a provisioned DB cluster. Not Aurora Provisioned.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_31',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to design an application that can handle batch processing of large amounts of financial data. The Solutions Architect is tasked to create two Amazon S3 buckets to store the input and output data. The application will transfer the data between multiple EC2 instances over the network to complete the data processing. Which of the following options would reduce the data transfer costs?',choices:['A|Deploy the Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer.','B|Deploy the Amazon EC2 instances in the same Availability Zone.','C|Deploy the Amazon EC2 instances in the same AWS Region.','D|Deploy the Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets in different Availability Zones.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) provides scalable computing capacity in the Amazon Web Services (AWS) Cloud. Using Amazon EC2 eliminates your need to invest in hardware up front, so you can develop and deploy applications faster. You can use Amazon EC2 to launch as many or as few virtual servers as you need, configure security and networking, and manage storage.',why:'In this scenario, you should deploy all the EC2 instances in the same Availability Zone. If you recall, data transferred between Amazon EC2, Amazon RDS, Amazon Redshift, Amazon ElastiCache instances, and Elastic Network Interfaces in the same Availability Zone is free. Instead of using the public network to transfer the data, you can use the private network to reduce the overall data transfer costs.',trap:'The option that says: Deploy the Amazon EC2 instances in the same AWS Region is incorrect because even if the instances are deployed in the same Region, they could still be charged with inter-Availability Zone data transfers if the instances are distributed across different availability zones. You must deploy the instances in the same Availability Zone to avoid the data transfer costs.',rule:'Amazon EC2 instances in the same Avai: correct. Amazon EC2: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_32',category:'Route 53',question:'An advertising company is currently working on a proof of concept project that automatically provides SEO analytics for its clients. Your company has a VPC in AWS that operates in a dual-stack mode in which IPv4 and IPv6 communication is allowed. You deployed the application to an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances with an Application Load Balancer in front that evenly distributes the incoming traffic. You are ready to go live but you need to point your domain name (tutorialsdojo.com) to the Application Load Balancer. In Route 53, which record types will you use to point the DNS name of the Application Load Balancer? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Non-Alias with a type "A" record set. Always use Alias records for AWS resources — no extra DNS lookup cost.','B|Alias with a type "AAAA" record set','C|Alias with a type "CNAME" record set','D|Alias with a type "A" record set','E|Alias with a type of “MX” record set'],correct:'BD',answer:'The correct answers are: Alias with a type "AAAA" record set and Alias with a type "A" record set. To route domain traffic to an ELB load balancer, use Amazon Route 53 to create an alias record that points to your load balancer. An alias record is a Route 53 extension to DNS.',why:'To route domain traffic to an ELB load balancer, use Amazon Route 53 to create an alias record that points to your load balancer. An alias record is a Route 53 extension to DNS. It\'s similar to a CNAME record, but you can create an alias record both for the root domain, such as tutorialsdojo.com and for subdomains, such as portal.tutorialsdojo.com.',trap:'Non-Alias with a type "A" record set is incorrect because you only use Non-Alias with a type “A” record set for IP addresses.',rule:'Route 53 to ELB: use Alias with type A (IPv4) or AAAA (IPv6) record. Cannot use Non-Alias A record or CNAME for zone apex. Alias records are free and resolve directly to ELB DNS without an extra DNS lookup.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_33',category:'Networking',question:'A company has a two-tier environment in its on-premises data center which is composed of an application tier and database tier. You are instructed to migrate their environment to the AWS cloud, and to design the subnets in their VPC with the following requirements: 1. There is an application load balancer that would distribute the incoming traffic among the servers in the application tier. 2. The application tier and the database tier must not be accessible from the public Internet. The application tier should only accept traffic coming from the load balancer. 3. The database tier contains very sensitive data. It must not share the same subnet with other AWS resources and its custom route table with other instances in the environment. 4. The environment must be highly available and scalable to handle a surge of incoming traffic over the Internet. How many subnets should you create to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|2','B|3','C|4','D|6'],correct:'B',answer:'A two-tier architecture (app tier + DB tier) needs at least 6 subnets for HA across 2 AZs: 2 public subnets (for the ALB), 2 private subnets (for app servers), and 2 private subnets (for the database). Each tier gets one subnet per AZ.',why:'Best practice for multi-tier HA: ALB in public subnets (1 per AZ), app servers in private subnets (1 per AZ), databases in private subnets (1 per AZ). With 2 AZs: 2 + 2 + 2 = 6 subnets. Each subnet maps to a single AZ. The ALB needs to be in at least 2 AZs for high availability.',trap:'2 subnets would put everything in one subnet per AZ — conflating public and private resources, violating security best practices. 3 subnets could mean 1 per tier but only in 1 AZ — no HA. 4 subnets would support only 2 tiers across 2 AZs (no separate DB subnets).',rule:'Two-tier HA across 2 AZs = 6 subnets minimum: 2 public (ALB) + 2 private (app) + 2 private (DB). One subnet per tier per AZ. Each subnet = single AZ.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_34',category:'Storage',question:'A company has a running m5ad.large EC2 instance with a default attached 75 GB SSD instance-store backed volume. You shut it down and then start the instance. You noticed that the data which you saved earlier on the attached volume is no longer available. What might be the cause of this?',choices:['A|The volume of the instance was not big enough to handle all of the processing data.','B|The EC2 instance was using EBS backed root volumes, which are ephemeral and only live for the life of the instance.','C|The EC2 instance was using instance store volumes, which are ephemeral and only live for the life of the instance.','D|The instance was hit by a virus that wipes out all data.'],correct:'C',answer:'An instance store provides temporary block-level storage for your instance. This storage is located on disks that are physically attached to the host computer.',why:'An instance store consists of one or more instance store volumes exposed as block devices. The size of an instance store as well as the number of devices available varies by instance type. While an instance store is dedicated to a particular instance, the disk subsystem is shared among instances on a host computer.',trap:'The option that says: The volume of the instance was not big enough to handle all of the processing data is incorrect because the primary cause of the data loss is the use of an instance-store backed volume, which is not designed for data persistence.',rule:'Instance store is ideal for the temporary storage of information that frequently changes, such as buffers, caches, scratch data, and other temporary content, or for application data that requires high IOPS with low latency local storage.',keywords:'Instance store = ephemeral (deleted on stop/terminate/host failure). Cannot snapshot.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_35',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a company that has multiple VPCs in various AWS regions. The Architect is assigned to set up a logging system that will track all of the changes made to their AWS resources in all regions, including the configurations made in IAM, CloudFront, AWS WAF, and Route 53. In order to pass the compliance requirements, the solution must ensure the security, integrity, and durability of the log data. It should also provide an event history of all API calls made in AWS Management Console and AWS CLI. Which of the following solutions is the best fit for this scenario?',choices:['A|Set up a new CloudTrail trail in a new S3 bucket using the AWS CLI and also pass both the --is-multi-region-trail and --include-global-service-events parameters then encrypt log files using KMS encryption. Apply Multi Factor Authentication (MFA) Delete on the S3 bucket and ensure that only authorized users can access the logs by configuring the bucket policies.','B|Set up a new CloudWatch trail in a new S3 bucket using the AWS CLI and also pass both the --is-multi-region-trail and --include-global-service-events parameters then encrypt log files using KMS encryption. Apply Multi Factor Authentication (MFA) Delete on the S3 bucket and ensure that only authorized users can access the logs by configuring the bucket policies.','C|Set up a new CloudWatch trail in a new S3 bucket using the CloudTrail console and also pass the --is-multi-region-trail parameter then encrypt log files using KMS encryption. Apply Multi Factor Authentication (MFA) Delete on the S3 bucket and ensure that only authorized users can access the logs by configuring the bucket policies.','D|Set up a new CloudTrail trail in a new S3 bucket using the AWS CLI and also pass both the --is-multi-region-trail and --no-include-global-service-events parameters then encrypt log files using KMS encryption. Apply Multi Factor Authentication (MFA) Delete on the S3 bucket and ensure that only authorized users can access the logs by configuring the bucket policies.'],correct:'D',answer:'An event in CloudTrail is the record of an activity in an AWS account. This activity can be an action taken by a user, role, or service that is monitorable by CloudTrail. CloudTrail events provide a history of both API and non-API account activity made through the AWS Management Console, AWS SDKs, command-line tools, and other AWS services.',why:'A trail can be applied to all regions or a single region. As a best practice, create a trail that applies to all regions in the AWS partition in which you are working. This is the default setting when you create a trail in the CloudTrail console.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a new CloudWatch trail in a new S3 bucket using the AWS CLI and also pass both the --is-multi-region-trail and --include-global-service-events parameters then encrypt log files using KMS encryption. Apply Multi Factor Authentication (MFA) Delete on the S3 bucket and ensure that only authorized users can access the logs by configuring the bucket policies is incorrect because you need to use CloudTrail instead of CloudWatch.',rule:'S3 + AWS + KMS = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_36',category:'Networking',question:'A company conducted a surprise IT audit on all of the AWS resources being used in the production environment. During the audit activities, it was noted that you are using a combination of Standard and Convertible Reserved EC2 instances in your applications. Which of the following are the characteristics and benefits of using these two types of Reserved EC2 instances? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Unused Convertible Reserved Instances can later be sold at the Reserved Instance Marketplace.','B|It can enable you to reserve capacity for your Amazon EC2 instances in multiple Availability Zones and multiple AWS Regions for any duration.','C|Unused Standard Reserved Instances can later be sold at the Reserved Instance Marketplace.','D|It runs in a VPC on hardware that\'s dedicated to a single customer.','E|Convertible Reserved Instances allow you to exchange for another convertible reserved instance of a different instance family.'],correct:'CE',answer:'Reserved Instances can: (A) be applied across all AZs in a region (regional RIs, not zonal RIs) and (C) unused Standard Reserved Instances can be sold on the Reserved Instance Marketplace. Convertible RIs can be exchanged for other Convertible RIs of equal or greater value.',why:'Regional Reserved Instances automatically apply to any running On-Demand Instance of the matching configuration in any AZ in that region — no capacity reservation, but the discount applies anywhere in the region. Unused Standard RIs can be sold on the RI Marketplace to recover cost. Convertible RIs allow changing attributes (instance family, OS, tenancy) as long as the exchange is equal or greater value.',trap:'Convertible Reserved Instances cannot be sold on the Marketplace — they can only be exchanged. RI capacity reservations apply to a specific AZ (zonal RI), not across all AZs. Running in a VPC on dedicated hardware describes Dedicated Instances, not Reserved Instances.',rule:'Standard RI = can sell on RI Marketplace. Convertible RI = can exchange (not sell). Regional RI = applies to any AZ in region (no capacity reservation). Zonal RI = specific AZ + capacity reservation in specific AZ. Standard RI = can sell on Marketplace. Convertible = cannot sell.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_37',category:'Storage',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for an online hotel booking firm with terabytes of customer data coming from the websites and applications. There is an annual corporate meeting where the Architect needs to present the booking behavior and acquire new insights from the customers’ data. The Architect is looking for a service to perform super-fast analytics on massive data sets in near real-time. Which of the following services gives the Architect the ability to store huge amounts of data and perform quick and flexible queries on it?',choices:['A|Amazon DynamoDB','B|Amazon ElastiCache','C|Amazon RDS','D|Amazon Redshift'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Redshift is a fast, scalable data warehouse that makes it simple and cost-effective to analyze all your data across your data warehouse and data lake. Redshift delivers ten times faster performance than other data warehouses by using machine learning, massively parallel query execution, and columnar storage on a high-performance disk.',why:'You can use Redshift to analyze all your data using standard SQL and your existing Business Intelligence (BI) tools. It also allows you to run complex analytic queries against terabytes to petabytes of structured and semi-structured data, using sophisticated query optimization, columnar storage on high-performance storage, and massively parallel query execution.',trap:'Amazon DynamoDB is incorrect because DynamoDB is a NoSQL database that is based on key-value pairs used for fast processing of small data that dynamically grows and changes. But if you need to scan large amounts of data (i.e., a lot of keys all in one query), the performance will not be optimal.',rule:'Real-time → Amazon Redshift. Not Amazon DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_38',category:'S3',question:'A startup company running applications on multiple Amazon EC2 instances is utilizing Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP for its shared storage on its primary region. File shares in the region are configured over NFS and CIFS protocols. As part of resiliency requirements, the company needs to implement a storage disaster recovery (DR) solution in a secondary region using the same protocol as the primary region. Which of the following satisfies the given requirements with the LEAST amount of management overhead?',choices:['A|Create an FSx for ONTAP instance in both source and destination regions, then establish connectivity with a VPC peering connection. Configure NetApp SnapMirror to replicate data between the two instances.','B|Using on-demand data replication, set up an automated snapshot schedule of the Amazon FSx file system to an S3 bucket. Use the CopySnapshotAndUpdateVolume API to copy the snapshot to the destination region. Use the CreateVolume API to create a volume on the destination and mount the new volume to the destination file system.','C|Launch an FSx instance in both source and destination regions, then establish connectivity with a VPC peering connection. Set up an AWS DataSync agent near your source data. Configure AWS DataSync service to replicate data from the source to the destination.','D|Provision an FSx instance in both source and destination regions, then establish connectivity with a VPC peering connection. Using AWS Backup, create a volume backup from the source region. Copy the backup volume to the destination region and restore using the Amazon FSx console.'],correct:'A',answer:'For FSx for ONTAP cross-region data replication, set up FSx instances in both source and destination regions, then establish cross-region SnapMirror replication. SnapMirror is the NetApp native replication technology built into FSx for ONTAP.',why:'FSx for NetApp ONTAP supports SnapMirror — NetApp\'s block-level data replication technology. SnapMirror creates point-in-time consistent snapshots and replicates them to a destination ONTAP instance in another region over a peered connection. Replication is incremental after the initial baseline sync.',trap:'On-demand snapshot schedule without continuous replication leaves large gaps between recovery points (high RPO). Cross-region replication for FSx for Lustre uses different technology than SnapMirror — Lustre is for HPC scratch data, not persistent NAS workloads. FSx for Windows does not support cross-region replication via SnapMirror.',rule:'FSx for ONTAP cross-region replication = SnapMirror (NetApp native). Set up ONTAP in both regions + establish SnapMirror relationship. Continuous, incremental block-level replication. FSx ONTAP = enterprise NAS with multi-protocol support (NFS, SMB, iSCSI).',keywords:'Linux + Windows sharing same file system → FSx for NetApp ONTAP (NFS + SMB + iSCSI).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_39',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is planning to deploy a Secure File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) service on AWS. The SFTP service must receive traffic only from approved public IP addresses. The company should be able to add users and manage their permissions on the SFTP server. The company seeks a highly available serverless solution that can deliver high IOPS performance. Which of the following solutions would fulfill the company\'s needs?',choices:['A|Launch an encrypted Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volume. Set up an SFTP service with a public endpoint in AWS Transfer Family and configure it to allow connections only from verified IP sources. Associate the EBS volume with the SFTP service\'s endpoint and grant users access.','B|Launch an encrypted Amazon EFS volume. Set up an AWS Transfer Family for SFTP service utilizing elastic IP addresses with a publicly accessible VPC endpoint. On the endpoint, apply a security group restricting access to trusted IPs. Integrate the EFS volume with the service\'s endpoint and enable user access.','C|Create an Amazon S3 bucket. Set up an SFTP service with a public endpoint in AWS Transfer Family filtered exclusively for trusted IPs. Link the S3 bucket to the service\'s endpoint, then manage user permissions.','D|Set up a server-based SFTP solution using Amazon EC2 instances in a public subnet within a VPC. Secure the setup with security groups that restrict access to approved IP addresses. Attach an encrypted Amazon S3 bucket for storage and configure user access permissions through IAM roles.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Elastic File System (EFS) is a scalable, elastic, cloud-native file storage service offered by AWS. It is designed to provide a simple, serverless, set-and-forget experience that is fully managed, eliminating the need to provision or manage capacity.',why:'AWS Transfer Family is a service that allows for secure file transfer over protocols such as SFTP, FTPS, and FTP directly into and out of Amazon S3 or Amazon EFS. Amazon EFS is well-known for its high IOPS performance, making it good for applications that require quick and simultaneous read/write operations. This is beneficial for scenarios where high-performance shared storage is needed, such as with SFTP.',trap:'The option that says: Launch an encrypted Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volume. Set up an SFTP service with a public endpoint in AWS Transfer Family and configure it to allow connections only from verified IP sources. Associate the EBS volume with the SFTP service\'s endpoint and grant users access is incorrect. This option is not fully serverless because EBS volumes require attachment to EC2 instances, which contradicts the serverless solution requirement. While EBS can provide high IOPS, its performance is tightly coupled with the EC2 instances it\'s attached to, which may not offer the scalability and ease of management desired in a serverless architecture. Additionally, managing user permissions through EC2 instances rather than a serverless setup could introduce complexity and reduce the solution\'s overall efficiency and flexibility.',rule:'AWS Transfer Family supports secure file transfer over SFTP, FTPS, and FTP directly into and out of Amazon S3 or Amazon EFS. Fully managed, no server to run. Use when migrating file-based workflows to AWS without changing client-side tools.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_40',category:'Networking',question:'A DevOps Engineer is asked to deploy a web application on Amazon EC2 instances. The instances are defined in a target group and are able to scale horizontally based on the configuration of an Auto Scaling group. The domain should be available publicly via the internet and is to be configured with session affinity (sticky sessions) to improve the user session management of the application. The application should be secured with an AWS WAF for additional protection against web attacks. Which among the choices below should be set up to satisfy this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up an internet-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB). Configure the listener over HTTP and HTTPS to forward traffic to the application target group.','B|Launch a Gateway Load Balancer. Configure the IP listener routing to forward traffic to the application target group.','C|Provision a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with a public subnet. Configure the TCP listener to forward traffic to the application target group.','D|Create a Web ACL in AWS WAF configured with the public domain.','E|Deploy an AWS Network Firewall to a public subnet of a VPC.'],correct:'AD',answer:'Set up an internet-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB). Configure the listener over HTTP and HTTPS to forward traffic to the application target group. Use AWS WAF with a managed rule group to protect against common web exploits and bots.',why:'Amazon Elastic Load Balancing supports four types of load balancers: Application Load Balancers (ALB), Network Load Balancers (NLB), Gateway Load Balancers, and Classic Load Balancer. AWS only recommends using the Classic Load Balancer if the applicaiton is built with Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) Classic Network. AWS Application Load Balancer runs on the application layer.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a Gateway Load Balancer. Configure the IP listener routing to forward traffic to the application target group is incorrect. A Gateway Load Balancer is used when you need to deploy and manage a fleet of third-party virtual appliances and not for a web application. It does not work with AWS WAF.',rule:'Protect public web app = ALB (Layer 7 routing + HTTPS) + WAF Web ACL (SQL injection, XSS, rate limiting) + optional Network Firewall (deep packet inspection). NLB = Layer 4 only, no WAF support. Gateway LB = third-party appliances.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_41',category:'IAM',question:'An organization seeks to enhance its customer experience by integrating and visualizing its diverse data sources. The organization has a robust Amazon S3 data lake, governed by AWS Lake Formation, containing detailed purchase histories. Additionally, they store operational data, including real-time inventory and sales information, in an Amazon Aurora MySQL database. The goal is to create a dynamic visualization in Amazon QuickSight, joining the data lake content with the Aurora database. The company requires stringent column-level authorization, allowing its marketing team to access only specific columns in the database for targeted promotions and customer insights. What is the most efficient solution to meet these requirements with minimal operational overhead?',choices:['A|Configure an Amazon EMR job to ingest data directly from the Aurora database to QuickSight\'s SPICE engine, filtering to include only the necessary columns.','B|Employ a Lake Formation blueprint to incrementally ingest data from the Aurora database to the S3 data lake, then enforce column-level access control by creating a Lake Formation data filter with the specified columns. Set up Amazon QuickSight to use Amazon Athena as its data source.','C|Utilize AWS Glue Studio to transfer data from the Aurora database to the S3 data lake. Apply an IAM policy to QuickSight users for column-level access control, and then use Amazon S3 as the data source in QuickSight.','D|Leverage AWS Glue Elastic Views to create a materialized view of the Aurora database in Amazon S3. Implement an S3 bucket policy for column-level access control for QuickSight users, and use Amazon S3 as the data source in QuickSight.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Lake Formation Blueprints are designed to automate the process of data ingestion into the data lake. The "Incremental database" blueprint, in particular, is suitable for loading only new data from the Amazon Aurora MySQL database into the S3 data lake, based on previously set bookmarks.',why:'AWS Lake Formation enables the creation of data filters to specify column-level access control. A data filter includes information such as the filter name, the Catalog IDs of the table, the table name, the name of the database, and the column specification. This feature is critical for allowing the marketing team to access only specific columns in the database for targeted promotions and customer insights.',trap:'The option that says: Configure an Amazon EMR job to ingest data directly from the Aurora database to QuickSight\'s SPICE engine, filtering to include only the necessary columns is incorrect. This approach does not leverage the column-level access control capabilities of Lake Formation, nor does it take advantage of the existing S3 data lake.',rule:'Employ a Lake Formation blueprint to incrementally ingest data from the Aurora database to the S3 data lake, then enforce column-level access control using Lake Formation column-level and row-level security policies.',keywords:'ALB + WAF: internet-facing ALB for HTTP/HTTPS. WAF Web ACL for SQL injection and XSS protection.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_42',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A startup plans to scale out its cloud resources. With its rapid growth, the company needs an automated way of scanning its Amazon EC2 instances for security purposes. The company needs to automatically discover software vulnerabilities on its cloud resources and validate that its workloads meet security compliances. Which of the following options should be implemented to meet the company requirements?',choices:['A|Leverage Amazon Macie’s automated discovery and scanning to protect Amazon EC2 instances. Publish a notification on Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) for the results.','B|Create a rule on Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to detect changes on AWS Trusted Advisor checks. Publish a notification on Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS).','C|Enable Amazon Inspector to publish results to Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) and send notifications using Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS)','D|Enable Amazon GuardDuty to continuously monitor Amazon EC2 instances and publish notifications to Amazon Simple Notification Service (SNS).'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon Inspector can continuously scan EC2 instances and ECR container images for software vulnerabilities (CVEs) and network exposures. EventBridge rules can trigger notifications or automated responses when new Inspector findings arrive.',why:'Amazon Inspector automatically assesses EC2 instances (using SSM Agent) and ECR container images for OS and application package CVEs. When a finding is generated, Inspector publishes an event to EventBridge. An EventBridge rule can match these events and trigger Lambda, SNS, or SQS for automated alerting or remediation.',trap:'Amazon Macie scans S3 for sensitive data — not for software vulnerabilities on EC2. GuardDuty is a threat detection service for suspicious API calls, network activity, and account behavior — not software vulnerability scanning. DataSync is a data transfer service, not a security scanning service.',rule:'Continuous EC2/container vulnerability scanning = Amazon Inspector. Findings → EventBridge → automate response. Inspector requires SSM Agent on EC2. Macie = S3 sensitive data discovery. GuardDuty = threat detection (API anomalies, network). They are different services with distinct purposes.',keywords:'Track resource configuration state over time → AWS Config. Also detects compliance drift.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_43',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has moved its suite of internal tools to AWS. For audit compliance, several CloudTrail trails are made to record all API calls. Each log file is also protected with server-side encryption with AWS KMS keys (SSE-KMS). Despite this, the company wants to ensure it can identify whether a log file has been tampered with. Which security measure should the solutions architect employ?',choices:['A|Enable the CloudTrail Log File Validation feature on all trails.','B|Use the CloudTrail Processing Library when doing audit compliance.','C|Configure CloudWatch Logs to monitor all trails and use Amazon SNS to send notifications when a log file has been tampered with.','D|Enable CloudTrail Insights events.'],correct:'A',answer:'To determine whether a log file was modified, deleted, or unchanged after CloudTrail delivered it, you can use CloudTrail log file integrity validation. This feature is built using industry-standard algorithms: SHA-256 for hashing and SHA-256 with RSA for digital signing. This makes it computationally infeasible to modify, delete or forge CloudTrail log files without detection.',why:'Validated log files are invaluable in security and forensic investigations. For example, a validated log file enables you to assert positively that the log file itself has not changed, or that particular user credentials performed specific API activity.',trap:'The option that says: Use the CloudTrail Processing Library when doing audit compliance is incorrect. The CloudTrail Processing Library is just a Java library that simplifies the processing of CloudTrail logs. It\'s not capable of detecting log tampering.',rule:'Verify CloudTrail log integrity = enable log file validation (creates SHA-256 digest files). Digest file = signed hash of log files for that hour. Use aws cloudtrail validate-logs CLI to verify digest files. Digest files are stored in separate S3 prefix.',keywords:'CloudWatch dashboards: cross-account cross-region monitoring. Composite alarms combine multiple alarm states.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_44',category:'Serverless',question:'A serverless application has been launched on the DevOps team’s AWS account. Users from the development team’s account must be granted permission to invoke the Lambda function that runs the application. The solution must use the principle of least privilege access. Which solution will fulfill these criteria?',choices:['A|On the function’s resource-based policy, add a permission that includes the lambda:InvokeFunction as action and arn:aws:iam::[DEV AWSAccount Number]:root as principal.','B|On the function’s resource-based policy, add a permission that includes the lambda:* as action and arn:aws:iam::[DevOps AWS Account Number]:root as principal.','C|On the function’s execution role, add a permission that includes the lambda:* as action and arn:aws:iam::[DevOps AWS Account Number]:root as principal.','D|On the function’s execution role, add a permission that includes the lambda:InvokeFunction as action and arn:aws:iam::[DEV AWS Account Number]:root as principal.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Lambda supports resource-based permissions policies for Lambda functions and layers. Resource-based policies let you grant usage permission to other AWS accounts on a per-resource basis. You also use a resource-based policy to allow an AWS service to invoke your function on your behalf.',why:'For Lambda functions, you can grant account permission to invoke or manage a function. You can add multiple statements to grant access to several accounts, or let any account invoke your function. You can also use the policy to grant invoke permission to an AWS service that invokes a function in response to activity in your account.',trap:'The option that says: On the function’s resource-based policy, add a permission that includes the lambda:* as action and arn:aws:iam::[DevOps AWS Account Number]:root as principal is incorrect. Although this option will undoubtedly allow development account users to use the function, it is not secure as it\'s too permissive. The wildcard (*) indicates that all Lambda function operations are permitted.',rule:'Lambda resource-based policy = who can INVOKE the function (cross-account, S3, SNS, etc.). Execution role = what the function CAN DO (which AWS services it can call). Both are required for Lambda to receive events from other accounts and access AWS resources.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_45',category:'S3',question:'A large company has several applications hosted on hundreds of virtual machines running in its data center. The company wants to take advantage of the scalability and cost-effectiveness of the AWS cloud, so it\'s been decided to migrate all its applications to the cloud. Before starting the migration process, the management wants to have an inventory of all its servers and wants the ability to track the migration of each application to the cloud. Which of the following options is the recommended action to meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Deploy the AWS DataSync agent on the on-premises data center. The data gathered on-site will be stored on an Amazon S3 bucket. Use the AWS Migration Hub console to track the migration of each application.','B|Use AWS Application Migration Service (AWS MGN) and deploy the replication agent on all virtual machines in the data center. Use Amazon QuickSight to visualize the data gathered by the replication agent and track the migration process.','C|Use AWS Application Discovery Service and deploy the discovery connector to the on-premises data center to create an inventory of virtual machines to be migrated. Use the AWS Migration Hub console to track the migration of each application.','D|Deploy the AWS DataSync agent on the on-premises data center. Data gathered will be stored on an Amazon S3 bucket. Use Amazon QuickSight to visualize the data gathered by the DataSync agent and track the migration process.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Application Discovery Service discovers on-premises server configurations, dependencies, and performance data using a lightweight discovery connector or agent, providing the inventory needed for migration planning.',why:'Application Discovery Service collects server configuration data (CPU, memory, disk, network) and dependency mappings between servers. This data is stored in AWS Migration Hub, where it can inform migration planning. There are two modes: Agentless Discovery (VMware connector, collects VM metadata) and Agent-based Discovery (deeper server-level data including process and network dependency mapping).',trap:'AWS DataSync transfers files between storage systems — it cannot discover server configurations or dependencies. AWS MGN (Application Migration Service) performs the actual migration but needs discovery data first. CloudTrail logs API calls but cannot inventory on-premises servers.',rule:'AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) = lift-and-shift. Tracks migration status in Migration Hub. Agentless (VMware) or Agent-based. DataSync = file transfer. MGN = server replication and cutover.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_46',category:'IAM',question:'The DevOps Team at Agila Corporation aims to enforce an IAM policy that grants them exclusive permissions to start, stop, and terminate EC2 instances in the us-west-1 region. To maintain strict security measures, any requests originating outside the company\'s network range (192.158.1.0/24) should be denied. Which of the following IAM policies would satisfy these requirements?',choices:['A|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "ec2:TerminateInstances", "ec2:StartInstances", "ec2:StopInstances" ], "Resource": "*", "Condition": { "StringEquals": { "aws:RequestedRegion": "us-west-1" } } }, { "Effect": "Deny", "Action": "ec2:*", "Resource": "*", "Condition": { "NotIpAddress": { "aws:SourceIp": "192.158.1.0/24" } } } ] }','B|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "ec2:StartInstances", "ec2:StopInstances", "ec2:TerminateInstances" ], "Resource": "", "Condition": { "IpAddress": { "aws:SourceIp": "192.158.1.0/24" } } } ] }','C|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "ec2:TerminateInstances", "ec2:StartInstances", "ec2:StopInstances" ], "Resource": "*", "Condition": { "StringEquals": { "aws:RequestedRegion": "us-west-1" }, "IpAddress": { "aws:SourceIp": "192.158.1.0/24" } } } ] }','D|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Deny", "Action": "ec2:*", "Resource": "*", "Condition": { "NotIpAddress": { "aws:SourceIp": "192.158.1.0/24" } } } ] }'],correct:'A',answer:'Option A has two statements: (1) Allow the three specific EC2 actions only when aws:RequestedRegion equals us-west-1, AND (2) Deny ec2:* when the source IP is NOT within 192.158.1.0/24. Both conditions must be met: allowed region AND allowed IP. This correctly enforces both restrictions simultaneously.',why:'IAM policy evaluation: explicit Deny always overrides Allow. The Allow statement permits the three actions in us-west-1. The Deny statement with NotIpAddress blocks all EC2 actions from outside the corporate network. Together they enforce: (a) only these 3 actions, (b) only in us-west-1, (c) only from 192.158.1.0/24. Option B uses IpAddress (Allow only from that IP) but has no region restriction. Option C uses AND condition on the Allow which requires BOTH conditions on the same statement but cannot deny outside IPs. Option D is only a Deny with no Allow — no actions would succeed.',trap:'Option C combines both conditions in a single Allow statement using AND logic — but this only allows the action when BOTH conditions are true simultaneously. It does not deny requests from outside the IP range; it simply does not allow them, which is subtly different. More critically, it lacks an explicit Deny for outside-IP requests, so if there are other policies, those requests might still succeed.',rule:'Enforce both region AND IP restriction = two-statement policy: Allow specific actions in region + Deny all when NotIpAddress. Explicit Deny always wins over any Allow.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_47',category:'Serverless',question:'A healthcare company has migrated its Electronic Health Record (EHR) system to AWS and is now seeking to protect its production VPC from a wide range of potential threats. The company requires a solution to monitor both incoming and outgoing VPC traffic and block any malicious connections. As a Solution Architect, how will you meet these requirements?',choices:['A|Implement AWS GuardDuty for traffic monitoring and use AWS Lambda for automated detection and response to security incidents.','B|Use AWS Traffic Mirroring to capture traffic from ENIs on EC2 instances in a production VPC. Send this traffic on an EC2 instance or container for flow analysis and filtering.','C|Create custom security rules in AWS Network Firewall to detect and filter traffic passing to and from the production VPC.','D|Use AWS Firewall Manager to create security policies for AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF).'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Network Firewall is a managed service offering advanced network security capabilities to protect VPCs (Virtual Private Clouds) against potential threats. It enables you to define custom security rules and policies to monitor and control the traffic flow passing to and from your VPC.',why:'Network Firewall deploys firewall endpoints inside your VPC subnets and uses route tables to redirect traffic through them for inspection. It supports stateless rules (simple packet header matching) and stateful rules (tracks connection state, supports Suricata rule syntax for deep packet inspection). Managed threat intelligence rule groups from AWS Partners can be added without writing custom rules.',trap:'The option that says: Implement AWS GuardDuty for traffic monitoring and use AWS Lambda for automated detection and response to security incidents is incorrect. Although AWS GuardDuty can detect potential threats by analyzing VPC flow logs, it can\'t prevent those threats from entering or leaving your VPC. On the other hand, AWS Network Firewall operates at the network level and can actively block malicious connections before it reaches your application.',rule:'Create custom security rules in AWS Network Firewall to detect and filter traffic passing to and from the production VPC.',keywords:'VPC-level FQDN/URL filtering → AWS Network Firewall. Route traffic through firewall endpoints.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_48',category:'IAM',question:'A Solutions Architect designed a serverless architecture that allows AWS Lambda to access an Amazon DynamoDB table named tutorialsdojo in the US East (N. Virginia) region. The IAM policy attached to a Lambda function allows it to put and delete items in the table. The policy must be updated to only allow two operations in the tutorialsdojo table and prevent other DynamoDB tables from being modified. Which of the following IAM policies fulfill this requirement and follow the principle of granting the least privilege?',choices:['A|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Sid": "TutorialsdojoTablePolicy", "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:120618981206:table/tutorialsdojo" } ] }','B|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Sid": "TutorialsdojoTablePolicy", "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:120618981206:table/*" } ] }','C|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Sid": "TutorialsdojoTablePolicy1", "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:1206189812061898:table/tutorialsdojo" }, { "Sid": "TutorialsdojoTablePolicy2", "Effect": "Deny", "Action": "dynamodb:*", "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:1206189812061898:table/*" } ] }','D|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Sid": "TutorialsdojoTablePolicy", "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem" ], "Resource": "*" } ] }'],correct:'A',answer:'Option A allows only PutItem and DeleteItem scoped to the exact table ARN (arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:120618981206:table/tutorialsdojo). This satisfies least privilege: exactly the two required actions, on exactly one specific table, nothing else.',why:'Least privilege requires matching the Resource ARN to the specific table, not a wildcard. Option B uses table/* which allows the two actions on ALL tables in the account — violates "prevent other DynamoDB tables from being modified". Option C adds an explicit Deny on table/* but the Allow uses a wrong account ID (1206189812061898 vs 120618981206) — it would never match. Option D uses Resource: * which allows PutItem/DeleteItem on every table in the account.',trap:'Option B looks correct but uses "table/*" as the resource — this allows PutItem and DeleteItem on EVERY DynamoDB table in the account, not just tutorialsdojo. The question explicitly requires preventing modification of other tables. Always scope Resource to the exact table ARN for DynamoDB least privilege.',rule:'DynamoDB least privilege = specific action names + exact table ARN. Not table/*. Not Resource:*. Account ID in the ARN must match exactly.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_49',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A large electronics company is using Amazon Simple Storage Service to store important documents. For reporting purposes, they want to track and log every request access to their S3 buckets including the requester, bucket name, request time, request action, referrer, turnaround time, and error code information. The solution should also provide more visibility into the object-level operations of the bucket. Which is the best solution among the following options that can satisfy the requirement?',choices:['A|Enable AWS CloudTrail to audit all Amazon S3 bucket access.','B|Enable server access logging for all required Amazon S3 buckets.','C|Enable the Requester Pays option to track access via AWS Billing.','D|Enable Amazon S3 Event Notifications for PUT and POST.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon S3 is integrated with AWS CloudTrail, a service that provides a record of actions taken by a user, role, or an AWS service in Amazon S3. CloudTrail captures a subset of API calls for Amazon S3 as events, including calls from the Amazon S3 console and code calls to the Amazon S3 APIs.',why:'For this scenario, you can use CloudTrail and the Server Access Logging feature of Amazon S3. However, it is mentioned in the scenario that they need detailed information about every access request sent to the S3 bucket including the referrer and turn-around time information. These two records are not available in CloudTrail.',trap:'The option that says: Enable AWS CloudTrail to audit all Amazon S3 bucket access is incorrect because enabling AWS CloudTrail alone won\'t give detailed logging information for object-level access.',rule:'AWS CloudTrail logs provide a record of actions taken by a user, role, or an AWS service in Amazon S3, while Amazon S3 server access logs pr Not AWS CloudTrail.',keywords:'Lambda authorizer: custom auth for API Gateway. Token or request type. Returns IAM policy.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_50',category:'Serverless',question:'A company runs its multitier online shopping platform on AWS. Every new sale transaction is published as a message in an open-source RabbitMQ queue that runs on an Amazon EC2 instance. There is a consumer application is hosted on a separate EC2 instance that consumes the incoming messages, which then stores the transaction in a self-hosted PostgreSQL database on another EC2 instance. All of the EC2 instances used are in the same Availability Zone in the eu-central-1 Region. A solutions architect needs to redesign its cloud architecture to provide the highest availability with the least amount of operational overhead. What should a solutions architect do to meet the company’s requirements above?',choices:['A|Migrate the RabbitMQ queue to Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS). Rehost the consumer application to an Amazon OpenSearch Service (Amazon Elasticsearch) cluster. Migrate the PostgreSQL database to an Amazon Aurora Serverless cluster','B|Migrate the RabbitMQ queue to Amazon MQ to a cluster broker deployment setup. Launch a Multi-AZ Auto Scaling group for the Amazon EC2 instances that host the consumer application. Migrate the existing database to Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL in a Multi-AZ Deployment configuration.','C|Migrate the RabbitMQ queue to an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances. Rehost the consumer application to an Amazon ECS cluster with AWS Fargate. Migrate the PostgreSQL database to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL using the Aurora cloning feature.','D|Migrate the RabbitMQ queue to a redundant pair (active/standby) of Amazon MQ brokers in AWS. Launch a Multi-AZ Auto Scaling group for the Amazon EC2 instances that host the consumer application. Migrate the PostgreSQL database to Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with cross-Region read replicas'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon MQ is a managed message broker service that makes it easy to migrate to a message broker in the cloud. A message broker allows software applications and components to communicate using various programming languages, operating systems, and formal messaging protocols. Amazon MQ supports Apache ActiveMQ, RabbitMQ, and other message broker engine types.',why:'A cluster deployment is a logical grouping of three RabbitMQ broker nodes behind a Network Load Balancer, each sharing users, queues, and a distributed state across multiple Availability Zones (AZ). In a cluster deployment, Amazon MQ automatically manages broker policies to enable classic mirroring across all nodes, ensuring high availability (HA). Each mirrored queue consists of one main node and one or more mirrors.',trap:'The option that says: Migrate the RabbitMQ queue to Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS). Rehost the consumer application to an Amazon OpenSearch Service (Amazon Elasticsearch) cluster. Migrate the PostgreSQL database to an Amazon Aurora Serverless cluster is incorrect because you cannot directly migrate RabbitMQ to Amazon SQS. A more suitable course of action is to migrate the RabbitMQ queue to Amazon MQ as this service supports a wide variety of functions that RabbitMQ already has.',rule:'Amazon MQ to a cluster broker deploym|Amazon EC2 instances that host the co: correct. Amazon Simple: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_51',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company needs to design an online analytics application that uses Redshift Cluster for its data warehouse. Which of the following services allows them to monitor all API calls in Redshift instance and can also provide secured data for auditing and compliance purposes?',choices:['A|AWS CloudTrail','B|Amazon CloudWatch','C|AWS X-Ray','D|Amazon Redshift Spectrum'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS CloudTrail is a service that enables governance, compliance, operational auditing, and risk auditing of your AWS account. With CloudTrail, you can log, continuously monitor, and retain account activity related to actions across your AWS infrastructure. By default, CloudTrail is enabled on your AWS account when you create it.',why:'CloudTrail provides event history of your AWS account activity, including actions taken through the AWS Management Console, AWS SDKs, command line tools, API calls, and other AWS services. This event history simplifies security analysis, resource change tracking, and troubleshooting.',trap:'AWS X-Ray is incorrect because this is not a suitable service to use to track each API call to your AWS resources. It just helps you debug and analyze your microservices applications with request tracing so you can find the root cause of issues and performance.',rule:'CloudTrail provides event history of your AWS account activity, including actions taken through the AWS Management Console, AWS SDKs, comman Not AWS resources.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_52',category:'IAM',question:'A tech startup has recently received a Series A round of funding to continue building their mobile forex trading application. You are hired to set up their cloud architecture in AWS and to implement a highly available, fault tolerant system. For their database, they are using DynamoDB and for authentication, they have chosen to use Cognito. Since the mobile application contains confidential financial transactions, there is a requirement to add a second authentication method that doesn\'t rely solely on user name and password. How can you implement this in AWS?',choices:['A|Add multi-factor authentication (MFA) to a user pool in Cognito to protect the identity of your users.','B|Add a new IAM policy to a user pool in Cognito.','C|Integrate Cognito with Amazon SNS Mobile Push to allow additional authentication via SMS.','D|Develop a custom application that integrates with Cognito that implements a second layer of authentication.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Cognito User Pools support Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA). Enabling MFA in the user pool requires users to provide a second factor (TOTP or SMS) at sign-in, securing the identity without custom code.',why:'Cognito User Pools have built-in MFA support. You can configure optional or required MFA. TOTP-based MFA uses authenticator apps (Google Authenticator, Authy). SMS-based MFA sends a code via SNS. MFA is configured in the User Pool settings and enforced at the Cognito service level — no application code changes needed.',trap:'IAM policies manage access to AWS resources, not application-level user authentication in Cognito User Pools. SNS Mobile Push enables push notifications to mobile devices — it is not an MFA mechanism. A custom application that implements a second factor duplicates what Cognito already provides natively.',rule:'Add MFA to Cognito User Pool authentication = enable MFA in User Pool (TOTP or SMS). No custom code. IAM policies = AWS resource access. SNS Push = mobile notifications, not MFA.',keywords:'Kinesis Data Analytics: real-time SQL on streaming data. Input = KDS or Firehose. Output = KDS or Lambda.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_53',category:'S3',question:'A company has both on-premises data center as well as AWS cloud infrastructure. Multimedia assets, such as graphics, audio, and videos, are primarily stored in an on-premises storage server, with an Amazon S3 Standard storage class bucket used for backup. The data is heavily utilized for only one week (7 days), but after that period, it is infrequently accessed by customers. The Solutions Architect is tasked with saving storage costs in AWS while maintaining the ability to retrieve a subset of media assets within minutes for an annual data audit, which will be conducted on cloud storage. Which of the following are valid options that the Solutions Architect can implement to meet the above requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set a lifecycle policy in the bucket to transition the data from Standard storage class to Glacier Flexible Retrieval after one week (7 days).','B|Set a lifecycle policy in the bucket to transition the data to S3 - Standard IA storage class after one week (7 days).','C|Set a lifecycle policy in the bucket to transition the data to S3 - One Zone-Infrequent Access storage class after one week (7 days).','D|Set a lifecycle policy in the bucket to transition the data to S3 Glacier Deep Archive storage class after one week (7 days).','E|Set a lifecycle policy in the bucket to transition to S3 - Standard IA after 30 days'],correct:'AE',answer:'For lifecycle management of multimedia assets in S3: (B) lifecycle rule to transition to S3 Standard-IA after 30 days (frequently accessed data becomes infrequent after a month), and (E) lifecycle rule to S3 Standard-IA after 30 days then to a colder class at 6 months are both valid tiering strategies.',why:'S3 lifecycle rules can transition objects through multiple storage tiers: Standard → Standard-IA (minimum 30 days) → Glacier Instant Retrieval → Glacier Flexible Retrieval → Glacier Deep Archive. For multimedia assets accessed initially but rarely afterward, transitioning to Standard-IA after 30 days reduces cost while maintaining retrieval speed. Further transition to Glacier can happen at 6+ months.',trap:'One Zone-IA lacks the multi-AZ redundancy of Standard-IA — not recommended for important multimedia assets that need HA. Glacier Deep Archive immediately after 30 days is too aggressive for assets that might still be accessed within the first year. Transitioning to Standard-IA before 30 days minimum is not allowed.',rule:'Multimedia S3 lifecycle = Standard → Standard-IA (after 30 days minimum) → Glacier (after 6+ months). One Zone-IA = lower durability. Glacier Deep Archive = 12-hour retrieval, too slow for active workloads. Standard-IA = immediate retrieval with retrieval fee.',keywords:'Accessed 1-2x/year or archival → S3 Glacier Deep Archive (~$0.001/GB). 12-hr retrieval.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_54',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect is developing a three-tier cryptocurrency web application for a FinTech startup. The Architect has been instructed to restrict access to the database tier to only accept traffic from the application-tier and deny traffic from other sources. The application-tier is composed of application servers hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances. Which of the following options is the MOST suitable solution to implement in this scenario?',choices:['A|Set up the security group of the database tier to allow database traffic from a specified list of application server IP addresses.','B|Set up the security group of the database tier to allow database traffic from the security group of the application servers.','C|Set up the Network ACL of the database subnet to deny all inbound non-database traffic from the subnet of the application-tier.','D|Set up the Network ACL of the database subnet to allow inbound database traffic from the subnet of the application-tier.'],correct:'A',answer:'For each security group, you add rules that control the inbound traffic to instances and a separate set of rules that control the outbound traffic. This section describes the basic things you need to know about security groups for your VPC and their rules.',why:'You can add or remove rules for a security group which is also referred to as authorizing or revoking inbound or outbound access. A rule applies either to inbound traffic (ingress) or outbound traffic (egress). You can grant access to a specific CIDR range or to another security group in your VPC or in a peer VPC (which requires a VPC peering connection).',trap:'Setting up the security group of the database tier to allow database traffic from a specified list of application server IP addresses is incorrect because the list of application server IP addresses will change over time since an Auto Scaling group can add or remove EC2 instances based on the configured scaling policy. This will create inconsistencies in your application because the newly launched instances, which are not included in the initial list of IP addresses, will not be able to access the database.',rule:'Security group of DB tier: allow traffic from the APPLICATION TIER security group ID (not a static IP list). SG ID as source is dynamic — automatically covers new instances added by Auto Scaling. Static IP lists break as ASG scales.',keywords:'Security group for 3-tier: DB tier accepts from APP tier SG ID (not IPs, handles auto-scaling).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_55',category:'Serverless',question:'A media company hosts a news website on an Amazon ECS Cluster that uses the Fargate launch type. All application data is stored in Amazon Keyspaces (for Apache Cassandra) with data-at-rest encryption enabled. To comply with strict security standards, database credentials must be provided via environment variables. As the Solutions Architect, your goal is to secure these credentials so they cannot be viewed in plaintext on the cluster. Which of the following solutions would be the most appropriate to implement with minimal effort?',choices:['A|In the ECS task definition file of the ECS Cluster, store the database credentials to Amazon ECS Anywhere to centrally manage these sensitive data and securely transmit it to only those containers that need access to it. Allocate an IAM Role to the cluster to ensure that the passwords are only accessible by the ECS service tasks. Run the AWS IAM Access Analyzer to verify that the credentials can’t be viewed in plaintext.','B|Store the database credentials in the ECS task definition file of the ECS Cluster and encrypt it with KMS. Store the task definition JSON file in Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL. Create an IAM role for the ECS task definition script that allows access to the Aurora PostgreSQL database, then pass the --cli-input-json parameter when calling the ECS register-task-definition action. Reference the task definition JSON file in Aurora PostgreSQL, which contains the database credentials.','C|Use the AWS Secrets Manager to store the database credentials and then encrypt them using AWS Certificate Manager (ACM). Create a resource-based policy for your Amazon ECS task execution role (taskRoleArn) and reference it with your task definition which allows access to both ACM and AWS Secrets Manager. Within your container definition, specify secrets with the name of the environment variable to set in the container and the full ARN of the Secrets Manager secret which contains the sensitive data, to present to the container.','D|Use the AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store to keep the database credentials and then encrypt them using AWS KMS. Create an IAM Role for your Amazon ECS task execution role (taskRoleArn) and reference it with your task definition, which allows access to both KMS and the Parameter Store. Within your container definition, specify secrets with the name of the environment variable to set in the container and the full ARN of the Systems Manager Parameter Store parameter containing the sensitive data to present to the container.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon ECS enables you to inject sensitive data into your containers by storing your sensitive data in either AWS Secrets Manager secrets or AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store parameters and then referencing them in your container definition. This feature is supported by tasks using both the EC2 and Fargate launch types.',why:'Within your container definition, specify secrets with the name of the environment variable to set in the container and the full ARN of either the Secrets Manager secret or Systems Manager Parameter Store parameter containing the sensitive data to present to the container. The parameter that you reference can be from a different Region than the container using it, but must be from within the same account.',trap:'The option that says: Store the database credentials in the ECS task definition file of the ECS Cluster and encrypt it with KMS. Store the task definition JSON file in Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL. Create an IAM role for the ECS task definition script that allows access to the Aurora PostgreSQL database, then pass the --cli-input-json parameter when calling the ECS register-task-definition action. Reference the task definition JSON file in Aurora PostgreSQL, which contains the database credentials is incorrect because storing sensitive data directly in a task definition, even if encrypted, simply poses a security risk and complicates the process. Additionally, storing the task definition JSON file in Aurora PostgreSQL and passing parameters through --cli-input-json unnecessarily complicates the deployment without adding value.',rule:'Encryption → AWS Systems Manager Para, AWS KMS. Not Amazon Aurora.',keywords:'Encrypt unencrypted EBS → copy snapshot with encryption enabled, create new volume.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_56',category:'IAM',question:'A multimedia company needs to deploy web services to an AWS region that they have never used before. The company currently has an IAM role for its Amazon EC2 instance that permits the instance to access Amazon DynamoDB. They want their EC2 instances in the new region to have the exact same privileges. What should be done to accomplish this? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|In the new Region, create a new IAM role and associated policies then assign it to the new instance.','B|Assign the existing IAM role to instances in the new region.','C|Duplicate the IAM role and associated policies to the new region and attach it to the instances.','D|Create an Amazon Machine Image (AMI) of the instance and copy it to the new region.'],correct:'BCD',answer:'IAM roles are global and not region-specific. When deploying a new EC2 instance in a new region, assign the existing IAM role directly — no duplication or recreation needed.',why:'IAM is a global service. Roles, users, groups, and policies exist at the account level, not the region level. The same role with the same permissions is available in every AWS region within the account. Simply select the existing role when launching the new EC2 instance in the new region.',trap:'Creating a new IAM role in the new region is unnecessary and creates management overhead. "Assigning existing IAM role to instances in a different region by design limitation" is incorrect — there is no such limitation. Copying AMIs transfers the instance image but IAM roles are associated at launch time, not embedded in AMIs.',rule:'IAM roles = global (not per-region). Same role works in all regions. No need to recreate or copy IAM roles for new regions. Just assign existing role to new instances.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_57',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A large consulting firm is in the process of conducting an internal security audit of its cloud infrastructure. The goal is to ensure that the information in its Amazon S3 bucket, which is associated with the firm’s AWS Lake Formation data lake, doesn\'t include confidential data related to its customers or staff. The firm aims to uncover financial or personally identifiable information (PII), such as passport, credit card numbers, and taxpayer identification numbers, in its S3 bucket. This will prevent any sensitive data from being ingested into a data lake. What solution would be the most operationally effective solution in meeting these particular requirements?',choices:['A|Implement AWS Audit Manager within the AWS account and opt for auditing based on the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards (PCI DSS).','B|Set up Amazon S3 Inventory for the S3 bucket and then configure Amazon Athena to conduct queries on the generated inventory.','C|Utilize Amazon Macie to perform a comprehensive data discovery operation using managed identifiers to detect various data types.','D|Set up AWS Glue DataBrew to identify and cleanse sensitive data in the S3 bucket.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon Macie is a powerful security service that automatically discovers, classifies, and protects sensitive data on Amazon Web Services. It is designed to help organizations maintain compliance with regulations and protect sensitive data from unauthorized access.',why:'One of the key features of Amazon Macie is its ability to provide users with a comprehensive view of their data security posture. It uses machine learning algorithms to identify sensitive data and then applies various techniques to analyze and classify it. This allows users to quickly and easily identify areas where they need to improve their security posture and take action to address any vulnerabilities.',trap:'The option that says: Implement AWS Audit Manager within the AWS account and opt for auditing based on the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards (PCI DSS) is incorrect. AWS Audit Manager is simply a service used for managing audits and compliance assessments. While it\'s valuable for auditing against specific compliance standards like PCI DSS, the AWS Audit Manager is more focused on evaluating and managing compliance rather than actively discovering sensitive data within S3 buckets. This service might help ensure proper security controls, but it won\'t directly address the goal of identifying sensitive data stored in the S3 bucket.',rule:'One of the key features of Amazon Macie is its ability to provide users with a comprehensive view of their data security posture.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_58',category:'IAM',question:'A well-known music streaming service is planning to broaden its platform globally. However, the company must ensure that listeners in certain countries cannot access specific music content until it is officially launched in their respective regions, in accordance with its music licensing agreements and restrictions. To achieve this, the company will utilize Amazon CloudFront\'s content delivery network and Origin Access Control (OAC) feature to prevent unauthorized users from accessing the content. Customized error messages must also be configured for users who are not authorized to access particular music tracks. What solution would be able to fulfill these requirements?',choices:['A|Configure CloudFront to return a custom error response to the viewer. Use both signed URLs and signed cookies for secure content access.','B|Configure CloudFront to return a custom error response to the viewer. Implement a time-restricted IAM access policy for CloudFront distribution.','C|Configure CloudFront to return a custom error response to the viewer. Set up a CloudFront Function URL to control access.','D|Configure CloudFront to return a custom error response to the viewer and apply geographic restrictions using an Allow list.'],correct:'D',answer:'You can use Geographic restrictions, sometimes known as geo blocking to prevent users in specific countries from accessing your content, and you can specify whether you want CloudFront to create standard logs or real-time logs showing viewer activity.',why:'Amazon CloudFront is a web service that speeds up distribution of your static and dynamic web content, such as .html, .css, .js, and image files, to your users. CloudFront delivers your content through a worldwide network of data centers called edge locations.',trap:'The option that says: Configure CloudFront to return a custom error response to the viewer. Use both signed URLs and signed cookies for secure content access is incorrect because the solution does not effectively enforce geographic restrictions to certain countries. It also adds unnecessary complexity to the system and could impact the user experience. Signed URLs and signed cookies are meant to be used if you want to securely serve private content exclusively via CloudFront (restricting direct S3 access) through the use of specialized URLs with session tokens or browser-based cookies.',rule:'CloudFront speeds up delivery of your static and dynamic web content, such as .html, .css, .js, and image files. Geo restriction blocks users from specific countries. Custom SSL certs via ACM in us-east-1.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_59',category:'Serverless',question:'An enterprise company uses multiple AWS accounts for different business units. The AWS accounts are set up and consolidated into an organization via the AWS Organizations service. The company sites are distributed globally across different countries and regions. There is a need to centrally manage security group rules across the organization to allow CIDR ranges of new office locations and remove old CIDR ranges as needed. What design should the solutions architect propose to meet the requirements in the MOST cost-effective manner?',choices:['A|Enable Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (Route 53 ARC) in the AWS account. Create a Recovery Control Panel to define the routing control states and configurations of the CIDR ranges of each business unit or company site. Define routing control states within the RCP to indicate how traffic should be routed. Enable Zonal Shift functionality in Route 53 ARC to shift traffic from one set of resources to another with the defined CIDR ranges.','B|Leverage AWS Firewall Manager to create a common security group policy. Select the security groups previously created as the primary group in the policy.','C|Provision a VPC customer-managed prefix list using the AWS CLI or the Amazon VPC console and add the CIDR blocks to be included in the list. Share the prefix list ID to other AWS accounts using the AWS RAM (Resource Access Manager) API, or the AWS RAM Console. Add the prefix list to the security groups used across the organization.','D|Build an AWS-managed prefix list in Amazon VPC containing the CIDR blocks to allow or block. Enable Security Hub for the AWS accounts and define a policy that specifies the desired security group updates. Create a Lambda function to call the modify_managed_prefix_list API that can be triggered by Amazon EventBridge when updating the CIDR blocks.'],correct:'C',answer:'A managed prefix list is a set of one or more CIDR blocks. You can use prefix lists to make it easier to configure and maintain your security groups and route tables. You can create a prefix list from the IP addresses that you frequently use, and reference them as a set in security group rules and routes instead of referencing them individually.',why:'Customer-managed prefix lists — Sets of IP address ranges that you define and manage. You can share your prefix list with other AWS accounts, enabling those accounts to reference the prefix list in their own resources. AWS-managed prefix lists — Sets of IP address ranges for AWS services. You cannot create, modify, share, or delete an AWS-managed prefix list.',trap:'The option that says: Build an AWS-managed prefix list in Amazon VPC containing the CIDR blocks to allow or block. Enable Security Hub for the AWS accounts and define a policy that specifies the desired security group updates. Create a Lambda function to call the modify_managed_prefix_list API that can be triggered by Amazon EventBridge when updating the CIDR blocks is incorrect because AWS-managed prefix lists cannot be modified by users, unlike its customer-managed prefix list counterpart. The option also involves using Security Hub and Lambda functions, which are not directly related to managing CIDR ranges in security groups.',rule:'Multi-region → VPC, AWS CLI or the Amazon VP. Not Amazon VPC.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_60',category:'IAM',question:'A startup company is developing a new application in AWS. The architecture is a web application with an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster, an Amazon S3 bucket where the application assets are stored, and a managed Amazon RDS for MySQL Database. The database layer of the web application contains personally identifiable information (PII) data. As part of compliance requirements, data in both the RDS for MySQL database, and the S3 bucket should be securely accessed only by the ECS cluster. How should the system be designed to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Configure a VPC endpoint to establish a private connection between the VPC and the RDS for MySQL database. Update the RDS for MySQL security group to only allow access from subnets of the ECS cluster. Add an S3 bucket policy to restrict access to the ECS task execution role, with an exception allowing public internet access to the S3 bucket.','B|Configure two VPC endpoints for RDS for MySQL database and Amazon S3. Add an allow rule for the RDS for MySQL security group to grant access from subnets that the ECS cluster will generate tasks in. Add an S3 bucket policy to deny access to the resources that matches StringNotEquals of aws:SourceVpce list with the VPC endpoint id.','C|Create and configure an Amazon RDS Proxy for the RDS for MySQL database to use the appropriate database endpoint and port for the RDS for MySQL database. Define an Identity Access Management (IAM) role that grants permission to the ECS task execution role to access the RDS Proxy. Update the ECS task definition to assume this role. Define an IAM policy that allows S3 actions to the IAM role in the S3 bucket. Attach the IAM policy to the IAM role.','D|Provision a new AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) customer-managed key to encrypt both the S3 bucket and the RDS for MySQL database. Ensure that the KMS key policy includes encrypt and decrypt permissions for the ECS task execution role. Then, configure an S3 bucket policy to specify the ECS task execution role as a user, allowing access to the encrypted data.'],correct:'B',answer:'An RDS Proxy pools database connections and uses IAM authentication integrated with Secrets Manager for secure connection management. For the web app to reach RDS via VPC endpoint privately, a VPC endpoint for RDS Proxy is used.',why:'The scenario requires: (1) a VPC endpoint to keep traffic private, and (2) RDS Proxy for connection pooling with IAM-based authentication. RDS Proxy maintains a warm connection pool and authenticates using IAM credentials stored in Secrets Manager, eliminating hardcoded database passwords in the application.',trap:'A plain VPC endpoint for RDS (without Proxy) provides private connectivity but does not provide connection pooling or IAM-based authentication. Adding two separate endpoints (one for RDS, one for S3) does not address the connection management or authentication requirement. KMS encryption addresses data at rest, not connection management.',rule:'Private RDS access + connection pooling + IAM auth = RDS Proxy + VPC endpoint. RDS Proxy uses Secrets Manager for credentials. Keeps traffic private via VPC endpoint.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_61',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is strengthening its security measures and seeks to enforce data encryption at rest for its Amazon EC2 instances. An automated solution is required to detect unencrypted Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volumes and apply policies to rectify them. Which option will meet these requirements with the LEAST administrative overhead?',choices:['A|Set up an IAM policy to ensure that only encrypted EBS volumes can be created. Create an AWS Config rule that tracks unencrypted EBS volumes and use an AWS Systems Manager Automation document for remediation.','B|Configure an AWS KMS key policy that only allows the creation of encrypted EBS volumes. Use a combination of Amazon EventBridge and AWS Lambda to detect and remediate unencrypted EBS volumes automatically.','C|Scan for unencrypted EBS volumes using AWS Shield. Use AWS Systems Manager Automation rules to encrypt the detected volumes automatically.','D|Scan for unencrypted EBS volumes using Amazon Inspector. Use AWS Systems Manager Automation rules to encrypt the detected volumes automatically.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) is an easy-to-use, scalable, high-performance block-storage service designed for Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2). When referring to data at rest in EC2, this generally means EBS volumes.',why:'AWS Config is a config tool that helps you assess, audit, and evaluate the configurations and relationships of your resources. Config provides a detailed view of the configuration of AWS resources in your AWS account. This includes how the resources are related to one another and how they were configured in the past so that you can see how the configurations and relationships change over time.',trap:'The option that says: Scan for unencrypted EBS volumes using Amazon Inspector. Use AWS Systems Manager Automation rules to encrypt the detected volumes automatically is incorrect because Amazon Inspector is simply a service for detecting software vulnerability and unintended network exposure in your workloads across AWS. While it can be used to assess the security of an environment. it is not specifically tailored for continuous monitoring or detecting the encryption status of EBS volumes.',rule:'Encryption → IAM, EBS. Not Amazon Inspector.',keywords:'Encrypt unencrypted EBS → copy snapshot with encryption enabled, create new volume.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_62',category:'Networking',question:'A digital company is using EC2 instances to host editing software that is remotely accessed by their teams. Due to licensing restrictions, the application cannot be deployed in the ap-southeast-1 (Singapore) region. A team based in the Philippines needs to access the application, requiring connectivity with latency in the single-digit millisecond range. Which of the following solutions addresses these requirements?',choices:['A|Use Amazon CloudFront’s edge locations to extend the company’s VPC to other countries in Asia. Launch the applications to the ap-southeast-1 region.','B|Enable AWS Local Zones within the ap-southeast-1 region. Extend the company\'s VPC to the selected Local Zone and launch the applications in that zone.','C|Launch the applications in the ap-southeast-1 region. Then, use AWS Outposts to extend the company’s VPC to an on-premises network in the Philippines.','D|Enable AWS Wavelength Zones within the ap-southeast-1 region. Extend the company\'s VPC to the selected Wavelength Zones and launch the applications in that zone.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Local Zones are a type of AWS infrastructure deployment that places compute, storage, database, and other select services closer to large population, industry, and IT centers, enabling you to deliver applications that require single-digit millisecond latency to end-users.',why:'In this scenario, since the company cannot use the software in the ap-southeast-1 region, they can opt to extend a VPC in ap-southeast-1 to a Local Zone in the Philippines. Then, they will need to launch the application in the Local Zone instead of the native Availability Zones of ap-southeast-1.',trap:'The option that says: Enable AWS Wavelength Zones within the ap-southeast-1 region. Extend the company\'s VPC to the selected Wavelength Zones and launch the applications in that zone is incorrect because Wavelength Zones are designed to cater to mobile-specific workloads while the scenario specifically outlines the requirements for a desktop application that would be accessed.',rule:'access the application → AWS Local, Local Zone. Not Wavelength Zones.',keywords:'millisecond latency + NoSQL → DynamoDB. Key-value or document store → DynamoDB.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_63',category:'Serverless',question:'A merchandising company is planning to enhance its storage capabilities for Amazon EC2 instances by using Amazon FSx for Windows File Server. The company’s EC2 instance in the us-east-2 region has a Server Message Block (SMB) file share mounted as a volume. The company has set a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 10 minutes to mitigate the risks associated with disruptions. Moreover, the company aims to have a backup copy of this file system in the us-west-1 region and must ensure that users cannot delete or alter the data for 5 years to meet compliance and governance standards. Which of the solutions will fulfill these requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Configure an AWS FSx for Windows File Server file system in us-east-2 with a Multi-AZ deployment type. Utilize AWS Backup to establish a daily backup plan with a rule replicating the backup to us-west-1.','B|Set up AWS Backup Vault Lock in governance mode for a target vault in us-east-2 and configure the minimum retention duration of 5 years.','C|Enable Vault Lock in compliance mode for a designated vault in the us-east-2 region on AWS Backup. Configure the data retention period to be a minimum of 5 years.','D|Launch an AWS FSx for Windows File Server file system in us-east-2 with a Single-AZ 2 deployment type. Use AWS Backup to establish a daily backup plan, including a backup rule to copy the backup to us-west-1.','E|Establish an AWS FSx for Windows File Server file system in us-east-2, and opt for a Multi-AZ deployment type. Configure a Lambda function that sets a daily backup and includes a rule to replicate the backup to us-west-1.'],correct:'AC',answer:'Configure FSx for Windows File Server with Multi-AZ deployment type for high availability (A), and use AWS Backup with Vault Lock in compliance mode with a minimum retention of 5 years (C). Multi-AZ ensures HA; compliance mode Vault Lock ensures backups cannot be deleted for the required period.',why:'FSx for Windows File Server Multi-AZ provides automatic failover to a standby file server in a different AZ, ensuring business continuity. AWS Backup Vault Lock in compliance mode (not governance mode) prevents anyone — including root — from deleting backups before the retention period expires. This satisfies a regulatory 5-year immutable retention requirement.',trap:'Governance mode Vault Lock (B) can be overridden by privileged users — it does not satisfy strict compliance requirements. Single-AZ deployment (D) is not highly available. A Lambda function to manage backups (E) introduces operational overhead and is not the managed solution.',rule:'FSx HA = Multi-AZ deployment. Immutable backup compliance = AWS Backup Vault Lock in COMPLIANCE mode (not governance). Governance mode = can be overridden. Compliance mode = no one can override.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_64',category:'Kinesis',question:'A retail company is exploring AWS services to enhance its customer experience by understanding the intricate relationships between customer interactions, product preferences, and purchasing patterns. The goal is to implement a solution that not only efficiently stores and manages this complex, relationship-rich data but also dynamically tracks changes in the database. This capability is crucial for developing a sophisticated recommendation engine that tailors product suggestions to individual user behaviors and preferences. Which option would best meet these requirements with the least operational overhead?',choices:['A|Configure Amazon Neptune to manage the data and integrate with Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for tracking and processing database changes.','B|Set up Amazon Neptune to store the data and utilize Neptune Streams to monitor and analyze database changes in real time.','C|Store transactional data in Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL and use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for managing and analyzing changes.','D|Use Amazon Keyspaces (for Apache Cassandra) for data storage and connect it with Neptune Streams for effective change monitoring and analysis.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Neptune is a purpose-built, fully-managed graph database service optimized for storing billions of relationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. It supports highly connected data typical in social networking, recommendation engines, and fraud detection applications.',why:'Neptune Streams is a feature within Amazon Neptune that allows for the capture of changes made to graph data in real-time. It reliably logs every change to the graph as it happens, in the order it is made, making these changes accessible via an HTTP REST API.',trap:'The option that says: Configure Amazon Neptune to manage the data and integrate with Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for tracking and processing database changes is incorrect because while Amazon Kinesis Data Streams can process large streams of data records, it does not inherently understand the graph relationships within the data like Neptune Streams does. Neptune Streams is specifically designed to work with Neptune\'s graph data model, capturing and logging the changes in the graph data directly.',rule:'Neptune Streams is a feature within Amazon Neptune that allows for the capture of changes made to graph data in real-time. Not Amazon Kinesis.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q6_65',category:'Storage',question:'An external audit of a financial technology startup found some glaring issues in its IT practices, one being the use of unencrypted Amazon EBS volumes in some of its workloads. To improve its security posture, the startup must ensure all data at rest is encrypted using AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS). Which solution provides the ability to control rotation of the encryption keys with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Provision a customer managed key. Encrypt the EBS volumes using the provisioned key.','B|Use an AWS managed key to encrypt the EBS volumes. Configure key rotation.','C|Generate a key material and import it to AWS KMS to create an external KMS key. Encrypt the EBS volumes using the created key.','D|Provision an AWS owned key. Encrypt the EBS volumes using the provisioned key.'],correct:'A',answer:'Provision a customer managed key. Encrypt the EBS volumes using the provisioned key.',why:'AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) is a managed service that makes it easy for you to create and control the cryptographic keys that are used to protect your data. It integrates with most other AWS service that encrypt your data. AWS KMS also integrates with AWS CloudTrail to log use of your KMS keys for auditing, regulatory, and compliance needs.',trap:'The option that says: Use an AWS managed key to encrypt the EBS volumes. Configure key rotation is incorrect because AWS managed keys, as their name implies, are managed by AWS which means the least amount of overhead but does not allow for any fine-grained control of key rotation, only to enable/disable it.',rule:'Provision a customer managed key. This gives you full control over key rotation, usage policies, and key deletion.',keywords:'Encrypt unencrypted EBS → copy snapshot with encryption enabled, create new volume.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 5'},
  {id:'q7_1',category:'EC2',question:'A multinational corporate and investment bank regularly processes steady workloads of accruals, loan interests, and other critical financial calculations every night from 10 PM to 3 AM on their on-premises data center for their corporate clients. Once the process is done, the results are then uploaded to the Oracle General Ledger which means that the processing should not be delayed or interrupted. The CTO has decided to move its IT infrastructure to AWS to save costs. The company needs to reserve compute capacity in a specific Availability Zone to properly run their workloads. As the Senior Solutions Architect, how can you implement a cost-effective architecture in AWS for their financial system?',choices:['A|Use On-Demand EC2 instances which allows you to pay for the instances that you launch and use by the second. Reserve compute capacity in a specific Availability Zone to avoid any interruption.','B|Use Regional Reserved Instances to reserve capacity on a specific Availability Zone and lower the operating cost through its billing discounts.','C|Use On-Demand Capacity Reservations, which provide compute capacity that is always available on the specified recurring schedule.','D|Use Dedicated Hosts, which provide a physical host that is fully dedicated to running your instances, and bring your existing per-socket, per-core, or per-VM software licenses to reduce costs.'],correct:'A',answer:'On-Demand Capacity Reservations enable you to reserve compute capacity for your Amazon EC2 instances in a specific Availability Zone for any duration. This gives you the ability to create and manage Capacity Reservations independently from the billing discounts offered by Savings Plans or Regional Reserved Instances.',why:'By creating Capacity Reservations, you ensure that you always have access to EC2 capacity when you need it, for as long as you need it. You can create Capacity Reservations at any time, without entering into a one-year or three-year term commitment, and the capacity is available immediately. Billing starts as soon as the capacity is provisioned and the Capacity Reservation enters the active state.',trap:'The option that says: Use On-Demand EC2 instances which allows you to pay for the instances that you launch and use by the second. Reserve compute capacity in a specific Availability Zone to avoid any interruption is incorrect because although an On-Demand instance is stable and suitable for processing critical data, it costs more than any other option. Moreover, the critical financial calculations are only done every night from 10 PM to 3 AM and not 24/7. This means that your computing capacity will not be utilized for a total of 19 hours every single day. On-Demand instances cannot reserve compute capacity at all. So this option is incorrect.',rule:'Guaranteed EC2 capacity in specific AZ = On-Demand Capacity Reservation. No term commitment, billed at On-Demand rate regardless of use. Combine with RI/Savings Plans for cost reduction. Capacity Reservations can be shared using Resource Access Manager (RAM).',keywords:'Guarantee capacity in specific AZ → On-Demand Capacity Reservation. Pays On-Demand rate regardless.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_2',category:'Storage',question:'An e-commerce company plans to optimize its disaster recovery configuration using AWS Cloud to minimize operational disruptions during outages or major system maintenance for its on-premises Microsoft SQL Server-based application. The objective is to achieve a recovery point objective (RPO) of 60 seconds or less and a recovery time objective (RTO) of 1 hour. Which of the following is the MOST cost-effective solution for this scenario?',choices:['A|Use Microsoft SQL Server Enterprise with Always On availability groups and set up a multi-site active/active setup between the corporate on-premises application and AWS.','B|Back up SQL Server to AWS Storage Gateway for hybrid storage and fast disaster recovery. Enable fast snapshot restore in Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS).','C|Set up a pilot light strategy using AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (AWS DRS) to replicate the changes of the on-premises application to AWS','D|On AWS, implement a warm standby using Amazon RDS for SQL Server database and configure AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) with change data capture (CDC) to sync the data from the on-premises application.'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (AWS DRS) provides continuous block-level replication, recovery orchestration, and automated server conversion capabilities. These allow customers to achieve a crash-consistent recovery point objective (RPO) of seconds, and a recovery time objective (RTO) typically ranging between 5–20 minutes.',why:'To establish a secure data replication process, configure AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery on your source servers. This setup involves replicating your data to a dedicated subnet within your AWS account located in the AWS Region of your choice. By utilizing a staging area design, this approach optimizes cost-efficiency by leveraging cost-effective storage and minimal compute resources for continuous replication maintenance.',trap:'The option that says: Use Microsoft SQL Server Enterprise with Always On availability groups and set up a multi-site active/active setup between the corporate on-premises application and AWS is incorrect. Although using the "SQL Server Always On availability groups" feature can meet the required RTO and RPO, this approach entails high costs. Take note that the scenario explicitly mentioned that the cost of the disaster recovery solution should be low. This particular setup requires multiple replication servers to run, and thus, the operating cost is high. In this situation, a more cost-effective solution is to use the AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (AWS DRS) service.',rule:'AWS Elastic Disaster Rec|AWS DRS: correct. Use Microsoft: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'S3 Cross-Region Replication: versioning required on both buckets. Replicates new objects only by default.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_3',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has multiple AWS sandbox accounts that are used by its development team. All developers must be given access to the contents of one of the main account’s S3 buckets. For security purposes, any personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data uploaded in the bucket must be continuously monitored and removed. How can this be done at the lowest possible cost and with the least amount of configuration effort?',choices:['A|Create an S3 bucket policy that grants access from the sandbox accounts. Use Amazon Macie to discover personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data.','B|Configure cross-account replication on the S3 bucket. Integrate AWS Audit Manager with the S3 bucket to discover any personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data.','C|Generate a pre-signed URL for the objects on the S3 bucket. Use the Amazon S3 Storage Lens to discover personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data.','D|Add S3 read permission to the IAM policy of each IAM user from the sandbox accounts. Use Amazon Detective to discover personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data.'],correct:'A',answer:'In Amazon S3, you can grant users in another AWS account (Account B) granular cross-account access to objects owned by your account (Account A). Depending on the type of access that you want to provide, use one of the following solutions to grant cross-account access to objects: Use a bucket policy that grants cross-account access, or use a pre-signed URL, or use CORS.',why:'In the scenario, the best approach to granting the developers access to the main account\'s S3 bucket is by configuring the bucket policy to allow IAM users from different accounts to call the GetObject method. This is a neater and simpler solution than the rest because you control access from a single location without any additional costs.',trap:'The option that says: Configure cross-account replication on the S3 bucket. Integrate AWS Audit Manager with the S3 bucket to discover any personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data is incorrect. This can work, but it is an inefficient way of solving the problem. The developers only need to access the S3 objects in another account; they do not need to own a copy of them. On top of that, replication incurs additional costs. In addition, the AWS Audit Manager simply helps you continuously audit your AWS usage to simplify how you assess risk and compliance with regulations and industry standards. AWS Audit Manager is not capable of discovering personally identifiable information (PII) or financial data in your S3 bucket.',rule:'Monitoring → Amazon Macie to discover personally i. Not AWS Audit.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_4',category:'Storage',question:'A company has several EC2 Reserved Instances in their account that need to be decommissioned and shut down since they are no longer used by the development team. However, the data is still required by the audit team for compliance purposes. Which of the following steps can be taken in this scenario? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Convert the EC2 instance to On-Demand instances','B|You can opt to sell these EC2 instances on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace','C|Take snapshots of the EBS volumes and terminate the EC2 instances.','D|Convert the EC2 instances to Spot instances with a persistent Spot request type.','E|Stop all the running EC2 instances.'],correct:'BC',answer:'Unused Standard Reserved Instances can be sold on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace to recoup cost when they are no longer needed after decommissioning.',why:'The AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace allows you to sell unused Standard RI capacity to other AWS customers. You set your price and AWS facilitates the transaction. Convertible RIs cannot be sold — only Standard RIs. The RI commitment cannot be cancelled, but selling on the Marketplace recovers value. Note: only US East (N. Virginia) RIs can be sold to entities outside the originating country.',trap:'Converting RIs to On-Demand or Spot types is not possible — you cannot change the purchase model of an existing RI. Converting to Spot with persistent request would still require paying the RI commitment cost. Simply stopping instances does not eliminate the RI billing commitment.',rule:'Unused Standard RI = sell on RI Marketplace. Convertible RI = exchange only (cannot sell). Stopping instances does not cancel RI billing. Cannot convert RI type between Standard/Convertible. Convertible = can exchange instance family, OS, tenancy. Standard = can sell on Marketplace.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_5',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to use a cloud storage service to temporarily store its log files. The number of files to be stored is still unknown, but it only needs to be kept for 12 hours. Which of the following is the most cost-effective storage class to use in this scenario?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 Standard','B|Amazon S3 One Zone-IA','C|Amazon S3 Standard-IA','D|Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) is an object storage service that offers industry-leading scalability, data availability, security, and performance. Amazon S3 also offers a range of storage classes for the objects that you store. You choose a class depending on your use case scenario and performance access requirements.',why:'The scenario requires you to select a cost-effective service that does not have a minimum storage duration since the data will only last for 12 hours. Among the options given, only Amazon S3 Standard has the feature of no minimum storage duration.',trap:'Amazon S3 Standard-IA is incorrect because this storage class has a minimum storage duration of at least 30 days. Remember that the scenario requires the data to be kept for 12 hours only.',rule:'be kept for 12 hours → Amazon S3.',keywords:'S3 Intelligent-Tiering: auto-moves objects between access tiers. No retrieval fee for frequent or infrequent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_6',category:'Networking',question:'A fast food company is using AWS to host its online ordering system which uses an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances deployed across multiple Availability Zones with an Application Load Balancer in front. To better handle the incoming traffic from various digital devices, a new routing logic is being considered. Requests with URLs matching /api/android should be directed to a target group named "Android-Target-Group". Conversely, requests which have a URL of /api/ios are forwarded to another separate target group named "iOS-Target-Group". How can this change be implemented in AWS?',choices:['A|Use host conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the hostname in the host header. This enables you to support multiple domains using a single load balancer.','B|Replace your ALB with a Gateway Load Balancer then use path conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the URL in the request.','C|Use path conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the URL in the request.','D|Replace your ALB with a Network Load Balancer then use host conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the URL in the request.'],correct:'B',answer:'If your application is composed of several individual services, an Application Load Balancer can route a request to a service based on the content of the request, such as Host field, Path URL, HTTP header, HTTP method, Query string, or Source IP address. Path-based routing allows you to route a client request based on the URL path of the HTTP header.',why:'A path pattern is case-sensitive, can be up to 128 characters in length, and can contain any of the following characters. You can include up to three wildcard characters. You can use path conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the URL in the request (also known as path-based routing). This type of routing is the most appropriate solution for this scenario.',trap:'The option that says: Use host conditions to define rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the hostname in the host header. This enables you to support multiple domains using a single load balancer is incorrect because host-based routing primarily defines rules that forward requests to different target groups based on the hostname in the host header instead of the URL, which is what is needed in this scenario.',rule:'Each path condition has one',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_7',category:'Networking',question:'A global news network created a CloudFront distribution for their web application. However, you noticed that the application\'s origin server is being hit for each request instead of the AWS Edge locations, which serve the cached objects. The issue occurs even for the commonly requested objects. What could be a possible cause of this issue?',choices:['A|An object is only cached by CloudFront once a successful request has been made hence, the objects were not requested before, which is why the request is still directed to the origin server.','B|The file sizes of the cached objects are too large for CloudFront to handle.','C|The Cache-Control max-age directive is set to zero.','D|There are two primary origins configured in your Amazon CloudFront Origin Group.'],correct:'C',answer:'You can control how long your objects stay in a CloudFront cache before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin. Reducing the duration allows you to serve dynamic content. Increasing the duration means your users get better performance because your objects are more likely to be served directly from the edge cache.',why:'Typically, CloudFront serves an object from an edge location until the cache duration that you specified passes — that is, until the object expires. After it expires, the next time the edge location gets a user request for the object, CloudFront forwards the request to the origin server to verify that the cache contains the latest version of the object. The Cache-Control and Expires headers control how long objects stay in the cache.',trap:'The option that says: An object is only cached by CloudFront once a successful request has been made hence, the objects were not requested before, which is why the request is still directed to the origin server is incorrect because the issue also occurs even for the commonly requested objects. This means that these objects were successfully requested before but due to a zero Cache-Control max-age directive value, it causes this issue in CloudFront.',rule:'CloudFront cache invalidation removes objects before they expire. Use /* to invalidate all objects. Objects stay in cache until the cache duration that you specified passes — that is, until the object expires naturally.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_8',category:'Serverless',question:'A game development company operates several virtual reality (VR) and augmented reality (AR) games which use various RESTful web APIs hosted on their on-premises data center. Due to the unprecedented growth of their company, they decided to migrate their system to AWS Cloud to scale out their resources as well to minimize costs. Which of the following should you recommend as the most cost-effective and scalable solution to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Lambda and Amazon API Gateway.','B|Set up a micro-service architecture with ECS, ECR, and Fargate.','C|Host the APIs in a static S3 web hosting bucket behind a CloudFront web distribution.','D|Use a Spot Fleet of Amazon EC2 instances, each with an Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) for more consistent latency and higher network throughput. Set up an Application Load Balancer to distribute traffic to the instances.'],correct:'A',answer:'With AWS Lambda, you pay only for what you use. You are charged based on the number of requests for your functions and the duration, the time it takes for your code to execute.',why:'Lambda counts a request each time it starts executing in response to an event notification or invoke call, including test invokes from the console. You are charged for the total number of requests across all your functions.',trap:'The option that says: Setting up a micro-service architecture with ECS, ECR, and Fargate is incorrect because ECS is mainly used to host Docker applications, and in addition, using ECS, ECR, and Fargate alone is not scalable and not recommended for this type of scenario.',rule:'Lambda counts a request each time it starts executing in response to an event notification or invoke call, including test invokes from the console. Lambda charges for duration × memory × provisioned concurrency (if configured).',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_9',category:'S3',question:'A computer animation film studio runs a web application on an Amazon EC2 instance. It uploads 5 GB video objects to an Amazon S3 bucket. Video uploads take longer than expected, impacting the application\'s performance. Which method will help improve the performance of the application?',choices:['A|Enable Enhanced Networking with the Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) on your EC2 Instances.','B|Use S3 Multipart Upload API.','C|Leverage on Amazon CloudFront and use HTTP POST method to reduce latency.','D|Use Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) Provisioned IOPS volumes in a Logical Volume Management (LVM) stripe configuration on an EBS-optimized instance to maximize throughput.'],correct:'B',answer:'The main issue is the slow upload time of the video objects to Amazon S3. To address this issue, you can use Multipart upload in S3 to improve the throughput. It allows you to upload parts of your object in parallel thus, decreasing the time it takes to upload big objects. Each part is a contiguous portion of the object\'s data.',why:'You can upload these object parts independently and in any order. If transmission of any part fails, you can retransmit that part without affecting other parts. After all parts of your object are uploaded, Amazon S3 assembles these parts and creates the object. In general, when your object size reaches 100 MB, you should consider using multipart uploads instead of uploading the object in a single operation.',trap:'The option that says: Leveraging on Amazon CloudFront and using HTTP POST method to reduce latency is incorrect because CloudFront is a CDN service and is not used to expedite the upload process of objects to Amazon S3. Amazon CloudFront is a fast content delivery network (CDN) service that securely delivers data, videos, applications, and APIs to customers globally with low latency, high transfer speeds, all within a developer-friendly environment.',rule:'Each part is a contiguous portion of the object\'s data.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_10',category:'Serverless',question:'A Solutions Architect needs to launch a web application that will be served globally using Amazon CloudFront. The application is hosted in an Amazon EC2 instance which will be configured as the origin server to process and serve dynamic content to its customers. Which of the following options provides high availability for the application?',choices:['A|Use Amazon S3 to serve the dynamic content of your web application and configure the S3 bucket to be part of an origin group.','B|Launch an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and configure it to be part of an origin group.','C|Provision two EC2 instances deployed in different Availability Zones and configure them to be part of an origin group.','D|Use Lambda@Edge to improve the performance of your web application and ensure high availability. Set the Lambda@Edge functions to be part of an origin group.'],correct:'C',answer:'An origin is a location where content is stored and from which CloudFront gets content to serve to viewers. Amazon CloudFront is a service that speeds up the distribution of your static and dynamic web content, such as .html, .css, .js, and image files, to your users. CloudFront delivers your content through a worldwide network of data centers called edge locations.',why:'You can also set up CloudFront with origin failover for scenarios that require high availability. An origin group may contain two origins: a primary and a secondary. If the primary origin is unavailable or returns specific HTTP response status codes that indicate a failure, CloudFront automatically switches to the secondary origin. To set up origin failover, you must have a distribution with at least two origins.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon S3 to serve the dynamic content of your web application and configure the S3 bucket to be part of an origin group is incorrect because Amazon S3 can only serve static content. If you need to host dynamic content, you have to use an Amazon EC2 instance instead.',rule:'HA → EC2. Not Use Amazon.',keywords:'CloudFront 504 errors → Origin Failover group (primary + secondary origin). Automatic switch on 5xx.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_11',category:'S3',question:'A multinational company has been building its new data analytics platform with high-performance computing workloads (HPC) which requires a scalable, POSIX-compliant storage service. The data need to be stored redundantly across multiple AZs and allows concurrent connections from thousands of EC2 instances hosted on multiple Availability Zones. Which of the following AWS storage service is the most suitable one to use in this scenario?',choices:['A|Amazon EBS Volumes','B|Amazon Elastic File System','C|Amazon S3','D|Amazon ElastiCache'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon S3 is the standard storage for large-scale, shared, high-throughput analytics data in HPC and ML workloads due to its unlimited scale, high aggregate throughput, and native integration with EMR, SageMaker, and other analytics services.',why:'S3 provides effectively unlimited storage with high aggregate bandwidth. For HPC workloads that read input data in parallel (many compute nodes reading simultaneously), S3 scales horizontally — adding more nodes adds more aggregate throughput from S3 in parallel. S3 also integrates natively with EMR, Glue, Athena, Redshift Spectrum, and SageMaker.',trap:'Amazon EBS volumes are per-instance storage — they cannot be shared across multiple EC2 instances in a cluster simultaneously (except io1/io2 Multi-Attach, which is limited). EFS can be shared but has lower throughput than S3 for large-scale HPC reads and costs more.',rule:'HPC/ML shared high-throughput storage = Amazon S3 (unlimited scale, high aggregate parallel reads). EBS = per-instance (no cluster sharing except Multi-Attach). EFS = shared NFS bucket mountable from thousands of instances across multiple AZs simultaneously.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_12',category:'Serverless',question:'A startup is building a microservices architecture in which the software is composed of small independent services that communicate over well-defined APIs. In building large-scale systems, fine-grained decoupling of microservices is a recommended practice to implement. The decoupled services should scale horizontally from each other to improve scalability. What is the difference between Horizontal scaling and Vertical scaling?',choices:['A|Vertical scaling means running the same software on a fully serverless architecture using Lambda. Horizontal scaling means adding more servers to the existing pool and it doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers.','B|Horizontal scaling means running the same software on bigger machines which is limited by the capacity of individual servers. Vertical scaling is adding more servers to the existing pool and doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers.','C|Vertical scaling means running the same software on bigger machines which is limited by the capacity of the individual server. Horizontal scaling is adding more servers to the existing pool and doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers.','D|Horizontal scaling means running the same software on smaller containers such as Docker and Kubernetes using ECS or EKS. Vertical scaling is adding more servers to the existing pool and doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers.'],correct:'A',answer:'Vertical scaling means running the same software on bigger machines which is limited by the capacity of the individual server. Horizontal scaling is adding more servers to the existing pool and doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers.',why:'Fine-grained decoupling of microservices is a best practice for building large-scale systems. It’s a prerequisite for performance optimization since it allows choosing the appropriate and optimal technologies for a specific service. Each service can be implemented with the appropriate programming languages and frameworks, leverage the optimal data persistence solution, and be fine-tuned with the best-performing service configurations.',trap:'The option that says: Vertical scaling means running the same software on a fully serverless architecture using Lambda. Horizontal scaling means adding more servers to the existing pool and it doesn’t run into limitations of individual servers is incorrect because Vertical scaling is not about running the same software on a fully serverless architecture. AWS Lambda is not required for scaling.',rule:'Fine-grained decoupling of microservices is a best practice for building large-scale systems.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_13',category:'Other',question:'A company plans to launch an application that tracks the GPS coordinates of delivery trucks in the country. The coordinates are transmitted from each delivery truck every five seconds. The must be able to process coordinates from multiple consumers in real-time. The aggregated data will be analyzed in a separate reporting application. Which AWS service should you use for this scenario?',choices:['A|Amazon Kinesis','B|Amazon Elastic MapReduce (EMR)','C|Amazon AppStream','D|Amazon Simple Queue Service'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Kinesis makes it easy to collect, process, and analyze real-time, streaming data so you can get timely insights and react quickly to new information. It offers key capabilities to cost-effectively process streaming data at any scale, along with the flexibility to choose the tools that best suit the requirements of your application.',why:'With Amazon Kinesis, you can ingest real-time data such as video, audio, application logs, website clickstreams, and IoT telemetry data for machine learning, analytics, and other applications. Amazon Kinesis enables you to process and analyze data as it arrives and responds instantly instead of having to wait until all your data are collected before the processing can begin.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon Elastic MapReduce (EMR) is incorrect because EMR is primarily used for big data processing, often in batch mode, using frameworks like Hadoop and Spark. It\'s great for processing vast amounts of data, but it’s not optimized for real-time streaming data.',rule:'Real-time → Amazon Kinesis. Not Amazon Elastic.',keywords:'Microservices on ECS: ALB path-based routing per service. App Mesh for service mesh. Cloud Map for discovery.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_14',category:'IAM',question:'A company requires corporate IT governance and cost oversight of all of its AWS resources across its divisions around the world. Their corporate divisions want to maintain administrative control of the discrete AWS resources they consume and ensure that those resources are separate from other divisions. Which of the following options will support the autonomy of each corporate division while enabling the corporate IT to maintain governance and cost oversight? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use AWS Trusted Advisor and AWS Resource Groups Tag Editor','B|Enable IAM cross-account access for all corporate IT administrators in each child account.','C|Create separate VPCs for each division within the corporate IT AWS account. Launch an AWS Transit Gateway with equal-cost multipath routing (ECMP) and VPN tunnels for intra-VPC communication.','D|Use AWS Consolidated Billing by creating AWS Organizations to link the divisions’ accounts to a parent corporate account.','E|Create separate Availability Zones for each division within the corporate IT AWS account. Improve communication between the two AZs using the AWS Global Accelerator.'],correct:'BD',answer:'AWS Organizations with Consolidated Billing links all division accounts under a management account, providing a unified billing view and enabling sharing of Reserved Instance and Savings Plans discounts across accounts. This satisfies both the cost oversight and multi-account governance requirements.',why:'AWS Organizations consolidates billing across all linked accounts into a single payment. It enables SCPs for governance, creates an OU hierarchy for organizing accounts by division, and automatically shares RI and Savings Plans discounts across the organization. The management account gets a consolidated cost view.',trap:'AWS Trusted Advisor + Resource Groups Tag Editor provides cost and resource insights but does not consolidate accounts or billing. Enabling cross-account IAM access creates security complexity and does not provide a unified billing view. Creating separate VPCs per division does not consolidate billing — each VPC is still in a separate account.',rule:'Multi-account cost oversight + governance = AWS Organizations (Consolidated Billing). All accounts under management account. RI/Savings Plans shared across org. SCPs for governance. Consolidated Billing = cost aggregation, RI/Savings Plans sharing across accounts.',keywords:'Steady 24/7 workload 1-3 years → Reserved Instances. Commit for discount.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_15',category:'Kinesis',question:'A Solutions Architect designed a real-time data analytics system based on Kinesis Data Stream and Lambda. A week after the system has been deployed, the users noticed that it performed slowly as the data rate increases. The Architect identified that the performance of the Kinesis Data Streams is causing this problem. Which of the following should the Architect do to improve performance?',choices:['A|Increase the number of shards of the Kinesis stream by using the UpdateShardCount command.','B|Replace the data stream with Amazon Data Firehose instead.','C|Improve the performance of the stream by decreasing the number of its shards using the MergeShard command.','D|Implement Step Scaling to the Kinesis Data Stream.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams supports resharding, which lets you adjust the number of shards in your stream to adapt to changes in the rate of data flow through the stream. Resharding is considered an advanced operation.',why:'There are two types of resharding operations: shard split and shard merge. In a shard split, you divide a single shard into two shards. In a shard merge, you combine two shards into a single shard. Resharding is always pairwise in the sense that you cannot split into more than two shards in a single operation, and you cannot merge more than two shards in a single operation.',trap:'The option that says: Replacing the data stream with Amazon Data Firehose instead is incorrect because the throughput of Data Firehose is not exceptionally higher than Kinesis Data Streams. In fact, the throughput of an Amazon Kinesis data stream is designed to scale without limits via increasing the number of shards within a data stream.',rule:'Resharding is always pairwise in the sense that you cannot split into more than two shards in a single operation, and you cannot merge more than two shards. Merging: you can only merge two adjacent shards at a time.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_16',category:'Serverless',question:'A commercial bank has designed its next-generation online banking platform to use a distributed system architecture. The Solutions Architect was tasked to ensure that the architecture is highly scalable, cost-effective, and leverages Amazon EC2 for compute resources. Which of the following will provide the most suitable solution for this scenario?',choices:['A|Launch multiple EC2 instances and use Elastic Load Balancing to distribute traffic across the instances, which will host application services, while Amazon SNS will act as a highly-scalable buffer for messages as they travel between distributed applications.','B|Launch an Auto-Scaling group of EC2 instances to host your application services and an Amazon SQS queue. Include an Auto Scaling trigger to watch the SQS queue size which will either scale in or scale out the number of EC2 instances based on the queue.','C|Launch multiple EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer to host your application services, and an AWS Step Functions workflow which will act as a highly scalable buffer that stores messages as they travel between distributed applications.','D|Launch multiple On-Demand EC2 instances to host your application services and an Amazon SQS queue which will act as a highly-scalable buffer that stores messages as they travel between distributed applications.'],correct:'B',answer:'An Auto Scaling group allows you to maintain the health and availability of your application by scaling the number of EC2 instances up or down based on demand. This is particularly useful in a banking platform where traffic can be highly variable.',why:'Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS) is a fully managed message queuing service that enables you to decouple and scale microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications. In the context of a banking platform, SQS can act as a buffer for messages as they travel between distributed applications, ensuring that no message is lost and that the order of transactions is maintained.',trap:'The option that says: Launch multiple EC2 instances and use Elastic Load Balancing to distribute traffic across the instances, which will host application services, while Amazon SNS will act as a highly-scalable buffer for messages as they travel between distributed applications is incorrect because SNS is typically designed for pub/sub messaging and mobile notifications, which is not ideal for use cases where data consistency and transaction integrity are critical, such as in a banking platform. For reliable message queuing and to trigger scaling based on demand, SQS would be a more appropriate solution.',rule:'Cost-effective → EC2, Amazon SQS queue. Not Elastic Load Balancing.',keywords:'API Gateway throttling: per-method or per-stage limits. 429 error when throttled. Usage plans for client quotas.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_17',category:'S3',question:'A company is looking for a way to analyze the calls between customers and service agents. Each conversation is transcribed, JSON-formatted, and saved to an Amazon S3 bucket. The company’s solutions architect is tasked to design a solution for extracting and visualizing sentiments from the transcribed files. Which solution meets the requirements while minimizing the amount of operational overhead?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon Comprehend analysis job. Index the sentiment along with the transcript to an Amazon OpenSearch cluster. Visualize the results using the OpenSearch Dashboard.','B|Analyze the JSON files with Amazon Textract. Index the sentiment along with the transcript to an Amazon OpenSearch cluster. Visualize the results using Amazon Managed Grafana.','C|Create an Amazon Comprehend analysis job. Index the sentiment along with the transcript to an Amazon OpenSearch cluster. Visualize the results using Amazon Managed Grafana.','D|Train a custom Natural Language Processing (NLP) model using Amazon SageMaker. Index the sentiment along with the transcript to an Amazon OpenSearch cluster. Visualize the results using the OpenSearch Dashboard.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Comprehend uses machine learning to help you uncover the insights and relationships in your unstructured data.',why:'In this scenario, you can build the application with the help of Amazon Comprehend. You could expose the application through a RESTful endpoint, have it invoke a Lambda function that will call Amazon Comprehend for sentiment analysis, and index data into an Amazon OpenSearch cluster.',trap:'The option that says: Analyze the JSON files with Amazon Textract. Index the sentiment along with the transcript to an Amazon OpenSearch cluster. Visualize the results using Amazon Managed Grafana is incorrect. Amazon Textract is just an AI service used to extract text data from scanned documents in PNG, JPEG, TIFF, PDF formats and is not capable of running sentiment analysis. Furthermore, Grafana is more suited for the visualization of time-series data such as system metrics (CPU load, disk storage, memory utilization, temperature, etc). While there are hacks you can use to visualize non-time series like the one in the scenario, they come with additional overhead on your part. The built-in OpenSearch dashboard is enough to do the job.',rule:'Amazon Comprehend analysis job|Amazon OpenSearch cluster: correct. Amazon Textract: incorrect for this scenario.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_18',category:'Networking',question:'A company deployed a fleet of Windows-based EC2 instances with IPv4 addresses launched in a private subnet. Several software installed in the EC2 instances are required to be updated via the Internet. Which of the following services can provide the firm a highly available solution to safely allow the instances to fetch the software patches from the Internet but prevent outside network from initiating a connection?',choices:['A|Egress-Only Internet Gateway','B|VPC Endpoint','C|NAT Gateway','D|NAT Instance'],correct:'C',answer:'Windows EC2 instances in a private subnet with IPv4 addresses require a NAT Gateway in a public subnet to make outbound Internet connections. A NAT Gateway translates the private IP to a public IP for outbound traffic.',why:'A NAT Gateway is placed in a public subnet and assigned an Elastic IP. The private subnet route table routes 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway. The NAT Gateway translates outbound connections from private instances to its own EIP, receives the response, and forwards it back to the instance. This allows outbound-only Internet access from private subnets.',trap:'Egress-Only Internet Gateway is incorrect because this is primarily used for VPCs that use IPv6 to enable instances in a private subnet to connect to the Internet or other AWS services but prevent the Internet from initiating a connection with those instances, just like what NAT Instance and NAT Gateway do. The scenario explicitly says that the EC2 instances are using IPv4 addresses which is why Egress-only Internet gateway is invalid, even though it can provide the required high availability.',rule:'Private subnet IPv4 instances → Internet = NAT Gateway (in public subnet, with EIP). Egress-Only IGW = IPv6 only. VPC Endpoint = AWS services only, not Internet. IGW in private subnet = does not provide internet access (also needs route table entry pointing to IGW).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_19',category:'Other',question:'A Solutions Architect needs to set up the required compute resources for the application which have workloads that require high, sequential read and write access to very large data sets on local storage. Which of the following instance type is the most suitable one to use in this scenario?',choices:['A|Storage Optimized Instances','B|Memory Optimized Instances','C|Compute Optimized Instances','D|General Purpose Instances'],correct:'A',answer:'Storage optimized instances are designed for workloads that require high, sequential read and write access to very large data sets on local storage. They are optimized to deliver tens of thousands of low-latency, random I/O operations per second (IOPS) to applications.',why:'Storage-optimized instances use locally-attached NVMe SSDs (not EBS) that provide the highest sequential throughput available in EC2. The local NVMe removes network latency from the I/O path — data moves directly between CPU and SSD at memory-bus speeds. Examples: i4i, im4gn, is4gen. These are ephemeral — data is lost if the instance is stopped or terminated. Use them with data that can be rebuilt from S3 or for buffer/cache workloads.',trap:'Memory Optimized Instances is incorrect because these are designed to deliver fast performance for workloads that process large data sets in memory, which is quite different from handling high read and write capacity on local storage.',rule:'High sequential read/write IOPS on local storage (log processing, data warehousing) = Storage Optimized instances. Not Memory Optimized (large datasets in RAM). Not Compute Optimized (CPU-intensive). Not General Purpose (balanced). Storage Optimized = NVMe SSD, sequential reads.',keywords:'Amazon Transcribe: speech-to-text. Call Analytics: sentiment, PII detection, call categorization.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_20',category:'S3',question:'A company is planning to deploy a High Performance Computing (HPC) cluster in its VPC that requires a scalable, high-performance file system. The storage service must be optimized for efficient workload processing, and the data must be accessible via a fast and scalable file system interface. It should also work natively with Amazon S3 that enables you to easily process your S3 data with a high-performance POSIX interface. Which of the following is the MOST suitable service that you should use for this scenario?',choices:['A|Amazon Elastic File System (EFS)','B|Amazon FSx for Windows File Server','C|Amazon FSx for Lustre','D|Amazon Elastic Block Storage (EBS)'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon FSx for Lustre provides a high-performance file system optimized for fast processing of workloads such as machine learning, high performance computing (HPC), video processing, financial modeling, and electronic design automation (EDA).',why:'Operating high-performance file systems typically requires specialized expertise and administrative overhead, requiring you to provision storage servers and tune complex performance parameters. With Amazon FSx, you can launch and run a file system that provides sub-millisecond access to your data and allows you to read and write data at speeds of up to hundreds of gigabytes per second of throughput and millions of IOPS.',trap:'Amazon Elastic Block Storage (EBS) is incorrect because this service is not a scalable, high-performance file system.',rule:'Operating high-performance file systems typically requires specialized expertise and administrative overhead, requiring you to provision storage and compute resources separately and manage them independently.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_21',category:'Database',question:'A company has a fleet of running Spot EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer. The incoming traffic comes from various users across multiple AWS regions, and you would like to have the user\'s session shared among the fleet of instances. A Solutions Architect is required to set up a distributed session management layer that will provide scalable and shared data storage for the user sessions that supports multithreaded performance. The cache layer must also detect any node failures and replace the failed ones automatically. Which of the following would be the best choice to meet the requirement while still providing sub-millisecond latency for the users?',choices:['A|AWS ELB sticky sessions','B|Amazon ElastiCache for Redis Global Datastore','C|Amazon RDS database with RDS Proxy','D|Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached with Auto Discovery'],correct:'D',answer:'For sub-millisecond latency caching, ElastiCache is the best choice. In order to address scalability and to provide a shared data storage for sessions that can be accessed from any individual web server, you can abstract the HTTP sessions from the web servers themselves. A common solution for this is to leverage an In-Memory Key/Value store such as Redis and Memcached.',why:'For clusters running the Memcached engine, ElastiCache supports Auto Discovery—the ability for client programs to automatically identify all of the nodes in a cache cluster, and to initiate and maintain connections to all of these nodes.',trap:'The option that says: ELB sticky sessions is incorrect because the scenario does not require you to route a user to the particular web server that is managing that individual user’s session. Since the session state is shared among the instances, the use of the ELB sticky sessions feature is not recommended in this scenario.',rule:'Scalability → Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached with.',keywords:'sub-millisecond / in-memory caching → ElastiCache. Frequently read, rarely changes → cache it.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_22',category:'EC2',question:'A Solutions Architect is working for a weather station in Asia with a weather monitoring system that needs to be migrated to AWS. Since the monitoring system requires a low network latency and high network throughput, the Architect decided to launch the EC2 instances to a new cluster placement group. The system was working fine for a couple of weeks, however, when they try to add new instances to the placement group that already has running EC2 instances, they receive an \'insufficient capacity error\'. How will the Architect fix this issue?',choices:['A|Stop and restart the instances in the Placement Group and then try the launch again.','B|Create another Placement Group and launch the new instances in the new group.','C|Verify all running instances are of the same size and type and then try the launch again.','D|Submit a capacity increase request to AWS as you are initially limited to only 12 instances per Placement Group.'],correct:'A',answer:'A cluster placement group is a logical grouping of instances within a single Availability Zone. A cluster placement group can span peered VPCs in the same Region. Instances in the same cluster placement group enjoy a higher per-flow throughput limit for TCP/IP traffic and are placed in the same high-bisection bandwidth segment of the network.',why:'It is recommended that you launch the number of instances that you need in the placement group in a single launch request and that you use the same instance type for all instances in the placement group. If you try to add more instances to the placement group later, or if you try to launch more than one instance type in the placement group, you increase your chances of getting an insufficient capacity error.',trap:'The option that says: Create another Placement Group and launch the new instances in the new group is incorrect because to benefit from the enhanced networking, all the instances should be in the same Placement Group. Launching the new ones in a new Placement Group will not work in this case.',rule:'be migrated to aws → Placement Group. Not Placement Group.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_23',category:'Serverless',question:'A game company has a requirement of load balancing the incoming TCP traffic at the transport level (Layer 4) to their containerized gaming servers hosted in AWS Fargate. To maintain performance, it should handle millions of requests per second sent by gamers around the globe while maintaining ultra-low latencies. Which of the following must be implemented in the current architecture to satisfy the new requirement?',choices:['A|Launch a new Network Load Balancer.','B|Launch a new Application Load Balancer.','C|Create a new record in Amazon Route 53 with Weighted Routing policy to load balance the incoming traffic.','D|Launch a new microservice in AWS Fargate that acts as a load balancer since using an ALB or NLB with Fargate is not possible.'],correct:'B',answer:'Elastic Load Balancing automatically distributes incoming application traffic across multiple targets, such as Amazon EC2 instances, containers, IP addresses, and Lambda functions. It can handle the varying load of your application traffic in a single Availability Zone or across multiple Availability Zones.',why:'Network Load Balancer is best suited for load balancing of TCP traffic where extreme performance is required. Operating at the connection level (Layer 4), Network Load Balancer routes traffic to targets within Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (Amazon VPC) and is capable of handling millions of requests per second while maintaining ultra-low latencies. Network Load Balancer is also optimized to handle sudden and volatile traffic patterns.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a new Application Load Balancer is incorrect because it cannot handle TCP or Layer 4 connections, only Layer 7 (HTTP and HTTPS).',rule:'Network Load Balancer is best suited for load balancing of TCP traffic where extreme performance is required.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_24',category:'Storage',question:'An intelligence agency is currently hosting a learning and training portal in AWS. Your manager instructed you to launch a large EC2 instance with an attached EBS Volume and enable Enhanced Networking. What are the valid case scenarios in using Enhanced Networking? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|When you need a higher packet per second (PPS) performance','B|When you need a low packet-per-second performance','C|When you need high latency networking','D|When you need a consistently lower inter-instance latencies','E|When you need a dedicated connection to your on-premises data center'],correct:'AD',answer:'Enhanced networking benefits apply when: (A) you need higher packet per second (PPS) performance — ENA significantly increases PPS versus traditional networking, and (E) you need consistently lower inter-instance latencies for tightly coupled workloads.',why:'Enhanced Networking uses SR-IOV (Single Root I/O Virtualization) to provide high-performance networking. It achieves higher PPS (up to millions PPS), lower network jitter, and lower latency compared to the software-based networking of earlier instance types. It is enabled via the Elastic Network Adapter (ENA) or Intel 82599 VF interface. There is no additional charge.',trap:'Enhanced networking provides low latency inter-instance networking — not high latency. Low PPS performance is exactly what enhanced networking improves upon — you use it when you need higher PPS, not lower. A dedicated connection to on-premises is AWS Direct Connect, not a networking feature of EC2.',rule:'Enhanced Networking (ENA/SR-IOV) benefits: higher PPS, lower inter-instance latency, less jitter. Use for HPC, real-time, tightly-coupled workloads. No additional cost. Not for Direct Connect or WAN connectivity (use Direct Connect or VPN for that).',keywords:'Enhanced Networking: ENA (100Gbps) for higher PPS and lower latency. No extra charge. SR-IOV based.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_25',category:'Security',question:'There is a technical requirement by a financial firm that does online credit card processing to have a secure application environment on AWS. They are trying to decide on whether to use KMS or CloudHSM. Which of the following statements is right when it comes to CloudHSM and KMS?',choices:['A|No major difference. They both do the same thing.','B|If you want a managed service for creating and controlling your encryption keys but don\'t want or need to operate your own HSM, consider using AWS CloudHSM.','C|You should consider using AWS CloudHSM over AWS KMS if you require your keys stored in dedicated, third-party validated hardware security modules under your exclusive control.','D|AWS CloudHSM should always be used for any payment transactions.'],correct:'C',answer:'AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) is a managed service that makes it easy for you to create and control the encryption keys used to encrypt your data. The master keys that you create in AWS KMS are protected by FIPS 140-2 validated cryptographic modules. AWS KMS is integrated with most other AWS services that encrypt your data with encryption keys that you manage.',why:'By using AWS KMS, you gain more control over access to data you encrypt. You can use the key management and cryptographic features directly in your applications or through AWS services that are integrated with AWS KMS. Whether you are writing applications for AWS or using AWS services, AWS KMS enables you to maintain control over who can use your customer master keys and gain access to your encrypted data.',trap:'The option that says: No major difference. They both do the same thing is incorrect because KMS and CloudHSM are two different services. If you want a managed service for creating and controlling your encryption keys without operating your own HSM, you have to consider using AWS Key Management Service.',rule:'AWS CloudHSM over AWS KM: correct. AWS Key: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Need FIPS 140-2 Level 3 / dedicated key hardware / SSL offload → CloudHSM. KMS = Level 2.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_26',category:'Storage',question:'A company is using an Amazon RDS for MySQL 5.6 with Multi-AZ deployment enabled and several web servers across two AWS Regions. The database is currently experiencing highly dynamic reads due to the growth of the company’s website. The Solutions Architect tried to test the read performance from the secondary AWS Region and noticed a notable slowdown on the SQL queries. Which of the following options would provide a read replication latency of less than 1 second?',choices:['A|Migrate the existing database to Amazon Aurora and create a cross-region read replica.','B|Upgrade the MySQL database engine.','C|Use Amazon ElastiCache to improve database performance.','D|Create an Amazon RDS for MySQL read replica in the secondary AWS Region.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Aurora is a MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible relational database built for the cloud, that combines the performance and availability of traditional enterprise databases with the simplicity and cost-effectiveness of open source databases. Amazon Aurora is up to five times faster than standard MySQL databases and three times faster than standard PostgreSQL databases.',why:'It provides the security, availability, and reliability of commercial databases at 1/10th the cost. Amazon Aurora is fully managed by Amazon RDS, which automates time-consuming administration tasks like hardware provisioning, database setup, patching, and backups.',trap:'The option that says: Upgrade the MySQL database engine is incorrect because upgrading the database engine wouldn\'t improve the read replication latency to milliseconds. To achieve the read replication latency of less than 1-second requirement, you need to use Amazon Aurora replicas.',rule:'Amazon Aurora and create a cross: correct. Amazon Aurora: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_27',category:'Kinesis',question:'A manufacturing company launched a new type of IoT sensor. The sensor will be used to collect large streams of data records. You need to create a solution that can ingest and analyze the data in real-time with millisecond response times. Which of the following is the best option that you should implement in this scenario?',choices:['A|Ingest the data using Amazon Kinesis Data Streams and create an AWS Lambda function to store the data in Amazon Redshift.','B|Ingest the data using Amazon Data Firehose and create an AWS Lambda function to store the data in Amazon DynamoDB.','C|Ingest the data using Amazon Simple Queue Service and create an AWS Lambda function to store the data in Amazon Redshift.','D|Ingest the data using Amazon Kinesis Data Streams and create an AWS Lambda function to store the data in Amazon DynamoDB.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Kinesis Data Streams enables you to build custom applications that process or analyze streaming data for specialized needs. You can continuously add various types of data such as clickstreams, application logs, and social media to an Amazon Kinesis data stream from hundreds of thousands of sources.',why:'Based on the given scenario, the key points are "ingest and analyze the data in real-time" and "millisecond response times". For the first key point and based on the given options, you can use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams because it can collect and process large streams of data records in real time. For the second key point, you should use Amazon DynamoDB since it supports single-digit millisecond response times at any scale.',trap:'The option that says: Ingest the data using Amazon Kinesis Data Streams and create an AWS Lambda function to store the data in Amazon Redshift is incorrect because Amazon Redshift only delivers sub-second response times. Take note that as per the scenario, the solution must have millisecond response times to meet the requirements. Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX), which is a fully managed, highly available, in-memory cache for Amazon DynamoDB, can deliver microsecond response times.',rule:'Based on the given scenario, the key points are "ingest and analyze the data in real-time" and "millisecond response times". Not Amazon Redshift.',keywords:'Row-level DB change trigger → DynamoDB Streams → Lambda. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_28',category:'Storage',question:'A Solutions Architect is implementing a new High-Performance Computing (HPC) system in AWS that involves orchestrating several Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) tasks with an Amazon EC2 launch type that is part of an ECS cluster. The ECS cluster is configured with an ECS Capacity Provider to dynamically manage and scale the EC2 instances based on ECS task demand, ensuring sufficient compute resources are always available for high-throughput workloads. Users around the globe will frequently access the system, and it is expected that hundreds of ECS tasks will run most of the time. These tasks require high-frequency read and write operations to a shared storage system. The output data of each ECS task is around 10 MB, and although obsolete data is eventually archived and deleted, the total storage size will not exceed 10 TB. Which of the following is the MOST suitable solution that the Architect should recommend?',choices:['A|Launch an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) with Provisioned Throughput mode and set the performance mode to Max I/O. Configure the EFS file system as the container mount point in the ECS task definition of the ECS cluster.','B|Set up an SMB file share by creating an Amazon FSx for Windows File Server. Set the file share as the container mount point in the ECS task definition of the ECS cluster.','C|Launch an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system with Bursting Throughput mode and set the performance mode to General Purpose. Configure the EFS file system as the container mount point in the ECS task definition of the ECS cluster.','D|Launch an Amazon DynamoDB table with DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) and DynamoDB Streams enabled. Configure the table to be accessible by all ECS cluster instances. Set the DynamoDB table as the container mount point in the ECS task definition of the ECS cluster.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) provides simple, scalable file storage for use with your Amazon ECS tasks. With Amazon EFS, storage capacity is elastic, growing and shrinking automatically as you add and remove files. Your applications can have the storage they need when they need it.',why:'You can use Amazon EFS file systems with Amazon ECS to access file system data across your fleet of Amazon ECS tasks. That way, your tasks have access to the same persistent storage, no matter the infrastructure or container instance on which they land. When you reference your Amazon EFS file system and container mount point in your Amazon ECS task definition, Amazon ECS takes care of mounting the file system in your container.',trap:'The option that says: Set up an SMB file share by creating an Amazon FSx for Windows File Server. Set the file share as the container mount point in the ECS task definition of the ECS cluster is incorrect because is primarily designed for traditional Windows workloads and doesn’t provide the level of performance needed for high-frequency read and write operations in ECS tasks. It also doesn’t offer the low-latency access that is typically required in this scenario for a large number of ECS tasks.',rule:'Scalability → Amazon Elastic File System, Amazon EFS. Not Amazon FSx.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_29',category:'Networking',question:'A company plans to host a movie streaming app in AWS. The chief information officer (CIO) wants to ensure that the application is highly available and scalable. The application is deployed to an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances on multiple AZs. A load balancer must be configured to distribute incoming requests evenly to all EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones. Which of the following features should the Solutions Architect use to satisfy these criteria?',choices:['A|Amazon VPC IP Address Manager (IPAM)','B|Path-based Routing','C|Cross-zone load balancing','D|AWS Direct Connect SiteLink'],correct:'C',answer:'Cross-zone load balancing must be enabled on an ALB or NLB to distribute traffic evenly across instances in multiple AZs. The NLB path-based routing to content routes requests by URL path to specific target groups per region.',why:'Cross-zone load balancing allows the load balancer to distribute traffic across registered targets in all enabled AZs, not just the AZ the request arrives in. Without it, an AZ with fewer instances would receive less traffic per instance. For a movie streaming app, this ensures even distribution globally.',trap:'Amazon VPC IP Address Manager manages IP address space — it has no load balancing capability. Path-based routing directs requests to different target groups based on URL path — useful for microservices but not for cross-zone distribution.',rule:'Cross-zone load balancing = distribute traffic evenly across all targets in all AZs. Without it, each AZ load balancer node only routes within that AZ. Enable on ALB or NLB for even global distribution. IPAM = IP management service for planning and monitoring IP addresses across your AWS organization.',keywords:'EFS with ECS: shared file storage across all tasks in any AZ. Mount via EFS Access Points.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_30',category:'Serverless',question:'An application is using a Lambda function to process complex financial data that run for 15 minutes on average. Most invocations were successfully processed. However, you noticed that there are a few terminated invocations throughout the day, which caused data discrepancy in the application. Which of the following is the most likely cause of this issue?',choices:['A|The failed Lambda functions have been running for over 15 minutes and reached the maximum execution time.','B|The concurrent execution limit has been reached.','C|The Lambda function contains a recursive code and has been running for over 15 minutes.','D|The failed Lambda Invocations contain a ServiceException error which means that the AWS Lambda service encountered an internal error.'],correct:'A',answer:'A Lambda function consists of code and any associated dependencies. In addition, a Lambda function also has configuration information associated with it. Initially, you specify the configuration information when you create a Lambda function. Lambda provides an API for you to update some of the configuration data.',why:'You pay for the AWS resources that are used to run your Lambda function. To prevent your Lambda function from running indefinitely, you specify a timeout. When the specified timeout is reached, AWS Lambda terminates execution of your Lambda function. It is recommended that you set this value based on your expected execution time.',trap:'The option that says: The concurrent execution limit has been reached is incorrect because, by default, the AWS Lambda limits the total concurrent executions across all functions within a given region to 1000. By setting a concurrency limit on a function, Lambda guarantees that allocation will be applied specifically to that function, regardless of the amount of traffic processing the remaining functions. If that limit is exceeded, the function will be throttled but not terminated, which is in contrast with what is happening in the scenario.',rule:'Lambda provides an API for you to update some of the configuration data.',keywords:'Lambda max timeout = 15 minutes. Long-running → use ECS Fargate or Step Functions.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_31',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is trying to enable Cross-Region Replication to an S3 bucket but this option is disabled. Which of the following options is a valid reason for this? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|The Cross-Region Replication feature is only available for Amazon S3 - One Zone-IA','B|This is a premium feature which is only for AWS Enterprise accounts.','C|In order to use the Cross-Region Replication feature in S3, you need to first enable versioning on the bucket.','D|The Cross-Region Replication feature is only available for Amazon S3 - Infrequent Access.'],correct:'ACD',answer:'S3 Cross-Region Replication (CRR) requires two prerequisites: both the source and destination buckets must have versioning enabled, and the source bucket must have a replication rule configured. If either bucket has versioning suspended or disabled, replication will fail to enable.',why:'CRR asynchronously copies objects from the source bucket to one or more destination buckets in different regions after they are written. Versioning is mandatory because CRR tracks object versions to determine what needs replicating. The replication rule specifies the destination bucket ARN, storage class for replicated objects, and optional filters (prefix or tag). CRR does not replicate existing objects retroactively — only objects created or updated after the rule is enabled are replicated.',trap:'The option that says: This is a premium feature which is only for AWS Enterprise accounts is incorrect as this CRR feature is available to all Support Plans.',rule:'Amazon + S3 = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_32',category:'IAM',question:'A multinational manufacturing company has multiple accounts in AWS to separate their various departments such as finance, human resources, engineering and many others. There is a requirement to ensure that certain access to services and actions are properly controlled to comply with the security policy of the company. As the Solutions Architect, which is the most suitable way to set up the multi-account AWS environment of the company? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up a common IAM policy that can be applied across all AWS accounts.','B|Connect all departments by setting up a cross-account access to each of the AWS accounts of the company. Create and attach IAM policies to your resources based on their respective departments to control access.','C|Provide access to externally authenticated users via Identity Federation. Set up an IAM role to specify permissions for users from each department whose identity is federated from your organization or a third-party identity provider.','D|Use AWS Organizations and Service Control Policies to control services on each account.'],correct:'AD',answer:'AWS Organizations offers policy-based management for multiple AWS accounts. With Organizations, you can create groups of accounts, automate account creation, apply and manage policies for those groups. Organizations enable you to centrally manage policies across multiple accounts without requiring custom scripts and manual processes.',why:'Using AWS Organizations and Service Control Policies to control services on each account is the correct answer. Refer to the diagram below: AWS Organizations offers policy-based management for multiple AWS accounts. With Organizations, you can create groups of accounts, automate account creation, apply and manage policies for those groups.',trap:'The option that says: Setting up a common IAM policy that can be applied across all AWS accounts is incorrect because it is not possible to create a common IAM policy for multiple AWS accounts.',rule:'IAM + AWS = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'AWS Organizations: SCPs limit max permissions for all accounts. Consolidated billing. Account isolation.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_33',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A new DevOps engineer has created a CloudFormation template for a web application and she raised a pull request in GIT for you to check and review. After checking the template, you immediately told her that the template will not work. Which of the following is the reason why this CloudFormation template will fail to deploy the stack? (Note: The template has AWSTemplateFormatVersion, Parameters, and Outputs sections but is missing the Resources section.)',choices:['A|The value of the AWSTemplateFormatVersion is incorrect. It should be 2017-06-06.','B|The Resources section is missing.','C|An invalid section named Parameters is present. This will cause the CloudFormation stack to fail.','D|The Conditions section is missing.'],correct:'B',answer:'The Resources section is the only required section in a CloudFormation template. All other sections (Parameters, Outputs, Conditions, Mappings, etc.) are optional. A template without Resources will fail to deploy.',why:'CloudFormation templates describe AWS infrastructure as JSON or YAML. The only mandatory section is Resources — it defines the AWS resources to be created (EC2 instances, S3 buckets, etc.). All other sections are optional helpers: Parameters accept runtime input, Outputs expose values after deployment, Conditions enable conditional resource creation. Without Resources, there is nothing for CloudFormation to actually create.',trap:'The AWSTemplateFormatVersion value of 2010-09-09 is the correct and only accepted value — 2017-06-06 is not a valid version. Parameters is a valid optional section, not an invalid one. Conditions is also optional — its absence does not cause deployment failure.',rule:'CloudFormation only required section = Resources. All others (Parameters, Outputs, Conditions, Mappings, Metadata) are optional. AWSTemplateFormatVersion = 2010-09-09 is the only valid value.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_34',category:'CloudFormation',question:'A company developed a financial analytics web application hosted in a Docker container using MEAN (MongoDB, Express.js, AngularJS, and Node.js) stack. You want to easily port that web application to AWS Cloud which can automatically handle all the tasks such as balancing load, auto-scaling, monitoring, and placing your containers across your cluster. Which of the following services can be used to fulfill this requirement?',choices:['A|AWS CloudFormation','B|AWS Compute Optimizer','C|Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS)','D|AWS Elastic Beanstalk'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Elastic Beanstalk deploys and manages containerized or non-containerized web applications with managed infrastructure (EC2, Auto Scaling, ALB). For a MEAN stack Docker application, Elastic Beanstalk\'s Docker platform provides managed deployment with minimal operational overhead.',why:'Elastic Beanstalk supports Docker single-container and multi-container deployments. You provide a Dockerrun.aws.json or docker-compose.yml and Beanstalk handles provisioning EC2 instances, ELB, Auto Scaling, health monitoring, and deployment. It abstracts infrastructure management while allowing configuration access.',trap:'AWS CloudFormation is infrastructure-as-code for defining and provisioning AWS resources — it does not deploy or manage application code by itself. AWS Compute Optimizer analyzes existing infrastructure for right-sizing — not a deployment service.',rule:'Managed Docker web app deployment with least overhead = AWS Elastic Beanstalk. Supports Docker. Handles EC2, ALB, ASG automatically. CloudFormation = IaC, not app deployment. ECS = AWS-proprietary container orchestration. CloudFormation = IaC, not app deployment.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_35',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company plans to implement a network monitoring system in AWS. The Solutions Architect launched an EC2 instance to host the monitoring system and used CloudWatch to monitor, store, and access the log files of the instance. Which of the following provides an automated way to send log data to CloudWatch Logs from the Amazon EC2 instance?',choices:['A|CloudWatch Logs agent','B|CloudTrail with log file validation','C|AWS Transfer for SFTP','D|CloudTrail Processing Library'],correct:'A',answer:'CloudWatch Logs enables you to centralize the logs from all of your systems, applications, and AWS services that you use, in a single, highly scalable service. You can then easily view them, search them for specific error codes or patterns, filter them based on specific fields, or archive them securely for future analysis.',why:'The CloudWatch Logs agent has three components: the agent (runs on EC2 as a daemon), a configuration file (defines which log files to monitor and which log group to send them to), and the CLI plug-in. The agent monitors log files in real time and sends new entries to CloudWatch Logs continuously. Logs can then be searched with Logs Insights, trigger CloudWatch Alarms via metric filters, or be exported to S3 for archiving.',trap:'CloudTrail Processing Library is incorrect because this is just a Java library that provides an easy way to process AWS CloudTrail logs. It cannot send your log data to CloudWatch Logs.',rule:'Centralize logs from all systems and applications = CloudWatch Logs. Not CloudTrail (AWS API calls only). CloudWatch Logs supports custom log groups, metric filters, and insights queries. CloudWatch Logs agent = older single-purpose log agent (replaced by unified agent).',keywords:'Memory/disk/swap metrics = NOT default CW. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_36',category:'S3',question:'A global medical research company has a molecular imaging system that provides each client with frequently updated images of what is happening inside the human body at the molecular and cellular levels. The system is hosted in AWS and the images are hosted in an S3 bucket behind a CloudFront web distribution. When a fresh batch of images is uploaded to S3, it is required to keep the previous ones in order to prevent them from being overwritten. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to solve this issue?',choices:['A|Use versioned objects','B|Invalidate the files in your CloudFront web distribution','C|Add a separate cache behavior path for the content and configure a custom object caching with a Minimum TTL of 0','D|Add Cache-Control no-cache, no-store, or private directives in the S3 bucket'],correct:'A',answer:'Versioning is less expensive. You still have to pay for CloudFront to transfer new versions of your files to edge locations, but you don\'t have to pay for invalidating files.',why:'Versioning files in CloudFront works by appending a version string to the filename (e.g., main-v2.js instead of main.js). CloudFront caches content by URL path — a new filename is always a cache miss, so users get the new version immediately. Invalidation, by contrast, removes objects from edge caches but takes time to propagate and costs money per path. Using versioned filenames is free, instant, and lets you serve different versions to different users simultaneously.',trap:'Invalidating the files in your CloudFront web distribution is incorrect because even though using invalidation will solve this issue, this solution is more expensive as compared to using versioned objects.',rule:'Use versioned objects',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_37',category:'CloudWatch',question:'An online shopping platform has been deployed to AWS using Elastic Beanstalk. They simply uploaded their Node.js application, and Elastic Beanstalk automatically handles the details of capacity provisioning, load balancing, scaling, and application health monitoring. Since the entire deployment process is automated, the DevOps team is not sure where to get the application log files of their shopping platform. In Elastic Beanstalk, where does it store the application files and server log files?',choices:['A|Application files are stored in S3. The server log files can only be stored in the attached EBS volumes of the EC2 instances, which were launched by AWS Elastic Beanstalk.','B|Application files are stored in S3. The server log files can be stored directly in Glacier or in CloudWatch Logs.','C|Application files are stored in S3. The server log files can be optionally stored in CloudTrail or in CloudWatch Logs.','D|Application files are stored in S3. The server log files can also optionally be stored in S3 or in CloudWatch Logs.'],correct:'B',answer:'Elastic Beanstalk stores application files in S3. Server log files can optionally be stored in S3 — you can enable log rotation to S3 from the environment configuration, and logs can also stream to CloudWatch Logs.',why:'Elastic Beanstalk uses an S3 bucket to store application source bundles, AMI metadata, and other configuration artifacts. Instance logs are stored on the EC2 instances by default but can be rotated to S3 or streamed to CloudWatch Logs. Both are optional — the only required storage is S3 for application files.',trap:'Server log files are stored on the instance by default, not only in CloudWatch Logs. They can be stored in S3 optionally through log rotation. Saying they can ONLY be stored in certain places is incorrect — Elastic Beanstalk supports both S3 rotation and CloudWatch Logs streaming.',rule:'Elastic Beanstalk storage: app files = S3 (required). Server logs = EC2 instance (default), optionally rotate to S3 via environment configuration, optionally stream to CloudWatch Logs. Both S3 and CloudWatch are valid optional destinations for server logs.',keywords:'Elastic Beanstalk stores app files + optional server logs in S3. Configure via environment settings.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_38',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a VPC for its Human Resource department and another VPC located in different AWS regions for its Finance department. The Solutions Architect must redesign the architecture to allow the finance department to access all resources that are in the human resource department, and vice versa. An Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) must also be integrated for active traffic flow inspection and to block any vulnerability exploits. Which network architecture design in AWS should the Solutions Architect set up to satisfy the above requirement?',choices:['A|Create a Traffic Policy in Amazon Route 53 to connect the two VPCs. Configure the Route 53 Resolver DNS Firewall to do active traffic flow inspection and block any vulnerability exploits.','B|Establish a secure connection between the two VPCs using a NAT Gateway. Manage user sessions via the AWS Systems Manager Session Manager service.','C|Create a Direct Connect Gateway and add VPC attachments to connect all departments. Configure AWS Security Hub to secure the application traffic travelling between the VPCs.','D|Launch an AWS Transit Gateway and add VPC attachments to connect all departments. Set up AWS Network Firewall to secure the application traffic travelling between the VPCs.'],correct:'D',answer:'A transit gateway is a network transit hub that you can use to interconnect your virtual private clouds (VPCs) and on-premises networks. As your cloud infrastructure expands globally, inter-Region peering connects transit gateways together using the AWS Global Infrastructure. Your data is automatically encrypted and never travels over the public internet.',why:'Transit Gateway acts as a regional hub. Each VPC attaches to the TGW via a Transit Gateway Attachment. Route tables on the TGW control which attachments can communicate. A single TGW can connect hundreds of VPCs and on-premises networks (via VPN or Direct Connect). Unlike VPC Peering (non-transitive), TGW supports transitive routing: traffic from VPC-A can reach VPC-C by passing through TGW, without a direct peer between A and C.',trap:'The option that says: Create a Traffic Policy in Amazon Route 53 to connect the two VPCs. Configure the Route 53 Resolver DNS Firewall to do active traffic flow inspection and block any vulnerability exploits is incorrect because the Traffic Policy feature is commonly used in tandem with the geoproximity routing policy for creating and maintaining records in large and complex configurations. Moreover, the Route 53 Resolver DNS Firewall can only filter and regulate outbound DNS traffic for your virtual private cloud (VPC). It can neither do active traffic flow inspection nor block any vulnerability exploits.',rule:'Your data is automatically encrypted and never travels over the public internet.',keywords:'Connect many VPCs + on-premises = Transit Gateway. Hub-and-spoke. Supports transitive routing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_39',category:'Database',question:'A top university has recently launched its online learning portal where the students can take e-learning courses from the comforts of their homes. The portal is on a large On-Demand EC2 instance with a single Amazon Aurora database. How can you improve the availability of your Aurora database to prevent any unnecessary downtime of the online portal?',choices:['A|Create Amazon Aurora Replicas.','B|Deploy Aurora to two Auto-Scaling groups of EC2 instances across two Availability Zones with an elastic load balancer which handles load balancing.','C|Enable Hash Joins to improve the database query performance.','D|Use an Asynchronous Key Prefetch in Amazon Aurora to improve the performance of queries that join tables across indexes.'],correct:'A',answer:'Aurora Replicas improve read performance by offloading read traffic from the primary instance. Asynchronous key prefetch in Aurora can also improve performance for queries that access data in a predictable pattern.',why:'Aurora Replicas share the same underlying storage as the primary and serve read-only queries. Creating Aurora Replicas distributes read workload and reduces latency for read-heavy workloads like e-learning applications. Aurora Replicas can serve read traffic from the Reader Endpoint with automatic load balancing.',trap:'Deploying Aurora to two Auto-Scaling groups of EC2 instances across two Availability Zones with an elastic load balancer which handles load balancing is incorrect because Aurora is a managed database engine for RDS and not deployed on typical EC2 instances that you manually provision.',rule:'Scale Aurora reads = Aurora Replicas (shared storage, Reader endpoint load balances). Replicas add read capacity without adding storage overhead. Not EC2 Auto Scaling — Aurora is managed — no EC2 scaling needed. Replicas use shared storage volume, near-zero replica lag.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_40',category:'Serverless',question:'An airline company receives a lot of requests to book flights, update booking details, and flight check-ins. Since these requests flood the customer support teams, the management wants to build a self-service solution that can handle these requests without a human agent. This solution should be text-based, allowing users to type concerns in a chat box while AI analyzes intentions, provides answers, or fulfills predefined actions automatically. Which of the following options is the recommended solution for the above requirements?',choices:['A|Create a conversational chatbot using Amazon Comprehend for natural-language processing (NLP). Depending on the user’s intent, invoke AWS Lambda functions that can perform the needed actions.','B|Work with an AWS Managed Service Provider (MSP) to deploy a conversational chatbot using Amazon Polly for natural-language processing (NLP) and Speech Synthesis Markup Language (SSML) to enhance spoken responses. Integrate AWS Lambda functions as code hooks to perform actions based on user requests.','C|Deploy a conversational chatbot using Amazon Lex. Define conversation flow for specific user intentions. Integrate AWS Lambda functions as code hooks to perform actions based on user requests.','D|Deploy a conversational chatbot using Amazon Rekognition. Define conversation flow for specific user intentions. Create AWS Lambda functions that can be invoked depending on user intentions.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Lex is a fully managed AI service for building conversational interfaces (chatbots). It provides automatic speech recognition (ASR) for voice and natural language understanding (NLU) for text — perfect for an airline booking chatbot.',why:'Amazon Lex uses deep learning to understand natural language, define conversation flows (intents), and extract values from user utterances (slots). It integrates with Lambda for fulfillment logic and connects to the same technology underlying Alexa. You define intents (book flight, change seat) and slots (departure city, date) to capture booking details.',trap:'Amazon Comprehend analyzes text for sentiment, entities, and key phrases — it does not create interactive conversations. Using an AWS MSP to deploy a chatbot adds unnecessary cost and lead time for what is a managed service. Amazon Rekognition analyzes images and video — it has nothing to do with conversational interfaces.',rule:'Conversational chatbot (booking, natural language) = Amazon Lex. Defines intents + slots. Integrates with Lambda for fulfillment logic. Comprehend = text analysis/sentiment (no conversation). Rekognition = image/video analysis. Lex is the purpose-built conversational AI service.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_41',category:'Storage',question:'A tech company is running two production web servers hosted on Reserved EC2 instances with EBS-backed root volumes. These instances have a consistent CPU load of 90%. Traffic is being distributed to these instances by an Elastic Load Balancer. In addition, they also have Multi-AZ RDS MySQL databases for their production, test, and development environments. What recommendation would you make to reduce cost in this AWS environment without affecting availability and performance of mission-critical systems? Choose the best answer.',choices:['A|Consider using On-demand instances instead of Reserved EC2 instances','B|Consider not using a Multi-AZ RDS deployment for the development and test database','C|Consider using Spot instances instead of reserved EC2 instances','D|Consider removing the Elastic Load Balancer'],correct:'B',answer:'The scenario describes a development/test environment — using Spot Instances for non-production servers reduces cost by 70-90% with acceptable interruption risk.',why:'The company is using Reserved Instances for production (steady-state, appropriate) and has a Multi-AZ RDS for the development database (unnecessary cost). For development EC2 instances that do not need guaranteed availability, Spot Instances provide the largest discount. The key insight is that the development environment is not production — interruptions are tolerable.',trap:'On-Demand Instances are more expensive than Spot for non-production workloads. Removing the Elastic Load Balancer eliminates fault tolerance that may still be needed even in development. Not using Multi-AZ RDS for development/test is also a valid cost saving but is the secondary recommendation — the question is about the EC2 cost.',rule:'Dev/test EC2 instances = Spot Instances (70-90% discount, interruptions acceptable). Production = Reserved or On-Demand. Multi-AZ for dev DB = unnecessary cost (another saving). ELB = no direct application-level caching. Use ElastiCache in front of DB for caching.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_42',category:'Database',question:'A company is running an on-premises application backed by a 1TB MySQL 8.0 database. A couple of times each month, the production data is fully copied to a staging database at the request of the analytics team. The team can\'t work on the staging database until the copy is finished, which takes hours. Throughout this period, the application experiences intermittent downtimes as well. To expedite the process for the analytics team, a solutions architect must redesign the application\'s architecture in AWS. The application must also be highly resilient to disruptions. Which combination of actions best satisfies the given set of requirements while being the most cost-effective? (Select TWO)',choices:['A|Use an Amazon Aurora database with Multi-AZ Replicas.','B|Use an Amazon RDS database in a Multi-AZ Deployments configuration','C|Take a manual snapshot and restore it to a database in the staging environment.','D|Replicate the production database to a staging database using the mysqldump client utility','E|Clone the production database in the staging environment using Aurora cloning.'],correct:'AE',answer:'For an Aurora MySQL migration that supports fast database cloning for staging: (A) Amazon Aurora database with Multi-AZ Replicas for production HA, and (E) Aurora cloning to quickly create a staging database from the production snapshot without data copying.',why:'Aurora cloning creates a new cluster that shares storage pages with the source cluster using a copy-on-write mechanism. This is much faster than mysqldump (no data copying) and is storage-efficient (only changed pages are stored separately). The clone starts from a consistent point-in-time copy instantly.',trap:'RDS in Multi-AZ provides failover but does not support Aurora cloning — cloning is an Aurora-exclusive feature. Taking a manual snapshot and restoring takes time proportional to database size. mysqldump is slow, requires the target DB to be idle, and does not maintain point-in-time consistency under load.',rule:'Aurora Migration: mysqldump = slow for 1TB, data transfer cost. AWS DMS + S3 = fast bulk load + ongoing replication using change data capture. Aurora cloning feature lets you create fast dev/test copies. Aurora Multi-AZ = HA for production.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_43',category:'S3',question:'A startup is building IoT devices and monitoring applications. They are using IoT sensors to monitor the traffic in real-time by using an Amazon Kinesis Stream that is configured with default settings. It then sends the data to an Amazon S3 bucket every 3 days. When you checked the data in S3 on the 3rd day, only the data for the last day is present and no data is present from 2 days ago. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this issue?',choices:['A|Amazon S3 bucket has encountered a data loss.','B|Someone has manually deleted the record in Amazon S3.','C|By default, data records in Kinesis are only accessible for 24 hours from the time they are added to a stream.','D|The access of the Kinesis stream to the S3 bucket is insufficient.'],correct:'C',answer:'By default, records of a stream in Amazon Kinesis are accessible for up to 24 hours from the time they are added to the stream. You can raise this limit to up to 7 days by enabling extended data retention.',why:'Kinesis Data Streams uses a shard-based architecture. Each shard stores records for the configured retention window. After 24 hours (default) records are purged from shard storage — they cannot be recovered from KDS itself. Extended retention (7-365 days) lets you replay historical records but at additional cost per shard-hour. Records are not stored in S3 by default.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon S3 bucket has encountered a data loss is incorrect because Amazon S3 rarely experiences data loss. Amazon has an SLA for S3 that it commits to its customers. Amazon S3 Standard, S3 Standard–IA, S3 One Zone-IA, and S3 Glacier are all designed to provide 99.999999999% durability of objects over a given year. This durability level corresponds to an average annual expected loss of 0.000000001% of objects. Hence, Amazon S3 bucket data loss is highly unlikely.',rule:'Kinesis stream default retention = 24 hours. Extended retention = up to 7 days (or 365 days with long-term retention). Records older than retention period are lost — not an S3 data store. Kinesis Data Streams retains data from 24 hours up to 365 days (extended retention).',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_44',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has an application that uses multiple EC2 instances located in various AWS regions such as US East (Ohio), US West (N. California), and EU (Ireland). The manager instructed the Solutions Architect to set up a latency-based routing to route incoming traffic for www.tutorialsdojo.com to all the EC2 instances across all AWS regions. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Use a Network Load Balancer to distribute the load to the multiple EC2 instances across all AWS Regions.','B|Use Route 53 to distribute the load to the multiple EC2 instances across all AWS Regions.','C|Use an Application Load Balancer to distribute the load to the multiple EC2 instances across all AWS Regions.','D|Use AWS DataSync to distribute the load to the multiple EC2 instances across all AWS Regions.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Route 53 can load balance across EC2 instances in multiple AWS regions by using Latency routing (directs users to the lowest-latency region) or Weighted routing (distributes proportionally).',why:'Route 53 is the only AWS service that routes DNS queries to resources across multiple AWS regions. ALBs and NLBs operate within a single region. Route 53 Latency routing uses actual measured latency from users to each region to determine the optimal endpoint. Health checks remove unhealthy endpoints from rotation.',trap:'An NLB distributes traffic within a single region to targets in multiple AZs — it cannot route across regions. An ALB similarly operates within a single region. AWS DataSync is a data transfer service with no load balancing capability.',rule:'Load balance across multiple AWS regions = Route 53 (Latency or Weighted routing with health checks). ALB/NLB = single region only. DataSync = data transfer, not load balancing.',keywords:'One-time migration on-premises to AWS = DataSync. Storage Gateway = ongoing hybrid access.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_45',category:'Networking',question:'A company launched a cryptocurrency mining server on a Reserved EC2 instance in the us-east-1 region\'s private subnet that uses IPv6. Due to the financial data that the server contains, the system should be secured to prevent any unauthorized access and to meet regulatory compliance requirements. In this scenario, which VPC feature will allow the EC2 instance to communicate to the Internet but prevents inbound IPv6 traffic?',choices:['A|NAT Gateway','B|NAT instances','C|Egress-only Internet gateway','D|Internet Gateway'],correct:'C',answer:'An egress-only Internet gateway is a horizontally scaled, redundant, and highly available VPC component that allows outbound communication over IPv6 from instances in your VPC to the Internet, and prevents the Internet from initiating an IPv6 connection with your instances.',why:'IPv4 instances in a private subnet use a NAT Gateway (which uses an EIP) for outbound internet access. IPv6 addresses are globally routable by design — AWS does not provide NAT for IPv6. Instead, an Egress-Only Internet Gateway blocks all inbound IPv6 connections from the internet while allowing outbound connections. It functions like a stateful NAT but works at the protocol level — IPv6 addresses are not translated, just the routing is one-directional.',trap:'Internet Gateway is incorrect because this is primarily used to provide Internet access to your instances in the public subnet of your VPC and not for private subnets. However, with an Internet gateway, traffic originating from the public Internet will also be able to reach your instances. The scenario is asking you to prevent inbound access, so this is not the correct answer.',rule:'Take note that an egress-only Internet gateway is for use with IPv6 traffic only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_46',category:'Database',question:'A cryptocurrency company wants to go global with its international money transfer app. Your project is to make sure that the database of the app is highly available in multiple regions. What are the benefits of adding Multi-AZ deployments in Amazon RDS? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Provides enhanced database durability in the event of a DB instance component failure or an Availability Zone outage.','B|Significantly increases the database performance.','C|Creates a primary DB Instance and synchronously replicates the data to a standby instance in a different Availability Zone (AZ) in a different region.','D|Increased database availability in the case of system upgrades like OS patching or DB Instance scaling.','E|Provides SQL optimization.'],correct:'AD',answer:'RDS Multi-AZ benefits: (A) enhanced database durability in the event of DB instance component failure or AZ outage, and (D) increased database availability during system upgrades (the standby is upgraded first, then a failover occurs, minimizing downtime).',why:'RDS Multi-AZ maintains a synchronous standby replica in a different AZ. Primary benefits: (1) automatic failover on primary failure — CNAME flips to standby in 1-2 minutes, and (2) reduced downtime during maintenance (the standby is patched/upgraded first, then a failover promotes it to primary). Synchronous replication means zero data loss (RPO = 0).',trap:'Multi-AZ does NOT significantly increase performance — the standby cannot serve read traffic. Multi-AZ uses synchronous replication within a single region, not across regions — Option C says "in a different region" which is incorrect. SQL optimization has nothing to do with Multi-AZ.',rule:'RDS Multi-AZ benefits: enhanced durability (auto failover on AZ failure) + availability during upgrades (standby upgraded first). Does NOT improve performance (standby is read-inactive until failover). Read Replicas = improve read performance (separate endpoint needed).',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_47',category:'Serverless',question:'A Solutions Architect is managing a three-tier web application that processes credit card payments and online transactions. Static web pages are used on the front-end tier while the application tier contains a single Amazon EC2 instance that handles long-running processes. The data is stored in a MySQL database. The Solutions Architect is instructed to decouple the tiers to create a highly available application. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Move all the static assets and web pages to Amazon CloudFront. Use Auto Scaling in Amazon EC2 instance. Migrate the database to Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployments configuration.','B|Move all the static assets, web pages, and the backend application to a larger instance. Use Auto Scaling in Amazon EC2 instance. Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora.','C|Move all the static assets to Amazon S3. Set concurrency limit in AWS Lambda to move the application to a serverless architecture. Migrate the database to Amazon DynamoDB.','D|Move all the static assets and web pages to Amazon S3. Re-host the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) containers and enable Service Auto Scaling. Migrate the database to Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployments configuration.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) is a highly scalable, high performance container management service that supports Docker containers and allows you to easily run applications on a managed cluster of Amazon EC2 instances.',why:'The requirement in the scenario is to decouple the services to achieve a highly available architecture. To accomplish this requirement, you must move the existing setup to each AWS services. For static assets, you should use Amazon S3. You can use Amazon ECS for your web application and then migrate the database to Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployment.',trap:'The option that says: Move all the static assets to Amazon S3. Set concurrency limit in AWS Lambda to move the application to a serverless architecture. Migrate the database to Amazon DynamoDB is incorrect because Lambda functions can’t process long-running processes. Take note that a Lambda function has a maximum processing time of 15 minutes.',rule:'Amazon ECS makes it easy to use containers as a building block for your applications by eliminating the need for you to install, operate, and scale your own web server software. Elastic Beanstalk = managed app deployment platform.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_48',category:'Storage',question:'A disaster recovery team is planning to back up on-premises records to a local file server share through SMB protocol. To meet the company’s business continuity plan, the team must ensure that a copy of data from 48 hours ago is available for immediate access. Accessing older records with delay is tolerable. Which should the DR team implement to meet the objective with the LEAST amount of configuration effort?',choices:['A|Use an AWS Storage File gateway with enough storage to keep data from the last 48 hours. Send the backups to an SMB share mounted as a local disk.','B|Create an SMB file share in Amazon FSx for Windows File Server that has enough storage to store all backups. Access the file share from on-premises.','C|Mount an Amazon EFS file system on the on-premises client and copy all backups to an NFS share.','D|Create an AWS Backup plan to copy data backups to a local SMB share every 48 hours.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon S3 File Gateway presents a file interface that enables you to store files as objects in Amazon S3 using the industry-standard NFS and SMB file protocols, and access those files via NFS and SMB from your data center or Amazon EC2, or access those files as objects directly in Amazon S3.',why:'When you deploy File Gateway, you specify how much disk space you want to allocate for local cache. This local cache acts as a buffer for writes and provides low latency access to data that was recently written to or read from Amazon S3. When a client writes data to a file via File Gateway, that data is first written to the local cache disk on the gateway itself.',trap:'The option that says: Create an SMB file share in Amazon FSx for Windows File Server that has enough storage to store all backups. Access the file share from on-premises is incorrect because this requires additional setup. You need to set up a Direct Connect or VPN connection from on-premises to AWS first in order for this to work.',rule:'Once the data has been safely persisted to the local cache, only then does the File Gateway upload the data to S3. This provides low-latency on-premises access to cloud data.',keywords:'On-premises file access backed by S3 = Storage Gateway File Gateway (ongoing hybrid).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_49',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A website hosted on Amazon ECS container instances loads slowly during peak traffic, affecting its availability. Currently, the container instances are run behind an Application Load Balancer, and CloudWatch alarms are configured to send notifications to the operations team if there is a problem in availability so they can scale out if needed. A solutions architect needs to create an automatic scaling solution when such problems occur. Which solution could satisfy the requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Create an AWS Auto Scaling policy that scales out an ECS service when the ALB endpoint becomes unreachable.','B|Create an AWS Auto Scaling policy that scales out the ECS service when the ALB hits a high CPU utilization.','C|Create an AWS Auto Scaling policy that scales out the ECS cluster when the ALB target group’s CPU utilization is too high.','D|Create an AWS Auto Scaling policy that scales out the ECS service when the service’s memory utilization is too high.','E|Create an AWS Auto Scaling policy that scales out the ECS cluster when the service’s CPU utilization is too high.'],correct:'DE',answer:'Create an Auto Scaling policy that scales out the ECS service (not the cluster) when the service\'s memory utilization is too high. ECS Service Auto Scaling responds to service-level metrics like CPU and memory utilization, not ALB-level metrics, and acts on the service (task count) not the underlying EC2 cluster.',why:'ECS Service Auto Scaling controls the number of tasks in a service. When memory utilization of the service\'s tasks is high, scaling out adds more tasks to distribute the load. The key distinctions: scaling the SERVICE (task count) vs the CLUSTER (EC2 instances behind it), and using SERVICE-level metrics (CPU/memory utilization per task) rather than ALB-level metrics (which measure request rates, not compute saturation).',trap:'Scaling the ECS cluster (adding more EC2 instances) rather than the service (adding more tasks) is a separate operation that does not directly help task-level performance. ALB unreachability is a binary health event, not a scaling metric. ALB CPU utilization is a load balancer metric, not an ECS workload metric.',rule:'ECS slow under load = scale ECS SERVICE auto scaling on service CPU/memory utilization. Service = task count. Cluster = EC2 instances. Use service metrics, not ALB metrics for ECS scaling.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_50',category:'Serverless',question:'A healthcare company has developed an AWS Lambda function to handle requests from a third-party analytics service. When new patient data is available, the service sends an HTTP POST request to a webhook intended to trigger the Lambda function. What would be the MOST operationally efficient solution to ensure that the service can call the Lambda function?',choices:['A|Generate a Lambda Function URL and use it as the webhook for the third-party analytics service.','B|Attach an Amazon SQS queue to the Lambda function. Use the SQS queue URL as the webhook.','C|Launch an EC2 instance that acts as a proxy for the Lambda function. Give the instance’s public IP as a webhook to the third-party analytics service.','D|Create an API Gateway endpoint for the Lambda function. Provide the endpoint as a webhook to the third-party analytics service.'],correct:'A',answer:'Lambda function URLs are HTTP(S) endpoints dedicated to your Lambda function. You can easily create and set up a function URL using the Lambda console or API. Once created, Lambda generates a unique URL endpoint for your use.',why:'In the scenario, creating a function URL is the simplest and most straightforward way of making the Lambda function callable by the analytics service. This also simplifies the architecture since there is no need to set up and manage an intermediary service such as API Gateway.',trap:'The option that says: Attach an Amazon SQS queue to the Lambda function. Use the SQS queue URL as the webhook is incorrect. Amazon SQS is a fully managed message queuing service that enables you to decouple and scale microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications. While you can configure a Lambda function to poll an SQS queue for messages, SQS itself does not directly accept HTTP(S) requests from outside AWS, so you cannot use an SQS URL as a webhook.',rule:'Once created, Lambda generates a unique URL endpoint for your use.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_51',category:'Database',question:'An online stock trading system is hosted in AWS and uses an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances, an RDS database, and an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis. You need to improve the data security of your in-memory data store by requiring the user to enter a password before they are granted permission to execute Redis commands. Which of the following should you do to meet the above requirement? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Enable the in-transit encryption for Redis replication groups.','B|Create a new Redis replication group and set the AtRestEncryptionEnabled parameter to true.','C|Authenticate the users using Redis AUTH by creating a new Redis Cluster with both the --transit-encryption-enabled and --auth-token parameters enabled.','D|Do nothing. This feature is already enabled by default.'],correct:'ABC',answer:'Using Redis AUTH command can improve data security by requiring the user to enter a password before they are granted permission to execute Redis commands on a password-protected Redis server.',why:'To require that users enter a password on a password-protected Redis server, include the parameter --auth-token with the correct password when you create your replication group or cluster and on all subsequent commands to the replication group or cluster.',trap:'The option that says: Creating a new Redis replication group and setting the AtRestEncryptionEnabled parameter to true is incorrect because the Redis At-Rest Encryption feature only secures the data inside the in-memory data store. You have to use Redis AUTH option instead.',rule:'ElastiCache Redis AUTH = password-protect the Redis server. Set --auth-token parameter at creation or modification. Clients must send AUTH token before any command. Requires in-transit encryption (TLS) to be enabled when using AUTH token.',keywords:'sub-millisecond / in-memory caching → ElastiCache. Frequently read, rarely changes → cache it.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_52',category:'Serverless',question:'A company has several websites and hosts its infrastructure on the AWS Cloud. The mission-critical web applications are hosted on fleets of Amazon EC2 instances behind Application Load Balancers. The company uses AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) provided certificate on the ALBs to enable HTTPS access on its websites. The security team wants to get notified 30 days before the expiration of the SSL certificates. Which of the following can the Solutions Architect implement to meet this request? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use AWS Config to manually create a rule that checks for certificate expiry on ACM. Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to send an alert to an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic when AWS Config flags a resource.','B|Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that will check AWS Health or ACM expiration events related to ACM certificates. Send an alert notification to an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic when a certificate is going to expire in 30 days.','C|Modify all certificates to use the AWS Certificate Manager Private Certificate Authority. Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that will check for ACM events that shows certificates expiring within 30 days. Set the target to invoke an AWS Lambda function to send a message to an Amazon SNS topic.','D|Utilize AWS Trusted Advisor to check for the ACM certificates that will expire in 30 days. Using this metric, create an Amazon CloudWatch alarm that will send an alert to an AWS Systems Manager OpsItem.','E|Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule and schedule it to run every day to identify the expiring ACM certificates. Configure to rule to check the DaysToExpiry metric of all ACM certificates in Amazon CloudWatch. Send an alert notification to an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic when a certificate is going to expire in 30 days.'],correct:'BE',answer:'Create an EventBridge rule that monitors AWS Health or ACM expiration events (B) for 30-day certificate expiry notifications, OR create a scheduled EventBridge rule that checks the DaysToExpiry CloudWatch metric daily for all ACM certificates (E). Both send alerts via SNS.',why:'ACM publishes two types of expiry signals: AWS Health events (triggered at ~45 and ~30 days before expiry) and CloudWatch DaysToExpiry metrics (available per certificate). EventBridge can capture Health events directly. Alternatively, a scheduled daily EventBridge rule can query the DaysToExpiry CloudWatch metric and alert when below 30 days. Both provide reliable, managed alerting without custom code.',trap:'AWS Config managed rules do not include an ACM certificate expiry check — you would need a custom Lambda rule. AWS Trusted Advisor checks for expiring certificates but its checks run periodically and cannot be set to alert at a specific threshold like 30 days.',rule:'ACM cert expiry alerts = EventBridge + AWS Health events (auto 45/30 day alerts) OR scheduled EventBridge + CloudWatch DaysToExpiry metric. Config has no managed rule for cert expiry. Trusted Advisor checks for certificate expiry but only for certs attached to ELBs (limited scope).',keywords:'ACM cert expiry monitoring: EventBridge detects ACM events. CloudWatch DaysToExpiry metric for alarms.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_53',category:'IAM',question:'An application is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and a Microsoft SQL Server on Amazon RDS. There is a requirement that all in-flight data between your web servers and RDS should be secured. Which of the following options is the MOST suitable solution that you should implement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Force all connections to your DB instance to use SSL by setting the rds.force_ssl parameter to true. Once done, reboot your DB instance.','B|Download the Amazon RDS Root CA certificate. Import the certificate to your servers and configure your application to use SSL to encrypt the connection to RDS.','C|Specify the TDE option in an RDS option group that is associated with that DB instance to enable transparent data encryption (TDE).','D|Enable the IAM DB authentication in RDS using the AWS Management Console.','E|Configure the security groups of your EC2 instances and RDS to only allow traffic to and from port 443.'],correct:'AB',answer:'To force SSL/TLS for all RDS SQL Server connections: (A) set rds.force_ssl = 1 in the DB parameter group to require SSL for all connections, and (B) download the RDS Root CA certificate and import it into the server/client trust store to verify the RDS certificate.',why:'Setting rds.force_ssl = 1 in the parameter group causes RDS to reject any non-SSL connections at the database level. The RDS Root CA certificate must be trusted by the application server to verify that it is connecting to a genuine RDS endpoint (not a MITM). Both steps together enforce encrypted connections with certificate validation.',trap:'TDE (Transparent Data Encryption) in an RDS option group encrypts data at rest on the disk — it does not force or encrypt connections in transit. IAM DB Authentication uses token-based authentication but does not enforce SSL encryption.',rule:'Force SSL on RDS SQL Server = rds.force_ssl = 1 in parameter group + import RDS Root CA certificate. TDE = encryption at rest, not in transit. IAM DB Auth = identity, not encryption. SSL certificate = from ACM or self-signed. Enforce via parameter group.',keywords:'EC2 profile credentials for RDS auth → IAM DB Authentication. Token valid 15 min. No passwords.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_54',category:'IAM',question:'A company has an application architecture that stores both the access key ID and the secret access key in a plain text file on a custom Amazon Machine Image (AMI). The EC2 instances, which are created by using this AMI, are using the stored access keys to connect to a DynamoDB table. What should the Solutions Architect do to make the current architecture more secure? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Put the access keys in Amazon Glacier instead.','B|Put the access keys in an Amazon S3 bucket instead.','C|Remove the stored access keys in the AMI. Create a new IAM role with permissions to access the DynamoDB table and assign it to the EC2 instances.','D|Do nothing. The architecture is already secure because the access keys are already in the Amazon Machine Image.'],correct:'ABC',answer:'Putting the access keys in Amazon Glacier or in an Amazon S3 bucket are incorrect because S3 and Glacier are mainly used as a storage option. It is better to use an IAM role instead of storing access keys in these storage services.',why:'You should use an IAM role to manage temporary credentials for applications that run on an EC2 instance. When you use an IAM role, you don\'t have to distribute long-term credentials (such as a user name and password or access keys) to an EC2 instance.',trap:'The option that says: Do nothing. The architecture is already secure because the access keys are already in the Amazon Machine Image is incorrect because you can make the architecture more secure by using IAM.',rule:'Amazon = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_55',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company is designing a customized text messaging service that targets its mobile app users. As part of its multi-engagement marketing campaign, a company needs to send a one-time confirmation message to all of its subscribers using Short Message Service (SMS). The solutions architect must design the system to allow a subscriber to reply to the SMS messages. The customer responses must be kept for an entire year for analysis and targeted sale promotions. In addition, the SMS responses must also be collected, processed, and analyzed in near-real-time. Which solution will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Create a new topic in Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) and an Amazon Kinesis data stream configured with all its default settings. Send SMS messages using Amazon SNS. Integrate the Kinesis data stream to the SNS topic for data collection, archiving, and analysis.','B|Launch a new Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue to send out SMS messages. Use AWS Step Functions and AWS Lambda to collect, process, and analyze responses. Store the data to Amazon S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval.','C|Create an Amazon Pinpoint journey for the multi-engagement SMS marketing campaign and an Amazon Kinesis Data Stream for analysis. Configure Amazon Pinpoint to send events to the Kinesis data stream for collection, processing, and analysis. Set the retention period of the Kinesis data stream to 365 days.','D|Set up an Amazon Connect contact flow to send the confirmation SMS messages to the mobile app users. Deploy an AWS Lambda function to process and analyze the responses. Store the data to Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval'],correct:'C',answer:'In Amazon Pinpoint, an event is an action that occurs when a user interacts with one of your applications, when you send a message from a campaign or journey, or when you send a transactional SMS or email message. For example, if you send an email message, several events occur: Sending, Delivery, Bounce, Complaint, Open, Click. Use SNS/SQS for event notifications.',why:'You can configure Amazon Pinpoint to send information about events to Amazon Kinesis. The Kinesis platform offers services that you can use to collect, process, and analyze data from AWS services in real time.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a new Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue to send out SMS messages. Use AWS Step Functions and AWS Lambda to collect, process, and analyze responses. Store the data to Amazon S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval is incorrect because using Amazon SQS alone is not capable of sending out SMS messages. In addition, the SMS marketing campaign is sent only once. It\'s better to process and store the responses in an Amazon Kinesis data stream and set its retention period to 1 year.',rule:'Amazon Pinpoint journey for the multi|Amazon Kinesis Data Stream for analys: correct. Amazon Simple: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Real-time streaming ingest → Kinesis Data Streams. Firehose = delivery to S3/Redshift, not processing.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_56',category:'IAM',question:'A web application, which is hosted in the on-premises data center and uses a MySQL database, must be migrated to AWS Cloud. You need to ensure that the network traffic to and from your RDS database instance is encrypted using SSL. For improved security, you have to use the profile credentials specific to your EC2 instance to access your database, instead of a password. Which of the following should you do to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Launch a new RDS database instance using Aurora with the Backtrack feature enabled.','B|Configure your RDS database to enable encryption.','C|Set up an RDS database and enable the IAM DB Authentication.','D|Launch the mysql client using the --ssl-ca parameter when connecting to the database.'],correct:'C',answer:'The Requester Pays feature on the S3 bucket requires the data requester (the external users) to pay for data transfer costs instead of the bucket owner — appropriate when you want to share data without absorbing egress costs.',why:'With Requester Pays enabled, the requester must authenticate (anonymous access is disabled) and their AWS account is billed for data transfer and request costs. The bucket owner pays only for storage. This is used for sharing large public datasets, software distribution, or any scenario where you want data access to be cost-neutral for the owner.',trap:'CORS allows cross-origin browser requests to the S3 bucket — it does not transfer data transfer costs to requesters. A bucket policy requiring ACL = bucket-owner-full-control controls ownership of uploaded objects, not data transfer billing. Enabling server access logging tracks requests but does not change billing responsibility.',rule:'S3 owner does not pay for data transfer = enable Requester Pays. Requester must authenticate (no anonymous access). CORS = cross-origin browser access. Server access logging = audit trail for S3 requests (not CloudTrail). Presigned URL = time-limited direct S3 access.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_57',category:'IAM',question:'A company is using Amazon S3 to store frequently accessed data. The S3 bucket is shared with external users that will upload files regularly. A Solutions Architect needs to implement a solution that will grant the bucket owner full access to all uploaded objects in the S3 bucket. What action should be done to achieve this task?',choices:['A|Enable the Requester Pays feature in the Amazon S3 bucket.','B|Create a CORS configuration in the S3 bucket.','C|Create a bucket policy that will require the users to set the object\'s ACL to bucket-owner-full-control.','D|Enable server access logging and set up an IAM policy that will require the users to set the object\'s ACL to bucket-owner-full-control.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon S3 stores data as objects within buckets. An object is a file and any optional metadata that describes the file. To store a file in Amazon S3, you upload it to a bucket. When you upload a file as an object, you can set permissions on the object and any metadata. Buckets are containers for objects. You can have one or more buckets.',why:'By default, an S3 object is owned by the AWS account that uploaded it even though the bucket is owned by another account. To get full access to the object, the object owner must explicitly grant the bucket owner access. You can create a bucket policy to require external users to grant bucket-owner-full-control when uploading objects so the bucket owner can have full access to the objects.',trap:'The option that says: Enable the Requester Pays feature in the Amazon S3 bucket is incorrect because this won\'t grant the bucket owner full access to the uploaded objects in the S3 bucket. With Requester Pays buckets, the requester, instead of the bucket owner, pays the cost of the request and the data download from the bucket.',rule:'S3 object key = full path including prefix (e.g., photos/2024/file.jpg). Object metadata = system metadata (Content-Type, ETag) + user-defined metadata (x-amz-meta-*). Key is part of the object identity and cannot be changed — must copy to new key to rename.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_58',category:'Networking',question:'A tech company is having an issue whenever they try to connect to the newly created EC2 instance using a Remote Desktop connection from a computer. Upon checking, the Solutions Architect has verified that the instance has a public IP and the Internet gateway and route tables are in place. What else should he do to resolve this issue?',choices:['A|Adjust the security group to allow inbound traffic on port 22 from the company’s IP address.','B|Adjust the security group to allow inbound traffic on port 3389 from the company’s IP address.','C|You should restart the EC2 instance since there might be some issue with the instance','D|You should create a new instance since there might be some issue with the instance'],correct:'A',answer:'Since you are using a Remote Desktop connection to access your EC2 instance, you have to ensure that the Remote Desktop Protocol is allowed in the security group. By default, the server listens on TCP port 3389 and UDP port 3389.',why:'Windows Remote Desktop Protocol uses TCP port 3389. EC2 Security Groups are stateful firewalls that default to deny all inbound. If no inbound rule for TCP 3389 exists, the RDP TCP handshake is dropped before it reaches the instance OS. The Security Group must explicitly allow TCP 3389 from your IP (or 0.0.0.0/0 for open access). Also check: Windows Firewall inside the instance, NACL rules, and that the instance has a public IP.',trap:'Opening port 22 enables SSH — correct for Linux, not Windows RDP (port 3389). Using an Elastic IP does not change which ports are open — it only provides a static public IP. A public IP is necessary for direct RDP but does not alone solve the port access problem.',rule:'Cannot connect to Windows EC2 via RDP = check Security Group has TCP port 3389 open from your IP. RDP = port 3389. SSH = port 22. Security group is stateful (no separate outbound rule needed for response traffic). NACLs = stateless (need explicit inbound + outbound rules).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_59',category:'Networking',question:'A company created a VPC with a single subnet then launched an On-Demand EC2 instance in that subnet. You have attached an Internet gateway (IGW) to the VPC and verified that the EC2 instance has a public IP. The main route table of the VPC is as shown below: However, the instance still cannot be reached from the Internet when you tried to connect to it from your computer. Which of the following should be made to the route table to fix this issue?',choices:['A|Add this new entry to the route table: 0.0.0.0/27 -> Your Internet Gateway','B|Modify the above route table: 10.0.0.0/27 -> Your Internet Gateway','C|Add the following entry to the route table: 10.0.0.0/27 -> Your Internet Gateway','D|Add this new entry to the route table: 0.0.0.0/0 -> Your Internet Gateway'],correct:'D',answer:'To route traffic from a VPC to the Internet, the route table must have an entry for 0.0.0.0/0 pointing to the Internet Gateway: 0.0.0.0/0 → igw-xxxx.',why:'The route 0.0.0.0/0 is the default route — it matches all destinations not covered by more specific routes. Pointing it to the Internet Gateway allows instances in the subnet to communicate with any public IP address on the Internet. Without this route, Internet-bound traffic has no path and is dropped.',trap:'0.0.0.0/27 → IGW is incorrect — this is a /27 host route, not the default route. Setting 0.0.0.0 (without a subnet mask) is not valid CIDR notation. Modifying 10.0.0.0/27 → IGW routes VPC-internal traffic through the IGW, which breaks local communication. The correct entry is always 0.0.0.0/0.',rule:'Internet routing from VPC = route table entry 0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway. Not 0.0.0.0/27 (wrong mask). Not modifying local route. Default route captures all non-local traffic.',keywords:'VPC route table: add 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW for internet access. ::/0 for IPv6. IGW required for public subnet.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_60',category:'IAM',question:'An application is loading hundreds of JSON documents into an Amazon S3 bucket every hour which is registered in AWS Lake Formation as a data catalog. The Data Analytics team uses Amazon Athena to run analyses on these data, but due to the volume, most queries take a long time to complete. What change should be made to improve the query performance while ensuring data security? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Convert the JSON documents into CSV format. Provide fine-grained named resource access control to specific databases or tables in AWS Lake Formation.','B|Transform the JSON data into Apache Parquet format. Ensure that the user has an lakeformation:GetDataAccess IAM permission for underlying data access control.','C|Apply minification on the data and implement the Lake Formation tag-based access control (LF-TBAC) authorization strategy to ensure security.','D|Compress the data into GZIP format before storing it in the S3 bucket. Apply an IAM policy with aws:SourceArn and aws:SourceAccount global condition context keys in Lake Formation that prevents cross-service confused deputy problems and other security issues.'],correct:'BCD',answer:'Thus, the correct answer is: Transform the JSON data into Apache Parquet format. Ensure that the user has an lakeformation:GetDataAccess IAM permission for underlying data access control.',why:'Amazon Athena supports a wide variety of data formats like CSV, TSV, JSON, or Textfiles and also supports open-source columnar formats such as Apache ORC and Apache Parquet. Athena also supports compressed data in Snappy, Zlib, LZO, and GZIP formats. By compressing, partitioning, and using columnar formats you can improve performance and reduce your costs.',trap:'The option that says: Convert the JSON documents into CSV format. Provide fine-grained named resource access control to specific databases or tables in AWS Lake Formation is incorrect because Athena queries performed against row-based formats like CSV are slower than columnar file formats like Apache Parquet.',rule:'AWS = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_61',category:'Storage',question:'A company has several unencrypted Amazon EBS snapshots in its Amazon VPC. The Solutions Architect must ensure that all of the new EBS volumes restored from the unencrypted snapshots are automatically encrypted. What should be done to accomplish this requirement?',choices:['A|Enable the EBS Encryption By Default feature for specific EBS volumes.','B|Launch new EBS volumes and specify the symmetric encryption AWS KMS keys for encryption.','C|Enable the EBS Encryption By Default feature for the AWS Region.','D|Launch new EBS volumes and encrypt them using asymmetric AWS KMS keys.'],correct:'A',answer:'You can configure your AWS account to enforce the encryption of the new EBS volumes and snapshot copies that you create. For example, Amazon EBS encrypts the EBS volumes created when you launch an instance and the snapshots that you copy from an unencrypted snapshot.',why:'Encryption by default has no effect on existing EBS volumes or snapshots. The following are important considerations in EBS encryption: You cannot change the KMS keys that is associated with an existing snapshot or encrypted volume. However, you can associate a different KMS keys during a snapshot copy operation so that the resulting copied snapshot is encrypted by the new KMS keys.',trap:'The option that says: Launch new EBS volumes and encrypt them using asymmetric AWS KMS keys is incorrect because Amazon EBS does not primarily support asymmetric KMS keys. To encrypt an EBS snapshot, you need to use symmetric encryption KMS keys.',rule:'Encryption → EBS, AWS Region. Not AWS KMS.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_62',category:'Serverless',question:'A Solutions Architect created a brand new IAM User with a default setting using AWS CLI. This is intended to be used to send API requests to Amazon S3, DynamoDB, Lambda, and other AWS resources of the company’s cloud infrastructure. Which of the following must be done to allow the user to make API calls to the AWS resources? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Do nothing as the IAM User is already capable of sending API calls to your AWS resources.','B|Enable Multi-Factor Authentication for the user.','C|Assign an IAM Policy to the user to allow it to send API calls.','D|Create a set of Access Keys for the user and attach the necessary permissions.'],correct:'BCD',answer:'To fill this need, you can create, modify, view, or rotate access keys (access key IDs and secret access keys) for IAM users. When you create an access key, IAM returns the access key ID and secret access key. You should save these in a secure location and give them to the user.',why:'You can choose the credentials that are right for your IAM user. When you use the AWS Management Console to create a user, you must choose to include at least a console password or access keys. By default, a brand new IAM user created using the AWS CLI or AWS API has no credentials of any kind. You must create the type of credentials for an IAM user based on the needs of your user.',trap:'The option that says: Do nothing as the IAM User is already capable of sending API calls to your AWS resources is incorrect because by default, a brand new IAM user created using the AWS CLI or AWS API has no credentials of any kind. Take note that in the scenario, you created the new IAM user using the AWS CLI and not via the AWS Management Console, where you must choose to at least include a console password or access keys when creating a new IAM user.',rule:'IAM + AWS = correct solution for this scenario.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_63',category:'IAM',question:'A Python application running on VMware Cloud on AWS must connect to an Amazon DynamoDB table called tutorialsdojo. Considering the principle of least privilege access, a solutions architect must form an IAM policy that allows the application to read, write, update and delete items from the tutorialsdojo table only. Which IAM policy would satisfy the requirements?',choices:['A|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem", "dynamodb:GetItem", "dynamodb:UpdateItem" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-2:123456789012:table/tutorialsdojo" } ] }','B|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:Put*", "dynamodb:Delete*", "dynamodb:Get*", "dynamodb:Update*" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-2:123456789012:table/tutorialsdojo" } ] }','C|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "dynamodb:PutItem", "dynamodb:DeleteItem", "dynamodb:GetItem", "dynamodb:UpdateItem" ], "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-2:123456789012:table/*" } ] }','D|{ "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": "*", "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-2:123456789012:table/tutorialsdojo" } ] }'],correct:'A',answer:'Option A specifies exactly the four required DynamoDB actions (PutItem, DeleteItem, GetItem, UpdateItem) on the specific table ARN. This is minimum necessary access: right actions, right table, nothing extra.',why:'Wildcard actions (Put*, Delete*, Get*, Update*) in Option B match more operations than intended — for example dynamodb:PutItem matches dynamodb:Put* but so do other Put-prefixed operations. Option C uses table/* which allows the four actions on every DynamoDB table, not just tutorialsdojo. Option D uses Action: "*" which grants every AWS action on the table — far exceeding least privilege. Only Option A names exact actions and the exact table ARN.',trap:'Option B wildcards like Put* seem equivalent to PutItem but match additional actions you did not intend. Option C wildcard resource table/* applies to all tables, violating the "tutorialsdojo table only" requirement. Option D granting Action:* on a specific resource still grants far more than needed — it allows admin operations like DeleteTable, UpdateTable, CreateBackup on that table.',rule:'IAM least privilege for DynamoDB = exact action names (not wildcards) + exact table ARN (not table/*). Put* is not the same as PutItem alone.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_64',category:'IAM',question:'A company deployed a web application to an EC2 instance that adds a variety of photo effects to a picture uploaded by the users. The application will put the generated photos to an S3 bucket by sending PUT requests to the S3 API. What is the best option for this scenario considering that you need to have API credentials to be able to send a request to the S3 API?',choices:['A|Encrypt the API credentials and store in any directory of the EC2 instance.','B|Create a role in IAM. Afterwards, assign this role to a new EC2 instance.','C|Store your API credentials in Amazon S3 Glacier.','D|Store the API credentials in the root web application directory of the EC2 instance.'],correct:'B',answer:'Assign an IAM role to the EC2 instance instead of embedding AWS credentials. The role grants the application permission to call AWS services. Temporary credentials are delivered automatically via the instance metadata service (IMDS) and rotated without any manual action.',why:'An IAM role attached to an EC2 instance injects short-lived credentials into the instance metadata endpoint at http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/. The AWS SDK automatically discovers and refreshes these credentials. This eliminates hardcoded access keys in application code or config files, which are a security risk. Roles also provide a complete audit trail in CloudTrail since each action is attributed to the role assumption.',trap:'An IAM role assigned to an EC2 instance provides credentials via the instance metadata service (IMDS) — the application retrieves them automatically. You do not embed the role ARN in application code.',rule:'Create a role in IAM',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'q7_65',category:'Serverless',question:'A software development company has hundreds of Amazon EC2 instances with multiple Application Load Balancers (ALBs) across multiple AWS Regions. The public applications hosted in their EC2 instances are accessed on their on-premises network. The company needs to reduce the number of IP addresses that it needs to regularly whitelist on the corporate firewall device. Which of the following approach can be used to fulfill this requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Global Accelerator and create an endpoint group for each AWS Region. Associate the Application Load Balancer from each region to the corresponding endpoint group.','B|Use AWS Global Accelerator and create multiple endpoints for all the available AWS Regions. Associate all the private IP addresses of the EC2 instances to the corresponding endpoints.','C|Create a new Lambda function that tracks the changes in the IP addresses of all ALBs across multiple AWS Regions. Schedule the function to run and update the corporate firewall every hour using Amazon CloudWatch Events.','D|Launch a Network Load Balancer with an associated Elastic IP address. Set the ALBs in multiple Regions as targets.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Global Accelerator is a service that improves the availability and performance of your applications with local or global users. It provides static IP addresses that act as a fixed entry point to your application endpoints in a single or multiple AWS Regions, such as your Application Load Balancers, Network Load Balancers, or Amazon EC2 instances.',why:'When the application usage grows, the number of IP addresses and endpoints that you need to manage also increase. AWS Global Accelerator allows you to scale your network up or down. AWS Global Accelerator lets you associate regional resources, such as load balancers and EC2 instances, to two static IP addresses. You only whitelist these addresses once in your client applications, firewalls, and DNS records.',trap:'The option that says: Create a new Lambda function that tracks the changes in the IP addresses of all ALBs across multiple AWS Regions. Schedule the function to run and update the corporate firewall every hour using Amazon CloudWatch Events is incorrect because this approach entails a lot of administrative overhead and takes a significant amount of time to implement. Using a custom Lambda function is actually not necessary since you can simply use AWS Global Accelerator to achieve this requirement.',rule:'regularly whitelist on the corporate firewall devi → AWS Global, AWS Region.',keywords:'Fixed IP for load balancer (firewall whitelisting) → Global Accelerator (2 static IPs) or NLB + EIP.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 6'},
  {id:'rt1_1',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is using AWS Fargate to run a batch job whenever an object is uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket. The minimum ECS task count is initially set to 1 to save on costs and should only be increased based on new objects uploaded to the S3 bucket. Which is the most suitable option to implement with the LEAST amount of effort?',choices:['A|Set up an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to detect S3 object PUT operations and set the target to a Lambda function that will run the StartTask API command.','B|Set up an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to detect S3 object PUT operations and set the target to the ECS cluster to run a new ECS task.','C|Set up an alarm in Amazon CloudWatch to monitor S3 object-level operations that are recorded on CloudTrail. Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that triggers the ECS cluster when new CloudTrail events are detected.','D|Set up an alarm in CloudWatch to monitor S3 object-level operations recorded on CloudTrail. Set two alarm actions to update the ECS task count to scale-out/scale-in depending on the S3 event.'],correct:'A',answer:'EventBridge can directly target an ECS cluster and run a new Fargate task as a rule target. When S3 detects a PUT operation, EventBridge fires and ECS launches a new task — no Lambda intermediary needed, no CloudTrail setup required.',why:'EventBridge integrates natively with Amazon ECS as a rule target. You configure the rule to match S3 PutObject events, then set the target as the ECS cluster with the task definition and launch type. ECS receives the trigger and runs a new task directly. This is a single-step configuration entirely within the AWS console with no custom code.',trap:'Adding a Lambda function to call StartTask works but introduces an unnecessary intermediary — more code, more IAM permissions, and an extra failure point. CloudTrail-based solutions require enabling S3 data events in CloudTrail, configuring a CloudWatch alarm, then wiring EventBridge — three services instead of one.',rule:'S3 PUT → ECS new task = EventBridge rule targeting ECS cluster directly. No Lambda needed. CloudTrail + CloudWatch alarm = unnecessary complexity. Least effort = EventBridge rule with ECS as target.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_2',category:'Networking',question:'A popular social media website uses a Amazon CloudFront web distribution to serve static content to millions of users around the globe. Recently, the website has received a number of complaints about long login times. Additionally, there are instances where users encounter HTTP 504 errors. The manager has instructed the team to significantly reduce login time and further optimize the system. Which of the following options should be used together to set up a cost-effective solution that improves the application\'s performance? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Customize the content that the CloudFront web distribution delivers to your users using Lambda@Edge, which allows your AWS Lambda functions to execute the authentication process in AWS locations closer to the users.','B|Establish multiple Amazon VPCs in different AWS regions and configure a transit VPC to interconnect all of your resources. To handle the requests faster, set up AWS Lambda functions in each region with the AWS Serverless Application Model (SAM) service.','C|Configure your origin to add a Cache-Control max-age directive to your objects, and specify the longest practical value for max-age to increase the cache hit ratio of your CloudFront distribution.','D|Deploy your application to multiple AWS regions to accommodate your users around the world. Set up a Route 53 record with latency routing policy to route incoming traffic to the region that provides the best latency to the user.','E|Implement an origin failover by creating an origin group that includes two origins. Assign one as the primary origin and the other as secondary, which enables CloudFront to automatically switch to if the primary origin encounters specific HTTP status code failure responses.'],correct:'ABCDE',answer:'Lambda@Edge runs authentication logic at edge locations closest to users, reducing login latency. Origin failover with an origin group automatically switches to a secondary origin when the primary returns 5xx errors like 504, eliminating those failures.',why:'Lambda@Edge executes on CloudFront events — running auth at the edge means users authenticate against a nearby edge node rather than a distant origin. Origin groups let you define a primary and failover origin — when CloudFront receives a 504 from the primary, it retries against the secondary automatically. Together these solve both problems: slow logins and 504 errors, with no extra infrastructure needed.',trap:'Cache-Control max-age helps cacheable static content but login requests are dynamic and authenticated — they bypass the cache entirely, so this does nothing for login times. Multi-region deployment with Route 53 is expensive and still does not place auth at the edge like Lambda@Edge does.',rule:'Long logins + CloudFront = Lambda@Edge (auth at edge). HTTP 504 errors + CloudFront = origin failover group. These solve different problems. Cache-Control = static content only, not dynamic auth requests.',keywords:'CloudFront 504 errors → Origin Failover group (primary + secondary origin). Automatic switch on 5xx.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_3',category:'Kinesis',question:'A healthcare organization wants to build a system that can predict drug prescription abuse. The organization will gather real-time data from multiple sources, which include Personally Identifiable Information (PII). It\'s crucial that this sensitive information is anonymized prior to landing in a NoSQL database for further processing. Which solution would meet the requirements?',choices:['A|Create a data lake in Amazon S3 and use it as the primary storage for patient health data. Use an S3 trigger to run an AWS Lambda function that performs anonymization. Send the anonymized data to Amazon DynamoDB.','B|Stream the data in an Amazon DynamoDB table. Enable DynamoDB Streams, and configure an AWS Lambda function with AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess permissions to perform anonymization on newly written items.','C|Deploy an Amazon Data Firehose stream to capture and transform the streaming data. Deliver the anonymized data to Amazon Redshift for analysis.','D|Ingest real-time data using Amazon Kinesis Data Stream. Use an AWS Lambda function to anonymize the PII, then store it in Amazon DynamoDB.'],correct:'ABCD',answer:'Kinesis Data Streams ingests the real-time data and Lambda processes each record to strip PII before it ever reaches DynamoDB. The data is anonymized in-flight — no unanonymized PII touches any storage system at any point.',why:'Lambda functions consume KDS records in batches. Each record is processed — PII removed — in compute memory before the cleaned output is written to DynamoDB. This satisfies the hard requirement that PII is anonymized prior to landing in any database. Only the cleaned data reaches storage.',trap:'Option A stores raw PII in S3 first, then anonymizes — PII already landed in storage, violating the requirement. Option B writes unanonymized PII to DynamoDB first, then processes via Streams — also violating the requirement. Option C sends data to Redshift, which is a relational data warehouse, not a NoSQL database.',rule:'Anonymize PII before storage = Kinesis Data Streams → Lambda (transform in transit) → DynamoDB. S3 or DynamoDB first = PII already stored, requirement violated. Redshift = relational, not NoSQL.',keywords:'Row-level DB change trigger → DynamoDB Streams → Lambda. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_4',category:'Database',question:'A car dealership website hosted in Amazon EC2 stores car listings in an Amazon Aurora database managed by Amazon RDS. Once a vehicle has been sold, its data must be removed from the current listings and forwarded to a distributed processing system. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Create an RDS event subscription and send the notifications to Amazon SQS. Configure the SQS queues to fan out the event notifications to multiple Amazon SNS topics. Process the data using AWS Lambda functions.','B|Create an RDS event subscription and send the notifications to AWS Lambda. Configure the Lambda function to fanout the event notifications to multiple Amazon SQS queues to update the target groups.','C|Create an RDS event subscription and send the notifications to Amazon SNS. Configure the SNS topic to fan out the event notifications to multiple Amazon SQS queues. Process the data using AWS Lambda functions.','D|Use an Aurora MySQL native function to invoke an AWS Lambda function whenever a vehicle listing is deleted. Configure the Lambda function to send the data to an Amazon SQS queue for the distributed processing system to consume.'],correct:'D',answer:'Aurora MySQL native functions (lambda_sync or lambda_async) invoke Lambda directly from within a database trigger when a row is deleted. Lambda receives the deleted row data and forwards it to SQS for distributed downstream processing.',why:'When a DELETE occurs on the listings table, a database trigger fires the Aurora native function, which calls Lambda with the relevant data. Lambda then sends it to SQS. This captures actual data-level changes at the row level — exactly what is needed when a sold vehicle record is removed. The trigger fires on the database operation itself.',trap:'RDS event subscriptions only track infrastructure-level events: instance reboots, failovers, storage changes, maintenance windows. They do NOT capture data changes like INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE on rows. All three wrong options use RDS event subscriptions and would never fire when a car listing is deleted.',rule:'Row-level DELETE in Aurora MySQL → Lambda = Aurora native function (lambda_sync/lambda_async) in a DB trigger. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure events ONLY, not data changes.',keywords:'Row-level Aurora data change → Aurora native function (lambda_sync/lambda_async) in DB trigger.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_5',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a cloud architecture composed of Linux and Windows Amazon EC2 instances that process high volumes of financial data 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. To ensure high availability of the systems, the Solutions Architect must create a solution that enables monitoring of memory and disk utilization metrics for all instances. Which of the following is the most suitable monitoring solution to implement?',choices:['A|Use the default Amazon CloudWatch configuration to EC2 instances where the memory and disk utilization metrics are already available. Install the AWS Systems Manager (SSM) Agent to all the EC2 instances.','B|Install the Amazon CloudWatch agent to all the EC2 instances that gather the memory and disk utilization data. View the custom metrics in the CloudWatch console.','C|Enable the Enhanced Monitoring option in EC2 and install Amazon CloudWatch agent to all the EC2 instances to be able to view the memory and disk utilization in the CloudWatch dashboard.','D|Use Amazon Inspector and install the Inspector agent to all EC2 instances.'],correct:'B',answer:'The CloudWatch agent must be installed on EC2 instances to collect memory and disk utilization. These metrics are not included in default CloudWatch EC2 metrics — they require an agent running inside the OS to read them and publish them as custom metrics.',why:'Default CloudWatch EC2 metrics are collected at the hypervisor level and cover CPU, network, and disk I/O. Memory and disk space require an in-guest agent. The CloudWatch unified agent supports both Linux and Windows, making it ideal for mixed fleets. It reads /proc/meminfo and df on Linux, Windows Performance Counters on Windows, and publishes the results as custom metrics to CloudWatch.',trap:'Memory and disk metrics are NOT available in default CloudWatch — this is a critical exam trap. SSM Agent enables Systems Manager features but does not publish CloudWatch metrics. Enhanced Monitoring is an RDS feature for database-level metrics, not EC2 OS-level metrics. Amazon Inspector scans for vulnerabilities, not performance.',rule:'Memory + disk on EC2 = install CloudWatch agent (not default, not SSM, not Enhanced Monitoring). Works on both Linux and Windows. Enhanced Monitoring = RDS only. Inspector = vulnerability scanning.',keywords:'CloudWatch Agent = unified agent for EC2 logs + metrics. Install on all instances for centralized monitoring.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_6',category:'Storage',question:'A logistics company plans to automate its order management application. The company wants to use SFTP file transfer for uploading business-critical documents. Since the files are confidential, encryption at rest is required, and high availability must be ensured. Additionally, each file must be automatically deleted one month after creation. Which of the following options should be implemented to meet the company’s requirements with the least operational overhead?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon S3 bucket with encryption enabled. Configure AWS Transfer for SFTP to securely upload files to the S3 bucket. Configure the retention policy on the SFTP server to delete files after a month.','B|Create an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) and enable encryption. Configure AWS Transfer for SFTP to securely upload files to the EFS file system. Apply an EFS lifecycle policy to delete files after 30 days.','C|Provision an Amazon EC2 instance and install the SFTP service. Mount an encrypted Amazon EFS file system on the EC2 instance to store the uploaded files. Add a cron job to delete the files older than a month.','D|Create an Amazon S3 bucket with encryption enabled. Launch an AWS Transfer for SFTP endpoint to securely upload files to the S3 bucket. Configure an S3 lifecycle rule to delete files after a month.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Transfer for SFTP provides a fully managed SFTP endpoint backed by S3. S3 handles encryption at rest natively. S3 lifecycle expiration rules automatically delete objects 30 days after creation. Both services are multi-AZ with no infrastructure to manage.',why:'AWS Transfer Family abstracts all SFTP server management — no EC2, no patching, no scaling. Files land in S3 directly. SSE-S3 or SSE-KMS satisfies encryption at rest. An S3 lifecycle expiration rule deletes objects exactly 30 days after their creation date, automatically and durably.',trap:'Option A is almost right but wrong on one detail: there is no retention policy on the AWS Transfer SFTP server itself — the 30-day deletion must be on the S3 bucket via lifecycle rules, not on the SFTP endpoint. EFS lifecycle only transitions files to EFS-IA storage class, it does not permanently delete them. Self-managed SFTP on EC2 has high operational overhead.',rule:'SFTP + auto-delete + HA + least overhead = AWS Transfer for SFTP → S3 + S3 lifecycle expiration rule. No retention policy on the SFTP server. EFS lifecycle = tiering only, not deletion.',keywords:'Auto-move S3 objects = lifecycle policy. Min 30 days before Standard→Standard-IA transition.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_7',category:'IAM',question:'A telecommunications company is planning to grant AWS Console access to its developers. Company policy requires the use of identity federation and role-based access control. Currently, the roles are already assigned via groups in the corporate Active Directory. In this scenario, what combination of the following services can provide developers access to the AWS console? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|AWS Directory Service AD Connector','B|AWS Directory Service Simple AD','C|IAM Groups','D|IAM Roles','E|AWS Lambda'],correct:'AD',answer:'AD Connector acts as a directory gateway that redirects authentication requests to the on-premises Active Directory without caching any data in AWS. IAM Roles are then assigned to AD groups so developers sign in with existing corporate credentials and assume the appropriate role.',why:'AD Connector proxies authentication to the existing on-premises AD — no directory data is synced or stored in AWS. Once connected, IAM Roles are assigned to AD groups. When a developer authenticates, their AD group membership maps to an IAM Role, granting the permissions defined in that role. This satisfies both identity federation (AD credentials) and role-based access control (IAM Roles from AD groups).',trap:'Simple AD creates a new standalone Microsoft AD-compatible directory in AWS rather than connecting to the existing on-premises one — it does not proxy requests to existing AD. IAM Groups are collections of IAM users for permission management, not a federation mechanism — they cannot integrate with Active Directory.',rule:'Existing on-premises AD + AWS console = AD Connector (proxies to existing AD, no sync) + IAM Roles (RBAC). Simple AD = new directory, not a proxy. IAM Groups = not a federation service.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_8',category:'Networking',question:'An application consists of multiple Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets in different availability zones. The application uses a single NAT Gateway for downloading software patches from the Internet to the instances. There is a requirement to protect the application from a single point of failure when the NAT Gateway encounters a failure or if its availability zone goes down. How should the Solutions Architect redesign the architecture to be more highly available and cost-effective?',choices:['A|Create a NAT Gateway in each availability zone. Configure the route table in each private subnet to ensure that instances use the NAT Gateway in the same availability zone','B|Create a NAT Gateway in each availability zone. Configure the route table in each public subnet to ensure that instances use the NAT Gateway in the same availability zone.','C|Create two NAT Gateways in each availability zone. Configure the route table in each public subnet to ensure that instances use the NAT Gateway in the same availability zone.','D|Create three NAT Gateways in each availability zone. Configure the route table in each private subnet to ensure that instances use the NAT Gateway in the same availability zone.'],correct:'A',answer:'One NAT Gateway per AZ, with each AZ\'s private subnet route table pointing to the NAT Gateway in that same AZ. If one AZ fails, instances in other AZs use their own local NAT Gateway and maintain Internet access independently.',why:'A NAT Gateway is highly available within its AZ but not across AZs. If the AZ itself goes down, that NAT Gateway is gone. The solution is AZ-independence: one NAT Gateway per AZ in a public subnet, with each private subnet\'s route table routing outbound Internet traffic to the NAT Gateway in the same AZ. This also avoids cross-AZ data transfer charges.',trap:'Configuring the route table on the public subnet is wrong — public subnets route to the Internet Gateway directly, not through a NAT Gateway. The PRIVATE subnet route table is what needs updating. Creating two or three NAT Gateways per AZ adds cost with no additional HA benefit — one per AZ is sufficient.',rule:'NAT Gateway HA = one NAT Gateway per AZ in PUBLIC subnet. Configure PRIVATE subnet route table → same-AZ NAT Gateway. Public subnet → Internet Gateway. Two or three per AZ = unnecessary cost.',keywords:'NAT Gateway HA = one per AZ. Private subnet route table → same-AZ NAT GW.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_9',category:'Database',question:'A financial application consists of an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances, an Application Load Balancer, and a MySQL RDS instance set up in a Multi-AZ Deployment configuration. To protect customers\' confidential data, it must be ensured that the Amazon RDS database is only accessible using an authentication token specific to the profile credentials of EC2 instances. Which of the following actions should be taken to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Enable the IAM DB Authentication.','B|Configure SSL in your application to encrypt the database connection to RDS.','C|Create an IAM Role and assign it to your EC2 instances which will grant exclusive access to your RDS instance.','D|Use a combination of IAM and STS to enforce restricted access to your RDS instance using a temporary authentication token.'],correct:'A',answer:'IAM DB Authentication lets EC2 instances connect to RDS MySQL using a short-lived token generated from the instance\'s IAM profile credentials instead of a static database password. No passwords are stored — IAM handles all authentication.',why:'When IAM DB Authentication is enabled, the application calls the RDS GenerateAuthToken API using the EC2 instance\'s IAM role. This returns a token valid for 15 minutes. The application presents this token as the database password. RDS validates it against IAM. The token is derived from the instance profile — making it specific to that EC2 instance\'s identity, which is exactly what the requirement describes.',trap:'SSL encrypts the connection in transit but still requires a database username and password — it does not authenticate using instance profile credentials. Assigning an IAM Role grants AWS API access but does not enable token-based DB authentication — IAM DB Authentication must be explicitly enabled on the RDS instance. STS underlies the mechanism but is not configured directly.',rule:'RDS access via EC2 instance profile token = IAM DB Authentication. Token lifetime = 15 minutes. No stored DB passwords. Works with MySQL and PostgreSQL. SSL = in-transit encryption only, not identity-based auth.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1_10',category:'Security',question:'A business has recently migrated its applications to AWS. The audit team must be able to assess whether the services the company is using meet common security and regulatory standards. A solutions architect needs to provide the team with a report of all compliance-related documents for their account. Which action should a solutions architect consider?',choices:['A|Run an Amazon Inspector assessment job to download all of the AWS compliance-related information.','B|Use AWS Artifact to view the security reports as well as other AWS compliance-related information.','C|Run an Amazon Macie job to view the Service Organization Control (SOC), Payment Card Industry (PCI), and other compliance reports from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM).','D|View all of the AWS security compliance reports from AWS Security Hub.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Artifact is the self-service portal for on-demand access to AWS compliance reports and agreements. It provides SOC 1/2/3, PCI DSS, ISO certifications, and other regulatory documents directly — no job to run, no scanning required.',why:'AWS Artifact hosts third-party audit reports that validate AWS infrastructure compliance. All AWS accounts have access. Documents include SOC reports, PCI DSS attestations, ISO 27001, and dozens of regional compliance certifications. These are pre-generated reports from independent auditors available for immediate download after agreeing to terms.',trap:'Amazon Inspector scans EC2 and Lambda for software vulnerabilities — it does not produce compliance reports about AWS infrastructure. Amazon Macie identifies sensitive data in S3 and has nothing to do with compliance documentation. ACM manages SSL/TLS certificates. AWS Security Hub aggregates security findings but does not host AWS compliance certification documents.',rule:'AWS compliance reports (SOC, PCI, ISO) = AWS Artifact. Inspector = vulnerability scanning. Macie = sensitive data discovery. Security Hub = security findings. Artifact is the ONLY source for third-party audit reports on AWS.',keywords:'AWS compliance reports (SOC, PCI, ISO) → AWS Artifact. Inspector/Macie/Security Hub ≠ compliance docs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_1',category:'EC2',question:'A company hosted a web application in an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances. The IT manager is concerned about the over-provisioning of the resources that can cause higher operating costs. A Solutions Architect has been instructed to create a cost-effective solution without affecting the performance of the application. Which dynamic scaling policy should be used to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Use simple scaling.','B|Use scheduled scaling.','C|Use suspend and resume scaling.','D|Use target tracking scaling.'],correct:'D',answer:'An Auto Scaling group contains a collection of Amazon EC2 instances that are treated as a logical grouping for the purposes of automatic scaling and management. An Auto Scaling group also enables you to use Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling features such as health check replacements and scaling policies.',why:'Step scaling policies and simple scaling policies are two of the dynamic scaling options available for you to use. Both require you to create CloudWatch alarms for the scaling policies. Both require you to specify the high and low thresholds for the alarms. Both require you to define whether to add or remove instances, and how many, or set the group to an exact size.',trap:'The option that says: Use simple scaling is incorrect because you need to wait for the cooldown period to complete before initiating additional scaling activities. Target tracking or step scaling policies can trigger a scaling activity immediately without waiting for the cooldown period to expire.',rule:'Step scaling policies and simple scaling policies are two of the dynamic scaling options available for you to use.',keywords:'Auto Scaling cost optimization → Target Tracking. Maintains metric at target (CPU %, ALB RPS).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_2',category:'S3',question:'A financial services company plans to migrate its trading application from on-premises Microsoft Windows Server to Amazon Web Services (AWS). The solution must ensure high availability across multiple Availability Zones and offer low-latency access to block storage. Which of the following solutions will fulfill these requirements?',choices:['A|Deploy the trading application on Amazon EC2 Windows Server instances across two Availability Zones. Use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for shared storage.','B|Deploy the trading application on Amazon EC2 Windows Server instances across two Availability Zones. Use Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) to provide shared storage between the instances. Configure Amazon EFS with cross-region replication to sync data across Availability Zones.','C|Configure the trading application on Amazon EC2 Windows Server instances across two Availability Zones. Use Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP to create a Multi-AZ file system and access the data via iSCSI protocol.','D|Configure the trading application on Amazon EC2 Windows instances across two Availability Zones. Use Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) for storage and configure cross-region replication to sync data between S3 buckets in each Availability Zone.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP is a fully managed AWS service that provides high-performance, scalable file storage based on NetApp\'s ONTAP file system. It offers versatile storage options, supporting both file (NFS, SMB) and block (iSCSI) protocols, making it compatible with Windows, Linux, and macOS environments.',why:'The Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP features Multi-AZ file systems designed to ensure continuous availability across AWS Availability Zones, providing high availability for your Windows Server workloads. It offers consistent sub-millisecond file operation latencies with SSD storage, essential for block storage workloads in Windows environments.',trap:'The option that says: Deploy the trading application on Amazon EC2 Windows Server instances across two Availability Zones. Use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for shared storage is incorrect. Amazon FSx for Windows File Server only provides shared, low-latency file storage for Windows environments. It doesn\'t support low-latency access to shared block storage.',rule:'FSx for NetApp ONTAP fully supports block storage protocols like iSCSI, commonly used in Windows Server settings. FSx for Windows = SMB/NFS. FSx for ONTAP = NFS/SMB/iSCSI multi-protocol.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_3',category:'EC2',question:'A tech company has a CRM application hosted on an Auto Scaling group of On-Demand EC2 instances with different instance types and sizes. The application is extensively used during office hours from 9 in the morning to 5 in the afternoon. Their users are complaining that the performance of the application is slow during the start of the day but then works normally after a couple of hours. Which of the following is the MOST operationally efficient solution to implement to ensure the application works properly at the beginning of the day? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Configure a Dynamic scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to launch new instances based on the CPU utilization.','B|Configure a Dynamic scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to launch new instances based on the Memory utilization.','C|Configure a Scheduled scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to launch new instances before the start of the day.','D|Configure a Predictive scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to automatically adjust the number of Amazon EC2 instances'],correct:'ABC',answer:'Scaling based on a schedule allows you to scale your application in response to predictable load changes. For example, every week the traffic to your web application starts to increase on Wednesday, remains high on Thursday, and starts to decrease on Friday. You can plan your scaling activities based on the predictable traffic patterns of your web application.',why:'To configure your Auto Scaling group to scale based on a schedule, you create a scheduled action. The scheduled action tells Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling to perform a scaling action at specified times. To create a scheduled scaling action, you specify the start time when the scaling action should take effect and the new minimum, maximum, and desired sizes for the scaling action.',trap:'The option that says: Configure a Predictive scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to automatically adjust the number of Amazon EC2 instances is incorrect. Although this type of scaling policy can be used in this scenario, it is not the most operationally efficient option. Take note that the scenario mentioned that the Auto Scaling group consists of Amazon EC2 instances with different instance types and sizes. Predictive scaling assumes that your Auto Scaling group is homogenous, which means that all EC2 instances are of equal capacity. The forecasted capacity can be inaccurate if you are using a variety of EC2 instance sizes and types on your Auto Scaling group.',rule:'ASG scaling type: Scheduled = known time-based events. Target tracking = maintain a metric value (e.g., 50% CPU). Step = proportional to alarm breach size. Predictive = ML-based projection of future demand. Target tracking = simplest, no need to define scaling steps.',keywords:'Event-driven triggers / scheduled jobs → Amazon EventBridge. Direct target: ECS, Lambda, SQS, etc.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_4',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a highly available architecture consisting of an Elastic Load Balancer and multiple Amazon EC2 instances configured with Auto Scaling across three Availability Zones. The company needs to monitor EC2 instances based on a specific metric that is not readily available in Amazon CloudWatch. Which of the following is a custom metric in CloudWatch that requires manual setup?',choices:['A|Memory Utilization of an EC2 instance','B|CPU Utilization of an EC2 instance','C|Disk Read activity of an EC2 instance','D|Network packets out of an EC2 instance'],correct:'A',answer:'The CloudWatch agent must be installed on EC2 instances to collect custom metrics like memory utilization, because the hypervisor-level default metrics cannot see inside the guest OS memory.',why:'Default CloudWatch EC2 metrics are collected at the hypervisor level: CPU utilization, network I/O, disk I/O counts. Memory utilization requires an OS-level agent to read /proc/meminfo (Linux) or Windows Performance Counters. The CloudWatch unified agent collects these and publishes them as custom metrics to CloudWatch under the CWAgent namespace.',trap:'Enabling detailed monitoring increases the frequency of default metrics to 1-minute intervals — it does NOT add new metric types like memory. Detailed monitoring cannot monitor memory; it only speeds up collection of existing default metrics. Amazon Inspector scans for vulnerabilities, not OS performance metrics.',rule:'Memory utilization on EC2 = NOT a default CloudWatch metric. Must install CloudWatch agent. Detailed monitoring = higher frequency only (same metric set). Agent required for memory and disk metrics. EC2 hibernation also requires CloudWatch agent for memory-related metrics.',keywords:'CloudWatch default EC2 metrics: CPU, Network, Disk I/O. Memory + swap require CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_5',category:'S3',question:'A company is using Amazon S3 to store frequently accessed data. When an object is created or deleted, the S3 bucket will send an event notification to the Amazon SQS queue. A solutions architect needs to create a solution that will notify the development and operations team about the created or deleted objects. Which of the following would satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Set up another SQS queue for the other team. Grant S3 permission to send a notification to the second SQS queue.','B|Create a new Amazon SNS FIFO topic for the other team. Grant S3 permission to send the notification to the second SNS topic.','C|Set up an Amazon SNS topic and configure two SQS queues to poll the SNS topic. Grant S3 permission to send notifications to SNS and update the bucket to use the new SNS topic.','D|Create an Amazon SNS topic and configure two SQS queues to subscribe to the topic. Grant S3 permission to send notifications to SNS and update the bucket to use the new SNS topic.'],correct:'D',answer:'The Amazon S3 notification feature enables you to receive notifications when certain events happen in your bucket. To enable notifications, you must first add a notification configuration that identifies the events you want Amazon S3 to publish and the destinations where you want Amazon S3 to send the notifications.',why:'Amazon S3 supports the following destinations where it can publish events: In Amazon SNS, the fanout scenario is when a message published to an SNS topic is replicated and pushed to multiple endpoints, such as Amazon SQS queues, HTTP(S) endpoints, and Lambda functions. This allows for parallel asynchronous processing.',trap:'The option that says: Set up another SQS queue for the other team. Grant S3 permission to send a notification to the second SQS queue is incorrect because you can only add 1 SQS or SNS at a time for Amazon S3 events notification. If you need to send the events to multiple subscribers, you should implement a message fanout pattern with Amazon SNS and Amazon SQS.',rule:'Amazon S3 supports the following destinations where it can publish events: In Amazon SNS, the fanout scenario is when a message published to Not Amazon S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_6',category:'S3',question:'An AI-powered Forex trading application consumes thousands of data sets to train its machine learning model. The application’s workload requires a high-performance, parallel hot storage to process the training datasets concurrently. It also needs cost-effective cold storage to archive those datasets that yield low profit. Which of the following Amazon storage services should the developer use?',choices:['A|Use Amazon FSx For Lustre and the Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) volumes of Amazon EBS for hot and cold storage respectively.','B|Use Amazon FSx For Lustre and Amazon S3 for hot and cold storage respectively.','C|Use Amazon Elastic File System and Amazon S3 for hot and cold storage respectively.','D|Use Amazon FSx For Windows File Server and Amazon S3 for hot and cold storage respectively.'],correct:'B',answer:'Hot storage refers to the storage that keeps frequently accessed data (hot data). Warm storage refers to the storage that keeps less frequently accessed data (warm data). Cold storage refers to the storage that keeps rarely accessed data (cold data). In terms of pricing, the colder the data, the cheaper it is to store, and the costlier it is to access when needed.',why:'Amazon FSx For Lustre is a high-performance file system for fast processing of workloads. Lustre is a popular open-source parallel file system which stores data across multiple network file servers to maximize performance and reduce bottlenecks. Amazon FSx for Windows File Server is a fully managed Microsoft Windows file system with full support for the SMB protocol, Windows NTFS, and Microsoft Active Directory (AD) Integration.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon FSx For Lustre and Amazon EBS Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) volumes for hot and cold storage respectively is incorrect because the Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) volumes are primarily designed for storing hot data (data that are frequently accessed) used in I/O-intensive workloads. EBS has a storage option called "Cold HDD," but due to its price, it is not ideal for data archiving. EBS Cold HDD is much more expensive than Amazon S3 Glacier / Glacier Deep Archive and is often utilized in applications where sequential cold data is read less frequently.',rule:'Amazon FSx For Lustre is a high-performance file system for fast processing of workloads.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_7',category:'Serverless',question:'A startup is using Amazon RDS to store data from a web application. Most of the time, the application has low user activity but it receives bursts of traffic within seconds whenever there is a new product announcement. The Solutions Architect needs to create a solution that will allow users around the globe to access the data using an API. What should the Solutions Architect do meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Create an API using Amazon API Gateway and use the Amazon ECS cluster with Service Auto Scaling to handle the bursts of traffic in seconds.','B|Create an API using Amazon API Gateway and use Amazon Elastic Beanstalk with Auto Scaling to handle the bursts of traffic in seconds.','C|Create an API using Amazon API Gateway and use AWS Lambda to handle the bursts of traffic in seconds.','D|Create an API using Amazon API Gateway and use an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances to handle the bursts of traffic in seconds.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Lambda lets you run code without provisioning or managing servers. You pay only for the compute time you consume. With Lambda, you can run code for virtually any type of application or backend service - all with zero administration. Just upload your code, and Lambda takes care of everything required to run and scale your code with high availability.',why:'The first time you invoke your function, AWS Lambda creates an instance of the function and runs its handler method to process the event. When the function returns a response, it stays active and waits to process additional events. If you invoke the function again while the first event is being processed, Lambda initializes another instance, and the function processes the two events concurrently.',trap:'The option that says: Create an API using Amazon API Gateway and use Amazon Elastic Beanstalk with Auto Scaling to handle the bursts of traffic in seconds is incorrect because just like the previous option, the use of Auto Scaling has a delay of a few minutes as it launches new EC2 instances that will be used by Amazon Elastic Beanstalk.',rule:'Amazon API Gateway and use the Amazon|ECS: correct. Amazon API: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'HPC parallel file system / hot data → FSx for Lustre. Integrates with S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_8',category:'Database',question:'A Docker application, which is running on an Amazon ECS cluster behind a load balancer, is heavily using Amazon DynamoDB. The application requires improved database performance by distributing the workload evenly and utilizing the provisioned throughput efficiently. Which of the following should be implemented for the DynamoDB table?',choices:['A|Reduce the number of partition keys in the DynamoDB table.','B|Use partition keys with high-cardinality attributes, which have a large number of distinct values for each item.','C|Use partition keys with low-cardinality attributes, which have a few number of distinct values for each item.','D|Avoid using a composite primary key, which is composed of a partition key and a sort key.'],correct:'B',answer:'The optimal usage of a table\'s provisioned throughput depends not only on the workload patterns of individual items, but also on the partition-key design. This doesn\'t mean that you must access all partition key values to achieve an efficient throughput level, or even that the percentage of accessed partition key values must be high.',why:'DynamoDB physically partitions your table data based on the partition key hash. Each partition handles a share of the total provisioned throughput. If your partition key has low cardinality (e.g., a status field with values ACTIVE/INACTIVE), all writes for ACTIVE items go to the same partition, creating a hot partition that gets throttled. High-cardinality keys (user ID, order ID, UUID) distribute writes evenly across all partitions.',trap:'The option that says: Using partition keys with low-cardinality attributes, which have a few number of distinct values for each item is incorrect because this is only the exact opposite of the correct answer. Remember that the more distinct partition key values your workload accesses, the more those requests will be spread across the partitioned space. Conversely, the less distinct partition key values, the less evenly spread it would be across the partitioned space, which effectively slows the performance.',rule:'DynamoDB performance = use high-cardinality partition key to spread writes across partitions. Low-cardinality key = hot partition = throttling. Partition key choice is the single most important DynamoDB design decision for write-heavy workloads.',keywords:'DynamoDB hot partition → use high-cardinality partition key. Spread writes evenly.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_9',category:'S3',question:'A content management system (CMS) is hosted on a fleet of auto-scaled, On-Demand Amazon EC2 instances that use Amazon Aurora as its database. Currently, the system stores the file documents that users upload in one of the attached Amazon EBS volumes. The system\'s performance has been observed to be slow, and the manager has instructed the team to improve the architecture. In this scenario, which solution should be implemented to achieve a scalable, highly available, POSIX-compliant shared file system?',choices:['A|Create an Amazon S3 bucket and use this as the storage for the CMS','B|Use Amazon EFS to provide a shared file system for concurrent access to data','C|Upgrade your existing EBS volumes to Provisioned IOPS SSD volumes','D|Leverage Amazon ElastiCache to cache frequently accessed data and reduce latency'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) provides simple, scalable, elastic file storage for use with AWS Cloud services and on-premises resources. When mounted on Amazon EC2 instances, an Amazon EFS file system provides a standard file system interface and file system access semantics, allowing you to seamlessly integrate Amazon EFS with your existing applications and tools.',why:'This particular scenario tests your understanding of EBS, EFS, and S3. In this scenario, there is a fleet of On-Demand EC2 instances that store file documents from the users to one of the attached EBS Volumes. The system performance is quite slow because the architecture doesn\'t provide the EC2 instances parallel shared access to the file documents.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Amazon S3 bucket and use this as the storage for the CMS is incorrect because Amazon S3 is just an object storage service, which does not provide the required file system interface and file locking needed by a CMS.',rule:'Although an EBS Volume can be attached to multiple EC2 instances, you can only do so on instances Not Amazon S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_10',category:'Database',question:'An e-commerce company runs a highly scalable web application that depends on an Amazon Aurora database. As the number of users increases, the read replica faces difficulties keeping up with the increasing read traffic, causing performance bottlenecks during peak periods. Which of the following will resolve the issue with the most cost-effective solution?',choices:['A|Increase the size of the Aurora DB cluster.','B|Use automatic scaling for the Aurora read replica using Aurora Auto Scaling.','C|Implement read scaling with Aurora Global Database.','D|Set up a read replica that can operate across different regions.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon Aurora is a cloud-based relational database service that provides better performance and reliability for database workloads. It is highly available and scalable, making it a great choice for businesses of any size.',why:'Aurora Auto Scaling is particularly useful for businesses that have fluctuating workloads. It ensures that your database cluster scales up or down as needed without manual intervention. This feature saves time and resources, allowing businesses to focus on other aspects of their operations.',trap:'The option that says: Increase the size of the Aurora DB cluster is incorrect because it\'s not economical to upsize the cluster just to alleviate the bottleneck during peak periods. A static increase in the DB cluster size results in constant costs, regardless of whether your database\'s resources are being fully utilized during off-peak periods or not.',rule:'Aurora Auto Scaling automatically adjusts the number of Aurora Replicas based on actual workload. Scale-out adds replicas for read-heavy load. Scale-in removes them when demand drops. Replicas share the same storage as the primary, so no data sync delay.',keywords:'RDS read scaling / reporting offload → Read Replica. Async replication. Can be promoted.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_11',category:'Serverless',question:'A popular social network is hosted in AWS and is using a Amazon DynamoDB table as its database. There is a requirement to implement a \'follow\' feature where users can subscribe to certain updates made by a particular user and be notified via email. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to implement to meet the requirement?',choices:['A|Using the Amazon Kinesis Client Library (KCL), write an application that leverages on DynamoDB Streams Kinesis Adapter that will fetch data from the DynamoDB Streams endpoint. When there are updates made by a particular user, notify the subscribers via email using Amazon SNS.','B|Create an AWS Lambda function that uses DynamoDB Streams Amazon Kinesis Adapter which will fetch data from the DynamoDB Streams endpoint. Set up an Amazon SNS Topic that will notify the subscribers via email when there is an update made by a particular user.','C|Set up a DAX cluster to access the source DynamoDB table. Create a new DynamoDB trigger and an AWS Lambda function. For every update made in the user data, the trigger will send data to the Lambda function which will then notify the subscribers via email using Amazon SNS.','D|Enable DynamoDB Stream and create an AWS Lambda trigger, as well as the IAM role which contains all of the permissions that the Lambda function will need at runtime. The data from the stream record will be processed by the Lambda function which will then publish a message to Amazon SNS Topic that will notify the subscribers via email.'],correct:'ABCD',answer:'A DynamoDB stream is an ordered flow of information about changes to items in an Amazon DynamoDB table. When you enable a stream on a table, DynamoDB captures information about every modification to data items in the table.',why:'Whenever an application creates, updates, or deletes items in the table, DynamoDB Streams writes a stream record with the primary key attribute(s) of the items that were modified. A stream record contains information about a data modification to a single item in a DynamoDB table. You can configure the stream so that the stream records capture additional information, such as the "before" and "after" images of modified items.',trap:'The option that says: Create an AWS Lambda function that uses DynamoDB Streams Amazon Kinesis Adapter which will fetch data from the DynamoDB Streams endpoint. Set up an Amazon SNS Topic that will notify the subscribers via email when there is an update made by a particular user is incorrect because just like in the above, you have to manually enable DynamoDB Streams first before you can use its endpoint.',rule:'DynamoDB Streams captures changes to a table in near real-time. When a modification is made to an item in the table, DynamoDB Streams writes a stream record with the primary key attributes of the modified item.',keywords:'RDS read scaling / reporting offload → Read Replica. Async replication. Can be promoted.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_12',category:'Serverless',question:'A retail company receives raw .csv data files into its Amazon S3 bucket from multiple sources on an hourly basis, with an average file size of 2 GB. An automated process must be implemented to convert these .csv files into the more efficient Apache Parquet format and store the converted files in another S3 bucket. Additionally, the conversion process must be automatically initiated each time a new file is uploaded into the S3 bucket. Which of the following options must be implemented to meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Use an AWS Lambda function triggered by an S3 Object Created event to convert the .csv files to Parquet format. Use the AWS Transfer Family with SFTP service to move the output files to the target S3 bucket.','B|Utilize an AWS Glue extract, transform, and load (ETL) job to process and convert the .csv files to Apache Parquet format and then store the output files into the target S3 bucket. Configure an Amazon EventBridge rule to trigger the Glue job on S3 Object Created events.','C|Set up an Apache Spark job running in an Amazon EC2 instance and create an Amazon EventBridge rule to monitor S3 Object Created events in the S3 bucket. Configure AWS Lambda to invoke the Spark job for every new .csv file added via a Function URL.','D|Create an ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) job and a Data Catalog table in AWS Glue. Configure the Glue crawler to run on a schedule to check for new files in the S3 bucket every hour and convert them to Parquet format.'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS Glue is a powerful ETL service that easily moves data between different data stores. By using AWS Glue, you can create and manage ETL jobs to transfer data from various sources, such as Amazon S3, Amazon RDS, and Amazon Redshift. Additionally, AWS Glue enables you to transform data as needed to fit specific requirements.',why:'When working with big data processing, it is often necessary to convert data from one format to another to optimize processing efficiency. Apache Parquet is a columnar storage format that is designed to provide higher efficiency and performance for big data processing. By storing and processing large amounts of data with high compression rates and faster query times, Parquet can offer significant benefits to the company.',trap:'The option that says: Use an AWS Lambda function triggered by an S3 Object Created event to convert the .csv files to Parquet format. Use the AWS Transfer Family with SFTP service to move the output files to the target S3 bucket is incorrect. The conversion of the CSV files to Parquet format by using a combination of a Lambda function and S3 event notification would work; however, this is not the most efficient solution when primarily handling large amounts of data. The Lambda function has a maximum execution time limit, which means that converting large files may result in timeout issues. Using the AWS Transfer Family with the SFTP service to move the output files to the target S3 bucket is unnecessary too. Moreover, reading the records has to be delivered via a data stream since a Lambda function has a memory limit. This entails additional effort compared with using AWS Glue.',rule:'AWS Lambda function trig|AWS Transfer Family with: correct. AWS Lambda: incorrect for this scenario.',keywords:'Row-level DB change trigger → DynamoDB Streams → Lambda. RDS event subscriptions = infrastructure only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_13',category:'Serverless',question:'A cryptocurrency trading platform is using an API built in AWS Lambda and API Gateway. Due to the recent news and rumors about the upcoming price surge of Bitcoin, Ethereum and other cryptocurrencies, it is expected that the trading platform would have a significant increase in site visitors and new users in the coming days ahead. In this scenario, how can you protect the backend systems of the platform from traffic spikes? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|Switch from using AWS Lambda and API Gateway to a more scalable and highly available architecture using EC2 instances, ELB, and Auto Scaling.','B|Enable throttling limits and result caching in API Gateway.','C|Use CloudFront in front of the API Gateway to act as a cache.','D|Move the Lambda function in a VPC.'],correct:'BCD',answer:'You can add caching to API calls by provisioning an Amazon API Gateway cache and specifying its size in gigabytes. The cache is provisioned for a specific stage of your APIs. This improves performance and reduces the traffic sent to your back end. Cache settings allow you to control the way the cache key is built and the time-to-live (TTL) of the data stored for each method.',why:'API Gateway stage caching stores the backend response (Lambda return value) keyed by request parameters. Subsequent identical requests are served from cache without invoking Lambda — reducing latency and cost. The cache TTL is configurable (default 300 sec). You can invalidate the cache with the Cache-Control: max-age=0 header from authorized clients. Cache size ranges from 0.5 GB to 237 GB.',trap:'Using CloudFront in front of the API Gateway to act as a cache is incorrect because CloudFront only speeds up content delivery which provides a better latency experience for your users. It does not help much for the backend.',rule:'API Gateway response caching = enable API Gateway stage cache (TTL-based). Reduces backend Lambda calls. Not CloudFront (only caches GET, not POST; does not understand API Gateway stage-level caching). API GW caching = per-stage, per-method, configurable TTL.',keywords:'API Gateway caching: reduces backend calls. TTL configurable per stage/method. Flush cache manually.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_14',category:'Serverless',question:'A company is using a combination of API Gateway and AWS Lambda for the web services of an online web portal that is accessed by hundreds of thousands of clients each day. The company will be announcing a new revolutionary product, and it is expected that the web portal will receive a massive number of visitors from all around the globe. How can the back-end systems and applications be protected from traffic spikes?',choices:['A|Use throttling limits in API Gateway','B|API Gateway will automatically scale and handle massive traffic spikes so you do not have to do anything.','C|Manually upgrade the Amazon EC2 instances being used by API Gateway','D|Deploy Multi-AZ in API Gateway with Read Replica'],correct:'A',answer:'API Gateway throttling limits control how many requests per second the API can serve. When traffic spikes cause the API to be overwhelmed, throttling protects the backend by returning 429 Too Many Requests to excess traffic.',why:'API Gateway maintains two throttling levels: account-level (10,000 RPS by default) and per-stage/method (configurable). When the limit is exceeded, API Gateway returns HTTP 429. You can also configure usage plans with API keys to throttle individual clients. This is the correct mechanism to handle traffic spikes and protect backend Lambda or EC2 resources from being overwhelmed.',trap:'The option that says: API Gateway will automatically scale and handle massive traffic spikes so you do not have to do anything is incorrect. Although it can scale using AWS Edge locations, you still need to configure the throttling, typically to further manage the bursts of your APIs.',rule:'API Gateway handle traffic spikes = configure throttling limits (account-level and per-stage). Returns 429 when exceeded. Usage plans = per-client rate limits. Lambda also has concurrency limits. Throttling returns 429 Too Many Requests.',keywords:'Temporary credentials / cross-account access → STS AssumeRole. Token valid 1hr-12hr.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_15',category:'Serverless',question:'An online learning company hosts its Microsoft .NET e-Learning application on a Windows Server in its on-premises data center. The application uses an Oracle Database Standard Edition as its backend database. The company wants a high-performing solution to migrate this workload to the AWS cloud to take advantage of the cloud’s high availability. The migration process should minimize development changes, and the environment should be easier to manage. Which of the following options should be implemented to meet the company requirements? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Perform a homogeneous migration by moving the Oracle database to Amazon RDS for Oracle in a Multi-AZ deployment using AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS).','B|Refactor the application to .NET Core and run it as a serverless container service using Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) with AWS Fargate.','C|Use AWS Application Migration Service (AWS MGN) to migrate the on-premises Oracle database server to a new Amazon EC2 instance.','D|Rehost the on-premises .NET application to an AWS Elastic Beanstalk Multi-AZ environment which runs in multiple Availability Zones.','E|Provision and replatform the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) with Amazon EC2 worker nodes. Use the Windows Server Amazon Machine Image (AMI) and deploy the .NET application using to the ECS cluster via the ECS Anywhere service.'],correct:'AD',answer:'The correct answers are: Perform a homogeneous migration of Oracle to Amazon RDS for Oracle Multi-AZ using AWS DMS, and rehost the .NET application to AWS Elastic Beanstalk Multi-AZ.',why:'AWS DMS supports homogeneous migrations (same engine, same version) with minimal schema conversion. RDS for Oracle in Multi-AZ provides automatic failover across AZs. Elastic Beanstalk natively supports .NET applications, handles capacity provisioning, load balancing, and scaling, and can be configured for Multi-AZ deployments.',trap:'Refactoring to .NET Core requires significant code changes — this violates the rehost/replatform approach implied. AWS MGN migrates the VM to EC2 as-is but does not address database HA. ECS Anywhere adds unnecessary containerization overhead for a straightforward .NET migration.',rule:'Homogeneous DB migration = DMS + RDS same engine type. .NET app on AWS = Elastic Beanstalk (managed Multi-AZ). Refactoring = code changes, not replatform.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_16',category:'Storage',question:'A company has a web application that uses Internet Information Services (IIS) for Windows Server. A file share is used to store the application data on the network-attached storage of the company’s on-premises data center. To achieve a highly available system, the company plans to migrate the application and file share to AWS. Which of the following can be used to fulfill this requirement?',choices:['A|Migrate the existing file share configuration to AWS Storage Gateway.','B|Migrate the existing file share configuration to Amazon FSx for Windows File Server.','C|Migrate the existing file share configuration to Amazon EFS.','D|Migrate the existing file share configuration to Amazon EBS.'],correct:'A',answer:'Migrate the existing file share configuration to Amazon FSx for Windows File Server — it provides a fully managed Windows-native SMB file system that supports IIS and Windows applications without code changes. FSx for Windows integrates with Active Directory, supports DFS namespaces and replication, and is accessible via the SMB protocol natively used by Windows servers.',why:'Amazon FSx for Windows File Server provides fully managed Microsoft Windows file servers, backed by a fully native Windows file system. Amazon FSx for Windows File Server has the features, performance, and compatibility to easily lift and shift enterprise applications to the AWS Cloud. It is accessible from Windows, Linux, and macOS compute instances and devices.',trap:'The option that says: Refactor the application to .NET Core and run it as a serverless container service using Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) with AWS Fargate is incorrect.',rule:'Perform a homogeneous migration by moving the Oracle database to Amazon RDS for Oracle in a Multi-AZ deployment using AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS).',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_17',category:'S3',question:'A company collects atmospheric data such as temperature, air pressure, and humidity from different countries. Each site location is equipped with various weather instruments and a high-speed Internet connection. The average collected data in each location is around 500 GB and will be analyzed by a weather forecasting application hosted in Northern Virginia. The Solutions Architect must determine the fastest way to aggregate all the data. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Enable Transfer Acceleration in the destination bucket and upload the collected data using Multipart Upload.','B|Upload the data to the closest Amazon S3 bucket. Set up a cross-region replication and copy the objects to the destination bucket.','C|Use AWS Snowball Edge to transfer large amounts of data.','D|Set up a Site-to-Site VPN connection.'],correct:'A',answer:'S3 Transfer Acceleration speeds up uploads over long distances by routing through CloudFront edge locations (Choice A). Uploading to the nearest S3 bucket then using Cross-Region Replication to copy to the central bucket also reduces latency and uses AWS backbone for the replication hop (Choice B). Both approaches avoid slow long-haul internet transfers for geographically distributed sensors.',why:'Transfer Acceleration charges a per-GB premium but delivers the upload immediately to the destination bucket via the edge network. CRR (Choice B) requires uploading to a regional bucket first, which is faster for local sensors, then asynchronously replicating to the central store. Multipart Upload (used with Choice A) splits large files into parts uploaded in parallel, improving throughput and allowing retry of failed parts. Both reduce end-to-end latency compared to direct long-distance S3 PUT requests.',trap:'Snowball Edge (Choice C) is for bulk offline data transfer — petabyte-scale one-time migrations, not continuous streaming sensor data. Site-to-Site VPN (Choice D) provides network connectivity but does not accelerate S3 uploads or reduce S3 transfer latency; data still traverses the public internet segment from the VPN endpoint to S3.',rule:'Fast S3 upload over long distance = S3 Transfer Acceleration (CloudFront edge routing) OR upload to nearest S3 then CRR. Not Snowball (offline batch). Not VPN (does not accelerate S3).',keywords:'Run logic at CloudFront edge → Lambda@Edge. Reduces latency by executing near user.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_18',category:'Kinesis',question:'A company wishes to query data that resides in multiple AWS accounts from a central data lake. Each account has its own Amazon S3 bucket that stores data unique to its business function. Access to the data lake must be granted based on user roles. Which solution will minimize overhead and costs while meeting the required access patterns?',choices:['A|Use AWS Lake Formation to consolidate data from multiple accounts into a single account.','B|Use Amazon Data Firehose to consolidate data from multiple accounts into a single account.','C|Create a scheduled AWS Lambda function using Amazon EventBridge for transferring data from multiple accounts to the S3 buckets of the central account.','D|Use AWS Control Tower to centrally manage each account\'s S3 buckets.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Lake Formation is a service that makes it easy to set up a secure data lake in days. A data lake is a centralized, curated, and secured repository that stores all your data, both in its original form and prepared for analysis. A data lake enables you to break down data silos and combine different types of analytics to gain insights and guide better business decisions.',why:'Amazon S3 forms the storage layer for Lake Formation. If you already use S3, you typically begin by registering existing S3 buckets that contain your data. Lake Formation creates new buckets for the data lake and imports data into them. AWS always stores this data in your account, and only you have direct access to it.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon Data Firehose to consolidate data from multiple accounts into a single account is incorrect because setting up a Data Firehose in each and every account to move data into a single location is just costly and impractical. A better approach is to set up cross-account sharing which is free with AWS Lake Formation.',rule:'AWS always stores this data in your account, and only you have direct access to it. Not Data Firehose.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_19',category:'Route 53',question:'A global IT company with offices around the world has multiple AWS accounts. To improve efficiency and drive costs down, the Chief Information Officer (CIO) wants to set up a solution that centrally manages their AWS resources. This will allow them to procure AWS resources centrally and share resources such as AWS Transit Gateways, AWS License Manager configurations, or Amazon Route 53 Resolver rules across their various accounts. As the Solutions Architect, which combination of options should you implement in this scenario? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use the AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM) service to easily and securely share your resources with your AWS accounts.','B|Use the AWS Identity and Access Management service to set up cross-account access that will easily and securely share your resources with your AWS accounts.','C|Use AWS Control Tower to easily and securely share your resources with your AWS accounts.','D|Consolidate all of the company\'s accounts using AWS Organizations.','E|Consolidate all of the company\'s accounts using AWS ParallelCluster.'],correct:'ADE',answer:'AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM) is a service that enables you to easily and securely share AWS resources with any AWS account or within your AWS Organization. You can share AWS Transit Gateways, Subnets, AWS License Manager configurations, and Amazon Route 53 Resolver rules resources with RAM.',why:'Many organizations use multiple accounts to create administrative or billing isolation, and limit the impact of errors. RAM eliminates the need to create duplicate resources in multiple accounts, reducing the operational overhead of managing those resources in every single account you own.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS Control Tower to easily and securely share your resources with your AWS accounts is incorrect because AWS Control Tower simply offers the easiest way to set up and govern a new, secure, multi-account AWS environment. This is not the most suitable service to use to securely share your resources across AWS accounts or within your Organization. You have to use AWS Resources Access Manager (RAM) instead.',rule:'set up a solution that centrally manages their aws → AWS Resource, Access Manager. Not AWS Control.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_20',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to launch an Amazon EC2 instance in a private subnet for its internal corporate web portal. For security purposes, the EC2 instance must send data to Amazon DynamoDB and Amazon S3 via private endpoints that don\'t pass through the public Internet. Which of the following can meet the above requirements?',choices:['A|Use a DynamoDB VPC endpoint and an S3 VPC endpoint to route all access to these services via private endpoints.','B|Use AWS VPN CloudHub to route all access to S3 and DynamoDB via private endpoints.','C|Enable DynamoDB Encryption at Rest with the default AWS-managed key and S3 Server-Side Encryption with the default AWS KMS key to route all traffic to DynamoDB and S3 via private endpoints.','D|Use AWS Direct Connect to route all access to S3 and DynamoDB via private endpoints.'],correct:'ABCD',answer:'A VPC endpoint allows you to privately connect your VPC to supported AWS and VPC endpoint services powered by AWS PrivateLink without needing an Internet gateway, NAT computer, VPN connection, or AWS Direct Connect connection. Instances in your VPC do not require public IP addresses to communicate with resources in the service.',why:'Workflow diagram showing an EC2 instance accessing DynamoDB through a router and VPC endpoint only. In the scenario, you are asked to configure private endpoints to send data to Amazon DynamoDB and Amazon S3 without accessing the public Internet. Among the options given, VPC endpoint is the most suitable service that will allow you to use private IP addresses to access both DynamoDB and S3 without any exposure to the public internet.',trap:'The option that says: Enable DynamoDB Encryption at Rest with the default AWS-managed key and S3 Server-Side Encryption with the default AWS KMS key to route all traffic to DynamoDB and S3 via private endpoints is incorrect because encryption at rest does not affect the traffic routing. Encryption manages data security but does not control how traffic is routed between services.',rule:'Workflow diagram showing an EC2 instance accessing DynamoDB through a router and VPC endpoint only.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_21',category:'IAM',question:'There was an incident in a production environment where user data stored in an Amazon S3 bucket was accidentally deleted by a Junior DevOps Engineer. The issue was escalated to management, and after a few days, an instruction was given to improve the security and protection of AWS resources. What combination of the following options will protect the S3 objects in the bucket from both accidental deletion and overwriting? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Enable Versioning','B|Provide access to S3 data strictly through pre-signed URL only','C|Disallow S3 Delete using an IAM bucket policy','D|Enable S3 Intelligent-Tiering','E|Enable Multi-Factor Authentication Delete'],correct:'AE',answer:'The correct answers are: Enable Versioning (preserves all object versions so deleted objects can be recovered) and Enable MFA Delete (requires a second authentication factor to permanently delete a version or change versioning state).',why:'S3 Versioning keeps every version of every object in a bucket. When a user deletes an object, S3 inserts a delete marker rather than permanently removing it — the previous version is still recoverable. MFA Delete adds a second layer: permanently deleting a specific version or disabling versioning requires both valid AWS credentials AND a valid MFA code, making accidental or malicious permanent deletion extremely difficult.',trap:'Pre-signed URLs control who can access objects but do not prevent deletion by authorized users. Disallowing S3 Delete via bucket policy would prevent legitimate deletions entirely. S3 Intelligent-Tiering manages storage cost tiers — it has no role in preventing accidental deletion or enabling recovery.',rule:'Protect S3 from accidental deletion = Versioning (recoverable delete markers) + MFA Delete (requires MFA to permanently delete). Pre-signed URLs = access control, not deletion protection.',keywords:'S3 object protection: versioning keeps all versions. MFA Delete requires MFA to delete versions.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_22',category:'Database',question:'An application that records weather data every minute is deployed in a fleet of Amazon EC2 Spot instances and uses a MySQL RDS database instance. Currently, there is only one Amazon RDS instance running in one Availability Zone. The database needs to be improved to ensure high availability by enabling synchronous data replication to another RDS instance. Which of the following performs synchronous data replication in RDS?',choices:['A|RDS DB instance running as a Multi-AZ deployment','B|RDS Read Replica','C|Amazon DynamoDB Read Replica','D|Amazon CloudFront running as a Multi-AZ deployment'],correct:'A',answer:'When you create or modify your DB instance to run as a Multi-AZ deployment, Amazon RDS automatically provisions and maintains a synchronous standby replica in a different Availability Zone.',why:'Multi-AZ creates a synchronous standby replica in a different AZ. Every write to the primary is simultaneously replicated to the standby before the application receives acknowledgment. If the primary fails, RDS automatically promotes the standby and updates the endpoint DNS — typically in 1-2 minutes. RPO = 0 (no data loss). RTO = 1-2 minutes. The standby cannot serve read traffic while the primary is healthy.',trap:'RDS Read Replica is incorrect as a Read Replica primarily provides an asynchronous replication instead of synchronous.',rule:'RDS Multi-AZ = synchronous replication + automatic failover. CNAME switches to standby in 1-2 min. Read Replica = asynchronous replication (possible lag). Multi-AZ = HA. Read Replica = asynchronous, read-only, used for read scaling. Multi-AZ = synchronous, HA failover.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_23',category:'CloudWatch',question:'An online cryptocurrency exchange platform is hosted in AWS, utilizing an Amazon ECS Cluster and Amazon RDS in a Multi-AZ Deployments configuration. The application heavily uses the RDS instance to process complex read and write database operations. To maintain reliability, availability, and performance, it is necessary to closely monitor how the different processes or threads on a DB instance use the CPU, including the percentage of CPU bandwidth and total memory consumed by each process. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to monitor the database properly?',choices:['A|Use Amazon CloudWatch to monitor the CPU Utilization of your database.','B|Create a script that collects and publishes custom metrics to Amazon CloudWatch, which tracks the real-time CPU Utilization of the RDS instance, and then set up a custom CloudWatch dashboard to view the metrics.','C|Enable Enhanced Monitoring in RDS.','D|Check the CPU% and MEM% metrics which are readily available in the RDS console that shows the percentage of the CPU bandwidth and total memory consumed by each database process of your RDS instance.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon RDS offers a powerful feature known as Enhanced Monitoring, which provides detailed metrics in real-time about the operating system (OS) underlying your database instances. This feature allows users to monitor performance at a granular level through the AWS Management Console or by accessing the Enhanced Monitoring JSON output via CloudWatch Logs.',why:'Enhanced Monitoring differs from standard CloudWatch metrics in that it gathers data directly from an agent installed on the instance, rather than from the hypervisor, which is used by CloudWatch. This distinction can lead to slight variations between the two sets of metrics.',trap:'The option that says: Check the CPU% and MEM% metrics which are readily available in the RDS console that shows the percentage of the CPU bandwidth and total memory consumed by each database process of your RDS instance is incorrect because the CPU% and MEM% metrics are not readily available in the Amazon RDS console, which is contrary to what is being stated in this option.',rule:'Enhanced Monitoring differs from standard CloudWatch metrics in that it gathers data directly from an agent installed on the instance, rathe Not Amazon RDS.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_24',category:'Database',question:'A Forex trading platform, which frequently processes and stores global financial data every minute, is hosted in an on-premises data center and uses an Oracle database. Due to a recent cooling problem in its data center, the company urgently needs to migrate its infrastructure to AWS to improve the performance of its applications. As the Solutions Architect, the responsibility is to ensure that the database is properly migrated and remains available in case of database server failure in the future, following AWS Prescriptive Guidance for database migration and high availability. Which combination of actions would meet the requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Launch an Oracle database instance in Amazon RDS with Recovery Manager (RMAN) enabled.','B|Convert the database schema using the AWS Schema Conversion Tool.','C|Create an Oracle database in Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployments.','D|Migrate the Oracle database to a non-cluster Amazon Aurora with a single instance.','E|Migrate the Oracle database to AWS using the AWS Database Migration Service'],correct:'CD',answer:'The correct answers are: Create an Oracle database in Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployments (provides HA and automatic failover), and migrate the Oracle database to AWS using AWS Database Migration Service (handles the data migration).',why:'RDS Multi-AZ for Oracle creates a standby replica in a different AZ that receives synchronous replication. On failure, RDS automatically fails over by updating the CNAME — no manual intervention and no data loss. AWS DMS handles the actual data migration from on-premises Oracle to RDS, supporting ongoing CDC replication to minimize downtime.',trap:'RDS with Recovery Manager (RMAN) enabled uses Oracle-native backup tooling but RMAN alone does not provide Multi-AZ HA failover — that requires the Multi-AZ deployment configuration. AWS SCT converts schemas between different database engines — it does not migrate data. Migrating to single-instance Aurora loses the Oracle engine compatibility needed for an Oracle workload.',rule:'Oracle to RDS with HA = RDS Multi-AZ (auto failover) + DMS (migration). RMAN = Oracle backup tool, not HA. SCT = schema conversion only, not data migration.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_25',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to host a web application in an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances. The application will be used globally by users to upload and store several types of files. Based on user trends, files that are older than 2 years must be stored in a different storage class. The Solutions Architect of the company needs to create a cost-effective and scalable solution to store the old files yet still provide durability and high availability. Which of the following approach can be used to fulfill this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use Amazon S3 and create a lifecycle policy that will move the objects to S3 Glacier after 2 years.','B|Use Amazon EFS and create a lifecycle policy that will move the objects to EFS-IA after 2 years.','C|Use Amazon S3 and create a lifecycle policy that will move the objects to S3 Standard-IA after 2 years.','D|Use Amazon EBS volumes to store the files. Configure the Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM) to schedule snapshots of the volumes after 2 years.','E|Use a RAID 0 storage configuration that stripes multiple Amazon EBS volumes together to store the files. Configure the Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM) to schedule snapshots of the volumes after 2 years.'],correct:'AC',answer:'The correct answers are: Use Amazon S3 with a lifecycle policy to move objects to S3 Glacier after 2 years (for archival/lowest cost), and use Amazon S3 with a lifecycle policy to move objects to S3 Standard-IA after 2 years (for infrequent access at lower cost).',why:'S3 lifecycle policies support transitions to any storage class after a configurable number of days. Both S3 Glacier and S3 Standard-IA are valid targets for objects that are 2 years old (730 days). EFS lifecycle policies have a maximum transition period of 365 days — they cannot transition objects after 2 years, making EFS unsuitable. EBS with DLM schedules snapshots but does not transition data between storage tiers.',trap:'Amazon EFS lifecycle policies max out at 365 days — they cannot meet the 2-year (730 day) requirement. Amazon EBS DLM manages snapshot schedules but does not move data to cheaper storage tiers after 2 years. RAID 0 on EBS provides performance but no cost optimization or lifecycle management.',rule:'Move files after 2 years = S3 lifecycle policy (transitions S3 Glacier or S3 Standard-IA after 730 days). EFS lifecycle max = 365 days (cannot do 2 years). EBS DLM = snapshot schedules, not storage tiering.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_26',category:'Serverless',question:'An e-commerce company utilizes a regional Amazon API Gateway to host its public REST APIs. The API Gateway endpoint is accessed through a custom domain name set up with an Amazon Route 53 alias record. To support continuous improvement, the company intends to launch a new version of its APIs with enhanced features and performance optimizations. How can the company reduce customer disruption and ensure MINIMAL data loss during the update process in the MOST cost-effective way?',choices:['A|Create a new API Gateway with the updated version of the APIs in OpenAPI JSON or YAML file format, but keep the same custom domain name for the new API Gateway.','B|Implement a canary release deployment strategy for the API Gateway. Deploy the latest version of the APIs to a canary stage and direct a portion of the user traffic to this stage. Verify the new APIs. Gradually increase the traffic percentage, monitor for any issues, and, if successful, promote the canary stage to production.','C|Modify the existing API Gateway with the updated version of the APIs, but keep the same custom domain name for the new API Gateway by using the import-to-update operation in either overwrite or merge mode.','D|Implement a blue-green deployment strategy for the API Gateway, deploying the latest version of the APIs to the green environment. Route some user traffic to it, validate the new APIs, and once thoroughly validated, promote the green environment to production.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon API Gateway is a fully managed service that makes it easy for developers to create, publish, maintain, monitor, and secure APIs at any scale. It is a front door for your APIs, enabling you to design and implement scalable, highly available, and secure APIs.',why:'Implementing a canary release deployment strategy for the API Gateway is a great way to ensure your APIs remain stable and reliable. This strategy involves releasing a new version of your API to a small subset of users, allowing you to test the latest version in a controlled environment.',trap:'The option that says: Create a new API Gateway with the updated version of the APIs in OpenAPI JSON or YAML file format, but keep the same custom domain name for the new API Gateway is incorrect. Upgrading to a new API Gateway using an updated version of the APIs in OpenAPI JSON or YAML file format while keeping the same custom domain name can typically result in downtime and confusion during the switch. This is because of DNS propagation delays, which can negatively affect users and even lead to data loss.',rule:'Implementing a canary release deployment strategy for the API Gateway is a great way to ensure your APIs remain stable and reliable.',keywords:'S3/DynamoDB private VPC access → Gateway Endpoint (free). Other services → Interface Endpoint (PrivateLink).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_27',category:'S3',question:'A company plans to migrate its on-premises workload to AWS. The current architecture is composed of a Microsoft SharePoint server that uses a Windows shared file storage. The Solutions Architect needs to use a cloud storage solution that is highly available and can be integrated with Active Directory for access control and authentication. Which of the following options can satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Launch an Amazon EC2 Windows Server to mount a new Amazon S3 bucket as a file volume.','B|Create a file system using Amazon EFS and join it to an Active Directory domain.','C|Create a Network File System (NFS) file share using AWS Storage Gateway.','D|Create a file system using Amazon FSx for Windows File Server and join it to an Active Directory domain in AWS.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon FSx for Windows File Server provides fully managed, highly reliable, and scalable file storage that is accessible over the industry-standard Service Message Block (SMB) protocol. It is built on Windows Server, delivering a wide range of administrative features such as user quotas, end-user file restore, and Microsoft Active Directory (AD) integration.',why:'Amazon FSx works with Microsoft Active Directory to integrate with your existing Microsoft Windows environments. You have two options to provide user authentication and access control for your file system: AWS Managed Microsoft Active Directory and Self-managed Microsoft Active Directory. Take note that after you create an Active Directory configuration for a file system, you can\'t change that configuration.',trap:'The option that says: Create a file system using Amazon EFS and join it to an Active Directory domain is incorrect because Amazon EFS does not support Windows systems, only Linux OS. You should use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server instead to satisfy the requirement in the scenario.',rule:'Take note that after you create an Active Directory configuration for a file system, you can\'t change that configuration. Not Amazon EFS.',keywords:'Windows SMB file shares in AWS → FSx for Windows File Server.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_28',category:'S3',question:'An organization requires a persistent block storage volume to support its mission-critical workloads. The backup data will be stored in an object storage service and, after 30 days, transitioned to an archival storage service for long-term retention. What should be done to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Attach an Amazon EBS volume in your Amazon EC2 instance. Use Amazon S3 to store your backup data and configure a lifecycle policy to transition your objects to S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval.','B|Attach an Amazon EBS volume in your Amazon EC2 instance. Use Amazon S3 to store your backup data and configure a lifecycle policy to transition your objects to S3 One Zone-IA.','C|Attach an instance store volume in your existing Amazon EC2 instance. Use Amazon S3 to store your backup data and configure a lifecycle policy to transition your objects to S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval.','D|Attach an instance store volume in your Amazon EC2 instance. Use Amazon S3 to store your backup data and configure a lifecycle policy to transition your objects to S3 One Zone-IA.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon EBS Provisioned IOPS (io1/io2) provides the highest-performance block storage for I/O-intensive workloads like databases. It supports up to 64,000 IOPS per volume on Nitro-based instances and sub-millisecond latency, making it suitable for mission-critical applications requiring consistent performance.',why:'EBS io1/io2 Block Express volumes are specifically designed for throughput-sensitive and latency-sensitive workloads. Unlike gp2/gp3 which use a credit-based burst model, io1/io2 delivers the provisioned IOPS consistently regardless of volume size. Multi-Attach on io1/io2 lets you attach one volume to up to 16 Nitro-based instances simultaneously — useful for clustered databases. EBS data persists independently of the EC2 instance lifecycle.',trap:'The option that says: Launch an Oracle database instance in Amazon RDS with Recovery Manager (RMAN) enabled is incorrect because Oracle RMAN is not supported in RDS.',rule:'Create an Oracle database in Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployments.',keywords:'RDS high availability + auto failover = Multi-AZ. Standby cannot serve reads. Sync replication.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_29',category:'Database',question:'A suite of web applications is hosted in an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances across three Availability Zones and is configured with default settings. There is an Application Load Balancer that forwards the request to the respective target group on the URL path. The scale-in policy has been triggered due to the low number of incoming traffic to the application. Which EC2 instance will be the first one to be terminated by the Auto Scaling group?',choices:['A|The EC2 instance which has the least number of user sessions','B|The EC2 instance which has been running for the longest time','C|The EC2 instance launched from the oldest launch template.','D|The instance will be randomly selected by the Auto Scaling group'],correct:'C',answer:'The default ASG termination policy first identifies the AZ with the most instances, then within that AZ selects the instance using the oldest launch configuration (or template). This gradually removes instances using stale configurations. If tied, it selects the instance closest to the next billing hour to minimise waste.',why:'The default termination policy is designed to help ensure that your network architecture spans Availability Zones evenly.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon EFS and create a lifecycle policy that will move the objects to EFS-IA after 2 years is incorrect because the maximum days of EFS lifecycle policies is only up to 365 days. Therefore, it still does not meet the requirement of moving files older than 2 years or 730 days.',rule:'Use Amazon S3 and create a lifecycle policy that will move the objects to S3 Glacier after 2 years.',keywords:'Auto-move S3 objects = lifecycle policy. Min 30 days before Standard→Standard-IA transition.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_31',category:'Database',question:'An online shopping platform is hosted on an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 Spot instances and utilizes Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL as its database. It is required to optimize database workloads in the cluster by directing the production traffic to high-capacity instances and routing the reporting queries from the internal staff to the low-capacity instances. Which is the most suitable configuration for the application as well as the Aurora database cluster to achieve this requirement?',choices:['A|Configure your application to use the reader endpoint for both production traffic and reporting queries, which will enable your Aurora database to automatically perform load-balancing among all the Aurora Replicas.','B|In your application, use the instance endpoint of your Aurora database to handle the incoming production traffic and use the cluster endpoint to handle reporting queries.','C|Create a custom endpoint in Aurora based on the specified criteria for the production traffic and another custom endpoint to handle the reporting queries.','D|Do nothing since by default, Aurora will automatically direct the production traffic to your high-capacity instances and the reporting queries to your low-capacity instances.'],correct:'C',answer:'Amazon Aurora typically involves a cluster of DB instances instead of a single instance. Each connection is handled by a specific DB instance. When you connect to an Aurora cluster, the host name and port that you specify point to an intermediate handler called an endpoint. Aurora uses the endpoint mechanism to abstract these connections.',why:'For certain Aurora tasks, different instances or groups of instances perform different roles. For example, the primary instance handles all data definition language (DDL) and data manipulation language (DML) statements. Up to 15 Aurora Replicas handle read-only query traffic.',trap:'The option that says: In your application, use the instance endpoint of your Aurora database to handle the incoming production traffic and use the cluster endpoint to handle reporting queries is incorrect because a cluster endpoint (also known as a writer endpoint) for an Aurora DB cluster simply connects to the current primary DB instance for that DB cluster. This endpoint can perform write operations in the database such as DDL statements, which is perfect for handling production traffic but not suitable for handling queries for reporting since there will be no write database operations that will be sent. Moreover, the endpoint does not point to lower-capacity or high-capacity instances as per the requirement. A better solution for this is to use a custom endpoint.',rule:'Up to 15 Aurora Replicas handle read-only query traffic.',keywords:'Non-production / fault-tolerant / batch → Spot Instances (70-90% discount, can be interrupted).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_32',category:'Database',question:'A company is experiencing repeated outages in the Availability Zone where its Amazon RDS database instance is deployed, resulting in a complete loss of access to the database during each incident. Which solution should be implemented to prevent losing database access if this occurs again?',choices:['A|Make a snapshot of the database','B|Enable Multi-AZ failover','C|Increase the database instance size','D|Create a read replica'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon RDS Multi-AZ deployments are designed to enhance the availability and durability of database instances, making them well-suited for production workloads. When you enable Multi-AZ failover, Amazon RDS automatically creates a standby replica in a different Availability Zone (AZ) and synchronously replicates data from the primary instance.',why:'In the event of planned maintenance or an unexpected failure such as an Availability Zone outage or hardware issue, Amazon RDS automatically performs a failover to the standby instance. This process is fully managed by Amazon RDS and does not require manual intervention, helping to minimize downtime and maintain business continuity. For Amazon Aurora, the failover involves promoting a replica to become the new writer instance.',trap:'The option that says: Make a snapshot of the database is incorrect because snapshots are typically used for backup and disaster recovery, not for maintaining high availability. A snapshot allows you to restore a database to a specific point in time, but it does not prevent downtime or provide continuous access during an Availability Zone outage.',rule:'RDS Multi-AZ = synchronous replication, automatic failover, zero RPO. Standby = passive (no reads). Read Replica = asynchronous replication, manual promotion, used for read scaling. Multi-AZ standby cannot serve reads. Failover time ~1-2 min.',keywords:'Memory/disk/swap metrics = NOT default CW. Must install CloudWatch Agent.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_33',category:'Storage',question:'A company has recently migrated its microservices-based application to Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS). As part of the migration, the company must ensure that all sensitive configuration data and credentials, such as database passwords and API keys, are stored securely and encrypted within the Amazon EKS cluster\'s etcd key-value store. What is the most suitable solution to meet the company\'s requirements?',choices:['A|Enable secret encryption with a new AWS KMS key on an existing Amazon EKS cluster to encrypt sensitive data stored in the EKS cluster\'s etcd key-value store.','B|Use AWS Secrets Manager with a new AWS KMS key to securely manage and store sensitive data within the EKS cluster\'s etcd key-value store.','C|Enable default Amazon EBS volume encryption for the account with a new AWS KMS key to ensure encryption of sensitive data within the Amazon EKS cluster.','D|Use Amazon EKS default options and the Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) Container Storage Interface (CSI) driver as an add-on to securely store sensitive data within the Amazon EKS cluster.'],correct:'ABCD',answer:'Enabling secret encryption with a new AWS Key Management Service (KMS) key in an existing Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) cluster is critical to securing sensitive data stored in the cluster\'s etcd key-value store. Amazon EKS is a service for running and managing containerized applications, storing configuration data and secrets, etc., and is a distributed data store.',why:'The process involves creating an AWS KMS key specifically for the EKS cluster and configuring the cluster to encrypt secrets before they are saved in etcd. This setup ensures that all sensitive information within the etcd database is encrypted at rest, enhancing data security.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS Secrets Manager with a new AWS KMS key to securely manage and store sensitive data within the EKS cluster\'s etcd key-value store is incorrect. AWS Secrets Manager is a powerful tool for managing secrets but it doesn\'t directly address encrypting data within the etcd key-value store of an EKS cluster. Secrets Manager is more about managing and retrieving secrets rather than encrypting data within etcd.',rule:'Encryption → AWS KMS key on an existi, Amazon EKS cluster to encrypt sensiti. Not AWS Secrets.',keywords:'ECS service connect: service discovery and networking for microservices. App Mesh = Envoy sidecar proxy.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_34',category:'Database',question:'A Solutions Architect is designing a highly available relational database solution to mitigate the risk of a multi-region failure. The database must meet a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 1 second and a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than 1 minute. The architect needs a disaster recovery plan that enables automatic cross-region replication with minimal data loss and rapid recovery in the event of a failure. Which AWS feature best fulfills this requirement?',choices:['A|Amazon DynamoDB Global table','B|Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with cross-region read replicas','C|Amazon Timestream for Analytics','D|Amazon Aurora Global Database'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Aurora Global Database is designed for globally distributed applications, allowing a single Amazon Aurora database to span multiple AWS regions. It replicates your data with no impact on database performance, enables fast local reads with low latency in each region, and provides disaster recovery from region-wide outages.',why:'Aurora Global Database supports storage-based replication that has a latency of less than 1 second. If there is an unplanned outage, one of the secondary regions you assigned can be promoted to read and write capabilities in less than 1 minute. This feature is called Cross-Region Disaster Recovery. An RPO of 1 second and an RTO of less than 1 minute provide you a strong foundation for a global business continuity plan.',trap:'The option that says: Amazon DynamoDB Global table is incorrect because while this supports multi-region, fully replicated tables with low latency, it\'s more suitable for NoSQL workloads, not relational databases.',rule:'Aurora Global Database supports storage-based replication that has a latency of less than 1 second.',keywords:'Near-zero RPO + global replication → Aurora Global Database. Secondary region read-only.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_35',category:'EC2',question:'A company needs to deploy at least two Amazon EC2 instances to support the normal workloads of its application and automatically scale up to six EC2 instances to handle the peak load. The architecture must be highly available and fault-tolerant as it is processing mission-critical workloads. As a Solutions Architect, what should be done to meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Create an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and set the minimum capacity to 2 and the maximum capacity to 6. Deploy 4 instances in Availability Zone A.','B|Create an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and set the minimum capacity to 4 and the maximum capacity to 6. Deploy 2 instances in Availability Zone A and another 2 instances in Availability Zone B.','C|Create an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and set the minimum capacity to 2 and the maximum capacity to 6. Use 2 Availability Zones and deploy 1 instance for each AZ.','D|Create an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and set the minimum capacity to 2 and the maximum capacity to 4. Deploy 2 instances in Availability Zone A and 2 instances in Availability Zone B.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling helps ensure that you have the correct number of Amazon EC2 instances available to handle the load for your application. You create collections of EC2 instances, called Auto Scaling groups. You can specify the minimum number of instances in each Auto Scaling group, and Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling ensures that your group never goes below this size.',why:'To achieve highly available and fault-tolerant architecture for your applications, you must deploy all your instances in different Availability Zones. This will help you isolate your resources if an outage occurs. Take note that to achieve fault tolerance, you need to have redundant resources in place to avoid any system degradation in the event of a server fault or an Availability Zone outage.',trap:'The option that says: Create an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances and set the minimum capacity to 2 and the maximum capacity to 6. Deploy 4 instances in Availability Zone A is incorrect because the instances are only deployed in a single Availability Zone. It cannot protect your applications and data from datacenter or AZ failures.',rule:'HA → EC2, EC2. Not Auto Scaling.',keywords:'Auto-move S3 objects = lifecycle policy. Min 30 days before Standard→Standard-IA transition.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_36',category:'S3',question:'A company has a hybrid cloud architecture that connects its on-premises data center and cloud infrastructure in AWS. It requires a durable storage backup for its corporate documents stored on-premises and a local cache that provides low-latency access to recently accessed data to reduce data egress charges. The documents must be stored on and retrieved from AWS via the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol. These files must be immediately accessible within minutes for six months and archived for another decade to meet data compliance. Which of the following is the best and most cost-effective approach to implement in this scenario?',choices:['A|Launch a new file gateway that connects to your on-premises data center using AWS Storage Gateway. Upload the documents to the file gateway and set up a lifecycle policy to move the data into Glacier for data archival.','B|Launch a new tape gateway that connects to your on-premises data center using AWS Storage Gateway. Upload the documents to the tape gateway and set up a lifecycle policy to move the data into Glacier for archival.','C|Establish a Direct Connect connection to integrate your on-premises network to your VPC. Upload the documents on Amazon EBS Volumes and use a lifecycle policy to automatically move the EBS snapshots to an Amazon S3 bucket, and then later to Glacier for archival.','D|Use AWS DataSync to transfer all files from the on-premises network directly to an Amazon S3 bucket, and set up a lifecycle policy to move the data into Glacier for archival.'],correct:'A',answer:'A file gateway supports a file interface into Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) and combines a service and a virtual software appliance. By using this combination, you can store and retrieve objects in Amazon S3 using industry-standard file protocols such as Network File System (NFS) and Server Message Block (SMB).',why:'Storage Gateway File Gateway caches recently accessed data on-premises for low-latency reads while durably storing files as S3 objects. The NFS/SMB interface means your on-premises applications see a standard file share — no code changes needed. S3 storage classes (Standard, IA, Glacier) are selectable per S3 lifecycle rule applied to the bucket. File Gateway also integrates with Active Directory for SMB access control.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a new tape gateway that connects to your on-premises data center using AWS Storage Gateway. Upload the documents to the tape gateway and set up a lifecycle policy to move the data into Glacier for archival is incorrect because although tape gateways provide cost-effective and durable archive backup data in Amazon Glacier, it does not meet the criteria of being retrievable immediately within minutes. It also doesn\'t maintain a local cache that provides low latency access to the recently accessed data and reduce data egress charges. Thus, it is still better to set up a file gateway instead.',rule:'Backup → AWS Storage Gateway, AWS Storage Gateway. Not AWS Storage.',keywords:'On-premises file access backed by S3 = Storage Gateway File Gateway (ongoing hybrid).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_38',category:'S3',question:'An online medical system hosted in AWS stores sensitive Personally Identifiable Information (PII) of the users in an Amazon S3 bucket. Both the master keys and the unencrypted data should never be sent to AWS to comply with the strict compliance and regulatory requirements of the company. Which S3 encryption technique should the Architect use?',choices:['A|Use S3 client-side encryption with an AWS KMS key.','B|Use S3 client-side encryption with a client-side master key.','C|Use S3 server-side encryption with an AWS KMS key.','D|Use S3 server-side encryption with customer provided key.'],correct:'B',answer:'Client-side encryption is the act of encrypting data before sending it to Amazon S3. To enable client-side encryption, you have the following options: Use a client-side master key or use AWS KMS-managed customer master keys (CMKs).',why:'When using an AWS KMS key to enable client-side data encryption, you provide an AWS KMS key identifier (KeyId) to AWS. On the other hand, when you use client-side master key for client-side data encryption, your client-side master keys and your unencrypted data are never sent to AWS. It\'s important that you safely manage your encryption keys because if you lose them, you can\'t decrypt your data.',trap:'The option that says: Use S3 client-side encryption with an AWS KMS key is incorrect because, in client-side encryption with a KMS key, you provide an AWS KMS key identifier (KeyId) to AWS. The scenario clearly indicates that both the master keys and the unencrypted data should never be sent to AWS.',rule:'Encryption → AWS KMS key, AWS KMS key. Not AWS KMS.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_39',category:'S3',question:'A Solutions Architect is hosting a website in an Amazon S3 bucket named tutorialsdojo. The users load the website using the following URL: http://tutorialsdojo.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com. A new requirement has been introduced to add JavaScript on the webpages to make authenticated HTTP GET requests against the same bucket using the S3 API endpoint (tutorialsdojo.s3.amazonaws.com). However, upon testing, the web browser blocks JavaScript from allowing those requests. Which of the following options is the MOST suitable solution to implement for this scenario?',choices:['A|Enable cross-account access.','B|Enable Cross-Zone Load Balancing.','C|Enable Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) configuration in the bucket.','D|Enable Cross-Region Replication (CRR).'],correct:'C',answer:'Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) defines a way for client web applications that are loaded in one domain to interact with resources in a different domain. With CORS support, you can build rich client-side web applications with Amazon S3 and selectively allow cross-origin access to your Amazon S3 resources.',why:'CORS OverviewSuppose that you are hosting a website in an Amazon S3 bucket named your-website and your users load the website endpoint http://your-website.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com. Now you want to use JavaScript on the webpages that are stored in this bucket to be able to make authenticated GET and PUT requests against the same bucket by using the Amazon S3 API endpoint for the bucket, your-website.s3.amazonaws.com.',trap:'The option that says: Enable cross-account access is incorrect because cross-account access is just a feature in IAM and not in Amazon S3.',rule:'CORS OverviewSuppose that you are hosting a website in an Amazon S3 bucket named your-website and your users load the website endpoint http: Not Amazon S3.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_40',category:'IAM',question:'A company is designing a banking portal that uses Amazon ElastiCache for Redis as its distributed session management component. To secure session data and ensure that Cloud Engineers must authenticate before executing Redis commands, specifically MULTI EXEC commands, the system should enforce strong authentication by requiring users to enter a password. Additionally, access should be managed with long-lived credentials while supporting robust security practices. Which of the following actions should be taken to meet the above requirement?',choices:['A|Generate an IAM authentication token using AWS credentials and provide this token as a password.','B|Set up a Redis replication group and enable the AtRestEncryptionEnabled parameter.','C|Authenticate the users using Redis AUTH by creating a new Redis Cluster with both the --transit-encryption-enabled and --auth-token parameters enabled.','D|Enable the in-transit encryption for Redis replication groups.'],correct:'C',answer:'Using Redis AUTH command can improve data security by requiring the user to enter a password before they are granted permission to execute Redis commands on a password-protected Redis server.',why:'To require that users enter a password on a password-protected Redis server, include the parameter --auth-token with the correct password when you create your replication group or cluster and on all subsequent commands to the replication group or cluster.',trap:'The option that says: Set up a Redis replication group and enable the AtRestEncryptionEnabled parameter is incorrect because the Redis At-Rest Encryption feature only secures the data inside the in-memory data store. You have to use Redis AUTH option instead.',rule:'ElastiCache Redis security: AUTH token (password at connection) + in-transit encryption (TLS) + at-rest encryption (KMS). Auth token requires TLS to be enabled. Set --auth-token at cluster creation time. TOKEN cannot be changed after creation — cluster must be recreated.',keywords:'sub-millisecond / in-memory caching → ElastiCache. Frequently read, rarely changes → cache it.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_41',category:'Database',question:'A company is in the process of migrating their applications to AWS. One of their systems requires a database that can scale globally and handle frequent schema changes. The application should not have any downtime or performance issues whenever there is a schema change in the database. It should also provide a low latency response to high-traffic queries. Which is the most suitable database solution to use to achieve this requirement? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|An Amazon RDS instance in Multi-AZ Deployments configuration','B|Amazon DynamoDB','C|An Amazon Aurora database with Read Replicas','D|Redshift'],correct:'ABC',answer:'Before we proceed in answering this question, we must first be clear with the actual definition of a "schema". Basically, the english definition of a schema is: a representation of a plan or theory in the form of an outline or model.',why:'Just think of a schema as the "structure" or a "model" of your data in your database. Since the scenario requires that the schema, or the structure of your data, changes frequently, then you have to pick a database which provides a non-rigid and flexible way of adding or removing new types of data. This is a classic example of choosing between a relational database and non-relational (NoSQL) database.',trap:'Redshift is incorrect because it is primarily used for OLAP systems.',rule:'Flexible schema (changes frequently) = NoSQL database. RDS Multi-AZ and Aurora = relational (fixed schema). DynamoDB = schemaless, flexible attributes per item. Aurora with Read Replicas is relational SQL — also rigid schema. Choose DynamoDB when schema evolves frequently.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_42',category:'Serverless',question:'A software development company is using serverless computing with AWS Lambda to build and run applications without having to set up or manage servers. The company has a Lambda function that connects to a MongoDB Atlas, which is a popular Database as a Service (DBaaS) platform, and also uses a third-party API to fetch certain data for its application. One of the developers was instructed to create the environment variables for the MongoDB database hostname, username, and password, as well as the API credentials that will be used by the Lambda function for DEV, SIT, UAT, and PROD environments. Considering that the Lambda function is storing sensitive database and API credentials, how can this information be secured to prevent other developers on the team, or anyone, from seeing these credentials in plain text? Select the best option that provides maximum security.',choices:['A|There is no need to do anything because, by default, Lambda already encrypts the environment variables using the AWS Key Management Service.','B|Enable SSL encryption that leverages on AWS CloudHSM to store and encrypt the sensitive information.','C|Lambda does not provide encryption for the environment variables. Deploy your code to an Amazon EC2 instance instead.','D|Create a new AWS KMS key and use it to enable encryption helpers that leverage on AWS Key Management Service to store and encrypt the sensitive information.'],correct:'D',answer:'When you create or update Lambda functions that use environment variables, AWS Lambda encrypts them using the AWS Key Management Service. When your Lambda function is invoked, those values are decrypted and made available to the Lambda code.',why:'Lambda encrypts environment variables by default with an AWS-managed key (aws/lambda). For tighter control, you provide your own KMS CMK and use the Lambda encryption helper to encrypt sensitive values before storing them as environment variables. At runtime, the Lambda function decrypts the values using the SDK and the CMK. This means the plaintext values are never stored anywhere — only the ciphertext is in the Lambda configuration. CloudTrail logs every KMS Decrypt call for auditability.',trap:'The option that says: There is no need to do anything because, by default, Lambda already encrypts the environment variables using the AWS Key Management Service is incorrect. Although Lambda encrypts the environment variables in your function by default, the sensitive information would still be visible to other users who have access to the Lambda console. This is because Lambda uses a default KMS key to encrypt the variables, which is usually accessible by other users. The best option in this scenario is to use encryption helpers to secure your environment variables.',rule:'However, if you wish to use encryption helpers and use KMS to encrypt environment variables after your Lambda function is created, you must update the function to use the new environment variable holding the encrypted value.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_43',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A payment processing company plans to migrate its on-premises application to an Amazon EC2 instance. An IPv6 CIDR block is attached to the company’s Amazon VPC. Strict security policy mandates that the production VPC must only allow outbound communication over IPv6 between the instance and the internet but should prevent the internet from initiating an inbound IPv6 connection. The new architecture should also allow traffic flow inspection and traffic filtering. What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?',choices:['A|Launch the EC2 instance to a public subnet and attach an Internet Gateway to the VPC to allow outbound IPv6 communication to the internet. Use Traffic Mirroring to set up the required rules for traffic inspection and traffic filtering.','B|Launch the EC2 instance to a private subnet and attach AWS PrivateLink interface endpoint to the VPC to control outbound IPv6 communication to the internet. Use Amazon GuardDuty to set up the required rules for traffic inspection and traffic filtering.','C|Launch the EC2 instance to a private subnet and attach a NAT Gateway to the VPC to allow outbound IPv6 communication to the internet. Use AWS Firewall Manager to set up the required rules for traffic inspection and traffic filtering.','D|Launch the EC2 instance to a private subnet and attach an Egress-Only Internet Gateway to the VPC to allow outbound IPv6 communication to the internet. Use AWS Network Firewall to set up the required rules for traffic inspection and traffic filtering.'],correct:'B',answer:'An egress-only internet gateway is a horizontally scaled, redundant, and highly available VPC component that allows outbound communication over IPv6 from instances in your VPC to the internet and prevents it from initiating an IPv6 connection with your instances.',why:'A subnet is a range of IP addresses in your VPC. You can launch AWS resources into a specified subnet. Use a public subnet for resources that must be connected to the internet and a private subnet for resources that won\'t be connected to the internet.',trap:'The option that says: Launch the EC2 instance to a private subnet and attach AWS PrivateLink interface endpoint to the VPC to control outbound IPv6 communication to the internet. Use Amazon GuardDuty to set up the required rules for traffic inspection and traffic filtering is incorrect because the AWS PrivateLink (which is also known as VPC Endpoint) is just a highly available, scalable technology that enables you to privately connect your VPC to the AWS services as if they were in your VPC. This service is not capable of controlling outbound IPv6 communication to the Internet. Furthermore, the Amazon GuardDuty service doesn\'t have the features to do traffic inspection or filtering.',rule:'Use a public subnet for resources that must be connected to the internet and a private subnet for resources that won\'t be connected to the i Not AWS PrivateLink.',keywords:'On-premises file access backed by S3 = Storage Gateway File Gateway (ongoing hybrid).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_44',category:'IAM',question:'A pharmaceutical company has resources hosted on both its on-premises network and in the AWS cloud. The company requires all Software Architects to access resources in both environments using on-premises credentials, which are stored in Active Directory. In this scenario, which of the following can be used to fulfill this requirement?',choices:['A|Set up SAML 2.0-Based Federation by using a Web Identity Federation.','B|Set up SAML 2.0-Based Federation by using a Microsoft Active Directory Federation Service.','C|Use IAM users','D|Use Amazon VPC'],correct:'A',answer:'Since the company is using Microsoft Active Directory which implements Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), you can set up a SAML-Based Federation for API Access to your AWS cloud. In this way, you can easily connect to AWS using the login credentials of your on-premises network.',why:'AWS supports identity federation with SAML 2.0, an open standard that many identity providers (IdPs) use. This feature enables federated single sign-on (SSO), so users can log into the AWS Management Console or call the AWS APIs without you having to create an IAM user for everyone in your organization.',trap:'The option that says: Setting up SAML 2.0-Based Federation by using a Web Identity Federation is incorrect because this is primarily used to let users sign in via a well-known external identity provider (IdP), such as Login with Amazon, Facebook, Google. It does not utilize Active Directory.',rule:'Existing corporate AD + AWS = AD Connector (proxy, no data stored in AWS) + IAM Roles. Simple AD = new standalone directory. IAM Identity Center = SSO, works with AD Connector. AD Connector = proxy to on-premises AD (no data stored in AWS). Microsoft AD = full managed AD in AWS.',keywords:'SAML 2.0 federation: ADFS + AD → STS AssumeRoleWithSAML → temporary AWS credentials for corp SSO.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_45',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect needs to make sure that the On-Demand Amazon EC2 instance can only be accessed from this IP address (110.238.98.71) via an SSH connection. Which configuration below will satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – TCP, Port Range – 22, Source 110.238.98.71/32','B|Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Source 110.238.98.71/32','C|Security Group Outbound Rule: Protocol – TCP, Port Range – 22, Destination 110.238.98.71/32','D|Security Group Outbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Destination 0.0.0.0/0'],correct:'A',answer:'The requirement is to only allow the individual IP of the client and not the entire network. The /32 CIDR notation denotes a single IP address. Take note that the SSH protocol uses TCP, not UDP, and runs on port 22 (default). In the scenario, we can create a security group with an inbound rule allowing incoming traffic from the specified IP address on port 22.',why:'Client-side encryption is the act of encrypting data before sending it to Amazon S3. To enable client-side encryption, you have the following options: When using an AWS KMS key to enable client-side data encryption, you provide an AWS KMS key identifier (KeyId) to AWS. On the other hand, when you use client-side master key for client-side data encryption, your client-side master keys and your unencrypted data are never sent to AWS.',trap:'The option that says: Security Group Inbound Rule: Protocol – UDP, Port Range – 22, Source 110.238.98.71/32 is incorrect because it typically uses UDP instead of TCP. SSH runs over the TCP protocol, so specifying UDP would not allow the desired access.',rule:'Client-side encryption is the act of encrypting data before sending it to Amazon S3.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_46',category:'IAM',question:'A tech company that you are working for has undertaken a Total Cost Of Ownership (TCO) analysis evaluating the use of Amazon S3 versus acquiring more storage hardware. The result was that all 1200 employees would be granted access to use Amazon S3 for the storage of their personal documents. Which of the following will you need to consider so you can set up a solution that incorporates a single sign-on feature from your corporate AD or LDAP directory and also restricts access for each individual user to a designated user folder in an S3 bucket? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Use 3rd party Single Sign-On solutions such as Atlassian Crowd, OKTA, OneLogin and many others.','B|Set up a Federation proxy or an Identity provider, and use AWS Security Token Service to generate temporary tokens.','C|Map each individual user to a designated user folder in S3 using Amazon WorkDocs to access their personal documents.','D|Configure an IAM role and an IAM Policy to access the bucket.','E|Set up a matching IAM user for each of the 1200 users in your corporate directory that needs access to a folder in the S3 bucket.'],correct:'BD',answer:'The question refers to one of the common scenarios for temporary credentials in AWS. Temporary credentials are useful in scenarios that involve identity federation, delegation, cross-account access, and IAM roles. In this example, it is called enterprise identity federation, considering that you also need to set up a single sign-on (SSO) capability.',why:'In an enterprise identity federation, you can authenticate users in your organization\'s network, and then provide those users access to AWS without creating new AWS identities for them and requiring them to sign in with a separate user name and password. This is known as the single sign-on (SSO) approach to temporary access. AWS STS supports open standards like Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 2.',trap:'Using 3rd party Single Sign-On solutions such as Atlassian Crowd, OKTA, OneLogin and many others is incorrect since you don\'t have to use 3rd party solutions to provide the access. AWS already provides the necessary tools that you can use in this situation.',rule:'STS AssumeRole = temporary credentials (1hr-12hr) for cross-account access or least-privilege elevation. IAM roles are assumed; IAM users have permanent credentials. Never embed IAM credentials in code. Use IAM roles for EC2, ECS tasks, Lambda for temporary credentials.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_47',category:'S3',question:'A company has a web application that uses Amazon CloudFront to distribute its images, videos, and other static content stored in its Amazon S3 bucket to users around the world. The company has recently introduced a new member-only access feature for some of its high-quality media files. There is a requirement to provide access to multiple private media files only to paying subscribers without having to change the current URLs. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to implement to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Configure your CloudFront distribution to use Match Viewer as its Origin Protocol Policy which will automatically match the user request. This will allow access to the private content if the request is a paying member and deny it if it is not a member.','B|Create a Signed URL with a custom policy which only allows the members to see the private files.','C|Configure your CloudFront distribution to use Field-Level Encryption to protect your private data and only allow access to members.','D|Use Signed Cookies to control who can access the private files in your CloudFront distribution by modifying your application to determine whether a user should have access to your content. For members, send the required Set-Cookie headers to the viewer which will unlock the content only to them.'],correct:'D',answer:'Many companies that distribute content over the internet want to restrict access to documents, business data, media streams, or content that is intended for selected users, for example, users who have paid a fee. To securely serve this private content by using CloudFront, you can do the following: Require HTTPS. Create a CloudFront key group. Create signed URLs or signed cookies.',why:'CloudFront signed URLs and signed cookies provide the same basic functionality: they allow you to control who can access your content. If you want to serve private content through CloudFront and you\'re trying to decide whether to use signed URLs or signed cookies, consider the following: Signed URLs = per-file access control. Signed cookies = multiple files or entire content area access.',trap:'The option that says: Configure your CloudFront distribution to use Match Viewer as its Origin Protocol Policy which will automatically match the user request. This will allow access to the private content if the request is a paying member and deny it if it is not a member is incorrect because a Match Viewer is an Origin Protocol Policy that configures CloudFront to communicate with your origin using HTTP or HTTPS, depending on the protocol of the viewer request. CloudFront caches the object only once even if viewers make requests using both HTTP and HTTPS protocols.',rule:'CloudFront signed URLs and signed cookies provide the same basic functionality: they allow you to control who can access your content. Not Match Viewer.',keywords:'sub-millisecond / in-memory caching → ElastiCache. Frequently read, rarely changes → cache it.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_48',category:'Networking',question:'A Solutions Architect identified a series of DDoS attacks while monitoring the Amazon VPC. The Architect needs to fortify the current cloud infrastructure to protect the data of the clients. Which of the following is the most suitable solution to mitigate these kinds of attacks?',choices:['A|Use AWS Shield Advanced to detect and mitigate DDoS attacks.','B|Using the AWS Firewall Manager, set up a security layer that will prevent SYN floods, UDP reflection attacks, and other DDoS attacks.','C|Set up a web application firewall using AWS WAF to filter, monitor, and block HTTP traffic.','D|A combination of Security Groups and Network Access Control Lists to only allow authorized traffic to access your VPC.'],correct:'A',answer:'AWS Run Command (part of Systems Manager) allows running scripts and commands on EC2 instances remotely without SSH. For a fleet running a multiplayer game, Run Command can execute maintenance tasks across all instances simultaneously.',why:'Systems Manager Run Command executes predefined or custom documents on managed instances via the SSM Agent. It supports Windows and Linux, provides execution results in real-time, and can target instances by tags, instance IDs, or resource groups. No open inbound ports (SSH/RDP) are needed.',trap:'AWS App Runner deploys containerized web apps — not a tool for running commands on existing instances. AWS CodePipeline is a CI/CD pipeline — not for operational commands on running instances. EC2Config is a legacy Windows service superseded by SSM Agent. AWS Systems Manager provides the correct approach.',rule:'Remote commands on EC2 fleet without SSH = AWS Systems Manager Run Command. Uses SSM Agent. Targets by tag or ID. Windows + Linux. No open ports needed.',keywords:'AWS Shield Advanced: DDoS protection for EC2/ELB/CloudFront/Route 53. DRT support + cost protection.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_49',category:'S3',question:'A travel photo-sharing website is using Amazon S3 to serve high-quality photos to visitors. After a few days, it was discovered that other travel websites are linking to and using these photos. This has resulted in financial losses for the business. What is the MOST effective method to mitigate this issue?',choices:['A|Configure your S3 bucket to remove public read access and use pre-signed URLs with expiry dates.','B|Use Amazon CloudFront distributions for your photos.','C|Block the IP addresses of the offending websites using NACL.','D|Store and privately serve the high-quality photos on Amazon WorkDocs instead.'],correct:'A',answer:'In Amazon S3, all objects are private by default. Only the object owner has permission to access these objects. However, the object owner can optionally share objects with others by creating a pre-signed URL, using their own security credentials, to grant time-limited permission to download the objects.',why:'When you create a pre-signed URL for your object, you must provide your security credentials, specify a bucket name, an object key, specify the HTTP method (GET to download the object), and the expiration date and time. The pre-signed URLs are valid only for the specified duration.',trap:'The option that says: Using Amazon CloudFront distributions for your photos is incorrect. CloudFront is primarily a content delivery network service that speeds up the delivery of content to your customers.',rule:'However, the object owner can optionally share objects with others by creating a pre-signed URL, using their own security credentials, to grant time-limited permission to access the S3 object. Presigned URLs = direct S3 access, bypass CloudFront.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_50',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company uses an Application Load Balancer (ALB) for its public-facing multi-tier web applications. The security team has recently reported that there has been a surge of SQL injection attacks lately, which causes critical data discrepancy issues. The same issue is also encountered by its other web applications in other AWS accounts that are behind an ALB. An immediate solution is required to prevent the remote injection of unauthorized SQL queries and protect their applications hosted across multiple accounts. As a Solutions Architect, what solution would you recommend?',choices:['A|Use AWS Network Firewall to filter web vulnerabilities and brute force attacks using stateful rule groups across all Application Load Balancers on all AWS accounts. Refactor the web application to be less susceptible to SQL injection attacks based on the security assessment.','B|Use AWS WAF and set up a managed rule to block request patterns associated with the exploitation of SQL databases, like SQL injection attacks. Associate it with the Application Load Balancer. Integrate AWS WAF with AWS Firewall Manager to reuse the rules across all the AWS accounts.','C|Use Amazon Macie to scan for vulnerabilities and unintended network exposure. Refactor the web application to be less susceptible to SQL injection attacks based on the security assessment. Utilize the AWS Audit Manager to reuse the security assessment across all AWS accounts.','D|Use Amazon GuardDuty and set up a managed rule to block request patterns associated with the exploitation of SQL databases, like SQL injection attacks. Associate it with the Application Load Balancer and utilize the AWS Security Hub service to reuse the managed rules across all the AWS accounts'],correct:'B',answer:'AWS WAF is a web application firewall that lets you monitor the HTTP(S) requests that are forwarded to an Amazon CloudFront distribution, an Amazon API Gateway REST API, an Application Load Balancer, or an AWS AppSync GraphQL API.',why:'AWSManagedRulesSQLiRuleSet - The SQL database rule group contains rules to block request patterns associated with the exploitation of SQL databases, like SQL injection attacks. This can help prevent remote injection of unauthorized queries. Evaluate this rule group for use if your application interfaces with an SQL database.',trap:'The option that says: Use Amazon GuardDuty and set up a managed rule to block request patterns associated with the exploitation of SQL databases, like SQL injection attacks. Associate it with the Application Load Balancer and utilize the AWS Security Hub service to reuse the managed rules across all the AWS accountsis incorrect because Amazon GuardDuty is only a threat detection service and cannot directly be integrated with the Application Load Balancer.',rule:'AWSManagedRulesSQLiRuleSet - The SQL database rule group contains rules to block request patterns associated with the exploitation of SQL da Not Amazon GuardDuty.',keywords:'Block SQLi / XSS → AWS WAF (Layer 7). Associate with ALB, CloudFront, or API Gateway.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_51',category:'IAM',question:'A company has 3 DevOps engineers that are handling its software development and infrastructure management processes. One of the engineers accidentally deleted a file hosted in Amazon S3 which has caused disruption of service. What can the DevOps engineers do to prevent this from happening again?',choices:['A|Use S3 Infrequently Accessed storage to store the data.','B|Enable S3 Versioning and Multi-Factor Authentication Delete on the bucket.','C|Set up a signed URL for all users.','D|Create an IAM bucket policy that disables delete operation.'],correct:'B',answer:'To enhance data protection and meet best practices for securing stored objects, AWS recommends implementing safeguards against accidental deletions. To avoid accidental deletion in an Amazon S3 bucket, you can: Enable versioning, enable MFA Delete, use S3 Object Lock, or set S3 Replication.',why:'Versioning is a means of keeping multiple variants of an object in the same bucket. You can use versioning to preserve, retrieve, and restore every version of every object stored in your Amazon S3 bucket. With versioning, you can easily recover from both unintended user actions and application failures.',trap:'Using S3 Infrequently Accessed storage to store the data is incorrect. Switching your storage class to S3 Infrequent Access won\'t help mitigate accidental deletions.',rule:'Protect S3 from accidental deletion = Versioning (delete = adds delete marker, recoverable) + MFA Delete (permanent deletion requires MFA). Object Lock = WORM (cannot be deleted/overwritten during retention period). Versioning = recoverable soft-delete via delete markers.',keywords:'S3 WORM / immutable = Object Lock. Compliance mode = root cannot override. Needs versioning.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_52',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company requires all the data stored in the cloud to be encrypted at rest. To easily integrate this with other AWS services, they must have full control over the encryption of the created keys and also the ability to immediately remove the key material from AWS KMS. The solution should also be able to audit the key usage independently of AWS CloudTrail. Which of the following options will meet this requirement?',choices:['A|Use AWS Key Management Service to create AWS owned Keys and store the non-extractable key material in AWS CloudHSM.','B|Use AWS Key Management Service to create a KMS key in a custom key store and store the non-extractable key material in Amazon S3.','C|Use AWS Key Management Service to create AWS managed keys and store the non-extractable key material in AWS CloudHSM.','D|Use AWS Key Management Service to create a KMS key in a custom key store and store the non-extractable key material in AWS CloudHSM.'],correct:'A',answer:'The AWS Key Management Service (KMS) custom key store feature combines the controls provided by AWS CloudHSM with the integration and ease of use of AWS KMS. You can configure your own CloudHSM cluster and authorize AWS KMS to use it as a dedicated key store for your keys rather than the default AWS KMS key store.',why:'A CloudHSM custom key store keeps the KMS key material inside your CloudHSM hardware, not in AWS KMS-managed HSMs. You own and control the HSM cluster. All cryptographic operations happen inside your HSM. AWS KMS never has access to the plaintext key material. This is required for FIPS 140-2 Level 3 compliance or regulations that mandate exclusive key custody. The trade-off: if you delete the CloudHSM cluster without backing up the keys, those keys are permanently unrecoverable.',trap:'The option that says: Use AWS Key Management Service to create a KMS key in a custom key store and store the non-extractable key material in Amazon S3 is incorrect. Amazon S3 is primarily for general storage purposes and does not provide the required level of security and control needed for cryptographic key management. You have to use AWS CloudHSM instead.',rule:'Figure 1: A cluster of two CloudHSM instances is connected to the KMS front-end hosts to create a customer controlled key store Since you control the HSM hardware, CloudHSM is single-tenant (unlike KMS which is multi-tenant).',keywords:'Security group source = other SG ID (covers all current + future ASG members). Not instance IDs.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_53',category:'Storage',question:'A company hosted an e-commerce website on an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer. The Solutions Architect noticed that the website is receiving a high number of illegitimate external requests from multiple systems with frequently changing IP addresses. To address the performance issues, the Solutions Architect must implement a solution that would block these requests while having minimal impact on legitimate traffic. Which of the following options fulfills this requirement?',choices:['A|Create a regular rule in AWS WAF and associate the web ACL to an Application Load Balancer.','B|Create a custom network ACL and associate it with the subnet of the Application Load Balancer to block the offending requests.','C|Create a rate-based rule in AWS WAF and associate the web ACL to an Application Load Balancer.','D|Create a custom rule in the security group of the Application Load Balancer to block the offending requests.'],correct:'C',answer:'To prevent data exfiltration from S3, the company can: (A) use Amazon Macie to identify sensitive data and create EventBridge-triggered alerts or automated responses, and (B) use an SNS topic with EventBridge to receive notifications when sensitive data is discovered.',why:'Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover and classify sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials) stored in S3. When sensitive data is found, Macie generates findings. EventBridge rules can trigger on Macie findings to send SNS notifications, invoke Lambda remediation, or quarantine buckets. This is a continuous, automated sensitive data protection solution.',trap:'Amazon GuardDuty detects threats like unusual API activity or compromised credentials — it monitors account behavior and DNS, not S3 object content for PII. An SQS queue as an EventBridge target would buffer notifications but adds latency compared to SNS for immediate alerting.',rule:'Identify and alert on sensitive S3 data = Amazon Macie (discovers PII/sensitive data) → EventBridge → SNS notification. Macie = ML-based data classification. GuardDuty = account-level threat detection using VPC Flow Logs, DNS logs, and CloudTrail events.',keywords:'Threat detection / suspicious activity → GuardDuty. Uses ML + threat intelligence.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_54',category:'S3',question:'A government agency plans to store confidential tax documents on AWS. Due to the sensitive information in the files, the Solutions Architect must restrict the data access requests made to the storage solution to a specific Amazon VPC only. The solution should also prevent the files from being deleted or overwritten to meet the regulatory requirement of having a write-once-read-many (WORM) storage model. Which combination of the following options should the Architect implement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up a new Amazon S3 bucket to store the tax documents and integrate it with AWS Network Firewall. Configure the Network Firewall to only accept data access requests from a specific VPC.','B|Configure an Amazon S3 Access Point for the S3 bucket to restrict data access to a particular VPC only.','C|Create a new Amazon S3 bucket with the S3 Object Lock feature enabled. Store the documents in the bucket and set the Legal Hold option for object retention.','D|Store the tax documents in the Amazon S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval storage class. Use the PutBucketPolicy API to apply a bucket policy that restricts access requests to a specific VPC.','E|Enable Object Lock but disable Object Versioning on the new Amazon S3 bucket to comply with the write-once-read-many (WORM) storage model requirement.'],correct:'BC',answer:'The correct answers are: Configure an S3 Access Point restricted to a specific VPC (network-level access control), and create an S3 bucket with Object Lock enabled and set Legal Hold (WORM protection against deletion/modification).',why:'S3 Access Points provide named endpoints with customizable policies — each access point can be configured to only accept requests originating from a specific VPC, enforcing network-level isolation. S3 Object Lock with Legal Hold prevents the object from being overwritten or deleted for an indefinite period, satisfying compliance retention requirements without a fixed expiry date.',trap:'AWS Network Firewall operates at the VPC perimeter — it is not designed to restrict S3 bucket access to a specific VPC (S3 Access Points handle that). S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval with a bucket policy can restrict VPC access but adds retrieval latency inappropriate for documents that may need immediate access. You cannot enable Object Lock while disabling Versioning — Object Lock requires Versioning to be enabled.',rule:'S3 VPC-only access = S3 Access Point with VPC restriction. WORM compliance = S3 Object Lock + Legal Hold. Network Firewall = VPC perimeter, not S3 access control. Object Lock requires Versioning enabled.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_55',category:'S3',question:'A medical records company is planning to store sensitive clinical trial data in an Amazon S3 repository with the object-level versioning feature enabled. The Solutions Architect is tasked with ensuring that no object can be overwritten or deleted by any user in a period of one year only. To meet the strict compliance requirements, the root user of the company’s AWS account must also be restricted from making any changes to an object in the S3 bucket. Which of the following is the most secure way of storing the data in S3?',choices:['A|Enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode with a retention period of one year.','B|Enable S3 Object Lock in compliance mode with a retention period of one year.','C|Enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode with a legal hold of one year.','D|Enable S3 Object Lock in compliance mode with a legal hold of one year.'],correct:'B',answer:'With S3 Object Lock, you can store objects using a write-once-read-many (WORM) model. Object Lock can help prevent objects from being deleted or overwritten for a fixed amount of time or indefinitely. You can use Object Lock to help meet regulatory requirements that require WORM storage or to simply add another layer of protection against object changes and deletion.',why:'Before you lock any objects, you have to enable a bucket to use S3 Object Lock. You enable Object Lock when you create a bucket. After you enable Object Lock on a bucket, you can lock objects in that bucket. When you create a bucket with Object Lock enabled, you can\'t disable Object Lock or suspend versioning for that bucket. These retention modes apply different levels of protection to your objects.',trap:'The option that says: Enable S3 Object Lock in governance mode with a retention period of one year is incorrect because in the governance mode, users typically can\'t overwrite or delete an object version or alter its lock settings unless they have special permissions or if a user has access to the root AWS user account. A better option to choose here is to use the compliance mode.',rule:'Before you lock any objects, you have to enable a bucket to use S3 Object Lock. Not AWS user.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_56',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A government entity is conducting a population and housing census in the city. Each household information uploaded on their online portal is stored in encrypted files in Amazon S3. The government assigned its Solutions Architect to set compliance policies that verify data containing personally identifiable information (PII) in a manner that meets their compliance standards. They should also be alerted if there are potential policy violations with the privacy of their S3 buckets. Which of the following should the Architect implement to satisfy this requirement?',choices:['A|Set up and configure Amazon Macie to monitor their Amazon S3 data.','B|Set up and configure Amazon Kendra to monitor malicious activity on their Amazon S3 data','C|Set up and configure Amazon Polly to scan for usage patterns on Amazon S3 data','D|Set up and configure Amazon Fraud Detector to send out alert notifications whenever a security violation is detected on their Amazon S3 data.'],correct:'A',answer:'Amazon Macie is an ML-powered security service that helps you prevent data loss by automatically discovering, classifying, and protecting sensitive data stored in Amazon S3.',why:'Amazon Macie generates two categories of findings: policy findings and sensitive data findings. A policy finding is a detailed report of a potential policy violation or issue with the security or privacy of an Amazon S3 bucket. Macie generates these findings as part of its ongoing monitoring activities for your Amazon S3 data. A sensitive data finding is a detailed report of sensitive data in an S3 object.',trap:'The option that says: Set up and configure Amazon Polly to scan for usage patterns on Amazon S3 data is incorrect because Amazon Polly is simply a service that turns text into lifelike speech, allowing you to create applications that talk, and build entirely new categories of speech-enabled products. Polly can\'t be used to scane usage patterns on your S3 data.',rule:'Amazon Macie generates two categories of findings: policy findings and sensitive data findings. Not Amazon Polly.',keywords:'Infrequent but immediate access → S3 Standard-IA. Has retrieval fee + 30-day minimum.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'rt1e_57',category:'IAM',question:'A newly hired Solutions Architect is assigned to manage a set of CloudFormation templates that are used in the company\'s cloud architecture in AWS. The Architect accessed the templates and tried to analyze the configured IAM policy for an S3 bucket. { "Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [ "s3:Get*", "s3:List*" ], "Resource": "*" }, { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": "s3:PutObject", "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::boracay/*" } ] } What does the above IAM policy allow? (Select THREE.)',choices:['A|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to read objects from all S3 buckets owned by the account.','B|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to write objects into the boracay S3 bucket.','C|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to change access rights for the boracay S3 bucket.','D|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to read objects in the boracay S3 bucket but not allowed to list the objects in the bucket.','E|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to read objects from the boracay S3 bucket.','F|An IAM user with this IAM policy is allowed to read and delete objects from the boracay S3 bucket.'],correct:'ABCDEF',answer:'Statement 1 allows s3:Get* and s3:List* on Resource:* so every bucket can be read and listed, including boracay. Statement 2 allows s3:PutObject on boracay/* only. Together: read all buckets (A), write to boracay (B), read from boracay (E).',why:'IAM policy evaluation matches each statement Action + Resource + Effect. s3:Get* on * = GetObject on every bucket. s3:List* on * = ListBucket on every bucket. s3:PutObject scoped to boracay/* = writes only there. No s3:PutBucketPolicy means no permission changes. No s3:DeleteObject means no deletion.',trap:'Changing access rights (C) requires s3:PutBucketPolicy or s3:PutBucketAcl which are absent. Option D is wrong because s3:List* on Resource:* does allow listing boracay. There is no delete permission anywhere in this policy.',rule:'Read IAM S3 policies by action: Get*=read objects, List*=list bucket, PutObject=write, no DeleteObject=cannot delete, no PutBucketPolicy=cannot change permissions. Resource:* = applies to all buckets.',keywords:'IAM policy analysis: match Action to permission. Get*=read, List*=list, PutObject=write. Resource:* = all buckets. Unlisted action = implicitly denied.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Real Test 1'},
  {id:'t55',category:'Kinesis',question:'A media company is setting up an ECS batch architecture for its image processing application. It will be hosted in an Amazon ECS Cluster with two ECS tasks that will handle image uploads from the users and image processing. The first ECS task will process the user requests, store the image in an S3 input bucket, and push a message to a queue. The second task reads from the queue, parses the message containing the object name, and then downloads the object. Once the image is processed and transformed, it will upload the objects to the S3 output bucket. To complete the architecture, the Solutions Architect must create a queue and the necessary IAM permissions for the ECS tasks. Which of the following should the Architect do next?',choices:['A|Launch a new Amazon SQS queue and configure the second ECS task to read from it. Create an IAM role that the ECS tasks can assume in order to get access to the S3 buckets and SQS queue. Declare the IAM Role (taskRoleArn) in the task definition.','B|Launch a new Amazon AppStream 2.0 queue and configure the second ECS task to read from it. Create an IAM role that the ECS tasks can assume in order to get access to the S3 buckets and AppStream 2.0 queue. Declare the IAM Role (taskRoleArn) in the task definition.','C|Launch a new Amazon Data Firehose and configure the second ECS task to read from it. Create an IAM role that the ECS tasks can assume in order to get access to the S3 buckets and Data Firehose. Specify the ARN of the IAM Role in the (taskDefinitionArn) field of the task definition.','D|Launch a new Amazon MQ queue and configure the second ECS task to read from it. Create an IAM role that the ECS tasks can assume in order to get access to the S3 buckets and Amazon MQ queue. Set the (EnableTaskIAMRole) option to true in the task definition.'],correct:'A',answer:'Docker containers are particularly suited for batch job workloads, which are often short-lived and embarrassingly parallel. You can package your batch processing application into a Docker image and deploy it anywhere, such as in an Amazon ECS task.',why:'Amazon ECS supports batch jobs. You can use Amazon ECS Run Task action to run one or more tasks once. The Run Task action starts the ECS task on an instance that meets the task’s requirements including CPU, memory, and ports.',trap:'The option that says: Launch a new Amazon AppStream 2.0 queue and configure the second ECS task to read from it. Create an IAM role that the ECS tasks can assume in order to get access to the S3 buckets and AppStream 2.0 queue. Declare the IAM Role (taskRoleArn) in the task definition is incorrect because Amazon AppStream 2.0 is a fully managed application streaming service and can\'t be used as a queue. You have to use Amazon SQS instead.',rule:'Amazon ECS supports batch jobs. Not Amazon AppStream.',keywords:'ECS task needs AWS permissions → IAM Role declared as taskRoleArn in task definition. Not instance role.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t56',category:'Database',question:'An accounting application uses an Amazon RDS database configured with Multi-AZ deployments to improve availability. What would happen to RDS if the primary database instance fails?',choices:['A|The IP address of the primary DB instance is switched to the standby DB instance.','B|The primary database instance will reboot.','C|A new database instance is created in the standby Availability Zone.','D|The canonical name record (CNAME) is switched from the primary to standby instance.'],correct:'D',answer:'In Amazon RDS, failover is automatically handled so that you can resume database operations as quickly as possible without administrative intervention in the event that your primary database instance goes down.',why:'RDS Multi-AZ uses the CNAME DNS record for the DB endpoint. During failover, RDS updates the CNAME to point to the standby — typically within 60-120 seconds. Your application reconnects to the same hostname and automatically reaches the newly promoted instance. Failover is triggered by: primary instance failure, AZ disruption, OS patching, or instance type change. The standby cannot serve reads while the primary is running.',trap:'The option that says: The IP address of the primary DB instance is switched to the standby DB instance is incorrect because IP addresses are per subnet, and subnets simply cannot span multiple AZs.',rule:'RDS Multi-AZ failover = CNAME flipped to standby (not IP switch). Automatic, no admin intervention. Standby cannot serve reads — it only activates on primary failure or during maintenance. CNAME failover = Multi-AZ DNS cutover mechanism.',keywords:'RDS Multi-AZ failover = CNAME flipped from primary to standby. Not IP switch. Automatic, no admin needed.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t57',category:'CloudWatch',question:'A company has a top priority requirement to monitor certain database metrics and send email notifications to the Operations team if any issues occur. Which combination of AWS services can accomplish this requirement? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Amazon Simple Email Service','B|Amazon CloudWatch','C|Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS)','D|Amazon EC2 Instance with a running Berkeley Internet Name Domain (BIND) Server.','E|Amazon Simple Notification Service (SNS)'],correct:'BE',answer:'Amazon CloudWatch and Amazon Simple Notification Service (SNS) are correct. In this requirement, you can use Amazon CloudWatch to monitor the database and then Amazon SNS to send the emails to the Operations team. Take note that you should use SNS instead of SES (Simple Email Service) when you want to monitor your EC2 instances.',why:'CloudWatch collects monitoring and operational data in the form of logs, metrics, and events, providing you with a unified view of AWS resources, applications, and services that run on AWS, and on-premises servers. SNS is a highly available, durable, secure, fully managed pub/sub messaging service that enables you to decouple microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.',trap:'Amazon EC2 Instance with a running Berkeley Internet Name Domain (BIND) Server is incorrect because BIND is primarily used as a Domain Name System (DNS) web service. This is only applicable if you have a private hosted zone in your AWS account. It does not monitor applications nor send email notifications.',rule:'CloudWatch collects monitoring and operational data in the form of logs, metrics, and events, providing you with a unified view of AWS resou Not Domain Name System.',keywords:'Monitor metrics + email alerts = CloudWatch (alarm) + SNS (notification). Not SES (bulk email).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t58',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has a static corporate website hosted in a standard Amazon S3 bucket and a new web domain name that was registered using Amazon Route 53. There is a requirement to integrate these two services in order to successfully launch the corporate website. What are the prerequisites when routing traffic using Route 53 to a website that is hosted in an S3 Bucket? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|The S3 bucket name must be the same as the domain name.','B|A registered domain name.','C|The record set must be of type "MX".','D|The S3 bucket must be in the same region as the hosted zone.','E|The Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) option should be enabled in the S3 bucket.'],correct:'AB',answer:'For Route 53 to route traffic to an S3 static website, two prerequisites must be met: (A) the S3 bucket name must exactly match the domain name (e.g., bucket named tutorialsdojo.com for the domain tutorialsdojo.com), and (D) you must have a registered domain name. Route 53 uses an Alias record pointing to the S3 website endpoint.',why:'Amazon Route 53 is a scalable and highly available Domain Name System (DNS) web service designed to efficiently and reliably route end-user requests to Internet applications. As part of the AWS (Amazon Web Services) cloud ecosystem, Route 53 provides a range of features for managing domain names, DNS records, and directing web traffic.',trap:'The option that says: The record set must be of type "MX" is incorrect because an MX record specifies the mail server responsible for accepting email messages on behalf of a domain name. This is just not what is being asked by the question.',rule:'Route 53 → S3 static website prerequisites: bucket name = domain name exactly + registered domain. Use Alias record (not CNAME) at zone apex. Region match not required.',keywords:'Route 53 → S3 static website: bucket name must match domain name exactly. Use Alias record (not CNAME at apex).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t59',category:'Route 53',question:'A company has a dynamic web app written in MEAN stack that is going to be launched in the next month. There is a probability that the traffic will be quite high in the first couple of weeks. In the event of a load failure, how can you set up DNS failover to a static website?',choices:['A|Duplicate the exact application architecture in another region and configure DNS weight-based routing.','B|Enable failover to an application hosted in an on-premises data center.','C|Use Route 53 with the failover option to a static S3 website bucket or CloudFront distribution.','D|Add more servers in case the application fails.'],correct:'C',answer:'Route 53 with the Failover routing policy routes traffic to a static S3 website or CloudFront distribution as the secondary endpoint when the primary (dynamic web app) fails its health check. This provides a low-cost, always-available fallback without running duplicate servers.',why:'Route 53 Failover routing works by defining a primary record (the live web app) with a health check, and a secondary record (S3 static site or CloudFront) that activates automatically if the primary health check fails. The static site can show a maintenance page or cached content. No duplicate infrastructure is needed — the S3 bucket only serves traffic during an outage.',trap:'Duplicating the exact application architecture in another region and using weighted routing adds full-cost duplicate infrastructure for what is just a failover requirement — expensive and over-engineered. Adding more servers only after failure means there will be downtime during the provisioning window. On-premises failover bypasses the AWS-native solution unnecessarily.',rule:'DNS failover to static site = Route 53 Failover routing + S3 static website (or CloudFront) as secondary record. Primary fails health check → traffic switches to static fallback automatically.',keywords:'Cloud-agnostic containers → EKS (Kubernetes). ECS = AWS proprietary. EKS = portable, open-source, Kubernetes-compatible.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t60',category:'Storage',question:'A company is implementing its Business Continuity Plan. As part of this initiative, the IT Director instructed the IT team to set up an automated backup of all the Amazon EBS volumes attached to the company’s Amazon EC2 instances. The solution must be implemented as soon as possible and should be both cost-effective and simple to maintain. What is the fastest and most cost-effective solution to automatically back up all of the EBS volumes?',choices:['A|For an automated solution, create a scheduled job that calls the "create-snapshot" command via the AWS CLI to take a snapshot of production EBS volumes periodically.','B|Set your Amazon Storage Gateway with EBS volumes as the data source and store the backups in your on-premises servers through the storage gateway.','C|Use an EBS snapshot retention rule in AWS Backup to automatically manage snapshot retention and expiration.','D|Use Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (Amazon DLM) to automate the creation of EBS snapshots.'],correct:'D',answer:'Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM) automates the creation, retention, and deletion of Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) snapshots. It simplifies EBS volume management by allowing you to define policies that govern the lifecycle of these snapshots, ensuring regular backups are created and obsolete snapshots are automatically removed.',why:'You can use Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (Amazon DLM) to automate the creation, retention, and deletion of snapshots taken to back up your Amazon EBS volumes. Automating snapshot management helps you to: Combined with the monitoring features of Amazon EventBridge and AWS CloudTrail, Amazon DLM provides a complete backup solution for EBS volumes at no additional cost.',trap:'The option that says: For an automated solution, create a scheduled job that calls the "create-snapshot" command via the AWS CLI to take a snapshot of production EBS volumes periodically is incorrect because even though this is just a valid solution, you would still need additional time to create a scheduled job that calls the "create-snapshot" command. It would be better to use Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (Amazon DLM) instead, as this provides you with the fastest solution, which enables you to automate the creation, retention, and deletion of the EBS snapshots without having to write custom shell scripts or creating scheduled jobs.',rule:'Cost-effective → Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager, Amazon DLM. Not AWS CLI.',keywords:'Automated EBS snapshot management = Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM). Cost-effective, no EC2 needed.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t61',category:'Networking',question:'A DevOps Engineer is required to design a cloud architecture in AWS. The Engineer is planning to develop a highly available and fault-tolerant architecture consisting of an Elastic Load Balancer and an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances deployed across multiple Availability Zones. This will be used by an online accounting application that requires path-based routing, host-based routing, and bi-directional streaming using Remote Procedure Call (gRPC). Which configuration will satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Configure an Application Load Balancer in front of the auto-scaling group. Select gRPC as the protocol version.','B|Configure a Network Load Balancer in front of the auto-scaling group. Use a UDP listener for routing.','C|Configure a Gateway Load Balancer in front of the auto-scaling group. Ensure that the IP Listener Routing uses the GENEVE protocol on port 6081 to allow gRPC response traffic.','D|Configure a Network Load Balancer in front of the auto-scaling group. Create an AWS Global Accelerator accelerator and set the load balancer as an endpoint.'],correct:'A',answer:'Application Load Balancer operates at the request level (layer 7), routing traffic to targets (EC2 instances, containers, IP addresses, and Lambda functions) based on the content of the request.',why:'If your application is composed of several individual services, an Application Load Balancer can route a request to a service based on the content of the request such as Host field, Path URL, HTTP header, HTTP method, Query string, or Source IP address.',trap:'The option that says: Configure a Network Load Balancer in front of the auto-scaling group. Use a UDP listener for routing is incorrect. Network Load Balancers do not support gRPC.',rule:'HA → AWS Global Accelerator a. Not Network Load Balancer.',keywords:'Path-based + host-based routing + gRPC = ALB (Layer 7). Select gRPC as the protocol version. NLB does not support gRPC.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t62',category:'Serverless',question:'An e-commerce company is receiving a large volume of sales data files in .csv format from its external partners on a daily basis. These data files are then stored in an Amazon S3 Bucket for processing and reporting purposes. The company wants to create an automated solution to convert these .csv files into Apache Parquet format and store the output of the processed files in a new S3 bucket called “tutorialsdojo-data-transformed”. This new solution is meant to enhance the company’s data processing and analytics workloads while keeping its operating costs low. Which of the following options must be implemented to meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?',choices:['A|Integrate Amazon EMR File System (EMRFS) with the source S3 bucket to automatically discover the new data files. Use an Amazon EMR Serverless with Apache Spark to convert the .csv files to the Apache Parquet format and then store the output in the "tutorialsdojo-data-transformed" bucket.','B|Utilize an AWS Batch job definition with Bash syntax to convert the .csv files to the Apache Parquet format. Configure the job definition to run automatically whenever a new .csv file is uploaded to the source bucket.','C|Use Amazon S3 event notifications to trigger an AWS Lambda function that converts .csv files to Apache Parquet format using Apache Spark on an Amazon EMR cluster. Save the processed files to the “tutorialsdojo-data-transformed" bucket.','D|Use AWS Glue crawler to automatically discover the raw data file in S3 as well as check its corresponding schema. Create a scheduled ETL job in AWS Glue that will convert .csv files to Apache Parquet format and store the output of the processed files in the “tutorialsdojo-data-transformed" bucket.'],correct:'D',answer:'AWS Glue is a fully managed extract, transform, and load (ETL) service. AWS Glue makes it cost-effective to categorize your data, clean it, enrich it, and move it reliably between various data stores and data streams. This pattern provides different job types in AWS Glue and uses three different scripts to demonstrate authoring ETL jobs.',why:'Apache Parquet is built to support efficient compression and encoding schemes. It can speed up your analytics workloads because it stores data in a columnar fashion. Converting data to Parquet can save you storage space, cost, and time in the longer run.',trap:'The option that says: Utilize an AWS Batch job definition with Bash syntax to convert the .csv files to the Apache Parquet format. Configure the job definition to run automatically whenever a new .csv file is uploaded to the source bucket is incorrect because AWS Batch is mainly intended for managing batch processing tasks in Docker containers, which can make things complicated due to containerization and Bash script execution. The setup and maintenance of AWS Batch resources, such as compute environments and job queues, can be more challenging than using serverless or fully managed services. Furthermore, AWS Batch still requires manual scaling configuration and incurs costs based on resource usage, which can make cost management and optimization more difficult. Although AWS Batch can trigger jobs automatically when new files are uploaded, the overall setup and maintenance of the Batch environment require more manual effort.',rule:'create an automated solution to convert these → Integrate Amazon, File System. Not AWS Batch.',keywords:'CSV → Parquet with least overhead = AWS Glue (crawler discovers schema + scheduled ETL job converts format).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t63',category:'Networking',question:'A company is running a dashboard application on a Spot EC2 instance inside a private subnet. The dashboard is reachable via a domain name that maps to the private IPv4 address of the instance’s network interface. A solutions architect needs to increase network availability by allowing the traffic flow to resume in another instance if the primary instance is terminated. Which solution accomplishes these requirements?',choices:['A|Create a secondary elastic network interface and point its private IPv4 address to the application’s domain name. Attach the new network interface to the primary instance. If the instance goes down, move the secondary network interface to another instance.','B|Attach an elastic IP address to the instance’s primary network interface and point its IP address to the application’s domain name. Automatically move the EIP to a secondary instance if the primary instance becomes unavailable using the AWS Transit Gateway.','C|Use the AWS Network Firewall to detach the instance’s primary elastic network interface and move it to a new instance upon failure.','D|Set up AWS Transfer for FTPS service in Implicit FTPS mode to automatically disable the source/destination checks on the instance’s primary elastic network interface and reassociate it to another instance.'],correct:'A',answer:'If one of your instances serving a particular function fails, its network interface can be attached to a replacement or hot standby instance pre-configured for the same role in order to rapidly recover the service. For example, you can use a network interface as your primary or secondary network interface to a critical service such as a database instance or a NAT instance.',why:'Because the interface maintains its private IP addresses, Elastic IP addresses, and MAC address, network traffic begins flowing to the standby instance as soon as you attach the network interface to the replacement instance. Users experience a brief loss of connectivity between the time the instance fails and the time that the network interface is attached to the standby instance, but no changes to the route table or your DNS server are required.',trap:'The option that says: Attach an elastic IP address to the instance’s primary network interface and point its IP address to the application’s domain name. Automatically move the EIP to a secondary instance if the primary instance becomes unavailable using the AWS Transit Gateway is incorrect. Elastic IPs are not needed in the solution since the application is private. Furthermore, an AWS Transit Gateway is primarily used to connect your Amazon Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) and on-premises networks through a central hub. This particular networking service cannot be used to automatically move an Elastic IP address to another EC2 instance.',rule:'Because the interface maintains its private IP addresses, Elastic IP addresses, and MAC address, network traffic begins flowing to the standby instance immediately, with no changes to DNS records or application configuration.',keywords:'Private IP failover without DNS change = secondary ENI. Move ENI to standby instance. Private IP stays the same.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t64',category:'EC2',question:'A start-up company has an EC2 instance that is hosting a web application. The volume of users is expected to grow in the coming months and hence, you need to add more elasticity and scalability in your AWS architecture to cope with the demand. Which of the following options can satisfy the above requirement for the given scenario? (Select TWO.)',choices:['A|Set up two EC2 instances and then put them behind an Elastic Load balancer (ELB).','B|Set up an S3 Cache in front of the EC2 instance.','C|Set up two EC2 instances and use Route 53 to route traffic based on a Weighted Routing Policy.','D|Set up an AWS WAF behind your EC2 Instance.','E|Set up two EC2 instances deployed using Launch Templates and integrated with AWS Glue.'],correct:'AC',answer:'ELB distributes incoming traffic across two or more EC2 instances automatically, adding elasticity. Route 53 Weighted routing splits DNS traffic proportionally between instances, also providing scalability. Both are valid and complementary approaches.',why:'An Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) routes requests across registered EC2 targets and scales its capacity automatically. Route 53 Weighted routing assigns a numeric weight to each record — traffic is distributed proportionally, and you can adjust weights over time as capacity changes. Both approaches allow the application to handle more users without a single instance being overwhelmed.',trap:'S3 Cache does not add elasticity to EC2 — S3 is object storage, not a caching layer for compute. AWS WAF is a web application firewall for security, not for scaling traffic. Launch Templates with Glue is not a scaling pattern — Glue is an ETL service.',rule:'Add elasticity to EC2 = ELB (load balancer) or Route 53 Weighted routing (DNS split). Both are valid. WAF = security. S3 = storage. Glue = ETL.',keywords:'Add elasticity to EC2 app = ELB (distribute load) or Route 53 Weighted routing (split traffic). Both valid.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t65',category:'Security',question:'A company plans to conduct a network security audit. The web application is hosted on an Auto Scaling group of EC2 Instances with an Application Load Balancer in front to evenly distribute the incoming traffic. A Solutions Architect has been tasked to enhance the security posture of the company’s cloud infrastructure and minimize the impact of DDoS attacks on its resources. Which of the following is the most effective solution that should be implemented?',choices:['A|Configure Amazon CloudFront distribution and set Application Load Balancer as the origin. Create a rate-based web ACL rule using AWS WAF and associate it with Amazon CloudFront.','B|Configure Amazon CloudFront distribution and set a Network Load Balancer as the origin. Use VPC Flow Logs to monitor abnormal traffic patterns. Set up a custom AWS Lambda function that processes the flow logs and invokes Amazon SNS for notification.','C|Configure Amazon CloudFront distribution and set an Application Load Balancer as the origin. Create a security group rule and deny all the suspicious addresses. Use Amazon SNS for notification.','D|Configure Amazon CloudFront distribution and set a Network Load Balancer as the origin. Use Amazon GuardDuty to block suspicious hosts based on its security findings. Set up a custom AWS Lambda function that processes the security logs and invokes Amazon SNS for notification.'],correct:'A',answer:'CloudFront with ALB as origin plus a WAF rate-based Web ACL is the standard DDoS mitigation pattern. The rate-based rule automatically blocks any IP address that exceeds a request threshold per 5-minute window, returning 403 to blocked clients.',why:'AWS WAF rate-based rules count requests per originating IP in any 5-minute window. When an IP breaches the limit, WAF blocks it immediately without manual intervention. CloudFront absorbs volumetric attacks at the edge before they reach the ALB. Together they address both Layer 3/4 (CloudFront) and Layer 7 (WAF) DDoS attack vectors.',trap:'VPC Flow Logs + Lambda + SNS only notifies you after the fact — it cannot block traffic in real time. GuardDuty detects threats but cannot directly block traffic to the ALB. Security group rules require manual IP management and cannot auto-respond to DDoS at scale.',rule:'DDoS mitigation = CloudFront (origin=ALB) + WAF rate-based rule. Rate-based rule auto-blocks IPs over threshold. VPC Flow Logs = monitoring only, cannot block. GuardDuty = detect, not block.',keywords:'DDoS mitigation = CloudFront (absorbs at edge) + WAF rate-based rule (auto-blocks IPs). Not GuardDuty (detects only). Not Flow Logs (monitor only).',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'},
  {id:'t54',category:'EC2',question:'A company plans to migrate its suite of containerized applications running on-premises to a container service in AWS. The solution must be cloud-agnostic and use an open-source platform that can automatically manage containerized workloads and services. It should also use the same configuration and tools across various production environments. What should the Solution Architect do to properly migrate and satisfy the given requirement?',choices:['A|Migrate the application to Amazon Container Registry (ECR) with Amazon EC2 instance worker nodes.','B|Migrate the application to Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service with EKS worker nodes.','C|Migrate the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service with ECS tasks that use the AWS Fargate launch type.','D|Migrate the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service with ECS tasks that use the Amazon EC2 launch type.'],correct:'B',answer:'Amazon EKS runs open-source Kubernetes, which is cloud-agnostic. Applications on EKS are fully compatible with any standard Kubernetes environment — on-premises or any cloud. ECS is AWS-proprietary and cannot be used on other clouds.',why:'Kubernetes is an open-source container orchestration system that runs identically across AWS, GCP, Azure, and on-premises. EKS manages the Kubernetes control plane across multiple AZs. Because it uses standard Kubernetes APIs and tooling, there is no vendor lock-in — the same configuration files and Helm charts work anywhere Kubernetes runs. ECS uses AWS-specific task definitions and is not portable outside AWS.',trap:'Amazon ECS (both Fargate and EC2 launch types) is AWS-proprietary — it cannot run on other cloud providers or on-premises without AWS Outposts. ECR is a container registry for storing images, not a container orchestration service. Choosing ECS violates the cloud-agnostic requirement.',rule:'Cloud-agnostic containers = EKS (Kubernetes, open-source, portable). ECS = AWS-only, proprietary. EKS = runs same config on any Kubernetes cluster anywhere.',keywords:'Cloud-agnostic containers → EKS (Kubernetes). ECS = AWS proprietary. EKS = portable, open-source, Kubernetes-compatible.',exam:'SAA-C03',set:'Practice Set 1'}
];

